1308,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 4.517'),(1309,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 4.518-4.519'),(1310,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 4.519-4.520'),(1311,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 4.521-4.522'),(1312,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 4.522-4.524'),(1313,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 4.524-4.525'),(1314,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 4.525-4.526'),(1315,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 4.527-4.528'),(1316,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 4.529-4.531'),(1317,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 4.532'),(1318,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 4.532-4.535'),(1319,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 4.535'),(1320,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 4.536-4.538'),(1321,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 4.538'),(1322,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 4.539-4.542'),(1323,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 4.543-4.544'),(1324,'And now to Tydeus\' son, Diomedes, Pallas Athene gave might and courage, that he should prove himself pre-eminent amid all the Argives, and win glorious renown. –'),(1325,' She kindled from his helm and shield flame unwearying,  like to the star of harvesttime that shineth bright above all others when he hath bathed him in the stream of Ocean.'),(1326,' Even such flame did she kindle from his head and shoulders; and she sent him into the midst where men thronged the thickest.'),(1327,'Now there was amid the Trojans one Dares, a rich man and blameless,  a priest of Hephaestus; '),(1328,'and he had two sons, Phegeus and Idaeus, both well skilled in all manner of fighting.'),(1329,'  These twain separated themselves from the host and went forth against him'),(1330,'they in their car, while he charged on foot upon the ground.'),(1331,'  And when they were come near, as they advanced against each other,  first Phegeus let fly his far-shadowing spear'),(1332,'and over the left shoulder of the son of Tydeus passed the point of the spear, and smote him not.'),(1333,'  Then Tydeus\' son rushed on with the bronze'),(1334,'and not in vain did the shaft speed from his hand, but he smote his foe on the breast between the nipples, and thrust him from the car.'),(1335,'  And Idaeus sprang back, and left the beauteous chariot, and had no heart to bestride his slain brother.'),(1336,'  Nay, nor would he himself have escaped black fate, had not Hephaestus guarded him, and saved him, enfolding him in darkness, that his aged priest might not be utterly fordone with grief.'),(1337,'  Howbeit the horses did the son of great souled Tydeus drive forth and give to his comrades to bring to the hollow ships.'),(1338,'  But when the great-souled Trojans beheld the two sons of Dares, the one in flight and the other slain beside the car, the hearts of all were dismayed.'),(1339,'  And flashing-eyed Athene  took furious Ares by the hand and spake to him, saying:'),(1340,'\"Ares, Ares, thou bane of mortals, thou blood-stained stormer of walls, shall we not now leave the Trojans and Achaeans to fight, to whichsoever of the two it be that father Zeus shall vouchsafe glory? But for us twain, let us give place, and avoid the wrath of Zeus.\"'),(1341,' So spake she, and led furious Ares forth from the battle.   '),(1342,'Then she made him to sit down on the sandy banks of Scamander, and the Trojans were turned in flight by the Danaans.'),(1343,'  Each one of the captains slew his man; '),(1344,'first the king of men, Agamemnon, thrust from his car the leader of the Halizones, great Odius,'),(1345,' for as he turned first of all to flee he fixed his spear in his back between the shoulders and drave it through his breast; and he fell with a thud, and upon him his armour clanged. '),(1346,'And Idomeneus slew Phaestus, son of Borus the Maeonian, that had come from deep-soiled Tarne.'),(1347,'  Him even as he was mounting his chariot Idomeneus, famed for his spear, pierced with a thrust of his long spear through the right shoulder;'),(1348,'and he fell from his car, and hateful darkness gat hold of him.'),(1349,'Him then the squires of Idomeneus stripped of his armour;'),(1350,'Him then the squires of Idomeneus stripped of his armour;'),(1351,' for Artemis herself had taught him to smite all wild things that the mountain forest nurtureth.'),(1352,'  Yet in no wise did the archer Artemis avail him now, neither all that skill in archery wherein of old he excelled; '),(1353,' but the son of Atreus, Menelaus famed for his spear, smote him as he fled before him with a thrust of his spear in the back between the shoulders, and drave it through his breast.  So he fell face foremost, and upon him his armour clanged.'),(1354,'And Meriones slew Phereclus, son of Tecton,  Harmon\'s son, whose hands were skilled to fashion all manner of curious work;'),(1355,'And Meriones slew Phereclus, son of Tecton,  Harmon\'s son, whose hands were skilled to fashion all manner of curious work;'),(1356,'  He it was that had also built for Alexander the shapely ships, source of ills, that were made the bane of all the Trojans and of his own self, seeing he knew not in any wise the oracles of the gods.'),(1357,'  After him Meriones pursued, and when he had come up with him, smote him in the right buttock'),(1358,'and the spear-point passed clean through even to the bladder beneath the bone;'),(1359,'and he fell to his knees with a groan, and death enfolded him.'),(1360,'And Pedaeus, Antenor\'s son, was slain of Meges;  he was in truth a bastard, howbeit goodly Theano had reared him carefully even as her own children, to do pleasure to her husband.'),(1361,'  To him Phyleus\' son, famed for his spear, drew nigh and smote him with a cast of his sharp spear on the sinew of the head;'),(1362,'and straight through amid the teeth the bronze shore away the tongue at its base.'),(1363,'  So he fell in the dust, and bit the cold bronze with his teeth.'),(1364,'And Eurypylus, son of Euaemon, slew goodly Hypsenor, son of Dolopion high of heart, that was made priest of Scamander, and was honoured of the folk even as a god—upon him did Eurypylus, Euaemon\'s glorious son,  rush with his sword as he fled before him, and in mid-course smite him upon the shoulder and lop off his heavy arm.'),(1365,'So the arm all bloody fell to the ground'),(1366,'and down over his eyes came dark death and mighty fate. '),(1367,'Thus toiled they in the mighty conflict; '),(1368,' but of Tydeus\' son couldst thou not have told with which host of the twain he was joined, whether it was with the Trojans that he had fellowship or with the Achaeans.'),(1369,'  For he stormed across the plain like unto a winter torrent at the full, that with its swift flood sweeps away the embankments;'),(1370,'this the close-fenced embankments hold not back,  neither do the walls of the fruitful vineyards stay its sudden coming when the rain of Zeus driveth it on; '),(1371,'and before it in multitudes the fair works of men fall in ruin.'),(1372,'  Even in such wise before Tydeus\' son were the thick battalions of the Trojans driven in rout, nor might they abide him for all they were so many.'),(1373,'  But when the glorious son of Lycaon was ware of him as he raged across the plain and drove the battalions in rout before him, forthwith he bent against the son of Tydeus his curved bow, and with sure aim smote him as he rushed onwards upon the right shoulder on the plate of his corselet;'),(1374,'through this sped the bitter arrow  and held straight on its way, and the corselet was spattered with blood.'),(1375,' Over him then shouted aloud the glorious son of Lycaon:'),(1376,' \"Rouse you, great-souled Trojans, ye goaders of horses.  '),(1377,'Smitten is the best man of the Achaeans, and I deem he will not for long endure the mighty shaft, if in very truth the king,  the son of Zeus, sped me on my way when I set forth from Lycia.\"'),(1378,'So spake he vauntingly;'),(1379,' howbeit that other did the swift arrow not lay low, but he drew back, and took his stand before his horses and chariot, and spake to Sthenelus, son of Capaneus:\"'),(1380,'Rouse thee, good son of Capaneus; get thee down from the car,  that thou mayest draw forth from my shoulder the bitter arrow.\"'),(1381,'So spake he, and Sthenelus leapt from his chariot to the ground, and stood beside him, and drew forth the swift arrow clean through his shoulder; '),(1382,'and the blood spurted up through the pliant tunic.'),(1383,'  And thereat Diomedes, good at the war-cry, made prayer:'),(1384,'  \"Hear me, child of Zeus that beareth the aegis, unwearied one!  If ever with kindly thought thou stoodest by my father\'s side amid the fury of battle, even so do thou now be likewise kind to me, Athene.'),(1385,' Grant that I may slay this man, and that he come within the cast of my spear, that hath smitten me or ever I was ware of him, and boasteth over me, '),(1386,'So spake he in prayer, '),(1387,'and Pallas Athene heard him, and made his limbs light, his feet and his hands above;'),(1388,'and she drew near to his side and spake to him winged words:'),(1389,' \"Be of good courage now, Diomedes, to fight against the Trojans,  '),(1390,' for in thy breast have I put the might of thy father, the dauntless might, such as the horseman Tydeus, wielder of the shield, was wont to have.'),(1391,'  And the mist moreover have I taken from thine eyes that afore was upon them, to the end that thou mayest well discern both god and man.  '),(1392,'Wherefore now if any god come hither to make trial of thee,  do not thou in any wise fight face to face with any other immortal gods'),(1393,'save only if Aphrodite, daughter of Zeus, shall enter the battle, her do thou smite with a thrust of the sharp bronze.\"'),(1394,'When she had thus spoken, the goddess, flashing-eyed Athene, departed, and the son of Tydeus returned again and mingled with the foremost fighters;  and though afore his heart had been eager to do battle with the Trojans,'),(1395,'now verily did fury thrice so great lay hold upon him, even as upon a lion that a shepherd in the field, guarding his fleecy sheep, hath wounded as he leapt over the wall of the sheep-fold, but hath not vanquished; '),(1396,'his might hath he roused, but thereafter maketh no more defence,  but slinketh amid the farm buildings,and the flock all unprotected is driven in rout'),(1397,'and the sheep are strewn in heaps, but the lion in his fury leapeth forth from the high fold; '),(1398,'even in such fury did mighty Diomedes mingle with the Trojans.'),(1399,'Then slew he Astynous and Hypeiron, shepherd of the host;  the one he smote above the nipple with a cast of his bronze-shod spear, and the other he struck with his great sword upon the collar-bone beside the shoulder, and shore off the shoulder from the neck and from the back.'),(1400,'These then he let be, but went his way in pursuit of Abas and Polyidus, sons of the old man Eurydamas, the reader of dreams; '),(1401,' howbeit they came not back for the old man to interpret dreams for them, but mighty Diomedes slew them.'),(1402,'  Then went he on after Xanthus and Thoön, sons twain of Phaenops, and both well beloved; '),(1403,'and their father was fordone with grievous old age, and begat no other son to leave in charge of his possessions.'),(1404,'  There Diomedes slew them, and bereft them of dear life, both the twain; but for the father he left lamentation and grievous sorrow, seeing they lived not for him to welcome them on their return; '),(1405,'and the next of kin divided his goods. '),(1406,'Then took he two sons of Priam, Dardanus\' son,  Echemmon and Chromius, the twain being in one car.  '),(1407,'Even as a lion leapeth among the kine and breaketh the neck of a heifer or a cow as they graze in a woodland pasture, so did Tydeus\' son thrust both these in evil wise from their car, sorely against their will, and thereafter despoiled them of their armour '),(1408,'and the horses he gave to his comrades to drive to the ships.'),(1409,'But Aeneas was ware of him as he made havoc of the ranks of warriors, and went his way along the battle amid the hurtling of the spears in quest of godlike Pandarus, if so be he might anywhere find him.'),(1410,'He found the son of Lycaon, goodly and valiant,  and took his stand before his face, and spake to him, saying:'),(1411,'\"Pandarus, where now are thy bow and thy winged arrows, and thy fame?'),(1412,' Therein may no man of this land vie with thee, nor any in Lycia declare himself to be better than thou. '),(1413,'Come now, lift up thy hands in prayer to Zeus, and let fly a shaft at this man,  whoe\'er he be that prevaileth thus, and hath verily wrought the Trojans much mischief, seeing he hath loosed the knees of many men and goodly'),(1414,'if indeed he be not some god that is wroth with the Trojans, angered by reason of sacrifices;'),(1415,'with grievous weight doth the wrath of god rest upon men.'),(1416,'To him then spake the glorious son of Lycaon:'),(1417,'  \"Aeneas, counsellor of the brazen-coated Trojans, to the wise-hearted son of Tydeus do I liken him in all things, knowing him by his shield and his crested helm, and when I look on his horses; '),(1418,'yet I know not surely if he be not a god.'),(1419,'  But if he be the man I deem him, even the wise-hearted son of Tydeus,  not without the aid of some god doth he thus rage, but one of the immortals standeth hard by him, his shoulders wrapped in cloud, and turned aside from him my swift shaft even as it lighted.'),(1420,'For already have I let fly a shaft at him, and I smote him upon the right shoulder clean through the plate of his corselet; '),(1421,'  and I deemed that I should send him forth to Aïdoneus, yet I subdued him not;'),(1422,'verily he is some wrathful god.'),(1423,'  And horses have I not at hand, neither car whereon I might mount'),(1424,'yet in Lycaon\'s halls, I ween, there be eleven fair chariots, new-wrought, new-furnished'),(1425,'with cloths spread over them;'),(1426,' and by each standeth its yoke of horses feeding on white barley and spelt.'),(1427,'Aye, and as I set out hither the old spearman Lycaon straitly charged me in our well-built house:'),(1428,'he bade me be mounted on horse and car, riding there to be lord among the Trojans in the strong encounters.'),(1429,'verily it had been better far!'),(1430,'verily it had been better far!'),(1431,'—but spared the horses lest in the multitude of men they should lack fodder, they that were wont to eat their fill.'),(1432,'  So I left them, and am come on foot to Ilios, trusting in my bow; '),(1433,' but this, meseems, was to avail me not. '),(1434,'Already have I let fly a shaft at two chieftains, the son of Tydeus and Atreus\' son, and smitten them fairly, and from them both of a surety I drew forth blood, yet did I but arouse them the more.'),(1435,'Wherefore with ill hap was it that I took from the peg my curved bow  on that day when I led my Trojans to lovely Ilios to do pleasure to Hector.'),(1436,'But if so be I shall return and behold with mine eyes my native land and my wife and great, high-roofed palace, then may some alien forthwith cut my head from me,  if I break not this bow with my hands and cast it into the blazing fire; '),(1437,'for worthless as wind doth it attend me.\"'),(1438,'To him then spake in answer Aeneas, leader of the Trojans:'),(1439,' \"Nay, speak not thus;'),(1440,' things shall in no wise be any better before that we twain with horses and chariot  go to face this man and make trial of him in arms.'),(1441,'Nay, come, mount upon my car, that thou mayest see of what sort are the horses of Tros, well skilled to course fleetly hither and thither over the plain whether in pursuit or in flight.'),(1442,'  They twain will bring the two of us safely to the city,  if again Zeus shall vouchsafe glory to Tydeus\' son Diomedes.'),(1443,'Come, therefore, take thou now the lash and the shining reins, and I will dismount to fight;'),(1444,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 5.228'),(1445,'from MILESTONE 225 to MILESTONE 230\n======================================================================\nThen made answer to him the glorious son of Lycaon:'),(1446,'  \"Aeneas, keep thou the reins thyself, and drive thine own horses; '),(1447,'better will they draw the curved car under their wonted charioteer, if so be we must flee from the son of Tydeus.  '),(1448,'I would not that they take fright and run wild, and for want of thy voice be not minded to bear us forth from the battle,  and so the son of great-souled Tydeus leap upon us and slay the two of us, and drive off the single-hooved horses.'),(1449,'  Nay, drive thou thyself thine own car and thine own horses, and I will abide this man\'s onset with my sharp spear.\" '),(1450,'So saying they mounted upon the inlaid car and  eagerly drave the swift horses against the son of Tydeus.  '),(1451,'And Sthenelus, the glorious son of Capaneus, saw them and straightway spake to Tydeus\' son winged words:\"'),(1452,'Diomedes, son of Tydeus, dear to my heart, I behold two valiant warriors eager to fight against thee,  endued with measureless strength. '),(1453,'The one is well skilled with the bow, even Pandarus, and moreover avoweth him to be the son of Lycaon;'),(1454,'while Aeneas avoweth himself to be born of peerless Anchises, and his mother is Aphrodite.'),(1455,'  Nay, come, let us give ground on the car, neither rage thou thus,  I pray thee, amid the foremost fighters, lest thou haply lose thy life.\"'),(1456,'Then with an angry glance from beneath his brows mighty Diomedes spake to him:'),(1457,'Talk not thou to me of flight, for I deem thou wilt not persuade me.'),(1458,'  Not in my blood is it to fight a skulking fight or to cower down; '),(1459,'still is my strength steadfast.'),(1460,'  And I have no mind to mount upon a car, but even as I am will I go to face them; '),(1461,'that I should quail Pallas Athene suffereth not.'),(1462,'  As for these twain, their swift horses shall not bear both back from us again, even if one or the other escape.'),(1463,'  And another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart.'),(1464,'  If so be Athene, rich in counsel, shall vouchsafe me this glory, to slay them both, then do thou hold here these swift horses, binding the reins taut to the chariot rim; but be mindful to rush upon the horses of Aeneas and drive them forth from the Trojans to the host of the well-greaved Achaeans.'),(1465,'  For they are of that stock wherefrom Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, gave to Tros recompense for his son Ganymedes, for that they were the best of all horses that are beneath the dawn and the sun.  Of this stock the king of men Anchises stole a breed, putting his mares to them while Laomedon knew naught thereof.'),(1466,'  And from these a stock of six was born him in his palace; '),(1467,'\nfour he kept himself and reared at the stall, and the other two he gave to Aeneas, devisers of rout.'),(1468,' Could we but take these twain, we should win us goodly renown.\"'),(1469,'Thus they spake on this wise one to the other,  and forthwith drew near those other twain, driving the swift horses.  '),(1470,'And Lycaon\'s glorious son spake first to him, saying:'),(1471,' \"Thou son of lordly Tydeus, stalwart and wise of heart, verily my swift shaft subdued thee not, the bitter arrow; '),(1472,' \"Thou son of lordly Tydeus, stalwart and wise of heart, verily my swift shaft subdued thee not, the bitter arrow; '),(1473,' \n  So saying, he poised and hurled his far-shadowing spear, and smote upon the shield of Tydeus\' son; and straight therethrough sped the point of bronze and reached the corselet.'),(1474,'and straight therethrough sped the point of bronze and reached the corselet.'),(1475,'  Then over him shouted aloud the glorious son of Lycaon:\"'),(1476,'Thou art smitten clean through the belly, and not for long, methinks,  shalt thou endure; '),(1477,'but to me hast thou granted great glory.'),(1478,'Then with no touch of fear spake to him mighty Diomedes:'),(1479,'Thou hast missed and not hit; '),(1480,'but ye twain, I deem, shall not cease till one or the other of you shall have fallen and glutted with his blood Ares, the warrior with tough shield of hide.\"'),(1481,'  So spake he and hurled; '),(1482,'and Athene guided the spear upon his nose beside the eye, and it pierced through his white teeth.'),(1483,'  So the stubborn bronze shore off his tongue at its root, and the spear-point came out by the base of the chin.   '),(1484,'Then he fell from out the car,  and his armour all bright and flashing clanged upon him, and the swift-footed horses swerved aside;'),(1485,'and there his spirit and his strength were undone.'),(1486,'But Aeneas leapt down with shield and long spear, seized with fear lest perchance the Achaeans might drag from him the dead man.  '),(1487,'Over him he strode like a lion confident in his strength, and before him he held his spear and his shield that was well balanced on every side,  eager to slay the man whosoever should come to seize the corpse, and crying a terrible cry.'),(1488,'  But the son of Tydeus grasped in his hand a stone—a mighty deed—one that not two men could bear, such as mortals now are; '),(1489,'yet lightly did he wield it even alone.'),(1490,'  Therewith he smote Aeneas on the hip, where the thigh turns in the hip joint,—the cup, men call it—'),(1491,'and crushed the cup-bone, and broke furthermore both sinews, and the jagged stone tore the skin away.'),(1492,'Then the warrior fell upon his knees'),(1493,'and thus abode, and with his stout hand leaned he  upon the earth'),(1494,'and dark night enfolded his eyes.'),(1495,'And now would the king of men, Aeneas, have perished, had not the daughter of Zeus, Aphrodite, been quick to mark, even his mother, that conceived him to Anchises as he tended his kine.'),(1496,'About her dear son she flung her white arms,  and before him she spread a fold of her bright garment to be a shelter against missiles, lest any of the Danaans with swift horses might hurl a spear of bronze into his breast and take away his life. '),(1497,'She then was bearing her dear son forth from out the battle;'),(1498,'but the son of Capaneus forgat not  the commands that Diomedes good at the war-cry laid upon him.  He held his own single-hooved horses away from the turmoil, binding the reins taut to the chariot rim, but rushed upon the fair-maned horses of Aeneas, and drave them forth from the Trojans into the host of the well-greaved Achaeans'),(1499,' and gave them to Deïpylus his dear comrade, whom he honoured above all the companions of his youth, because he was like-minded with himself; him he bade drive them to the hollow ships.'),(1500,'Then did the warrior mount his own car and take the bright reins, and straightway drive his stout-hooved horses in eager quest of Tydeus\' son.'),(1501,'  He the while had gone in pursuit of Cypris with his pitiless bronze, discerning that she was a weakling goddess, and not one of those that lord it in the battle of warriors,—no Athene she, nor Enyo, sacker of cities.  '),(1502,'But when he had come upon her as he pursued her through the great throng,  then the son of great-souled Tydeus thrust with his sharp spear and leapt upon her, and wounded the surface of her delicate hand, '),(1503,'and forthwith through the ambrosial raiment that the Graces themselves had wrought for her the spear pierced the flesh upon the wrist above the palm '),(1504,'and forth flowed the immortal blood of the goddess,  the ichor, such as floweth in the blessed gods'),(1505,'for they eat not bread neither drink flaming wine, wherefore they are bloodless, and are called immortals.'),(1506,'She then with a loud cry let fall her son'),(1507,'and Phoebus Apollo took him in his arms  and saved him in a dark cloud, lest any of the Danaans with swift horses might hurl a spear of bronze into his breast and take away his life.'),(1508,'  But over her shouted aloud Diomedes good at the war-cry:'),(1509,' \"Keep thee away, daughter of Zeus, from war and fighting.'),(1510,'  Sufficeth it not that thou beguilest weakling women?'),(1511,'  But if into battle thou wilt enter, verily methinks thou shalt shudder at the name thereof, if thou hearest it even from afar.\"'),(1512,'So spake he, and she departed frantic, and was sore distressed;'),(1513,'and wind-footed Iris took her and led her forth from out the throng, racked with pain, and her fair flesh was darkened.'),(1514,'  Anon she found furious Ares abiding on the left of the battle, '),(1515,'and upon a cloud was his spear leaning, and at hand were his swift horses twain.'),(1516,'Then she fell upon her knees and with instant prayer begged for her dear brother\'s horses with frontlets of gold:'),(1517,' \"Dear brother, save me, and give me thy horses,  that I may get me to Olympus, where is the abode of the immortals.  '),(1518,'For sorely am I pained with a wound which a mortal man dealt me, Tydeus\' son, that would now fight even with father Zeus.\" '),(1519,'So spake she, and Ares gave her his horses with frontlets of gold;'),(1520,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 5.364-5.366'),(1521,'from MILESTONE 365 to MILESTONE 370\n======================================================================\nStraightway then they came to the abode of the gods, to steep Olympus'),(1522,'and there wind-footed, swift Iris stayed the horses and loosed them from the car, and cast before them food ambrosial; '),(1523,' but fair Aphrodite flung herself upon the knees of her mother Dione.'),(1524,'She clasped her daughter in her arms, and stroked her with her hand and spake to her, saying: '),(1525,' \"Who now of the sons of heaven, dear child, hath entreated thee thus wantonly, as though thou wert working some evil before the face of all?\"'),(1526,'  To her then made answer laughter-loving Aphrodite: '),(1527,'\"Tydeus\' son, Diomedes high of heart, wounded me, for that I was bearing forth from out the war my dear son Aeneas, who is in my eyes far the dearest of all men.'),(1528,'  For no longer is the dread battle one between Trojans and Achaeans;  nay, the Danaans now fight even with the immortals.\"'),(1529,'To her then made answer Dione, the fair goddess:'),(1530,' \"Be of good heart, my child, and endure for all thy suffering; '),(1531,'for full many of us that have dwellings on Olympus have suffered at the hands of men, in bringing grievous woes one upon the other.'),(1532,'  So suffered Ares, when Otus and mighty Ephialtes, the sons of Aloeus, bound him in cruel bonds'),(1533,'and in a brazen jar he lay bound for thirteen months;'),(1534,'and then would Ares, insatiate of war, have perished, had not the stepmother of the sons of Aloeus, the beauteous Eëriboea,  brought tidings unto Hermes;'),(1535,'and he stole forth Ares, that was now sore distressed, for his grievous bonds were overpowering him.'),(1536,'So suffered Hera, when the mighty son of Amphitryon smote her on the right breast with a three-barbed arrow; then upon her too came pain that might in no wise be assuaged.'),(1537,'then upon her too came pain that might in no wise be assuaged.'),(1538,'  And so suffered monstrous Hades even as the rest a bitter arrow, when this same man, the son of Zeus that beareth the aegis, smote him in Pylos amid the dead, and gave him over to pains.'),(1539,'  But he went to the house of Zeus and to high Olympus with grief at heart, pierced through with pains; '),(1540,'  But he went to the house of Zeus and to high Olympus with grief at heart, pierced through with pains; '),(1541,'But Paeëon spread thereon simples that slay pain, and healed him;'),(1542,'for verily he was in no wise of mortal mould.'),(1543,'Rash man, worker of violence, that recked not of his evil deeds, seeing that with his arrows he vexed the gods that hold Olympus.'),(1544,'Rash man, worker of violence, that recked not of his evil deeds, seeing that with his arrows he vexed the gods that hold Olympus.'),(1545,'Rash man, worker of violence, that recked not of his evil deeds, seeing that with his arrows he vexed the gods that hold Olympus.'),(1546,'  Wherefore now let Tydeus\' son, for all he is so mighty, beware lest one better than thou fight against him, lest in sooth Aegialeia, the daughter of Adrastus, passing wise, wake from sleep with her long lamentings all her household, as she wails for her wedded husband, the best man of the Achaeans, even she, '),(1547,'She spake, and with both her hands wiped the ichor from the arm;'),(1548,' the arm was restored, and the grievous pains assuaged.'),(1549,'  But Athene and Hera, as they looked upon her, sought to anger Zeus, son of Cronos, with mocking words.'),(1550,'  But Athene and Hera, as they looked upon her, sought to anger Zeus, son of Cronos, with mocking words.'),(1551,'  And among them the goddess flashing-eyed Athene was first to speak: \"Father Zeus, wilt thou anywise be wroth with me for the word that I shall say?'),(1552,'Of a surety now Cypris has been urging some one of the women of Achaea to follow after the Trojans, whom now she so wondrously loveth; and while stroking such a one of the fair-robed women of Achaea,  she hath scratched upon her golden brooch her delicate hand.\"'),(1553,'So spake she, but the father of men and gods smiled, and calling to him golden Aphrodite, said:'),(1554,' \"Not unto thee, my child, are given works of war; nay, follow thou after the lovely works of marriage,  and all these things shall be the business of swift Ares and Athene.\"'),(1555,'On this wise spake they one to the other; but Diomedes, good at the war-cry, leapt upon Aeneas, though well he knew that Apollo himself held forth his arms above him; '),(1556,'yet had he no awe even of the great god, but was still eager  to slay Aeneas and strip from him his glorious armour. '),(1557,'Thrice then he leapt upon him, furiously fain to slay him, and thrice did Apollo beat back his shining shield.'),(1558,'  But when for the fourth time he rushed upon him like a god, then with a terrible cry spake to him Apollo that worketh afar:'),(1559,'  \"Bethink thee, son of Tydeus, and give place, neither be thou minded to be like of spirit with the gods; seeing in no wise of like sort is the race of immortal gods and that of men who walk upon the earth.\"'),(1560,'So spake he, and the son of Tydeus gave ground a scant space backward, avoiding the wrath of Apollo that smiteth afar.'),(1561,'  Aeneas then did Apollo set apart from the throng in sacred Pergamus where was his temple builded.'),(1562,'  There Leto and the archer Artemis healed him in the great sanctuary, and glorified him;'),(1563,' but Apollo of the silver bow fashioned a wraith  in the likeness of Aeneas\' self and in armour like to his; and over the wraith the Trojans and goodly Achaeans smote the bull\'s-hide bucklers about one another\'s breasts, the round shields and fluttering targets.'),(1564,' Then unto furious Ares spake Phoebus Apollo:'),(1565,'  \"Ares, Ares, thou bane of mortals, thou blood-stained stormer of walls, wilt thou not now enter into the battle and withdraw this man therefrom, this son of Tydeus, who now would fight even against father Zeus?'),(1566,'  Cypris first hath he wounded in close fight on the hand at the wrist, and thereafter rushed he upon mine own self like unto a god.\" '),(1567,'  So spake he, and himself sate him down upon the height of Pergamus, and baneful Ares entered amid the Trojans\' ranks and urged them on, in the likeness of swft Acamas, leader of the Thracians.'),(1568,'To Priam\'s sons, nurtured of Zeus, he called, saying:'),(1569,' \"Ye sons of Priam, the king nurtured of Zeus,  how long will ye still suffer your host to be slain by the Achaeans?'),(1570,'Shall it be until such time as they fight about our well-built gates?'),(1571,'   Low lieth a man whom we honoured even as goodly Hector, Aeneas, son of great-hearted Anchises.'),(1572,' Nay, come, let us save from out the din of conflict our noble comrade.\"'),(1573,'  So saying he aroused the strength and spirit of every man.'),(1574,'  And Sarpedon moreover sternly chid goodly Hector, saying:\"'),(1575,'Hector, where now is the strength gone that aforetime thou hadst?  '),(1576,'Thou saidst forsooth that without hosts and allies thou wouldst hold the city alone with the aid of thy sisters\' husbands and thy brothers; '),(1577,' howbeit of these can I now neither behold nor mark anyone, but they cower as dogs about a lion; '),(1578,'and it is we that fight, we that are but allies among you.'),(1579,'  For I that am but an ally am come from very far; '),(1580,'afar is Lycia by eddying Xanthus,  where I left my dear wife and infant son, and my great wealth the which every man that is in lack coveteth.'),(1581,'  Yet even so urge I on the Lycians, and am fain myself to fight my man, '),(1582,'though here is naught of mine such as the Achaeans might bear away or drive'),(1583,' whereas thou standest and dost not even urge thy hosts to abide and defend their wives.'),(1584,'  Beware lest thou and they, as if caught in the meshes of all-ensnaring flax, become a prey and spoil unto your foemen; and they shall anon lay waste your well-peopled city.'),(1585,'  On thee should all these cares rest by night and day, '),(1586,' and thou shouldest beseech the captains of thy far-famed allies to hold their ground unflinchingly, and so put away from thee strong rebukings.\" '),(1587,'So spake Sarpedon, and his word stung Hector to the heart.  '),(1588,'Forthwith he leapt in his armour from his chariot to the ground,  and brandishing his two sharp spears went everywhere throughout the host, urging men to fight, and roused the dread din of battle.'),(1589,'  So they rallied and took their stand with their faces towards the Achaeans; '),(1590,'and the Argives in close throng abode their coming and fled not.'),(1591,' And even as the wind carrieth chaff about the sacred threshing-floors  of men that are winnowing, when fair-haired Demeter amid the driving blasts of wind separates the grain from the chaff, and the heaps of chaff grow white; '),(1592,'even so now did the Achaeans grow white over head and shoulders beneath the cloud of dust that through the midst of the warriors the hooves of their horses beat up to the brazen heaven, as the fight was joined again'),(1593,' and the charioteers wheeled round.'),(1594,'  The might of their hands they bare straight forward'),(1595,'and about the battle furious Ares drew a veil of night to aid the Trojans, ranging everywhere; '),(1596,'so fulfilled he the behest of Phoebus Apollo of the golden sword, who bade him  rouse the spirit of the Trojans, whenso he saw that Pallas Athene was departed;'),(1597,'  for she it was that bare aid to the Danaans.'),(1598,'And Apollo himself sent Aeneas forth from out the rich sanctuary, and put courage in the breast of the shepherd of the host.'),(1599,' And Aeneas took his place in the midst of his comrades'),(1600,'and these waxed glad  as they saw him come to join them alive and whole and possessed of valiant courage.'),(1601,'  Howbeit they questioned him not at all'),(1602,'for toil of other sort forbade them, even that which he of the silver bow was stirring, and Ares the bane of mortals, and Discord that rageth without ceasing.'),(1603,'On the other side the Aiantes twain and Odysseus and Diomedes  roused the Danaans to fight;'),(1604,'yet these even of themselves quailed not before the Trojans\' violence and their onsets, but stood their ground like mists that in still weather the son of Cronos setteth on the mountain-tops moveless, what time the might of the North Wind sleepeth and of the other furious winds  that blow with shrill blasts and scatter this way and that the shadowy clouds; '),(1605,'even so the Danaans withstood the Trojans steadfastly, and fled not.'),(1606,'  And the son of Atreus ranged throughout the throng with many a word of command:'),(1607,' \"My friends, be men, and take to you hearts of valour, and have shame each of the other in the fierce conflict.'),(1608,'Of men that have shame more are saved than are slain,'),(1609,'but from them that flee cometh neither glory nor any avail.\" '),(1610,' \nHe spake, and hurled his spear swiftly and smote a foremost warrior, a comrade of great-souled Aeneas, Deïcoön,  son of Pergasus, whom the Trojans honoured even as the sons of Priam, for that he was swift to fight amid the foremost.'),(1611,'Him did lord Agamemnon smite with his spear upon the shield'),(1612,'and this stayed not the spear, but clean through it passed the bronze, and into the lower belly he drave it through the belt; '),(1613,' and he fell with a thud, and upon him his armour clanged.'),(1614,'Then Aeneas slew two champions of the Danaans, the sons of Diocles, Crethon and Orsilochus, whose father dwelt in well-built Pheme, a man rich in substance, and in lineage was he sprung from the river  Alpheius that flows in broad stream through the land of the Pylians, and that begat Orsilochus to be king over many men.'),(1615,'  And Orsilochus begat greatsouled Diocles, and of Diocles were born twin sons, Crethon and Orsilochus, well skilled in all manner of fighting.'),(1616,'  Now when the twain had reached manhood, they followed with the Argives on the black ships to Ilios famed for its horses, seeking to win recompense for the sons of Atreus, Agamemnon and Menelaus'),(1617,'but their own selves in that land did the doom of death enfold.'),(1618,'  Like them two lions upon the mountain tops  are reared by their dam in the thickets of a deep wood; '),(1619,'and the twain snatch cattle and goodly sheep and make havoc of the farmsteads of men, until themuselves are slain by the hands of men with the sharp bronze;'),(1620,' even in such wise were these twain vanquished beneath the hands of Aeneas, and fell like tall fir-trees.'),(1621,'  But as they fell Menelaus dear to Ares had pity for them, and strode through the foremost fighters, harnessed in flaming bronze and brandishing his spear; and Ares roused his might with intent that he might be vanquished beneath the hands of Aeneas.'),(1622,'and Ares roused his might with intent that he might be vanquished beneath the hands of Aeneas.'),(1623,'  But Antilochus, son of great-souled Nestor, beheld him, and strode through the foremost fighters; '),(1624,'for greatly did he fear for the shepherd of the host, lest aught befall him, and he utterly thwart them of their toil.'),(1625,'  Now the twain were holding forth their hands and their sharp spears each against the other, fain to do battle,'),(1626,' when Antilochus came close beside the shepheard of the host.'),(1627,'Then Aeneas abode not, swift warrior though he was, when he beheld the two holding their ground side by side;'),(1628,'and they, when they had dragged the dead to the host of the Achaeans, laid the hapless pair in the arms of their comrades, '),(1629,' \nThen the twain slew Pylaemenes, peer of Ares, the leader of the great-souled Paphlagonian shieldmen.'),(1630,'  Him as he stood still, the son of Atreus, spear-famed Menelaus, pierced with his spear, smiting him upon the collar-bone;'),(1631,'  and Antilochus made a cast at Mydon, his squire and charioteer, the goodly son of Atymnius'),(1632,'even as he was turning the single-hooved horses,'),(1633,'and smote him with a stone full upon the elbow;'),(1634,'and the reins, white with ivory, fell from his hands to the ground in the dust.'),(1635,' Then Antilochus leapt upon him and drave his sword into his temple'),(1636,' and gasping he fell forth from out the well-built car headlong in the dust on his head and shoulders.'),(1637,'—for he lighted on deep sand—.'),(1638,'—for he lighted on deep sand—.'),(1639,'until his horses kicked him and cast him to the ground in the dust;'),(1640,'and them Antilochus lashed, and drave into the host of the Achaeans.'),(1641,'  But Hector marked them across the ranks, and rushed upon them shouting aloud'),(1642,'and with him followed the strong battalions of the Trojans; '),(1643,'and Ares led them and the queen Enyo, she bringing ruthless Din of War, while Ares wielded in his hands a monstrous spear,  and ranged now in front of Hector and now behind him.'),(1644,'At sight of him Diomedes, good at the war-cry shuddered;'),(1645,'and even as a man in passing over a great plain halteth in dismay at a swift-streaming river that floweth on to the sea, and seeing it seething with foam starteth backward,  even so now did the son of Tydeus give ground, and he spake to the host:\"'),(1646,'Friends, look you how we were ever wont to marvel at goodly Hector, deeming him a spearman and a dauntless warrior;'),(1647,'whereas ever by his side is some god that wardeth from him ruin'),(1648,' even as now Ares is by his side in the likeness of a mortal man.'),(1649,'  But with faces turned toward the Trojans give ye ground ever backwards, neither rage ye to fight amain with gods.\"'),(1650,'So spake he, and the Trojans came very close to them.'),(1651,'  Then Hector slew two warriors well skilled in fight, Menesthes and Anchialus, the twain being in one car.'),(1652,'  And as they fell great Telamonian Aias had pity of them'),(1653,'and came and stood close at hand, and with a cast of his shining spear smote Amphius, son of Selagus, that dwelt in Paesus, a man rich in substance, rich in corn-land; '),(1654,'but fate led him to bear aid to Priam and his sons.'),(1655,'  Him Telamonian Aias smote upon the belt, and in the lower belly was the far-shadowing spear fixed, and he fell with a thud.'),(1656,'  Then glorious Aias rushed upon him to strip him of his armour'),(1657,'and the Trojans rained upon him their spears, all sharp and gleaming'),(1658,'and his shield caught many thereof.'),(1659,'  But he planted his heel upon the corpse and drew forth the spear of bronze, '),(1660,'yet could he not prevail likewise to strip the rest of the fair armour from his shoulders'),(1661,'for he was sore pressed with missiles.'),(1662,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 5.623-5.626'),(1663,'from MILESTONE 620 to MILESTONE 626\n======================================================================\nand he gave ground and was made to reel. '),(1664,'So these toiled in the mighty conflict'),(1665,'but Tlepolemus, son of Heracles, a valiant man and tall, was roused by resistless fate against godlike Sarpedon.'),(1666,'  And when they were come near as they advanced one against the other, the son and grandson of Zeus the cloud-gatherer, then Tlepolemus was first to speak, saying:'),(1667,' \"Sarpedon, counsellor of the Lycians, why must thou be skulking here, that art a man unskilled in battle?'),(1668,'  They speak but a lie that say thou art sprung from Zeus that beareth the aegis, seeing thou art inferior far to those warriors that were sprung from Zeus in the days of men of old.'),(1669,'Of other sort, men say, was mighty Heracles, my father, staunch in fight, the lionhearted, '),(1670,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 5.640-5.642'),(1671,'but yours is the heart of coward and your people are dying.'),(1672,'In no wise methinks shall thy coming from Lycia prove a defence to the men of Troy,  though thou be never so strong, but thou shalt be vanquished by my hand and pass the gates of Hades.'),(1673,'And to him Sarpedon, captain of the Lycians, made answer:'),(1674,'\"Tlepolemus, thy sire verily destroyed sacred Ilios through the folly of the lordly man, Laomedon,  who chid with harsh words him that had done him good service, and rendered him not the mares for the sake of which he had come from afar.'),(1675,' But for thee, I deem that death and black fate shall here be wrought by my hands, and that vanquished beneath my spear thou shalt yield glory to me, and thy soul to Hades of the goodly steeds.\"'),(1676,'  So spake Sarpedon, and Tlepolemus lifted on high his ashen spear,'),(1677,'and the long spears sped from the hands of both at one moment.'),(1678,'  Sarpedon smote him full upon the neck, and the grievous point passed clean through, '),(1679,'and down upon his eyes came the darkness of night and enfolded him.'),(1680,'  And Tlepolemus smote Sarpedon upon the left thigh with his long spear, and the point sped through furiously and grazed the bone; howbeit his father as yet warded from him destruction.'),(1681,'Then his goodly companions bare godlike Sarpedon forth from out the fight'),(1682,'and the long spear burdened him sore,  as it trailed,'),(1683,' but no man marked it or thought in their haste to draw forth from his thigh the spear of ash, that he might stand upon his feet; '),(1684,'such toil had they in tending him. '),(1685,' And on the other side the well-greaved Achaeans bare Tlepolemus from out the fight,.'),(1686,' and goodly Odysseus  of the enduring soul was ware of it, and his spirit waxed furious within him;'),(1687,' and he pondered then in heart and soul whether he should pursue further after the son of Zeus that thundereth aloud, or should rather take the lives of more Lycians.'),(1688,' But not for great-hearted Odysseus was it ordained  to slay with the sharp bronze the valiant son of Zeus; '),(1689,'wherefore Athene turned his mind toward the host of the Lycians.'),(1690,'  Then slew he Coeranus and Alastor and Chromius and Alcandrus and Halius and Noëmon and Prytanis; '),(1691,'and yet more of the Lycians would goodly Odysseus have slain,  but that great Hector of the flashing helm was quick to see '),(1692,'and strode through the foremost fighters harnessed in flaming bronze, bringing terror to the Danaans.'),(1693,'  Then glad at his coming was Sarpedon, son of Zeus, and spake to him a piteous word:'),(1694,'\"Son of Priam, suffer me not to lie here a prey to the Danaans, but bear me aid;'),(1695,'thereafter, if need be, let life depart from me in your city, seeing it might not be that I should return home to mine own native land to make glad my dear wife and infant son.\"'),(1696,'So spake he, yet Hector of the flashing helm spake no word in answer,  but hastened by, eager with all speed to thrust back the Argives and take the lives of many.'),(1697,'Then his goodly comrades made godlike Sarpedon to sit beneath a beauteous oak of Zeus that beareth the aegis, '),(1698,'  and forth from his thigh valiant Pelagon, that was his dear comrade, thrust the spear of ash;'),(1699,' and his spirit failed him, and down over his eyes a mist was shed.'),(1700,'  Howbeit he revived, and the breath of the North Wind as it blew upon him made him to live again after in grievous wise he had breathed forth his spirit.'),(1701,'But the Argives before the onset of Ares and Hector harnessed in bronze  neither turned them to make for the black ships, nor yet could they hold out in fight, but they ever gave ground backward, when they heard that Ares was amid the Trojans.'),(1702,'Who then was first to be slain and who last by Hector, Priam\'s son, and brazen Ares?'),(1703,'  Godlike Teuthras, and thereafter Orestes, driver of horses, Trechus, spearman of Aetolia, and Oenomaus, and Helenus, son of Oenops, and Oresbius with flashing taslet, he that dwelt in Hyle on the border of the Cephisian mere, having great care of his wealth; '),(1704,'and beside him other men of Boiotia lived and held the fine fertile country.'),(1705,'But when the goddess, white-armed Hera, was ware of them as they made havoc of the Argives in the fierce conflict, forthwith she spake winged words to Athene:'),(1706,'\"Out upon it, thou child of Zeus that beareth the aegis, unwearied one,  verily it was for naught that we pledged our word to Menelaus, that not until he had sacked well-walled Ilios should he get him home, if we are to suffer baneful Ares thus to rage.'),(1707,'  Nay, come, let us twain likewise bethink us of furious valour.\"'),(1708,'\nSo spake she, and the goddess, flashing-eyed Athene, failed not to hearken.'),(1709,'  Then Hera, the queenly goddess, daughter of great Cronos, went to and fro harnessing the horses of golden frontlets.'),(1710,' and Hebe quickly put to the car on either side the curved wheels of bronze, eight-spoked, about the iron axle-tree.'),(1711,' Of these the felloe verily is of gold imperishable,  and thereover are tires of bronze fitted, a marvel to behold; '),(1712,'and the naves are of silver, revolving on this side and on that;'),(1713,'and the body is plaited tight with gold and silver thongs, and two rims there are that run about it.'),(1714,'  From the body stood forth the pole of silver'),(1715,'and on the end  thereof she bound the fair golden yoke, and cast thereon the fair golden breast-straps;'),(1716,'and Hera led beneath the yoke the swift-footed horses, and was eager for strife and the war-cry.'),(1717,'But Athene, daughter of Zeus that beareth the aegis, let fall upon her father\'s floor her soft robe,  richly broidered, that herself had wrought and her hands had fashioned'),(1718,'and put on her the tunic of Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, and arrayed her in armour for tearful war.'),(1719,'About her shoulders she flung the tasselled aegis, fraught with terror, all about which Rout is set as a crown,  and therein is Strife, therein Valour, and therein Onset, that maketh the blood run cold, and therein is the head of the dread monster, the Gorgon, dread and awful, a portent of Zeus that beareth the aegis.'),(1720,'  And upon her head she set the helmet with two horns and with bosses four, wrought of gold, and fitted with the men-at-arms of an hundred cities.'),(1721,'  Then she stepped upon the flaming car and grasped her spear, heavy and huge and strong, wherewith she vanquisheth the ranks of men—of warriors with whom she is wroth, she, the daughter of the mighty sire.'),(1722,'  And Hera swiftly touched the horses with the lash'),(1723,'and self-bidden groaned upon their hinges the gates of heaven which the Hours had in their keeping,  to whom are entrusted great heaven and Olympus, whether to throw open the thick cloud or shut it to.'),(1724,'There through the gate they drave their horses patient of the goad;'),(1725,'  There through the gate they drave their horses patient of the goad; and they found the son of Cronos as he sat apart from the other gods on the topmost peak of many-ridged Olympus.'),(1726,'  Then the goddess, white-armed Hera, stayed the horses, and made question of Zeus most high, the son of Cronos, and spake to him:'),(1727,'\"Father Zeus, hast thou no indignation with Ares for these violent deeds, that he hath destroyed so great and so goodly a host of the Achaeans recklessly and in no seemly wise to my sorrow;  while at their ease Cypris and Apollo of the silver bow take their joy, having set on this madman that regardeth not any law?'),(1728,'  Father Zeus, wilt thou in any wise be wroth with me if I smite Ares in sorry fashion and drive him out of the battle?\" '),(1729,' \nThen in answer spake to her Zeus, the cloud-gatherer:'),(1730,'  \"Nay, come now, rouse against him Athene, driver of the spoil, who has ever been wont above others to bring sore pain upon him.\"'),(1731,'So spake he, and the goddess, white-armed Hera, failed not to hearken, but touched her horses with the the lash'),(1732,'and nothing loath the pair flew on between earth and starry heaven.'),(1733,'  As far as a man seeth with his eyes into the haze of distance as he sitteth on a place of outlook and gazeth over the wine-dark deep, even so far do the loud-neighing horses of the gods spring at a bound.'),(1734,'But when they were come to the land of Troy and the two flowing rivers, where the Simoïs and Scamander join their streams,  there the goddess, white-armed Hera, stayed her horses, and loosed them from the car, and shed thick mist about them;'),(1735,'and Simoïs made ambrosia to spring up for them to graze upon.'),(1736,'\nThen the goddesses twain went their way with steps like those of timorous doves, eager to bring aid to the Argive warriors.'),(1737,'  And when they were come where the most and the bravest stood close thronging about mighty Diomedes, tamer of horses, in semblance like ravening lions or wild boars, whose is no weakling strength, there the goddess, white-armed Hera,  stood and shouted in the likeness of great-hearted Stentor of the brazen voice, whose voice is as the voice of fifty other men:'),(1738,' \"Fie, ye Argives, base things of shame fair in semblance only!'),(1739,'  So long as goodly Achilles was wont to fare into battle, never would the Trojans come forth even before the Dardanian gate; '),(1740,' for of his mighty spear had they dread;'),(1741,'but now far from the city they are fighting at the hollow ships.\" '),(1742,'So saying she roused the strength and spirit of every man.'),(1743,'  And to the side of Tydeus\' son sprang the goddess, flashing-eyed Athene.'),(1744,'  She found that prince beside his horses and car,  cooling the wound that Pandarus had dealt him with his arrow.'),(1745,'For the sweat vexed him beneath the broad baldric of his round shield;'),(1746,'  For the sweat vexed him beneath the broad baldric of his round shield; therewith was he vexed and his arm grew weary, so he was lifting up the baldric and wiping away the dark blood.'),(1747,'  Then the goddess laid hold of the yoke of his horses, and said:'),(1748,'  \"Verily little like himself was the son that Tydeus begat.'),(1749,' Tydeus was small in stature, but a warrior.'),(1750,'  Even when I would not suffer him to fight or make a show of prowess, what time he came, and no Achaean with him, on an embassage to Thebes into the midst of the many Cadmeians—  I bade him feast in their halls in peace—yet he having his valiant soul as of old challenged the youths of the Cadmeians and vanquished them in everything full easily;  so               \' present a helper was I to him.'),(1751,' I bade him feast in their halls in peace—'),(1752,'yet he having his valiant soul as of old challenged the youths of the Cadmeians and vanquished them in everything full easily;  '),(1753,'so present a helper was I to him. '),(1754,'But as for thee, I verily stand by thy side and guard thee,  and of a ready heart I bid thee fight with the Trojans,'),(1755,'yet either hath weariness born of thy many onsets entered into thy limbs, or haply spiritless terror possesseth thee.'),(1756,'  Then art thou no offspring of Tydeus, the wise-hearted son of Oeneus.\"'),(1757,'Then in answer to her spake mighty Diomedes:.'),(1758,' \"I know thee, daughter of Zeus that beareth the aegis;'),(1759,'therefore with a ready heart will I tell thee my thought and hide it not.'),(1760,'  In no wise doth spiritless terror possess me nor any slackness, but I am still mindful of thy behest which thou didst lay upon me.'),(1761,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 5.819-5.820'),(1762,'  Thou wouldest not suffer me to fight face to face with the other blessed gods, ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 819 to line 821'),(1763,'  Therefore it is that I now give ground myself and have given command to all the rest of the Argives to be gathered here likewise; for I discern Ares lording it over the battle-field.\"'),(1764,'for I discern Ares lording it over the battle-field.'),(1765,'  And the goddess, flashing-eyed Athene, answered him, saying:'),(1766,'\"Son of Tydeus, Diomedes, dear to my heart, fear thou not Ares for that, neither any other of the immortals; so present a helper am I to thee.  '),(1767,'Nay, come, at Ares first drive thou thy single-hooved horses,  and smite him in close fight, neither have thou awe of furious Ares that raveth here a full-wrought bane, a renegade, that but now spake with me and Hera, and made as though he would fight against the Trojans but give aid to the Argives; yet now he consorteth with the Trojans and hath forgotten these.\" '),(1768,'  So saying, with her hand she drew back Sthenelus, and thrust him from the car to earth, and he speedily leapt down; '),(1769,'and she stepped upon the car beside goodly Diomedes, a goddess eager for battle.'),(1770,' Loudly did the oaken axle creak beneath its burden, for it bare a dread goddess and a peerless warrior.  '),(1771,'for it bare a dread goddess and a peerless warrior.  '),(1772,' Then Pallas Athene grasped the lash and the reins,'),(1773,'and against Ares first she speedily drave the single-hooved horses.'),(1774,'  He was stripping of his armour huge Periphas that was far the best of the Aetolians, the glorious son of Ochesius.'),(1775,'  Him was blood-stained Ares stripping; '),(1776,'but Athene  put on the cap of Hades, to the end that mighty Ares should not see her.'),(1777,'Now when Ares, the bane of mortals, was ware of goodly Diomedes, he let be huge Periphas to lie where he was, even where at the first he had slain him and taken away his life but made straight for Diomedes, tamer of horses.'),(1778,'  And when they were now come near as they advanced one against the other, Ares first let drive over the yoke and the reins of the horses with his spear of bronze, eager to take away the other\'s life; '),(1779,'but the spear the goddess, flashing-eyed Athene, caught in her hand and thrust above the car to fly its way in vain.'),(1780,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 5.855-5.856'),(1781,'  Next Diomedes, good at the war-cry, drave at Ares with his spear of bronze, ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 855 to line 857'),(1782,' There did he thrust and smite him, rending the fair flesh, and forth he drew the spear again.  '),(1783,'Then brazen Ares bellowed  loud as nine thousand warriors or ten thousand cry in battle, when they join in the strife of the War-god; '),(1784,'and thereat trembling came upon Achaeans alike and Trojans, and fear gat hold of them;'),(1785,'so mightily bellowed Ares insatiate of war. '),(1786,'Even as a black darkness appeareth from the clouds  when after heat a blustering wind ariseth, even in such wise unto Diomedes, son of Tydeus, did brazen Ares appear, as he fared amid the clouds unto broad heaven.  '),(1787,'Speedily he came to the abode of the gods, to steep Olympus, and sate him down by the side of Zeus, son of Cronos, grieved at heart, and shewed the immortal blood flowing from the wound,  and with wailing spake to him winged words:'),(1788,' \"Father Zeus, hast thou no indignation to behold these violent deeds?'),(1789,'  Ever do we gods continually suffer most cruelly by one another\'s devices, whenas we show favour to men.'),(1790,'  Ever do we gods continually suffer most cruelly by one another\'s devices, whenas we show favour to men.'),(1791,' for thou art father to that mad and baneful maid, whose mind is ever set on deeds of lawlessness.'),(1792,' For all the other gods that are in Olympus are obedient unto thee, and subject to thee, each one of us; but to her thou payest no heed whether in word or in deed, '),(1793,'but to her thou payest no heed whether in word or in deed,  but rather settest her on, for that this pestilent maiden is thine own child.'),(1794,'Now hath she set on the son of Tydeus, Diomedes high of heart, to vent his rage upon immortal gods.'),(1795,'  Cypris first he wounded with a thrust in close fight upon the hand at the wrist, and thereafter rushed upon mine own self as he had been a god.'),(1796,'  Howbeit my swift feet bare  me away;'),(1797,' otherwise had I long suffered woes there amid the gruesome heaps of the dead, or else had lived strengthless by reason of the smitings of the spear.\"'),(1798,'Then with an angry glance from beneath his brows spake to him Zeus, the cloud-gatherer:\"'),(1799,'Sit thou not in any wise by me and whine, thou renegade..'),(1800,'  Most hateful to me art thou of all gods that hold Olympus,'),(1801,' for ever is strife dear to thee and wars and fightings.'),(1802,'  Thou hast the unbearable, unyielding spirit of thy mother, even of Hera; '),(1803,'her can I scarce control by my words.'),(1804,'  Wherefore it is by her promptings, meseems, that thou sufferest thus.'),(1805,'  Howbeit I will no longer endure that thou shouldest be in pain, for thou art mine offspring, and it was to me that thy mother bare  thee; '),(1806,'for thou art mine offspring, and it was to me that thy mother bare thee;'),(1807,'but wert thou born of any other god, thus pestilent as thou art, then long ere this hadst thou been lower than the sons of heaven.\" '),(1808,'He spake, and bade Paeëon heal his hurt;.'),(1809,' and Paeëon spread thereon simples that slay pain, and healed him;'),(1810,'for verily he was in no wise of mortal mould.'),(1811,'  Even as the juice of the fig speedily maketh to grow thick the white milk that is liquid, but is quickly curdled as a man stirreth it, even so swiftly healed he furious Ares.'),(1812,'  And Hebe bathed him, and clad him in beautiful raiment, '),(1813,'and he sate him down by the side of Zeus, son of Cronos, exulting in his glory.'),(1814,'\nThen back to the palace of great Zeus fared Argive Hera and Alalcomenean Athene, when they had made Ares, the bane of mortals, to cease from his man-slaying.'),(1815,' So was the dread strife of the Trojans and Achaeans left to itself, '),(1816,'and oft to this side and to that surged the battle over the plain, as they aimed one at the other their bronze-tipped spears between the Simoïs and the streams of Xanthus.'),(1817,'  Aias, son of Telamon, bulwark of the Achaeans was first to break a battalion of the Trojans, and to bring a light of deliverance to his comrades, for he smote a man that was chiefest among the Thracians, even Eüssorus\' son Acamas, a valiant man and tall. '),(1818,'Him he was first to smite upon the horn of his helmet with thick crest of horse-hair,  and drave the spear into his forehead so that the point of bronze pierced within the bone; '),(1819,'and darkness enfolded his eyes.'),(1820,'And Diomedes, good at the war-cry, slew Axylus, Teuthras\' son, that dwelt in well-built Arisbe, a man rich in substance, that was beloved of all men; '),(1821,' for he dwelt in a home by the high-road and was wont to give entertainment to all. '),(1822,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 6.16-6.19'),(1823,'so they two passed beneath the earth.'),(1824,'  Then Euryalus slew Dresus and Opheltius'),(1825,'and went on after Aesepus and Pedasus, whom on a time the fountain-nymph Abarbarea bare to peerless Bucolion.'),(1826,'  Now Bucolion was son of lordly Laomedon, his eldest born, though the mother that bare him was unwed; '),(1827,' he while shepherding his flocks lay with the nymph in love, and she conceived and bare twin sons.'),(1828,'  Of these did the son of Mecisteus loose the might and the glorious limbs and strip the armour from their shoulders.'),(1829,'And Polypoetes staunch in fight slew Astyalus, '),(1830,' and Odysseus with his spear of bronze laid low Pidytes of Percote, and Teucer goodly Aretaon.'),(1831,' And Antilochus, son of Nestor, slew Ablerus with his bright spear, and the king of men, Agamemnon, '),(1832,'slew Elatus that dwelt in steep Pedasus by the banks of fair-flowing Satnioeis.'),(1833,'  And the warrior Leïtus slew Phylacus, as he fled before him; '),(1834,'and Eurypylus laid Melanthius low. '),(1835,'But Adrastus did Menelaus, good at the warcry, take alive; '),(1836,'for his two horses, coursing in terror over the plain, became entangled in a tamarisk bough, and breaking the curved car at the end of the pole,  themselves went on toward the city whither the rest were fleeing in rout; but their master rolled from out the car beside the wheel headlong in the dust upon his face.'),(1837,'  And to his side came Menelaus, son of Atreus, bearing  his far-shadowing spear.'),(1838,'  Then Adrastus clasped him by the knees and besought him:'),(1839,'\"Take me alive, thou son of Atreus, and accept a worthy ransom;'),(1840,' treasures full many lie stored in the palace of my wealthy father, bronze and gold and iron wrought with toil; thereof would my father grant thee ransom past counting,  should he hear that I am alive at the ships of the Achaeans.\"'),(1841,'So spake he, and sought to persuade the other\'s heart in his breast,'),(1842,'and lo, Menelaus was about to give him to his squire to lead to the swift ships of the Achaeans, '),(1843,'but Agamemnon came running to meet him, and spake a word of reproof, saying:'),(1844,'  \"Soft-hearted Menelaus, why carest thou thus for the men?'),(1845,'  Hath then so great kindness been done thee in thy house by Trojans?'),(1846,'  Of them let not one escape sheer destruction and the might of our hands, nay, not the man-child whom his mother bears in her womb; let not even him escape,  but let all perish together out of Ilios, unmourned and unmarked.\"'),(1847,'So spake the warrior, and turned his brother\'s mind, for he counselled aright; '),(1848,'so Menelaus with his hand thrust from him the warrior Adrastus, '),(1849,'and lord Agamemnon smote him on the flank, and he fell backward;'),(1850,'and the son of Atreus  planted his heel on his chest, and drew forth the ashen spear.  '),(1851,'Then Nestor shouted aloud, and called to the Argives:'),(1852,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 6.67-6.70'),(1853,' \"My friends, Danaan warriors, squires of Ares, let no man now abide behind in eager desire for spoil, that he may come to the ships bearing the greatest store;  nay, let us slay the men; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 67 to line 71'),(1854,'So saying he aroused the strength and spirit of every man. '),(1855,'Then would the Trojans have been driven again by the Achaeans dear to Ares up to Ilios, vanquished in their weakness,  had not the son of Priam, Helenus, far the best of augurs, come up to Aeneas and Hector, and said to them:'),(1856,' \"Aeneas and Hector, seeing that upon you above all others rests the war-toil of Trojans and Lycians, for that in every undertaking ye are the best both in war and in counsel,  hold ye your ground, and go ye this way and that throughout the host and keep them back before the gates, or ever in flight they fling themselves in their women\'s arms, and be made a joy to their foemen.'),(1857,'But when ye have aroused all our battalions, we verily will abide here and fight against the Danaans,  sore wearied though we be, '),(1858,'for necessity weighs hard upon us;'),(1859,'but do thou, Hector, go thy way to the city and speak there to her that is thy mother and mine;'),(1860,'let her gather the aged wives to the temple of flashing-eyed Athene in the citadel, and when she has opened with the key the doors of the holy house,  the robe that seemeth to her the fairest and amplest in her hall, and that is far dearest to her own self, this let her lay upon the knees of fair-haired Athene, and vow to her that she will sacrifice in her temple twelve sleek heifers that have not felt the goad, if she will have compassion  on the city and the Trojan\'s wives and their little children; in hope she may hold back from sacred Ilios the son of Tydeus, that savage spearman, a mighty deviser of rout, who has verily, meseems, proved himself the mightiest of the Achaeans.'),(1861,'  Not even Achilles did we ever fear on this wise, that leader of men,  who, they say, is born of a goddess; '),(1862,'nay this man rageth beyond all measure, and no one can vie with him in might.\"'),(1863,'So spake he, and Hector was in no wise disobedient unto his brother\'s word.  '),(1864,'Forthwith he leapt in his armour from his chariot to the ground, and brandishing his two sharp spears went everywhere throughout host,  urging them to fight; and he roused the dread din of battle.'),(1865,'So they rallied, and took their stand with their faces toward the Achaeans'),(1866,'and the Argives gave ground and ceased from slaying; and they deemed that one of the immortals had come down from starry heaven to bear aid to the Trojans, that they rallied thus.'),(1867,'  And Hector shouted aloud and called to the Trojans:'),(1868,'“Ye Trojans, high of heart, and far-famed allies, be men, my friends, and bethink you of furious valour, the while I go to Ilios and bid the elders that give counsel, and our wives '),(1869,'So saying, Hector of the flashing helm departed,'),(1870,'and the black hide at either end smote against his ankles and his neck, even the rim that ran about the outermost edge of his bossed shield.'),(1871,'But Glaucus, son of Hippolochus, and the son of Tydeus  came together in the space between the two hosts, eager to do battle.  '),(1872,'And when the twain were now come near as they advanced one against the other, Diomedes, good at the war-cry, was first to speak, saying:'),(1873,'Who art thou, mighty one, among mortal men?'),(1874,'  For never have I seen thee in battle where men win glory  until this day, '),(1875,'but now hast thou come forth far in advance of all in thy hardihood, in that thou abidest my far-shadowing spear.'),(1876,'  Unhappy are they whose children face my might.'),(1877,'  But and if thou art one of the immortals come down from heaven, then will I not fight with the heavenly gods.'),(1878,'  Nay, for even the son of Dryas, mighty Lycurgus, lived not long, seeing that he strove with heavenly gods—'),(1879,'he that on a time drave down over the sacred mount of Nysa the nursing mothers of mad Dionysus'),(1880,'and they all let fall to the ground their wands, smitten with an ox-goad by man-slaying Lycurgus.'),(1881,'  But Dionysus fled, and plunged beneath the wave of the sea, and Thetis received him in her bosom, filled with dread, '),(1882,'for mighty terror gat hold of him at the man\'s threatenings.'),(1883,'  Then against Lycurgus did the gods that live at ease wax wroth, and the son of Cronos made him blind; '),(1884,'and he lived not for long, seeing that he was hated of all the immortal gods.  '),(1885,'So would not I be minded to fight against the blessed gods.'),(1886,'  But if thou art of men, who eat the fruit of the field, draw nigh, that thou mayest the sooner enter the toils of destruction.\"'),(1887,'Then spake to him the glorious son of Hippolochus: '),(1888,' \"Great-souled son of Tydeus, wherefore inquirest thou of my lineage?'),(1889,'Even as are the generations of leaves, such are those also of men.'),(1890,' As for the leaves, the wind scattereth some upon the earth, but the forest, as it bourgeons, putteth forth others when the season of spring is come;'),(1891,'even so of men one generation springeth up and another passeth away.'),(1892,'  Howbeit, if thou wilt, hear this also, that thou mayest know well my lineage; and many there be that know it.'),(1893,'  There is a city Ephyre in the heart of Argos, pasture-land of horses, and there dwelt Sisyphus that was craftiest of men, Sisyphus, son of Aeolus;'),(1894,'and he begat a son Glaucus; and Glaucus in turn sired Bellerophon the blameless.'),(1895,'  To him the gods granted beauty and lovely manliness; '),(1896,'but Proetus in his heart devised against him evil, and drave him, seeing he was mightier far, from the land of the Argives;'),(1897,'for Zeus had made them subject to his sceptre.'),(1898,'  Now the wife of Proetus, fair Anteia, lusted madly for Bellerophon, to lie with him in secret love,'),(1899,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 6.161-6.162'),(1900,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 6.163'),(1901,'\"Either die thyself, Proetus, or slay Bellerophon,  seeing he was minded to lie with me in love against my will.\"'),(1902,'So she spake, and wrath gat hold upon the king to hear that word. '),(1903,'To slay him he forbare, for his soul had awe of that;  but he sent him to Lycia, and gave him baneful tokens, graving in a folded tablet many signs and deadly,  and bade him show these to his own wife\'s father, that he might be slain.'),(1904,'So he went his way to Lycia under the blameless escort of the gods.'),(1905,' And when he was come to Lycia and the stream of Xanthus, then with a ready heart did the king of wide Lycia do him honour:'),(1906,' for nine days\' space he shewed him entertainment, and slew nine oxen.  '),(1907,'Howbeit when the tenth rosy-fingered Dawn appeared,  then at length he questioned him and asked to see whatever token he bare from his daughter\'s husband, Proetus.'),(1908,'  But when he had received from him the evil token of his daughter\'s husband, first he bade him slay the raging Chimaera.'),(1909,'  She was of divine stock, not of men, in the fore part a lion, in the hinder a serpent, and in the midst a goat, breathing forth in terrible wise the might of blazing fire. And Bellerophon slew her, trusting in the signs of the gods. '),(1910,'Next fought he with the glorious Solymi,'),(1911,' and this, said he was the mightest battle of warriors that ever he entered;  '),(1912,'and thirdly he slew the Amazons, women the peers of men.'),(1913,'And against him, as he journeyed back therefrom, the king wove another cunning wile;'),(1914,'he chose out of wide Lycia the bravest men and set an ambush; '),(1915,'but these returned not home in any wise'),(1916,'since all of them were killed by blameless Bellerophon'),(1917,' But when the king now knew that he was the valiant offspring of a god, he kept him there, and offered him his own daughter, and gave to him the half of all his kingly honour; '),(1918,'moreover the Lycians meted out for him a demesne pre-eminent above all,  a fair tract of orchard and of plough-land, to possess it.  '),(1919,'And the lady bare to wise-hearted Bellerophon three children, Isander and Hippolochus and Laodameia.'),(1920,'  With Laodameia lay Zeus the counsellor, and she bare godlike Sarpedon, the warrior harnessed in bronze.'),(1921,'  But when even Bellerophon came to be hated of all the gods, then verily he wandered alone over the Aleian plain, devouring his own soul, and shunning the paths of men; '),(1922,'and Isander his son was slain by Ares, insatiate of battle, as he fought against the glorious Solymi; '),(1923,' and his daughter was slain in wrath by Artemis of the golden reins.'),(1924,'But Hippolochus begat me and of him do I declare that I am sprung;'),(1925,' and he sent me to Troy and straitly charged me ever to be bravest and pre-eminent above all, and not bring shame upon the race of my fathers,  that were far the noblest in Ephyre and in wide Lycia.  '),(1926,'This is the lineage and the blood whereof I avow me sprung.'),(1927,'So spake he, and Diomedes, good at the warcry, waxed glad.'),(1928,'  He planted his spear in the bounteous earth, and with gentle words spake to the shepherd of the host:'),(1929,'  \"Verily now art thou a friend of my father\'s house from of old:'),(1930,'for goodly Oeneus on a time entertained peerless Bellerophon in his halls, and kept him twenty days;'),(1931,'and moreover they gave one to the other fair gifts of friendship.'),(1932,'  Oeneus gave a belt bright with scarlet,  and Bellerophon a double cup of gold which I left in my palace as I came hither.  '),(1933,'But Tydeus I remember not, seeing I was but a little child when he left, what time the host of the Achaeans perished at Thebes.  '),(1934,'Therefore now am I a dear guest-friend to thee in the midst of Argos,  and thou to me in Lycia'),(1935,'So let us shun one another\'s spears even amid the throng; '),(1936,'full many there be for me to slay, both Trojans and famed allies, whomsoever a god shall grant me and my feet overtake;  and many Achaeans again for thee to slay whomsoever thou canst.  '),(1937,'And let us make exchange of armour, each with the other, that these men too may know that we declare ourselves to be friends from our fathers\' days.\" '),(1938,'When they had thus spoken, the twain leapt down from their chariots and clasped each other\'s hands and pledged their faith.  '),(1939,'And then from Glaucus did Zeus, son of Cronos, take away his wit,  seeing he made exchange  of armour with Diomedes, son of Tydeus, giving golden for bronze, the worth of an hundred oxen for the worth of nine.'),(1940,'But when Hector was come to the Scaean gate and the oak-tree, round about him came running the wives and daughters of the Trojans asking of their sons and brethren and friends  and husbands.'),(1941,' But he thereupon bade them make prayer to the gods, all of them in turn;'),(1942,'yet over many were sorrows hung.'),(1943,'But when he was now come to the beauteous palace of Priam, adorned with polished colonnades '),(1944,'and in it were fifty chambers of polished stone,  built each hard by the other; therein the sons of Priam were wont to sleep beside their wedded wives; and for his daughters over against them on the opposite side within the court were twelve roofed chambers of polished stone, built each hard by the other;  therein slept Priam\'s sons-in-law beside their chaste wives'),(1945,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 6.251-6.252'),(1946,'there his bounteous mother came to meet him, leading in Laodice, fairest of her daughters to look upon; and she clasped him by the hand and spake and addressed him·[251,252] '),(1947,' \"My child, why hast thou left the fierce battle and come hither?'),(1948,'  Of a surety the sons of the Achaeans, of evil name, are pressing sore upon thee as they fight about our city'),(1949,'and thy heart hath bid thee come hitherward and lift up thy hands to Zeus from the citadel.'),(1950,'  But stay till I have brought thee honey-sweet wine that thou mayest pour libation to Zeus and the other immortals first,  and then shalt thou thyself have profit thereof, if so be thou wilt drink.  '),(1951,'When a man is spent with toil wine greatly maketh his strength to wax, even as thou art spent with defending thy fellows.\" '),(1952,'Then in answer to her spake great Hector of the flashing helm:'),(1953,' \"Bring me no honey-hearted wine, honoured mother,  lest thou cripple me, and I be forgetful of my might and my valour;  '),(1954,'Moreover with hands unwashen I have awe to pour libation of flaming wine to Zeus;'),(1955,'nor may it in any wise be that a man should make prayer to the son of Cronos, lord of the dark clouds, all befouled with blood and filth.'),(1956,'  Nay, do thou go to the temple of Athene,  driver of the spoil, with burnt-offerings, when thou hast gathered together the aged wives; '),(1957,'and the robe that seemeth to thee the fairest and amplest in thy hall, and that is dearest far to thine own self, this do thou lay upon the knees of fair-haired Athene and vow to her that thou wilt sacrifice in her temple twelve sleek heifers that have not felt the goad,  if she will take pity on Troy and the Trojans\' wives and their little children;  in hope she may hold back the son of Tydeus from sacred Ilios, that savage spearman, a mighty deviser of rout. '),(1958,' So go thou to the temple of Athene, driver of the spoil;  and I will go after Paris, to summon him, if haply he will hearken to my bidding.'),(1959,'  Would that the earth might straightway gape for him!'),(1960,' for in grievous wise hath the Olympian reared him as a bane to the Trojans and to great-hearted Priam, and the sons of Priam.'),(1961,'  If I but saw him going down to the house of Hades,  then might I deem that my heart had forgotten its woe.\"'),(1962,'So spake he, and she went to the hall and called to her handmaidens;'),(1963,' and they gathered together the aged wives throughout the city.'),(1964,'  But the queen herself went down to the vaulted treasurechamber wherein were her robes, richly broidered, the handiwork of Sidonian women,  whom godlike Alexander had himself brought from Sidon, as he sailed over the wide sea on that journey on the which he brought back high-born Helen.'),(1965,'  Of these Hecabe took one, and bare it as an offering for Athene, the one that was fairest in its broiderings and amplest,  and shone like a star'),(1966,'and lay undermost of all.'),(1967,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 6.296'),(1968,'Now when they were come to the temple of Athene in the citadel, the doors were opened for them by fair-cheeked Theano, daughter of Cisseus, the wife of Antenor, tamer of horses; '),(1969,' for her had the Trojans made priestess of Athene.'),(1970,' Then with sacred cries they all lifted up their hands to Athene;'),(1971,'and fair-cheeked Theano took the robe and laid it upon the knees of fair-haired Athene, and with vows made prayer to the daughter of great Zeus:'),(1972,'  \"Lady Athene, that dost guard our city, fairest among goddesses, break now the spear of Diomedes, and grant furthermore that himself may fall headlong before the Scaean gates; to the end that we may now forthwith sacrifice to thee in thy temple twelve sleek heifers that have not felt the goad, if thou wilt take pity  on Troy and the Trojans\' wives and their little children.\"  '),(1973,'So spake she praying, but Pallas Athene denied the prayer.'),(1974,'Thus were these praying to the daughter of great Zeus, but Hector went his way to the palace of Alexander, the fair palace that himself had builded with the men  that were in that day the best builders in deep-soiled Troy; these had made him a chamber and hall and court hard by the palaces of Priam and Hector in the citadel.'),(1975,'  There entered in Hector, dear to Zeus, and in his hand he held a spear of eleven cubits'),(1976,'and before him blazed  the spear-point of bronze, around which ran a ring of gold.'),(1977,'  He found Paris in his chamber busied with his beauteous arms, his shield and his corselet, and handling his curved bow; '),(1978,' and Argive Helen sat amid her serving-women and appointed to them their glorious handiwork.'),(1979,'  And at sight of him Hector rebuked him with words of shame:'),(1980,'  And at sight of him Hector rebuked him with words of shame: \"Strange man, thou dost not well to nurse this anger in thy heart.'),(1981,'  Thy people are perishing about the town and the steep wall in battle, and it is because of thee that the battle-cry and the war are ablaze about this city;'),(1982,'thou wouldest thyself vent wrath on any other,  whomso thou shouldest haply see shrinking from hateful war.  '),(1983,'Nay, then, rouse thee, lest soon the city blaze with consuming fire.\" '),(1984,' \nAnd to him did godlike Alexander make answer, saying:'),(1985,' \"Hector, seeing that thou dost chide me duly, and not beyond what is due, therefore will I tell thee;'),(1986,'and do thou take thought and hearken unto me.'),(1987,'  Not so much by reason of wrath and indignation against the Trojans sat I in my chamber, but I was minded to yield myself to sorrow.'),(1988,'  Even now my wife sought to turn my mind with gentle words and urged me to the war:'),(1989,' and I, mine own self, deem that it will be better so; '),(1990,'victory shifteth from man to man.'),(1991,' But come now, tarry a while, let me don my harness of war;'),(1992,'and methinks I shall overtake thee.'),(1993,'and methinks I shall overtake thee.'),(1994,'So said he, and Hector of the flashing helm answered him not a word,'),(1995,' but unto him spake Helen with gentle words:'),(1996,'O Brother of me that am a dog, a contriver of mischief and abhorred of all,  I would that on the day when first my mother gave me birth an evil storm-wind had borne me away to some mountain or to the wave of the loud-resounding sea, where the wave might have swept me away or ever these things came to pass.  '),(1997,'Howbeit, seeing the gods thus ordained these ills,  would that I had been wife to a better man, that could feel the indignation of his fellows and their many revilings.'),(1998,'  But this man\'s understanding is not now stable, nor ever will be hereafter; '),(1999,'thereof I deem that he will e\'en reap the fruit.'),(2000,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 6.354-6.358'),(2001,'from MILESTONE 355 to MILESTONE 360\n======================================================================\nThen made answer to her great Hector of the flashing helm:  \"Bid me not sit, Helen, for all thou lovest me;'),(2002,'thou wilt not persuade me.  '),(2003,'Even now my heart is impatient to bear aid to the Trojans that sorely long for me that am not with them.'),(2004,' Nay, but rouse thou this man, and let him of himself make haste, that he may overtake me while yet I am within the city.'),(2005,'  For I shall go to my home, that I may behold my housefolk, my dear wife, and my infant son; '),(2006,'for I know not if any more I shall return home to them again, or if even now the gods will slay me beneath the hands of the Achaeans.\" '),(2007,'So saying, Hector of the flashing helm departed,  '),(2008,'and came speedily to his well-built house.  But he found not white-armed Andromache in his halls; she with her child and a fair-robed handmaiden had taken her stand upon the wall, weeping and wailing.'),(2009,' So Hector when he found not his peerless wife within,  went and stood upon the threshold, and spake amid the serving-women:\"'),(2010,'Come now, ye serving-women, tell me true;'),(2011,'whither went white-armed Andromache from the hall?'),(2012,'Is she gone to the house of any of my sisters or my brothers\' fair-robed wives, or to the temple of Athene, where the other  fair-tressed women of Troy are seeking to propitiate he dread goddess?\"'),(2013,'Then a busy house-dame spake to him, saying:'),(2014,'\"Hector, seeing thou straitly biddest us tell thee true, neither is she gone to any of thy sisters or thy brothers\' fair-robed wives, nor yet to the temple of Athene, where the other  fair-tressed Trojan women are seeking to propitiate the dread goddess, but she went to the great wall of Ilios, for that she heard the Trojans were sorely pressed, and great grew the strength of Achaians'),(2015,'So is she gone in haste to the wall, like one beside herself;'),(2016,' and with her the nurse beareth the child.'),(2017,'  So spake the house-dame, and Hector hasted from the house back over the same way along the well-built streets.  '),(2018,'When now he was come to the gate, as he passed through the great city, the Scaean gate, whereby he was minded to go forth to the plain, there came running to meet him his bounteous wife,  Andromache, daughter of great-hearted Eëtion, Eëtion that dwelt beneath wooded Placus, in Thebe under Placus, and was lord over the men of Cilicia; for it was his daughter that bronze-harnessed Hector had to wife.'),(2019,'for it was his daughter that bronze-harnessed Hector had to wife.'),(2020,'She now met him, and with her came a handmaid bearing in her bosom  the tender boy, a mere babe, the well-loved son of Hector, like to a fair star.  Him Hector was wont to call Scamandrius, but other men Astyanax; '),(2021,'for only Hector guarded Ilios.'),(2022,' Then Hector smiled, as he glanced at his boy in silence,  '),(2023,'but Andromache came close to his side weeping, and clasped his hand and spake to him, saying:'),(2024,'Ah, my husband, this prowess of thine will be thy doom, neither hast thou any pity for thine infant child nor for hapless me that soon shall be thy widow; -'),(2025,'for soon will the Achaeans  all set upon thee and slay thee.'),(2026,'But for me it were better to go down to the grave if I lose thee, '),(2027,' for nevermore shall any comfort be mine, when thou hast met thy fate, but only woes.'),(2028,'  Neither father have I nor queenly mother.'),(2029,'  My father verily goodly Achilles slew,  for utterly laid he waste the well-peopled city of the Cilicians, even Thebe of lofty gates.'),(2030,'  He slew Eëtion, yet he despoiled him not, for his soul had awe of that; but he burnt him in his armour, richly dight, and heaped over him a barrow; '),(2031,'and all about were elm-trees planted by nymphs of the mountain, daughters of Zeus that beareth the aegis.'),(2032,'  And the seven brothers that were mine in our halls, all these on the selfsame day entered into the house of Hades, '),(2033,'for all were slain of swift-footed, goodly Achilles, amid their kine of shambling gait and their white-fleeced sheep.'),(2034,'  And my mother, that was queen beneath wooded Placus, her brought he hither with the rest of the spoil, but thereafter set her free, when he had taken ransom past counting; and in her father\'s halls Artemis the archer slew her.'),(2035,'  Nay, Hector, thou art to me father and queenly mother,  thou art brother, and thou art my stalwart husband.  '),(2036,'Come now, have pity, and remain here on the wall, lest thou make thy child an orphan and thy wife a widow.'),(2037,'  And for thy host, stay it by the wild fig-tree, where the city may best be scaled, and the wall is open to assault.'),(2038,'  For thrice at this point came the most valiant in company with the twain Aiantes and glorious Idomeneus and the sons of Atreus and the valiant son of Tydeus, and made essay to enter:'),(2039,'  whether it be that one well-skilled in soothsaying told them, or haply their own spirit urgeth and biddeth them thereto.\"'),(2040,'  Then spake to her great Hector of the flashing helm:'),(2041,'\n\n \"Woman, I too take thought of all this,'),(2042,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 6.441-6.443'),(2043,'from MILESTONE 440 to MILESTONE 450\n====================================================================== \nNor doth mine own heart suffer it, seeing I have learnt to be valiant  always and to fight amid the foremost Trojans, striving to win my father\'s great glory and mine own.'),(2044,'For of a surety know I this in heart and soul:'),(2045,'  the day shall come when sacred Ilios shall be laid low, and Priam, and the people of Priam with goodly spear of ash.'),(2046,'  Yet not so much doth the grief of the Trojans that shall be in the aftertime move me, neither Hecabe\'s own, nor king Priam\'s, nor my brethren\'s, many and brave, who then shall fall in the dust beneath the hands of their foemen, as doth thy grief, when some brazen-coated Achaean  shall lead thee away weeping and rob thee of thy day of freedom.  '),(2047,'Then haply in Argos shalt thou ply the loom at another s bidding, or bear water from Messeis or Hypereia, sorely against thy will, and strong necessity shall be laid upon thee.'),(2048,'  And some man shall say as he beholdeth thee weeping:'),(2049,'  \"Lo, the wife of Hector, that was pre-eminent in war above all the horse-taming Trojans, in the day when men fought about Ilios.\"  '),(2050,'So shall one say; '),(2051,'and to thee shall come fresh grief in thy lack of a man like me to ward off the day of bondage.'),(2052,'  But let me be dead, and let the heaped-up earth cover me, '),(2053,'So saying, glorious Hector stretched out his arms to his boy, '),(2054,'but back into the bosom of his fair-girdled nurse shrank the child crying, affrighted at the aspect of his dear father, and seized with dread of the bronze and the crest of horse-hair,  as he marked it waving dreadfully from the topmost helm.'),(2055,'Aloud then laughed his dear father and queenly mother;'),(2056,' and forthwith glorious Hector took the helm from his head and laid it all-gleaming upon the ground.'),(2057,'  But he kissed his dear son, and fondled him in his arms,  and spake in prayer to Zeus and the other gods:'),(2058,'\"Zeus and ye other gods, grant that this my child may likewise prove, even as I, pre-eminent amid the Trojans, and as valiant in might, and that he rule mightily over Ilios.'),(2059,'  And some day may some man say of him as he cometh back from war,‘He is better far than his father’; '),(2060,' and may he bear the blood-stained spoils of the foeman he hath slain, and may his mother\'s heart wax glad.\"'),(2061,'So saying, he laid his child in his dear wife\'s arms, and she took him to her fragrant bosom, smiling through her tears; '),(2062,'and she took him to her fragrant bosom, smiling through her tears;'),(2063,'and her husband was touched with pity at sight of her,  and stroked her with his hand, and spake to her, saying:'),(2064,' \"Dear wife, in no wise, I pray thee, grieve overmuch at heart'),(2065,'no man beyond my fate shall send me forth to Hades; '),(2066,'only his doom, methinks, no man hath ever escaped, be he coward or valiant, when once he hath been born.'),(2067,'  Nay, go thou to the house and busy thyself with thine own tasks, the loom and the distaff, and bid thy handmaids ply their work:'),(2068,' but war shall be for men, for all, but most of all for me, of them that dwell in Ilios.\"'),(2069,'So spake glorious Hector and took up his helm  with horse-hair crest; '),(2070,'and his dear wife went forthwith to her house, oft turning back, and shedding big tears.'),(2071,'  Presently she came to the well-built palace of man-slaying Hector and found therein her many handmaidens; and among them all she roused lamentation. '),(2072,'  So in his own house they made lament for Hector while yet he lived;'),(2073,'for they deemed that he should never more come back from battle, escaped from the might and the hands of the Achaeans. '),(2074,'and hastened through the city, trusting in his fleetness of foot.'),(2075,'  Even as when a stalled horse that has fed his fill at the manger breaketh his halter and runneth stamping over the plain—being wont to bathe him in the fair-flowing river—and exulteth;'),(2076,'  on high doth he hold his head, and about his shoulders  his mane floateth streamin'),(2077,'and as he glorieth in his splendour, his knees nimbly bear him to the haunts and pastures of mares; '),(2078,'even so Paris, son of Priam, strode down from high Pergamus, all gleaming in his armour like the shining sun, laughing for glee, and his swift feet bare him on.'),(2079,' Speedily then  he overtook goodly Hector, his brother, even as he was about to turn back from the place where he had dallied with his wife.'),(2080,'  Then godlike Alexander was first to speak to him, saying:'),(2081,' \"My brother, full surely I delay thee in thine haste by my long tarrying, and came not in due season, as thou badest me.\"'),(2082,'  Then in answer to him spake Hector of the flashing helm:\"'),(2083,'Strange man, no one that is rightminded could make light of thy work in battle, for thou art valiant;'),(2084,'but of thine own will art thou slack, and hast no care;'),(2085,' and thereat my heart is grieved within me, whenso I hear regarding thee words of shame  from the lips of the Trojans, who because of thee have grievous toil.'),(2086,'But let us go our way;'),(2087,'these things we will make good hereafter, if so be Zeus shall grant us to set for the heavenly gods that are for ever a bowl of deliverance in our halls, when we have driven forth from the land of Troy the well-greaved Achaeans.\"'),(2088,' So saying, glorious Hector hastened forth from the gates, and with him went his brother Alexander;'),(2089,'and in their hearts were both eager for war and battle.'),(2090,'  And as a god giveth to longing seamen  a fair wind when they have grown weary of beating the sea with polished oars of fir, and with weariness are their limbs fordone; even so appeared these twain to the longing Trojans.'),(2091,'Then the one of them slew the son of king Areithous, Menesthius, that dwelt in Arne, who was born of the mace-man  Areithous and ox-eyed Phylomedusa; '),(2092,'and Hector with his sharp spear smote Eioneus on the neck beneath the well-wrought helmet of bronze, and loosed his limbs.'),(2093,'And Glaucus, son of Hippolochus, leader of the Lycians, made a cast with his spear in the fierce conflict at Iphinous,  son of Dexios, as he sprang upon his car behind his swift mares, and smote him upon the shoulder; '),(2094,'so he fell from his chariot to the ground and his limbs were loosed.'),(2095,'But when the goddess, flashing-eyed Athene, was ware of them as they were slaying the Argives in the fierce conflict, she went darting down from the peaks of Olympus  to sacred Ilios.  '),(2096,'And Apollo sped forth to meet her, for he looked down from out of Pergamus and beheld her, and was fain to have victory for the Trojans.'),(2097,'  So the twain met one with the other by the oak-tree.'),(2098,'  Then to her spake first the king Apollo, son of Zeus:\"'),(2099,'Wherefore art thou again come thus eagerly from Olympus, thou daughter of great Zeus,  and why hath thy proud spirit sent thee?'),(2100,' Is it that thou mayest give to the Danaans victory to turn the tide of battle'),(2101,'seeing thou hast no pity for the Trojans, that perish?'),(2102,'  But if thou wouldst in anywise hearken unto me—and so would it be better far—'),(2103,'let us now stay the war and fighting  for this day.'),(2104,'Hereafter shall they fight again until they win the goal of Ilios, since thus it seemeth good to the hearts of you immortal goddesses, to lay waste this city.\"'),(2105,'And in answer to him spake the goddess, flashing-eyed Athene:'),(2106,' \"So be it, thou god that workest afar; '),(2107,' with this in mind am I myself come from Olympus to the midst of Trojans and Achaeans.'),(2108,' But come, how art thou minded to stay the battle of the warriors?\"'),(2109,'Then in answer to her spake king Apollo, son of Zeus: '),(2110,'\"Let us rouse the valiant spirit of horse-taming Hector, in hope that he may challenge some one of the Danaans in single fight  to do battle with him man to man in dread combat.  So shall the bronze-greaved Achaeans have indignation and rouse some one to do battle in single combat against goodly Hector.\" '),(2111,'So he spake, and the goddess, flashing-eyed Athene, failed not to hearken.'),(2112,'  And Helenus, the dear son of Priam, understood in spirit  this plan that had found pleasure with the gods in council; '),(2113,'and he came and stood by Hector\'s side, and spake to him, saying:'),(2114,' \"Hector, son of Priam, peer of Zeus in counsel, wouldst thou now in anywise hearken unto me? for I am thy brother.  '),(2115,'Make the Trojans to sit down, and all the Achaeans,  and do thou challenge whoso is best of the Achaeans to do battle with thee man to man in dread combat.'),(2116,' Not yet is it thy fate to die and meet thy doom; '),(2117,'for thus have I heard the voice of the gods that are for ever.\"'),(2118,'So spake he and Hector rejoiced greatly when he heard his words;  and he went into the midst and kept back the battalions of the Trojans with his spear grasped by the middle; '),(2119,'and they all sate them down, '),(2120,'and Agamemnon made the well-greaved Achaeans to sit.'),(2121,'  And Athene and Apollo of the silver bow in the likeness of vultures sate them  upon the lofty oak of father Zeus that beareth the aegis, rejoicing in the warriors; '),(2122,'and the ranks of these sat close, bristling with shields and helms and spears.'),(2123,' Even as there is spread over the face of the deep the ripple of the West Wind, that is newly risen, and the deep groweth black beneath it,  so sat the ranks of the Achaeans and Trojans in the plain.'),(2124,' And Hector spake between the two hosts:\"'),(2125,'Hear me, ye Trojans and well-greaved Achaeans, that I may speak what the heart in my breast biddeth me. '),(2126,'Our oaths the son of Cronos, throned on high, brought not to fulfillment,  but with ill intent ordaineth a time for both hosts, until either ye take well-walled Troy or yourselves be vanquished beside your sea-faring ships.'),(2127,'  With you are the chieftains of the whole host of the Achaeans;'),(2128,'of these let now that man whose heart soever biddeth him fight with me,  come hither from among you all to be your champion against goodly Hector.'),(2129,'And thus do I declare my word, and be Zeus our witness thereto:'),(2130,' if so be he shall slay me with the long-edged bronze, let him spoil me of my armour and bear it to the hollow ships, but my body let him give back to my home,  that the Trojans and the Trojan wives may give me my due meed of fire in my death.  '),(2131,'But if so be I slay him, and Apollo give me glory, I will spoil him of his armour and bear it to sacred Ilios and hang it upon the temple of Apollo, the god that smiteth afar, but his corpse will I render back to the well-benched ships,  that the long-haired Achaeans may give him burial, and heap up for him a barrow by the wide Hellespont.'),(2132,' And some one shall some day say even of men that are yet to be, as he saileth in his many-benched ship over the wine-dark sea:'),(2133,' ‘This is a barrow of a man that died in olden days,  whom on a time in the midst of his prowess glorious Hector slew.'),(2134,'and my glory shall never die.\" '),(2135,'and my glory shall never die.\" '),(2136,'So spake he, and they all became hushed in silence; '),(2137,'shame had they to deny him, but they feared to meet him.'),(2138,'  Howbeit at length Menelaus arose among them and spake,  chiding them with words of reviling, and deeply did he groan at heart: '),(2139,'\"Ah me, Ye braggarts, ye women of Achaea, men no more!'),(2140,'Surely shall this be a disgrace dread and dire, if no man of the Danaans shall now go to meet Hector.'),(2141,'  Nay, may ye one and all turn to earth and water,  ye that sit there each man with no heart in him, utterly inglorious.'),(2142,'Against this man will I myself arm me;'),(2143,'but from on high are the issues of victory holden of the immortal gods.\"'),(2144,'So spake he, and did on his fair armour.  '),(2145,'And now Menelaus, would the end of life have appeared for thee  at the hands of Hector, seeing he was mightier far, had not the kings of the Achaeans sprung up and laid hold of thee.  And Atreus\' son himself, wide-ruling Agamemnon, caught him by the right hand and spake to him, saying:'),(2146,' \"Thou art mad, Menelaus, nurtured of Zeus, and this thy madness beseemeth thee not.'),(2147,'  Hold back, for all thy grief, and be not minded in rivalry to fight with one better than thou, even with Hector, son of Priam, of whom others besides thee are adread.'),(2148,'Even Achilles shuddereth to meet this man in battle, where men win glory; and he is better far than thou.'),(2149,'  Nay, go thou for this present, and sit thee amid the company of thy fellows; against this man shall the Achaeans raise up another champion.'),(2150,'  Fearless though he be and insatiate of battle, methinks he will be glad to bend his knees in rest, if so be he escape from the fury of war and the dread conflict.\"'),(2151,'  So spake the warrior and turned his brother\'s mind, for he counselled aright; and Menelaus obeyed.'),(2152,'  Then with gladness his squires took his armour from his shoulders; '),(2153,'and Nestor rose up and spake amid the Argives: \"Fie upon you!'),(2154,'  In good sooth is great grief come upon the land of Achaea.'),(2155,'  Verily aloud would old Peleus groan, the driver of chariots, goodly counsellor, and orator of the Myrmidons, who on a time questioned me in his own house, and rejoiced greatly as he asked of the lineage and birth of all the Argives.  '),(2156,'If he were to hear that these were now all cowering before Hector  then would he lift up his hands to the immortals in instant prayer that his soul might depart from his limbs into the house of Hades.'),(2157,'  I would, O father Zeus and Athene and Apollo, that I were young as when beside swift-flowing Celadon the Pylians and Arcadians that rage with spears gathered together and fought  beneath the walls of Pheia about the streams of Iardanus.  '),(2158,'On their side stood forth Ereuthalion as champion, a godlike man, bearing upon his shoulders the armour of king Areithous, goodly Areithous that men and fair-girdled women were wont to call the mace-man,  for that he fought not with bow or long spear, but with a mace of iron brake the battalions.'),(2159,'  Him Lycurgus slew by guile and nowise by might, in a narrow way, where his mace of iron saved him not from destruction.'),(2160,' For ere that might be Lycurgus came upon him at unawares  and pierced him through the middle with his spear, and backward was he hurled upon the earth; '),(2161,'and Lycurgus despoiled him of the armour that brazen Ares had given him.'),(2162,'  This armour he thereafter wore himself amid the turmoil of Ares'),(2163,'but when Lycurgus grew old within his halls  he gave it to Ereuthalion, his dear squire, to wear.  '),(2164,'And wearing this armour did Ereuthalion challenge all the bravest; '),(2165,'but they trembled sore and were afraid, nor had any man courage to abide him.'),(2166,'  But me did my enduring heart set on to battle with him in my hardihood, '),(2167,'though in years I was youngest of all.'),(2168,'  So fought I with him, and Athene gave me glory.'),(2169,' The tallest was he and the strongest man that ever I slew:'),(2170,' as a huge sprawling bulk he lay stretched this way and that.'),(2171,'  Would I were now as young and my strength as firm, '),(2172,' then should Hector of the flashing helm soon find one to face him.'),(2173,'  Whereas ye that are chieftains of the whole host of the Achaeans,  even ye are not minded with a ready heart to meet Hector face to face.\"'),(2174,'So the old man chid them, and there stood up nine in all. '),(2175,'Upsprang far the first the king of men, Agamemnon, and after him Tydeus\' son, mighty Diomedes, and after them the Aiantes, clothed in furious valour,  and after them Idomeneus and Idomeneus\' comrade Meriones, the peer of Enyalius, slayer of men, and after them Eurypylus, the glorious son of Euaemon; and upsprang Thoas, son of Andraemon, and goodly Odysseus;'),(2176,'all these were minded to do battle with goodly Hector.'),(2177,'  Then among them spake again the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia:'),(2178,' Cast ye the lot now from the first unto the last for him whoso shall be chosen;'),(2179,'for he shall verily profit the well-greaved Achaeans and himself in his own soul shall profit withal, if so be he escape from the fury of war and the dread conflict.\" '),(2180,'  So said he, and they marked each man his lot and cast them in the helmet of Agamemnon, son of Atreus; '),(2181,'and the host made prayer, and lifted up their hands to the gods.'),(2182,'  And thus would one say with a lance up to the broad heaven:'),(2183,' \"Father Zeus, grant that the lot fall of Aias or the son of Tydeus  or else on the king himself of Mycene rich in gold.\"'),(2184,'So spake they, and the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, shook the helmet, and forth therefrom leapt the lot that themselves desired, even the lot of Aias.'),(2185,'And the herald bare it everywhither throughout the throng, and showed it from left to right to all the chieftains of the Achaeans;  but they knew it not, and denied it every man.  '),(2186,' but they knew it not, and denied it every man'),(2187,'But when in bearing it everywhither throughout the throng he was come to him that had marked it and cast it into the helm, even to glorious Aias, then Aias held forth his hand, and the herald drew near and laid the lot therein; and Aias knew at a glance the token on the lot, and waxed glad at heart.'),(2188,'  The lot then he cast upon the ground beside his foot, and spake:'),(2189,'\"My friends, of a surety the lot is mine, and mine own heart rejoiceth, for I deem that I shall vanquish goodly Hector.  '),(2190,'But come now, while I am doing on me my battle gear, make ye prayer the while to king Zeus, son of Cronos,  in silence by yourselves, that the Trojans learn naught thereof—nay, or openly, if ye will, since in any case we fear no man.'),(2191,'  For by force shall no man drive me in flight of his own will and in despite of mine, nor yet by skill; since as no skilless wight methinks was I born and reared in Salamis.\"'),(2192,'  So spake he, and they made prayer to king Zeus, son of Cronos;'),(2193,'and thus would one speak with a glance up to the broad heaven:'),(2194,' \"Father Zeus, that rulest from Ida, most glorious, most great, vouchsafe victory to Aias and that he win him glorious renown;'),(2195,'or if so be thou lovest Hector too, and carest for him, '),(2196,'So they spake, and Aias arrayed him in gleaming bronze.'),(2197,'  But when he had clothed about his flesh all his armour, then sped he in such wise as huge Ares goeth forth when he enters into battle amid warriors whom the son of Cronos  hath brought together to contend in the fury of soul-devouring strife.'),(2198,'Even in such wise sprang forth huge Aias, the bulwark of the Achaeans, with a smile on his grim face; '),(2199,'and he went with long strides of his feet beneath him, brandishing his far-shadowing spear.'),(2200,' Then were the Argives glad as they looked upon him,  but upon the Trojans crept dread trembling on the limbs of every man, and Hector\'s own heart beat fast within his breast.'),(2201,'  Howbeit in no wise could he any more flee or shrink back into the throng of the host, seeing he had made challenge to fight.  '),(2202,'So Aias drew near, bearing his shield that was like a city wall,  a shield of bronze with sevenfold bull\'s-hide, the which Tychius had wrought with toil, he that was far best of workers in hide, having his home in Hyle, who had made him his flashing shield of seven hides of sturdy bulls, and thereover had wrought an eighth layer of bronze.'),(2203,'  This Telamonian Aias bare before his breast,  and he came and stood close by Hector, and spake threatening: '),(2204,'\"Hector, now verily shalt thou know of a surety, man to man, what manner of chieftains there be likewise among the Danaans, even after Achilles, breaker of the ranks of men, the lion-hearted.'),(2205,' Howbeit he abideth amid his beaked seafaring ships  in utter wrath against Agamemnon, Atreus\' son, shepherd of the host; '),(2206,'yet are we such as to face thee, yea, full many of us.'),(2207,'But begin thou war and battle.'),(2208,'To him then made answer great Hector of the flashing helm:'),(2209,'\"Aias, sprung from Zeus, thou son of Telamon, captain of the host,  in no wise make thou trial of me as of some puny boy or a woman that knoweth not deeds of war.'),(2210,'Nay, full well know I battles and slayings of men.'),(2211,'  I know well how to wield to right, and well how to wield to left my shield of seasoned hide, which I deem a sturdy thing to wield in fight; '),(2212,' and I know how to charge into the mellay of chariots drawn by swift mares;'),(2213,'and I know how in close fight to tread the measure of furious Ares.'),(2214,'  Yet am I not minded to smite thee, being such a one as thou art, by spying thee at unawares; but rather openly, if so be I may hit thee.\" '),(2215,'He spake, and poised his far-shadowing spear, and hurled it;  and he smote Aias\' dread shield of sevenfold bull\'s-hide upon the outermost bronze, the eighth layer that was thereon.'),(2216,'  Through six folds shore the stubborn bronze, but in the seventh hide it was stayed.'),(2217,'  Then in turn Zeus-born Aias hurled his far-shadowing spear,  and smote upon the son of Priam\'s shield, that was well balanced upon every side.'),(2218,'Through the bright shield went the mighty spear, and through the corselet, richly dight, did it force its way;'),(2219,'  Through the bright shield went the mighty spear, and through the corselet, richly dight, did it force its way; '),(2220,'but he bent aside, and escaped black fate.'),(2221,'  Then the twain both at one moment drew forth with their hands their long spears, and fell to, in semblance like ravening lions or wild boars, whose is no weakling strength.'),(2222,'  Then the son of Priam smote full upon the shield of Aias with a thrust of his spear, howbeit the bronze brake not through, for its point was turned; '),(2223,' but Aias leapt upon him and pierced his buckler'),(2224,'and clean through went the spear and made him reel in his onset; even to his neck it made its way, and gashed it, and the dark blood welled up.  Yet not even so did Hector of the flashing-helm cease from fight, but giving ground he seized with stout hand a stone  that lay upon the plain, black and jagged and great; '),(2225,'therewith he smote Aias\' dread shield of sevenfold bull\'s-hide full upon the boss;'),(2226,'and the bronze rang about it.'),(2227,'Then Aias in turn lifted on high a far greater stone, and swung and hurled it, putting into the cast measureless strength;  and he burst the buckler inwards with the cast of the rock that was like unto a mill-stone, and beat down Hector\'s knees; '),(2228,'so he stretched upon his back, gathered together under his shield; '),(2229,'howbeit Apollo straightway raised him up.'),(2230,'  And now had they been smiting with their swords in close fight, but that the heralds, messengers of Zeus and men,  came, one from the Trojans and one from the brazen-coated Achaeans, even Talthybius and Idaeus, men of prudence both.'),(2231,'  Between the two they held forth their staves, and the herald Idaeus, skilled in prudent counsel, spake, saying:'),(2232,' \"Fight ye no more, dear sons, neither do battle; '),(2233,' both ye twain are loved of Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, and both are spearmen;'),(2234,'that verily know we all.'),(2235,' and it is well to yield obedience to night\'s behest.\" '),(2236,' and it is well to yield obedience to night\'s behest.\" '),(2237,' \nThen in answer to him spake Telamonian Aias:'),(2238,' \"Idaeus, bid ye Hector speak these words'),(2239,'  for it was he who of himself challenged to combat all our best.'),(2240,'and I verily will hearken even as he shall say.'),(2241,'and I verily will hearken even as he shall say.'),(2242,'\"Then spake unto him great Hector of the flashing helm:'),(2243,' \"Aias, seeing God gave thee stature and might, aye, and wisdom, and with thy spear thou art pre-eminent above all the Achaeans,  let us now cease from battle and strife for this day; '),(2244,'hereafter shall we fight again until God judge between us, and give victory to one side or the other.'),(2245,'  Howbeit night is now upon us'),(2246,'and it is well to yield obedience to night\'s behest, that thou mayest make glad all the Achaeans beside their ships,  and most of all the kinsfolk and comrades that are thine'),(2247,'and I throughout the great city of king Priam shall make glad the Trojan men and Trojan women with trailing robes, who because of me will enter the gathering of the gods with thanksgivings.'),(2248,'  But come, let us both give each to the other glorious gifts,  to the end that many a one of Achaeans and Trojans alike may thus say: '),(2249,'‘The twain verily fought in rivalry of soul-devouring strife, but thereafter made them a compact and were parted in friendship.'),(2250,'When he had thus said, he brought and gave him his silver-studded sword with its scabbard and well-cut baldric;'),(2251,'  and Aias gave his belt bright with scarlet.'),(2252,'So they parted, and one went his way to the host of the Achaeans and the other betook him to the throng of the Trojans.'),(2253,'  And these waxed glad when they saw Hector coming to join them alive and whole, escaped from the fury of Aias and his invincible hands;'),(2254,' and they brought him to the city scarce deeming that he was safe.'),(2255,'And Aias on his part was led of the well-greaved Achaeans unto goodly Agamemnon, filled with joy of his victory. '),(2256,'And when they were now come to the huts of the son of Atreus, then did the king of men, Agamemnon slay there a bull,  a male of five years, for the son of Cronos, supreme in might.  '),(2257,'This they flayed and dressed, and cut up all the limbs.  Then they sliced these cunningly, and spitted them and roasted them carefully and drew all off the spits.'),(2258,' But when they had ceased from their labour and had made ready the meal,  they feasted, nor did their hearts lack aught of the equal feast.  '),(2259,'And unto Aias for his honour was the long chine given by the warrior son of Atreus, wide-ruling Agamemnon.'),(2260,'But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, first of all the old man began to weave the web of counsel for them,  even Nestor, whose rede had of old ever seemed the best.  '),(2261,'He with good intent addressed their gathering and spake among them:'),(2262,'Son of Atreus and ye other princes of the hosts of Achaea, lo, full many long-haired Achaeans are dead, whose dark blood keen Ares hath now spilt about fair-flowing Scamander,  and their souls have gone down to the house of Hades; '),(2263,'therefore were it well that thou make the battle of the Achaeans to cease at daybreak, and we will gather to hale hither on carts the corpses with oxen and mules;'),(2264,' and we will burn them a little way from the ships that each man may bear their bones home to their children,  whenso we return again to our native land.'),(2265,' And about the pyre let us heap a single barrow, rearing it from the plain for all alike,'),(2266,'and thereby build with speed a lofty wall, a defence for our ships and for ourselves.'),(2267,'  And therein let us build gates close-fastening,  that through them may be a way for the driving of chariots; '),(2268,' and without let us dig a deep ditch hard by, which shall intervene and keep back chariots and footmen, lest ever the battle of the lordly Trojans press heavily upon us.'),(2269,'\nSo spake he, and all the kings assented thereto.'),(2270,'  And of the Trojans likewise was a gathering held in the citadel of Ilios, a gathering fierce and tumultuous, beside Priam\'s doors.'),(2271,'  Among them wise Antenor was first to speak, saying:\"'),(2272,'Hearken to me, ye Trojans and Dardanians and allies, that I may speak what the heart in my breast biddeth me.'),(2273,'  Come ye now, let us give Argive Helen and the treasure with her unto the sons of Atreus to take away.'),(2274,'  Now do we fight after proving false to our oaths of faith, '),(2275,'wherefore have I no hope that aught will issue to our profit, if we do not thus.\" '),(2276,'When he had thus spoken he sate him down, '),(2277,'and among them uprose  goodly Alexander, lord of fair-haired Helen; he made answer, and spake to him winged words:'),(2278,'Antenor, this that thou sayest is no longer to my pleasure;'),(2279,'yea thou knowest how to devise better words than these.'),(2280,'  But if thou verily speakest this in earnest,  then of a surety have the gods themselves destroyed thy wits. '),(2281,'Howbeit I will speak amid the gathering of horse-taming Trojans and declare outright:'),(2282,'my wife will I not give back; '),(2283,'but the treasure that I brought from Argos to our home, all this am I minded to give, and to add thereto from mine own store.'),(2284,' When he had thus spoken he sate him down,'),(2285,'\nand among them uprose Priam, son of Dardanus, peer of the gods in counsel.  He with good intent addressed their gathering, and spake among them:'),(2286,' \"Hearken to me, ye Trojans and Dardanians and allies, that I may say what the heart in my breast biddeth me.'),(2287,'  For this present take ye your supper throughout the city, even as of old, and take heed to keep watch, and be wakeful every man; '),(2288,'and at dawn let Idaeus go to the hollow ships to declare to Atreus\' sons, Agamemnon and Menelaus, the word of Alexander, for whose sake strife hath been set afoot.'),(2289,'  And let him furthermore declare to them this word of wisdom, whether they are minded to cease from dolorous war till we have burned the dead; '),(2290,'thereafter shall we fight again until God judge between us, and give victory to one side or the other.'),(2291,'So spake he, and they readily hearkened to him, and obeyed; '),(2292,' then they took their supper throughout the host by companies,'),(2293,'and at dawn Idaeus went his way to the hollow ships.'),(2294,'  There he found in the place of gathering the Danaans, squires of Ares, beside the stern of Agamemnon\'s ship; '),(2295,'and the loud-voiced herald took his stand in the midst and spake among them:'),(2296,'  \"Son of Atreus, and ye other princes of the hosts of Achaea, Priam and the other lordly Trojans bade me declare to you—if haply it be your wish and your good pleasure—the saying of Alexander, for whose sake strife hath been set afoot.'),(2297,'The treasure that Alexander brought to Troy  in his hollow ships'),(2298,'—would that he had perished first!'),(2299,'—all this he is minded to give, and to add thereto from his own store'),(2300,'but the wedded wife of glorious Menelaus, he declares he will not give; '),(2301,'though verily the Trojans bid him do it'),(2302,'Moreover they bade me declare unto you this word also, whether ye be minded  to cease from dolorous war till we have burned the dead; '),(2303,'thereafter shall we fight again until God judge between us and give victory to one side or the other.\" '),(2304,'So spake he, and they all became hushed in silence.'),(2305,' But at length there spake among them Diomedes, good at the war-cry:'),(2306,'  \"Let no man now accept the treasure from Alexander, nay, nor Helen; '),(2307,'known is it, even to him who hath no wit at all, that now the cords of destruction are made fast upon the Trojans.'),(2308,'So spake he, and all the sons of the Achaeans shouted aloud, applauding the saying of Diomedes, tamer of horses.'),(2309,' Then to Idaeus spake lord Agamemnon:'),(2310,' \"Idaeus, verily of thyself thou hearest the word of the Achaeans, how they make answer to thee; and mine own pleasure is even as theirs.'),(2311,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 7.407-7.408'),(2312,' But as touching the dead I in no wise grudge that ye burn them;  ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 407 to line 411'),(2313,'But to our oaths let Zeus be witness, the loud-thundering lord of Hera.'),(2314,'So saying, he lifted up his staff before the face of all the gods, and Idaeus went his way back to sacred Ilios.  '),(2315,'Now they were sitting in assembly, Trojans and Dardanians alike,  all gathered in one body waiting until Idaeus should come;'),(2316,'and he came and stood in their midst and declared his message.'),(2317,'  Then they made them ready with all speed for either task, some to bring the dead, and others to seek for wood.'),(2318,'  And the Argives over against them hasted from the benched ships,  some to bring the dead and others to seek for wood.'),(2319,'The sun was now just striking on the fields, as he rose from softly-gliding, deep-flowing Oceanus, and climbed the heavens, when the two hosts met together.'),(2320,'Then was it a hard task to know each man again;  '),(2321,'Then was it a hard task to know each man again;'),(2322,'\n howbeit with water they washed from them the clotted blood,'),(2323,'But great Priam would not suffer his folk to wail aloud; '),(2324,' so in silence they heaped the corpses upon the pyre, their hearts sore stricken; and when they had burned them with fire they went their way to sacred Ilios.'),(2325,'  And in like manner over against them the well-greaved Achaeans heaped the corpses upon the pyre, their hearts sore stricken, and when they had burned them with fire they went their way to the hollow ships.'),(2326,'Now when dawn was not yet, but night was still \'twixt light and dark, then was there gathered about the pyre the chosen host of the Achaeans,  and they made about it a single barrow, rearing it from the plain for all alike; and thereby they built a wall and a lofty rampart, a defence for their ships and for themselves.'),(2327,'  And therein they made gates, close-fastening, that through them might be a way for the driving of chariots.'),(2328,'  And without they dug a deep ditch hard by, wide and great, and therein they planted stakes. '),(2329,'Thus were they toiling, the long-haired Achaeans; '),(2330,'and the gods, as they sat by the side of Zeus, the lord of the lightning, marvelled at the great work of the brazen-coated Achaeans.'),(2331,'  And among them Poseidon, the Shaker of Earth, was first to speak: '),(2332,' \"Father Zeus, is there now anyone of mortals on the face of the boundless earth, that will any more declare to the immortals his mind and counsel?'),(2333,' Seest thou not that now again the long-haired Achaeans have builded them a wall to defend their ships, and about it have drawn a trench,'),(2334,'  but gave not glorious hecatombs to the gods?'),(2335,'  Of a surety shall the fame thereof reach as far as the dawn spreadeth, and men will forget the wall that I and Phoebus Apollo built with toil for the warrior Laomedon.\"'),(2336,'Then greatly troubled, Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, spake to him:'),(2337,' \"Ah me, thou Shaker of Earth, wide of sway, what a thing thou hast said!'),(2338,'Another of the gods might haply fear this device, whoso was feebler far than thou in hand and might; whereas thy fame shall of a surety reach as far as the dawn spreadeth.'),(2339,'whereas thy fame shall of a surety reach as far as the dawn spreadeth.'),(2340,'  Go to now, when once the long-haired Achaeans have gone with their ships to their dear native land,  then do thou burst apart the wall and sweep it all into the sea, and cover the great beach again with sand, that so the great wall of the Achaeans may be brought to naught of thee.\"'),(2341,'On this wise spake they, one to the other,  and the sun set, and the work of the Achaeans was accomplished; and they slaughtered oxen throughout the huts and took supper.'),(2342,'  And ships full many were at hand from Lemnos, bearing wine, sent forth by Jason\'s son, Euneus, whom Hypsipyle bare to Jason, shepherd of the host.'),(2343,'  And for themselves alone unto the sons of Atreus, Agamemnon and Menelaus, had Euneus given wine to be brought them, even a thousand measures.'),(2344,'  From these ships the long-haired Achaeans bought them wine, some for bronze, some for gleaming iron, some for hides, some for whole cattle, '),(2345,' and some for slaves; and they made them a rich feast'),(2346,'So the whole night through the long-haired Achaeans feasted, and the Trojans likewise in the city, and their allies; '),(2347,'and all night long Zeus, the counsellor, devised them evil, thundering in terrible wise.'),(2348,'  Then pale fear gat hold of them, '),(2349,' and they let the wine flow from their cups upon the ground, neither durst any man drink until he had made a drink-offering to the son of Cronos, supreme in might.'),(2350,'  Then they laid them down, and took the gift of sleep.'),(2351,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 8.1-8.3'),(2352,' Now Dawn the saffron-robed was spreading over the face of all the earth, and Zeus that hurleth the thunderbolt made a gathering of the gods upon the topmost peak of many-ridged Olympus, ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 1 to line 4'),(2353,'  \"Hearken unto me, all ye gods and goddesses, that I may speak what the heart in my breast biddeth me.'),(2354,'Let not any goddess nor yet any god essay this thing, to thwart my word, but do ye all alike assent thereto, that with all speed I may bring these deeds to pass.'),(2355,'  Whomsoever I shall mark minded apart from the gods to go and bear aid either to Trojans or Danaans, smitten in no seemly wise shall he come back to Olympus,'),(2356,'the gates whereof are of iron and the threshold of bronze, as far beneath Hades as heaven is above earth: '),(2357,' then shall ye know how far the mightiest am I of all gods.'),(2358,'Nay, come, make trial, ye gods, that ye all may know.'),(2359,'Make ye fast from heaven a chain of gold,  and lay ye hold thereof, all ye gods and all goddesses; '),(2360,'yet could ye not drag to earth from out of heaven Zeus the counsellor most high, not though ye laboured sore.'),(2361,'  But whenso I were minded to draw of a ready heart, then with earth itself should I draw you and with sea withal; '),(2362,' and the rope should I thereafter bind about a peak of Olympus and all those things should hang in space.'),(2363,'  By so much am I above gods and above men.\"'),(2364,'So spake he, and they all became hushed in silence, marvelling at his words;'),(2365,'for full masterfully did he address their gathering.'),(2366,'  But at length there spake among them the goddess, flashing-eyed Athene:\"'),(2367,'Father of us all, thou son of Cronos, high above all lords, well know we of ourselves that thy might is unyielding,'),(2368,'yet even so have we pity for the Danaan spearmen who now shall perish and fulfill an evil fate.'),(2369,' Yet verily will we refrain us from battle, even as thou dost bid;'),(2370,' howbeit counsel will we offer to the Argives which shall be for their profit, that they perish not all by reason of thy wrath.\"'),(2371,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 8.38'),(2372,'Be of good cheer, Tritogeneia, dear child.  '),(2373,'do not lose heart; for I say this not in outright anger, and my meaning toward you is kindly.'),(2374,'So saying, he let harness beneath his car his bronze-hooved horses, swift of flight, with flowing manes of gold; and with gold he clad himself about his body, and grasped the well-wrought whip of gold, and stepped upon his car  and touched the horses with the lash to start them; '),(2375,'and nothing loath the pair sped onward midway between earth and starry heaven.'),(2376,'  To Ida he fared, the many-fountained, mother of wild beasts, even to Gargarus, where is his demesne and his fragrant altar.'),(2377,'  There did the father of men and gods stay his horses,  and loose them from the car, and shed thick mist upon them; '),(2378,'and himself sat amid the mountain peaks exulting in his glory, looking upon the city of the Trojans and the ships of the Achaeans.'),(2379,'But the long-haired Achaeans took their meal hastily throughout the huts, and as they rose up therefrom arrayed them in armour; '),(2380,' and in like manner, the Trojans, on their side, armed themselves throughout the city;'),(2381,'fewer they were, but even so were they eager to contend in battle through utter need, for their children\'s sake and their wives'),(2382,'  And all the gates were opened, and the host hasted forth, footmen alike and charioteers; '),(2383,'and a great din arose.'),(2384,'  But when they were met together and come into one place, then clashed they their shields and spears, and the fury of bronze-mailed warriors; '),(2385,'and the bossed shields closed each with each, and a great din arose.'),(2386,'  Then were heard alike the sound of groaning and the cry of triumph  of the slayers and the slain, and the earth flowed with blood.    '),(2387,'Now as long as it was morn and the sacred day was waxing, so long the missiles of either side struck home, and the folk kept falling.'),(2388,'  But when the sun had reached mid heaven, then verily the Father lifted on high his golden scales,  and set therein two fates of grievous death, one for the horse-taming Trojans, and one for the brazen-coated Achaeans; then he grasped the balance by the midst and raised it, '),(2389,'  But when the sun had reached mid heaven, then verily the Father lifted on high his golden scales,  and set therein two fates of grievous death, one for the horse-taming Trojans, and one for the brazen-coated Achaeans; then he grasped the balance by the midst and raised it, '),(2390,'and down sank the day of doom of the Achaeans.'),(2391,' So the Achaeans\' fates settled down upon the bounteous earth and those of the Trojans were raised aloft toward wide heaven.'),(2392,'  Then himself he thundered aloud from Ida, and sent a blazing flash amid the host of the Achaeans; '),(2393,'and at sight thereof they were seized with wonder, and pale fear gat hold of all. '),(2394,'Then had neither Idomeneus the heart to abide, nor Agamemnon, nor yet the Aiantes twain, squires of Ares; '),(2395,' only Nestor of Gerenia abode, the warder of the Achaeans, and he nowise of his own will, but his horse was sore wounded, seeing goodly Alexander, lord of fair-haired Helen, had smitten him with an arrow upon the crown of the head where the foremost hairs of horses grow upon the skull, and where is the deadliest spot.'),(2396,'  So, stung with agony the horse leapt on high as the arrow sank into his brain, and he threw into confusion horses and car as he writhed upon the bronze.'),(2397,'  And while the old man sprang forth and with his sword was cutting away the traces, meanwhile the swift horses of Hector came on through the tumult, bearing a bold charioteer,  even Hector. '),(2398,'And now would the old man here have lost his life, had not Diomedes, good at the war-cry, been quick to see; and he shouted with a terrible shout, urging on Odysseus:\"'),(2399,'And now would the old man here have lost his life, had not Diomedes, good at the war-cry, been quick to see; and he shouted with a terrible shout, urging on Odysseus:\"'),(2400,'Zeus-born son of Laërtes, Odysseus of many wiles, whither fleest thou with thy back turned, like a coward in the throng?'),(2401,'  Let it not be that as thou fleest some man plant his spear in thy back.'),(2402,''),(2403,'  Nay, hold thy ground, that we may thrust back from old Nestor this wild warrior.\"\nSo spake he, howbeit the much-enduring goodly Odysseus heard him not, but hasted by to the hollow ships of the Achaeans.  '),(2404,'But the son of Tydeus, alone though he was, mingled with the foremost fighters,  and took his stand before the horses of the old man, Neleus\' son, and spake and addressed him with winged words:\"'),(2405,'Old sir, of a surety young warriors press thee sore; whereas thy might is broken and grievous old age attends thee, and thy squire is a weakling and thy horses slow.'),(2406,'  Nay, come, mount upon my car, that thou mayest see of what sort are the horses of Tros, well skilled to course fleetly hither and thither over the plain whether in pursuit or in flight, even those that once I took from Aeneas, devisers of rout.  '),(2407,'Thy horses shall our two squires tend, but these twain  shall thou and I drive straight against the horse-taming Trojans, that Hector too may know whether my spear also rageth in my hands.\" '),(2408,' \nSo spake he, and the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, failed not to hearken.'),(2409,'So the mares of Nestor were tended by the two squires, valiant Sthenelus and Eurymedon the kindly; '),(2410,' and the other twain mounted both upon the car of Diomedes.'),(2411,'Nestor took in his hands the shining reins, and touched the horses with the lash,'),(2412,'and speedily they drew nigh to Hector.'),(2413,'  Upon him then as he charged straight at them the son of Tydeus made a cast: '),(2414,'him he missed, but his squire that drave the chariot, Eniopeus, son of Thebaeus, high of heart,  even as he was holding the reins, he smote on the breast beside the nipple.'),(2415,' So he fell from out the car, and the swift-footed horses swerved aside thereat;'),(2416,'and there his spirit and his strength were undone.'),(2417,'  Then was the soul of Hector clouded with dread sorrow for his charioteer.'),(2418,'  Yet left he him to lie there, albeit he sorrowed for his comrade, and sought him a bold charioteer; '),(2419,'nor did his horses twain long lack a master,'),(2420,'for straightway he  found  Iphitus\'  son, bold Archeptolemus, and made him mount behind his swift-footed horses, and gave the reins into his hands.'),(2421,'  Then had ruin come and deeds beyond remedy been wrought, and they had been penned in Ilios like lambs, had not the father of men and gods been quick to see.'),(2422,'  He thundered terribly and let fly his white lightning-bolt, and down before the horses of Diomedes he hurled it to earth; '),(2423,' and a terrible flame arose of burning sulphur, and the two horses, seized with terror, cowered beneath the car.'),(2424,'  Then from the hands of Nestor slipped the shining reins, and he waxed afraid at heart, and spake to Diomedes:\"'),(2425,'Son of Tydeus, come now, turn thou in flight thy single-hooved horses.'),(2426,'  Seest thou not that victory from Zeus waited not on thee?'),(2427,'  Now to yon man doth Zeus, the son of Cronos, vouchsafe glory for this day;'),(2428,'hereafter shall he grant it also to us, if so be he will.'),(2429,' But a man may in no wise thwart the purpose of Zeus, be he never so valiant; for in sooth he is mightier far.'),(2430,'   And in answer to him spake Diomedes, good at the war cry:\"'),(2431,'Yea, verily, old sir, all this hast thou spoken according to right.'),(2432,' But herein dread grief cometh upon my heart and soul,'),(2433,' for Hector will some day say, as he speaketh in the gathering of the Trojans:'),(2434,'‘Tydeus\' son, driven in flight before me, betook him to the ships.'),(2435,'and then let the wide earth open beneath me.'),(2436,'and then let the wide earth open beneath me.'),(2437,'And in answer to him spake the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia:\"'),(2438,'Ah me, thou son of wise-hearted Tydeus, what a thing hast thou said!  '),(2439,'For though Hector shall call thee coward and weakling, yet will not the Trojans or the Dardanians hearken to him,  nor the wives of the great-souled Trojans, bearers of the shield, they whose lusty husbands thou hast hurled in the dust.'),(2440,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 8.157-8.158'),(2441,'So spake he, and turned in flight his single-hooved horses, back through the tumult; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 157 to line 160'),(2442,' Over him then shouted aloud great Hector of the flashing helm:'),(2443,'\"Son of Tydeus, above all others were the Danaans with swift steeds wont to honour thee with a seat of honour and meats and full cups, but now will they scorn thee;'),(2444,' thou art, it appeareth, no better than a woman.'),(2445,' thou art, it appeareth, no better than a woman.'),(2446,'  Begone, cowardly puppet; since through no flinching of mine  shalt thou mount upon our walls, and carry away our women in thy ships; '),(2447,'before that will I deal thee thy doom.'),(2448,'So spake he, and the son of Tydeus was divided in counsel whether he should not wheel his horses and fight him face to face.'),(2449,'Thrice he wavered in heart and soul  and thrice from the mountains of Ida Zeus the counsellor thundered, giving to the Trojans a sign and victory to turn the tide of battle.'),(2450,'And Hector shouted aloud and called to the Trojans:'),(2451,'\"Ye Trojans and Lycians and Dardanians, that fight in close combat, be men, my friends, and bethink you of furious valour.'),(2452,'  I perceive that of a ready heart the son of Cronos hath given unto me victory and great glory, and to the Danaans woe.'),(2453,'  Fools they are, that contrived forsooth these walls, weak and of none account;'),(2454,'these shall not withhold our might, '),(2455,'and our horses shall lightly leap over the digged ditch.'),(2456,'  But when I be at length come amid the hollow ships, then see ye that consuming fire be not forgotten, that with fire I may burn the ships and furthermore slay the men, even the Argives beside their ships, distraught by reason of the smoke.\"'),(2457,'So saying he shouted to his horses, and said: '),(2458,'\"Xanthus, and thou Podargus, and Aethon, and goodly Lampus,  now pay me back your tending wherewith in abundance Andromache, daughter of great-hearted Eëtion, set before you honey-hearted wheat, and mingled wine for you to drink when your souls bade you,  sooner than for me, that avow me to be her stalwart husband.'),(2459,'Nay, haste ye in pursuit, that we may take the shield of Nestor, the fame whereof now reacheth unto heaven, that it is all of gold, the rods alike and the shield itself; and may take moreover from the shoulders of horse-taming Diomedes  his breastplate richly-dight, which Hephaestus wrought with toil. '),(2460,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 8.196-8.197'),(2461,'So spake he vauntingly, and queenly Hera had indignation thereat; she shook herself on her throne and made high Olympus to quake,  and to the mighty god Poseidon she spake, saying:'),(2462,'\"Ah me, thou Shaker of Earth, wide of sway, not even hath the heart in thy breast pity of the Danaans that are perishing.'),(2463,'  Yet in thine honour do they bring to  Helice and  Aegae  offerings many and gracious '),(2464,'and hitherto thou didst wish them victory.'),(2465,'  For did we but will, all we that are aiders of the Danaans, to drive back the Trojans and to withhold Zeus whose voice is borne afar, then, in vexation of spirit, would he sit alone there upon Ida.\"'),(2466,'Then, his heart sore troubled, the lord, the Shaker of Earth, spake to her:\"'),(2467,'Hera, reckless in speech, what a word hast thou spoken!'),(2468,'  It is not I that were fain to see us all at strife with Zeus, son of Cronos, for he verily is mightier far.\"'),(2469,'On this wise spake they, one to the other; '),(2470,'and now was all the space that the moat of the wall enclosed on the side of the ships filled alike with chariots and shield-bearing men  huddled together: '),(2471,'and huddled they were by Hector, Priam\'s son, the peer of swift Ares, now that Zeus vouchsafed him glory.'),(2472,'  And now would he have burned the shapely ships with blazing fire, had not queenly Hera put it in Agamemnon\'s mind himself to bestir him, and speedily rouse on the Achaeans.'),(2473,'  So he went his way along the huts and ships of the Achaeans, bearing his great purple cloak in his stout hand, and took his stand by Odysseus\' black ship, huge of hull, that was in the midst so that a shout could reach to either end, both to the huts of Aias, son of Telamon,  and to those of Achilles; for these had drawn up their shapely ships at the furthermost ends, trusting in their valour and in the strength of their hands.'),(2474,' There uttered he a piercing shout, calling aloud to the Danaans:\"'),(2475,'Fie, ye Argives, base things of shame fair in semblance only.'),(2476,'  Whither are gone our boastings, when forsooth we declared that we were bravest, the boasts that when ye were in Lemnos ye uttered vaingloriously as ye ate abundant flesh of straight-horned kine and drank bowls brim full of wine, saying that each man would stand to face in battle an hundred, aye, two hundred Trojans!'),(2477,' whereas now can we match not even one,  this Hector, that soon will burn our ships with blazing fire. '),(2478,'Father Zeus, was there ever ere now one among mighty kings whose soul thou didst blind with blindness such as this, and rob him of great glory?'),(2479,'Yet of a surety do I deem that never in my benched ship did I pass by fair altar of thine on my ill-starred way hither,  but upon all I burned the fat and the thighs of bulls, in my eagerness to lay waste well-walled Troy.'),(2480,'  Nay, Zeus, this desire fulfill thou me:'),(2481,' ourselves at least do thou suffer to flee and escape, and permit not the Achaeans thus to be vanquished by the Trojans.\" '),(2482,'  So spake he, and the Father had pity on him as he wept, and vouchsafed him that his folk should be saved and not perish.'),(2483,'  Forthwith he sent an eagle, surest of omens among winged birds, holding in his talons a fawn, the young of a swift hind.'),(2484,'  Beside the fair altar of Zeus he let fall the fawn,  even where the Achaeans were wont to offer sacrifice to Zeus from whom all omens come.  '),(2485,'So they, when they saw that it was from Zeus that the bird was come, leapt the more upon the Trojans and bethought them of battle.'),(2486,'Then might no man of the Danaans, for all they were so many, vaunt that he before the son of Tydeus guided his swift horses  to drive them forth across the trench and to fight man to man; nay he was first by far to slay a mailed warrior of the Trojans, even Agelaus, Phradraon\'s son.'),(2487,'  He in sooth had turned his horses to flee, '),(2488,'but as he wheeled about Diomedes fixed his spear in his back between the shoulders, and drave it through his breast;'),(2489,' so he fell from out the car, and upon him his armour clanged.'),(2490,'And after him came the sons of Atreus, Agamemnon and Menelaus, and after them the Aiantes, clothed in furious valour, and after them Idomeneus and Idomeneus\' comrade, Meriones, peer of Enyalius, slayer of men,  and after them Eurypylus, the glorious son of Euaemon;'),(2491,'and Teucer came as the ninth, stretching his back-bent bow, and took his stand beneath the shield of Aias, son of Telamon.'),(2492,' Then would Aias move his shield aside from over him'),(2493,'and the warrior would spy his chance; and when he had shot his bolt and had smitten one in the throng,  then would that man fall where he was and give up his life, and Teucer would hie him back, and as a child beneath his mother, so betake him for shelter to Aias;'),(2494,'and Aias would ever hide him with his shining shield.'),(2495,'Whom first then of the Trojans did peerless Teucer slay?  '),(2496,'Orsilochus first and Ormenus and Ophelestes and  Daetor and Chromius and godlike Lycophontes and Amopaon, Polyaemon\'s son, and Melanippus.  All these, one after another, he brought down to the bounteous  earth.'),(2497,'  And at sight of him Agamemnon, king of men, waxed glad, as with his mighty bow he made havoc of the battalions of the Trojans;'),(2498,' and he came and stood by his side and spake to him, saying:'),(2499,'\"Teucer, beloved, son of Telamon, captain of hosts, shoot on in this wise, if so be thou mayest prove a light of deliverance to the Danaans and a glory to thy father Telamon, who reared thee when thou wast a babe, and for all thou wast a bastard cherished thee in his own house;'),(2500,' him, far away though he be, do thou bring to honour.'),(2501,'Moreover, I will declare to thee as it verily shall be brought to pass. '),(2502,' If Zeus that beareth the aegis, and Athene shall vouchsafe me to lay waste the well-built citadel of Ilios, in thy hand first after mine own self will I place a meed of honour,  either a tripod or two horses with their car, or a woman that shall go up into thy bed.\" '),(2503,'Then in answer to him spake peerless Teucer:'),(2504,' \"Most glorious son of Atreus, why urgest thou me on, that of myself am eager?  '),(2505,'Verily I forbear not so far as might is in me,  but from the time when we drave them toward Ilios, even from that moment I lie in wait with my bow and slay the men.'),(2506,'  Eight long-barbed arrows have I now let fly, and all are lodged in the flesh of youths swift in battle; '),(2507,'only this mad dog can I not smite.\"'),(2508,'  He spake, and shot another arrow from the string straight against Hector; and his heart was fain to smite him.'),(2509,'  Howbeit him he missed, but peerless Gorgythion he smote in the breast with his arrow, Priam\'s valiant son, that a mother wedded from Aesyme had born,  even fair Castianeira, in form like to the goddesses.  '),(2510,'And he bowed his head to one side like a poppy that in a garden is laden with its fruit and the rains of spring; so bowed he to one side his head, laden with his helmet.'),(2511,'And Teucer shot another arrow from the string  straight against Hector, and his heart was fain to smite him.'),(2512,'for Apollo made his dart to swerve,'),(2513,'for Apollo made his dart to swerve,'),(2514,'but Archeptolemus, the bold charioteer of Hector, as he hasted into battle he smote on the breast beside the nipple.'),(2515,' So he fell from out the car, and the swift-footed horses swerved aside thereat; '),(2516,' and there his spirit and his strength were undone.'),(2517,'Then was the soul of Hector clouded with dread sorrow for his charioteer.'),(2518,'Yet left he him to lie there, though he sorrowed for his comrade, and bade Cebriones, his own brother, that was nigh at hand, take the reins of the horses;'),(2519,' and he heard and failed not to hearken.'),(2520,'  And himself Hector leapt to the ground from his gleaming car crying a terrible cry, '),(2521,'and seizing a stone in his hand made right at Teucer, and his heart bade him smite him.'),(2522,'Now Teucer had drawn forth from the quiver a bitter arrow, and laid it upon the string, '),(2523,'but even as he was drawing it back Hector of the flashing helm  smote him beside the shoulder where the collar-bone parts the neck and the breast, where is the deadliest spot;'),(2524,'but his hand grew numb at the wrist, and he sank upon his knees and thus abode, and the bow fell from his hand.'),(2525,'  Howbeit Aias was not unmindful of his brother\'s fall, but ran and bestrode him and flung before him his shield as a cover.'),(2526,'  Then two trusty comrades stooped beneath him, even Mecisteus, son of Echius, and goodly Alastor, and bare him, groaning heavily, to the hollow ships. '),(2527,'  Then once again the Olympian aroused might in the hearts of the Trojans; '),(2528,'and they thrust the Achaeans straight toward the deep ditch; '),(2529,' as Hektor ranged in their foremost ranks in the pride of his great strength.'),(2530,'And even as a hound pursueth with swift feet after a wild boar or a lion, and snatcheth at him from behind  either at flank or buttock, and watcheth for him as he wheeleth; even so Hector pressed upon the long-haired Achaeans, ever slaying the hindmost; '),(2531,' and they were driven in rout.'),(2532,'But when in their flight  they had passed through stakes and trench, and many had been vanquished beneath the hands of the Trojans,  then beside their ships they halted and abode, calling one upon the other, and lifting up their hands to all the gods they made fervent prayer each man of them.'),(2533,'  But Hector wheeled this way and that his fair-maned horses, and his eyes were as the eyes of the Gorgon or of Ares, bane of mortals.'),(2534,'  Now at sight of them the goddess, white-armed Hera, had pity; and forthwith spake winged words to Athene:\"'),(2535,'Out upon it, thou child of Zeus that beareth the aegis, shall not we twain any more take thought of the Danaans that are perishing, even for this last time?  '),(2536,'Now will they fill up the measure of evil doom and perish  before the onset of one single man, even of Hector, Priam\'s son, who now rageth past all bearing, and lo, hath wrought evils manifold.\"'),(2537,'Then spake unto her the goddess, flashing-eyed Athene:\"'),(2538,'Yea, verily, fain were I that this fellow lose strength and life, slain beneath the hands of the Argives in his own native land; '),(2539,'  howbeit mine own father rageth with evil mind, cruel that he is, ever froward, a thwarter of my purposes; '),(2540,'neither hath he any memory of this, that full often I saved his son when he was fordone by reason of Eurystheus\' tasks.'),(2541,'For verily he would make lament toward heaven and from heaven would Zeus  send me forth to succour him.  '),(2542,'Had I but known all this in wisdom of my heart when Eurystheus sent him forth to the house of Hades the Warder, to bring from out of Erebus the hound of loathed Hades, then had he not escaped the sheer-falling waters of Styx.'),(2543,'  Howbeit now Zeus hateth me, and hath brought to fulfillment the counsels of Thetis, that kissed his knees and with her hand clasped his chin, beseeching him to show honour to Achilles, sacker of cities.'),(2544,'  Verily the day shall come when he shall again call me his flashing-eyed darling. '),(2545,'But now make thou ready for us twain our single-hooved horses,  the while I enter into the palace of Zeus, that beareth the aegis, and array me in armour for battle, to the end that I may see whether Priam\'s son, Hector of the flashing helm, will rejoice when we twain appear to view along the dykes of battle. Nay of a surety many a one of the Trojans shall glut the dogs and birds '),(2546,'So spake she, and the goddess, white-armed Hera, failed not to hearken.'),(2547,'  She then went to and fro harnessing the horses of golden frontlets, even Hera, the queenly goddess, daughter of great Cronos; '),(2548,'but Athene, daughter of Zeus that beareth the aegis,  let fall upon her father\'s floor her soft robe, richly broidered, that herself had wrought and her hands had fashioned, and put on her the tunic of Zeus the cloud-gatherer, and arrayed her in armour for tearful war.'),(2549,'Then she stepped upon the flaming car and grasped her spear,  heavy and huge and strong, wherewith she vanquisheth the ranks of men, of warriors with whom she is wroth, she the daughter of the mighty sire.'),(2550,'And Hera swiftly touched the horses with the lash,'),(2551,'and self-bidden groaned upon their hinges the gates of heaven, which the Hours had in their keeping, to whom are entrusted great heaven and Olympus,  whether to throw open the thick cloud or shut it to.'),(2552,' There through the gate they drave their horses patient of the goad.'),(2553,'But when father Zeus saw them from Ida he waxed wondrous wroth, and sent forth golden-winged Iris to bear a message:\"'),(2554,'Up, go, swift Iris; turn them back and suffer them not to come face to face with me'),(2555,' seeing it will be in no happy wise that we shall join in combat.'),(2556,'For thus will I speak and verily this thing shall be brought to pass.'),(2557,'I will maim their swift horses beneath the chariot, and themselves will I hurl from out the car, and will break in pieces the chariot;'),(2558,' nor in the space of ten circling years  shall they heal them of the wounds wherewith the thunderbolt shall smite them;'),(2559,' that she of the flashing eyes may know what it is to strive against her own father.'),(2560,'But against Hera have I not so great indignation nor wrath'),(2561,' seeing she is ever wont to thwart me in whatsoe\'er I have decreed.'),(2562,'So spake he, and storm-footed Iris hasted to bear his message,  and went forth from the mountains of Ida to high Olympus.'),(2563,'And even at the entering-in of the gate of many-folded Olympus she met them and stayed them, and declared to them the saying of Zeus:'),(2564,'Why is it that the hearts are mad within your breasts? '),(2565,'Why is it that the hearts are mad within your breasts? '),(2566,'The son of Cronos suffereth not that ye give succour to the Argives. '),(2567,'For on this wise he threateneth, even as he will bring it to pass: he will maim your swift horses beneath your chariot, and yourselves will he hurl from out the car, and will break in pieces the chariot'),(2568,'nor in the space of ten circling years shall ye heal you of the wounds wherewith the thunderbolt shall smite you;'),(2569,' that thou mayest know, thou of the flashing eyes, what it is to strive against thine own father. '),(2570,'But against Hera hath he not so great indignation nor wrath,'),(2571,'seeing she is ever wont to thwart him in whatsoe\'er he hath decreed.'),(2572,'  But most dread art thou, thou bold and shameless thing, if in good sooth thou wilt dare to raise thy mighty spear against Zeus.\" '),(2573,'  When she had thus spoken swift-footed Iris departed; but Hera spake to Athene, saying:\"'),(2574,'Out upon it, thou child of Zeus that beareth the aegis! I verily will no more suffer that we twain seek to wage war against Zeus for mortals\' sake.'),(2575,'  Of them let one perish and another live,  even as it may befall; '),(2576,'and for him, let him take his own counsel in his heart and judge between Trojans and Danaans, as is meet.'),(2577,'So spake she, and turned back her single-hooved horses.'),(2578,'  Then the Hours unyoked for them their fair-maned horses, and tethered them at their ambrosial mangers,  and leaned the chariot against the bright entrance wall; '),(2579,'and the goddesses sate them down upon golden thrones amid the other gods, with sore grief at heart.'),(2580,'But father Zeus drave from Ida his well-wheeled chariot and his horses unto Olympus, and came to the session of the gods.'),(2581,'  And for him the famed Shaker of Earth both unyoked his horses and set the car upon a stand, and spread thereover a cloth; '),(2582,'and Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, himself sat upon his throne of gold, and beneath his feet great Olympus quaked.'),(2583,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 8.444-8.445'),(2584,'Only Athene and Hera  sat apart from Zeus, and spake no word to him nor made question. ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 444 to line 446'),(2585,'  \"Why are ye thus grieved, Athene and Hera?'),(2586,'Surely ye twain be not grown weary with making havoc of the Trojans in battle, wherein men win glory, seeing ye cherish against them wondrous hate!'),(2587,'  Come what will, seeing I have such might and hands irresistible, all the gods that are in Olympus could not turn me; '),(2588,'and for you twain, trembling gat hold of your glorious limbs or ever ye had sight of war and the grim deeds of war.'),(2589,' For thus will I speak, and verily this thing had been brought to pass:'),(2590,'  not upon your car, once ye were smitten by the thunderbolt, would ye have fared back to Olympus, where is the abode of the immortals.\"'),(2591,'So spake he, and thereat murmured Athene and Hera,'),(2592,' that sat by his side and were devising ills for the Trojans.'),(2593,'Athene verily held her peace and said naught,  wroth though she was with father Zeus, and fierce anger gat hold of her; '),(2594,'howbeit Hera\'s breast contained not her anger, but she spake to him, saying:\"'),(2595,'Most dread son of Cronos, what a word hast thou said!'),(2596,'Well know we of ourselves that thine is no weakling strength; '),(2597,'yet even so have we pity for the Danaan spearmen  who now shall perish and fulfill an evil fate.'),(2598,'Yet verily will we refrain us from battle, if so thou biddest;'),(2599,'howbeit counsel will we offer to the Argives which shall be for their profit, that they perish not all by reason of thy wrath.\" '),(2600,'Then in answer spake to her Zeus the cloud-gatherer:'),(2601,'  \"At dawn shalt thou behold, if so be thou  wilt, O  ox-eyed, queenly  Hera,  the most mighty son of Cronos making yet more grievous havoc of the great host of Argive spearmen; '),(2602,'for dread Hector shall not  refrain him from battle until the  swift-footed son of Peleus be uprisen beside his ships  on the day when at the sterns of the ships they shall be fighting in grimmest stress about Patroclus fallen; '),(2603,'for thus it is ordained of heaven. '),(2604,'But of thee I reck not in thine anger, no, not though thou shouldst go to the nethermost bounds of earth and sea, where abide Iapetus and Cronos,  and have joy neither in the rays of Helios Hyperion nor in any breeze, but deep Tartarus is round about them.'),(2605,' Though thou shouldst fare even thither in thy wanderings, yet reck I not of thy wrath, seeing there is naught more shameless than thou.\"'),(2606,'So said he; howbeit white-armed Hera spake no word in answer.'),(2607,'  Then into Oceanus fell the bright light of the sun drawing black night over the face of the earth, the giver of grain.'),(2608,'  Sorely against the will of the Trojans sank the daylight, but over the Achaeans welcome, aye, thrice-prayed-for, came the darkness of night.'),(2609,'Then did glorious Hector make a gathering of the Trojans,  leading them apart from the ships beside the eddying river in an open space, where the ground shewed clear of dead.'),(2610,'  Forth from their chariots they stepped upon the ground, to hearken to the word that Hector dear to Zeus spake among them.'),(2611,' In his hand he held a spear of eleven cubits, '),(2612,'and before him blazed  the spear-point of bronze, around which ran a ring of gold.'),(2613,'Thereon he leaned, and spake his word among the Trojans:\"'),(2614,'Hearken to me, ye Trojans and Dardanians and allies: I deemed  but now to make havoc of the ships and all the Achaeans, and so return back again to windy Ilios; '),(2615,'but darkness came on ere that might be, the which above all else hath now saved the Argives and their ships upon the beach of the sea.'),(2616,'So then for this present let us yield to black night and make ready our supper;'),(2617,'loose ye from the cars your fair-maned horses, and cast fodder before them;'),(2618,'  and from the city bring ye oxen and goodly sheep with speed, and get you honey-hearted wine and bread from your houses, and furthermore gather abundant wood, that all night long until early dawn we may burn fires full many and the gleam thereof may reach to heaven,  lest haply even by night the long-haired Achaeans make haste to take flight over the broad back of the sea.'),(2619,'  Nay, verily, not without a struggle let them board their ships neither at their ease; but see ye that many a one of them has a missile to brood over even at home, being smitten either with an arrow or sharp-pointed spear  as he leapt upon his ship; that so others may dread to bring tearful war against the horse-taming Trojans.'),(2620,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 8.517-8.519'),(2621,' And let heralds, dear to Zeus, make proclamation throughout the city that stripling boys and old men of hoary temples gather them round the city upon the battlement builded of the gods;  ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 517 to line 523'),(2622,'and let a diligent watch be kept, lest an ambush enter the city while the host is afield.'),(2623,'Thus be it, great-hearted Trojans, even as I proclaim; '),(2624,'of counsel, good and sound for this present, be this enough;  but more will I proclaim at dawn amid the horse-taming Trojans.  '),(2625,'I pray in high hope to Zeus and the other gods to drive out from hence these dogs borne by the fates, whom the fates bare on their black ships.'),(2626,'Howbeit for the night will we guard our own selves,  but in the morning at the coming of dawn arrayed in our armour let us arouse sharp battle at the hollow ships.'),(2627,'  I shall know whether the son of Tydeus, mighty Diomedes, will thrust me back from the ships to the wall, or whether I shall slay him with the bronze  and bear off his bloody spoils.'),(2628,'  Tomorrow shall he come to know his valour, whether he can abide the on-coming of my spear.'),(2629,'  Nay, amid the foremost, methinks, shall he lie smitten with a spear-thrust, and full many of his comrades round about him at the rising of to-morrow\'s sun. '),(2630,'I would that mine own self I might be immortal and ageless all my days,  and that I might be honoured even as Athene and Apollo, so surely as now this day bringeth evil upon the Argives.'),(2631,'So Hector addressed their gathering, and thereat the Trojans shouted aloud.  '),(2632,'Their sweating horses they loosed from beneath the yoke, and tethered them with thongs, each man beside his own chariot;'),(2633,' and from the city they brought oxen and goodly sheep with speed, and got them honey-hearted wine and bread from their houses, and furthermore gathered abundant wood;'),(2634,'And from the plain the winds bore the savour up into heaven'),(2635,'These then with high hearts abode the whole night through along the dykes of war, and their fires burned in multitudes.'),(2636,'  Even as in heaven about the gleaming moon the stars shine clear, when the air is windless,'),(2637,'and forth to view appear all mountain peaks and high headlands and glades'),(2638,' and from heaven breaketh open the infinite air, and all stars are seen, and the shepherd joyeth in his heart;'),(2639,' even in such multitudes between the ships and the streams of Xanthus shone the fires that the Trojans kindled before the face of Ilios.'),(2640,'A thousand fires were burning in the plain and by each sat fifty men in the glow of the blazing fire.'),(2641,'  And their horses, eating of white barley and spelt, '),(2642,' Thus kept the Trojans watch'),(2643,'but the Achaeans were holden of wondrous Panic, the handmaid of numbing fear and with grief intolerable were all the noblest stricken.'),(2644,'Even as two winds stir up the teeming deep,  the North Wind and the West Wind that blow from Thrace, coming suddenly'),(2645,'and forthwith the dark wave reareth itself in crests and casteth much tangle out along the sea; '),(2646,'even so were the hearts of the Achaeans rent within their breasts.'),(2647,'But the son of Atreus, stricken to the heart with sore grief,  went this way and that, bidding the clear-voiced heralds summon every man by name to the place of gathering, but not to shout aloud;'),(2648,'and himself he toiled amid the foremost.'),(2649,'So they sat in the place of gathering, sore troubled'),(2650,'and Agamemnon stood up weeping even as a fountain of dark water  that down over the face of a beetling cliff poureth its dusky stream'),(2651,'even so with deep groaning spake he amid the Argives, saying:'),(2652,'\"My friends, leaders and rulers of the Argives, great Zeus, son of Cronos, hath ensnared me in grievous blindness of heart, cruel god! seeing that of old he promised me, and bowed his head thereto,  that not until I had sacked well-walled Ilios should I get me home; but now hath he planned cruel deceit, and biddeth me return inglorious to Argos, when I have lost much people.'),(2653,'  So, I ween, must be the good pleasure of Zeus supreme in might, who hath laid low the heads of many cities,  yea, and shall lay low;'),(2654,'for his power is above all.  '),(2655,'Nay, come, even as I shall bid let us all obey:'),(2656,' let us flee with our ships to our dear native land; '),(2657,'for no more is there hope that we shall take broad-wayed Troy.\"'),(2658,'So spake he, and they all became hushed in silence. '),(2659,' Long time were they silent in their grief, the sons of the Achaeans'),(2660,'but at length there spake among them Diomedes, good at the war-cry:'),(2661,'Son of Atreus, with thee first will I contend in thy folly, where it is meet, O king, '),(2662,'even in the place of gathering:'),(2663,'My valour didst thou revile at the first amid the Danaans,  and saidst that I was no man of war but a weakling; '),(2664,'and all this know the Achaeans both young and old.'),(2665,'  But as for thee, the son of crooked-counselling Cronos hath endowed thee in divided wise:'),(2666,' with the sceptre hath he granted thee to be honoured above all, but valour he gave thee not, wherein is the greatest might.'),(2667,'  Strange king, dost thou indeed deem that the sons of the Achaeans are thus unwarlike and weaklings as thou sayest?'),(2668,'Nay, if thine own heart is eager to return, get thee gone;'),(2669,'before thee lies the way, and thy ships stand beside the sea, all the many ships that followed thee from Mycenae.'),(2670,'  Howbeit the other long-haired Achaeans will abide here until we have laid waste Troy.'),(2671,'Nay, let them also flee in their ships to their dear native land; '),(2672,'yet will we twain, Sthenelus and I, fight on, until we win the goal of Ilios; for with the aid of heaven are we come.'),(2673,'yet will we twain, Sthenelus and I, fight on, until we win the goal of Ilios; for with the aid of heaven are we come.'),(2674,'  So spake he, and all the sons of the Achaeans shouted aloud, applauding the word of Diomedes, tamer of horses.'),(2675,'  Then uprose and spake among them the horseman Nestor:\"'),(2676,'Son of Tydeus, above all men art thou mighty in battle,  and in council art the best amid all those of thine own age.  '),(2677,'Not one of all the Achaeans will make light of what thou sayest neither gainsay it'),(2678,' yet hast thou not reached a final end of words.'),(2679,'  Moreover, thou art in sooth but young, thou mightest e\'en be my son, my youngest born; '),(2680,'yet thou givest prudent counsel to the princes of the Argives, seeing thou speakest according to right.'),(2681,'  But come, I that avow me to be older than thou will speak forth and will declare the whole;'),(2682,'neither shall any man scorn my words, no, not even lord Agamemnon.'),(2683,'  A clanless, lawless, hearthless man is he that loveth dread strife among his own folk.'),(2684,'  Howbeit for this present let us yield to black night and make ready our supper; '),(2685,'and let sentinels post themselves severally along the digged ditch without the wall.'),(2686,'  To the young men give I this charge; '),(2687,'but thereafter do thou, son of Atreus, take the lead'),(2688,'for thou art most kingly.'),(2689,'this were but right and seemly for thee.'),(2690,'this were but right and seemly for thee.'),(2691,'Full are thy huts of wine that the ships of the Achaeans bring thee each day from Thrace, over the wide sea; '),(2692,'all manner of entertainment hast thou at hand, seeing thou art king over many.'),(2693,'  And when many are gathered together thou shalt follow him whoso shall devise  the wisest counsel. '),(2694,'And sore need have all the Achaeans of counsel both good and prudent, seeing that foemen hard by the ships are kindling their many watchfires;'),(2695,'what man could rejoice thereat?'),(2696,' This night shall either bring to ruin or save our host.'),(2697,'So spake he, and they readily hearkened to him and obeyed.'),(2698,'  Forth hasted the sentinels in their harness around Nestor\'s son Thrasymedes, shepherd of the host, and Ascalaphus and Ialmenus, sons of Ares, and Meriones and Aphareus and Deïpyrus, and the son of Creon, goodly Lycomedes.'),(2699,'  Seven were the captains of the sentinels, and with each fared an hundred youths bearing long spears in their hands; '),(2700,'then they went and sate them down midway betwixt trench and wall; '),(2701,'and there they kindled a fire and made ready each man his meal. '),(2702,'But the son of Atreus led the counsellors of the Achaeans all together  to his hut, and set before them a feast to satisfy the heart.  '),(2703,'So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them.'),(2704,'  But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, first of all the old man began to weave the web of counsel for them, even Nestor, whose rede had of old ever seemed the best.'),(2705,' He with good intent addressed their gathering and spake among them:'),(2706,'\"Most glorious son of Atreus, Agamemnon, king of men, with thee will I begin and with thee make an end, for that thou art king over many hosts, and to thee Zeus hath vouchsafed the sceptre and judgements, that thou mayest take counsel for thy people.'),(2707,'  Therefore it beseemeth thee above all others both to speak and to hearken, and to fulfilll also for another whatsoever his heart may bid him speak for our profit; '),(2708,'for on thee will depend whatsoever any man may begin.'),(2709,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 9.103'),(2710,'So will I speak what seemeth to me to be best.  ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 103 to line 108'),(2711,'Nay, for I, mine own self, urgently sought to dissuade thee;'),(2712,'but you, giving way to your proud heart\'s anger, dishonored a great man, one whom the immortals honor, since you have taken his prize and keep it.'),(2713,'Howbeit let us still even now take thought how we may make amends, and persuade him with kindly gifts and with gentle words.\" '),(2714,' \nTo him then spake in answer the king of men, Agamemnon:'),(2715,'  \"Old sir, in no false wise hast thou recounted the tale of my blind folly.  '),(2716,'Blind I was, myself I deny it not.'),(2717,'  Of the worth of many hosts is the man whom Zeus loveth in his heart, even as now he honoureth this man and destroyeth the host of the Achaeans.'),(2718,'  Yet seeing I was blind, and yielded to my miserable passion,  I am minded to make amends and to give requital past counting.  '),(2719,'In the midst of you all let me name the glorious gifts; seven tripods that the fire hath not touched, and ten talents of gold and twenty gleaming cauldrons, and twelve strong horses, winners in the race, that have won prizes by their fleetness.'),(2720,'  Not without booty were a man, nor unpossessed of precious gold, whoso had wealth as great as the prizes my single-hooved steeds have won me.'),(2721,'  And I will give seven women skilled in goodly handiwork, women of Lesbos, whom on the day when himself took well-built Lesbos I chose me from out the spoil,  and that in beauty surpass all women folk.'),(2722,'  These will I give him, and amid them shall be she that then I took away, the daughter of Briseus; '),(2723,'and I will furthermore swear a great oath that never went I up into her bed neither had dalliance with her as is the appointed way of mankind, even of men and women.'),(2724,'All these things shall be ready to his hand forthwith;'),(2725,'  and if hereafter it so be the gods grant us to lay waste the great city of Priam, let him then enter in, what time we Achaeans be dividing the spoil, and heap up his ship with store of gold and bronze, and himself choose twenty Trojan women  that be fairest after Argive Helen.'),(2726,' And if we return to Achaean Argos, the richest of lands, he shall be my son, '),(2727,'and I will honour him even as Orestes that is reared in all abundance, my son well-beloved. '),(2728,'Three daughters have I in my well-builded hall,  Chrysothemis, and Laodice, and Iphianassa; of these let him lead to the house of Peleus which one he will, without gifts of wooing, '),(2729,'and I will furthermore give a dower full rich, such as no man ever yet gave with his daughter.'),(2730,'And seven well-peopled cities will I give him,  Cardamyle Enope, and grassy Hire, and sacred Pherae and Antheia with deep meadows, and fair Aepeia and vine-clad Pedasus.'),(2731,'  All are nigh to the sea, on the uttermost border of sandy Pylos, '),(2732,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 9.154-9.156'),(2733,'and in them dwell men rich in flocks and rich in kine,  men that shall honour him with gifts as though he were a god, and beneath his sceptre shall bring his ordinances to prosperous fulfillment.'),(2734,'Let him yield—'),(2735,' Hades, I ween, is not to be soothed, neither overcome, wherefore he is most hated by mortals of all gods.'),(2736,'  And let him submit himself unto me, seeing I am more kingly, and avow me his elder in years.\"\n '),(2737,' \nThen made answer the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia:'),(2738,' \"Most glorious son of Atreus, Agamemnon, king of men, the gifts that thou offerest the prince Achilles may no man any more condemn.'),(2739,'  Come, therefore, let us send forth chosen men to go forthwith to the hut of Peleus\' son, Achilles.'),(2740,'  Nay, rather, whomsoever I shall choose, let them consent.'),(2741,' First of all let Phoenix, dear to Zeus, lead the way, and after him great Aias and goodly Odysseus; '),(2742,' and of the heralds let Odius and Eurybates attend them. '),(2743,'And now bring ye water for our hands, and bid keep holy silence, that we may make prayer unto Zeus, son of Cronos, if so be he will have compassion upon us.\"'),(2744,'\nSo said he and the words that he spake were pleasing unto all. '),(2745,'\nThen heralds poured water over their hands,  and youths filled the bowls brim full of drink, and served out to all, pouring first drops for libation into the cups.'),(2746,'  But when they had made libation and had drunk to their hearts\' content, they went forth from the hut of Agamemnon, son of Atreus. '),(2747,'And the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia,  laid straight command upon them with many a glance at each, and chiefly upon Odysseus, that they should make essay to persuade the peerless son of Peleus.'),(2748,'\nSo the twain went their way along the shore of the loud-resounding sea, with many an instant prayer to the god that holdeth the earth and shaketh it, that they might easily persuade the great heart of the son of Aeacus.'),(2749,'  And they came to the huts and the ships of the Myrmidons, and found him delighting his soul with a clear-toned lyre, fair and richly wrought, whereon was a bridge of silver; this had he taken from the spoil when he laid waste the city of Eëtion.'),(2750,'  Therewith was he delighting his soul, and he sang of the glorious deeds of warriors;'),(2751,' and Patroclus alone sat over against him in silence, waiting until Aeacus\' son should cease from singing. But the twain came forward and goodly Odysseus led the way, and they took their stand before his face;'),(2752,'and Achilles leapt up in amazement with the lyre in his hand, and left the seat whereon he sat; '),(2753,'  and in like manner Patroclus when he beheld the men uprose.'),(2754,' Then swift-footed Achilles greeted the two and spake, saying:'),(2755,'\"Welcome, '),(2756,'verily ye be friends that are come—sore must the need be — ye that even in mine anger are to me the dearest of the Achaeans.\"'),(2757,'\nSo saying, goodly Achilles led them in  and made them sit on couches and rugs of purple; '),(2758,'and forthwith he spake to Patroclus, that was near:\"'),(2759,'Set forth a larger bowl, thou son of Menoetius; mingle stronger drink, and prepare each man a cup, '),(2760,'for these be men most dear, that are beneath my roof.\" '),(2761,' \nSo he spake, and Patroclus gave ear to his dear comrade.'),(2762,'  He cast down a great fleshing-block in the light of the fire and laid thereon a sheep\'s back and a fat goat\'s, and the chine of a great hog withal, rich with fat.'),(2763,'  And Automedon held them for him, while goodly Achilles carved.'),(2764,'  Then he sliced the meat with care and spitted it upon spits, and the son of Menoetius, a godlike man, made the fire blaze high.'),(2765,'  But when the fire had burned down and the flame was abated, he scattered the embers and laid thereover the spits, and sprinkled the morsels with holy salt when he had set them upon the fire-dogs.  '),(2766,'But when he had roasted the meat and laid it on platters,  Patroclus took bread and dealt it forth on the table in fair baskets, while Achilles dealt the meat.'),(2767,' Himself he sate him down over against godlike Odysseus, by the other wall, and bade Patroclus, his comrade, offer sacrifice to the gods;'),(2768,' and Patroclus cast burnt-offering into the fire. '),(2769,'So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them.'),(2770,'  But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, Aias nodded to Phoenix; '),(2771,'and goodly Odysseus was ware thereof, and filling a cup with wine he pledged Achilles:'),(2772,' \"Hail, O Achilles, '),(2773,'  \"Hail, O Achilles, of the equal feast have we no stinting, either in the hut of Agamemnon, son of Atreus, or now in thine; for here is abundance that satisfies the heart to feast withal.'),(2774,'  Yet matters of the delicious feast are not in our thoughts, nay, Zeus-nurtured one, it is utter ruin that we behold, and are afraid; '),(2775,' for it is in doubt whether we save the benched ships or they perish, except thou clothe thee in thy might.'),(2776,'  Hard by the ships and the wall have the Trojans, high of heart, and their far-famed allies set their bivouac, and kindled many fires throughout the host, and they deem that they shall no more be stayed,  but will fall upon our black ships.'),(2777,' And Zeus, son of Cronos, shows them signs upon the right with his lightnings, '),(2778,'and Hector exulting greatly in his might rageth furiously, trusting in Zeus, and recketh not of men nor gods, '),(2779,'for mighty madness hath possessed him.'),(2780,'  His prayer is that with all speed sacred Dawn may appear, '),(2781,'for he declareth that he will hew from the ships\' sterns the topmost ensigns, and burn the very hulls with consuming fire, and amidst them make havoc of the Achaeans, distraught by reason of the smoke.'),(2782,'  This then is the great fear of my heart, lest the gods fulfill for him his boastings, and it be our fate to  perish here in Troy, far from horse-pasturing Argos.'),(2783,'  Nay, up then, if thou art minded even at the last to save from the war-din of the Trojans the sons of the Achaeans, that are sore bested.'),(2784,'  To thine own self shall sorrow be hereafter, nor can healing  be found for ill once wrought—'),(2785,'nay, rather, ere it be too late bethink thee how thou mayest ward from the Danaans the day of evil.'),(2786,'  Good friend, surely it was to thee that thy father Peleus gave command on the day when he sent thee to Agamemnon forth from Phthia:'),(2787,'‘My son, strength shall Athene and Hera  give thee if they be so minded, but do thou curb thy proud spirit in thy breast, '),(2788,'for gentle-mindedness is the better part; '),(2789,'and withdraw thee from strife, contriver of mischief, that so the Argives both young and old may honour thee the more.'),(2790,'On this wise did that old man charge thee, but thou forgettest.'),(2791,' Yet do thou lease even now,  and put from thee thy bitter wrath.  '),(2792,' To thee Agamemnon offereth worthy gifts, so thou wilt cease from thine anger.'),(2793,' Nay come, hearken thou to me, and I will tell the tale of all the gifts that in his hut Agamemnon promised thee:  '),(2794,'seven tripods, that the fire hath not touched, and ten talents of gold  and twenty gleaming cauldrons, and twelve strong horses, winners in the race that have won prizes by their fleetness.'),(2795,' Not without booty were a man nor unpossessed of precious gold, whoso had wealth as great as the prizes Agamemnon\'s horses have won by their speed.'),(2796,'  And he will give seven women skilled in goodly handiwork, women of Lesbos, whom on the day when thou thyself tookest well-built Lesbos he chose him from the spoil, and that in beauty surpassed all women folk.'),(2797,'  These will he give thee, and amid them shall be she whom he then took away, the daughter of Briseus; '),(2798,'and he will furthermore swear a great oath,  that never went he up into her bed, neither had dalliance with her, as is the appointed way, O king, of men and women.'),(2799,'  All these things shall be ready to thy hand forthwith; '),(2800,'and if hereafter it so be the gods grant us to lay waste the great city of Priam, do thou then enter in,  what time we Achaeans be dividing the spoil, and heap up thy ship with store of gold and bronze, and thyself choose twenty Trojan women that be fairest after Argive Helen.'),(2801,'  And if we return to Achaean Argos, richest of lands, thou shalt be his son, '),(2802,'and he will honour thee even as Orestes, his growing son who is brought up there in abundant luxury.'),(2803,'  Three daughters has he in his well-builded hall, Chrysothemis, and Laodice, and Ophianassa; of these mayest thou lead to the house of Peleus which one thou wilt, without gifts of wooing;'),(2804,'and he will furthermore give a dower  full rich, such as no man ever yet gave with his daughter.  '),(2805,'And seven well-peopled cities will he give thee, Cardamyle, Enope, and grassy Hire, and sacred Pherae, and Antheia, with deep meadows, and fair Aipeia, and vine-clad Pedasus. '),(2806,' All are nigh the sea, on the uttermost borders of sandy Pylos, '),(2807,'and in them dwell men rich in flocks and rich in kine, men that shall honour thee with gifts as though thou wert a god, and beneath thy sceptre shall bring thy ordinances to prosperous fulfillment.'),(2808,'  All this will he bring to pass for thee, if thou but cease from thy wrath.'),(2809,'  But if the son of Atreus be too utterly hated by thee at heart, himself and his gifts, yet have thou pity at least on the rest of the Achaeans, that are sore bested throughout the host; these shall honour thee as though thou wert a god, '),(2810,'for verily shalt thou win great glory in their eyes.'),(2811,'Now mightest thou slay Hector, seeing he would come very nigh thee  in his baneful rage, for he deemeth there is no man like unto him among the Danaans that the ships brought hither.\"'),(2812,'\nThen in answer to him spake swift-footed Achilles: '),(2813,'\"Zeus-born son of Laërtes, Odysseus of many wiles, needs must I verily speak my word outright, even as I am minded,  and as it shall be brought to pass, that ye sit not by me here on this side and on that and prate endlessly.'),(2814,'  For hateful in my eyes, even as the gates of Hades, is that man that hideth one thing in his mind and sayeth another.'),(2815,'  Nay, I will speak what seemeth to me to be best.'),(2816,'  Not me, I ween, shall Atreus\' son, Agamemnon, persuade, nor yet shall the other Danaans, seeing there were to be no thanks, it seemeth, for warring against the foeman ever without respite.'),(2817,'  Like portion hath he that abideth at home, and if one warreth his best, '),(2818,'and in one honour are held both the coward and the brave; '),(2819,' death cometh alike to the idle man and to him that worketh much.  '),(2820,'Neither have I aught of profit herein, that I suffered woes at heart, ever staking my life in fight.  '),(2821,'Even as a bird bringeth in her bill to her unfledged chicks whatever she may find, but with her own self it goeth ill,  even so was I wont to watch through many a sleepless night, and bloody days did I pass in battle, fighting with warriors for their women\'s sake.'),(2822,'   Twelve cities of men have I laid waste with my ships and by land eleven, I avow, throughout the fertile land of Troy; '),(2823,' from out all these I took much spoil and goodly, and all would I ever bring and give to Agamemnon, this son of Atreus; '),(2824,'but he staying behind, even beside his swiftships, would take and apportion some small part, but keep the most.'),(2825,'  Some he gave as prizes to chieftains and kings, '),(2826,' and for them they abide untouched; but from me alone of the Achaeans hath he taken and keepeth my wife, the darling of my heart.'),(2827,'  Let him lie by her side and take his joy.'),(2828,' But why must the Argives wage war against the Trojans?'),(2829,'  Why hath he gathered and led hither his host, this son of Atreus?'),(2830,'  Was it not for fair-haired Helen\'s sake?'),(2831,'  Do they then alone of mortal men love their wives, these sons of Atreus?'),(2832,'  Nay, for whoso is a true man and sound of mind, loveth his own and cherisheth her, even as I too loved her with all my heart, though she was but the captive of my spear.'),(2833,'  But now, seeing he hath taken from my arms my prize, and hath deceived me,  let him not tempt me that know him well; '),(2834,'he shall not persuade me.  '),(2835,'Nay, Odysseus, together with thee and the other princes let him take thought to ward from the ships consuming fire.'),(2836,'  Verily full much hath he wrought without mine aid; lo, he hath builded a wall and digged a ditch hard by,  wide and great, and therein hath he planted stakes; '),(2837,'yet even so availeth he not to stay the might of man-slaying Hector.'),(2838,'  But so long as I was warring amid the Achaeans Hector had no mind to rouse battle far from the wall, but would come only so far as the Scaean gates and the oak-tree; '),(2839,' there once he awaited me in single combat and hardly did he escape my onset.  '),(2840,'But now, seeing I am not minded to battle with goodly Hector, tomorrow will I do sacrifice to Zeus and all the gods, and heap well my ships, when I have launched them on the sea; then shalt thou see, if so be thou wilt, and carest aught therefor,  my ships at early dawn sailing over the teeming Hellespont, and on board men right eager to ply the oar; '),(2841,'and if so be the great Shaker of the Earth grants me fair voyaging, on the third day shall I reach deep-soiled Phthia.'),(2842,'  Possessions full many have I that I left on my ill-starred way hither, '),(2843,' and yet more shall I bring from hence, gold and ruddy bronze, and fair-girdled women and grey iron—all that fell to me by lot; '),(2844,'howbeit my prize hath he that gave it me taken back in his arrogant pride, even lord Agamemnon, son of Atreus.  '),(2845,'To him do ye declare all, even as I bid,  openly, to the end that other Achaeans also may be wroth, if haply he hopeth to deceive yet some other of the Danaans, seeing he is ever clothed in shamelessness.'),(2846,'  Yet not in my face would he dare to look, though he have the front of a dog.'),(2847,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 9.374'),(2848,' for utterly hath he deceived me and sinned against me.'),(2849,'  Never again shall he beguile me with words; '),(2850,' the past is enough for him.'),(2851,' Nay, let him go to his ruin in comfort, '),(2852,'seeing that Zeus the counsellor hath utterly robbed him of his wits.'),(2853,'  Hateful in my eyes are his gifts, I count them at a hair\'s worth.  '),(2854,'Not though he gave me ten times, aye twenty times all that now he hath,  and if yet other should be added thereto I care not whence, not though it were all the wealth that goeth in to Orchomenus, or to Thebes of Egypt, where treasures in greatest store are laid up in men\'s houses,—Thebes which is a city of an hundred gates wherefrom sally forth through each two hundred warriors with horses and cars; '),(2855,' —nay, not though he gave gifts in number as sand and dust; not even so shall Agamemnon any more persuade my soul, until he hath paid the full price of all the despite that stings my heart.'),(2856,'  And the daughter of Agamemnon, son of Atreus, will I not wed, not though she vied in beauty with golden Aphrodite  and in handiwork were the peer of flashing-eyed Athene:'),(2857,' not even so will I wed her;'),(2858,'let him choose another of the Achaeans that is of like station with himself and more kingly than I.'),(2859,'  For if the gods preserve me, and I reach my home, Peleus methinks will thereafter of himself seek me a wife.'),(2860,'  Many Achaean maidens there be throughout Hellas and Phthia, daughters of chieftains that guard the cities; of these whomsoever I choose shall I make my dear wife.'),(2861,'Full often was my proud spirit fain to take me there a wedded wife, a fitting helpmeet,  and to have joy of the possessions that the old man Peleus won him.  '),(2862,'For in my eyes not of like worth with life is even all that wealth that men say Ilios possessed, the well-peopled citadel, of old in time of peace or ever the sons of the Achaeans came,—nay, nor all that the marble threshold of the Archer  Phoebus Apollo encloseth in rocky Pytho.  '),(2863,'For by harrying may cattle be had and goodly sheep, and tripods by the winning and chestnut horses withal; but that the spirit of man should come again when once it hath passed the barrier of his teeth, neither harrying availeth nor winning.'),(2864,'  For my mother the goddess, silver-footed Thetis, telleth me that twofold fates are bearing me toward the doom of death:'),(2865,' if I abide here and war about the city of the Trojans, then lost is my home-return, but my renown shall be imperishable;'),(2866,'but if I return home to my dear native land,  lost then is my glorious renown, yet shall my life long endure, neither shall the doom of death come soon upon me.'),(2867,'  Aye, and I would counsel you others also to sail back to your homes; seeing there is no more hope that ye shall win the goal of steep Ilios; '),(2868,'for mightily doth Zeus, whose voice is borne afar,  hold forth his hand above her, and her people are filled with courage.'),(2869,'  But go ye your way and declare my message to the chieftains of the Achaeans'),(2870,'—for that is the office of elders—'),(2871,'to the end that they may devise some other plan in their minds better than this, even such as shall save their ships, and the host of the Achaeans  beside the hollow ships; seeing this is not to be had for them, which now they have devised, by reason of the fierceness of my anger.'),(2872,'  Howbeit let Phoenix abide here with us, and lay him down to sleep, that he may follow with me on my ships to my dear native land on the morrow, if so he will; '),(2873,'but perforce will I not take him.\"'),(2874,'  So spake he, and they all became hushed in silence, marveling at his words; '),(2875,'for with exceeding vehemence did he deny them.'),(2876,'  But at length there spake among them the old horseman Phoenix, bursting into tears, '),(2877,'for that greatly did he fear for the ships of the Achaeans:\"'),(2878,'If verily thou layest up in thy mind, glorious Achilles,  the purpose of returning, neither art minded at all to ward from the swift ships consuming fire, for that wrath hath fallen upon thy heart; how can I then, dear child, be left here without thee, alone?  '),(2879,'It was to thee that the old horseman Peleus sent me on the day when he sent thee to Agamemnon, forth from Phthia,  a mere child, knowing naught as yet of evil war, neither of gatherings wherein men wax preeminent.'),(2880,'  For this cause sent he me to instruct thee in all these things, to be both a speaker of words and a doer of deeds.  '),(2881,'Wherefore, dear child, I am not minded hereafter  to be left alone without thee, nay, not though a god himself should pledge him to strip from me my old age and render me strong in youth as in the day when first I left Hellas, the home of fair women, fleeing from strife with my father Amyntor, son of Ormenus; for he waxed grievously wroth against me by reason of his fair-haired concubine,  whom himself he ever cherished, and scorned his wife, my mother.'),(2882,'  So she besought me by my knees continually, to have dalliance with that other first myself, that the old man might be hateful in her eyes.'),(2883,'I hearkened to her and did the deed, '),(2884,'but my father was ware thereof forthwith and cursed me mightily, and invoked the dire Erinyes  that never should there sit upon his knees a dear child begotten of me; '),(2885,'and the gods fulfilled his curse, even Zeus of the nether world and dread Persephone.'),(2886,'Then might the heart in my breast in no wise be any more stayed to linger in the halls of my angered father. '),(2887,'My fellows verily and my kinsfolk beset me about  with many prayers and sought to stay me there in the halls, and many goodly sheep did they slaughter, and sleek kine of shambling gait, and many swine, rich with fat, were stretched to singe over the flame of Hephaestus, and wine in plenty was drunk from the jars of that old man.'),(2888,'  For nine nights\' space about mine own body did they watch the night through; '),(2889,'in turn kept they watch, neither were the fires quenched, one beneath the portico of the well-fenced court, and one in the porch before the door of my chamber. '),(2890,'Howbeit when the tenth dark night was come upon me,  then verily I burst the cunningly fitted doors of my chamber and leapt the fence of the court full easily, unseen of the watchmen and the slave women.'),(2891,' Thereafter I fled afar through spacious Hellas, and came to deep-soiled Phthia, mother of flocks,  unto king Peleus; '),(2892,'and he received me with a ready heart, and cherished me as a father cherisheth his only son and well-beloved, that is heir to great possessions; and he made me rich and gave much people to me, '),(2893,'and I dwelt on the furthermost border of Phthia, ruling over the Dolopians.'),(2894,'  And I reared thee to be such as thou art, O godlike Achilles, loving thee from may heart; for with none other wouldest thou go to the feast neither take meat in the hall, till I had set thee on my knees and given thee thy fill of the savoury morsel cut first for thee, and had put the wine cup to thy lips.'),(2895,'  Full often hast thou wetted the tunic upon my breast, sputtering forth the wine in thy sorry helplessness.'),(2896,' So have I suffered much for thee and toiled much, ever mindful of this that the gods would in no wise vouchsafe me a son born of mine own body.  Nay.'),(2897,' it was thou that I sought to make my son, O godlike Achilles,  to the end that thou mayest hereafter save me from shameful ruin.  Wherefore Achilles, do thou master thy proud spirit;'),(2898,' it was thou that I sought to make my son, O godlike Achilles,  to the end that thou mayest hereafter save me from shameful ruin.  Wherefore Achilles, do thou master thy proud spirit;'),(2899,'it beseemeth thee not to have a pitiless heart.'),(2900,'  Nay, even the very gods can bend, and theirs withal is more excellent worth and honour and might.  '),(2901,'Their hearts by incense and reverent vows  and libations and the savour of sacrifice do men turn from wrath with supplication, whenso any man transgresseth and doeth sin.'),(2902,'  For Prayers are the daughters of great Zeus, halting and wrinkled and of eyes askance, and they are ever mindful to follow in the steps of Sin.'),(2903,'  Howbeit Sin is strong and fleet of foot, wherefore she far out-runneth them all, and goeth before them over the face of all the earth making men to fall, '),(2904,'and Prayers follow after, seeking to heal the hurt.'),(2905,'  Now whoso revereth the daughters of Zeus when they draw nigh, him they greatly bless, and hear him, when he prayeth;  '),(2906,'but if a man denieth them and stubbornly refuseth, then they go their way and make prayer to Zeus, son of Cronos, that Ate may follow after such a one to the end that he may fall and pay full atonement.'),(2907,'  Nay, Achilles, see thou too that reverence attend upon the daughters of Zeus, even such as bendeth the hearts of all men that are upright.'),(2908,'  For if the son of Atreus were not offering thee gifts and telling of yet others hereafter, but were ever furiously wroth, I of a surety should not bid thee cast aside thine anger and bear aid to the Argives even in their sore need.  '),(2909,'But now he offereth thee many gifts forthwith, and promiseth thee more hereafter,  and hath sent forth warriors to beseech thee, choosing them that are best throughout the host of the Achaeans, and that to thine own self are dearest of the Argives; '),(2910,'have not thou scorn of their words, neither of their coming hither; '),(2911,'though till then no man could blame thee that thou wast wroth. '),(2912,'Even in this manner have we heard the fame of men of old  that were warriors, whenso furious wrath came upon any; '),(2913,'won might they be by gifts, and turned aside by pleadings.'),(2914,' Myself I bear in mind this deed of old days and not of yesterday, how it was; '),(2915,'and I will tell it among you that are all my friends.'),(2916,'The Curetes on a time were fighting and the Aetolians staunch in battle  around the city of Calydon, and were slaying one another, the Aetolians defending lovely Calydon and the Curetes fain to waste it utterly in war.'),(2917,'  For upon their folk had Artemis of the golden throne sent a plague in wrath that Oeneus offered not to her the first-fruits of the harvest in his rich orchard land; '),(2918,' whereas the other gods feasted on hecatombs, and it was to the daughter of great Zeus alone that he offered not, whether haply he forgat, or marked it not; '),(2919,'and he was greatly blinded in heart. '),(2920,'and he was greatly blinded in heart. '),(2921,'  Thereat the Archer-goddess, the child of Zeus, waxed wroth and sent against him a fierce wild boar, white of tusk,  that wrought much evil, wasting the orchard land of Oeneus; '),(2922,'many a tall tree did he uproot and cast upon the ground, aye, root and apple blossom therewith.'),(2923,' But the boar did Meleager, son of Oeneus, slay, when he had gathered out of many cities huntsmen  and hounds; '),(2924,'for not of few men could the boar have been slain, '),(2925,'so huge was he; and many a man set he upon the grievous pyre.'),(2926,' But about his body the goddess brought to pass much clamour and shouting concerning his head and shaggy hide, between the Curetes and the great-souled Aetolians.'),(2927,'  Now so long as Meleager, dear to Ares, warred, so long went it ill with the Curetes, nor might they abide without their wall, for all they were very many.  '),(2928,'But when wrath entered into Meleager, wrath that maketh the heart to swell in the breasts also of others, even though they be wise,  he then, wroth at heart against his dear mother Althaea, abode beside his wedded wife, the fair Cleopatra, daughter of Marpessa of the fair ankles, child of Evenus, and of Idas that was mightiest of men that were then upon the face of earth; '),(2929,'who also took his bow to face the king  Phoebus Apollo for the sake of the fair-ankled maid. Her of old in their halls had her father and honoured mother called Halcyone by name, for that the mother herself in a plight even as that of the halcyon-bird of many sorrows, wept because Apollo that worketh afar had snatched her child away.'),(2930,'  By her side lay Meleager nursing his bitter anger, wroth because of his mother\'s curses; for she prayed instantly to the gods, being grieved for her brother\'s slaying; and furthermore instantly beat with her hands upon the all-nurturing earth, calling upon Hades and dread Persephone,  the while she knelt and made the folds of her bosom wet with tears, that they should bring death upon her son; '),(2931,'and the Erinys that walketh in darkness heard her from Erebus, even she of the ungentle heart.'),(2932,'Now anon was the din of the foemen risen about their gates, and the noise of the battering of walls, '),(2933,'and to Meleager the elders  of the Aetolians made prayer, sending to him the best of the priests of the gods, that he should come forth and succour them, and they promised him a mighty gift; '),(2934,'they bade him, where the plain of lovely Calydon was fattest, there choose a fair tract of fifty acres, the half of it vineland, '),(2935,'   And earnestly the old horseman Oeneus besought him, standing upon the threshold of his high-roofed chamber, and shaking the jointed doors, in prayer to his son,'),(2936,' and earnestly too did his sisters and his honoured mother beseech him  '),(2937,'—but he denied them yet more—'),(2938,'and earnestly his companions that were truest and dearest to him of all; '),(2939,'yet not even so could they persuade the heart in his breast, until at the last his chamber was being hotly battered, and the Curetes were mounting upon the walls and firing the great city.'),(2940,'  Then verily his fair-girdled wife besought Meleager with wailing, and told him all the woes that come on men whose city is taken; '),(2941,'the men are slain and the city is wasted by fire, and their children and low-girdled women are led captive of strangers.'),(2942,'  Then was his spirit stirred, as he heard the evil tale, and he went his way and did on his body his gleaming armour.'),(2943,' Thus did he ward from the Aetolians the day of evil, yielding to his own spirit; '),(2944,'and to him thereafter they paid not the gifts, many and gracious; yet even so did he ward from them evil.'),(2945,'  But, friend, let me not see thee thus minded in heart, neither let heaven turn thee into this path; '),(2946,'it were a harder task to save the ships already burning. '),(2947,'Nay, come while yet gifts may be had; '),(2948,'the Achaeans shall honour thee even as a god. '),(2949,'But if without gifts thou enter into the battle, the bane of men,  thou shalt not then be in like honour, for all thou mayest ward off the battle.\"\nThen in answer to him spake Achilles, swift of foot:\"'),(2950,'Phoenix, old sire, my father, nurtured of Zeus, in no wise have I need of this honour:'),(2951,' honoured have I been, I deem, by the apportionment of Zeus, which shall be mine amid the beaked ships so long as the breath  abideth in my breast and my knees are quick.'),(2952,' And another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart; '),(2953,'seek not to confound my spirit by weeping and sorrowing, to do the pleasure of the warrior, son of Atreus; '),(2954,'it beseemeth thee not to cherish him, lest thou be hated of me that cherish thee.'),(2955,'  Well were it that with me thou shouldest vex him whosoever vexeth me.  '),(2956,'Be thou king even as I am, and share the half of my honour.'),(2957,'  Howbeit these shall bear my message, but abide thou here and lay thee down on a soft couch, '),(2958,'and at break of day we will take counsel whether to return to our own or to tarry here.\"'),(2959,' \n  He spake and to Patroclus nodded his brow in silence that he should spread for Phoenix a thick couch, that the others might forthwith bethink them to depart from the hut.'),(2960,'  But among them Aias, the godlike son of Telamon, spake, saying:\"'),(2961,'Zeus—born son of Laërtes, Odysseus of many wiles,  let us go our way, '),(2962,'for the fulfillment of the charge laid on us will not methinks be brought to pass by our coming hither; '),(2963,'and it behoveth us with speed to declare the message, though it be no wise good, to the Danaans, that, I ween, now sit waiting therefor.  '),(2964,'But Achilles hath wrought to fury the proud heart within him,  cruel man!  neither recketh he of the love of his comrades wherewith we ever honoured him amid the ships above all others—pitiless one!'),(2965,'  Lo, a man accepteth recompense from the slayer of his brother, or for his dead son; '),(2966,'and the slayer abideth in his own land for the paying of a great price,  and the kinsman\'s heart and proud spirit are restrained by the taking of recompense.'),(2967,'  But as for thee, the gods have put in thy breast a heart that is obdurate and evil by reason of one only girl; '),(2968,'whereas we now offer thee seven, far the best that there be, and many other gffts besides; '),(2969,'nay then, take to thee a heart of grace,  and have respect unto thine hall; '),(2970,'for under thy roof are we come from the host of the Danaans, and we would fain be nearest to thee and dearest beyond all other Achaeans as many as there be.\"'),(2971,'Then in answer to him spake Achilles, swift of foot:\"'),(2972,'Aias, sprung from Zeus, thou son of Telamon, captain of the host,  all this thou seemest to speak almost after mine own mind; '),(2973,'but my heart swelleth with wrath whenso I think of this, how the son of Atreus hath wrought indignity upon me amid the Argives, as though I were some alien that had no rights.'),(2974,'  Howbeit do ye go and declare my message, '),(2975,' for I will not sooner bethink me of bloody war until wise-hearted Priam\'s son, even goodly Hector, be come to the huts and ships of the Myrmidons, as he slays the Argives, and have smirched the ships with fire.'),(2976,'  But about my hut and my black ship  I deem that Hector will be stayed, eager though he be for battle.\"'),(2977,'So spake he, but they took each man a two handled cup, and when they had made libation went their way along the lines of ships, '),(2978,'and Odysseus led.'),(2979,' But Patroclus bade his comrades and the handmaids spread forthwith a thick couch for Phoenix; '),(2980,' and they obeyed, and spread the couch, as he bade, fleeces and a rug and soft fabric of linen.'),(2981,'  There the old man laid him down and waited for bright Dawn.'),(2982,'  But Achilles slept in the innermost part of the well-builded hut, '),(2983,'and by his side lay a woman that he had brought from Lesbos,  even the daughter of Phorbas, fair-cheeked Diomede.'),(2984,'  And Patroclus laid him down on the opposite side, '),(2985,'and by him in like manner lay fair-girdled Iphis, whom goodly Achilles had given him when he took steep Scyrus, the city of Enyeus.'),(2986,' \nBut when the others were now come to the huts of the son of Atreus, '),(2987,' the sons of the Achaeans stood up on this side and that and pledged them in cups of gold, and questioned them, '),(2988,'and the king of men, Agamemnon, was the first to ask:\"'),(2989,'Come, tell me now, Odysseus, greatly to be praised, thou great glory of the Achaeans, is he minded to ward off consuming fire from the ships,  or said he nay, and doth wrath still possess his proud spirit?\"'),(2990,'Then much-enduring goodly Odysseus answered him:'),(2991,' \"Most glorious son of Atreus, Agamemnon, king of men, he verily is not minded to quench his wrath but is filled yet more with fury, and will have none of thee, or of thy gifts.'),(2992,'  For thine own self he biddeth thee to take counsel amid the Argives how thou mayest save the ships and the host of the Achaeans.'),(2993,'  But himself he threateneth that at break of day he will launch upon the sea his well-benched curved ships. '),(2994,'Aye and he said that he would counsel others also  to sail back to their homes, seeing there is no more hope that ye shall win the goal of steep Ilios; '),(2995,'for mightily doth Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, hold forth his hand above her, and her people are filled with courage.'),(2996,'  So spake he, '),(2997,'and these be here also to tell thee this, even they that followed with me, Aias and the heralds twain, men of prudence both.'),(2998,'  But the old man Phoenix laid him down there to rest, for so Achilles bade, that he may follow with him on his ships to his dear native land on the morrow, if he will, '),(2999,'but perforce will he not take him.\"'),(3000,'\nSo spake he, and they all became hushed in silence marvelling at his words; '),(3001,'\nfor full masterfully did he address their gathering.'),(3002,'  Long time were they silent in their grief, the sons of the Achaeans,'),(3003,' but at length there spake among them Diomedes, good at the war-cry:\"'),(3004,'Most glorious son of Atreus, Agamemnon, king of men, would thou hadst never besought the peerless son of Peleus, nor offered countless gifs; '),(3005,'haughty is he even of himself, '),(3006,'and now hast thou yet far more set him amid haughtinesses.'),(3007,'  But verily we will let him be; he may depart or he may tarry; '),(3008,'hereafter will he fight when the heart in his breast shall bid him, and a god arouse him.'),(3009,'But come, even as I shall bid, let us all obey.'),(3010,'  For this present go ye to your rest, when ye have satisfied your hearts with meat and wine, '),(3011,'for therein is courage and strength; '),(3012,'but so soon as fair, rosy-fingered Dawn appeareth, forthwith do thou array before the ships thy folk and thy chariots, and urge them on; and fight thou thyself amid the foremost.\"'),(3013,'\n  So spake he, and all the kings assented thereto, marvelling at the words of Diomedes, tamer of horses.'),(3014,' Then they made libation, and went every man to his hut, and there laid them down and took the gift of sleep.'),(3015,' Now beside their ships all the other chieftains of the host of the Achaeans were slumbering the whole night through, overcome of soft sleep'),(3016,'but Agamemnon, son of Atreus, shepherd of the host, was not holden of sweet sleep, so many things debated he in mind.'),(3017,'  Even as when the lord of fair-haired Hera lighteneth, what time he maketh ready either a mighty rain unspeakable or hail or snow, when the snow-flakes sprinkle the fields, or haply the wide mouth of bitter war; even so often did Agamemnon groan from the deep of his breast,  and his heart trembled within him.  '),(3018,'So often as he gazed toward the Trojan plain, he marvelled at the many fires that burned before the face of Ilios, and at the sound of flutes and pipes, and the din of men; '),(3019,'but whensoever he looked toward the ships and the host of the Achaeans,  then many were the hairs that he pulled from his head by the very roots in appeal to Zeus that is above, and in his noble heart he groaned mightily.'),(3020,'  And this plan seemed to his mind the best, to go first of all to Nestor, son of Neleus, if so be he might contrive with him some goodly device  that should be for the warding off of evil from the Danaan host.  '),(3021,'So he sate him up and did on his tunic about his breast, and beneath his shining feet bound his fair sandals, and thereafter clad him in the tawny skin of a lion, fiery and great, a skin that reached his feet; and he grasped his spear.'),(3022,' And even in like manner was Menelaus holden of trembling fear'),(3023,'—for on his eyelids too sleep settled not down—'),(3024,'lest aught should befall the Argives who for his sake had come to Troy over the wide waters of the sea, pondering in their hearts fierce war.  '),(3025,'With a leopard\'s skin first he covered his broad shoulders, a dappled fell,  and lifted up and set upon his head a helmet of bronze, and grasped a spear in his stout hand.'),(3026,'  Then he went his way to rouse his brother, that ruled mightily over all the Argives, and was honoured of the folk even as a god.'),(3027,' Him he found putting about his shoulders his fair armour  by the stern of his ship, '),(3028,'and welcome was he to him as he came.  '),(3029,'To him first spake Menelaus, good at the war-cry:'),(3030,'Wherefore, my brother, art thou thus arming?'),(3031,'  Wilt thou be rousing some man of thy comrades to spy upon the Trojans?'),(3032,'Nay, sorely am I afraid lest none should undertake for thee this task,  to go forth alone and spy upon the foemen, through the immortal night;'),(3033,'right hardy of heart must that man be.'),(3034,'Then in answer to him spake lord Agamemnon:'),(3035,' \"Need have we, both thou and I, O Menelaus, fostered of Zeus, of shrewd counsel that shall save and deliver  the Argives and their ships, seeing the mind of Zeus is turned.  '),(3036,'To the sacrifices of Hector, it seemeth, his heart inclineth rather than to ours.'),(3037,' For never have I seen neither heard by the telling of another that one man devised in one day so many terrible deeds, as Hector, dear to Zeus, hath wrought upon the sons of the Achaeans, by himself alone,  he that is not the dear son of goddess or of god.'),(3038,'Deeds hath he wrought that methinks will be a sorrow to the Argives for ever and aye,'),(3039,'so many evils hath he devised against the Achaeans.'),(3040,'  But go now, run swiftly along the lines of ships and call hither Aias and Idomeneus'),(3041,'and I will go to goodly Nestor  and bid him arise, if so be he will be minded to go to the sacred company of the sentinels and give them charge.'),(3042,'To him would they hearken as to no other,'),(3043,'for his son is captain over the guard, he and Meriones, comrade of Idomeneus; '),(3044,'for to them above all we entrusted this charge.'),(3045,'  Then made answer to him Menelaus, good at the war-cry:'),(3046,' \"With what meaning doth thy word thus charge and command me?  '),(3047,'Shall I abide there with them, waiting until thou shalt come, or run back to thee again, when I have duly laid on them thy command?\"'),(3048,'And to him did the king of men, Agamemnon, make answer, saying:  \"Abide there, lest haply we miss each other as we go'),(3049,'for many are the paths throughout the camp.'),(3050,'But lift up thy voice wheresoever thou goest, and bid men be awake, calling each man by his lineage and his father\'s name, giving due honour to each'),(3051,'and be not thou proud of heart  but rather let us ourselves be busy;'),(3052,'even thus I ween hath Zeus laid upon us even at our birth the heaviness of woe.'),(3053,'So spake he, and sent forth his brother when he had duly given him commandment.'),(3054,'But he went his way after Nestor, shepherd of the host,'),(3055,'and found him by his hut and his black ship  on his soft bed,'),(3056,'and beside him lay his armour richly dight, his shield and two spears and gleaming helmet.'),(3057,'  And by his side lay the flashing girdle, wherewith the old man was wont to gird himself, whenso he arrayed him for battle, the bane of men, and led forth his people, for he yielded not to grievous old age.'),(3058,'  He rose upon his elbow, lifting up his head, and spake to the son of Atreus, and questioned him, saying:'),(3059,' \"Who art thou that art faring alone by the ships throughout the camp in the darkness of night, when other mortals are sleeping? Seekest thou one of thy mules, or of thy comrades? '),(3060,'What would you of me?\''),(3061,'What would you of me?\''),(3062,'Then made answer the king of men, Agamemnon:'),(3063,' \"Nestor, son of Neleus, great glory of the Achaeans, thou shalt know Agamemnon, son of Atreus, whom beyond all others Zeus hath set amid toils continually,  so long as the breath abideth in my breast and my knees are quick.  '),(3064,'I wander thus, because sweet sleep settleth not upon mine eyes, but war is a trouble to me and the woes of the Achaeans.'),(3065,' Wondrously do I fear for the Danaans, nor is my mind firm, but I am tossed to and fro, and my heart  leapeth forth from out my breast, and my glorious limbs tremble beneath me.'),(3066,'But if thou wouldest do aught, seeing on thee too sleep cometh not, come, let us go to the sentinels, that we may look to them, lest fordone with toil and drowsiness they be slumbering'),(3067,'and have wholly forgot their watch.'),(3068,'  The foemen bivouac hard by, nor know we at all whether haply they may not be fain to do battle even in the night.\"'),(3069,'Then made answer to him the horseman Nestor of Gerenia:'),(3070,' \"Most glorious son of Atreus, Agamemnon, king of men, of a surety not all his purposes shall Zeus the counsellor fulfill for Hector,  even all that now he thinketh; '),(3071,'nay methinks he shall labour amid troubles yet more than ours, if so be Achilles shall turn his heart from grievous anger.'),(3072,'Howbeit with thee will I gladly follow'),(3073,'but let us moreover arouse others also, both the son of Tydeus, famed for his spear, and Odysseus,  and the swift Aias, and the valiant son of Phyleus. '),(3074,'And I would that one should go and summon these also, the godlike Aias and lord Idomeneus, '),(3075,'for their ships are furthest of all and nowise nigh at hand. '),(3076,'But Menelaus will I chide, dear though he be and honoured,  aye, though thou shouldest be angry with me, nor will I hide my thought, for that he sleepeth thus, and hath suffered thee to toil alone.'),(3077,'Now had it been meet that he laboured among all the chieftains beseeching them'),(3078,'for need has come upon them that may no longer be borne.\"'),(3079,'And to him did the king of men, Agamemnon, make answer, saying:'),(3080,'  \"Old sir, at another time shalt thou chide him even at mine own bidding, '),(3081,'seeing he is often slack and not minded to labour, neither yielding to sloth nor to heedlessness of mind, but ever looking to me and awaiting my leading.'),(3082,'But now he awoke even before myself, and came to me,'),(3083,' and myself I sent him forth to summon those of whom thou inquirest.'),(3084,'But let us go;'),(3085,'we shall find them before the gates amid the sentinels, for there I bade them gather.\" '),(3086,'Then made answer to him the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia:'),(3087,' \"So will no man be wroth at him or disobey him  of all the Argives, whenso he urgeth any man or giveth commands.\"'),(3088,'So saying he did on his tunic about his breast, and beneath his shining feet bound his fair sandals and around him buckled a purple cloak of double fold and wide, whereon the down was thick.'),(3089,'  And he grasped a mighty spear, tipped with sharp bronze, and went his way among the ships of the brazen-coated Achaeans.'),(3090,'  Then Odysseus first, the peer of Zeus in counsel, did the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, awaken out of sleep with his voice'),(3091,'and forthwith the call rang all about his mind  and he came forth from the hut and spake to them, saying:'),(3092,' \"How is it that ye fare thus alone by the ships throughout the camp in the immortal night? What need so great hath come upon you?\"'),(3093,'Then made answer to him the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia:'),(3094,'\"Zeus-born son of Laërtes, Odysseus of many wiles'),(3095,'for great sorrow hath overmastered the Achaeans.'),(3096,'Nay, follow, that we may arouse another also, whomsoever it behoveth to take counsel, whether to flee or to fight.'),(3097,'So spake he, and Odysseus of many wiles went to the hut and cast about his shoulders a shield richly dight, and followed after them.'),(3098,'  And they came to Tydeus\' son, Diomedes'),(3099,'and him they found outside his hut with his arms; and around him his comrades were sleeping with their shields beneath their heads,'),(3100,'and around him his comrades were sleeping with their shields beneath their heads,'),(3101,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 10.152-10.154'),(3102,'But the warrior was sleeping,  and beneath him was spread the hide of an ox of the field, and beneath his head was stretched a bright carpet.'),(3103,'  To his side came the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, and woke him, stirring him with a touch of his heel, and aroused him, and chid him to his face:\"'),(3104,'why slumberest thou the whole night through in sleep?'),(3105,'why slumberest thou the whole night through in sleep?'),(3106,'  Knowest thou not that the Trojans on the rising ground of the plain are camped hard by the ships, and but scant space still holdeth them off?\"'),(3107,'So said he, but the other right swiftly sprang up out of sleep, and he spake and addressed him with winged words:\"'),(3108,'and from toil thou never ceasest.'),(3109,'and from toil thou never ceasest.'),(3110,'  Are there not other sons of the Achaeans that be younger, who might then rouse each one of the kings, going everywhere throughout the host?'),(3111,'  But with thee, old sir, may no man deal.\" '),(3112,'Then the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, answered him:\"'),(3113,'Nay verily, friend, all this hast thou spoken according to right.'),(3114,'  Peerless sons have I, and folk there be full many, of whom any one might go and call others.'),(3115,'  But in good sooth great need hath overmastered the Achaeans, '),(3116,'for now to all it standeth on a razor\'s edge, either woeful ruin for the Achaeans, or to live.'),(3117,'  But go now and rouse swift Aias and the son of Phyleus, '),(3118,'—if so be thou pitiest me.'),(3119,'—if so be thou pitiest me.'),(3120,'So spake he, and Diomedes clad about his shoulders the skin of a lion, fiery and great, a skin that reached his feet, and grasped his spear, '),(3121,'and he went his way, and roused those warriors from where they were, and brought them.'),(3122,'  Now when they had joined the company of the sentinels as they were gathered together, they found not the leaders of the sentinels asleep, but all were sitting awake with their arms.'),(3123,'  And even as dogs keep painful watch about sheep in a fold, when they hear the wild beast, stout of heart, that cometh through the wood  among the hills'),(3124,'and a great din ariseth about him of men and dogs, and from them sleep perisheth;'),(3125,'even so from their eyelids did sweet sleep perish, as they kept watch through the evil night;'),(3126,'for toward the plain were they ever turning if haply they might hear the Trojans coming on.'),(3127,'  At sight of them the old man waxed glad and heartened them, and spake and addressed them with winged words:'),(3128,' \"Even so now, dear children, keep your watch, '),(3129,'neither let sleep seize any man, lest we become a cause of rejoicing to our foes.'),(3130,'So saying he hasted through the trench'),(3131,'and there followed with him  the kings of the Argives, even all that had been called to the council.'),(3132,'But with them went Meriones and the glorious son of Nestor;'),(3133,' for of themselves they bade these share in their counsel.'),(3134,'So they went through and out from the digged ditch and sate them down in an open space, where the ground shewed clear of dead men fallen, '),(3135,' even where mighty Hector had turned back again from destroying the Argives, when night enfolded him.'),(3136,'There they sate them down and spake one to the other'),(3137,'and among them the horse-man, Nestor of Gerenia, was first to speak: '),(3138,'\"My friends, is there then no man who would trust his own venturous spirit  to go among the great-souled Trojans, if so be he might slay some straggler of the foemen, or haply hear some rumour among the Trojans, and what counsel they devise among themselves, whether to abide where they be by the ships afar, or to withdraw again to the city,  seeing they have worsted the Achaeans?'),(3139,'All this might he learn, and come back to us unscathed:'),(3140,'great would his fame be under heaven among all men, and a goodly gift shall be his.  '),(3141,'For of all the princes that hold sway over the ships,  of all these shall every man give him a black ewe with a lamb at the teat'),(3142,'— therewith may no possession compare;—and ever shall he be with us at feasts and drinking-bouts.\" '),(3143,'So said he, and they all became hushed in silence.'),(3144,' Then spake among them Diomedes, good at the war-cry:'),(3145,'  \"Nestor, my heart and proud spirit urge me to enter the camp of the foemen that are near, even of the Trojans; '),(3146,'howbeit if some other man were to follow with me, greater comfort would there be, and greater confidence.'),(3147,'When two go together, one discerneth before the other  how profit may be had; '),(3148,'whereas if one alone perceive aught, yet is his wit the shorter, and but slender his device.'),(3149,'So spake he, and many there were that were fain to follow Diomedes.  '),(3150,'Fain were the two Aiantes, squires of Ares, fain was Meriones, and right fain the son of Nestor,  fain was the son of Atreus, Menelaus, famed for his spear, and fain too was the stead-fast Odysseus to steal into the throng of the Trojans'),(3151,'for ever daring was the spirit in his breast'),(3152,' Then among them spake the king of men, Agamemnon:'),(3153,' \"Diomedes, son of Tydeus, dear to my heart,  that man shalt thou choose as thy comrade, whomsoever thou wilt, the best of them that offer themselves, for many are eager.'),(3154,'  And do not thou out of reverent heart leave the better man behind, and take as thy comrade one that is worse, yielding to reverence, and looking to birth, nay, not though one be more kingly.\"'),(3155,' So said he, since he feared for the sake of aired Menelaus '),(3156,' So said he, since he feared for the sake of aired Menelaus '),(3157,' \"If of a truth ye bid me of myself choose me a comrade, how should I then forget godlike Odysseus, whose heart and proud spirit are beyond all others eager  in all manner of toils; and Pallas Athene loveth him.  '),(3158,'If he but follow with me, even out of blazing fire might we both return, for wise above all is he in understanding.'),(3159,'Then spake unto him much enduring goodly Odysseus:'),(3160,' \"Son of Tydeus, praise me not over-much, neither blame me in aught: '),(3161,' this thou sayest among the Argives that themselves know all.'),(3162,'Nay, let us go'),(3163,'for verily the night is waning and dawn draweth near; lo, the stars have moved onward, and of the night more than two watches have past, and the third alone is left us.\" '),(3164,'So saying the twain clothed them in their dread armour.'),(3165,'  To Tydeus\' son Thrasymedes, staunch in fight, gave a two-edged sword'),(3166,' for his own was left by his ship—'),(3167,'and a shield'),(3168,'and about his head he set a helm of bull\'s hide without horn and without crest, a helm that is called a skull-cap, and that guards the heads of lusty youths.'),(3169,'  And Meriones gave to Odysseus a bow and a quiver and a sword, and about his head he set a helm wrought of hide'),(3170,'and with many a tight-stretched thong was it made stiff within,'),(3171,'while without the white teeth of a boar of gleaming tusks were set thick on this side and that,  well and cunningly'),(3172,'and within was fixed a lining of felt.'),(3173,'This cap Autolycus on a time stole out of Eleon when he had broken into the stout-built house of Amyntor, son of Ormenus; and he gave it to Amphidamas of Cythem to take to Scandeia'),(3174,'and Amphidamas gave it to Molus as a guest-gift,  but he gave it to his own son Meriones to wear;'),(3175,'and now, being set thereon, it covered the head of Odysseus.'),(3176,'So when the twain had clothed them in their dread armour, they went their way and left there all the chieftains.'),(3177,'And for them Pallas Athene sent forth on their right a heron, hard by the way, '),(3178,' and though they saw it not through the darkness of night, yet they heard its cry.'),(3179,' And Odysseus was glad at the omen, and made prayer to Athene:'),(3180,' \"Hear me, child of Zeus, that beareth the aegis, thou that dost ever stand by my side in all manner of toils, nor am I unseen of thee where\'er I move; '),(3181,' now again be thou my friend, Athene, as ne\'er thou wast before, and grant that with goodly renown we come back to the ships, having wrought a great work that shall be a sorrow to the Trojans.'),(3182,'And after him again prayed Diomedes, good at the war-cry:'),(3183,'Hearken thou now also to me, child of Zeus, unwearied one.'),(3184,'  Follow now with me even as thou didst follow with my father, goodly Tydeus, into Thebes, what time he went forth as a messenger of the Achaeans.'),(3185,'Them he left by the Asopus, the brazen-coated Achaeans, and he bare a gentle word thither to the Cadmeians;  '),(3186,'but as he journeyed back he devised deeds right terrible  with thee, fair goddess, for with a ready heart thou stoodest by his side.'),(3187,'Even so now of thine own will stand thou by my side, and guard me.'),(3188,'  And to thee in return will I sacrifice a sleek heifer, broad of brow, unbroken, which no man hath yet led beneath the yoke.'),(3189,'  Her will I sacrifice to thee and will overlay her horns with gold.\" '),(3190,'  So they spake in prayer and Pallas Athene heard them.  '),(3191,'But when they had prayed to the daughter of great Zeus, they went their way like two lions through the black night, amid the slaughter, amid the corpses, through the arms and the black blood.'),(3192,'Nay, nor did Hector suffer the lordly Trojans  to sleep, but he called together all the noblest, as many as were leaders and rulers of the Trojans; '),(3193,'and when he had called them together he contrived a cunning plan, and said:'),(3194,' \"Who is there now that would promise me this deed and bring it to pass for a great gift?'),(3195,'Verily his reward shall be sure.'),(3196,'  For I will give him a chariot and two horses with high arched necks, even those that be the best at the swift ships of the Achaeans, to the man whosoever will dare—and for himself win glory withal— to go close to the swift-faring ships, and spy out whether the swift ships be guarded as of old,  or whether by now our foes, subdued beneath our hands, are planning flight among themselves and have no mind to watch the night through, being fordone with dread weariness.\"'),(3197,'So spake he and they all became hushed in silence.  '),(3198,'Now there was among the Trojans one Dolon, the son of Eumedes  the godlike herald, a man rich in gold, rich in bronze, that was ill-favoured to look upon, but withal swift of foot; '),(3199,'and he was the only brother among five sisters.'),(3200,'He then spake a word to the Trojans and to Hector:\"'),(3201,'Hector, my heart and proud spirit urge me  to go close to the swift-faring ships and spy out all.  '),(3202,'But come, I pray thee, lift up thy staff and swear to me that verily thou wilt give me the horses and the chariot, richly dight with bronze, even them that bear the peerless son of Peleus.  And to thee shall I prove no vain scout, neither one to deceive thy hopes.'),(3203,'  For I will go straight on to the camp, even until I come to the ship of Agamemnon, where, I ween, the chieftains will be holding council, whether to flee or to fight.\"'),(3204,'So spake he, and Hector took the staff in his hands, and sware to him, saying: '),(3205,'\"Now be my witness Zeus himself, the loud-thundering lord of Hera,  that on those horses no other man of the Trojans shall mount, but it is thou, I declare, that shalt have glory in them continually.\" '),(3206,'So spake he, and swore thereto an idle oath, and stirred the heart of Dolon.  '),(3207,'Forthwith then he cast about his shoulders his curved bow, and thereover clad him in the skin of a grey wolf,  and on his head he set a cap of ferret skin, and grasped a sharp javelin, and went his way toward the ships from the host;'),(3208,'howbeit he was not to return again from the ships, and bear tidings to Hector.'),(3209,'But when he had left the throng of horses and of men'),(3210,'he went forth eagerly on the way, and Odysseus, sprung from Zeus, was ware of him as he drew nigh,  and spake to Diomedes: '),(3211,'\"Yonder, Diomedes, cometh some man from the camp, I know not  whether as a spy upon our ships, or with intent to strip one or another of the corpses of the dead.'),(3212,' But let us suffer him at the first to pass by us on the plain  a little way'),(3213,'and thereafter let us rush forth upon him and seize him speedily;'),(3214,'and if so be he outrun us twain by speed of foot ever do thou hem him in toward the ships away from the host, darting after him with thy spear, lest in any wise he escape toward the city.'),(3215,'So saying the twain laid them down among the dead apart from the path, '),(3216,' but he ran quickly past them in his witlessness.'),(3217,'But when he was as far off as is the range of mules in ploughing'),(3218,' —for they are better than oxen to draw through deep fallow land the jointed plough—'),(3219,'then the two ran after him, and he stood still when he heard the sound,'),(3220,' for in his heart he supposed that they were friends coming from   amid the Trojans to turn him back, and that Hector was withdrawing the host.'),(3221,'But when they were a spear-cast off or even less, he knew them for foemen and plied his limbs swiftly in flight, '),(3222,'and they speedily set out in pursuit.'),(3223,'  And as when two sharp-fanged hounds,—skilled in the hunt, press hard on a doe or a hare in a wooded place, and it ever runneth screaming before them; even so did the son of Tydeus, and Odysseus, sacker of cities, cut Dolon off from the host and ever pursue hard after him.'),(3224,'  But when he was now about to come among the sentinels, as he fled towards the ships, then verily Athene put strength into Tydeus\' son, that no man among the brazen-coated Achaeans might before him boast to have dealt the blow, and he come too late.'),(3225,'  And mighty Diomedes rushed upon him with his spear, and called:'),(3226,'  \"Stand, or I shall reach thee with the spear, and I deem thou shalt not long escape sheer destruction at my hand.\" '),(3227,'He spake, and hurled his spear, but of purpose he missed the man, \nand Dolon stood still, seized with terror,  stammering and pale with fear, and the teeth clattered in his mouth; '),(3228,'and over his right shoulder passed the point of the polished spear, and fixed itself in the ground;'),(3229,'and Dolon stood still, seized with terror,  stammering and pale with fear, '),(3230,'and the teeth clattered in his mouth;'),(3231,'in green fear; '),(3232,'and the twain panting for breath came upon him, and seized his hands; '),(3233,'and he with a burst of tears spake to them, saying:'),(3234,' \"Take me alive, and I will ransom myself; '),(3235,'for at  home have I store of bronze and gold and iron, wrought with toil;  thereof would my father grant you ransom past counting, should he hear that I am alive at the ships of the Achaeans.'),(3236,'Then in answer to him spake Odysseus of many wiles:'),(3237,' \"Be of good cheer, and let not death be in thy thoughts.'),(3238,'But come, tell me this, and declare it truly.'),(3239,'  Whither dost thou fare thus alone to the ships from the host in the darkness of night, when other mortals are sleeping?'),(3240,'Is it with intent to strip one or another of the corpses of the dead?'),(3241,' Did Hector send thee forth to the hollow ships to spy out all, '),(3242,'or did thine own heart bid thee?\"'),(3243,' To him then Dolon made answer, and his limbs trembled beneath him: '),(3244,'\"With many infatuate hopes did Hector lead my wits astray, who pledged him to give me the single-hooved horses of the lordly son of Peleus, and his chariot richly dight with bronze; and he bade me go through the swift, black night close to the foemen, and spy out  whether the swift ships be guarded as of old, or whether by now our foes, subdued beneath our hands, are planning flight among themselves, and have no mind to watch the night through, being fordone with dread weariness.\"'),(3245,'  Then smiling upon him Odysseus of many wiles made answer:'),(3246,' \"Verily now on great rewards was thy heart set, even the horses of the wise-hearted son of Aeacus'),(3247,'but hard are they for mortal men to master or to drive, save only for Achilles whom an immortal mother bare.'),(3248,' But come tell me this, and declare it truly'),(3249,'where now, as thou camest hither, didst thou leave Hector, shepherd of the host?'),(3250,'Where lies his battle-gear, and where his horses?'),(3251,'  And how are disposed the watches and the sleeping-places of the other Trojans? '),(3252,'And what counsel devise they among themselves?—to abide  where they be by the ships afar, or to withdraw again to the city, seeing they have worsted the Achaeans?\" '),(3253,'Then made answer to him Dolon, son of Eumedes:'),(3254,' \"Verily now will I frankly tell thee all.  Hector with all them that are counsellors  is holding council by the tomb of godlike Ilus, away from the turmoil; but as touching the guards whereof thou askest, O warrior, no special guard keepeth or watcheth the host.'),(3255,'Hector with all them that are counsellors  is holding council by the tomb of godlike Ilus, away from the turmoil;'),(3256,'but as touching the guards whereof thou askest, O warrior, no special guard keepeth or watcheth the host.'),(3257,'  By all the watch-fires of the Trojans verily, they that needs must, lie awake and bid one another keep watch, '),(3258,' but the allies, summoned from many lands, are sleeping; '),(3259,'for to the Trojans they leave it to keep watch'),(3260,'seeing their own children abide not nigh, neither their wives.'),(3261,'Then in answer to him spake Odysseus of many wiles'),(3262,' How is it now, do they sleep mingled with the horse-taming Trojans,  or apart?'),(3263,'tell me at large that I may know.'),(3264,'Then made answer to him Dolon, son of Eumedes:'),(3265,'\"Verily now this likewise will I frankly tell thee. '),(3266,'Towards the sea lie the Carians and the Paeonians, with curved bows, and the Leleges and Caucones, and the goodly Pelasgi.  And towards Thymbre fell the lot of the Lycians and the lordly Mysians, and the Phrygians that fight from chariots and the Maeonians, lords of chariots.'),(3267,'But why is it that ye question me closely regarding all these things? '),(3268,'For if ye are fain to enter the throng of the Trojans, lo, here apart be the Thracians, new comers, the outermost of all'),(3269,' and among them their king Rhesus, son of Eïoneus.'),(3270,'His be verily the fairest horses that ever I saw, and the greatest,'),(3271,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 10.437'),(3272,'from MILESTONE 435 to MILESTONE 440\n====================================================================== \nAnd his chariot is cunningly wrought with gold and silver'),(3273,'and armour of gold brought he with him, huge of size, a wonder to behold.'),(3274,'  Such armour it beseemeth not that mortal men should wear, but immortal gods.'),(3275,' But bring ye me now to the swift-faring ships, or bind me with a cruel bond and leave me here, that ye may go and make trial of me,  whether or no I have spoken to you according to right.\"'),(3276,'Then with an angry glance from beneath his brows, spake to him mighty Diomedes:'),(3277,' \"Nay, I  bid thee, Dolon, put no thought of escape in thy heart, '),(3278,'even though thou hast brought good tidings, seeing thou hast come into our hands.'),(3279,'  For if so be we release thee now or let thee go,  yet even hereafter wilt thou come to the swift ships of the Achaeans, either to spy upon us, or to fight in open combat;'),(3280,'but if, subdued beneath my hands, thou lose thy life, never again wilt thou prove a bane to the Argives.\" '),(3281,'He spake, and the other was at point to touch his chin with his stout hand  and make entreaty, but Diomedes sprang upon him with his sword and smote him full upon the neck, and shore off both the sinews'),(3282,'and even while he was yet speaking his head was mingled with the dust.'),(3283,'Then from him they stripped the cap of ferret skin from off his head, and the wolf\'s hide, and the back-bent bow and the long spear, '),(3284,' and these things did goodly Odysseus hold aloft in his hand to Athene, the driver of the spoil, and he made prayer, and spake, saying:'),(3285,' \"Rejoice, goddess, in these, for on thee, first of all the immortals in Olympus, will we call; but send thou us on against the horses and the sleeping-places of the Thracian warriors.\"'),(3286,'for on thee, first of all the immortals in Olympus, will we call;'),(3287,'but send thou us on against the horses and the sleeping-places of the Thracian warriors.\"'),(3288,' So spake he, and lifted from him the spoils on high, and set them on a tamarisk bush, '),(3289,'and set thereby a mark plain to see, gathering handfuls of reeds and luxuriant branches of tamarisk, lest they two might miss the place as they came back through the swift, black night.'),(3290,' But the twain went forward through the arms and the black blood,  and swiftly came in their course to the company of the Thracian warriors.'),(3291,'Now these were slumbering, foredone with weariness, and their goodly battle-gear lay by them on the ground, all in due order, in three rows'),(3292,'and hard by each man was his yoke of horses.'),(3293,'But Rhesus slept in the midst, and hard by him his swift horses  were tethered by the reins to the topmost rim of the chariot.  '),(3294,'Him Odysseus was first to espy, and shewed him to Diomedes:'),(3295,' \"Lo, here, Diomedes, is the man, and here are the horses whereof Dolon, that we slew, told us.'),(3296,'But come now, put forth mighty strength;'),(3297,'it beseemeth thee not at all  to stand idle with thy weapons; nay, loose the horses;'),(3298,'or do thou slay the men, and I will look to the horses.'),(3299,'So spake he, and into the other\'s heart flashing-eyed Athene breathed might, and he fell to slaving on this side and on that'),(3300,'and from them uprose hideous groaning as they were smitten with the sword, and the earth grew red with blood.'),(3301,'  And even as a lion cometh on flocks unshepherded, on goats or on sheep, and leapeth upon them with fell  intent, so up and down amid the Thracian warriors went the son of Tydeus until he had slain twelve. '),(3302,'But whomsoever the son of Tydeus drew nigh and smote with the sword,  him would Odysseus of the many wiles seize by the foot from behind and drag aside, with this thought in mind, that the fair-maned horses might easily pass through and not be affrighted at heart as they trod over dead men;'),(3303,'for they were as yet unused thereto.'),(3304,'But when the son of Tydeus came to the king,  him the thirteenth he robbed of honey-sweet life, as he breathed hard, '),(3305,'for like to an evil dream there stood above his head that night the son of Oeneus\' son, by the devise of Athene.'),(3306,'Meanwhile steadfast Odysseus loosed the single-hooved horses and bound them together with the reins, and drave them forth from the throng,  smiting them with his bow, for he had not thought to take in his hands the bright whip from the richly dight car; '),(3307,'and he whistled to give a sign to goodly Diomedes. '),(3308,'But he tarried and pondered what most reckless deed he might do, whether to take the chariot, where lay the war-gear richly dight,  and draw it out by the pole, or lift it on high and so bear it forth, or whether he should rather take the lives of yet more Thracians.'),(3309,'  The while he was pondering this in heart, even then Athene drew nigh and spake to goodly Diomedes:'),(3310,' \"Bethink thee now of returning, son of great-souled Tydeus,  to the hollow ships, lest thou go thither in full flight, and haply some other god rouse up the Trojans.\"'),(3311,'So spake she, and he knew the voice of the goddess as she spoke, and swiftly mounted the horses; and Odysseus smote them with his bow, '),(3312,'So spake she, and he knew the voice of the goddess as she spoke, and swiftly mounted the horses; and Odysseus smote them with his bow, '),(3313,'and they sped toward the swift ships of the Achaeans.'),(3314,'  But no blind watch did Apollo of the silver bow keep when he saw Athene attending the son of Tydeus; '),(3315,'in wrath against her he entered the great throng of the Trojans, and aroused a counsellor of the Thracians, Hippocoön, the noble kinsman of Rhesus.'),(3316,'And he leapt up out of sleep,  and when he saw the place empty where the swift horses had stood, and the men gasping amid gruesome streams of blood, then he uttered a groan, and called by name upon his dear comrade.'),(3317,'And from the Trojans arose a clamour and confusion unspeakable as they hasted together; and they gazed upon the terrible deeds,  even all that the warriors had wrought and thereafter gone to the hollow ships.'),(3318,'and they gazed upon the terrible deeds,  even all that the warriors had wrought and thereafter gone to the hollow ships.'),(3319,'But when these were now come to the place where they had slain the spy of Hector, then Odysseus, dear to Zeus, stayed the swift horses, and the son of Tydeus leaping to the ground placed the bloody spoils in the hands of Odysseus, and again mounted; '),(3320,' and he touched the horses with the lash, and nothing loath the pair sped on to the hollow ships, '),(3321,'for there were they fain to be.'),(3322,'And Nestor was first to hear the sound, and he spake, saying:'),(3323,' \"My frieads, leaders and rulers of the Argives, shall I be wrong, or speak the truth?'),(3324,'Nay, my heart bids me speak.'),(3325,'  The sound of swift-footed horses strikes upon mine ears.'),(3326,'I would that Odysseus and the valiant Diomedes may even thus speedily have driven forth from among the Trojans single-hooved horses; '),(3327,'but wondrously do I fear at heart lest those bravest of the Argives have suffered  some ill through the battle din of the Trojans.\" '),(3328,'  Not yet was the word fully uttered, when they came themselves.  '),(3329,'Down they leapt to earth, and the others were seized with joy and welcomed them with hand-clasps and with gentle words.'),(3330,'  And the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, was first to question them:'),(3331,' \'Come, tell me, honoured Odysseus, great glory of the Achaians, how did you win with this horses? Did you go into the great company of the Troyans or did some god that met you give you them? '),(3332,'Wondrous like are they to rays of the sun. '),(3333,'Ever do I mingle in battle with the Trojans and nowise methinks do I tarry by the ships, old warrior though I be;'),(3334,'  howbeit never yet saw I such horses neither thought of such.'),(3335,'Nay, methinks some god hath met you and given you them;'),(3336,'for both of you twain doth Zeus the cloud-gatherer love and the daughter of Zeus that beareth the aegis, even flashing-eyed Athene.\"'),(3337,'Then in answer spake unto him Odysseus of many wiles:'),(3338,'  \"Nestor, son of Neleus, great glory of the Achaeans, easily might a god that willed it bestow even better horses than these, for the gods are mightier far.'),(3339,'But these horses, old sir, whereof thou askest, are newly come from Thrace'),(3340,'and their lord did brave Diomedes  slay, and beside him twelve of his comrades, all them that were the best. '),(3341,'And for the thirteenth we slew a scout near the ships, one that Hector and the other lordly Trojans had sent forth to spy upon our camp.\"'),(3342,'So spake he, and drave the single-hooved horses through the trench,  exultingly'),(3343,'and with him went joyously the rest of the Achaeans.  '),(3344,'But when they were come to the well-builded hut of the son of Tydeus, the horses they bound with shapely thongs at the manger where stood the swift-footed horses of Diomedes, eating honey-sweet corn.'),(3345,'  And on the stern of his ship did Odysseus place the bloody spoils of Dolon until they should make ready a sacred offering to Athene.'),(3346,'But for themselves they entered the sea and washed away the abundant sweat from shins and necks and thighs.  '),(3347,'And when the wave of the sea had washed the abundant sweat  from their skin, and their hearts were refreshed, they went into polished baths and bathed.'),(3348,'But when the twain had bathed and anointed them richly with oil, they sate them down at supper, and from the full mixing-bowl they drew off honey-sweet wine and made libation to Athene.'),(3349,' Now Dawn rose from her couch from beside lordly Tithonus, to bring light to immortals and to mortal men; '),(3350,'and Zeus sent forth Strife unto the swift ships of the Achaeans, dread Strife, bearing in her hands a portent of war.'),(3351,'  And she took her hand by Odysseus\' black ship, huge of hull, that was in the midst so that a shout could reach to either end, both to the huts of Aias, son of Telamon, and to those of Achilles; for these had drawn up their shapely ships at the furthermost ends, trusting in their valour and the strength of their hands.  There stood the goddess and uttered a great and terrible shout, a shrill cry of war, and in the heart of each man of the Achaeans she put great strength to war and to fight unceasingly.'),(3352,'  And to them forthwith war became sweeter than to return in their hollow ships to their dear native land.'),(3353,'  But the son of Atreus shouted aloud, and bade the Argives array them for battle,'),(3354,'and himself amid them did on the gleaming bronze.'),(3355,'and himself amid them did on the gleaming bronze.'),(3356,'next he did on about his chest the corselet  that on a time Cinyras had given him for a guest-gift.  '),(3357,'For he heard afar in Cyprus the great rumour that the Achaeans were about to sail forth to Troy in their ships'),(3358,'wherefore he gave him the breastplate to do pleasure to the king'),(3359,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 11.24-11.25'),(3360,'from MILESTONE 20 to MILESTONE 30\n======================================================================\nand serpents of cyanus writhed up toward the neck, three on either side, like rainbows that the son of Cronos hath set in the clouds, a portent for mortal men.'),(3361,'And about his shoulders he flung his sword, '),(3362,'whereon gleamed  studs of gold, while the scabbard about it was of silver, fitted with golden chains.'),(3363,'  And he took up his richly dight, valorous shield, that sheltered a man on both sides, a fair shield, and round about it were ten circles of bronze, and upon it twenty bosses  of tin,  gleaming white, and in the midst of them was one of dark cyanus. '),(3364,'And thereon was set as a crown the Gorgon, grim of aspect, glaring terribly, and about her were Terror and Rout.'),(3365,'From the shield was hung a baldric of silver,'),(3366,'and thereon writhed a serpent of cyanus, that had  three heads turned this way and that, growing forth from one neck.'),(3367,'And upon his head he set his helmet with two horns and with bosses four, with horsehair crest,'),(3368,'and terribly did the plume nod from above.'),(3369,' And he took two mighty spears, tipped with bronze; '),(3370,'keen they were, and far from him into heaven shone the bronze; '),(3371,' and thereat Athene and Hera thundered, doing honour to the king of Mycenae, rich in gold. '),(3372,'Then on his own charioteer each man laid command to hold in his horses well and orderly there at the trench, but themselves on foot, arrayed in their armour, ranged swiftly forward. '),(3373,' and a cry unquenchable rose up before the face of Dawn.'),(3374,'Long in advance of the charioteers were they arrayed at the trench, but after them a little space followed the charioteers.'),(3375,'  And among them the son of Cronos roused an evil din, and down from on high from out of heaven he sent dew-drops dank with blood, for that he was about  to send forth to Hades many a valiant head.'),(3376,'And the Trojans over against them on the rising ground of the plain mustered about great Hector and peerless Polydamas and Aeneas that was honoured of the folk of the Trojans even as a god, and the three sons of Antenor, Polybus and goodly Agenor  and young Acamas, like to the immortals.'),(3377,'And Hector amid the foremost bare his shield that was well balanced upon every side.  Even as from amid the clouds there gleameth a baneful star, all glittering, and again it sinketh behind the shadowy clouds, even so Hector would now appear amid the foremost  and now amid the hindmost giving them commands; '),(3378,'and all in bronze he flashed like the lightning of father Zeus that beareth the aegis.'),(3379,'And as reapers over against each other drive their swathes in a rich man\'s field of wheat or barley'),(3380,'and the handfuls fall thick and fast; '),(3381,' even so the Trojans and Achaeans leapt upon one another and made havoc, nor would either side take thought of ruinous flight;'),(3382,'and equal heads had the battle, and they raged like wolves.'),(3383,' And Strife, that is fraught with many groanings, was glad as she looked thereon; '),(3384,'for alone of the gods she was with them in their fighting;  whereas the other gods were not among them, but abode in peace in their own halls, where for each one a fair palace was builded amid the folds of Olympus.'),(3385,'  And all were blaming the son of Cronos, lord of the dark clouds, for that he willed to give glory to the Trojans.'),(3386,'  Howbeit of them the father recked not;'),(3387,'but aloof from the others he sat apart exulting in his glory, looking upon the city of the Trojans, and the ships of the Achaeans, on the flashing of the bronze, and on the slayers and the slain. '),(3388,'Now as long as it was morn and the sacred day was waxing'),(3389,'  so long the missiles of either side struck home, and the folk kept falling;'),(3390,'but at the hour when a woodman maketh ready his meal in the glades of a mountain, when his arms are grown tired with felling tall trees, and weariness cometh upon his soul, and desire of sweet food seizeth his heart,  even then the Danaans by their valour brake the battalions, calling to their fellows through the lines.'),(3391,'  And among them Agamemnon rushed forth the first and slew a warrior, Bienor, shepherd of the host,—himself and after him his comrade, Oïleus, driver of horses.'),(3392,' Oïleus verily leapt down from his chariot and stood and faced him'),(3393,' but even as he rushed straight upon him the king smote him on the forehead with his sharp spear, nor was the spear stayed by his helm, heavy with bronze, but passed through it and through the bone, and all his brain was spattered about within; '),(3394,'so stayed he him in his fury.'),(3395,'  These then did Agamemnon, king of men, leave there,  gleaming with their naked breasts, when he had stripped off their tunics'),(3396,'and went on to slay Isus and Antiphus, two sons of Priam, one a bastard and one born in wedlock, the twain being in one car:'),(3397,'  the bastard the reins, but glorious Antiphus stood by his side to fight.  '),(3398,'These twain had Achilles on a time  bound with fresh withes amid the spurs of Ida, taking them as they were herding their sheep, and had set them free for a ransom.'),(3399,'  But now the son of Atreus, wide-ruling Agamemnon, struck Isus on the breast above the nipple with a cast of his spear, and Antiphus he smote hard by the ear with his sword, and cast him from the chariot.'),(3400,'  Then he made haste to strip from the twain their goodly battle-gear, knowing them full well'),(3401,'for he had seen them before by the swift ships, when Achilles, fleet of foot brought them from Ida.'),(3402,'  And as a lion easily crusheth the little ones of a swift hind, when he hath seized them with his strong teeth,  and hath come to their lair, and taketh from them their tender life,'),(3403,'—and the mother, though she chance to be very near, cannot succour them'),(3404,'for on herself too cometh dread trembling'),(3405,'and swiftly she darteth through the thick brush and the woodland, hasting and sweating before the onset of the mighty beast; '),(3406,' even so was no one of the Trojans able to ward off destruction from these twain, but themselves were driven in flight before the Argives. '),(3407,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 11.122-11.127'),(3408,'for the shining reins had slipped from their hands, and the two horses were running wild; '),(3409,'but he rushed against them like a lion,  the son of Atreus'),(3410,'and the twain made entreaty to him from the car:'),(3411,'\"Take us alive, thou son of Atreus, and accept a worthy ransom;'),(3412,'treasures full many he stored in the palace of Antimachus, bronze and gold and iron, wrought with toil; thereof would our father grant thee ransom past counting,  should he hear that we are alive at the ships of the Achaeans.\"'),(3413,'So with weeping the twain spake unto the king with gentle words, '),(3414,'but all ungentle was the voice they heard:'),(3415,' \"If ye are verily the sons of wise-hearted Antimachus, who on a time in the gathering of the Trojans, when Menelaus  had come on an embassage with godlike Odysseus, bade slay him then and there, neither suffer him to return to the Achaeans, now of a surety shall ye pay the price of your father\'s foul outrage.\"'),(3416,'He spake, and thrust Peisander from his chariot to the ground, smiting him with his spear upon the breast,'),(3417,'and backward was he hurled upon the earth.'),(3418,'  But Hippolochus leapt down, and him he slew upon the ground, and shearing off his arms with the sword, and striking off his head, sent him rolling, like a round stone, amid the throng.'),(3419,'These then he let be'),(3420,'but where chiefly the battalions were being driven in rout, there leapt he in, and with him other well-greaved Achaeans.'),(3421,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 11.150-11.151'),(3422,'  Footmen were ever slaying footmen as they fled perforce, and horsemen horse-men \n— ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 150 to line 153'),(3423,' And lord Agamemnon, ever slaying, followed after, calling to the Argives.'),(3424,'  And as when consuming fire falls upon thick woodland, and the whirling wind beareth it everywhither, and the thickets fall utterly as they are assailed by the onrush of the fire; '),(3425,'even so beneath Agamemon, son of Atreus, fell the heads of the Trojans as they fled, and many horses with high-arched necks rattled  empty cars along the dykes of battle, lacking their peerless charioteers'),(3426,'who were lying upon the ground dearer far to the vultures than to their wives. '),(3427,'But Hector did Zeus draw forth from the missiles and the dust, from the man-slaying and the blood and the din;'),(3428,' but the son of Atreus followed after, calling fiercely to the Danaans.  '),(3429,'And past the tomb of ancient Ilos, son of Dardanus, over the midst of the plain, past the wild fig-tree they sped, striving to win to the city'),(3430,'and ever did the son of Atreus follow shouting, and with gore were his invincible hands bespattered'),(3431,'  But when they were come to the Scaean gates and the oak-tree, there then the two hosts halted and awaited each the other.'),(3432,'Howbeit some were still being driven in rout over the midst of the plain like kine that a lion hath scattered, coming upon them in the dead of night;'),(3433,'all hath he scattered, but to one appeareth sheer destruction;'),(3434,' her neck he seizeth first in his strong teeth and breaketh it and thereafter devoureth the blood and all the inward parts:'),(3435,'  even in like manner did lord Agamemnon, son of Atreus, follow hard upon the Trojans, ever slaying the hindmost'),(3436,'and they were driven in rout'),(3437,'And many fell from their chariots upon their faces or upon their backs  beneath the hands of Atreus\' son'),(3438,'for around and before him he raged with his spear.'),(3439,'But when he was now about to come beneath the city and the steep wall, then, verily, the father of men and gods came down from heaven and sate him down on the peaks of many-fountained Ida; '),(3440,'and in his hands he held the thunder-bolt.'),(3441,'  And he sent forth golden-winged Iris to bear his message:'),(3442,'\"Up go, swift Iris, and declare this word unto Hector:'),(3443,'So long as he shall see Agamemnon, shepherd of the host, raging amid the fore-most fighters, laying waste the ranks of men, so long let him hold back, and bid the rest of the host  fight with the foe in the fierce conflict.  '),(3444,'But when, either wounded by a spear-thrust or smitten by an arrow, Agamemnon shall leap upon his chariot, then will I vouchsafe strength to Hector to slay and slay until he come to the well-benched ships, and the sun sets and sacred darkness cometh on.'),(3445,'  So spake he, and wind-footed swift Iris failed not to hearken, but went down from the hills of Ida to sacred Ilios.'),(3446,'She found the son of wise-hearted Priam, goodly Hector, standing in his jointed car; '),(3447,'and swift-footed Iris drew nigh him and spake unto him, saying:'),(3448,'  \"Hector, son of Priam, peer of Zeus in counsel, Zeus the father hath sent me forth to declare to thee this message.'),(3449,'So long as thou shalt see Agamemnon, shepherd of the host, raging amid the foremost fighters, laying waste the ranks of men, so long do thou give place from battle, but bid the rest of the host  fight with the foe in the fierce conflict.  '),(3450,'But when either wounded by a spear-thrust or smitten with an arrow Agamemnon shall leap upon his chariot, then will Zeus vouchsafe strength to thee to slay and slay until thou come to the well-benched ships, and the sun sets and sacred darkness cometh on.\" '),(3451,'  When she had thus spoken swift-footed Iris departed; and Hector leapt in his armour from his chariot to the ground, and brandishing his two sharp spears went everywhere throughout the host, urging them to fight, and roused the dread din of battle.'),(3452,'So they rallied, and took their stand with their faces toward the Achaeans,  and the Argives over against them made strong their battalions.'),(3453,'And the battle was set in array, and they stood over against each other, '),(3454,'and among them Agamemnon rushed forth the first, and was minded to fight far in advance of all.'),(3455,'Tell me now, ye Muses, that have dwellings on Olympus, who it was that first came to face Agamemnon,  either of the Trojans themselves or of their famed allies. '),(3456,'It was Iphidamas, son of Antenor, a valiant man and tall, that was nurtured in deep-soiled Thrace, mother of flocks'),(3457,'and Cisseus reared him in his house while he was yet but a little child, even his mother\'s father, that begat fair-cheeked Theano.'),(3458,'  But when he came to the measure of glorious youth he sought to keep him there, and offered him his own daughter;'),(3459,'howbeit, a bridegroom newly wed, forth from his bridal chamber he went after the rumour of the coming of the Achaeans, with twelve beaked ships that followed him.'),(3460,'  Now these he had left at Percote, the shapely ships,  but himself had come by land to Ilios; '),(3461,'he it was that now came to face Agamemnon, son of Atreus.'),(3462,'  And when they were come near as they advanced one against the other, the son of Atreus missed, and his spear was turned aside, but Iphidamas stabbed him on the girdle beneath the corselet,  and put his weight into the thrust, trusting in his heavy hand'),(3463,'howbeit he pierced not the flashing girdle, for long ere that the spear-point struck the silver, and was bent like lead.'),(3464,'  Then wide-ruling Agamamnon seized the spear in his hand and drew it toward him furiously like a lion, and pulled it from the hand of Iphidamas, '),(3465,' and smote him on the neck with his sword and loosed his limbs. '),(3466,'So there he fell, and slept a sleep of bronze, unhappy youth, far from his wedded wife, bearing aid to his townsfolk—far from the bride of whom he had known no joy, yet much had he given for her; '),(3467,'first he gave an hundred kine, and thereafter promised a thousand,  goats and sheep together, which were herded for him in flocks past counting.'),(3468,'Then did Agamemnon, son of Atreus, strip him and went through the throng of the Achaeans bearing his goodly armour. '),(3469,'But when Coön, pre-eminent among warriors, eldest son of Antenor, marked him, strong grief  enfolded his eyes for his brother\'s fall'),(3470,'and he took his stand on one side with his spear, unseen of goodly Agamemnon, and stabbed him full upon the arm below the elbow, and clean through went the point of the shining spear.'),(3471,'Thereat shuddered Agamemnon king of men, '),(3472,' yet even so he ceased not from battle and war, but, wind-nurtured spear in hand, leapt upon Coön.'),(3473,'Now he was eagerly drawing by the foot Iphidamas, his own brother, begotten of the one father, and was calling upon all the bravest, '),(3474,'but even as he dragged him through the throng Agamemnon smote him with a thrust of his bronze-shod spear beneath his bossed shield,  and loosed his limbs; '),(3475,'and he drew near and struck off his head over Iphidamas.'),(3476,'  There then the sons of Antenor beneath the hands of the king, the son of Atreus, fulfilled the measure of their fate, and went down to the house of Hades.'),(3477,'But Agamemnon ranged along the ranks of the other warriors  with spear and sword and great stones, so long as the blood welled yet warm from his wound'),(3478,'But when the wound waxed dry, and the blood ceased to flow, then sharp pains came upon the mighty son of Atreus.  '),(3479,'And even as when the sharp dart striketh a woman in travail,  the piercing dart that the Eilithyiae, the goddesses of childbirth, send—even the daughters of Hera that have in their keeping bitter pangs; even so sharp pains came upon the mighty son of Atreus.'),(3480,'Then he leapt upon his chariot and bade his charioteer drive to the hollow ships'),(3481,'for he was sore pained at heart.'),(3482,' And he uttered a piercing shout, and called to the Danaans:'),(3483,'\"My friends, leaders and rulers of the Argives, do ye now ward from the seafaring ships the grievous din of battle, for Zeus the counsellor suffereth me not to war the whole day through against the Trojans.\"'),(3484,'  So spake he, and the charioteer lashed the fair-maned horses towards the hollow ships, '),(3485,'and nothing loath the pair sped onward.'),(3486,'  With foam were their breasts flecked, and with dust their bellies stained beneath them as they bore the wounded king forth from the battle.'),(3487,'But when Hector saw Agamemnon departing,  to Trojans and Lycians he called with a loud shout:'),(3488,' \"Ye Trojans and Lycians and Dardanians that fight in close combat, be men, my friends, and bethink you of furious valour.'),(3489,'Gone is the best of the men, and to me hath Zeus, son of Cronos granted great glory.'),(3490,'Nay, drive your single-hooved horses straight towards '),(3491,'So saving he aroused the strength and spirit of every man.'),(3492,'  And even as when a huntsman sets his white-toothed hounds upon a wild boar or a lion, so upon the Achaeans did  Hector, son of Priam, peer of Ares, the bane of mortals, set the great-souled Trojans.  '),(3493,'Himself with high heart he strode among the foremost, and fell upon the conflict like a blustering tempest, that leapeth down and lasheth to fury the violet-hued deep.'),(3494,'Who then was first to be slain, and who last by  Hector, Priam\'s son, when Zeus vouchsafed him glory?  Asaeus first, and Autonous, and Opites and Dolops, son of Clytius, and Opheltius, and Agelaus, and Aesymnus, and Orus, and Hipponous, staunch in fight.  '),(3495,'Asaeus first, and Autonous, and Opites and Dolops, son of Clytius, and Opheltius, and Agelaus, and Aesymnus, and Orus, and Hipponous, staunch in fight.'),(3496,'These leaders of the Danaans he slew and thereafter fell upon the multitude,  and even as when the West Wind driveth the clouds of the white South Wind, smiting them with a violent squall, '),(3497,'and many a swollen wave rolleth onward, and on high the spray is scattered beneath the blast of the wandering wind; '),(3498,'even so many heads of the host were laid low by Hector.'),(3499,'  Then had ruin come, and deeds beyond remedy been wrought, and now would the Achaeans in flight have flung themselves upon their ships, had not Odysseus called to Diomedes, son of Tydeus:'),(3500,' \"Tydeus\' son, what has come over us that we have forgotten our furious valour?'),(3501,'  Nay, come thou hither, good friend, and take thy stand by my side'),(3502,'for verily shame  will it be if Hector of the flashing helm shall take the ships.'),(3503,'Then in answer to him spake mighty Diomedes:'),(3504,' \"Of a surety will I abide and endure'),(3505,' but for scant space shall be our profit, for Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, plainly willeth to give victory to the Trojans rather than to us.'),(3506,'  He spake, and thrust Thymbraeus from his chariot to the ground, smiting him with his spear on the left breast'),(3507,'and Odysseus smote Molion, the godlike squire of that prince.'),(3508,'These then they let be, when they had made them cease from war; '),(3509,'but the twain ranged throughout the throng, making havoc of it, as when two boars  with high hearts fall upon hunting hounds;'),(3510,' even so they turned again upon the Trojans and slew them'),(3511,'and the Achaeans gladly had respite in their flight before goodly Hector.'),(3512,'Then took they a chariot and two men, the best of their people, sons twain of Merops of Percote, that was above all men  skilled in prophesying, and would not suffer his sons to go into war, the bane of men; '),(3513,'but the twain would in no wise hearken to him'),(3514,'for the fates of black death were leading them on'),(3515,'  These did the son of Tydeus, Diomedes, famed for his spear, rob of spirit and of life, and took from them their goodly battle-gear. '),(3516,'while Odysseus killed Hypeirochos and Hippodamos.'),(3517,'Then the son of Cronos stretched evenly for them the line of battle, as he looked down from Ida'),(3518,'and they kept slaying one another.'),(3519,'  Tydeus\' son wounded the warrior Agastrophus, son of Paeon, on the hip with a thrust of his spear; '),(3520,'nor were his horses  near at hand for him to flee, but he was greatly blinded at heart;'),(3521,'for his squire held the horses withdrawn apart, and he on foot was raging amid the foremost fighters until he lost his life.'),(3522,' But Hector was quick to mark them across the ranks, and rushed upon them, shouting, '),(3523,'and with him followed the battalions of the Trojans.'),(3524,'  At sight of him Diomedes, good at the war-cry, shuddered, and forthwith spake to Odysseus that was near:'),(3525,' \"On us twain is this ruin rolling, even mighty Hector; '),(3526,'but come, let us stand, and ward off his onset abiding where we are.'),(3527,'He spake and poised his far-shadowing spear, and hurled it, nor missed he the mark at which he aimed, but smote him on the head, on the top of the helmet'),(3528,'but the bronze was turned aside by bronze, and reached not his fair flesh'),(3529,'for it was stayed by the threefold crested helm, which Phoebus Apollo had bestowed upon him.  '),(3530,'But Hector sprang back a wondrous way, and mingled with the throng,  and he fell upon his knees and thus abode, and with his stout hand leaned upon the earth, '),(3531,'and dark night enfolded his eyes.'),(3532,'  But while the son of Tydeus was following after the cast of his spear far through the foremost fighters, where he had seen it fix itself in the earth, meanwhile Hector revived again, and leaping back into his chariot  drave forth into the throng, and escaped black fate.'),(3533,'And rushing after him with his spear mighty Diomedes spake to him:'),(3534,' \"Now again, thou dog, art thou escaped from death, '),(3535,'though verily thy bane came nigh thee;'),(3536,'but once more hath Phoebus Apollo saved thee, to whom of a surety thou must make prayer whenso thou goest amid the hurtling of spears.'),(3537,'  Verily I will yet make an end of thee when I meet thee hereafter, if so be any god is helper to me likewise.'),(3538,'  But now will I make after the rest, whomsoever I may light upon.\" '),(3539,'So spake he, and went on to strip of his armour the son of Paeon, famed for his spear.  '),(3540,'But Alexander, lord of fair-haired Helen,  aimed an arrow at Tydeus\' son, shepherd of the host, leaning the while against a pillar on the barrow that men\'s hands reared for Ilus, son of Dardanus, an elder of the people in days of old.'),(3541,'Now Diomedes was stripping the gleaming corselet of valiant Agastrophus from about his breast, and the shield from off his shoulder,  and his heavy helm'),(3542,'when Paris drew the centre-piece of the bow and smote him—for not in vain did the shaft speed from his hand—upon the flat of the right foot'),(3543,'and the arrow passed clean through and fixed itself in the ground; '),(3544,'and with a right merry laugh Paris leapt up from his lair and spake vauntingly:'),(3545,'  \"Thou art smitten, not in vain hath my shaft sped;'),(3546,'would that I had smitten thee in the nethermost belly, and taken away thy life.'),(3547,' So would the Trojans have had respite from their woe, who now tremble before thee as bleating goats before a lion.\"'),(3548,'But with no touch of fear mighty Diomedes spake to him:'),(3549,'  \"Bowman, reviler, proud of thy curling locks, thou ogler of girls! O that thou wouldst make trial of me man to man in armour, then would thy bow and thy swift-falling arrows help thee not; '),(3550,'whereas now having but grazed the flat of my foot thou boastest vainly.'),(3551,'I reck not thereof, any more than if a woman had struck me or a witless child'),(3552,' for blunt is the dart of one that is a weakling and a man of naught.'),(3553,'  Verily in other wise when sped by my hand, even though it do but touch, does the spear prove its edge, and forthwith layeth low its man;'),(3554,'torn then with wailing are the two cheeks of his wife, and his children fatherless, '),(3555,'while he, reddening the earth with his blood,  rotteth away, more birds than women around him.'),(3556,'So spake he, and to him did Odysseus, famed for his spear, draw nigh, and take his stand before him, '),(3557,'and Diomedes sat down behind him, and drew forth the sharp arrow from his foot, and a sore pang shot through his flesh.'),(3558,'  Then leapt he upon his chariot and bade his charioteer  drive to the hollow ships, for he was sore pained at heart.'),(3559,'  Then leapt he upon his chariot and bade his charioteer  drive to the hollow ships, for he was sore pained at heart.'),(3560,'Now Odysseus famed for his spear, was left alone, nor did anyone of the Argives abide by him, for that fear had laid hold of them all.'),(3561,'  Then mightily moved he spake unto his own great-hearted spirit:'),(3562,' \"Woe is me; what is to befall me?'),(3563,'Great evil were it if I flee,  seized with fear of the throng; '),(3564,'yet this were a worse thing, if I be taken all alone'),(3565,'for the rest of the Danaans hath the son of Cronos scattered in flight.'),(3566,'But why doth my heart thus hold converse with me?  '),(3567,'For I know that they are cowards that depart from battle, whereas whoso is pre-eminent in fight, him verily it behoveth '),(3568,'While he pondered thus in mind and heart, meanwhile the ranks of the shield-bearing Trojans came on and hemmed him in the midst, setting among them their own bane.  '),(3569,'And even as hounds and lusty youths press upon a boar on this side and on that,  and he cometh forth from the deep thicket, whetting his white tusks in his curving jaws, and they charge upon him on either side, and thereat ariseth the sound of the gnashing of tusks; but forthwith they abide his onset, how dread soever he be; even so then around Odysseus, dear to Zeus, did the Trojans press.'),(3570,'  But first he smote peerless Deïopites from above in the shoulder, leaping upon him with sharp spear; and thereafter he slew Thoön and Eunomus, '),(3571,'and then Chersidamas as he leapt down from his car he stabbed with his spear upon the navel beneath his bossed shield;'),(3572,' and he fell in the dust and clutched the ground with his palm.  '),(3573,'These then he let be, but smote Charops, son of Hippasus, with a thrust of his spear, even the own brother of wealthy Socus. '),(3574,'  \"Odysseus, greatly to be praised, insatiate in wiles and in toil, this day shalt thou either boast over both the sons of Hippasus, for that thou hast slain two such warriors and stripped them of their armour, or else smitten by my spear shalt thou lose thy life.\"'),(3575,'So saying, he smote upon his shield that was well balanced upon every side.'),(3576,'  Through the bright shield went the mighty spear, and through the corselet, richly dight, did it force its way, and all the flesh it tore from his side; but Pallas Athene suffered it not to pierce the bowels of the warrior.'),(3577,' And Odysseus knew that the spear had in no wise lighted on a fatal spot,  and he drew back and spake to Socus, saying: '),(3578,'\"Ah wretch, of a surety is sheer destruction come upon thee'),(3579,'Verily hast thou made me to cease from warring against the Trojans; '),(3580,'but upon thee I deem that here this day death and black fate shall come, and that vanquished beneath my spear thou  shalt yield glory to me, and thy soul to Hades of the goodly steeds.'),(3581,'He spake, and the other turned back and started to flee, but even as he turned Odysseus fixed the spear in his back between the shoulders, and drave it through his breast.'),(3582,'  And he fell with a thud, and goodly Odysseus exulted over him:'),(3583,'  \"Ah Socus, son of wise-hearted Hippasus, tamer of horses, the end of death has been too quick in coming upon thee; thou hast not escaped it.'),(3584,'Ah poor wretch, thy father and queenly mother shall not close thine eyes in death, but the birds that eat raw flesh shall rend thee, beating their wings thick and fast about thee; '),(3585,'If I die, the brilliant Achaians will bury me in honour.\''),(3586,'So saying he drew the mighty spear of wise-hearted Socus forth from his flesh and from his bossed shield'),(3587,'and when it was drawn out the blood gushed forth and distressed his spirit.'),(3588,'  But the great-souled Trojans, when they beheld the blood of Odysseus,  called one to another through the throng and made at him all together.'),(3589,'But he gave ground, and shouted to his comrades;'),(3590,'thrice shouted he then loud as a man\'s head can shout, and thrice did Menelaus, dear to Ares, hear his call'),(3591,'and forthwith he spake to Aias that was nigh at hand:'),(3592,'  \"Aias, sprung from Zeus, thou son of Telamon, captain of the host, in mine ears rang the cry of Odysseus, of the steadfast heart, like as though the Trojans had cut him off in the fierce conflict and were over-powering him alone as he is.'),(3593,'to bear him aid is the better course.'),(3594,'to bear him aid is the better course.'),(3595,'  I fear lest some evil befall him, alone mid the Trojans, valiant though he be, and great longing for him come upon the Danaans.\"'),(3596,'So saying he led the way, and Aias followed, a godlike man.'),(3597,'Then found they Odysseus, dear to Zeus '),(3598,'and round about the Trojans beset him, as tawny jackals in the mountains  about a horned stag that hath been wounded, that a man hath smitten with an arrow from the string;'),(3599,'from him the stag hath escaped and fleeth swiftly so long as the blood flows warm and his knees are quick,'),(3600,'but when at length the swift arrow overpowereth him, then ravening jackals rend him amid the mountains  in a shadowy grove;'),(3601,'but lo, God bringeth against them a murderous lion'),(3602,'but lo, God bringeth against them a murderous lion, and the jackals scatter in flight, and he rendeth the prey:'),(3603,' even so then did the Trojans, many and valiant, beset Odysseus round about, the wise and crafty-minded; but the warrior darting forth with his spear warded off the pitiless day of doom.'),(3604,'  Then Aias drew near, bearing his shield that was like a city wall, and stood forth beside him, and the Trojans scattered in flight, one here, one there.'),(3605,'and the Trojans scattered in flight, one here, one there.'),(3606,'  And warlike Menelaus led Odysseus forth from the throng, holding him by the hand, till his squire drave up the horses and car. '),(3607,'Then Aias leapt upon the Trojans and slew Doryclus,  bastard son of Priam, and after him smote Pandocus with a thrust, and likewise Lysander and Pyrasus and Pylartes.  '),(3608,'And as when a river in flood cometh down upon a plain, a winter torrent from the mountains, driven on by the rain of Zeus, and many a dry oak and many a pine it beareth in its course,  and much drift it casteth into the sea; even so glorious Aias charged tumultuously over the plain on that day, slaying horses and men. '),(3609,'Nor did Hector as yet know aught thereof, for he was fighting on the left of all the battle by the banks of the river Scamander, where chiefly  the heads of warriors were falling, and a cry unquenchable arose, round about great Nestor and warlike Idomeneus.'),(3610,' With these had Hector dalliance, and terrible deeds he wrought with the spear and in horsemanship, and he laid waste the battalions of the young men. '),(3611,'Yet would the goodly Achaeans in no wise have given ground from their course,  had not Alexander, the lord of fair-haired Helen, stayed Machaon, shepherd of the host, in the midst of his valorous deeds, and smitten him on the right shoulder with a three-barbed arrow.'),(3612,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 11.508-11.509'),(3613,'lest haply men should slay him in the turning of the fight.'),(3614,'  And forthwith Idomeneus spake to goodly Nestor:\"Nestor, son of Neleus, great glory of the Achaeans, come, get thee upon thy chariot, and let Machaon mount beside thee, and swiftly do thou drive to the ships thy single-hooved horses.'),(3615,'  For a leech is of the worth of many other men  for the cutting out of arrows and the spreading of soothing simples.\"'),(3616,'So spake he, and the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, failed not to hearken.'),(3617,'Forthwith he got him upon his chariot, and beside him mounted Machaon, the son of Asclepius the peerless leech;'),(3618,'and he touched the horses with the lash, and nothing loath the pair sped on  to the hollow ships,'),(3619,' for there were they fain to be.'),(3620,'But Cebriones beheld the Trojans being driven in rout, as he stood by Hector\'s side in his chariot, and he spake to him, saying:'),(3621,'Hector, we twain have dalliance with the Danaans here, on the skirts of dolorous war,'),(3622,'whereas the other  Trojans are driven in rout confusedly, both horses and men.'),(3623,'well do I know him,'),(3624,'well do I know him,'),(3625,'for wide is the shield he hath about his shoulders.  '),(3626,'Nay, let us too drive thither our horses and car, where most of all horsemen and footmen, vying in evil rivalry, '),(3627,'So saying he smote the fair-maned horses with the shrill-sounding las'),(3628,'and they, feeling the blow, fleetly bare the swift car amid the Trojans and Achaeans,'),(3629,'and with blood was all the axle  sprinkled beneath, and the rims round about the car, with the drops that smote upon them from the horses\' hooves and from the tires.'),(3630,'  And Hector was eager to enter the throng of muen, to leap in and shatter it'),(3631,'and an evil din of war he sent among the Danaans, and scant rest did he give his spear.'),(3632,'  Nay, he ranged among the ranks of the other warriors with spear and sword and with great stones; only he avoided battle with Aias, son of Telamon.'),(3633,'Now father Zeus, throned on high, roused Aias to flight, '),(3634,' and he stood in a daze, and on his back he cast his sevenfold shield of bull\'s-hide, and with an anxious glance toward the throng he gave way, like a wild beast, ever turning him about and retreating slowly step by step.  '),(3635,'And even as a tawny lion is driven from the fold of the kine by dogs and country folk'),(3636,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 11.551-11.552'),(3637,'but he in his lust for flesh goeth straight on, yet accomplisheth naught thereby,\nὃ δὲ κρειῶν ἐρατίζων ἰθύει, ἀλλ̓ οὔ τι πρήσσει·[551,552]\n########################################################################\n\n======================================================================\nfrom MILESTONE 540 to MILESTONE 560\n======================================================================\n for thick the darts fly to meet him, hurled by bold hands, and blazing brands withal, before which he quaileth, how eager soever he be, '),(3638,' and at dawn he departeth with sullen heart; '),(3639,'so Aias then gave way before the Trojans sullen at heart, and sorely against his will,'),(3640,'for exceedingly did he fear for the ships of the Achaeans.'),(3641,'And as when an ass that passeth by a cornfield getteth the better of boys—a lazy ass about whose ribs many a cudgel is broken,  and he goeth in and wasteth the deep grain,'),(3642,'and the boys beat him with cudgels, '),(3643,'though their might is but puny, '),(3644,'and hardly do they drive him forth when he hath had his fill of fodder; '),(3645,'even so then did the Trojans, high of heart, and their allies, gathered from many lands, smite great Aias, son of Telamon,  with spears full upon his shield, and ever press upon him.  '),(3646,'And Aias would now be mindful of his furious valour, and wheeling upon them would hold back the battalions of the horse-taming Trojans,'),(3647,' and now again he would turn him to flee.'),(3648,' But he barred them all from making way to the swift ships,  and himself stood between Trojans and Achaeans, battling furiously.'),(3649,'  And the spears hurled by bold hands were some of them lodged in his great shield, as they sped onward, and many, ere ever they reached his white body, stood fixed midway in the earth, fain to glut themselves with flesh. '),(3650,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 11.575-11.579'),(3651,'  But when Euaemon\'s glorious son, Eurypylus, saw him oppressed by thick-flying missiles, he came and stood by his side and hurled with his shining spear, and smote Apisaon, son of Phausius, shepherd of the host, in the liver below the midriff, and straightway loosed his knees; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 575 to line 584'),(3652,'But when godlike Alexander marked him stripping the harness from Apisaon, forthwith he drew his bow against Eurypylus, and smote him with an arrow on the right thigh;'),(3653,'and the reed of the arrow brake, yet was his thigh made heavy.'),(3654,'  Then back he shrank into the throng of his comrades, avoiding fate, and he uttered a piercing shout, and called to the Danaans:\"'),(3655,'My friends, leaders and rulers of the Argives, turn ye and stand, and ward off the pitiless day of doom from Aias who is oppressed with missiles; nor do I deem  that he will escape from dolorous war.  '),(3656,'Nay verily, stand ye and face the foe about great Aias, son of Telamon.'),(3657,'So spake the wounded Eurypylus'),(3658,'and they came and stood close beside him, leaning their shields against their shoulders and holding their spears on high;'),(3659,'and toward them came Aias,'),(3660,' and turned and stood when he had reached the throng of his comrades.'),(3661,'So fought they like unto blazing fire;'),(3662,'but the mares of Neleus, all bathed in sweat, bare Nestor forth from the battle, and bare also Machaon, shepherd of the host.'),(3663,'  And swift-footed goodly Achilles beheld and marked him, '),(3664,' for Achilles was standing by the stern of his ship, huge of hull, gazing upon the utter toil of battle and the tearful rout.'),(3665,'  And forthwith he spake to his comrade Patroclus, calling to him from beside the ship; '),(3666,'and he heard, and came forth from the hut like unto Ares; and this to him was the beginning of evil.'),(3667,'  Then the valiant son of Menoetius spake the first:'),(3668,'  What need hast thou of me?\"'),(3669,'  What need hast thou of me?\"'),(3670,'And in answer to him spake Achilles, swift of foot:'),(3671,' \"Goodly son of Menoetius, dear to this heart of mine, now methinks will the Achaeans be standing about my knees in prayer, '),(3672,' for need has come upon them that may no longer be borne.  '),(3673,'Yet go now, Patroclus, dear to Zeus, and ask Nestor who it is that he bringeth wounded from out the war.'),(3674,'Of a truth from behind he seemeth in all things like Machaon, son of Asclepius, but I saw not the eyes of the man, '),(3675,'since the horses were tearing forward and swept on by me.\''),(3676,'So spake he, and Patroclus gave ear to his dear comrade, and went running along the huts and the ships of the Achaeans.'),(3677,'But when those others were come to the hut of the son of Neleus, they stepped forth upon the bounteous earth,  and Eurymedon the squire loosed old Nestor\'s horses from the car'),(3678,'and the twain dried the sweat from their tunics standing in the breeze by the shore of the sea'),(3679,'and thereafter they went into the hut and sate them down on chairs.'),(3680,' And for them fair-tressed Hecamede mixed a potion,  she that old Nestor had taken from out of Tenedos, when Achilles sacked it, the daughter of great-hearted Arsinous; for the Achaeans had chosen her out for him, for that in counsel he was ever best of all.  '),(3681,'She first drew before the twain a table, fair, with feet of cyanus, and well-polished, and set thereon  a basket of bronze, and therewith an onion, a relish for their drink, and pale honey, and ground meal of sacred barley; and beside them a beauteous cup, that the old man had brought from home, studded with bosses of gold; '),(3682,'four were the handles thereof, and about each  twain doves were feeding, while below were two supports.'),(3683,'Another man could scarce have availed to lift that cup from the table, when it was full, but old Nestor would raise it right easily. '),(3684,'Therein the woman, like to the goddesses, mixed a potion for them with Pramnian wine, and on this she grated cheese of goat\'s milk  with a brazen grater, and sprinkled thereover white barley meal and she bade them drink, when she had made ready the potion.'),(3685,'  Then when the twain had drunk, and sent from them parching thirst, they took delight in tales, speaking each to the other; and lo, Patroclus stood at the doors, a godlike man.'),(3686,'  At sight of him the old man sprang from his bright chair, and took him by the hand and led him in, and bade him be seated.'),(3687,'  But Patroclus from over against him refused, and spake, saying:'),(3688,' \"I may not sit, old sir, fostered of Zeus, nor wilt thou persuade me.'),(3689,'  Revered and to be dreaded is he who sent me forth to learn  who it is that thou bringest home wounded.  '),(3690,'But even of myself I know, and behold Machaon, shepherd of the host.'),(3691,' And now will I go back again a messenger, to bear word to Achilles.'),(3692,'  Well knowest thou, old sir, fostered of Zeus, of what sort is he, dread man;'),(3693,' lightly would he blame even one in whom was no blame.'),(3694,'  Then made answer the horseman Nestor of Gerenia:'),(3695,'\"Wherefore now doth Achilles thus have pity for the sons of the Achaeans, as many as have been smitten with missiles?'),(3696,'  Nor knoweth he at all what grief hath arisen throughout the camp; '),(3697,'for the best men lie among the ships smitten by darts or wounded with spear-thrusts.'),(3698,'  Smitten is the son of Tydeus, mighty Diomedes, wounded with spearthrust is Odysseus, famed for his spear, and Agamemnon'),(3699,'and smitten is Eurypylus too with an arrow in the thigh,'),(3700,'and this man beside have I but now borne forth from the war smitten with an arrow from the string.'),(3701,'  Yet Achilles,  valiant though he be, careth not for the Danaans, neither hath pity.  '),(3702,'Doth he wait until the swift ships hard by the sea, in despite of the Argives, shall blaze with consuming fire, and ourselves be slain man after man?'),(3703,'For my strength is not such as of old it was in my supple limbs.'),(3704,'  Would that I were young and my strength were as when strife was set afoot between the Eleans and our folk about the lifting of kine, what time I slew Itymoneus, the valiant son of Hypeirochus, a man that dwelt in Elis, when I was driving off what we had seized in reprisal; '),(3705,'and he while fighting for the kine  was smitten amid the foremost by a spear from my hand; and he fell, and the country folk about him fled in terror.'),(3706,'And booty exceeding great did we drive together from out the plain, fifty herds of kine, as many flocks of sheep, as many droves of swine, as many roving herds of goats,  and chestnut horses an hundred and fifty, all mares, and many of them had foals at the teat.'),(3707,' These then we drave into Neleian Pylos by night into the citadel, '),(3708,'and Neleus was glad at heart for that much spoil had fallen to me when going as a stripling into war.'),(3709,'  And heralds made loud proclamation at break of dawn that all men should come to whomsoever a debt was owing in goodly Elis;'),(3710,'and they that were leaders of the Pylians gathered together and made division,'),(3711,'for to many did the Epeians owe a debt, seeing that we in Pylos were few and oppressed.'),(3712,'  For mighty Heracles had come and oppressed us in the years that were before, and all that were our bravest had been slain.'),(3713,'  Twelve were we that were sons of peerless Neleus, '),(3714,'and of these I alone was left, and all the rest had perished;'),(3715,'wherefore the brazen-coated Epeans, proud of heart thereat'),(3716,'  And from out the spoil old Neleus chose him a herd of kine and a great flock of sheep, choosing three hundred and their herdsman with them.'),(3717,'  For to him a great debt was owing in goodly Elis, even our horses, winners of prizes, with their car,  that had gone to the games,'),(3718,' for they were to race for a tripod; '),(3719,'but Augeias, king of men, kept them there, and sent back their driver, sorrowing for his horses.'),(3720,' By reason of these things, both deeds and words, was the old man wroth and chose him recompense past telling;  '),(3721,'and the rest he gave to the people  to divide, that so far as in him lay no man might go defrauded of an equal share.'),(3722,'So we were disposing of all that there was, and round about the city were offering sacrifice to the gods;'),(3723,'and on the third day the Epeians came all together, many men and single-hooved horses, with all speed, '),(3724,'and among them the two Moliones did on their battle-gear,  though they were as yet but stripligs unskilled in furious valour.'),(3725,'Now there is a city Thryoessa, a steep hill, far off on the Alpheius, the nethermost of sandy Pylos;'),(3726,'about this they set their camp, fain to raze it utterly.  '),(3727,'But when they had coursed over the whole plain to us came Athene,  speeding down from Olympus by night with the message that we should array us for battle, and nowise loath were the folk she gathered in Pylos, but right eager for war.'),(3728,'  Now Neleus would not suffer me to arm myself, but hid away my horses, '),(3729,'for he deemed that as yet I knew naught of deeds of war.'),(3730,'  Howbeit even so I was pre-eminent among our horsemen, on foot though I was, for so did Athene order the fight.'),(3731,'There is a river Minyeïus that empties into the sea hard by Arene, where we waited for bright Dawn, we the horsemen of the Pylians, and the throngs of footmen flowed ever after.'),(3732,'  Thence with all speed, arrayed in our armour, we came at midday to the sacred stream of Alpheius. '),(3733,'There we sacrificed goodly victims to Zeus, supreme in might, and a bull to Alpheius, and a bull to Poseidon, but to flashing-eyed Athene a heifer of the herd;  and thereafter we took supper throughout the host by companies, and laid us down to sleep, each man in his battlegear, about the streams of the river.'),(3734,'But the great-souled Epeians were marshalled about the city, fain to raze it utterly; '),(3735,'but ere that might be there appeared unto them a mighty deed of war;'),(3736,' for when the bright sun stood above the earth we made prayer to Zeus and Athene, and joined battle.'),(3737,'   But when the strife of the Pylians and Epeians began, I was first to slay my man, and to get me his single-hooved horses—even the spearman Mulius; '),(3738,'son by marriage was he of Augeias,  and had to wife his eldest daughter, fair-haired Agamede, who knew all simples that the wide earth nourisheth.'),(3739,'  Him as he came against me I smote with may bronze-tipped spear, and he fell in the dust; '),(3740,'but I leapt upon his chariot and took my stand amid the foremost fighters.'),(3741,'But the great-souled Epeians  fled one here, one there, when they saw the man fallen, even him that was leader of the horsemen and preeminent in fight.'),(3742,'  But I sprang upon them like a black tempest and fifty chariots I took, and about each one two warriors bit the ground, quelled by my spear.'),(3743,'  And now had I slain the two Moliones, of the blood of Actor, but that their father, the wide-ruling Shaker of Earth, saved them from war, and shrouded them in thick mist.'),(3744,'  Then Zeus vouchsafed great might to the men of Pylos'),(3745,'for so long did we follow through the wide plain,  slaying the men and gathering their goodly battle-gear, even till we drave our horses to Buprasium, rich in wheat, and the rock of Olen and the place where is the hill called the hill of Alesium,'),(3746,'whence Athene again turned back the host. Then I slew the last man, and left him;'),(3747,'Then I slew the last man, and left him;'),(3748,'but the Achaeans drave back their swift horses  from Buprasium to Pylos, and all gave glory among the gods to Zeus, and to Nestor among men.'),(3749,'Of such sort was I among warriors, as sure as ever I was.'),(3750,' But Achilles would alone have profit of his valour.'),(3751,'Nay, verily, methinks he will bitterly lament hereafter, when the folk perisheth.'),(3752,'  Ah, friend, of a surety Menoetius thus laid charge upon thee on the day when he sent thee forth from Phthia to Agamemnon.  And we twain were within, I and goodly Odysseus, and in the halls we heard all things, even as he gave thee charge.'),(3753,'For we had come to the well-builded house of Peleus,  gathering the host throughout the bounteous land of Achaia.'),(3754,'There then we found in the house the warrior Menoetius and thee, and with you Achilles;'),(3755,'and the old man Peleus, driver of chariots, was burning the fat thighs of a bull to Zeus that hurleth the thunderbolt, in the enclosure of the court, '),(3756,'and he held in his hand a golden cup,  pouring forth the flaming wine to accompany the burning offerings.'),(3757,'Ye twain were busied about the flesh of the bull, and lo, we stood in the doorway; '),(3758,'and Achilles, seized with wonder, sprang up, and took us by the hand and led us in, and bade us be seated, and he set before us abundant entertainment, all that is the due of strangers. '),(3759,'  But when we had had our fill of food and drink, I was first to speak, and bade you follow with us; '),(3760,'and ye were both right eager, and those twain laid on you many commands.'),(3761,'Old Peleus bade his son Achilles ever be bravest, and pre-eminent above all,'),(3762,' but to thee did Menoetius, son of Actor, thus give command: '),(3763,' ‘My child, in birth is Achilles nobler than thou, but thou art the elder though in might he is the better far.'),(3764,'Yet do thou speak to him well a word of wisdom and give him counsel, and direct him; '),(3765,'Yet do thou speak to him well a word of wisdom and give him counsel, and direct him; '),(3766,'and he will obey thee to his profit.'),(3767,'This is what the old man told you, you have forgotten.'),(3768,'Yet even now at the last do thou speak thus to wise-hearted Achilles, if so be he may hearken.'),(3769,'Who knows but that heaven helping thou mightest rouse his spirit with thy persuading? '),(3770,' A good thing is the persuasion of a friend.'),(3771,'But if in his heart he is shunning some oracle  and his queenly mother hath declared to him aught from Zeus, yet let him send thee forth, and with thee let the rest of the host of the Myrmidons follow, if so be thou mayest prove a light of deliverance to the Danaans; '),(3772,'and let him give thee his fair armour to bear into the war, in hope that the Trojans may take thee for him, and so hold aloof from battle,  and the warlike sons of the Achaeans may take breath, wearied though they be;'),(3773,'for scant is the breathing-space in battle.'),(3774,'  And lightly might ye that are unwearied drive men that are wearied with battle back toward the city from the ships and the huts.\"'),(3775,'So spake he, and roused the heart in the breast of Patroclus,  and he set out to run along the line of the ships to Achilles, son of Aeacus.  '),(3776,'But when in his running Patroclus was come to the ships of godlike Odysseus, where was their place of gathering and of the giving of dooms, whereby also were builded their altars of the gods, there Eurypylus met him,  the Zeus-born son of Euaemon, smitten in the thigh with an arrow, limping from out the battle.'),(3777,'  And in streams down from his head and shoulders flowed the sweat, and from his grievous wound the black blood was gushing, '),(3778,'yet was his spirit unshaken.'),(3779,'  At sight of him the valiant son of Menoetius had pity on him,  and with wailing spake to him winged words:'),(3780,'\"Ah ye wretched men, leaders and lords of the Danaans, thus then were ye destined, far from your friends and your native land, to glut with your white fat the swift dogs in Troy.'),(3781,'But come, tell me this, Eurypylus, warrior fostered of Zeus,  will the Achaeans haply still hold back mighty Hector, or will they now perish, slain beneath his spear?\" '),(3782,'And to him again made answer the wounded Eurypylus:\"'),(3783,'No longer, Zeus-born Patroclus, will there be any defence of the Achaeans, but they will fling themselves upon the black ships.'),(3784,'  For verily all they that aforetime were bravest, lie among the ships smitten by darts or wounded with spear-thrusts at the hands of the Trojans, '),(3785,'whose strength ever waxeth'),(3786,'But me do thou succour, and lead me to my black ship, and cut the arrow from my thigh, and wash the black blood from it  with warm water, and sprinkle thereon kindly simples of healing power, whereof men say that thou hast learned from Achilles, whom Cheiron taught, the most righteous of the Centaurs. '),(3787,'For the leeches, Podaleirius and Machaon, the one methinks lieth wounded amid the huts,  having need himself of a goodly leech, and the other in the plain abideth the sharp battle of the Trojans.\"'),(3788,'and the other in the plain abideth the sharp battle of the Trojans.'),(3789,'\"And to him again spake the valiant son of Menoetius: '),(3790,'What shall we do, warrior Eurypylus?'),(3791,'What shall we do, warrior Eurypylus?'),(3792,'  I am on my way to declare to wise-hearted Achilles a message  wherewith Nestor of Gerenia, warder of the Achaeans, charged me.  '),(3793,'Nay, but even so will I not neglect thee that art in grievous plight.'),(3794,'He spake and clasped the shepherd of the host beneath the breast, and led him to his hut,'),(3795,'and his squire when he saw them strewed upon the ground hides of oxen.'),(3796,'  There Patroclus made him lie at length,  and with a knife cut from his thigh the sharp-piercing arrow, and from the wound washed the black blood with warm water, and upon it cast a bitter root, when he had rubbed it between his hands, a root that slayeth pain, which stayed all his pangs; '),(3797,'and the wound waxed dry, and the blood ceased.'),(3798,' So then amid the huts the valiant son of Menoetius was tending the wounded Eurypylus,'),(3799,'but the others, Argives and Trojans, fought on in throngs'),(3800,'nor were the ditch of the Danaans and their wide wall above long to protect them,  the wall that they had builded as a defence for their ships and had drawn a trench about it'),(3801,'—yet they gave not glorious hecatombs to the gods—'),(3802,'that it might hold within its bounds their swift ships and abundant spoil, and keep all safe.'),(3803,'Howbeit against the will of the immortal gods was it builded; '),(3804,'wherefore for no long time did it abide unbroken.'),(3805,'  As long as Hector yet lived, and Achilles yet cherished his wrath, and the city of king Priam was unsacked, even so long the great wall of the Achaeans likewise abode unbroken. '),(3806,'But when all the bravest of the Trojans had died and many of the Argives—some were slain and some were left—  and the city of Priam was sacked in the tenth year, and the Argives had gone back in their ships to their dear native land, then verily did Poseidon and Apollo take counsel to sweep away the wall'),(3807,'bringing against it the might of all the rivers that flow forth from the mountains of Ida to the sea—  Rhesus and Heptaporus and Caresus and Rhodius, and Granicus and Aesepus, and goodly Scamander, and Simois, by the banks whereof many shields of bull\'s-hide and many helms fell in the dust, and the race of men half-divine'),(3808,'—of all these did Phoebus Apollo turn the mouths together,  and for nine days\' space he drave their flood against the wall; '),(3809,'and Zeus rained ever continually, that the sooner he might whelm the wall in the salt sea.'),(3810,'And the Shaker of Earth, bearing his trident in his hands, was himself the leader, and swept forth upon the waves all the foundations of beams and stones, that the Achaeans had laid with toil,  and made all smooth along the strong stream of the Hellespont, and again covered the great beach with sand, when he had swept away the wall; '),(3811,'and the rivers he turned back to flow in the channel, where aforetime they had been wont to pour their fair streams of water. '),(3812,'Thus were Poseidon and Apollo to do in the aftertime; '),(3813,' but then war and the din of war blazed about the well-builded wall, and the beams of the towers rang, as they were smitten;'),(3814,'and the Argives, conquered by the scourge of Zeus, were penned by their hollow ships, and held in check in terror of Hector,'),(3815,'the mighty deviser of rout,  while he as aforetime fought like unto a whirlwind.'),(3816,'And as when, among hounds and huntsmen, a wild boar or a lion wheeleth about, exulting in his strength, '),(3817,'and these array them in ranks in fashion like a wall, and stand against him, and hurl from their hands javelins thick and fast; '),(3818,' yet his valiant heart feareth not nor anywise quaileth, though his valour is his bane;'),(3819,'and often he wheeleth him about and maketh trial of the ranks of men, and wheresoever he chargeth,'),(3820,' there the ranks of men give way:'),(3821,' even on this wise Hector went ever through the throng and besought his comrades,  urging them to cross the trench.'),(3822,'Howbeit his swift-footed horses dared not, but loudly they neighed, standing on the sheer brink,'),(3823,'for the trench affrighted them, so wide was it, easy neither to o\'erleap at a bound nor to drive across; '),(3824,'for over-hanging banks stood all about its circuit on this side and on that,  and at the top it was set with sharp stakes that the sons of the Achaeans had planted, close together and great, a defence against foemen.'),(3825,' Not lightly might a horse, tugging at the wheeled car, get within that circuit; but the footmen were eager, if thy might achieve it. '),(3826,' Then verily Polydamas drew nigh to Hector, and spake, saying: '),(3827,'“Hector, and ye other leaders of the Trojans and allies, it is but folly that we seek to drive across the trench our swift horses; '),(3828,'hard in sooth is it to cross'),(3829,' for sharp stakes are set in it, and close anigh them is the wall of the Achaeans. There is it no wise possible for charioteers to descend and fight; '),(3830,'for the space is narrow, and then methinks shall we suffer hurt.'),(3831,'  For if Zeus, that thundereth on high, is utterly to crush our foes in his wrath, and is minded to give aid unto the Trojans, there verily were I too fain that this might forthwith come to pass, that the Achaeans should perish here far from Argos, and have no name;'),(3832,' but if they turn upon us and we be driven back from the ships and become entangled in the digged ditch, then methinks shall not one man of us return back to the city from before the Achaeans when they rally, even to bear the tidings.'),(3833,'  But come, even as I shall bid, let us all obey'),(3834,'As for the horses, let the squires hold them back by the trench, but let us on foot, arrayed in our armour, follow all in one throng after Hector; '),(3835,'and the Achaeans will not withstand us, if so be the bonds of destruction are made fast upon them.\" '),(3836,'  So spake Polydamas, and his prudent counsel was well pleasing unto Hector, and forthwith he leapt in his armour from his chariot to the ground.'),(3837,' Nor did the other Trojans remain gathered together upon their chariots, but they all leapt forth when they beheld goodly Hector afoot.'),(3838,'Then on his own charioteer each man laid command to hold in his  horses well and orderly there at the trench, '),(3839,'but the men divided and arrayed themselves, and marshalled in five companies they followed after the leaders.'),(3840,'Some went with Hector and peerless Polydamas,  even they that were most in number and bravest, and that were most fain to break through the wall and fight by the hollow ships'),(3841,'and with them followed Cebriones as the third; '),(3842,'for by his chariot had Hector left another man, weaker than Cebriones.'),(3843,'  The second company was led by Paris and Alcathous and Agenor, and the third by Helenus and godlike Deïphobus—  sons twain of Priam; '),(3844,'and a third was with them, the warrior Asius,—Asius son of Hyrtacus, whom his horses tawny and great had borne from Arisbe, from the river Selleïs.'),(3845,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 12.98-12.100'),(3846,'And of the fourth company the valiant son of Anchises was leader, even Aeneas, and with him were Antenor\'s two sons,  Archelochus and Acamas, well skilled in all manner of fighting.  ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 98 to line 104'),(3847,'for these seemed to him to be the bravest beyond all others after his own self, '),(3848,'but he was pre-eminent even amid all.'),(3849,'  These then when they had fenced one another with their well-wrought shields of bull\'s-hide, made straight for the Danaans, full eagerly, nor deemed they that they would any more be stayed, but would fall upon the black ships. '),(3850,'Then the rest of the Trojans and their far-famed allies obeyed the counsel of blameless Polydamas,'),(3851,' but Asius, son of Hyrtacus, leader of men, was not minded to leave there his horses and his squire the charioteer, but chariot and all he drew nigh to the swift ships, fool that he was!  for he was not to escape the evil fates, and return, glorying in horses and chariot,  back from the ships to windy Ilios.'),(3852,'Nay, ere that might be, fate, of evil name, enfolded him, by the spear of Idomeneus, the lordly son of Deucalion.'),(3853,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 12.118-12.119'),(3854,'from MILESTONE 115 to MILESTONE 125\n======================================================================\n  there drave he through his horses and car, and at the gate he found not the doors shut nor the long bar drawn, but men were holding them flung wide open, if so be they might save any of their comrades fleeing from out the battle toward the ships.'),(3855,'Thither of set purpose drave he his horses, and after him followed his men with shrill cries,  '),(3856,'for they deemed that they would no more be stayed of the Achaeans, but would fall upon the black ships—fools that they were!  for at the gate they found two warriors most valiant, high-hearted sons of Lapith spearmen, the one stalwart Polypoetes, son of Peirithous,  and the other Leonteus, peer of Ares the bane of men.'),(3857,'These twain before the high gate stood firm even as oaks of lofty crest among the mountains, that ever abide the wind and rain day by day, firm fixed with roots great and long;'),(3858,'  even so these twain, trusting in the might of their arms, abode the oncoming of great Asius, and fled not.'),(3859,'But their foes came straight against the well-built wall, lifting on high their shields of dry bull\'s-hide with loud shouting, round about king Asius, and Iamenus, and Orestes,  and Adamas, son of Asius, and Thoön and Oenomaus.  '),(3860,'And the Lapiths for a time from within the wall had been rousing the well-greaved Achaeans to fight in defence of the ships;'),(3861,'but when they saw the Trojans rushing upon the wall, while the Danaans with loud cries turned in flight,  forth rushed the twain and fought in front of the gate like wild boars that amid the mountains abide the tumultuous throng of men and dogs that cometh against them, and charging from either side they crush the trees about them, cutting them at the root, and therefrom ariseth a clatter of tusks,  till one smite them and take their life away: '),(3862,'even so clattered the bright bronze about the breasts of the twain, as they were smitten with faces toward the foe; '),(3863,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 12.152-12.153'),(3864,'For the men above kept hurling stones from the well-built towers,  in defence of their own lives and of the huts and of the swift-faring ships.'),(3865,'  And like snow-flakes the stones fell ever earthward, like flakes that a blustering wind, as it driveth the shadowy clouds, sheddeth thick and fast upon the bounteous earth;'),(3866,'even so flowed the missiles from the hands of these, of Achaeans  alike and Trojans;'),(3867,'and helms rang harshly and bossed shields, as they were smitten with great stones.'),(3868,'Then verily Asius, son of Hyrtacus, uttered a groan, and smote both his thighs, and in sore indignation he spake, saying:'),(3869,' \"Father Zeus, of a surety thou too then art utterly a lover of lies,  '),(3870,' for I deemed not that the Achaean warriors would stay our might and our invincible hands. '),(3871,'But they like wasps of nimble waist, or bees that have made their nest in a rugged path, and leave not their hollow home, but abide,  and in defence of their young ward off hunter folk; even so these men, though they be but two, are not minded to give ground from the gate, till they either slay or be slain.'),(3872,'So spake he, but with these words he moved not the mind of Zeus, '),(3873,'for it was to Hector that Zeus willed to vouchsafe glory.'),(3874,'  But others were fighting in battle about the other gates, '),(3875,'and hard were it for me, as though I were a god, to tell the tale of all these things,.'),(3876,'for everywhere about the wall of stone rose the wondrous-blazing fire;'),(3877,'for the Argives, albeit in sore distress, defended their ships perforce;'),(3878,'and the gods were grieved at heart,  all that were helpers of the Danaans in battle'),(3879,'And the Lapiths clashed in war and strife.'),(3880,'Then the son of Peirithous, mighty Polypoetes, cast with his spear and smote Damasus through the helmet with cheek pieces of bronze; '),(3881,' and the bronze helm stayed not the spear, but the point of bronze brake clean through the bone, and all the brain was spattered about within; '),(3882,'so stayed he him in his fury.'),(3883,' And thereafter he slew Pylon and Ormenus.'),(3884,'And Leonteus, son of Ares, smote Hippomachus, son of Antimachus, with a cast of his spear, striking him upon the girdle.'),(3885,'  And again he drew from its sheath his sharp sword and darting upon him through the throng smote Antiphates first in close fight, '),(3886,'so that he was hurled backward upon the ground; '),(3887,'and thereafter Menon, and Iamenus, and Orestes, all of these one after the other he brought down to the bounteous earth. '),(3888,'  While they were stripping from these their shining arms, meanwhile the youths that followed with Polydamas and Hector, even they that were most in number and bravest, and that most were fain to break through the wall and burn the ships with fire, these still tarried in doubt, as they stood by the trench.'),(3889,'  For a bird had come upon them, as they were eager to cross over, an eagle of lofty flight, skirting the host on the left, and in its talons it bore a blood-red, monstrous snake, still alive as if struggling, nor was it yet forgetful of combat, it writhed backward, and smote him that held it on the breast beside the neck'),(3890,'  till the eagle, stung with pain, cast it from him to the ground, and let it fall in the midst of the throng, and himself with a loud cry sped away down the blasts of the wind.'),(3891,' And the Trojans shuddered when they saw the writhing snake lying in the midst of them, a portent of Zeus that beareth the aegis.'),(3892,'  Then verily Polydamas drew near, and spake to bold Hector:'),(3893,'\"Hector, ever dost thou rebuke me in the gatherings of the folk, though I give good counsel, since it were indeed unseemly that a man of the people should speak contrariwise to thee, be it in council or in war, but he should ever increase thy might; '),(3894,' yet now will I speak even as seemeth to me to be best.  '),(3895,'Let us not go forward to fight with the Danaans for the ships.  '),(3896,'For thus, methinks, will the issue be, seeing that in sooth this bird has come upon the Trojans, as they were eager to cross over, an eagle of lofty flight, skirting the host on the left,  bearing in his talons a blood-red, monstrous snake, still living'),(3897,'yet straightway let it fall before he reached his own nest, neither finished he his course, to bring and give it to his little ones'),(3898,'—even so shall we, though we break the gates and the wall of the Achaeans by our great might, and the Achaeans give way,  come back over the selfsame road from the ships in disarray; '),(3899,'for many of the Trojans shall we leave behind, whom th Achaeans shall slay with the bronze in defense of the ships.'),(3900,'  On this wise would a soothsayer interpret, one that in his mind had clear knowledge of omens, and to whom the folk gave ear.\" '),(3901,'  Then with an angry glance from beneath his brows spake to him Hector of the flashing helm:'),(3902,' \"Polydamas, this that thou sayest is no longer to my pleasure; '),(3903,'yea, thou knowest how to devise better words than these.  '),(3904,'But if thou verily speakest thus in earnest, then of a surety have the gods themselves destroyed thy wits,  seeing thou biddest me forget the counsels of loud-thundering Zeus, that himself promised me and bowed his head thereto.'),(3905,' But thou biddest us be obedient to birds long of wing, that I regard not, nor take thought thereof, whether they fare to the right, toward the Dawn and the sun,  or to the left toward the murky darkness. nay, for us, let us be obedient to the counsel of great Zeus, that is king over all mortals and immortals.  '),(3906,' nay, for us, let us be obedient to the counsel of great Zeus, that is king over all mortals and immortals.'),(3907,'One omen is best, to fight for one\'s country.'),(3908,'Wherefore dost thou fear war and battle?'),(3909,'  For if the rest of us be slain one and all at the ships of the Argives, yet is there no fear that thou shouldest perish,'),(3910,'—for thy heart is—not staunch in fight nor warlike.'),(3911,'  Howbeit, if thou shalt hold aloof from battle, or shalt beguile with thy words an other, and turn him from war,  forthwith smitten by my spear shalt thou lose thy life.\"'),(3912,'So spake he and led the way; and they followed after with a wondrous din; '),(3913,'and thereat Zeus, that hurleth the thunderbolt, roused from the mountains of Ida a blast of wind, that bare the dust straight against the ships'),(3914,'and he bewildered the mind of the Achaeans, but vouchsafed glory to the Trojans and to Hector.'),(3915,'  Trusting therefore in his portents and in their might they sought to break the great wall of the Achaeans.'),(3916,'The pinnets of the fortifications they dragged down and overthrew the battlements, and pried out the supporting beams that the Achaeans had set  first in the earth as buttresses for the wall.  '),(3917,'These they sought to drag out, and hoped to break the wall of the Achaeans.'),(3918,' Howbeit not even now did the Danaans give ground from the path, but closed up the battlements with bull\'s-hides, and therefrom cast at the foemen, as they came up against the wall.'),(3919,'  And the two Aiantes ranged everywhere along the walls urging men on, and arousing the might of the Achaeans.'),(3920,'  One man with gentle words, another with harsh would they chide, whomsoever they saw giving ground utterly from the fight:'),(3921,' \"Friends, whoso is pre-eminent among the Danaans, whoso holds a middle place,  or whoso is lesser, for in nowise are all men equal in war, now is there a work for all, and this, I ween, ye know even of yourselves.'),(3922,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 12.272'),(3923,'----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 272 to line 276'),(3924,'So shouted forth the twain, and aroused the battle of the Achaeans.'),(3925,'  And as flakes of snow fall thick on a winter\'s day, when Zeus, the counsellor,  bestirreth him to snow, shewing forth to men these arrows of his '),(3926,'and he lulleth the winds and sheddeth the flakes continually, until he hath covered the peaks of the lofty mountains and the high headlands, and the grassy plains, and the rich tillage of men; aye, and over the harbours and shores of the grey sea is the snow strewn,  albeit the wave as it beateth against it keepeth it off, '),(3927,'but all things beside are wrapped therein, when the storm of Zeus driveth it on:'),(3928,'  even so from both sides their stones flew thick, some upon the Trojans, and some from the Trojans upon the Achaeans, as they cast at one another; '),(3929,'and over all the wall the din arose.'),(3930,'  Yet not even then would the Trojans and glorious Hector have broken the gates of the wall and the long bar, had not Zeus the counsellor roused his own son, Sarpedon, against the Argives, as a lion against sleek kine.  '),(3931,'Forthwith he held before him his shield that was well balanced upon every side,  a fair shield of hammered bronze'),(3932,'This he held before him, and brandished two spears, and so went his way like a mountain-nurtured lion  that hath long lacked meat, and his proud spirit biddeth him go even into the close-built fold to make an attack upon the flocks'),(3933,'For even though he find thereby the herdsmen with dogs and spears keeping watch over the sheep, yet is he not minded to be driven from the steading ere he maketh essay;  but either he leapeth amid the flock and seizeth one, or is himself smitten as a foremost champion by a javelin from a swift hand:'),(3934,' even so did his spirit then urge godlike Sarpedon to rush upon the wall, and break-down the battlements.'),(3935,'Straightway then he spake to Glaucus, son of Hippolochus:'),(3936,'  \"Glaucus, wherefore is it that we twain are held in honour above all with seats, and messes, and full cups in Lycia, and all men gaze upon us as on gods?  Aye, and we possess a great demesne by the banks of Xanthus, a fair tract of orchard and of wheat-bearing plough-land.'),(3937,'  Therefore now it behoveth us to take our stand amid the foremost Lycians, and confront the blazing battle that many a one of the mail-clad Lycians may say:'),(3938,' \"Verily no inglorious men be these that rule in Lycia, even our kings, they that eat fat sheep  and drink choice wine, honey-sweet:  '),(3939,'nay, but their might too is goodly, seeing they fight amid the foremost Lycians.'),(3940,'  Ah friend, if once escaped from this battle we were for ever to be ageless and immortal, neither should I fight myself amid the foremost,  nor should I send thee into battle where men win glory; '),(3941,'but now—for in any case fates of death beset us, fates past counting, which no mortal may escape or avoid—now let us go forward, whether we shall give glory to another, or another to us.\"\" '),(3942,'So spake he, and Glaucus turned not aside,  neither disobeyed him, '),(3943,'but the twain went straight forward, leading the great host of the Lycians.'),(3944,'At sight of them, Menestheus, son of Peteos, shuddered,'),(3945,'for it was to his part of the wall that they came, bearing with them ruin;'),(3946,'and he looked in fear along the wall of the Achaeans, in hope that he might see one of the leaders who would ward off bane from his comrades;'),(3947,' and he marked the Aiantes twain, insatiate in war, standing there, and Teucer that was newly come from his hut, close at hand;'),(3948,'howbeit it was no wise possible for him to shout so as to be heard of them'),(3949,' so great a din was there, and the noise went up to heaven of smitten shields and helms with crests of horse-hair,  and of the gates,'),(3950,'for all had been closed, and before them stood the foe, and sought to break them by force, and enter in.'),(3951,'Forthwith then to Aias he sent the herald Thoötes:\"'),(3952,'Go, goodly Thoötes, run thou, and call Aias, or rather the twain'),(3953,'for that were far best of all,  seeing that here will utter ruin soon be wrought. '),(3954,'Hard upon us here press the leaders of the Lycians, who of old have ever been fierce in mighty conflicts.'),(3955,'But if with them too yonder the toil of war and strife have arisen, yet at least let valiant Aias, son of Telamon, come alone,  and let Teucer, that is well skilled with the bow, follow with him.\"'),(3956,'So spake he, and the herald failed not to hearken as he heard, but set him to run beside the wall of the brazen-coated Achaeans, and he came and stood by the Aiantes, and straightway said:'),(3957,'\"Ye Aiantes twain, leaders of the brazen-coated Achaeans,  the son of Peteos, nurtured of Zeus, biddeth you go thither, that, though it be but for a little space, ye may confront the toil of war—both of you, if so may be, '),(3958,'for that were far best Of all, seeing that yonder will utter ruin soon be wrought.'),(3959,'  Hard upon them there press the leaders of the Lycians, who of old  have ever been fierce in mighty conflicts. '),(3960,'But if here too war and strife have arisen, yet at least let valiant Aias, son of Telamon, go alone, and let Teucer, that is well skilled with the bow, follow with him.\" '),(3961,'So spake he, and great Telamonian Aias failed not to hearken.'),(3962,' Forthwith he spake winged words to the son of Oïleus:'),(3963,'\"Aias, do ye twain, thou and strong Lycomedes, stand fast here and urge on the Danaans to fight amain, '),(3964,'but I will go thither, and confront the war,'),(3965,'and quickly will I come again, when to the full I have borne them aid.'),(3966,'  So saying Telamonian Aias departed, and with him went Teucer, his own brother, begotten of one father,'),(3967,'and with them Pandion bare the curved bow of Teucer.'),(3968,'Now when, as they passed along within the wall, they reached the post of great-souled Menestheus—and to men hard pressed they came—  the foe were mounting upon the battlements like a dark whirlwind, even the mighty leaders and rulers of the Lycians; '),(3969,'and they clashed together in fight, and the battle-cry arose.'),(3970,'and they clashed together in fight, and the battle-cry arose.'),(3971,'Not easily with both hands could a man, such as mortals now are, hold it, were he never so young and strong'),(3972,'but Aias  lifted it on high and hurled it, and he shattered the four-horned helmet, and crushed together  all the bones of the head of Epicles; '),(3973,'and he fell like a diver from the high wall, and his spirit left his bones.'),(3974,'  And Teucer smote Glaucus, the stalwart son of Hippolochus, as he rushed upon them, with an arrow from the high wall, where he saw his arm uncovered; and he stayed him from fighting.'),(3975,'  Back from the wall he leapt secretly, that no man of the Achaeans might mark that he had been smitten, and vaunt over him boastfully.'),(3976,' But over Sarpedon came grief at Glaucus\' departing, so soon as he was ware thereof, yet even so forgat he not to fight, but smote with a thrust of his spear Alcmaon, son of Thestor, with sure aim,  and again drew forth the spear.  '),(3977,'yet even so forgat he not to fight, but smote with a thrust of his spear Alcmaon, son of Thestor, with sure aim,  and again drew forth the spear. '),(3978,'And Alcmaon, following the spear, fell headlong, and about him rang his armour, dight with bronze.  But Sarpedon with strong hands caught hold of the battlement and tugged, and the whole length of it gave way, and the wall above was laid bare, and he made a path for many. '),(3979,' But against him came Aias and Teucer at the one moment: Teucer smote him with an arrow on the gleaming baldric of his sheltering shield about his breast,'),(3980,'but Zeus warded off the fates from his own son that he should not be laid low at the ships\' sterns; '),(3981,'and Aias leapt upon him and thrust against his shield, but the spear-point  passed not through, howbeit he made him reel in his onset.'),(3982,'So he gave ground a little  space from  the  battlement,'),(3983,'yet withdrew not wholly, for his spirit hoped to win him glory.'),(3984,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 12.408'),(3985,'from MILESTONE 405 to MILESTONE 410\n======================================================================\nYe Lycians, wherefore are ye thus slack in furious valour?'),(3986,'  Hard is it for me, how mighty so ever I be, alone to breach the wall, and make a path to the ships.'),(3987,'the more men the better work.\"'),(3988,'the more men the better work.\"'),(3989,'So spake he; and they, seized with fear of the rebuke of their king, pressed on the more around about their counsellor and king, '),(3990,' and the Argives over against them made strong their battalions within the wall; and before them was set a mighty work.'),(3991,'  For neither could the mighty Lycians break the wall of the Danaans, and make a path to the ships, nor ever could the Danaan spearmen thrust back the Lycians  from the walI, when once they had drawn nigh thereto.  '),(3992,'But as two men with measuring-rods in hand strive about the landmark-stones in a common field, and in a narrow space contend each for his equal share; even so did the battlements hold these apart'),(3993,'and over them  they smote the bull\'s-hide bucklers about one another\'s breasts, the round shields and fluttering targets.'),(3994,'And many were wounded in the flesh by thrusts of the pitiless bronze, both whensoever any turned and his back was left bare, as they fought, and many clean through the very shield.'),(3995,'  Yea, everywhere the walls and battlements were spattered with blood of men from both sides, from Trojans and Achaeams alike.'),(3996,' Howbeit even so they could not put the Achaeans to rout, but they held their ground, as a careful woman that laboureth with her hands at spinning, holdeth the balance and raiseth the weight and the wool in either scale, making them equal,  that she may win a meagre wage for her children; '),(3997,'so evenly was strained their war and battle, until Zeus vouchsafed the glory of victory to Hector, son of Priam, that was first to leap within the wall of the Achaeans '),(3998,'he uttered a piercing shout, calling aloud to the Trojans:'),(3999,'  \"Rouse you horse-taming Trojans, break the wall of the Argives, and fling among the ships wondrous-blazing fire.\" '),(4000,'So spake he, urging them on, and they all heard with their ears, and rushed straight upon the wall in one mass, '),(4001,'  And Hector grasped and bore a stone that lay before the gate, thick at the base, but sharp at the point; '),(4002,'not easily might two men, the mightiest of the folk, have upheaved it from the ground upon a wain—men, such as mortals now are—'),(4003,'yet lightly did he wield it even alone; '),(4004,' and the son of crooked-counselling Cronos made it light for him.'),(4005,'And  as when a shepherd easily beareth the fleece of a ram, taking it in one hand, and but little doth the weight thereof burden him; even so Hector lifted up the stone and bare it straight against the doors that guarded the close and strongly fitted gates—'),(4006,'  double gates they were, and high, and two cross bars held them within, and a single bolt fastened them.'),(4007,'  He came and stood hard by, and planting himself smote them full in the midst, setting his feet well apart that his cast might lack no strength; and he brake off both the hinges, '),(4008,'and the stone fell within by its own weight,  and loudly groaned the gates on either side, nor did the bars hold fast, but the doors were dashed apart this way and that beneath the onrush of the stone.'),(4009,'And glorious Hector leapt within, his face like sudden night; '),(4010,'and he shone in terrible bronze wherewith his body was clothed about, and in his hands  he held two spears.'),(4011,'None that met him could have held him back, none save the gods, when once he leapt within the gates;'),(4012,'and his two eyes blazed with fire.'),(4013,' And he wheeled him about in the throng, and called to the Trojans to climb over the wall; '),(4014,'and they hearkened to his urging.'),(4015,'Forthwith some clomb over the wall, and others poured in  by the strong-built gate, '),(4016,'and the Danaans were driven in rout among the hollow ships, and a ceaseless din arose.'),(4017,' Now Zeus, when he had brought the Trojans and Hector to the ships, left the combatants there to have toil and woe unceasingly, but himself turned away his bright eyes, and looked afar, upon the land of the Thracian horsemen,  and of the Mysians that fight in close combat, and of the lordly Hippemolgi that drink the milk of mares, and of the Abii, the most righteous of men.'),(4018,' To Troy he no longer in any wise turned his bright eyes, '),(4019,'for he deemed not in his heart that any of the immortals would draw nigh to aid either Trojans or Danaans.'),(4020,' But the lord, the Shaker of Earth, kept no blind watch, '),(4021,'for he sat marvelling at the war and the battle, high on the topmost peak of wooded Samothrace'),(4022,'for from thence all Ida was plain to see; and plain to see were the city of Priam, and the ships of the Achaeans.'),(4023,'  There he sat, being come forth from the sea, and he had pity on the Achaeans that they were overcome by the Trojans, and against Zeus was he mightily wroth.'),(4024,'Forthwith then he went down from the rugged mount, striding forth with swift footsteps'),(4025,'and the high mountains trembled and the woodland beneath the immortal feet of Poseidon as he went.'),(4026,'  Thrice he strode in his course, and with the fourth stride he reached his goal, even Aegae, where was his famous palace builded in the depths of the mere, golden and gleaming, imperishable for ever. '),(4027,'Thither came he, and let harness beneath his car his two bronze hooved horses, swift of flight, with flowing manes of gold;  and with gold he clad himself about his body, and grasped the well-wrought whip of gold, and stepped upon his car, and set out to drive over the waves.'),(4028,' Then gambolled the sea-beasts beneath him on every side from out the deeps, for well they knew their lord'),(4029,'and in gladness the sea parted before him;'),(4030,' right swiftly sped they on, and the axle of bronze was not wetted beneath; '),(4031,'and unto the ships of the Achaeans did the prancing steeds bear their lord. '),(4032,'There is a wide cavern in the depths of the deep mere, midway between Tenedos and rugged Imbros. '),(4033,'There Poseidon,the Shaker of Earth, stayed his horses,  and loosed them from the car, and cast before them food ambrosial to graze upon'),(4034,'and about their feet he put hobbles of gold, neither to be broken nor loosed, that they might abide fast where they were against the return of their lord; '),(4035,'and himself he went to the host of the Achaeans.'),(4036,'But the Trojans, all in one body, like flame or tempest-blast were following furiously after  Hector, son of Priam, with loud shouts and cries, '),(4037,'and they deemed that they would take the ships of the Achaeans, and slay thereby all the bravest.'),(4038,' Howbeit Poseidon, the Enfolder and Shaker of Earth, set him to urge on the Argives, when he had come forth from the deep sea,  in the likeness of Calchas, both in form and untiring voice. '),(4039,'To the two Aiantes spake he first, that were of themselves full eager:'),(4040,' \"Ye Aiantes twain, ye two shall save the host of the Achaeans, if ye are mindful of your might, and think not of chill rout.'),(4041,' Not otherwhere do I dread the invincible hands  of the Trojans that have climbed over the great wall in their multitude, '),(4042,'for the well-greaved Achaeans will hold back all;'),(4043,'nay it is here that I have wondrous dread lest some evil befall us, here where yon madman is leading on like a flame of fire, even Hector, that boasts him to be a son of mighty Zeus.'),(4044,'  But in the hearts of you twain may some god put it, here to stand firm yourselves, and to bid others do the like; '),(4045,'so might ye drive him back from the swift-faring ships, despite his eagerness, aye, even though the Olympian himself be urging him on.\" '),(4046,'Therewith the Enfolder and Shaker of Earth  smote the twain with his staff, and filled them with valorous strength and made their limbs light, their feet and their hands above.'),(4047,' And himself, even as a hawk, swift of flight, speedeth forth to fly, and poising himself aloft above a high sheer rock, darteth over the plain to chase some other bird;  even so from them sped Poseidon, the Shaker of Earth. '),(4048,'And of the twain swift Aias, son of Oïleus, was first to mark the god, and forthwith spake to Aias, son of Telamon:'),(4049,' \"Aias, seeing it is one of the gods who hold Olympus that in the likeness of the seer biddeth the two of us fight beside the ships—  not Calchas is he, the prophet, and reader of omens, '),(4050,'for easily did I know the tokens behind him of feet and of legs as he went from us; and plain to be known are the gods '),(4051,'and plain to be known are the gods '),(4052,'—lo, mine own heart also within my breast is the more eager to war and do battle,  and my feet beneath and my hands above are full fain.'),(4053,'Then in answer spake to him Telamonian Aias:'),(4054,' \"Even so too mine own hands invincible are fain now to grasp the spear, and my might is roused, and both my feet are swift beneath me; '),(4055,'and I am eager to meet even in single fight  Hector, Priam\'s son, that rageth incessantly.\" '),(4056,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 13.81-13.82'),(4057,'and meanwhile the Enfolder of Earth roused the Achaeans that were in the rear beside the swift ships, and were refreshing their heart'),(4058,' Their limbs were loosed by their grievous toil and therewithal sorrow waxed in their hearts, as they beheld the Trojans that had climbed over the great wall in their multitude.'),(4059,' Aye, as they looked upon these they let tears fall from beneath their brows,'),(4060,' for they deemed not that they should escape from ruin.'),(4061,'But the Shaker of Earth,  lightly passing among them, aroused their strong battalions. '),(4062,'To Teucer first he came and to Leïtus, to bid them on, and to the warrior Peneleos, and Thoas and Deïpyrus, and Meriones and Antilochus, masters of the war-cry;'),(4063,'to these he spake, spurring them on with winged words:  '),(4064,'\"Shame, ye Argives, mere striplings!'),(4065,'It was in your fighting that I trusted for the saving of our ships;'),(4066,'but if ye are to flinch from grievous war, then of a surety hath the day now dawned for us to be vanquished beneath the Trojans. '),(4067,'Out upon it! Verily a great marvel is this that mine eyes behold,  a dread thing that I deemed should never be brought to pass: the Trojans are making way against our ships, they that heretofore were like panic-stricken hinds that in the woodland become the prey of jackals and pards and wolves, as they wander vainly in their cowardice, nor is there any fight in them.'),(4068,'  Even so the Trojans aforetime had never the heart to abide and face the might and the hands of the Achaeans, no not for a moment.'),(4069,' But lo, now far from the city they are fighting at the hollow ships because of the baseness of our leader and the slackness of the folk, that, being at strife with him, have no heart to defend  the swift-faring ships, but are slain in the midst of them. '),(4070,'But if in very truth the warrior son of Atreus, wide-ruling Agamemnon, is the cause of all, for that he wrought dishonour on the swift-footed son of Peleus, yet may we in no wise prove slack in war.'),(4071,'the hearts of good men admit of atonement. '),(4072,'the hearts of good men admit of atonement. '),(4073,'But it is no longer well that ye are slack in furious valour, all ye that are the best men in the host.'),(4074,'Myself I would not quarrel with one that was slack in war, so he were but a sorry wight, '),(4075,'but with you I am exceeding wroth at heart'),(4076,'  Ye weaklings, soon ye shall cause yet greater evil by this slackness.'),(4077,'Nay, take in your hearts, each man of you, shame and indignation; '),(4078,'for in good sooth mighty is the conflict that has arisen.'),(4079,' Hector, good at the war-cry, is fighting at the ships, strong in his might, and hath broken the gates and the long bar.\" '),(4080,'  Thus did the Earth-enfolder arouse the Achaeans with his word of command, '),(4081,'and round about the twain Aiantes their battalions took their stand,so strong in might, that not Ares might have entered in and made light of them, nor yet Athene, the rouser of hosts;'),(4082,'for they that were the chosen bravest abode the onset of the Trojans and goodly Hector,  fencing spear with spear, '),(4083,'buckler pressed on buckler, helm on helm, and man on man;'),(4084,'and the horse-hair crests on the bright helmet-ridges touched each other, as the men moved their heads, in such close array stood they one by another, '),(4085,'and spears in stout hands overlapped each other, as they were brandished,'),(4086,'and their minds swerved not, but they were fain to fight.'),(4087,'Then the Trojans drave forward in close throng and Hector led them, pressing ever forward, like a boulder from a cliff that a river swollen by winter rains thrusteth from the brow of a hill, when it has burst with its wondrous flood the foundations of the ruthless stone;'),(4088,'the springing boulder flies on, and the forest thunders beneath it;'),(4089,'and the stone runs unwavering on a strong course, till it reaches the flat land, then rolls no longer for all its onrush;'),(4090,'so Hektor for a while threatened lightly to break through the shelters and ships of the Achaians and reach the water cutting his way'),(4091,'But when he collided with the dense battalions he was stopped, hard, beaten in on himself'),(4092,' And the sons of the Achaeans faced him, thrusting with swords and two-edged spears, and drave him back from them, '),(4093,'so that he gave ground and was made to reel.'),(4094,'Then he uttered a piercing shout, calling aloud to the Trojans:'),(4095,'  \"Ye Trojans and Lycians and Dardanians that fight in close combat, stand ye fast.'),(4096,' No long space shall the Achaeans hold me back, for all they have arrayed themselves in fashion like a wall; nay, methinks, they will give ground before my spear, if verily the highest of gods hath urged me on, the loud-thundering lord of Hera.\" '),(4097,'  So saying, he aroused the strength and spirit of every man. '),(4098,'Then among them with high heart strode Deïphobus, son of Priam, and before him he held his shield that was well-balanced upon every side, stepping forward lightly on his feet and advancing under cover of his shield. '),(4099,'And Meriones aimed at him with his bright spear,  and cast, and missed not, but smote the shield of bull\'s hide, that was well balanced upon every side'),(4100,'yet drave not in any wise therethrough; nay, well ere that might be, the long spear-shaft was broken in the socket; '),(4101,'and Deïphobus held from him the shield of bull\'s hide, and his heart was seized with fear  of the spear of wise-hearted Meriones;'),(4102,'but that warrior shrank back into the throng of his comrades, and waxed wondrous wroth both for the loss of victory and for the spear which he had shattered.'),(4103,'And he set out to go along the huts and ships of the Achaeans to fetch him a long spear that he had left in his hut.'),(4104,'But the rest fought on, and a cry unquenchable arose.'),(4105,'  And Teucer, son of Telamon, was first to slay his man, even the spearman Imbrius, the son of Mentor, rich in horses.'),(4106,' He dwelt in Pedaeum before the sons of the Achaeans came, and had to wife a daughter of Priam that was born out of wedlock, even Medesicaste; '),(4107,'but when the curved ships of the Danaans came  he returned back to Ilios and was pre-eminent among the Trojans, and he dwelt in the house of Priam'),(4108,'who held him in like honour with his own children.'),(4109,' Him did the son of Telamon smite beneath the ear with a thrust of his long spear, and again drew forth the spear; '),(4110,'and he fell like an ash-tree that, on the summit of a mountain that is seen from afar on every side,  is cut down by the bronze, and bringeth its tender leafage to the ground; '),(4111,'even so fell he, and about him rang his armour dight with bronze.'),(4112,' And Teucer rushed forth eager to strip from him his armour, '),(4113,'but Hector, even as he rushed, cast at him with his bright spear.'),(4114,' Howbeit Teucer, looking steadily at him, avoided the spear of bronze by a little, '),(4115,' but Hector smote Amphimachus, son of Cteatus, the son of Actor, in the breast with his spear as he was coming into the battle; '),(4116,'and he fell with a thud, and upon him his armour clanged.'),(4117,' Then Hector rushed forth to tear from the head of great-hearted Amphimachus the helm that was fitted to his temples, '),(4118,' but Aias lunged with his bright spear at Hector as he rushed,'),(4119,'yet in no wise reached he his flesh, for he was all clad in dread bronze;'),(4120,'but he smote the boss of his shield, and thrust him back with mighty strength,'),(4121,'so that he gave ground backward from the two corpses, and the Achaeans drew them off.  '),(4122,' Amphimachus then did Stichius and goodly Menestheus, leaders of the Athenians, carry to the host of the Achaeans'),(4123,'and Imbrius the twain Aiantes bare away, their hearts fierce with furious valour. And as when two lions that have snatched away a goat from sharp-toothed hounds, bear it through the thick brush,  holding it in their jaws high above the ground, even so the twain warrior Aiantes held Imbrius on high, and stripped him of his armour.'),(4124,'And the head did the son of Oïleus cut from the tender neck, being wroth for the slaying of Amphimachus, and with a swing he sent it rolling through the throng like a ball; '),(4125,' and it fell in the dust before the feet of Hector.'),(4126,'Then verily Poseidon waxed mightily wroth at heart when his son\'s son fell in the dread conflict, and he went his way along the huts and ships of the Achaeans to arouse the Danaans; but for the Trojans was he fashioning woes.'),(4127,'  And there met him Idomeneus, famed for his spear, on his way from a comrade that he had but now found coming from the battle smitten in the knee with the sharp bronze.'),(4128,' Him his comrades bare forth, but Idomeneus had given charge to the leeches, and was going to his hut, '),(4129,'for he was still fain to confront the battle; '),(4130,' and the lord, the Shaker of Earth, spake to him, likening his voice to that of Andraemon\'s son Thoas, that in all Pleuron and steep Calydon was lord over the Aetolians, and was honoured of the folk even as a god:'),(4131,'Idomeneus, thou counsellor of the Cretans, where now I pray thee,  are the threats gone, wherewith the sons of the Achaeans threatened the Trojans?\"'),(4132,'And to him Idomeneus, leader of the Cretans, made answer:'),(4133,'O Thoas, there is no man now at fault, so far as I wot thereof; '),(4134,'for we are all skilled in war.'),(4135,' Neither is any man holden of craven error,  nor doth any through dread withdraw him from evil war, '),(4136,'but even thus, I ween, must it be the good pleasure of the son of Cronos, supreme in might, that the Achaeans should perish here far from Argos, and have no name.'),(4137,'But, Thoas, seeing that aforetime thou wast ever staunch in fight, and dost also urge on another'),(4138,'wheresoever thou seest one shrinking from fight, '),(4139,'And Poseidon, the Shaker of Earth, answered him:'),(4140,' \"Idomeneus, never may that man any more return home from Troy-land, but here may he become the sport of dogs, whoso in this day\'s course of his own will shrinketh from fight.'),(4141,' Up then, take thine harness and get thee forth:'),(4142,'herein beseems it that we play the man together, in hope there may be help in us, though we be but two.'),(4143,' Prowess comes from fellowship even of right sorry folk, but we twain know well how to do battle even with men of valour.\"'),(4144,'So spake he, and went back again, a god into the toil of men; '),(4145,' and Idomeneus, as soon as he was come to his well-built hut, did on his fair armour about his body, and grasped two spears, and went his way like the lightning that the son of Cronos seizeth in his hand and brandisheth from gleaming Olympus, showing forth a sign to mortals'),(4146,'and brightly flash the rays thereof; '),(4147,' even so shone the bronze about his breast as he ran.'),(4148,'And Meriones, his valiant squire, met him, while yet he was near the hut; '),(4149,'for he was on his way to fetch him a spear of bronze; '),(4150,'and mighty Idomeneus spake to him:'),(4151,' \"Meriones, Molus\' son, swift of foot, thou dearest of my comrades,  wherefore art thou come, leaving the war and battle?'),(4152,'Art thou haply wounded, and doth the point of a dart distress thee?  Have you come back with someone\'s message for me?'),(4153,'Nay, of mine own self am I fain, not to abide in the huts, but to fight.'),(4154,'To him again the wise Meriones made answer:'),(4155,'  \"Idomeneus, counsellor of the brazen-coated Cretans, I am on my way to fetch a spear, if perchance thou hast one left in the huts; '),(4156,'for the one that I bare of old have I shattered, as I cast at the shield of the overweening Deïphobus.'),(4157,'And to him Idomeneus, leader of the Cretans, made answer:'),(4158,'  \"Spears, if thou wilt, thou shalt find, be it one or twenty, standing in the hut against the bright entrance wall, spears of the Trojans whereof it is my wont to despoil their slain.'),(4159,'For I am not minded to fight with the foemen while standing afar off;'),(4160,'wherefore I have spears and bossed shields,and helms and corselets are there in all the pride of their shining.'),(4161,'Then to him the wise Meriones made answer:'),(4162,' \"Aye, in mine own hut also and my black ship are many spoils of the Trojans'),(4163,'but I have them not at hand to take thereof.'),(4164,'For I deem that I too am not forgetful of valour,  but I take my stand amid the foremost in battle, where men win glory, whenso the strife of war ariseth.'),(4165,'Some other of the brazen-coated Achaeans might sooner be unaware of my fighting, but thou methinks of thine own self knowest it well.\"'),(4166,'And to him Idomeneus, leader of the Cretans, made answer:'),(4167,'what need hast thou to tell the tale thereof?'),(4168,'what need hast thou to tell the tale thereof?'),(4169,'For if now all the best of us were being told off besides the ships for an ambush, wherein the valour of men is best discerned—there the coward cometh to light and the man of valour; '),(4170,'the skin of the coward changes colour one way and another, and the heart inside him has no control to make him sit steady,'),(4171,'but the brave man\'s skin will not change colour, nor is he too much frightened, once he has taken his place in the hidden position, but his prayer is to close as soon as may be in bitter division:'),(4172,'and there no man could make light of your battle strength or your hand\'s work.'),(4173,'For if so be thou wert stricken by a dart in the toil of battle, or smitten with a thrust, not from behind in neck or back would the missile fall;  nay, but on thy breast would it light or on thy belly, as thou wert pressing on into the dalliance of the foremost fighters.'),(4174,' But come, no longer let us loiter here and talk thus like children, lest haply some man wax wroth beyond measure; '),(4175,'nay, but go thou to the hut, and get thee a mighty spear.\" '),(4176,'  So spake he, and Meriones, the peer of swift Ares, speedily took from the hut a spear of bronze, and followed Idomeneus with high thought of battle.'),(4177,' And even as Ares, the bane of mortals, goeth forth to war, and with him followeth Rout, his son, valiant alike and fearless,  that turneth to flight a warrior, were he never so staunch of heart— '),(4178,'these twain arm themselves and go forth from Thrace to join the Ephyri or the great-hearted Phlegyes'),(4179,' yet they hearken not to both sides, but give glory to one or the other'),(4180,'even in such wise did Meriones and Idomeneus, leaders of men,  go forth into the fight, harnessed in flaming bronze.'),(4181,'And Meriones spake first to Idomeneus, saying:'),(4182,'Son of Deucalion, at what point art thou eager to enter the throng?'),(4183,' On the right of all the host, or in the centre, or shall it be on the left?'),(4184,' For verily, methinks, in no other place  do the long-haired Achaeans so fail in the fight.\"'),(4185,'And to him again Idomeneus, leader of the Cretans, made answer:'),(4186,'Among the midmost ships there be others for defence, the two Aiantes, and Teucer, best of all the Achaeans in bowmanship,  and a good man too in close fight; '),(4187,'these shall drive Hector, Priam\'s son, to surfeit of war, despite his eagerness, be he never so stalwart.'),(4188,' Hard shall it be for him, how furious soever for war, to overcome their might and their invincible hands, and to fire the ships, unless the son of Cronos should himself  cast a blazing brand upon the swift ships. '),(4189,'But to no man would great Telamonian Aias yield, to any man that is mortal, and eateth the grain of Demeter, and may be cloven with the bronze or crushed with great stones.'),(4190,' Nay, not even to Achilles, breaker of the ranks of men,  would he give way, in close fight at least; '),(4191,'but in fleetness of foot may no man vie with Achilles.'),(4192,'But for us twain, do thou, even as thou sayest,make for the left of the host, that we may know forthwith whether we shall give glory to another or another to us.\" '),(4193,'So spake he, and Meriones, the peer of swift Ares, led the way until they came to the host, at the point whither Idomeneus bade him go.\n Now when the Trojans had sight of Idomeneus, in might as it were a flame, himself and his squire clad in armour richly dight, they called one to another through the throng, and all made at him; '),(4194,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 13.333'),(4195,'from MILESTONE 330 to MILESTONE 340\n======================================================================\nAnd as gusts come thick and fast when shrill winds are blowing,  on a day when dust lies thickest on the roads, and the winds raise up confusedly a great cloud of dust; even so their battle clashed together, and they were eager in the throng to slay one another with the sharp bronze.'),(4196,' And the battle, that brings death to mortals, bristled with long spears  which they held for the rending of flesh, '),(4197,'and eyes were blinded by the blaze of bronze from gleaming helmets, and corselets newly burnished, and shining shields, as men came on confusedly.'),(4198,' Sturdy in sooth would he have been of heart that took joy at sight of such toil of war, and grieved not.'),(4199,'  Thus were the two mighty sons of Cronos, divided in purpose, fashioning grievous woes for mortal warriors.'),(4200,'Zeus would have victory for the Trojans and Hector, so giving glory to Achilles, swift of foot; '),(4201,'yet was he in no wise minded that the Achaean host should perish utterly before the face of Ilios,  but was fain only to give glory to Thetis and to her son, strong of heart.'),(4202,'But Poseidon went among the Argives and urged them on, stealing forth secretly from the grey sea;'),(4203,'for it vexed him that they were being overcome by the Trojans, and against Zeus was he exceeding wroth.'),(4204,' Both the twain verily were of one stock and of one parentage,  but Zeus was the elder born and the wiser. '),(4205,'Therefore it was that Poseidon avoided to give open aid, but secretly sought ever to rouse the Argives throughout the host, in the likeness of a man.'),(4206,' So these twain knotted the ends of the cords of mighty strife and evil war, and drew them taut over both armies, '),(4207,'Then Idomeneus, albeit his hair was flecked with grey, called to the Danaans, and leaping amid the Trojans turned them to flight.'),(4208,'For he slew Othryoneus of Cabesus, a sojourner in Troy, that was but newly come following the rumour of war;  and he asked in marriage the comeliest of the daughters of Priam, even Cassandra; he brought no gifts of wooing, but promised a mighty deed, that he would drive forth perforce out of Troy-land the sons of Achaeans.'),(4209,'To him the old man Priam promised that he would give her, and bowed his head thereto,'),(4210,'and Othryoneus fought, trusting in his promise.  But Idomeneus aimed at him with his bright spear, and cast and smote him as he strode proudly on, nor did the corselet of bronze that he wore avail him, '),(4211,' But Idomeneus aimed at him with his bright spear, and cast and smote him as he strode proudly on,'),(4212,'nor did the corselet of bronze that he wore avail him, but the spear was fixed full in his belly,'),(4213,'and Idomeneus exulted over him and spake, saying:'),(4214,'and Idomeneus exulted over him and spake, saying:'),(4215,'\"Othryoneus, verily above all mortal men do I count thee happy,  if in good sooth thou shalt accomplish all that thou didst promise to Dardanian Priam;'),(4216,'and he promised thee his own daughter.'),(4217,' Aye, and we too would promise the like and would bring all to pass, and would give thee the comeliest of the daughters of the son of Atreus, bringing her forth from Argos that thou mightest wed her;  if only thou wilt make cause with us and sack the well-peopled city of Ilios.'),(4218,'Nay, follow with us, that at the seafaring ships we may make agreement about the marriage, for thou mayest be sure we deal not hardly in exacting gifts of wooing.\"'),(4219,'So saying, the warrior Idomeneus dragged him by the foot through the mighty conflict.'),(4220,'But Asius came to bear aid to Othryoneus,  on foot in front of his horses; '),(4221,'and these twain the squire that was his charioteer ever drave so that their breath smote upon the shoulders of Asius.'),(4222,'And he was ever fain of heart to cast at Idomeneus;'),(4223,'but the other was too quick for him, and smote him with a cast of his spear on the throat beneath the chin, and drave the bronze clean through. '),(4224,'And he fell as an oak falls, or a poplar,  or a tall pine that among the mountains shipwrights fell with whetted axes to be a ship\'s timber;'),(4225,'even so before his horses and chariot Asius lay out-stretched, moaning aloud and clutching at the bloody dust.'),(4226,'And the charioteer, stricken with terror, kept not the wits that afore he had,  neither dared turn the horses back and so escape from out the hands of the foemen; but Antilochus, staunch in fight, aimed at him, and pierced him through the middle with his spear'),(4227,'nor did the corselet of bronze that he wore avail him, but he fixed the spear full in his belly. '),(4228,'And gasping he fell from out his well-built car,  and the horses Antilochus, son of great-souled Nestor, drave forth from the Trojans into the host of the well-greaved Achaeans. '),(4229,'Then Deïphobus in sore grief for Asius drew very nigh to Idomeneus, and cast at him with his bright spear.'),(4230,' Howbeit Idomeneus, looking steadily at him, avoided the spear of bronze, '),(4231,' for he hid beneath the cover of his shield that was well-balanced upon every side, the which he was wont to bear, cunningly wrought with bull\'s hide and gleaming bronze, and fitted with two rods; '),(4232,'beneath this he gathered himself together, and the spear of bronze flew over; and harshly rang his shield, as the spear grazed thereon.'),(4233,'  Yet nowise in vain did Deïphobus let the spear fly from his heavy hand, but he smote Hypsenor, son of Hippasus, shepherd of the people, in the liver beneath the midriff, and straightway loosed his knees.'),(4234,'And Deïphobus exulted over him in terrible wise, and cried aloud:'),(4235,'\"Hah, in good sooth not unavenged lies Asius; nay, methinks,  even as he fareth to the house of Hades, the strong warder, will he be glad at heart, for lo, I have given him one to escort him on his way!\"'),(4236,'So spake he, and upon the Argives came sorrow by reason of his exulting, and beyond all did he stir the soul of wise-hearted Antilochus;. '),(4237,'howbeit, despite his sorrow, he was not unmindful of his dear comrade,  but ran and bestrode him, and covered him with his shield'),(4238,'Then two trusty comrades stooped down, even Mecisteus, son of Echius, and goodly Alastor, and bare Hypsenor, groaning heavily, to the hollow ships. '),(4239,'And Idomeneus slackened not in his furious might, but was ever fain  to enwrap some one of the Trojans in the darkness of night, or himself to fall in warding off ruin from the Achaeans. '),(4240,'Then the dear son of Aesyetes, fostered of Zeus, the warrior Alcathous—son by marriage was he to Anchises, and had married the eldest of his daughters, Hippodameia,  whom her father and queenly mother heartily loved in their hall, '),(4241,'for that she excelled all maidens of her years in comeliness, and in handiwork, and in wisdom;'),(4242,'wherefore the best man in wide Troy had taken her to wife'),(4243,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 13.434-13.435'),(4244,'——this Alcathous did Poseidon subdue beneath Idomeneus,  for he cast a spell upon his bright eyes and ensnared his glorious limbs\nτὸν τόθ̓ ὑπ̓ Ἰδομενῆϊ Ποσειδάων ἐδάμασσε θέλξας ὄσσε φαεινά, πέδησε δὲ φαίδιμα γυῖα·[434,435]\n########################################################################\n\n======================================================================\nfrom MILESTONE 424 to MILESTONE 445\n======================================================================\nthat he might nowise flee backwards nor avoid the spear; but as he stood fixed, even as a pillar or a tree, high and leafy, the warrior Idomeneus smote him with a thrust of his spear full upon the breast,  and clave his coat of bronze round about him, that aforetime ever warded death from his body, '),(4245,'but now it rang harshly as it was cloven about the spear.'),(4246,' And he fell with a thud, and the spear was fixed in his heart, that still beating made the butt thereof to quiver; '),(4247,'howbeit, there at length did mighty Ares stay its fury.'),(4248,'  But Idomeneus exulted over him in terrible wise, and cried aloud:\"Deïphobus, shall we now deem perchance that due requital hath been made—three men slain for one—'),(4249,'seeing thou boasteth thus?'),(4250,' For Zeus at the first begat Minos to be a watcher over Crete'),(4251,' For Zeus at the first begat Minos to be a watcher over Crete'),(4252,'and now have the ships brought me hither a bane to thee and thy father and the other Trojans.\" '),(4253,'  So spake he, and Deïphobus was divided in counsel, whether he should give ground and take to him as comrade some one of the great-souled Trojans, or should make trial by himself alone.'),(4254,' And as he pondered this thing seemed to him the better—to go after Aeneas;'),(4255,'and he found him standing last amid the throng, '),(4256,' for ever was Aeneas wroth against goodly Priam, for that brave though he was amid warriors Priam honoured him not a whit.'),(4257,' Then Deïphobus drew near and spake to him winged words:\"'),(4258,'Aeneas, counsellor of the Trojans, now in sooth it behoveth thee to bear aid to thy sister\'s husband, if in any wise grief for thy kin cometh upon thee.'),(4259,'  Nay, come thou with me, that we may bear aid to Alcathous, who, for all he was but thy sister\'s husband, reared thee in the halls when thou wast yet a little child; '),(4260,'he, I tell thee, hath been slain of Idomeneus, famed for his spear.'),(4261,'So spake he, and roused the heart in the breast of Aeneas, and he went to seek Idomeneus, with high thoughts of war.'),(4262,'  Howbeit terror gat not hold of Idomeneus, as he had been some petted boy, but he abode like a boar in the mountains, that trusteth in his strength, and abideth the great, tumultuous throng of men that cometh against him, in a lonely place; '),(4263,'he bristleth up his back and his two eyes blaze with fire,'),(4264,' and he whetteth his tusks, eager to ward off dogs and men;'),(4265,'even so Idomeneus, famed for his spear, abode the oncoming of Aeneas to bear aid,'),(4266,'and gave not ground, but called to his comrades, looking unto Ascalaphus, Aphareus, and Deïpyrus, and Meriones, and Antilochus, masters of the war-cry;'),(4267,' to these he spake winged words, and spurred them on:'),(4268,'Hither, friends, and bear aid to me that am alone'),(4269,'and sorely do I dread the oncoming of Aeneas, swift of foot, that cometh against me; right strong is he to slay men in battle, and he hath the flower of youth, wherein is the fulness of strength.'),(4270,'and he hath the flower of youth, wherein is the fulness of strength.'),(4271,'  Were we but of like age and our mood such as now it is, then forthwith should he win great victory, or haply I.\" '),(4272,'So spake he, and they all, having one spirit in their breasts, took their stand, each hard by the other, leaning their shields against their shoulders. '),(4273,'And Aeneas over against them called to his comrades,  looking unto Deïphobus, and Paris, and goodly Agenor, that with himself were leaders of the Trojans;'),(4274,'and after them followed the host, as sheep follow after the ram to water from the place of feeding'),(4275,'and the shepherd joyeth in his heart; '),(4276,'even so the heart of Aeneas was glad in his breast,  when he saw the throng of the host that followed after him.'),(4277,'Then over Alcathous they clashed in close fight with their long spears,'),(4278,'and about their breasts the bronze rang terribly as they aimed each at the other in the throng; '),(4279,'and above all the rest two men of valour,  Aeneas and Idomeneus, peers of Ares, were eager each to cleave the other\'s flesh with the pitiless bronze.'),(4280,' And Aeneas first cast at Idomeneus'),(4281,'but he, looking steadily at him, avoided the spear of bronze, and the lance of Aeneas sank quivering down in to the earth,  for that it sped in vain from his mighty hand.'),(4282,'But Idomeneus cast and smote Oenomaus, full upon the belly, and brake the plate of his corselet, and the bronze let forth the bowels therethrough;'),(4283,'and he fell clawing the dust in his fingers.'),(4284,'And Idomeneus drew forth from out the corpse the far-shadowing spear,  yet could he not prevail likewise to strip the rest of the fair armour from his shoulders'),(4285,'since he was sore pressed with missiles.'),(4286,'For the joints of his feet were not firm as of old in a charge, that he might rush forth after his own cast, '),(4287,'or avoid another\'s.'),(4288,'Wherefore in close fight he warded off the pitiless day of doom,  but in flight his feet no longer bare him swiftly from the war. '),(4289,'And as he drew back step by step Deïphobus cast at him with his shining spear,'),(4290,'for verily he ever cherished a ceaseless hate against him.'),(4291,' Howbeit this time again he missed him, and smote with his spear Ascalaphus, son of Enyalius, '),(4292,'and through the shoulder the mighty spear held its way;'),(4293,' and he fell in the dust and clutched the ground with his palm.'),(4294,'But as yet loud-voiced dread Ares wist not at all that his son had fallen in the mighty conflict; but he sat on the topmost peak of Olympus beneath the golden clouds, constrained by the will of Zeus, '),(4295,'Then over Ascalaphus they clashed in close fight, '),(4296,'and Deïphobus tore from Ascalaphus his shining helm, but Meriones, the peer of swift Ares, leapt upon Deïphobus and smote his arm with his spear,  and from his hand the crested helm fell to the ground with a clang.'),(4297,'And Meriones sprang forth again like a vulture, and drew forth the mighty spear from the upper arm of Deïphobus, and shrank back in the throng of his comrades'),(4298,'But Polites, the own brother of Deïphobus, stretched his arms around his waist,  and led him forth from out the dolorous war, until he came to the swift horses that stood waiting for him at the rear of the battle and the conflict with their charioteer and chariot richly dight.'),(4299,'These bare him to the city groaning heavily and sore distressed '),(4300,'and down ran the blood from his newly wounded arm.'),(4301,' But the rest fought on, and a cry unquenchable arose. '),(4302,'Then Aeneas leapt upon Aphareus, son of Caletor, that was turned toward him, and struck him on the throat with his sharp spear, '),(4303,'and his head sank to one side, and his shield was hurled upon him and his helm withal, and death that slayeth the spirit encompassed him.'),(4304,'  Then Antilochus, biding his time, leapt upon Thoön, as he turned his back, and smote him with a thrust, and wholly severed the vein that runneth along the back continually until it reacheth the neck; '),(4305,'this he severed wholly. '),(4306,'and Thoön fell on his back in the dust, stretching out both his hands to his dear comrades.'),(4307,'  But Antilochus leapt upon him and set him to strip the armour from off his shoulders, looking warily around the while; '),(4308,'for the Trojans encircled him and thrust from this side and from that upon his broad, shining shield; howbeit they prevailed not to pierce through and graze the tender flesh of Antilochus with the pitiless bronze;'),(4309,'for mightily did Poseidon, the Shaker of Earth,  guard Nestor\'s son, even in the midst of many darts.'),(4310,' For never aloof from the foe was Antilochus, but he ranged among them, '),(4311,'nor ever was his spear at rest, but was ceaselessly brandished and shaken; '),(4312,'and he ever aimed in heart to cast at some foeman, or rush upon him in close fight. '),(4313,'  But as he was aiming amid the throng he was not unmarked of Adamas, son of Asius, who smote him full upon the shield with a thrust of the sharp bronze, setting upon him from nigh at hand.'),(4314,' But the spear-point was made of none avail by Poseidon, the dark-haired god,  who begrudged it the life of Antilochus. '),(4315,'And the one part of the spear abode here, like a charred stake, in the shield of Antilochus, and half lay on the ground;'),(4316,'and Adamas shrank back into the throng of his comrades, avoiding fate.'),(4317,'But Meriones followed after him as he went and cast with his spear, and smote him midway between the privy parts and the navel, where most of all Ares is cruel to wretched mortals.'),(4318,'  Even there he fixed his spear,'),(4319,'and the other, leaning over the shaft which pierced him, writhed as a bull that herdsmen amid the mountains have bound with twisted withes and drag with them perforce; '),(4320,'even so he, when he was smitten, writhed a little while, but not long, till the warrior Meriones came near and drew the spear forth from out his flesh;'),(4321,' and darkness enfolded his eyes.'),(4322,'Then in close fight Helenus smote Deïpyrus on the temple with a great Thracian sword, and tore away his helm,'),(4323,'and the helm, dashed from his head, fell to the ground, and one of the Achaeans gathered it up as it rolled amid the feet of the fighters; '),(4324,' and down upon the eyes of Deïpyrus came the darkness of night, and enfolded him.'),(4325,'But the son of Atreus was seized with grief thereat, even Menelaus, good at the war-cry, '),(4326,'and he strode forth with a threat against the prince, the warrior Helenus, brandishing his sharp spear, '),(4327,'while the other drew the centre-piece of his bow.'),(4328,'So the twain at the one moment let fly,  the one with his sharp spear, and the other with an arrow from the string.'),(4329,'Then the son of Priam smote Menelaus on the breast with his arrow, on the plate of his corselet, and off therefrom glanced the bitter arrow. '),(4330,'And as from a broad shovel in a great threshing-floor the dark-skinned beans or pulse  leap before the shrill wind and the might of the winnower; even so from the corselet of glorious Menelaus glanced aside the bitter arrow and sped afar.'),(4331,' But the son of Atreus, Menelaus, good at the war-cry, cast, and smote Helenus on the hand wherewith he was holding the polished bow, '),(4332,'and into the bow  clean through the hand was driven the spear of bronze.'),(4333,'Then back he shrank into the throng of his comrades, avoiding fate, letting his hand hang down by his side;'),(4334,'and the ashen spear trailed after him.'),(4335,' This then great-souled Agenor drew forth from his hand, and bound the hand with a strip of twisted sheep\'s wool, '),(4336,'But Peisander made straight at glorious Menelaus; '),(4337,'howbeit an evil fate was leading him to the end of death, to be slain by thee, Menelaus, in the dread conflict. '),(4338,'And when they were come near, as they advanced one against the other,  the son of Atreus missed, and his spear was turned aside; but Peisander thrust and smote the shield of glorious Menelaus, yet availed not to drive the bronze clean through, '),(4339,'For the wide shield stayed it and the spear brake in the socket;'),(4340,'yet had he joy at heart, and hope for victory.'),(4341,'  But the son of Atreus drew his silver-studded sword, and leapt upon Peisander; '),(4342,'and he from beneath his shield grasped a goodly axe of fine bronze, set on a haft of olive-wood, long and well-polished; '),(4343,'and at the one moment they set each upon the other.'),(4344,' Peisander verily smote Menelaus upon the horn of his helmet with crest of horse-hair  —on the topmost part beneath the very plume; but Menelaus smote him as he came against him, on the forehead above the base of the nose'),(4345,'and the bones crashed loudly, and the two eyeballs, all bloody, fell before his feet in the dust, and he bowed and fell; '),(4346,'and Menelaus set his foot upon his breast, and despoiled him of his arms, and exulted, saying:'),(4347,'  \"ln such wise of a surety shall ye leave the ships of the Danaans, drivers of swift horses, ye overweening Trojans, insatiate of the dread din of battle. Aye, and of other despite and shame lack ye naught, wherewith ye have done despite unto me, ye evil dogs, and had no fear at heart of the grievous wrath of Zeus, that thundereth aloud, the god of hospitality,  who shall some day destroy your high city.'),(4348,'For ye bare forth wantonly over sea my wedded wife and therewithal much treasure, when it was with her that ye had found entertainment; '),(4349,'and now again ye are full fain to fling consuming fire on the sea-faring ships, and to slay the Achaean warriors.'),(4350,' Nay, but ye shall be stayed from your fighting, how eager soever ye be!'),(4351,'Father Zeus, in sooth men say that in wisdom thou art above all others, both men and gods, '),(4352,'yet it is from thee that all these things come;'),(4353,'in such wise now dost thou shew favour to men of wantonness, even the Trojans, whose might is always froward,  nor can they ever have their fill of the din of evil war.'),(4354,'Of all things is there satiety, of sleep, and love, and of sweet song, and the goodly dance; of \nthese things verily a man would rather have his fill than of war;'),(4355,'but the Trojans are insatiate of battle.\" '),(4356,'  With this peerless Menelaus stripped from the body the bloody armour and gave it to his comrades, and himself went back again, and mingled with the foremost fighters.'),(4357,'Then there leapt forth against him the son of king Pylaemenes, even Harpalion, that followed his dear father to Troy unto the war,  but came not back again to his dear native land.'),(4358,'He then thrust with his spear full upon the shield of the son of Atreus, from nigh at hand, yet availed not to drive the bronze clean through, and back he shrank into the throng of his comrades, avoiding fate, glancing warily on every side, lest some man should wound his flesh with the bronze.'),(4359,'  But as he drew back, Meriones let fly at him a bronze-tipped arrow, and smote him on the right buttock, '),(4360,'and the arrow passed clean through even to the bladder beneath the bone.'),(4361,' And sitting down where he was in the arms of his dear comrades he breathed forth his life, and lay stretched out like a worm on the earth; '),(4362,' and the black blood flowed forth and wetted the ground.'),(4363,'Him the great-hearted Paphlagonians tended, and setting him in a chariot they bare him to sacred Ilios, '),(4364,'sorrowing the while, and with them went his father, shedding tears;'),(4365,'but there was no blood-price gotten for his dead son.'),(4366,'  And for his slaying waxed Paris mightily wroth at heart, for among the many Paphlagonians Harpalion had been his host; '),(4367,'and in wrath for his sake he let fly a bronze-tipped arrow.'),(4368,' A certain Euchenor there was, son of Polyidus the seer, a rich man and a valiant, and his abode was in Corinth.  He embarked upon his ship knowing full well the deadly fate to be,'),(4369,'for often had his old sire, good Polyidus, told it him, to wit, that he must either perish of dire disease in his own halls, or amid the ships of the Achaeans be slain by the Trojans;'),(4370,'wherefore he avoided at the same time the heavy fine of the Achaeans  and the hateful disease, that he might not suffer woes at heart.'),(4371,'and ear '),(4372,'and ear '),(4373,'and forthwith his spirit departed from his limbs, and hateful darkness gat hold of him. '),(4374,'So fought they like unto blazing fire;'),(4375,'but Hector, dear to Zeus, had not heard, nor wist at all  that on the left of the ships his hosts were being slain by the Argives; '),(4376,'and soon would the Achaeans have gotten them glory,'),(4377,'of such might was the Enfolder and Shaker of Earth that urged on the Argives and withal aided them by his own strength.'),(4378,'Nay, Hector pressed on where at the first he had leapt within the gate and the wall,  and had burst the close ranks of the Danaan shield-men, even in the place where were the ships of Aias and Protesilaus, drawn up along the beach of the grey sea,'),(4379,'and beyond them the wall was builded lowest; there, as in no place beside, the men and their horses waxed furious in fight.'),(4380,'  There the Boeotians and the Ionians, of trailing tunics, and the Locrians, and Phthians, and glorious Epeians, had much ado to stay his onset upon the ships, and availed not to thrust back from themselves goodly Hector, that was like a flame of fire,—even they that were picked men of the Athenians;'),(4381,' and among them Menestheus, son of Peteos, was leader, and there followed with him Pheidas and Stichius and valiant Bias, '),(4382,'while the Epeians were led by Meges, son of Phyleus, and Araphion and Dracius, and in the forefront of the Phthians were Medon and Podarces, staunch in fight.'),(4383,' The one, verily, even Medon, was a bastard son of godlike Oïleus  and brother of Aias, '),(4384,'but he dwelt in Phylace, far from his native land, for that he had slain a man of the kin of his stepmother Eriopis, that Oïleus had to wife;'),(4385,'and the other, Podarces, was the son of Iphiclus, son of Phylacus.'),(4386,' These, harnessed in their armour, in the forefront of the great-souled Phthians,  were fighting in defence of the ships together with the Boeotians. '),(4387,'And Aias, the swift son of Oïleus, would no more in any wise depart from the side of Aias, son of Telamon, no not for an instant; but even as in fallow land two wine-dark oxen with one accord strain at the jointed plough,'),(4388,'and about  the roots of their horns oozeth up the sweat in streams'),(4389,'the twain the polished yoke alone holdeth apart as they labour through the furrow, '),(4390,'till the plough cutteth to the limit or the field;'),(4391,' even in such wise did the two Aiantes take their stand and abide each hard by the other\'s side.'),(4392,'After the son of Telamon verily there followed many valiant hosts of his comrades,  who would ever take from him his shield, whenso weariness and sweat came upon his limbs.'),(4393,'But the Locrians followed not with the great-hearted son of Oïleus, '),(4394,'for their hearts abode not steadfast in close fight,'),(4395,'seeing they had no brazen helms with thick plumes of horse-hair,  neither round shields, nor spears of ash, but trusting in bows and well-twisted slings of sheep\'s wool had they followed with him to Ilios; with these thereafter they shot thick and fast, and sought to break the battalions of the Trojans'),(4396,'So the one part in front with their war-gear, richly dight,  fought with the Trojans and with Hector in his harness of bronze, and the others behind kept shooting from their cover; '),(4397,'and the Trojans bethought them no more of fight, '),(4398,'for the arrows confounded them. '),(4399,'Then in sorry wise would the Trojans have given ground from the ships and huts unto windy Ilios,  had not Polydamas drawn nigh to bold Hector, and said:'),(4400,'\"Hector, hard to deal with art thou, that thou shouldest hearken to words of persuasion.'),(4401,' Forasmuch as god has given to thee as to none other works of war, therefore in counsel too art thou minded to have wisdom beyond all;'),(4402,'but in no wise shalt thou be able of thine own self to compass all things.'),(4403,'  To one man hath God given works of war, to another the dance, to another the lyre and song, and in the breast of another Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, putteth a mind of understanding, wherefrom many men get profit, and many he saveth; but he knoweth it best himself.'),(4404,'  So will I speak what seemeth to me to be best.'),(4405,' Behold all about thee blazeth a circle of war, '),(4406,'and the great-souled Trojans, now that they have passed over the wall, are some of them standing aloof with their arms, and others are fighting, fewer men against more, scattered among the ships.'),(4407,' Nay, fall thou back, and call hither all the bravest. '),(4408,'Then shall we consider all manner of counsel, whether we shall fall upon the many-benched ships, if so be the god willeth to give us victory, or thereafter shall return unscathed back from the ships. '),(4409,'Verily, for myself,  I fear lest the Achaeans shall pay back the debt of yesterday, seeing there abideth by the ships a man insatiate of war, who no longer, methinks, will hold him utterly aloof from battle.'),(4410,'So spake Polydamas, and his prudent counsel was well pleasing unto Hector, and forthwith he leapt in his armour from his chariot to the ground;  and he spake and addressed him with winged words:'),(4411,'\"Polydamas, do thou hold back here all the bravest, but I will go thither and confront the war, '),(4412,'and quickly will I come again, when to the full I have laid on them my charge.'),(4413,'So spake he, and set forth, in semblance like a snowy mountain,  and with loud shouting sped he through the Trojans and allies. '),(4414,'And they hasted one and all toward the kindly Polydamas, son of Panthous when they heard the voice of Hector.'),(4415,'But he ranged through the foremost fighters, in quest of Deïphobus, and the valiant prince Helenus, and Adamas, son of Asius, and Asius, son of Hyrtacus,  if haply he might find them.'),(4416,'But he found them no more in any wise unscathed or free from bane'),(4417,'but some were lying at the sterns of the ships of the Achaeans, slain by the hands of the Argives, and some were within the wall, smitten by darts or wounded with spear-thrusts.'),(4418,'  But one he presently found on the left of the tearful battle, even goodly Alexander, the lord of fair-tressed Helen, heartening his comrades and urging them on to fight; and he drew near and spake to him with words of shame:'),(4419,'\"Evil Paris, most fair to look upon, thou that art mad after women, thou beguiler,  where, I pray thee, is Deïphobus, and the valiant prince Helenus, and Adamas, son of Asius, and Asius, son of Hyrtacus?'),(4420,' Aye, and where, tell me, is Othryoneus?'),(4421,' Now is steep Ilios wholly plunged into ruin; '),(4422,'now, thou mayest see, is utter destruction sure.'),(4423,'Then spake unto him again godlike Alexander:'),(4424,'  \"Hector, seeing it is thy mind to blame one in whom is no blame, at some other time have I haply withdrawn me from war rather than now, for my mother bare not even me wholly a weakling.'),(4425,' For from the time thou didst rouse the battle of thy comrades beside the ships, even from that time we abide here and have dalliance with the Danaans  ceaselessly;'),(4426,'but our comrades are dead of whom thou makest question'),(4427,'Only Deïphobus and the valiant prince Helenus have departed, both of them smitten in the arm with long spears; '),(4428,'yet the son of Cronos warded off death.'),(4429,' But now lead thou on whithersoever thy heart and spirit bid thee, '),(4430,' and as for us, we will follow with thee eagerly, nor, methinks, shall we be anywise wanting in valour, so far as we have strength;'),(4431,'but beyond his strength may no man fight, how eager soever he be.\" '),(4432,'So spake the warrior, and turned his brother\'s mind; '),(4433,'and Phalces, and Orthaeus, and godlike Polyphetes, and Palmys, and Ascanius, and Morys, son of Hippotion, who had come from deep-soiled Ascania on the morn before to relieve their fellows, '),(4434,'and now Zeus roused them to fight.'),(4435,'  And they came on like the blast of direful winds that rusheth upon the earth beneath the thunder of father Zeus, and with wondrous din mingleth with the sea, and in its track are many surging waves of the loud-resounding sea, high-arched and white with foam, some in the van and after them others; '),(4436,' even so the Trojans, in close array, some in the van and after them others, flashing with bronze, followed with their leaders.'),(4437,' And Hector, son of Priam, led them, the peer of Ares, the bane of mortals.'),(4438,'Before him he held his shield that was well-balanced upon every side, his shield thick with hides, whereon abundant bronze had been welded,'),(4439,' and about his temples waved the crest of his shining helm'),(4440,'And everywhere on this side and on that he strode forward and made trial of the battalions, if so be they would give way before him, as he advanced under cover of his shield;'),(4441,'yet could he not confound the heart in the breast of the Achaeans.'),(4442,' And Aias came on with long strides, and was first to challenge him:'),(4443,'  \"Good sir, draw nigh; '),(4444,'wherefore seekest thou thus vainly to affright the Argives?'),(4445,' In no wise, I tell thee, are we ignorant of battle, but by the evil scourge of Zeus were we Achaeans subdued.'),(4446,'Verily, thy heart hopeth, I ween, to despoil our ships,'),(4447,'but be sure we too have hands to defend them.'),(4448,'  In good sooth your well-peopled city is like, ere that, to be taken and laid waste beneath our hands.'),(4449,' And for thine own self, I declare that the day is near when in flight thou shalt pray to father Zeus and the other immortals, that thy fair-maned horses may be swifter than falcons— '),(4450,' Even as he thus spake, there flew forth a bird upon the right hand, an eagle of lofty flight; '),(4451,'and thereat the host of the Achaeans shouted aloud, heartened by the omen;'),(4452,' but glorious Hector made answer:'),(4453,' \"Aias, witless in speech, thou braggart, what a thing hast thou said.'),(4454,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 13.825-13.831'),(4455,'  I would that I mine own self were all my days as surely the son of Zeus, that beareth the aegis, and my mother were the queenly Hera, and that I were honoured even as are Athene and Apollo, as verily this day beareth evil for the Argives, one and all; and among them shalt thou too be slain, if thou have the heart  to abide my long spear, that shall rend thy lily-like skin; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 825 to line 833'),(4456,'So spake he, and led the way;'),(4457,'and they followed after with a wondrous din, and the host shouted behind. '),(4458,'But the Argives on the other side cried out, and would not forget their warcraft, but stood the attack of the bravest Trojans,'),(4459,'and the clamour from both was driven high to Zeus\' shining aether.'),(4460,' And the cry of battle was not unmarked of Nestor, albeit at his wine, but he spake winged words to the son of Asclepius:\"'),(4461,'Bethink thee, goodly Machaon, how these things are to be; '),(4462,'louder in sooth by the ships waxes the cry of lusty youths.'),(4463,'  Howbeit do thou now sit where thou art and quaff the flaming wine, until fair-tressed Hecamede shall heat for thee a warm bath, and wash from thee the clotted blood'),(4464,'but I will go straightway to a place of outlook and see what is toward.\"'),(4465,'So spake he and took the well-wrought shield of his son,  horse-taming Thrasymedes, that was lying in the hut, all gleaming with bronze; '),(4466,'but the son had the shield of his father.'),(4467,' And he grasped a valorous spear, tipped with sharp bronze, and took his stand outside the hut, and forthwith saw a deed of shame, even the Achaeans in rout and the Trojans high of heart driving them;'),(4468,' and the wall of the Achaeans was broken down.'),(4469,'And as when the great sea heaveth darkly with a soundless swell, and forebodeth the swift paths of the shrill winds, albeit but vaguely, nor do its waves roll forward to this side or to that until some settled gale cometh down from Zeus;  even so the old man pondered, his mind divided this way and that, whether he should haste into the throng of the Danaans of swift steeds, or go after Agamemnon, son of Atreus, shepherd of the host.'),(4470,' And as he pondered, this thing seemed to him the better—to go after the son of Atreus.'),(4471,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 14.24-14.25'),(4472,'  and about their bodies rang the stubborn bronze, as they thrust one at the other with swords and two-edged spears. '),(4473,'And Nestor was met by the kings, fostered of Zeus, as they went up from the ships, even all they that had been smitten with the bronze, the son of Tydeus, and Odysseus, and Atreus\' son, Agamemnon.'),(4474,'  Far apart from the battle were their ships drawn up on the shore of the grey sea;'),(4475,'for these had they drawn up to land in the foremost row, but had builded the wall close to the hindmost.'),(4476,'For albeit the beach was wide, yet might it in no wise hold all the ships, and the host was straitened;'),(4477,' wherefore they had drawn up the ships row behind row, and had filled up the wide mouth of all the shore that the headlands shut in between them.'),(4478,' The kings therefore were faring all in one body, leaning each on his spear, to look upon the war and the combat, '),(4479,'and grieved were the hearts in their breasts.'),(4480,' And old Nestor met them, and made the spirit to quail in the breasts of the Achaeans.'),(4481,'Then lord Agamemnon lifted up his voice and spake to him:'),(4482,'\"O Nestor, son of Neleus, great glory of the Achaeans, wherefore hast thou left the war, the bane of men, and come hither? '),(4483,'I fear me lest in sooth mighty Hector make good his word and the threats wherewith on a time he threatened us,  as he spake amid the Trojans, even that he would not return to Ilios from the ships till he had burned the ships with fire and furthermore slain the men.'),(4484,'and now all this is verily being brought to pass. Out upon it!'),(4485,'and now all this is verily being brought to pass. Out upon it!'),(4486,'surely the other well-greaved Achaeans  are laying up wrath against me in their hearts, even as doth Achilles, and have no mind to fight by the sterns of the ships.\"'),(4487,'Then made answer to him the horseman Nestor of Gerenia:\"'),(4488,'Yea, verily, these things have now been brought to pass and are here at hand, neither could Zeus himself, that thundereth on high, fashion them otherwise.'),(4489,'  For, lo, the wall has been thrown down, wherein we put our trust that it should be an unbreakable bulwark for our ships and ourselves.'),(4490,' And the foemen at the swift ships maintain a ceaseless fight, and make no end; '),(4491,'nor couldst thou any more tell, wert thou to look never so closely, from what side the Achaeans are driven in rout,  so confusedly are they slain, and the cry of battle goeth up to heaven.'),(4492,'But for us, let us take thought how these things are to be, if so be wit may aught avail.'),(4493,'But into the war I bid not that we should enter; '),(4494,'in no wise may a wounded man do battle.\" '),(4495,'Then again made answer the king of men, Agamemnon:'),(4496,'  \"Nestor, seeing they are fighting at the sterns of the ships, and the well-built wall hath availed not, nor in any wise the trench, whereat the Danaans laboured sore, and hoped in their hearts that it would be an unbreakable bulwark for their ships and for themselves'),(4497,'even so, I ween, must it be the good pleasure of Zeus, supreme in might,  that the Achaeans should perish here far from Argos, and have no name. '),(4498,'I knew it when with a ready heart he was aiding the Danaans, and I know it now when he is giving glory to our foes, even as to the blessed gods, and hath bound our might and our hands.'),(4499,' Nay, come, even as I shall bid, let us all obey.'),(4500,'  Let us drag down the ships that are drawn up in the first line hard by the sea, and let us draw them all forth into the bright sea, and moor them afloat with anchor-stones, till immortal night shall come, if so be that even at her bidding the Trojans will refrain from war; '),(4501,'and thereafter might we drag down all the ships.'),(4502,'  For in sooth I count it not shame to flee from ruin, nay, not though it be by night.'),(4503,' Better it is if one fleeth from ruin and escapeth, than if he be taken.\"'),(4504,'Then with an angry glance from beneath his brows Odysseus of many wiles addressed him:'),(4505,'Son of Atreus, what a word hath escaped the barrier of thy teeth! '),(4506,'Doomed man that thou art, would that thou wert in command of some other, inglorious army,  and not king over us, to whom Zeus hath given, from youth right up to age, to wind the skein of grievous wars till we perish, every man of us.'),(4507,'Art thou in truth thus eager to leave behind thee the broad-wayed city of the Trojans, for the sake of which we endure many grievous woes?'),(4508,'  Be silent, lest some other of the Achaeans hear this word, that no man should in any wise suffer to pass through his mouth at all, no man who hath understanding in his heart to utter things that are right, and who is a sceptred king to whom hosts so many yield obedience as are the Argives among whom thou art lord.'),(4509,' But now have I altogether scorn of thy wits, that thou speakest thus'),(4510,'seeing thou biddest us, when war and battle are afoot, draw down our well-benched ships to the sea, that so even more than before the Trojans may have their desire, they that be victors even now, and that on us utter destruction may fall.'),(4511,'For the Achaeans  will not maintain their fight once the ships are drawn down to the sea, but will ever be looking away, and will withdraw them from battle.'),(4512,' Then will thy counsel prove our bane, thou leader of hosts.\" '),(4513,'To him then made answer, Agamemnon, king of men:\"'),(4514,'Odysseus, in good sooth thou hast stung my heart with harsh reproof; '),(4515,' yet I urge not that against their will the sons of the Achaeans should drag the well-benched ships down to the sea.'),(4516,' But now I would there were one who might utter counsel better than this of mine, be he young man or old; '),(4517,'right welcome were it unto me.'),(4518,'Then among them spake also Diomedes, good at the war-cry:'),(4519,'not long shall we seek him,'),(4520,'not long shall we seek him,'),(4521,'if so be ye are minded to give ear, and be no wise vexed and wroth, each one of you, for that in years I am the youngest among you.'),(4522,'Nay, but of a goodly father do I too declare that I am come by lineage, even of Tydeus, whom in Thebe the heaped-up earth covereth.'),(4523,'  For to Portheus were born three peerless sons, and they dwelt in Pleuron and steep Calydon, even Agrius and Melas, and the third was the horseman Oeneus, that was father to my father, '),(4524,'and in valour was pre-eminent among them.'),(4525,'He verily abode there, but my father went wandering to Argos, and there was settled, '),(4526,' for so I ween was the will of Zeus and the other gods.'),(4527,'And he wedded one of the daughters of Adrastus, and dwelt in a house rich in substance, and abundance was his of wheat-bearing fields, and many orchards of trees round about, and withal many sheep; '),(4528,'and with his spear he excelled all the Argives.'),(4529,' Of these things it must be that ye have heard, whether I speak sooth.'),(4530,'Wherefore ye shall not say that by lineage I am a coward and a weakling, and so despise my spoken counsel, whatsoever I may speak aright.'),(4531,' Come, let us go down to the battle, wounded though we be, since needs we must.'),(4532,'Thereafter will we hold ourselves aloof from the fight,  beyond the range of missiles, lest haply any take wound on wound; '),(4533,'but the others will we spur on and send into battle, even them that hitherto have done pleasure to their resentment, and that stand aloof and fight not.\"'),(4534,'So spake he, and they readily hearkened to him and obeyed'),(4535,'So they set out to go, and the king of men, Agamemnon, led them.'),(4536,'  And no blind watch did the famed Shaker of Earth keep, but went with them in likeness of an old man, and he laid hold of the right hand of Agamemnon, son of Atreus, and spake, and addressed him with winged words:'),(4537,'\"Son of Atreus, now in sooth, methinks, doth the baneful heart of Achilles  rejoice within his breast, as he beholdeth the slaughter and rout of the Achaeans, seeing he hath no understanding, no, not a whit.'),(4538,' Nay, even so may he perish, and a god bring him low. '),(4539,'But with thee are the blessed gods in no wise utterly wroth; nay, even yet, I ween, shall the leaders and rulers of the Trojans  raise the dust of the wide plain, and thyself behold them fleeing to the city from the ships and huts.\"'),(4540,'So saying, he shouted mightily, as he sped over the plain. '),(4541,'Loud as nine thousand warriors, or ten thousand, cry in battle when they join in the strife of the War-god,  even so mighty a shout did the lord, the Shaker of Earth, send forth from his breast.'),(4542,' and in the heart of each man of the Achaeans he put great strength, to war and fight unceasingly. '),(4543,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 14.153-14.154'),(4544,'Now Hera of the golden throne, standing on a peak of Olympus, therefrom had sight of him, ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 154 to line 158'),(4545,'And Zeus she marked seated on the topmost peak of many-fountained Ida, and hateful was he to her heart.'),(4546,'Then she took thought, the ox-eyed, queenly Hera,  how she might beguile the mind of Zeus that beareth the aegis. '),(4547,'And this plan seemed to her mind the best—to go to Ida, when she had beauteously adorned her person, if so be he might desire to lie by her side and embrace her body in love, and she might shed a warm and gentle sleep  upon his eyelids and his cunning mind. '),(4548,'So she went her way to her chamber, that her dear son Hephaestus had fashioned for her, and had fitted strong doors to the door-posts with a secret bolt, that no other god might open.'),(4549,'Therein she entered, and closed the bright doors.'),(4550,'  With ambrosia first did she cleanse from her lovely body every stain, and anointed her richly with oil, ambrosial, soft, and of rich fragrance; '),(4551,'were this but shaken in the palace of Zeus with threshold of bronze, even so would the savour thereof reach unto earth and heaven.'),(4552,'  Therewith she annointed her lovely body, and she combed her hair, and with her hands pIaited the bright tresses, fair and ambrosial, that streamed from her immortal head.'),(4553,' Then she clothed her about in a robe ambrosial, which Athene had wrought for her with cunning skill, and had set thereon broideries full many; '),(4554,' and she pinned it upon her breast with brooches of gold, '),(4555,'and she girt about her a girdle set with an hundred tassels, and in her pierced ears she put ear-rings with three clustering drops;'),(4556,'and abundant grace shone therefrom.'),(4557,'And with a veil over all did the bright goddess  veil herself, a fair veil, all glistering, '),(4558,'and white was it as the sun;'),(4559,'and beneath her shining feet she bound her fair sandals.'),(4560,' But when she had decked her body with all adornment, she went forth from her chamber, and calling to her Aphrodite, apart from the other gods, she spake to her, saying:'),(4561,'  \"Wilt thou now hearken to me, dear child, in what I shall say? or wilt thou refuse me, being angered at heart for that I give aid to the Danaans and thou to the Trojans?\" '),(4562,'Then made answer to her Aphrodite, daughter of Zeus:\"'),(4563,'Hera, queenly goddess, daughter of great Cronos,  speak what is in thy mind; '),(4564,'my heart bids me fulfill it, if fulfill it I can, and it is a thing that hath fulfillment.\"'),(4565,'Then with crafty thought spake to her queenly Hera:\"'),(4566,'Give me now love and desire, wherewith thou art wont to subdue all immortals and mortal men.'),(4567,'  For I am faring to visit the limits of the all-nurturing earth, and Oceanus, from whom the gods are sprung, and mother Tethys, even them that lovingly nursed and cherished me in their halls, when they had taken me from Rhea, what time Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, thrust Cronos down to dwell beneath earth and the unresting sea.'),(4568,' Them am I faring to visit, and will loose for them their endless strife,'),(4569,'since now for a long time\'s space they hold aloof one from the other from the marriage-bed and from love, for that wrath hath come upon their hearts.'),(4570,' If by words I might but persuade the hearts of these twain, and bring them back to be joined together in love,  ever should I be called dear by them and worthy of reverence.\"'),(4571,'To her again spake in answer laughter-loving Aphrodite:'),(4572,'It may not be that I should say thee nay, nor were it seemly; '),(4573,'for thou sleepest in the arms of mightiest Zeus.\"'),(4574,'She spake, and loosed from her bosom the broidered zone,  curiously-wrought, wherein are fashioned all manner of allurements; '),(4575,'therein is love, therein desire, therein dalliance—beguilement that steals the wits even of the wise.'),(4576,' This she laid in her hands, and spake, and addressed her:\"'),(4577,'Take now and lay in thy bosom this zone,  curiously-wrought, wherein all things are fashioned;'),(4578,'I tell thee thou shalt not return with that unaccomplished, whatsoever in thy heart thou desirest.\"'),(4579,'So spake she, and ox-eyed, queenly Hera smiled, and smiling laid the zone in her bosom.'),(4580,'She then went to her house, the daughter of Zeus, Aphrodite,  but Hera darted down and left the peak of Olympus; on Pieria she stepped and lovely Emathia, and sped over the snowy mountains of the Thracian horsemen, even over their topmost peaks, '),(4581,'nor grazed she the ground with her feet;'),(4582,'and from Athos she stepped upon the billowy sea,  and so came to Lemnos, the city of godlike Thoas.'),(4583,'There she met Sleep, the brother of Death; and she clasped him by the hand, and spake and addressed him:'),(4584,' \"Sleep, lord of all gods and of all men, if ever thou didst hearken to word of mine, so do thou even now obey,'),(4585,' and I will owe thee thanks all my days.'),(4586,'Lull me to sleep the bright eyes of Zeus beneath his brows, so soon as I shall have lain me by his side in love.'),(4587,' And gifts will I give thee, a fair throne, ever imperishable, wrought of gold, '),(4588,'that Hephaestus, mine own son,  the god of the two strong arms, shall fashion thee with skill, and beneath it shall he set a foot-stool for the feet, whereon thou mayest rest thy shining feet when thou quaffest thy wine.\" '),(4589,' \nThen sweet Sleep made answer to her, saying: '),(4590,'\"Hera, queenly goddess, daughter of great Cronos, another of the gods, that are for ever, might I lightly lull to sleep, aye, were it even the streams of the river  Oceanus, from whom they all are sprung; '),(4591,'but to Zeus, son of Cronos, will I not draw nigh, neither lull him to slumber, unless of himself he bid me.'),(4592,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 14.249-14.251'),(4593,'from MILESTONE 250 to MILESTONE 260\n======================================================================\nI, verily, beguiled the mind of Zeus, that beareth the aegis, being shed in sweetness round about him, '),(4594,'and thou didst devise evil in thy heart against his son, when thou hadst roused the blasts of cruel winds over the face of the deep, and thereafter didst bear him away unto well-peopled Cos, far from all his kinsfolk.'),(4595,'But Zeus, when he awakened, was wroth, and flung the gods hither and thither about his palace, and me above all he sought, '),(4596,'and would have hurled me from heaven into the deep to be no more seen, had Night not saved me—Night that bends to her sway both gods and men.'),(4597,'  To her I came in my flight, and besought her, and Zeus refrained him, albeit he was wroth, '),(4598,'  To her I came in my flight, and besought her, and Zeus refrained him, albeit he was wroth, for he had awe lest he do aught displeasing to swift Night.'),(4599,'And now again thou biddest me fulfill this other task, that may nowise be done.'),(4600,'To him then spake again ox-eyed, queenly Hera:'),(4601,'\"Sleep, wherefore ponderest thou of these things in thine heart?'),(4602,'  Deemest thou that Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, will aid the Trojans, even as he waxed wroth for the sake of Heracles, his own son?'),(4603,' Nay, come, I will give thee one of the youthful Graces to wed to be called thy wife'),(4604,'  So spake she, and Sleep waxed glad, and made answer saying: '),(4605,'\"Come now, swear to me by the inviolable water of Styx, and with one hand lay thou hold of the bounteous earth, and with the other of the shimmering sea, that one and all they may be witnesses betwixt us twain, even the gods that are below with Cronos,  that verily thou wilt give me one of the youthful Graces, even Pasithea, that myself I long for all my days.'),(4606,'So spake he, and the goddess, white-armed Hera, failed not to hearken, but sware as he bade, and invoked by name all the gods below Tartarus, that are called Titans.'),(4607,'  But when she had sworn and made an end of the oath, the twain left the cities of Lemnos and Imbros, and clothed about in mist went forth, speeding swiftly on their way.'),(4608,'To many-fountained Ida they came, the mother of wild creatures, even to Lectum, where first they left the sea;'),(4609,'and the twain fared on over the dry land,  and the topmost forest quivered beneath their feet.'),(4610,'There Sleep did halt, or ever the eyes of Zeus beheld him, and mounted up on a fir-tree exceeding tall, the highest that then grew in Ida; and it reached up through the mists into heaven.'),(4611,'Thereon he perched, thick-hidden by the branches of the fir,  in the likeness of a clear-voiced mountain bird, that the gods call Chalcis, and men Cymindis.'),(4612,'But Hera swiftly drew nigh to topmost Gargarus, the peak of lofty Ida, '),(4613,'and Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, beheld her.'),(4614,'And when he beheld her, then love encompassed his wise heart about,  even as when at the first they had gone to the couch and had dalliance together in love, their dear parents knowing naught thereof.'),(4615,' And he stood before her, and spake, and addressed her:\"'),(4616,'Hera, with what desire art thou thus come hither down from Olympus?'),(4617,'Lo, thy horses are not at hand, neither thy chariot, whereon thou mightest mount.\"'),(4618,'  Then with crafty mind the queenly Hera spake unto him:'),(4619,'\"I am faring to visit the limits of the all-nurturing earth, and Oceanus, from whom the gods are sprung, and mother Tethys, even them that lovingly nursed me and cherished me in their halls.'),(4620,'Them am I faring to visit, and will loose for them their endless strife, '),(4621,' since now for long time\'s apace they hold aloof one from the other from the marriage-bed and from love, for that wrath hath fallen upon their hearts.'),(4622,' And my horses stand at the foot of many-fountained Ida, my horses that shall bear me both over the solid land and the waters of the sea. '),(4623,'But now it is because of thee that I am come hither down from Olympus,  lest haply thou mightest wax wroth with me hereafter, if without a word I depart to the house of deep-flowing Oceanus.\" '),(4624,'Then in answer spake to her Zeus, the cloud-gatherer.'),(4625,' \"Hera, thither mayest thou go even hereafter. But for us twain, come, let us take our joy couched together in love;'),(4626,' for never yet did desire for goddess or mortal woman so shed itself about me and overmaster the heart within my breast—nay, not when I was seized with love of the wife of Ixion, who bare Peirithous, the peer of the gods in counsel;'),(4627,'nor of Danaë of the fair ankles, daughter of Acmsius,  who bare Perseus, pre-eminent above all warriors;'),(4628,'nor of the daughter of far-famed Phoenix, that bare me Minos and godlike Rhadamanthys; '),(4629,'nor of Semele, nor of Alcmene in Thebes, and she brought forth Heracles, her son stout of heart,'),(4630,' and Semele bare Dionysus, the joy of mortals;'),(4631,'nor of Demeter, the fair-tressed queen; nor of glorious Leto; nay, nor yet of thine own self, as now I love thee, and sweet desire layeth hold of me.'),(4632,'Then with crafty mind the queenly Hera spake unto him:'),(4633,' \"Most dread son of Cronos, what a word hast thou said.'),(4634,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 14.331-14.332'),(4635,'If now thou art fain to be couched in love on the peaks of Ida, where all is plain to view, what ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 331 to line 335'),(4636,' Then verily could not I arise from the couch and go again to thy house; that were a shameful thing.'),(4637,' But if thou wilt, and it is thy heart\'s good pleasure, thou hast a chamber, that thy dear son Hephaestus fashioned for thee, and fitted strong doors upon the door-posts.'),(4638,' Thither let us go and lay us down, since the couch is thy desire.'),(4639,'Then in answer to her spake Zeus, the cloud-gatherer:'),(4640,' \"Hera, fear thou not that any god or man shall behold the thing, '),(4641,'with such a cloud shall I enfold thee withal, a cloud of gold.'),(4642,'Therethrough might not even Helios discern us twain,  albeit his sight is the keenest of all for beholding.\"'),(4643,'Therewith the son of Cronos clasped his wife in his arms,'),(4644,'and beneath them the divine earth made fresh-sprung grass to grow, and dewy lotus, and crocus, and hyacinth, thick and soft, that upbare them from the ground.'),(4645,'  Therein lay the twain, and were clothed about with a cloud, fair and golden,'),(4646,'wherefrom fell drops of glistering dew. '),(4647,'Thus in quiet slept the Father on topmost Gargarus, by sleep and love overmastered, and clasped in his arms his wife.'),(4648,' But sweet Sleep set out to run to the ships of the Argives  to bear word to the Enfolder and Shaker of Earth. '),(4649,'And he came up to him, and spake winged words, saying:\"'),(4650,'With a ready heart now, Poseidon, do thou bear aid to the Danaans, and vouchsafe them glory, though it be for a little space, while yet Zeus sleepeth; for over him have I shed soft slumber, '),(4651,' and Hera hath beguiled him to couch with her in love.'),(4652,'So spake he and departed to the glorious tribes of men, but Poseidon he set on yet more to bear aid to the Danaans.'),(4653,' Forthwith then he leapt forth amid the foremost, and cried aloud:'),(4654,'\"Argives, are we again in good sooth to yield victory to Hector,  son of Priam, that he may take the ships and win him glory? '),(4655,'Nay, even so he saith, and vaunteth that it shall be, for that Achilles abideth by the hollow ships, filled with wrath at heart.'),(4656,'Howbeit him shall we in no wise miss overmuch if we others bestir ourselves to bear aid one to the other.'),(4657,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 14.370'),(4658,'In the shields that are best in the host and largest let us harness ourselves, and our heads let us cover with helms all-gleaming, and in our hands take the longest spears, and so go forth.'),(4659,'And I will lead the way, nor, methinks,  will Hector, son of Priam, longer abide, how eager soever he be. '),(4660,'And whoso is a man, staunch in fight, but hath a small shield on his shoulder, let him give it to a worser man, and himself harness him in a large shield.\" '),(4661,'So spake he, and they readily hearkened to him, and obeyed.'),(4662,' And the kings themselves, albeit they were wounded, set them in array,  even the son of Tydeus, and Odysseus, and Atreus\' son Agamemnon. '),(4663,'And going throughout all the host, they made exchange of battle-gear.'),(4664,'In good armour did the good warrior harness him, and to the worse they gave the worse.'),(4665,'Then when they had clothed their bodies in gleaming bronze, they set forth, '),(4666,'and Poseidon, the Shaker of Earth, led them,  bearing in his strong hand a dread sword, long of edge, like unto the lightning, '),(4667,'wherewith it is not permitted that any should mingle in dreadful war, but terror holds men aloof therefrom.'),(4668,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 14.388'),(4669,' But the Trojans over against them was glorious Hector setting in array. ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 388 to line 393'),(4670,'And the sea surged up to the huts and ships of the Argives,'),(4671,'and the two sides clashed with a mighty din.'),(4672,'Not so loudly bellows the wave of the sea upon the shore,  driven up from the deep by the dread blast of the North Wind,'),(4673,'nor so loud is the roar of blazing fire in the glades of a nuountain when it leapeth to burn the forest,'),(4674,'nor doth the wind shriek so loud amid the high crests of the oaks—the wind that roareth the loudest in its rage—  as then was the cry of Trojans and Achaeans, shouting in terrible wise as they leapt upon each other. '),(4675,'At Aias did glorious Hector first cast his spear, as he was turned full toward him, and missed him not, but smote him where the two baldrics—  one of his shield and one of his silver-studded sword—were stretched across his breast; '),(4676,'and they guarded his tender flesh.'),(4677,' And Hector waxed wroth for that the swift shaft had flown vainly from his hand, and back he shrank into the throng of his comrades, avoiding fate. '),(4678,'But thereupon as he drew back, great Telamonian Aias smote him with a stone;  for many there were, props of the swift ships, that rolled amid their feet as they fought; of these he lifted one on high, and smote Hector on the chest over the shield-rim, hard by the neck, and set him whirling like a top with the blow; and he spun round and round. '),(4679,'And even as when beneath the blast of father Zeus an oak falleth uprooted,  and a dread reek of brimstone ariseth therefrom—then verily courage no longer possesseth him that looketh thereon and standeth near by, for dread is the bolt of great Zeus—even so fell mighty Hector forthwith to the ground in the dust.'),(4680,' And the spear fell from his hand, but the shield was hurled upon him,  and the helm withal, and round about him rang his armour dight with bronze. '),(4681,'Then with loud shouts they ran up, the sons of the Achaeans, hoping to drag him off, and they hurled their spears thick and fast;'),(4682,'but no one availed to wound the shepherd of the host with thrust or with cast,'),(4683,'for ere that might be, the bravest stood forth to guard him,  even Polydamas, and Aeneas, and goodly Agenor, and Sarpedon, leader of the Lycians, and peerless Glaucus withal,'),(4684,'and of the rest was no man unheedful of him, but before him they held their round shields;'),(4685,'and his comrades lifted him up in their arms and bare him forth from the toil of war until he came to the swift horses  that stood waiting for him at the rear of the battle and the conflict, with their charioteer and chariot richly dight.'),(4686,'These bare him groaning heavily toward the city.'),(4687,'But when they were now come to the ford of the fair-flowing river, even eddying Xanthus, that immortal Zeus begat,  there they lifted him from the chariot to the ground and poured water upon him.'),(4688,' And he revived, and looked up with his eyes, and kneeling on his knees he vomited forth black blood.'),(4689,' Then again he sank back upon the ground, and both his eyes were enfolded in black night; '),(4690,'and the blow still overwhelmed his spirit. '),(4691,'  But when the Argives saw Hector withdrawing, they leapt yet the more upon the Trojans, and bethought them of battle.'),(4692,' Then far the first did swift Aias, son of Oïleus, leap upon Satnius and wound him with a thrust of his sharp spear, even the son of Enops, whom a peerless Naiad nymph conceived  to Enops, as he tended his herds by the banks of Satnioeis. '),(4693,'To him did the son of Oïleus, famed for his spear, draw nigh, and smite him upon the flank;'),(4694,'and he fell backward, and about him Trojans and Danaans joined in fierce conflict.'),(4695,'To him then came Polydamas, wielder of the spear, to bear him aid,  even the son of Panthous, and he cast and smote upon the right shoulder Prothoënor, son of Areïlycus, and through the shoulder the mighty spear held its way; and he fell in the dust and clutched the ground with his palm.'),(4696,' And Polydamas exulted over him in terrible wise, and cried aloud:'),(4697,'\"Hah, methinks, yet again from the strong hand of the great-souled son of Panthous  hath the spear leapt not in vain. Nay, one of the Argives hath got it in his flesh, and leaning thereon for a staff; methinks, will he go down into the house of Hades.'),(4698,'So spake he, but upon the Argives came sorrow by reason of his exulting,'),(4699,'and beyond all did he stir the soul of Aias, wise of heart,  the son of Telamon, '),(4700,'for closest to him did the man fall.'),(4701,'Swiftly then he cast with his bright spear at the other, even as he was drawing back.'),(4702,'And Polydamas himself escaped black fate, springing to one side; but Archelochus, son of Antenor, received the spear; '),(4703,'for to him the gods purposed death.'),(4704,'  Him the spear smote at the joining of head and neck on the topmost joint of the spine, and it shore off both the sinews.'),(4705,' And far sooner did his head and mouth and nose reach the earth as he fell, than his legs and knees.'),(4706,'Then Aias in his turn called aloud to peerless Polydamas:'),(4707,'  \"Bethink thee, Polydamas, and tell me in good sooth, was not this man worthy to be slain in requital for Prothoënor?'),(4708,'No mean man seemeth he to me, nor of mean descent, but a brother of Antenor, tamer of horses, or haply a son; '),(4709,'for he is most like to him in build.'),(4710,'  So spake he, knowing the truth full well, and sorrow seized the hearts of the Trojans.'),(4711,'Then Acamas, as he bestrode his brother, smote with a thrust of his spear the Boeotian Promachus,'),(4712,'who was seeking to drag the body from beneath him by the feet. '),(4713,'And over him Acamas exulted in terrible wise, and cried aloud:'),(4714,'\"Ye Argives, that rage with the bow, insatiate of threatenings,  not for us alone, look you, shall there be toil and woe, but even in like manner shall ye too be slain.'),(4715,'Mark how your Promachus sleepeth, vanquished by my spear, to the end that the blood-price of my brother be not long unpaid.'),(4716,'Aye, and for this reason doth a man pray  that a kinsman be left him in his halls, to be a warder off of ruin.\"'),(4717,'So spake he, and upon the Argives came sorrow by reason of his exuIting,'),(4718,'and beyond all did he stir the soul of wise-hearted Peneleos.'),(4719,'He rushed upon Acamas'),(4720,'but Acamas abode not the onset of the prince Peneleos.'),(4721,'Howbeit Peneleos thrust and smote Ilioneus,  son of Phorbas, rich in herds, whom Hermes loved above all the Trojans and gave him wealth;'),(4722,'and to him the mother bare Ilioneus, an only child.'),(4723,' Him then did Peneleos smite beneath the brow at the roots of the eyes, '),(4724,'and drave out the eyeball, and the shaft went clean through the eye  and through the nape ot the neck, and he sank down stretching out both his hands.'),(4725,'But Peneleos drawing his sharp sword let drive full upon his neck, and smote off to the the ground the head with the helmet'),(4726,'and still the mighty spear stood in the eye; '),(4727,'and holding it on high like a poppy-head  he shewed it to the Trojans, and spake a word exultingly:'),(4728,'Tell, I pray you, ye Trojans, to the dear father and the mother of lordly Ilioneus to make wailing in their halls'),(4729,'for neither will the wife of Promachus, son of Alegenor, rejoice in the coming of her dear husband, '),(4730,'So spake he, and thereat trembIing seized the limbs of them all, and each man gazed about to see how he might escape utter destruction.'),(4731,'TeIl me now, ye Muses, that have dwellings on Olympus, who was first of the Achaeans to bear away the bloody spoils of warriors,  when once the famed Shaker of Earth had turned the battle. '),(4732,'Aias verily was first, the son of Telamon. He smote Hyrtius, the son of Gyrtius, leader of the Mysians stalwart of heart;'),(4733,'and Antilochus stripped the spoils from Phalces and Mermerus, '),(4734,'and Meriones slew Morys and Hippotion,  and Teucer laid low Prothoön and Periphetes;'),(4735,'thereafter Atreus\' son smote with a thrust in the flank Hyperenor, shepherd of the host, and the bronze let forth the bowels, as it clove through,'),(4736,'and his soul sped hastening through the stricken wound, and darkness enfolded his eyes.'),(4737,' But most men did Aias slay, the swift son of Oïleus;'),(4738,'for there was none other like him to pursue with speed of foot amid the rout of men, when Zeus turned them to flight.'),(4739,' But when the Trojans in their flight had passed over the palisade and the trench, and many had been vanquished beneath the hands of the Danaans, then beside their chariots they stayed, and were halted, pale with fear, terror-stricken; '),(4740,'and Zeus awoke  on the peaks of Ida beside Hera of the golden throne. Then he sprang up, and stood, and saw Trojans alike and Achaeans, these in rout, and the Argives driving them on from the rear, and amid them the lord Poseidon. '),(4741,'And Hector he saw lying on the plain, while about him sat his comrades,  and he was gasping with painful breath, distraught in mind, and vomiting blood; for not the weakest of the Achaeans was it that had smitten him.'),(4742,' At sight of him the father of men and gods had pity, and with a dread glance from beneath his brows he spake to Hera, saying:'),(4743,'\"Hera, that art hard to deal with, it is the craft of thine evil wiles  that hath stayed goodly Hector from the fight, and hath driven the host in rout. '),(4744,'Verily I know not but thou shalt yet be the first to reap the fruits of thy wretched ill-contriving, and I shall scourge thee with stripes. '),(4745,'Dost thou not remember when thou wast hung from on high, and from thy feet I suspended two anvils, and about thy wrists cast  a band of gold that might not be broken?'),(4746,'And in the air amid the clouds thou didst hang,'),(4747,'and the gods had indignation throughout high Olympus; howbeit they availed not to draw nigh and loose thee. '),(4748,'Nay, whomsoever I caught, I would seize and hurl from the threshold until he reached the earth, his strength all spent.'),(4749,'Yet not even so was my heart  eased of its ceaseless pain for godlike Heracles, whom thou when thou hadst leagued thee with the North Wind and suborned his blasts, didst send over the unresting sea, by thine evil devising, and thereafter didst bear him away unto well-peopled Cos.'),(4750,' Him did I save from thence, and brought again  to horse-pasturing Argos, albeit after he had laboured sore. '),(4751,'Of these things will I mind thee yet again, that thou mayest cease from thy beguilings, to the end that thou mayest see whether they anywise avail thee, the dalliance and the couch, wherein thou didst lie with me when thou hadst come forth from among the gods, and didst beguile me.\" '),(4752,'So spake he, and the ox-eyed, queenly Hera shuddered;  and she spake and addressed him with winged words:'),(4753,'\"Hereto now be Earth my witness and the broad Heaven above, and the down-flowing water of Styx, which is the greatest and most dread oath for the blessed gods, and thine own sacred head, and the couch of us twain, couch of our wedded love,  whereby I verily would never forswear myself '),(4754,'—not by my will doth Poseidon, the Shaker of Earth, work harm to the Trojans and Hector, and give succour to their foes. Nay, I ween, it is his own soul that urgeth and biddeth him on, and he hath seen the Achaeans sore-bested by their ships and taken pity upon them.'),(4755,'  But I tell thee, I would counsel even him to walk in that way, wherein thou, O lord of the dark cloud, mayest lead him.\"'),(4756,'So spake she, and the father of men and gods smiled, and made answer, and spake to her with winged words: '),(4757,'\"If in good sooth, O ox-eyed, queenly Hera,  thy thought hereafter were to be one with my thought as thou sittest among the immortals, then would Poseidon, how contrary soever his wish might be, forthwith bend his mind to follow thy heart and mine.'),(4758,'But if verily thou speakest in frankness and in truth, go thou now among the tribes of gods and call  Iris to come hither, and Apollo, famed for his bow, that she may go amid the host of the brazen-coated Achaeans, and bid the lord Poseidon that he cease from war, and get him to his own house; but let Phoebus Apollo rouse Hector to the fight,  and breathe strength into him again, and make him forget the pains that now distress his heart; and let him drive the Achaeans back once more, when he has roused in them craven panic; so shall they flee and fall among the many-benched ships of Achilles, son of Peleus,'),(4759,'and he shall send forth his comrade  Patroclus '),(4760,'howbeit him shall glorious Hector slay with the spear before the face of Ilios, after himself hath slain many other youths, and among them withal my son, goodly Sarpedon.'),(4761,'And in wrath for Patroclus shall goodly Achilles slay Hector.'),(4762,'Then from that time forth shall I cause a driving back of the Trojans from the ships  evermore continually, until the Achaeans shall take steep Ilios through the counsels of Athene.'),(4763,'But until that hour neither do I refrain my wrath, nor will I suffer any other of the immortals to bear aid to the Danaans here, until the desire of the son of Peleus be fulfilled,  even as I promised at the first and bowed my head thereto, on the day when the goddess Thetis clasped my knees, beseeching me to do honour to Achilles, sacker of cities.\" '),(4764,'So spake he, and the goddess, white-armed Hera, failed not to hearken, but went her way from the mountains of Ida unto high Olympus.'),(4765,'  And even as swiftly darteth the mind of a man who hath travelled over far lands and thinketh in the wisdom of his heart,\"Would I were here, or there,\" and many are the wishes he conceiveth: even so swiftly sped on in her eagerness the queenly Hera;'),(4766,'and she came to steep Olympus, and found  the immortal gods gathered together in the house of Zeus, '),(4767,'and at sight of her they all sprang up, and greeted her with cups of welcome.'),(4768,'She on her part let be the others, but took the cup from Themis, of the fair cheeks,'),(4769,'for she ran first to meet her, and spake, and addressed her with winged words:'),(4770,'Thou art as one distraught.'),(4771,'Thou art as one distraught.'),(4772,'In good sooth the son of Cronos hath affrighted thee, he thine own husband.\"'),(4773,'Then made answer to her, the goddess, white-armed Hera:'),(4774,'\"Ask me not at large concerning this, O goddess Themis;'),(4775,'of thyself thou knowest what manner of mood is his, how over-haughty and unbending.'),(4776,' Nay, do thou begin for the gods the equal feast in the halls'),(4777,'and this shalt thou hear amid all the immortals, even what manner of evil deeds Zeus declareth.'),(4778,'In no wise, methinks, will it delight in like manner the hearts of all, whether mortals or gods, if so be any even now still feasteth with a joyful mind.\"'),(4779,'  When she had thus spoken, queenly Hera sate her down, and wroth waxed the gods throughout the hall of Zeus.'),(4780,' And she laughed with her lips, but her forehead above her dark brows relaxed not, and, moved with indignation, '),(4781,'she spake among them all:'),(4782,' \"Fools, that in our witlessness are wroth against Zeus!'),(4783,'  In sooth we are even yet fain to draw nigh unto him and thwart him of his will by word or by constraint'),(4784,'but he sitteth apart and recketh not, neither giveth heed thereto;'),(4785,'for he deemeth that among the immortal gods he is manifestly supreme in might and strength.'),(4786,' Wherefore content ye yourselves with whatsoever evil thing he sendeth upon each.'),(4787,'  Even now I deem that sorrow hath been wrought for Ares,'),(4788,'seeing that his son, dearest of men to him, hath perished in battle, even Ascalaphus, whom mighty Ares declareth to be his own.\" '),(4789,'So spake she, but Ares smote his sturdy thighs with the flat of his hands, and with wailing spake, and said:'),(4790,'  \"Count it not blame for me now, O ye that have dwellings on Olympus, if I go to the ships of the Achaeans and avenge the slaying of my son, even though it be my fate to be smitten with the bolt of Zeus, and to lie low in blood and dust amid the dead.\"'),(4791,'So spake he and bade Terror and Rout yoke his horses,  and himself did on his gleaming armour. '),(4792,'Then would yet greater and more grievous wrath and anger have been stirred between Zeus and the immortals, had not Athene, seized with fear for all the gods, sped forth through the doorway, and left the throne whereon she sat, and taken the helm from the head of Ares and the shield from his shoulders;  and she took from his strong hand the spear of bronze, and set it down'),(4793,'and with words rebuked furious Ares:\"'),(4794,'Thou madman, distraught of wit, thou art beside thyself! '),(4795,'Verily it is for naught that thou hast ears for hearing, and thine understanding and sense of right are gone from thee.'),(4796,'  Hearest thou not what the goddess, white-armed Hera, saith, she that is but now come from Olympian Zeus?'),(4797,' Wouldest thou thyself fulfill the measure of manifold woes, and so return to Olympus despite thy grief, perforce, and for all the rest sow the seeds of grievous woe?'),(4798,' For he will forthwith leave the Trojans, high of heart, and the Achaeans, and will hie him to Olympus to set us all in tumult, and will lay hands upon each in turn, the guilty alike and him in whom is no guilt.'),(4799,' Wherefore now I bid thee put away thy wrath for thine own son.'),(4800,'For ere now many a one more excellent than he in might and strength of hand hath been slain,  or will yet be slain; '),(4801,'and a hard thing it is to preserve the lineage and offspring of men.'),(4802,'She spake she, and made furious Ares to sit down upon his throne.'),(4803,'But Hera called Apollo forth from out the hall, and Iris, that is the messenger of the immortal gods;  and she spake and addressed them with winged words:\"'),(4804,'Zeus biddeth you twain go to Ida with all the speed ye may;'),(4805,'and when ye have come, and looked upon the face of Zeus, then do ye whatsoever he may order and command.\" '),(4806,'When she had thus spoken queenly Hera returned again  and sate her down upon her throne; '),(4807,'and the twain sprang up and sped forth upon their way.'),(4808,'To many-fountained Ida they came, mother of wild beasts, and found Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, seated on topmost Gargarus;'),(4809,'and about him a fragrant cloud was wreathed.'),(4810,'The twain then came before the face of Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, '),(4811,' and at sight of them his heart waxed nowise wroth, for that they had speedily obeyed the words of his dear wife.'),(4812,'And to Iris first he spake winged words:'),(4813,'\"Up, go, swift Iris; unto the lord Poseidon bear thou all these tidings, and see thou tell him true.'),(4814,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 15.160-15.161'),(4815,'  Bid him cease from war and battle, and go to join the tribes of gods, or into the bright sea. ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 160 to line 166'),(4816,' Yet his heart counteth it but a little thing to declare himself the peer of me of whom even the other gods are adread.\"'),(4817,'So spake he, and wind-footed, swift Iris failed not to hearken, but went down from the hills of Ida to sacred Ilios.'),(4818,'  And as when from the clouds there flieth snow or chill hail, driven by the blast of the North Wind that is born in the bright heaven, even so fleetly sped in her eagerness swift Iris; and she drew nigh, and spake to the glorious Shaker of Earth, saying:'),(4819,' \"A message for thee, O Earth-Enfolder, thou dark-haired god,  have I come hither to bring from Zeus, that beareth the aegis.'),(4820,'He biddeth thee cease from war and battle, and go to join the tribes of gods, or into the bright sea.'),(4821,' And if so be thou wilt not obey his words, but shalt set them at naught, he threateneth that he will himself come hither to set his might against thine in battle;'),(4822,'  and he biddeth thee avoid thee out of his hands; for he avoweth him to be better far than thou in might, and the elder born.'),(4823,' Yet thy heart counteth it but a little thing to declare thyself the peer of him, of whom even the other gods are adread.\" '),(4824,'Then, stirred to hot anger, the glorious Shaker of Earth spake unto her: '),(4825,' \"Out upon it, verily strong though he be he hath spoken overweeningly, if in sooth by force and in mine own despite he will restrain me that am of like honour with himself. '),(4826,'For three brethren are we, begotten of Cronos, and born of Rhea,—Zeus, and myself, and the third is Hades, that is lord of the dead below.'),(4827,'And in three-fold wise are all things divided, and unto each hath been apportioned his own domain.'),(4828,' I verily, when the lots were shaken, won for my portion the grey sea to be my habitation for ever, and Hades won the murky darkness, while Zeus won the broad heaven amid the air and the clouds;'),(4829,'but the earth and high Olympus remain yet common to us all. '),(4830,'Wherefore will I not in any wise walk after the will of Zeus; nay in quiet  let him abide in his third portion, how strong soever he be.'),(4831,'And with might of hand let him not seek to affright me, as though I were some coward.'),(4832,'His daughters and his sons were it better for him to threaten with blustering words, even them that himself begat, who perforce will hearken to whatsoever he may bid.\"'),(4833,' Then wind-footed swift Iris answered him:'),(4834,'\"Is it thus in good sooth, O Earth-Enfolder, thou dark-haired god, that I am to bear to Zeus this message, unyielding and harsh, or wilt thou anywise turn thee; '),(4835,'for the hearts of the good may be turned?'),(4836,'Thou knowest how the Erinyes ever follow to aid the elder-born.\"'),(4837,' Then answered her again Poseidon, the Shaker of Earth:'),(4838,'\"Goddess Iris, this word of thine is right fitly spoken; '),(4839,'and a good thing verily is this, when a messenger hath an understanding heart.'),(4840,'But herein dread grief cometh upon my heart and soul, whenso any is minded to upbraid with angry words  one of like portion with himself, to whom fate hath decreed an equal share.'),(4841,'But herein dread grief cometh upon my heart and soul, whenso any is minded to upbraid with angry words  one of like portion with himself, to whom fate hath decreed an equal share.'),(4842,'yet another thing will I tell thee, and make this threat in my wrath:'),(4843,'if in despite of me, and of Athene, driver of the spoil,  and of Hera, and Hermes, and lord Hephaestus, he shall spare steep Ilios, and shall be minded not to lay it waste, neither to give great might to the Argives, let him know this, that between us twain shall be wrath that naught can appease.'),(4844,'So saying, the Shaker of Earth left the host of the Achaeans, and fared to the sea and plunged therein; and the Achaean warriors missed him sore. '),(4845,'  Then unto Apollo spake Zeus, the cloud-gatherer:'),(4846,' \"Go now, dear Phoebus, unto Hector, harnessed in bronze,'),(4847,'for now is the Enfolder and Shaker of Earth gone into the bright sea, avoiding our utter wrath; '),(4848,'else verily had others too heard of our strife,  even the gods that are in the world below with Cronos.'),(4849,'But this was better for both, for me and for his own self, that ere then he yielded to my hands despite his wrath, for not without sweat would the issue have been wrought.'),(4850,' But do thou take in thine hands the tasselled aegis,  and shake it fiercely over the Achaean warriors to affright them withal.'),(4851,'And for thine own self, thou god that smitest afar, let glorious Hector be thy care, '),(4852,'and for this time\'s space rouse in him great might, even until the Achaeans shall come in flight unto their ships and the Hellespont.'),(4853,'From that moment will I myself contrive word and deed,  to the end that yet again the Achaeans may have respite from their toil.\"'),(4854,'So spake he, nor was Apollo disobedient to his father s bidding, but went down from the hills of Ida, like a fleet falcon, the slayer of doves, that is the swiftest of winged things.'),(4855,'He found the son of wise-hearted Priam, even goodly Hector,  sitting up, for he lay no longer, and he was but newly gathering back his spirit, and knew his comrades round about him'),(4856,'and his gasping and his sweat had ceased, for the will of Zeus, that beareth the aegis, revived him.'),(4857,' And Apollo, that worketh afar, drew nigh unto him, and said:\"'),(4858,'Hector, son of Priam, why is it that thou apart from the rest  abidest here fainting?'),(4859,'Is it haply that some trouble is come upon thee?\"'),(4860,'Then, his strength all spent, spake to him Hector of the flashing helm:\"'),(4861,'Who of the gods art thou, mightiest one, that dost make question of me face to face?'),(4862,' Knowest thou not that at the sterns of the Achaeans\' ships as I made havoc of his comrades, Aias, good at the war-cry, smote me  on the breast with a stone, and made me cease from my furious might? '),(4863,'Aye, and I deemed that on this day I should behold the dead and the house of Hades, when I had gasped forth my life.\" '),(4864,'Then spake to him again the lord Apollo, that worketh afar:\"'),(4865,'Be now of good cheer'),(4866,'so mighty a helper hath the son of Cronos  sent forth from Ida to stand by thy side and succour thee, even me, Phoebus Apollo of the golden sword, that of old ever protect thee, thyself and the steep citadel withal.'),(4867,'But come now, bid thy many charioteers drive against the hollow ships their swift horses,'),(4868,' and I will go before and make smooth all the way for the chariots, and will turn in flight the Achaean warriors.'),(4869,'So saying, he breathed great might into the shepherd of the host. '),(4870,'And even as when a stalled horse that has fed his fill at the manger, breaketh his halter, and runneth stamping over the plain —  being wont to bathe him in the fair-flowing river— and exulteth'),(4871,'on high doth he hold his head and about his shoulders his mane floateth streaming, '),(4872,'and as he glorieth in his splendour his knees nimbly bear him to the haunts and pastures of mares; '),(4873,'even so swiftly plied Hector his feet and knees,  urging on his charioteers, when he had heard the voice of the god.'),(4874,'But as when dogs and country-folk pursue a horned stag or a wild goat,'),(4875,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 15.273-15.274'),(4876,'but a sheer rock or a shadowy thicket saveth him from them, nor is it their lot to find him;  ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 273 to line 276'),(4877,' even so the Danaans for a time ever followed on in throngs, thrusting with swords and two-edged spears'),(4878,'but when they saw Hector going up and down the ranks of men'),(4879,'they were frightened, and by their feet collapsed all their bravery.'),(4880,'Then among them spake Thoas, son of Andraemon, far the best of the Aetolians, well-skilled in throwing the javelin, but a good man too in close fight, '),(4881,'and in the place of assembly could but few of the Achaeans surpass him, when the young men were striving in debate.'),(4882,' He with good intent addressed their gathering, and spake among them:'),(4883,'\"Now look you, verily a great marvel is this that mine eyes behold, how that now he is risen again and hath avoided the fates, even Hector.'),(4884,'In sooth the heart of each man of us hoped that he had died beneath the hands of Aias, son of Telamon.'),(4885,'  But lo, some one of the gods hath again delivered and saved Hector, who verily hath loosed the knees of many Danaans, as, I deem, will befall even now'),(4886,'since not without the will of loud-thundering Zeus doth he stand forth thus eagerly as a champion.'),(4887,'Nay come, even as I shall bid, let us all obey.'),(4888,' The multitude let us bid return to the ships,'),(4889,'but ourselves, all we that declare us to be the the best in the host, let us take our stand, if so be we first may face him, and thrust him back with our outstretched spears; '),(4890,'methinks, for all his eagerness he will fear at heart to enter into the throng of the Danaans.'),(4891,' So spake he, and they readily hearkened and obeyed.'),(4892,'They that were in the company of Aias and prince Idomeneus, and Teucer, and Meriones, and Meges, the peer of Ares, called to the chieftains, and marshalled the fight, fronting Hector and the Trojans,'),(4893,' but behind them the multitude fared back to the ships of the Achaeans.'),(4894,'Then the Trojans drave forward in close throng, and Hector led them, advancing with long strides,'),(4895,'while before him went Phoebus Apollo, his shoulders wrapped in cloud, bearing the fell aegis, girt with shaggy fringe, awful, gleaming bright, that the smith  Hephaestus gave to Zeus to bear for the putting to rout of warriors; '),(4896,'this Apollo bare in his hands as he led on the host. '),(4897,'And the Argives in close throng abode their coming, and the war-cry rose shrill from either side, and the arrows leapt from the bow-string, '),(4898,'and many spears, hurled by bold hands,  were some of them lodged in the flesh of youths swift in battle, and many of them, or ever they reached the white flesh, stood fixed midway in the earth, fain to glut themselves with flesh.'),(4899,'Now so long as Phoebus Apollo held the aegis moveless in his hands, even so long the missiles of either side reached their mark and the folk kept falling; '),(4900,' but when he looked full in the faces of the Danaans of swift horses, and shook the aegis, and himself shouted mightily withal, then made he their hearts to faint within their breasts, and they forgat their furious might. '),(4901,'And as when two wild beasts drive in confusion a herd of kine or a great flock of sheep in the darkness of black night,  when they have come upon them suddenly, and a herdsman is not by, even so were the Achaeans driven in rout with no might in them; '),(4902,'for upon them Apollo had sent panic, and unto the Trojans and Hector was he giving glory.'),(4903,'Then man slew man as the fight was scattered. '),(4904,'Hector laid low Stichius and Arcesilaus,  the one a leader of the brazen-coated Boeotians, and the other a trusty comrade of great-souled Menestheus;'),(4905,'and Aeneas slew Medon and Iasus.'),(4906,'The one verily, Medon, was a bastard son of godlike Oïleus, and brother of Aias, '),(4907,' but he dwelt in Phylace far from his native land, for that he had slain a man of the kin of his stepmother, Eriopis that Oïleus had to wife;'),(4908,'and Iasus was a captain of the Athenians, and was called the son of Sphelus, son of Bucolus.'),(4909,'And Mecisteus did Polydamas slay, and Polites slew Echius  in the forefront of the fight, and Clonius was slain of goodly Agenor. '),(4910,'And Deïochus did Paris smite from behind, as he fled amid the foremost fighters, upon the base of the shoulder, and drave the bronze clean through. '),(4911,'While they were stripping the armour from these, meanwhile the Achaeans were flinging themselves into the digged trench and against the palisade,  fleeing this way and that, and were getting them within their wall perforce. '),(4912,'And Hector shouted aloud, and called to the Trojans:\"Speed ye against the ships, and let be the blood-stained spoils.'),(4913,'Whomsoever I shall mark holding aloof from the ships on the further side, on the very spot shall I devise his death, nor shall his  kinsmen and kinswomen give him his due meed of fire in death, but the dogs shall rend him in front of our city.\"'),(4914,'So saying, with a downward sweep of his arm he smote his horses with the lash, and called aloud to the Trojans along the ranks;'),(4915,'and they all raised a shout, and even with him drave the steeds that drew their chariots, with a wondrous din;'),(4916,' and before them Phoebus Apollo lightly dashed down with his feet the banks of the deep trench, and cast them into the midst thereof, bridging for the men a pathway long and broad, even as far as a spear-cast, when a man hurleth, making trial of his strength.'),(4917,'  Therethrough they poured forward rank on rank, and before them went Apollo, bearing the priceless aegis.'),(4918,' And full easily did he cast down the wall of the Achaeans, even as when a boy scattereth the sand by the sea, one that makes of it a plaything in his childishness, and then again confounds it with hands and feet as he maketh sport:'),(4919,'  so lightly didst thou, O archer Phoebus, confound the long toil and labour of the Achaeans, and on themselves send rout.'),(4920,'So then beside their ships the Danaans halted, and were stayed, calling one upon the other, and lifting up their hands to all the gods they made fervent prayer, each man of them;'),(4921,' and most of all prayed Nestor of Gerenia, the warder of the Achaeans, stretching forth his two hands to the starry heaven:'),(4922,'\"O father Zeus, if ever any man of us in wheat-bearing Argos burned to thee fat thigh-pieces of bull or of ram with the prayer that he might return, and thou didst promise and nod thy head thereto,  be thou now mindful of these things, and ward from us, O Olympian god, the pitiless day of doom, nor suffer the Achaeans thus to be vanquished by the Trojans.\"'),(4923,'So he spake in prayer, and Zeus the counsellor thundered aloud, hearing the prayer of the aged son of Neleus. '),(4924,'But the Trojans, when they heard the thunder of Zeus that beareth the aegis,  leapt yet the more upon the Argives and bethought them of battle.'),(4925,'And as when a great billow of the broad-wayed sea sweepeth down over the bulwarks of a ship, whenso it is driven on by the might of the wind,'),(4926,'which above all maketh the waves to swell; '),(4927,'even so did the Trojans with a great cry rush down over the wall, —  they in their cars, but the Achaeans high up on the decks of their black ships to which they had climbed, fought therefrom with long pikes that lay at hand for them upon the ships for sea-fighting,— jointed pikes, shod at the tip with bronze.'),(4928,'  And Patroclus, so long as the Achaeans and Trojans were fighting about the wall aloof from the swift ships, even so long sat in the hut of kindly Eurypylus, and was making him glad with talk, and on his grievous wound was spreading simples to assuage his dark pangs.'),(4929,'  But when he saw the Trojans rushing upon the wall, while the Danaans with loud cries turned in flight, then he uttered a groan, and smote his two thighs with the flat of his hands, and with wailing spake, saying:\"'),(4930,'Eurypylus, in no wise may I abide longer with thee here,  albeit thy need is sore; '),(4931,'for lo, a mighty struggle hath arisen. '),(4932,'Nay, as for thee, let thy squire bring thee comfort, but I will hasten to Achilles, that I may urge him on to do battle.'),(4933,'Who knows but that, heaven helping, I may rouse his spirit with my persuading?'),(4934,'A good thing is the persuasion of a comrade.\" '),(4935,'  When he had thus spoken his feet bare him on; '),(4936,'but the Achaeans firmly abode the oncoming of the Trojans, yet availed not to thrust them back from the ships, albeit they were fewer, '),(4937,'nor ever could the Trojans break the battalions of the Danaans and make way into the midst of the huts and the ships.'),(4938,'  But as the carpenter\'s line maketh straight a ship\'s timber in the hands of a cunning workman, that is well skilled in all manner of craft by the promptings of Athene, so evenly was strained their war and battle.'),(4939,'So fought they on, divers of them about divers ships,  but Hector made straight for glorious Aias. '),(4940,'They twain were labouring in the toil of war about the same ship, nor might the one drive back the other and burn the ship with fire, nor the other thrust him in back, now that a god had brought him nigh.'),(4941,'Then did glorious Aias cast his spear and smite upon the breast Caletor, son of Clytius,  as he was bearing fire against the ship; '),(4942,'and he fell with a thud, and the torch dropped from out his hand.'),(4943,' But Hector, when his eyes beheld his cousin fallen in the dust in front of the black ship, called to the Trojans and Lycians with a loud shout:'),(4944,'  \"Ye Trojans and Lycians and Dardanians that fight in close combat, in no wise give ye ground from battle in this strait: nay, save ye the son of Clytius, lest so be the Achaeans strip him of his armour, now that he is fallen amid the gathering of the ships.\"'),(4945,'So saying, he hurled at Aias with his bright spear; '),(4946,'but Lycophron, Mastor\'s son, a squire of Aias from Cythera, who dwelt with him, for that he had slain a man in sacred Cythera—him Hector smote upon the head above the ear with the sharp bronze, even as he stood near Aias'),(4947,'and backward in the dust  he fell to the ground from off the stern of the ship and his limbs were loosed. '),(4948,'And Aias shuddered, and spake unto his brother:'),(4949,'Good Teucer, verily a true comrade of us twain hath been laid low, even the son of Mastor, whom while he abode with us, being come from Cythera, we honoured in our halls even as our own parents.'),(4950,' Him hath great-souled Hector slain.'),(4951,'Where now are thy arrows that bring swift death, and the bow that Phoebus Apollos gave thee?\" '),(4952,'So spake he, and the other hearkened, and ran, and took his stand close beside him, bearing in his hand his bent-back bow and the quiver that held his arrows; '),(4953,'and full swiftly did he let fly his shafts upon the Trojans.'),(4954,' And he smote Cleitus, the glorious son of Peisenor, comrade of Polydamas, the lordly son of Panthous, even as he was holding the reins in his hand, '),(4955,'and was busied with his horses'),(4956,'for thither was he driving them, where the most battalions were being driven in rout, thus doing pleasure unto Hector and the Trojans.'),(4957,'But full swiftly  upon himself came evil that not one of them could ward off, how fain soever they were.'),(4958,'For upon the back of his neck lighted the arrow fraught with groanings,'),(4959,'and he fell from the chariot, and thereat the horses swerved aside, rattling the empty car.'),(4960,'And the prince Polydamas swiftly marked it, and was first to stride toward the horses.'),(4961,'  These he gave to Astynous, son of Protiaon, and straitly enjoined him to hold them near at hand, watching him the while; '),(4962,'and he himself went back and mingled with the foremost fighters.'),(4963,'Then Teucer drew forth another arrow for Hector, harnessed in bronze, and would have made him cease from battle by the ships of the Achaeans,  had he but smitten him while he was showing his prowess and taken away his life. '),(4964,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 15.461-15.464'),(4965,'and his arrow  heavy with bronze was turned aside, and the bow fell from his hand.'),(4966,'Then Teucer shuddered, and spake to his brother:'),(4967,'\"Now look you, in good sooth a god is utterly bringing to naught the counsels of our battle, in that he hath cast the bow from my hand, and hath broken the newly-twisted string that I bound fast  this morning that it might avail to bear the arrows that should leap thick and fast therefrom.\"'),(4968,'Then great Telamonian Aias answered him:'),(4969,'Aye, friend, but leave thou thy bow and thy many arrows to lie where they are, seeing that a god has confounded them, in malice toward the Danaans;'),(4970,'but take thou in thy hand a long spear and a shield upon thy shoulder,  and do battle with the Trojans, and urge on the rest of the folk. '),(4971,'Verily not without a struggle, for all they have overpowered us, shall they take our well-benched ships; nay, let us bethink us of battle.\" '),(4972,'So spake he, and Teucer laid the bow again within the hut, but about his shoulders put a fourfold shield,  and upon his mighty head set a well-wrought helmet with horse-hair crest; and terribly did the plume nod from above; '),(4973,'and he took a valorous spear, tipped with sharp bronze, and went his way, and swiftly ran and took his stand by the side of Aias.'),(4974,'But when Hector saw that Teucer\'s shafts had been brought to naught,  to Trojans and Lycians he called with a loud shout'),(4975,'“Ye Trojans and Lycians and Dardanians that fight in close combat, be men, my friends, and bethink you of furious valour amid the hollow ships;'),(4976,'for verily mine eyes have seen how Zeus hath brought to naught the shafts of a man that is a chieftain.'),(4977,'  Full easy to discern is the aid Zeus giveth to men, both to whomso he vouchsafeth the glory of victory, and whomso again he minisheth, and hath no mind to aid, even as now he minisheth the might of the Argives, and beareth aid to us.'),(4978,' Nay, fight ye at the ships in close throngs, '),(4979,'and if so be any of you,  smitten by dart or thrust, shall meet death and fate, let him lie in death.'),(4980,'No unseemly thing is it for him to die while fighting for his country.'),(4981,' Nay, but his wife is safe and his children after him, and his house and his portion of land are unharmed, if but the Achaeans be gone with their ships to their dear native land.\"'),(4982,'  So saying, he aroused the strength and spirit of every man. '),(4983,'And Aias again, over against him called to his comrades:'),(4984,'Shame on you, Argives, '),(4985,'now is it sure that we must either perish utterly or find deliverance by thrusting back the peril from the ships.'),(4986,' Think ye haply that if Hector of the flashing helm take the ships,  ye shall come afoot each man of you to his own native land? '),(4987,'Hear ye not Hector urging on all his host in his fury to burn the ships?'),(4988,' Verily it is not to the dance that he biddeth them come, but to battle.'),(4989,'And for us there is no counsel or device better than this,  that in close combat we bring our hands and our might against theirs. '),(4990,'Better is it once for all either to die or live, than long to be straitened in dread conflict thus bootlessly beside the ships at the hands of men that be meaner.\" '),(4991,'So saying, he aroused the strength and spirit of every man.'),(4992,'  Then Hector slew Schedius, son of Perimedes, a leader of the Phocians, and Aias slew Laodamas, the leader of the footmen, the glorious son of Antenor; '),(4993,'and Polydamas laid low Otus of Cyllene, comrade of Phyleus\' son, captain of the great-souled Epeians.'),(4994,' And Meges saw, and leapt upon him,'),(4995,'but Polydamas swerved from beneath him and him Meges missed;'),(4996,'and him Meges missed;'),(4997,'for Apollo would not suffer the son of Panthous to be vanquished amid the foremost fighters;'),(4998,'but with a spear-thrust he smote Croesmus full upon the breast.'),(4999,'and the other set him to strip the armour from his shoulders.'),(5000,'and the other set him to strip the armour from his shoulders.'),(5001,' Meanwhile upon him leapt Dolops, well skilled with the spear, the son of Lampus, whom Lampus, son of Laomedon, begat, even his bravest son, well skilled in furious might; he it was that then thrust with his spear full upon the shield of Phyleus\' son, setting upon him from nigh at hand.'),(5002,'But his cunningly-wrought corselet saved him,  the corselet that he was wont to wear, fitted with plates of mail. '),(5003,'This Phyleus had brought from out of Ephyre, from the river Seleïs.'),(5004,' For a guest-friend of his, the king of men Euphetes, had given it him that he might wear it in war, a defence against foe-men; '),(5005,'and this now warded death from the body of his son.'),(5006,'  Then Meges thrust with his sharp spear upon the topmost socket of the helm of bronze with horse-hair plume which Dolops wore, and shore therefrom the plume of horse-hair, '),(5007,'and all the plume, bright with its new scarlet dye, fell in the dust. '),(5008,'Now while Meges abode and fought with Dolops, and yet hoped for victory,  meanwhile warlike Menelaus came to bear him aid, and he took his stand on one side with his spear, unmarked of Dolops, and cast and smote him on the shoulder from behind;'),(5009,'and the spear in its fury sped through his breast, darting eagerly onward, '),(5010,'and he fell upon his face;'),(5011,'and the twain made for him to strip from his shoulders his armour wrought of bronze.'),(5012,'  But Hector called to his kinsmen, one and all, and first did he chide Hicetaon\'s son, strong Melanippus.'),(5013,' He until this time had been wont to feed his kine of shambling gait in Percote, while the foemen were yet afar'),(5014,'but when the curved ships of the Danaans came,  he returned back to Ilios, and was pre-eminent among the Trojans; and he dwelt in the house of Priam, who held him in like honour with his own children.'),(5015,'Him did Hector chide, and spake and addressed him, saying:'),(5016,'In good sooth, Melanippus, are we to be thus slack?'),(5017,'Hath thine own heart no regard for thy kinsman that is slain? '),(5018,' Seest thou not in what wise they are busied about the armour of Dolops?'),(5019,'Nay, come thou on;'),(5020,'for no longer may we fight with the Argives from afar, till either we slay them, or they utterly take steep Ilios, and slay her people.\" '),(5021,'So saying, he led the way, and the other followed with him, a godlike man. '),(5022,' And the Argives did great Telamonian Aias urge on, saying:'),(5023,'\"My friends, be men, and take ye shame in your hearts, and have shame each of the other in the fierce conflict.'),(5024,'Of men that have shame more are saved than are slain;'),(5025,'but from them that flee springeth neither glory nor any avail.'),(5026,'  So spake he, and they even of themselves were eager to ward off the foe, but they laid up his word in their hearts, and fenced in the ships with a hedge of bronze; '),(5027,'and against them Zeus urged on the Trojans.'),(5028,' Then Menelaus, good at the war-cry, exhorted Antilochus:\"'),(5029,'Antilochus, none other of the Achaeans is younger than thou,  nor swifter of foot, nor valiant as thou art in fight;'),(5030,'I would thou mightest leap forth, and smite some man of the Trojans.'),(5031,'He spake, and hasted back again himself, but aroused the other, '),(5032,'and Antilochus leapt forth from amid the foremost fighters and, glancing warily about him, hurled with his bright spear,'),(5033,'and back did the Trojans shrink  from the warrior as he cast'),(5034,'Not in vain did he let fly his spear, but smote Hicetaon\'s son, Melanippus, high of heart, as he was coming to the battle, upon the breast beside the nipple; '),(5035,'and he fell with a thud, and darkness enfolded his eyes.'),(5036,'And Antilochus sprang upon him, as a hound that darteth upon a wounded fawn,  that a hunter with sure aim hath smitten as it leapt from its lair, and hath loosed its limbs;'),(5037,'even in such wise upon thee, O Melanippus, leapt Antilochus staunch in fight, to strip from thee thine armour.'),(5038,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 15.583-15.584'),(5039,'Howbeit he was not unseen of goodly Hector, who came running to meet him amid the battle; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 583 to line 591'),(5040,'even so fled the son of Nestor; and the Trojans and Hector  with wondrous shouting poured forth upon him their darts fraught with groanings;'),(5041,'but he turned and stood, when he had reached the host of his comrades. '),(5042,'But the Trojans, like ravening lions, rushed upon the ships and were fulfilling the behests of Zeus, who ever roused great might in them, but made the hearts  of the Argives to melt, and took away their glory, while he spurred on the others.'),(5043,'For his heart was set on giving glory to Hector, son of Priam, to the end that he might cast upon the beaked ships unwearied, wondrous-blazing fire, and so fulfill to the uttermost the presumptuous prayer of Thetis.'),(5044,'Even for this was Zeus the counsellor waiting,  that his eyes might behold the glare of a burning ship; '),(5045,'for from that time forth was he to ordain a driving-back of the Trojans from the ships, and to grant glory to the Danaans.'),(5046,' With this intent he was rousing against the hollow ships Hector son of Priam, that was himself full eager.'),(5047,'  And he was raging like Ares, wielder of the spear, or as when consuming fire rageth among the mountains in the thickets of a deep wood; '),(5048,'and foam came forth about his mouth, and his two eyes blazed beneath his dreadful brows, and round about his temples terribly shook the helm of Hector as he fought;'),(5049,' for Zeus out of heaven was himself his defender, and vouchsafed him honour and glory, alone as he was amid so many warriors.'),(5050,'For brief was his span of life to be, '),(5051,'since even now Pallas Athene was hastening on the day of his doom beneath the might of the son of Peleus.'),(5052,'  But fain was he to break the ranks of men, making trial of them wheresoever he saw the greatest throng and the goodliest arms.'),(5053,'Yet not even so did he avail to break them, for all he was so eager; '),(5054,'for they abode firm-fixed as it were a wall, like a crag, sheer and great, hard by the grey sea,  that abideth the swift paths of the shrill winds, and the swelling waves that belch forth against it; '),(5055,'even so the Danaans withstood the Trojans steadfastly, and fled not.'),(5056,'But Hector shining all about as with fire leapt among the throng, and fell upon them; even as when beneath the clouds a fierce-rushing wave,  swollen by the winds, '),(5057,'falleth upon a swift ship, and she is all hidden by the foam thereof, and the dread blast of the wind roareth against the sail, and the hearts of the sailors shudder in their fear, '),(5058,'for that by little are they borne forth from death; '),(5059,'even so were the hearts of the Achaeans rent within their breasts.'),(5060,'  Hector came on against them, as a murderous lion on cattle who in the low-lying meadow of a great marsh pasture by hundreds, and among them a herdsman who does not quite know how fo tight a wild beast off from killing a horn-curved '),(5061,'ox, and keeps pace with the first and the last of the cattle always, but the lion making his spring at the middle eats an ox as the rest stampede; '),(5062,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 15.636-15.640'),(5063,'Of him, a father baser by far, was begotten a son goodlier in all manner of excellence, both in fleetness of foot and in fight, and in mind he was among the first of the men of Mycenae;'),(5064,'he it was who then yielded to Hector the glory of victory.'),(5065,'  For, as he turned back, he tripped upon the rim of the shield that himself bare, a shield that reached to the feet, a defence against javelins:'),(5066,'thereon he stumbled and fell backward, and about his temples his helm rang wondrously as he fell. '),(5067,'And Hector was quick to mark it, and ran, and stood close beside him,  and fixed his spear in his breast, and slew him hard by his dear comrades;'),(5068,'and they availed not to aid him, albeit they sorrowed for their comrade;'),(5069,'for themselves were sore adread of goodly Hector. '),(5070,'Now were they got among the ships, and the outermost ships encircled them, even they that had been drawn up in the first line; '),(5071,'but their foes rushed on.'),(5072,'  And the Argives gave way perforce from the outermost ships, but abode there beside their huts, all in one body, and scattered not throughout the camp;'),(5073,'for shame withheld them and fear;'),(5074,'and unceasingly they called aloud one to the other.'),(5075,' And above all others Nestor of Gerenia, the warder of the Achaeans,  besought each man, adjuring him by them that begat him, saying:'),(5076,'\"My friends, play the man, and take in your hearts shame of other men, and be ye mindful, each man of you, of children and wife, of possessions and of his parents, whether in the case of any they be living or be dead.'),(5077,' For the sake of them that are not here with us do I now beseech you to stand firm, and turn not back in flight.\"'),(5078,'So saying, he aroused the strength and spirit of every man'),(5079,'and from their eyes Athene thrust away the wondrous cloud of mist, '),(5080,'and mightily did light come to them from either hand,  both from the side of the ships and from that of evil war. '),(5081,'And all beheld Hector, good at the war-cry, and his comrades, alike they that stood in the rear and fought not, and all they that did battle by the swift ships.'),(5082,'Now was it no more pleasing to the soul of great-hearted Aias  to stand in the place where the rest of the sons of the Achaeans stood aloof, '),(5083,'but he kept faring with long strides up and down the decks of the ships, and he wielded in his hands a long pike for sea-fighting, a pike jointed with rings, of a length two and twenty cubits.'),(5084,'And as a man well-skilled in horsemanship  harnesseth together four horses chosen out of many, and driveth them in swift course from the plain toward a great city along a highway'),(5085,'while many marvel at him, both men-folk and women, '),(5086,'and ever with sure step he leapeth, and passeth from horse to horse, while they speed on; '),(5087,' even so Aias kept ranging with long strides over the many decks of the swift ships, and his voice went up to heaven, as ever with terrible cries he called to the Danaans to defend their ships and huts.'),(5088,'Nor did Hector abide amid the throng of the mail-clad Trojans, '),(5089,' but as a tawny eagle darteth upon a flock of winged fowl that are feeding by a river\'s bank—a flock of wild geese, or cranes, or long-necked swans, even so Hector made for a dark-prowed ship, rushing straight thereon; '),(5090,'and from behind Zeus was pushing him onward  hard with his big hand, and stirred on his people beside him.'),(5091,'Then again keen battle was set afoot beside the ships.'),(5092,'Thou wouldst have deemed that all unwearied and unworn they faced one another in war, so furiously did they fight.'),(5093,' And in their fighting they were minded thus: '),(5094,'The Achaeans  verily deemed that they should never escape from out the peril, but should perish, while for the Trojans, the heart in each man\'s breast hoped that they should fire the ships and slay the Achaean warriors.'),(5095,'Such were their thoughts as they stood, each host against the other. '),(5096,'But Hector laid hold of the stern of a seafaring ship,  a fair ship, swift upon the brine, that had borne Protesilaus to Troy, but brought him not back again to his native land.'),(5097,'About his ship Achaeans and Trojans were slaying one another in close combat, '),(5098,'nor did they longer hold aloof and thus endure the flight of arrows and darts,  but standing man against man in oneness of heart, they fought with sharp battle-axes and hatchets, and with great swords and two-edged spears.'),(5099,' And many goodly blades, bound with dark thongs at the hilt, fell to the ground, some from the hands and some from the shoulders  of the warriors as they fought; '),(5100,'and the black earth flowed with blood. '),(5101,'But Hector, when he had grasped the ship by the stern, would not loose his hold, but kept the ensign in his hands, and called to the Trojans:\"'),(5102,'Bring fire, and therewithal raise ye the war-cry all with one voice; '),(5103,'now hath Zeus vouchsafed us a day that is recompense for all—  to take the ships that came hither in despite of the gods, and brought us many woes, by reason of the cowardice of the elders, who, when I was eager to fight at the sterns of the ships, kept me back, and withheld the host.'),(5104,'But if Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, then dulled our wits,  now of himself he urgeth and giveth command.\"'),(5105,'So spake he, and they leapt the more upon the Argives.'),(5106,'for he was sore beset with darts,'),(5107,'for he was sore beset with darts,'),(5108,'but, ever foreboding death, gave ground a little along the bridge of seven feet in height, and left the deck of the shapely ship.'),(5109,' There stood he on the watch, and with his spear he ever warded from the ship whosoever of the Trojans sought to bring unwearied fire; '),(5110,'and ever with terrible cries he called to the Danaans:'),(5111,'Friends, Danaan warriors, squires of Ares, be men, my friends, and bethink you of furious might.'),(5112,'  Do we haply deem that there are other helpers at our backs, or some stronger wall to ward off ruin from men?'),(5113,'In no wise is there hard at hand a city fenced with walls, whereby we might defend ourselves, having a host to turn the tide of battle; '),(5114,'nay, it is in the plain of the mail-clad Trojans  that we are set, with naught to support us but the sea, and far from our native land. '),(5115,'Therefore in the might of our hands is the light of deliverance, and not in slackness in fight.'),(5116,'He spake, and kept driving furiously at the foe with his sharp spear.'),(5117,'And whoso of the Trojans would rush upon the hollow ships with blazing fire, doing pleasure to Hector at his bidding,  for him would Aias wait, and wound him with a thrust of his long spear; '),(5118,'and twelve men did he wound in close fight in front of the ships.'),(5119,' Thus then they were warring around the well-benched ship,'),(5120,'but Patroclus drew nigh to Achilles, shepherd of the host, shedding hot tears, even as a fountain of dark water that down over the face of a beetling cliff poureth its dusky stream; '),(5121,' and swift-footed goodly Achilles had pity when he saw him, and spake and addressed him with winged words:'),(5122,' \"Why, Patroclus, art thou bathed in tears, like a girl, a mere babe, that runneth by her mother\'s side and biddeth her take her up, and clutcheth at her gown, and hindereth her in her going,  and tearfully looketh up at her, till the mother take her up? '),(5123,'Even like her, Patroclus, dost thou let fall round tears.'),(5124,' Hast thou haply somewhat to declare to the Myrmidons or to mine own self, or is it some tidings out of Phthia that thyself alone hast heard?'),(5125,' Still lives Menoetius, men tell us, Actor\'s son,  and still lives Peleus. son of Aeacus, amid the Myrmidons, '),(5126,'for which twain would we grieve right sore, were they dead.'),(5127,' Or art thou sorrowing for the Argives, how they are being slain beside the hollow ships by reason of their own presumptuous act?'),(5128,' Speak out; hide it not in thy mind;that we both may know.\"'),(5129,'  Then with a heavy groan, didst thou make answer, O knight Patroclus:'),(5130,' \"O Achilles, son of Peleus, far the mightiest of the Achaeans, be not wroth; '),(5131,'so great a sorrow hath overmastered the Achaeans.'),(5132,' For verily all they that aforetime were bravest, lie among the ships smitten by darts or wounded with spear-thrusts.'),(5133,'  Smitten is the son of Tydeus, mighty Diomedes, wounded with spear-thrust is Odysseus, famed for his spear, and Agamemnon, and smitten, too, is Eurypylus with an arrow in the thigh.'),(5134,' About these the leeches, skilled in many simples, are busied, seeking to heal their wounds; '),(5135,'but with thee may no man deal, Achilles.'),(5136,'  Never upon me let such wrath lay hold, as that thou dost cherish, O thou whose valour is but a bane!'),(5137,' Wherein shall any other even yet to be born have profit of thee, if thou ward not off shameful ruin from the Argives?'),(5138,' Pitiless one, thy father, meseems, was not the knight Peleus, nor was Thetis thy mother, '),(5139,'but the grey sea bare thee,  and the beetling cliffs, for that thy heart is unbending. '),(5140,'But if in thy mind thou art shunning some oracle, and thy queenly mother hath declared to thee aught from Zeus, yet me at least send thou forth speedily, and with me let the rest of the host of the Myrmidons follow, if so be I may prove a light of deliverance to the Danaans.'),(5141,'  And grant me to buckle upon my shoulders that armour of thine, in hope that the Trojans may take me for thee, and so desist from war, and the warlike sons of the Achaeans may take breath, wearied as they are; '),(5142,'for scant is the breathing-space in battle.'),(5143,' And lightly might we that are unwearied  drive men that are wearied with the battle back to the city from the ships and the huts.”'),(5144,' \nSo spake he in prayer, fool that he was, '),(5145,'for in sooth it was to be his own evil death and fate for which he prayed.'),(5146,' Then, his heart deeply stirred, spake to him swift-footed Achilles:'),(5147,' \"Ah me, Zeus-born Patroclus, what a thing hast thou said!'),(5148,'  Neither reck I of any oracle, that I wot of, nor has my queenly mother declared to me aught from Zeus; '),(5149,'but herein dread grief cometh upon heart and soul, whenso a man is minded to rob one that is his equal, and take from him his prize, for that he surpasseth him in power.'),(5150,'  Dread grief is this to me, seeing I have suffered woes at heart.'),(5151,' The girl that the sons of the Achaeans chose out for me as a prize, and that I won with my spear, when I had laid waste a well-walled city, her hath lord Agamemnon taken back from my arms, this son of Atreus, as though I were some alien that had no rights.'),(5152,'  Howbeit these things will we let be, as past and done.'),(5153,' In no wise, meseems, was I to be filled with ceaseless wrath at heart;'),(5154,' yet verily I deemed that I should not make an end of mine anger, until the hour when unto mine own ships should come the war-cry and the battle. '),(5155,'But come, do thou put upon thy shoulders my glorious armour,  and lead forth the war-loving Myrmidons to the fight, if in good sooth the dark cloud of the Trojans lieth encompassed the ships mightily, and those others abide with naught to support them but the shore of the sea, having but scant space of land still left them, even the Argives; while the whole city of the Trojans hath come forth against them  fearlessly,'),(5156,'for they see not the front of my helm shining hard at hand; '),(5157,'full soon in their flight would they fill the water-courses with their dead, were but lord Agamemnon of kindly mind toward me, '),(5158,'whereas now they are warring around the camp. '),(5159,' For not in the hands of Diomedes, son of Tydeus,  doth the spear rage, to ward off ruin from the Danaans, '),(5160,'neither as yet have I heard the voice of the son of Atreus, shouting from his hated head; '),(5161,'nay, it is the voice of man-slaying Hector that breaketh about me, as he calleth to the Trojans, and they with their din possess all the plain, and vanquish the Achaeans in battle.'),(5162,'  Yet even so, Patroclus, in warding destruction from the ships fall thou upon them mightily, lest verily they burn the ships with blazing fire and rob the Greeks of their desired return. '),(5163,'Howbeit do thou hearken, that I may put in thy mind the sum of my counsel, to the end that thou mayest win me great recompense and glory  at the hands of all the Danaans, and that they send back that beauteous girl, and therewithal give glorious gifts.'),(5164,' When thou hast driven them from the ships, come back,'),(5165,' and if the loud-thundering lord of Hera grant thee to win glory, be not thou fain apart from me to war  against the war-loving Trojans:'),(5166,' thou wilt lessen mine honour.'),(5167,'Nor yet do thou, as thou exultest in war and conflict, and slayest the Trojans, lead on unto Ilios, lest one of the gods that are for ever shall come down from Olympus and enter the fray; '),(5168,'right dearly doth Apollo, that worketh afar, love them.'),(5169,'  Nay, return thou back, when once thou hast set a light of deliverance amid the ships, and suffer the rest to battle over the plain.'),(5170,' For I would, O father Zeus, and Athene, and Apollo, that no man of the Trojans might escape death, of all that there are, neither any of the Argives, but that we twain might escape destruction,  that alone we might loose the sacred diadem of Troy.\"'),(5171,'On this wise spake they one to the other, but Aias no longer abode,'),(5172,'\n for he was sore beset with darts; '),(5173,'the will of Zeus was overmastering him, and the lordly Trojans with their missiles;'),(5174,'and terribly did the bright helm about his temples  ring continually, as it was smitten, for smitten it ever was upon the well-wrought cheek-pieces, '),(5175,'and his left shoulder grew weary as he ever firmly held his flashing shield; '),(5176,'nor might they beat it back about him, for all they pressed him hard with darts. '),(5177,'And evermore was he distressed by laboured breathing,  and down from his limbs on every side abundant sweat kept streaming, nor had he any wise respite to get his breath withal, '),(5178,'but every way evil was heaped upon evil. '),(5179,' \nTell me now, ye Muses, that have dwellings on Olympus, how fire was first flung upon the ships of the Achaeans.'),(5180,'\nIt was Hector that drew nigh to Aias  and smote his ashen spear with his great sword hard by the socket, at the base ot the point, and shore it clean away, '),(5181,'so that Telamonian Aias brandished all vainly a pointless spear, and far from him the head of bronze fell ringing to the ground. '),(5182,'And Aias knew in his noble heart, and shuddered  at the deeds of the gods, how that Zeus, who thundereth on high, brought utterly to naught the counsels of his battle, and would have victory for the Trojans.'),(5183,'Then he gave ground from out the darts;'),(5184,'  and the Trojans cast upon the swift ship unwearied fire, '),(5185,' and over her forthwith streamed a flame that might not be quenched.'),(5186,' So then was the ship\'s stern wreathed about with fire,'),(5187,' but Achilles  smote both his thighs and spake to Patroclus:'),(5188,' \"Up now, Zeus-born Patroclus, master of horsemen. '),(5189,'Lo, I see by the ships the rush of consuming fire.'),(5190,' Let it not be that they take the ships and there be no more escaping!'),(5191,' Do on my armour with all haste, and I will gather the host.\"'),(5192,'  So spake he,and Patroclus arrayed him in gleaming bronze.'),(5193,' The greaves first he set about his legs; beautiful they were, and fitted with silver ankle-pieces; '),(5194,'next he did on about his chest the corselet of the swift-footed son of Aeacus, richly-wrought, and spangled with stars.'),(5195,'  And about his shoulders he cast the silver-studded sword of bronze, and thereafter the shield, great and sturdy; '),(5196,'and upon his mighty head he set the well-wrought helmet with horse-hair crest, '),(5197,'and terribly did the plume nod from above;'),(5198,'and he took two valorous spears, that fitted his grasp.'),(5199,'  Only the spear of the peerless son of Aeacus he took not, the spear heavy and huge and strong; '),(5200,' this none other of the Achaeans could wield, but Achilles alone was skilled to wield it, even the Pelian spear of ash, that Cheiron had given to his dear father from the peak of Pelion, to be for the slaying of warriors.'),(5201,'  And the horses he bade Automedon yoke speedily, even him that he honoured most after Achilles, breaker of the ranks of men, and that in his eyes was faithful above all to abide his call in battle.'),(5202,'At his bidding then Automedon led beneath the yoke the fleet horses, Xanthus and Balius, that flew swift as the winds, horses  that the Harpy Podarge conceived to the West Wind, as she grazed on the meadow beside the stream of Oceanus.'),(5203,' And in the side-traces he set the goodly Pedasus that on a time Achilles had brought away, when he took the city of Eetion; and he, being but mortal, kept pace with immortal steeds. '),(5204,' \n  But Achilles went to and fro throughout the huts and let harness in their armour all the Myrmidons, '),(5205,'and they rushed forth like ravening wolves in whose hearts is fury unspeakable—wolves that have slain in the hills a great horned stag, and rend him,'),(5206,' and the jaws of all are red with gore; '),(5207,' and in a pack they go to lap with their slender tongues the surface of the black water from a dusky spring, belching forth the while blood and gore, '),(5208,'  the heart in their breasts unflinching, and their bellies gorged full; '),(5209,'even in such wise the leaders and rulers of the Myrmidons sped forth  round about the valiant squire of the swift-footed son of Aeacus.'),(5210,' And among them all stood warlike Achilles, urging on both horses and men that bear the shield.'),(5211,'\nFifty were the swift ships which Achilles, dear to Zeus, led to Troy,'),(5212,' and in each ship at the thole-pins were fifty men, his comrades; '),(5213,'and five leaders had he appointed in whom he trusted to give command, '),(5214,'and himself in his great might was king over all.'),(5215,'The one rank was led by Menesthius of the flashing corselet, son of Spercheius, the heaven-fed river.'),(5216,'  Him did fair Polydora, daughter of Peleus, bear to tireless Spercheius, a woman couched with a god, but in name she bare him to Borus, son of Perieres, who openly wedded her, when he had given gifts of wooing past counting.'),(5217,'And of the next company warlike Eudorus was captain,  the son of a girl unwed, and him did Polymele, fair in the dance, daughter of Phylas, bear.'),(5218,' Of her the strong Argeiphontes became enamoured, when his eyes had sight of her amid the singing maidens, in the dancing-floor of Artemis, huntress of the golden arrows and the echoing chase. '),(5219,'Forthwith then he went up into her upper chamber, and lay with her secretly,  even Hermes the helper, and she gave him a goodly son, Eudorus, pre-eminent in speed of foot and as a warrior.'),(5220,'But when at length Eileithyia, goddess of child-birth, had brought him to the light, and he saw the rays of the sun, then her did the stalwart and mighty Echecles, son of Actor,  lead to his home, when he had given countless gifts of wooing, and Eudorus did old Phylas nurse and cherish tenderly, loving him dearly, as he had been his own son.'),(5221,' And of the third company warlike Peisander was captain, son of Maemalus, a man pre-eminent among all the Myrmidons  in fighting with the spear, after the comrade of the son of Peleus.'),(5222,'And the fourth company did the old knight Phoenix lead, and the fifth Alcimedon, the peerless son of Laerces.'),(5223,' But when at length Achilles had set them all in array with their leaders, duly parting company from company, he laid upon them a stern command: '),(5224,' \n  \"Myrmidons, let no man, I bid you, be forgetful of the threats, wherewith heside the swift ships ye threatened the Trojans throughout all the time of my wrath, and upbraided me, each man of you, saying:\"'),(5225,'Cruel son of Peleus, surely it was on gall that thy mother reared thee, thou pitiless one, seeing that in their own despite thou holdest back thy comrades beside the ships.'),(5226,'  Nay, homeward let us return again with our seafaring ships, since in this wise evil wrath hath fallen upom thy heart.\"'),(5227,' With such words would ye ofttimes gather together and prate at me,'),(5228,' but now is set before you a great work of war, whereof in time past ye were enamoured.'),(5229,' Therefore let it be with valiant heart that each man fights with the Trojans.\"'),(5230,' So saying, he aroused the strength and spirit of every man, '),(5231,'and yet closer were their ranks serried when they heard their king.'),(5232,' And as when a man buildeth the wall of a high house with close-set stones, to avoid the might of the winds, even so close were arrayed their helms and bossed shields; '),(5233,' buckler pressed on buckler, helm upon helm, and man on man.'),(5234,' The horse-hair crests on the bright helmet-ridges touched each other, as the men moved their heads, in such close array stood they one by another.'),(5235,' And in the front of all two warriors arrayed themselves for war, even Patroclus and Automedon, both of one mind,  to war in the forefront of the Myrmidons.'),(5236,'But Achilles went into his hut, and opened the lid of a chest, fair and richly-dight, that silver-footed Thetis had set on his ship for him to carry with him, whem she had filled it well with tunics, and cloaks to keep off the wind, and woollen rugs.'),(5237,'  Therein had he a fair-fashioned cup, wherefrom neither was any other man wont to drink the flaming wine, nor was he wont to pour drink offerings to any other of the gods save only to father Zeus.'),(5238,' This cup he then took from the chest and cleansed it first with sulphur, and thereafter washed it in fair streams of water;  and himself he washed his hands, and drew flaming wine. '),(5239,'Then he made prayer, standing in the midst of the court, and poured forth the wine, looking up to heaven; '),(5240,'and not unmarked was he of Zeus, that hurleth the thunderbolt:'),(5241,'\"Zeus, thou king, Dodonaean, Pelasgian, thou that dwellest afar, ruling over wintry Dodona,—and about thee dwell the Selli,  thine interpreters, men with unwashen feet that couch on the ground. Aforetime verily thou didst hear my word, when I prayed: me thou didst honour, and didst mightily smite the host of the Achaeans; even so now also fulfill thou for me this my desire.'),(5242,'Myself verily will I abide in the gathering of the ships,  but my comrade am I sending forth amid the host of the Myrmidons to war:'),(5243,' with him do thou send forth glory, O Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, and make bold the heart in his breast, to the end that Hector, too, may know whether even alone my squire hath skill to fight, or whether his hands  then only rage invincible, whenso I enter the turmoil of Ares. '),(5244,'But when away from the ships he hath driven war and the din of war, thea all-unscathed let him come back to the swift ships with all his arms, and his comrades that fight in close combat.\" '),(5245,' \nSo spake he in prayer, and Zeus, the counsellor, heard him, '),(5246,' and a part the Father granted him, and a part denied. '),(5247,'That Patroclus should thrust back the war and battle from the ships he granted; but that he should return safe from out the battle he denied.'),(5248,'Achilles then, when he had poured libation and made prayer to father Zeus, went again into his tent, and laid the cup away in the chest, and came forth and  stood in front of the hut; for still his heart was fain to look upon the dread conflict of Trojans and Achaeans.'),(5249,'\nBut they that were arrayed together with great-hearted Patroclus marched forth, until with high spirits they leapt upon the Trojans.'),(5250,'Straightway they poured forth like wasps  of the wayside, that boys are wont to stir to wrath, ever tormenting them in their nests beside the way, foolish that they are; '),(5251,' and a common evil they make for many.'),(5252,' And the wasps, if so be some wayfaring ran as he passeth by rouse them unwittingly,  fly forth one and all in the valour of their hearts, and fight each in defence of his young; '),(5253,' having a heart and spirit like theirs the Myrmidons then poured forth from the ships, '),(5254,' and a cry unquenchable arose.'),(5255,' But Patroclus called to his comrades with a loud shout:'),(5256,'\"Myrmidons, ye comrades of Achilles, son of Peleus,  be men, my friends, and bethink you of furious valour, to the end that we may win honour for the son of Peleus, that is far the best of the Argives by the ships, himself and his squires that fight in close combat; and that the son of Atreus, wide-ruling Agamemnon, may know his blindness in that he honoured not at all the best of the Achaeans.\"'),(5257,'\n  So saying, he roused the strength and spirit of every man, and on the Trojans they fell all in a throng, '),(5258,'and round about them the ships echoed wondrously beneath the shouting of the Achaeans.'),(5259,' But when the Trojans saw the valiant son of Menoetius, himself and his squire, shining in their armour,  the heart of each man was stirred, and their battalions were shaken, for they deemed that by the ships the swift-footed son of Peleus had cast aside his wrath and had chosen friendliness; '),(5260,'and each man gazed about to see how he might escape utter destruction. '),(5261,' \nThen Patroclus was first to cast with his bright spear  straight into the midst where men thronged the thickest, even by the stern of the ship of great-souled Protesilaus, and smote Pyraechmes, that had led the Paeonians, lords of chariots, out of Amydon, from the wide-flowing Axius.'),(5262,' Him he smote on the right shoulder, '),(5263,' and backward in the dust he fell with a groan, and about him his comrades were driven in rout, even the Paeonians,'),(5264,'for upon them all had Patroclus sent panic, when he slew their leader that was pre-eminent in fight.'),(5265,' From out the ships then he drave them, and quenched the blazing fire.'),(5266,' And half-burnt the ship was left there,'),(5267,'  but the Trojans were driven in rout with a wondrous din, '),(5268,'and the Danaans poured in among the hollow ships, '),(5269,'and a ceaseless din arose. '),(5270,'And as when from the high crest of a great mountain Zeus, that gathereth the lightnings, moveth a dense cloud away, and forth to view appear all mountain peaks, and high headlands,  and glades, and from heaven breaketh open the infinite air; even so the Danaans, when they had thrust back from the ships consuming fire, had respite for a little time; howbeit there was no ceasing from war.'),(5271,' For not yet were the Trojans driven in headlong rout by the Achaeans, dear to Ares, from the black ships,  but still they sought to withstand them, and gave ground from the ships perforce. '),(5272,' \nThen man slew man of the chieftains as the fight was scattered.'),(5273,' First the valiant son of Menoetius smote the thigh of Areilycus with a cast of his sharp spear at the moment when he turned to flee, and drave the bronze clean through; '),(5274,' and the spear brake the bone, and he fell on his face on the ground.'),(5275,' And warlike Menelaus thrust and smote Thoas on the breast, where it was left bare beside the shield, and loosed his limbs.'),(5276,' And the son of Phyleus as he watched Amphiclus that was rushing upon him, proved quicker than his foe, and smote him upon the base of the leg, where  a man\'s muscle is thickest; '),(5277,'and round about the spear-point the sinews were rent apart;'),(5278,' and darkness enfolded his eyes. '),(5279,' Then of the sons of Nestor, the one, Antilochus, thrust at Atymnius with his sharp spear, and drave the spear of bronze through his flank; '),(5280,'and he fell forward.'),(5281,'But Maris, hard at hand,  rushed upon Antilochus with his spear, wroth for his brother\'s sake, and took his stand before the dead;'),(5282,'howbeit godlike Thrasymedes was too quick for him, and forthwith ere his foe could thrust, smote upon his shoulder, and missed not; '),(5283,'but the point of the spear shore the base of the arm away from the muscles, and utterly brake asunder the bone; '),(5284,' and he fell with a thud, and darkness enfolded his eyes.'),(5285,'So these twain, overcome by twain brethren, went their way to Erebus, goodly comrades of Sarpedon, spearmen sons of Araisodarus, him that reared the raging Chimaera, a bane to many men.'),(5286,'  And Aias, son of Oileus, leapt upon Cleobulus, and caught him alive, entangled in the throng; '),(5287,'but even there he loosed his might, smiting him upon the neck with his hilted sword.'),(5288,' Thereat all the blade grew warm with his blood,'),(5289,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 16.333-16.334'),(5290,'and down over his eyes came dark death and mighty fate. ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 333 to line 334'),(5291,'for with their spears either had missed the other, and both had cast in vain; '),(5292,'but again they rushed together with their swords.'),(5293,'Then Lyco let drive upon the horn of the helm with horse-hair crest, and the sword was shattered at the hilt; '),(5294,' but Peneleos smote him upon the neck beneath the ear, and all the blade sank in, so that naught but the skin held fast, and the head hung to one side, and his limbs were loosed.'),(5295,' And Meriones with swift strides overtook Acamas, and thrust and smote him, even as he was mounting his car, upon the right shoulder; '),(5296,'and he fell from his car and down over his eyes a mist was shed.'),(5297,'  Then Idomeneus smote Erymas upon the mouth with a thrust of the pitiless bronze, '),(5298,'and clean through passed the spear of bronze beneath the brain, and clave asunder the white bones;'),(5299,' and his teeth were shaken out, and both his eyes were filled with blood;'),(5300,'and up through mouth and nostrils he spurted blood as he gaped, '),(5301,'  and a black cloud of death enfolded him.'),(5302,' \nThese, then, leaders of the Damans, slew each his man.'),(5303,' And as murderous wolves fall upon lambs or kids, choosing them from out the flocks, when through the witlessness of the shepherd they are scattered among the mountains,'),(5304,'and the wolves seeing it,  forthwith harry the young whose hearts know naught of valour; '),(5305,'even so the Damans fell upon the Trojans, '),(5306,'and they bethougnt them of ill-sounding flight, and forgat their furious valour.'),(5307,'\nAnd the great Aias was ever fain to cast his spear at Hector, harnessed in bronze,'),(5308,'but he in his cunning of war, his broad shoulders  covered with shield of bull\'s-hide, ever watched the whirring of arrows and the hurtling of spears.'),(5309,' In sooth he knew the tide of victory was turning, '),(5310,'but even so he abode, and sought to save his trustv comrades.'),(5311,'And as when from Olympus a cloud fareth toward heaven  out of the bright air, when Zeus spreadeth forth the tempest, even so from the ships came the shouting and the rout of these; nor was it in good order that they crossed the trench again.'),(5312,' Hector verily did his swift-footed horses bear forth with his battle-gear, and he left tbe hosts of Troy, whom the digged trench held back against their will.'),(5313,'  And in the trench many pairs of swift horses, drawers of chariots, brake the pole at the end, and left the chariots of their lords. But Patroclus followed after, calling fiercely to the Danaans, with purpose of evil toward the Trojans,'),(5314,'while they with shouting and in flight filled all the ways, now that their ranks were broken; '),(5315,' and on high a cloud of dust was spread up beneath the clouds, and the single-hoofed horses strained back toward the city from the ships and the huts.'),(5316,' And Patroclus, wheresoever he saw the greatest throng huddled in rout, thither would with shouting; '),(5317,'and beneath his axle-trees men kept falling headlong from their cars, and the chariots were overturned. '),(5318,'  And straight over the trench leapt the swift horses—the immortal horses that the gods gave as glorious gifts to Peleus—in their onward flight, and against Hector did the heart of Patroclus urge him on, '),(5319,' but his swift horses ever bare Hector forth.'),(5320,' but his swift horses ever bare Hector forth.'),(5321,'And even as beneath a tempest the whole black earth is oppressed,  on a day in harvest-time, when Zeus poureth forth rain most violently, whenso in anger he waxeth wroth against men that by violence give crooked judgments in the place of gathering, and drive justice out, recking not of the vengeance of the gods;'),(5322,'and all their rivers flow in flood,  and many a hillside do the torrents furrow deeply, and down to the dark sea they rush headlong from the mountains with a mighty roar, and the tilled fields of men are wasted; '),(5323,'even so mighty was the roar of the mares of Troy as they sped on. '),(5324,' \nBut when Patroclus had cut off the foremost battalions, he hemmed them  back again towards the ships and would not suffer them for all their eagerness to set foot in the city, but in the mid-space between the ships and the river and the high wall he rushed among them and slew them, and got him vengeance for many a slain comrade.'),(5325,' There verily he first smote Pronous with a cast of his bright spear,  upon the breast where it was left bare beside the shield, and loosed his limbs; '),(5326,'and he feIl with a thud.'),(5327,' Next upon Thestor, son of Enops, he rushed.'),(5328,' Crouching he sat in his polished car, '),(5329,'for his wits were distraught with terror, and the reins had slipped from his hands, '),(5330,'but Patroclus drew nigh to him, and smote him  upon the right jaw with his spear, and drave it through his teeth; and he laid hold of the spear and dragged him over the chariot-rim, as when a man sitting upon a jutting rock draggeth to land a sacred fish from out the sea, with line and gleaming hook of bronze; '),(5331,'even so on the bright spear dragged he him agape from out the car,  and cast him down upon his face; '),(5332,'and life left him as he fell.'),(5333,' Then as Erylaus rushed upon him, he smote him full upon the head with a stone,'),(5334,' and his head was wholly cloven asunder within the heavy helmet; '),(5335,'and he fell headlong upon the earth, and death, that slayeth the spirit, was shed about him.'),(5336,'  Thereafter Erymas and Amphoterus, and Epaltes, and Tlepolemus, son of Damastor, and Echius and Pyris, and Ipheus and Evippus, and Polymelus, son of Argeas, all these one after another he brought down to the bounteous earth.'),(5337,'But when Sarpedon saw his comrades, that wear the tunic ungirt,  being laid low beneath the hands of Patroclus, son of Menoetius, he called aloud, upbraiding the godlike Lycians:'),(5338,' Now be ye swift to fight;'),(5339,' Now be ye swift to fight;'),(5340,' Now be ye swift to fight;'),(5341,' for I myself will meet this man, that I may know who he is that prevaileth here, and verily hath wrought the Trojans much mischief,  seeing he hath loosed the knees of many men and goodly.\"'),(5342,'He spake, and leapt in his armour from his chariot to the ground.'),(5343,' And Patroclus, over against him, when he beheld him, sprang from his chariot.'),(5344,' And as vultures crooked of talon and curved of beak fight with loud cries upom a high rock,  even so with cries rushed they one against the other.'),(5345,' And the son of crooked-counselling Cronos took pity when he saw them, and spake to Hera, his sister and his wife:\"'),(5346,'Ah, woe is me, for that it is fated that Sarpedon, dearest of men to me, be slain by Patroclus, son of Menoetius!'),(5347,'  And in twofold wise is my heart divided in counsel as I ponder in my thought whether I shall snatch him up while yet he liveth and set him afar from the tearful war in the rich land of Lycia, or whether I shall slay him now beneath the hands of the son of Menoetius.\" '),(5348,' \nThen ox-eyed queenly Hera answered him: '),(5349,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 16.440'),(5350,' \"Most dread son of Cronos, what a word hast thou said! ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 440 to line 440'),(5351,'but be sure that we other gods assent not all thereto.'),(5352,'but be sure that we other gods assent not all thereto.'),(5353,' And another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart:'),(5354,'  if thou send Sarpedon living to his house, bethink thee lest hereafter some other god also be minded to send his own dear son away from the fierce conflict; '),(5355,'for many there be fighting around the great city of Priam that are sons of the immortals, and among the gods wilt thou send dread wrath.'),(5356,'  But and if he be dear to thee, and thine heart be grieved, suffer thou him verily to be slain in the fierce conflict beneath the hands of Patroclus, son of Menoetius; '),(5357,'but when his soul and life have left him, then send thou Death and sweet Sleep to bear him away  until they come to the land of wide Lycia; and there shall his brethren and his kinsfolk give him burial with mound and pillar; '),(5358,'for this is the due of the dead.\"'),(5359,'So spake she, and the father of men and gods failed to hearken.'),(5360,'Howbeit he shed bloody rain-drops on the earth,  shewing honour to his dear son—his own son whom Patroclus was about to slay in the deep-soiled land of Troy, far from his native land.'),(5361,'\nNow when they were come near, as they advanced one against the other, then verily did Patroclus smite glorious Thrasymelus, that was the valiant squire of the prince Sarpedon;  him he smote on the lower belly, and loosed his limbs. '),(5362,'But Sarpedon missed him with his bright spear, as in turn he got upon him, but smote with his spear the horse Pedasus on the right shoulder; '),(5363,'and the horse shrieked aloud as he gasped forth his life, and down he fell in the dust with a moan, and his spirit flew from him.'),(5364,'  But the other twain reared this way and that, and the yoke creaked, and above them the reins were entangled, when the trace-horse lay low in the dust.'),(5365,' Howbeit for this did Automedon, famed for his spear, find him a remedy; '),(5366,'drawing his long sword from beside his stout thigh, he sprang forth and cut loose the trace-horse, and faltered not, '),(5367,' and the other two were righted, and strained at the reins; '),(5368,'and the two warriors came together again in soul-devouring strife. '),(5369,' \nThen again Sarpedon missed with his bright spear, and over the left shoulder of Patroclus went the point of the spear and smote him not. '),(5370,' But Patroclus in turn rushed on with the bronze, '),(5371,'and not in vain did the shaft speed from his hand, but smote his foe where the midriff is set close about the throbbing heart.'),(5372,' And he fell as an oak falls, or a poplar, or a tall pine, that among the mountains shipwrights fell with whetted axes to be a ship\'s timber;'),(5373,' even so before his horses and chariot he lay outstretched, moaning aloud and clutching at the bloody dust. '),(5374,' And as a lion cometh into the midst of a herd and slayeth a bull, tawny and high of heart amid the kine of trailing gait, and with a groan he perisheth beneath the jaws of the lion;  even so beneath Patroclus did the leader of the Lycian shieldmen struggle in death; and he called by name his dear comrade:'),(5375,' \"Dear Glaucus, warrior amid men of war, now in good sooth it behoveth thee to quit thee as a spearman and a dauntless warrior; '),(5376,' now be evil war thy heart\'s desire if indeed thou art swift to fight.'),(5377,'  First fare thou up and down everywhere, and urge on the leaders of the Lycians to fight for Sarpedon,'),(5378,' and thereafter thyself do battle with the bronze in my defence.'),(5379,'For to thee even in time to come shall I be a reproach and a hanging of the head, all thy days continually,  if so be the Achaeans shall spoil me of my armour, now that I am fallen amid the gathering of the ships.'),(5380,' Nay, hold thy ground valiantly, and urge on all the host.\"'),(5381,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 16.502-16.503'),(5382,'\nEven as he thus spake the end of death enfolded him, his eyes alike and his nostrils; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 502 to line 503'),(5383,' and at the one moment he drew forth the spear-point and the soul of Sarpedon. '),(5384,'And the Myrmidons stayed there the snorting horses, that were fain to flee now that they had left the chariot of their lords. '),(5385,' \nBut upon Glaucus came dread grief as he heard the voice of Sarpedon,'),(5386,'and his heart was stirred, for that he availed not to succour him.'),(5387,' And with his hand he caught and pressed his arm,'),(5388,' for his wound tormented him, the wound that Teucer, while warding off destruction from his comrades, had dealt him with his arrow as he rushed upon the high wall.'),(5389,' Then in prayer he spake to Apollo, that smiteth afar:'),(5390,'\"Hear me, O king that art haply in the rich land of Lycia  or haply in Troy, '),(5391,'but everywhere hast power to hearken unto a man that is in sorrow, even as now sorrow is come upon me. '),(5392,'For I have this grievous wound and mine arm on this side and on that is shot through with sharp pangs, nor can the blood be staunched; and my shoulder is made heavy with the wound, '),(5393,' and I avail not to grasp my spear firmly, neither to go and fight with the foe-men.'),(5394,'And a man far the noblest hath perished, even Sarpedon, the son of Zeus;'),(5395,'  and he succoureth not his own child.'),(5396,'Howbeit, do thou, O king, heal me of this grievous wound, and lull my pains, and give me might,  that I may call to my comrades, the Lycians, and urge them on to fight, and myself do battle about the body of him that is fallen in death.\"'),(5397,'\nSo spake he in prayer, and Phoebus Apollo heard him.'),(5398,' Forthwith he made his pains to cease, and staunched the black blood that flowed from his grievous wound, and put might into his heart.'),(5399,'  And Glaucus knew in his mind, and was glad that the great god had quickly heard his prayer.'),(5400,' First fared he up and down everywhere and urged on the leaders of the Lycians to fight for Sarpedon, '),(5401,'and thereafter went with long strides into the midst of the Trojans,  unto Polydamas, son of Panthous, and goodly Agenor, and he went after Aeneas, and after Hector, harnessed in bronze. And he came up to him and spake winged words, saying:\"'),(5402,'Hector, now in good sooth art thou utterly forgetful of the allies, that for thy sake far from their friends and their native land  are wasting their lives away, '),(5403,'yet thou carest not to aid them.'),(5404,' Low lies Sarpedon, leader of the Lycian shieldmen, he that guarded Lycia by his judgments and his might.'),(5405,' Him hath brazen Ares laid low beneath the spear of Patroclus. '),(5406,'Nay, friends, take your stand beside him, and have indignation in heart,  lest the Myrmidons strip him of his armour and work shame upon his corpse, being wroth for the sake of all the Danaans that have perished, whom we slew with our spears at the swift ships.\" '),(5407,' \nSo spake he, and the Trojans were utterly seized with grief, unbearable, overpowering; for Sarpedon  was ever the stay of their city, albeit he was a stranger from afar; '),(5408,'for much people followed with him, and among them he was himself pre-eminent in fight.'),(5409,' And they made straight for the Danaans full eagerly,'),(5410,'and Hector led them, in wrath for Sarpedon\'s sake.'),(5411,' But the Achaeans were urged on by Patroclus, of the shaggy heart, son of Menoetius.'),(5412,'  To the twain Aiantes spake he first, that were of themselves full eager:'),(5413,' \"Ye twain Aiantes, now be it your will to ward off the foe, being of such valour as of old ye were amid warriors, or even braver.'),(5414,' Low lies the man that was first to leap within the wall of the Achaeans, even Sarpedon.'),(5415,'Nay, let us seek to take him, and work shame upon his body,  and strip the armour from his shoulders, and many a one of his comrades that seek to defend his body let us slay with the pitiless bronze.\"'),(5416,'\nSo spake he, and they even of themselves were eager to ward off the foe. '),(5417,'Then when on both sides they had made strong their battalions, the Trojans and Lycians, and the Myrmidons and Achaeans,  they joined battle to fight for the body of him that was fallen in death, with terrible shouting;'),(5418,'and loud rang the harness of men.'),(5419,' And Zeus drew baneful night over the mighty conflict, that around his dear son might be waged the baneful toil of war. '),(5420,' \nAnd first the Trojans drave back the bright-eyed Achaeans, '),(5421,'  for smitten was a man in no wise the worst among the Myrmidons, even the son of great-souled Agacles, goodly Epeigeus, that was king in well-peopled Budeum of old, '),(5422,' but when he had slain a goodly man of his kin, to Peleus he came as a suppliant, and to silver-footed Thetis; '),(5423,' and they sent him to follow with Achilles, breaker of the ranks of men, to Ilios, famed for its horses, that he might fight with the Trojans.'),(5424,' Him, as he was laying hold of the corpse, glorious Hector smote upon the head with a stone; '),(5425,'and his head was wholly cloven asunder within the heavy helmet, '),(5426,' and he fell headlong upon the corpse, and death, that slayeth the spirit, was shed about him.'),(5427,'Then over Patroclus came grief for his slain comrade, and he charged through the foremost fighters like a fleet falcon that driveth in flight daws and starlings; '),(5428,' even so straight against the Lycians, O Patroclus, master of horsemen,  and against the Trojans didst thou charge, and thy heart was full of wrath for thy comrade. '),(5429,'And he smote Sthenelaus, the dear son of Ithaemenes, on the neck with a stone, and brake away therefrom the sinews; '),(5430,' and the foremost fighters and glorious Hector gave ground.'),(5431,'Far as is the flight of a long javelin,  that a man casteth, making trial of his strength, in a contest, haply, or in war beneath the press of murderous foemen, even so far did the Trojans draw back, and the Achaeans drave them.'),(5432,'And Glaucus first, the leader of the Lycian shieldmen, turned him about, and slew great-souled Bathycles,  the dear son of Chalcon, him that had his abode in Hellas, and for wealth and substance was pre-eminent among the Myrmidons.'),(5433,' Him did Glaucus smite full upon the breast with a thrust of his spear, turning suddenly upon rum, when the other was about to overtake him in pursuit.'),(5434,' And he fell with a thud,'),(5435,' and sore grief gat hold of the Achaeans,  for that a good man was fallen; '),(5436,'but mightily did the Trojans rejoice. And they came in throngs and took their stand about him,'),(5437,' nor did the Achaeans forget their valour, but bare their might straight toward the foe.'),(5438,' Then Meriones slew a warrior of the Trojans, in full armour, Laogonus, the bold son of Onetor,  one that was priest of Idaean Zeus, and was honoured of the folk even as a god:'),(5439,' him he smote beneath the jaw under the ear,'),(5440,' and forthwith his spirit departed from his limbs, and hateful darkness gat hold of hinu.'),(5441,' And Aeneas cast at Meriones his spear of bronze,'),(5442,' for he hoped to smite him as he advanced under cover of his shield.'),(5443,'  But Meriones, looking steadily at him, avoided the spear of bronze;'),(5444,' for he stooped forward, and the long spear fixed itself in the ground behind him, and the butt of the spear quivered; '),(5445,'howbeit there at length did mighty Ares stay its fury.'),(5446,'  [so that the vibrant shaft of Aineias was driven groundward, since it had been thrown in a vain cast from his big hand].'),(5447,' Then Aeneas waxed wroth at heart, and spake, saying:\"'),(5448,'Meriones, full soon, for all thou art a nimble dancer, would my spear have made thee to cease dancing for ever, had I but struck thee.\" '),(5449,' \nAnd Meriones, famed for his spear, made answer:'),(5450,'  \"Aeneas, hard were it for thee, valiant though thou art, to quench the might of every man, whosoever cometh against thee to rake defence.'),(5451,' Of mortal stuff, I ween, art thou as well.'),(5452,' If so be I should cast, and smite thee fairly with my sharp spear, quickly then, for all thou art strong and trustest in thy hands,  shouldst thou yield glory to me, and thy soul to Hades of the goodly steeds.\"'),(5453,'So spake he, but the valiant son of Menoetius rebuked him, saying:'),(5454,' \"Meriones, wherefore dost thou, that art a man of valour, speak on this wise?'),(5455,' Good friend, it is not for words of reviling that the Trojans will give ground from the corpse;'),(5456,'ere that shall the earth hold many a one.'),(5457,'  For in our hands is the issue of war; that of words is in the council.'),(5458,' Wherefore it beseemeth not in any wise to multiply words, but to fight.\"'),(5459,'So saying, he led the way, and the other followed, a godlike man.'),(5460,'And from them—even as the din ariseth of woodcutters in the glades of a mountain, and afar is the sound thereof heard—  so from them went up a clanging from the broad-wayed earth, a clanging of bronze and of hide and of well-wrought shields, as they thrust one at the other with swords and two-edged spears.'),(5461,' Nor could a man, though he knew him well, any more have discerned goodly Sarpedon, for that he was utterly enwrapped with darts and blood and dust,  from his head to the very soles of his feet. '),(5462,'And they ever thronged about the corpse as when in a farmstead flies buzz about the full milk-pails, in the season of spring, when the milk drenches the vessels;'),(5463,'even so thronged they about the corpse. Nor did Zeus anywise  turn his bright eyes from the fierce conflict, but ever looked down upon them, and debated in heart, pondering much about the slaying of Patroclus, whether in the fierce conflict even there over godlike Sarpedon, glorious Hector  should slay him likewise with the sword, and should strip the armour from his shoulders, or whether for yet more men he should make the utter toil of war to wax.'),(5464,' And as he pondered, this thing seemed to him the better, that the valiant squire of Achilles, Peleus\' son,  should again drive toward the city the Trojans and Hector, harnessed in bronze, and take the lives of many.'),(5465,'In Hector first of all he roused cowardly rout,'),(5466,' and he leapt upon his car and turned to flight, and called on the rest of the Trojans to flee; '),(5467,'for he knew the turning of the sacred scales of Zeus. '),(5468,' Then the valiant Lycians likewise abode not, but were driven in rout  one and all, when they saw their king smitten to the heart, lying in the gathering of the dead;'),(5469,'for many had fallen above him, when the son of Cronos strained taut the cords of the fierce conflict.'),(5470,' But from the shoulders of Sarpedon they stripped his shining harness of bronze,  and this the valiant son of Menoetius gave to his comrades to bear to the hollow ships. '),(5471,'And then unto Apollo spake Zeus, the cloud-gatherer:'),(5472,' \"Up now, dear Phoebus, go cleanse from Sarpedon the dark blood, when thou hast taken him forth from out the range of darts, and thereafter bear thou him far away, and bathe him in the streams of the river,  and anoint him with ambrosia, and clothe him about with immortal raiment, '),(5473,'and give him to swift conveyers to bear with them, even to the twin brethren, Sleep and Death, who shall set him speedily in the rich land of wide Lycia. There shall his brethren and his kinsfolk give him burial  with mound and pillar;'),(5474,' for this is the due of tne dead.\"'),(5475,'So spake he, nor was Apollo disobedient to his father\'s bidding,'),(5476,' but went down from the hills of Ida into the dread din of battle. Forthwith then he lifted up goodly Sarpedon forth from out the range of darts, and when he had borne him far away, bathed him in the streams of the river,  and anointed him with ambrosia, and clothed him about with immortal raiment,'),(5477,'and gave him to swift conveyers to bear with them, even to the twin brethren, Sleep and Death, who set him speedily in the rich land of wide Lycia.'),(5478,'But Patroclus with a call to his horses and to Automedon,  pressed after the Trojans and Lycians, and was greatly blinded in heart, fool that he was!'),(5479,'for had he observed the word of the son of Peleus, he would verily have escaped the evil fate of black death.'),(5480,'But ever is the intent of Zeus stronger than that of men,'),(5481,'for he driveth even a valiant man in rout, and robbeth him of victory  full easily, and again of himself he rouseth men to fight; '),(5482,'and he it was that now put fury in the breast of Patroclus.'),(5483,'\nThen whom first, whom last didst thou slay, Patroclus, when the gods called thee deathward? '),(5484,'\nAdrastus first, and Autonous, and Echeclus,  and Perimus, son of Megas, and Epistor, and Melanippus, and thereafter Elasus, and Mulius, and Pylartes:'),(5485,'and the others bethought them each man of flight. '),(5486,'and the others bethought them each man of flight. '),(5487,' \nThen would the sons of the Achaeans have taken high-gated Troy by the hands of Patroclus, for around and before him he raged with his spear,  had not Phoebus Apollo taken his stand upon the well-builded wall thinking thoughts of bane for him, but bearing aid to the Trojans.'),(5488,' Thrice did Patroclus set foot upon a corner of the high wall, and thrice did Apollo fling him back, thrusting against the bright shield with his immortal hands.'),(5489,'  But when for the fourth time he rushed on like a god, then with a terrible cry Apollo spake to him winged words:'),(5490,' \"Give back, Zeus-born Patroclus.'),(5491,' It is not fated, I tell thee, that by thy spear the city of the lordly Trojans shall be laid waste, nay, nor by that of Achilles, who is better far than thou.\"'),(5492,'\n  So spake he, and Patroclus gave ground a great space backward, avoiding the wrath of Apollo that smiteth afar.'),(5493,'\nBut Hector at the Scaean gate was staying his single-hoofed horses,'),(5494,'for he was divided in mind, whether he should drive again into the turmoil and do battle, or should call to the host to gather them within the wall.'),(5495,'  And while he pondered thus there drew nigh to him Phoebus Apollo in the likeness of a young man and a strong, even of Asius, that was uncle to horse-taming Hector, and own brother to Hecabe, but son of Dymas, that dwelt in Phrygia by the streams of Sangarius.'),(5496,'  In his likeness spake Apollo, the son of Zeus, unto Hector:'),(5497,'It beseemeth thee not.'),(5498,'It beseemeth thee not.'),(5499,'  I would that I were as much stronger than thou as I am weaker;'),(5500,'then straightway would it be to thine own hurt that thou drawest back from the war.'),(5501,' Nay, come, drive against Patroclus thy strong-hoofed horses, you might be able to kill him. Apollo might give you such glory.\''),(5502,' \nSo spake he, and went back again, a god into the toil of men. Then unto wise-hearted Cebriones glorious Hector gave command to lash his horses into the battle.'),(5503,' But Apollo went his way, and entered into the throng, and sent an evil panic upon the Argives,  and vouchsafed glory to the Trojans and to Hector.'),(5504,' But Hector let be the other Danaans, neither sought to stay them,'),(5505,' but drave his strong-hoofed horses against Patroclus; '),(5506,' and Patroclus over against him leapt from his chariot to the ground with a spear in his left hand, '),(5507,' while with the other he grasped a stone, shining and jagged, that his hand compassed about. Firmly he planted himself, and hurled it, neither had he long awe of his foe, nor sped he his missile in vain, but smote the charioteer of Hector, even Cebriones, a bastard son of glorious Priam, upon the forehead with the sharp stone, as he was holding the reins of the horses.'),(5508,'  And both his brows did the stone dash together, and the bone held not, but the eyes fell to the ground in the dust even there, before his feet.'),(5509,' And like a diver he fell from the well-wrought car, and his spirit left his bones.'),(5510,' Then with mocking words didst thou speak to him, knight Patroclus:'),(5511,'  \"Hah, look you, verily nimble is the man; how lightly he diveth!'),(5512,' In sooth if he were on the teeming deep, this man would satisfy many by seeking for oysters, leaping from his ship were the sea never so stormy, seeing that now on the plain he diveth lightly from his car. '),(5513,' Verily among the Trojans too there be men that dive.\" '),(5514,'  So saying he made for the warrior Cebriones with the rush of a lion that, while he wasteth the farm-stead, hath been smitten on the breast, and his own valour bringeth him to ruin;'),(5515,' even so upon Cebriones, O Patroclus, didst thou leap furiously.'),(5516,'  And Hector over against him leapt from his chariot to the ground.'),(5517,' So the twain joined in strife for Cebriones like two lions, that on the peaks of a mountain fight for a slain hind, both of them hungering, both high of heart; '),(5518,' even so for Cebriones the two masters of the war-cry,  even Patroclus, son of Menoetius, and glorious Hector, were fain each to cleave the other\'s flesh with the pitiless bronze.'),(5519,' Hector, when once he had seized the corpse by the head, would not loose his hold,'),(5520,' and Patroclus over against him held fast hold of the foot; '),(5521,'and about them the others, Trojans and Danaans, joined in fierce conflict.'),(5522,'  And as the East Wind and the South strive with one another in shaking a deep wood in the glades of a mountain,—a wood of beech and ash and smooth-barked cornel, and these dash one against the other their long boughs with a wondrous din, and there is a crashing of broken branches;  even so the Trojans and Achaeans leapt one upon another and made havoc, nor would either side take thought of ruinous flight.'),(5523,' And round about Cebriones many sharp spears were fixed, and many winged arrows that leapt from the bow-string, and many great stones smote against shields, as men fought around him.'),(5524,'  But he in the whirl of dust lay mighty in his mightiness, forgetful of his horsemanship. '),(5525,' \nNow as long as the sun bestrode mid-heaven, so long the missiles of either side reached their mark, and the folk kept falling; '),(5526,'but when he turned to the time for the unyoking of oxen,  then verily beyond their portion the Achaeans proved the better.'),(5527,'Forth from out the range of darts they drew the warrior Cebriones from the battle-din of the Trojans, and stripped the armour from his shoulders; and Patroclus with fell intent leapt upon the Trojans.'),(5528,' Thrice then leapt he upon them, the peer of swift Ares,  crying a terrible cry, and thrice he slew nine men.'),(5529,'But when for the fourth time he rushed on, like a god, then for thee, Patroclus, did the end of life appear; '),(5530,'for Phoebus met thee in the fierce conflict, an awful god.'),(5531,' And Patroclus marked him not as he passed through the turmuoil,  for enfolded in thick mist did he meet him; '),(5532,'and Apollo took his stand behind him, and smote his back and broad shoulders with the flat of his hand, and his eyes were made to whirl.'),(5533,' And from his head Phoebus Apollo smote the helmet, '),(5534,'that rang as it rolled  beneath the feet of the horses—the crested helm; and the plumes were befouled with blood and dust.'),(5535,' Not until that hour had the gods suffered that helm with plume of horse-hair to be befouled with dust, but ever did it guard the head and comely brow of a godlike man, even of Achilles; '),(5536,'but then Zeus vouchsafed it to Hector,  to wear upon his head, yet was destruction near at hand for him.'),(5537,'And in the hands of Patroclus the far-shadowing spear was wholly broken, the spear, heavy, and huge, and strong, and tipped with bronze;'),(5538,'  and from his shoulders the tasselled shield with its baldric fell to the ground, '),(5539,' and his corselet did Apollo loose—the prince, the son of Zeus.'),(5540,'  Then blindness seized his mind, and his glorious limbs were loosed beneath him, and he stood in a daze;'),(5541,'and from behind him from close at hand a Dardanian smote him upon the back between the shoulders with a cast of his sharp spear, even Panthous\' son, Euphorbus, that excelled all men of his years in casting the spear, and in horsemanship, and in speed of foot; '),(5542,'and lo, twenty warriors had he already cast  from their cars at his first coming with his chariot to learn his lesson of war.'),(5543,' He it was that first hurled his spear at thee, knight Patroclus, yet subdued thee not; '),(5544,'but he ran back again and mingled with the throng, when he had drawn forth the ashen spear from the flesh, and he abode not  Patroclus, unarmed though he was, in the fray. '),(5545,' But Patroclus, overcome by the stroke of the god and by the spear, drew back into the throng of his comrades, avoiding fate. '),(5546,' \nBut Hector, when he beheld great-souled Patroclus drawing back, smitten with the sharp bronze,  came nigh him through the ranks, and smote him with a thrust of his spear in the nethermost belly, and drave the bronze clean through; '),(5547,' and he fell with a thud, and sorely grieved the host of the Achaeans.'),(5548,' And as a lion overmastereth in fight an untiring boar, when the twain fight with high hearts on the peaks of a mountain  for a scant spring,'),(5549,' wherefrom both are minded to drink:'),(5550,' hard panteth the boar, yet the lion overcometh him by his might;'),(5551,' even so from the valiant son of Menoetius, after he had slain many, did Hector, Priam\'s son, take life away, smiting him from close at hand with his spear. And vaunting over him he spake winged words:'),(5552,'  \"Patroclus, thou thoughtest, I ween, that thou wouldest sack our city, and from the women of Troy wouldest take the day of freedom, and bear them in thy ships to thy dear native land, thou fool.'),(5553,' Nay, in front of them the swift horses of Hector stride forth to the fight, '),(5554,' and with the spear I myself am pre-eminent among the war-loving Trojans, even I that ward from them the day of doom; '),(5555,'but for thee, vultures shall devour thee here. '),(5556,'Ah, poor wretch, even Achilles, for all his valour, availed thee not, who, I ween, though himself abiding behind, laid strait command upon thee, as thou wentest forth: '),(5557,'\"Come not back, I charge thee, Patroclus, master of horsemen,  to the hollow ships, till thou hast cloven about the breast of man-slaying Hector the tunic red with his blood.\"'),(5558,' So, I ween, spake he to thee, and persuaded thy wits in thy witlessness.\"'),(5559,'\nThen, thy strength all spent, didst thou answer him, knight Patroclus:'),(5560,' \"For this time, Hector, boast thou mightily; '),(5561,' for to thee have  Zeus, the son of Cronos, and Apollo, vouchsafed victory, they that subdued me full easily, '),(5562,'for of themselves they took the harness from my shoulders.'),(5563,' But if twenty such as thou had faced me, here would all have perished, slain by my spear.'),(5564,' Nay, it was baneful Fate and the son of Leto that slew me,  and of men Euphorbus, '),(5565,'while thou art the third in my slaying. '),(5566,'And another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart:'),(5567,' verily thou shalt not thyself be long in life, but even now doth death stand hard by thee, and mighty fate, that thou be slain beneath the hands of Achilles, the peerless son of Aeacus.\"'),(5568,'  Even as he thus spake the end of death enfolded him; '),(5569,'and his soul fleeting from his limbs was gone to Hades, bewailing her fate, leaving manliness and youth.'),(5570,' And to him even in his death spake glorious Hector:'),(5571,'\n\"Patroclus, wherefore dost thou prophesy for me sheer destruction?'),(5572,'  Who knows but that Achilles, the son of fair-tressed Thetis, may first be smitten by my spear, and lose his life?\"'),(5573,'\nSo saying, he drew forth the spear of bronze from the wound, setting his foot upon the dead, and thrust him backward from the spear.'),(5574,' And forthwith he was gone with his spear after Automedon, the god-like squire of the swift-footed son of Aeacus, '),(5575,'for he was fain to smite him; '),(5576,' but his swift horses bare him away, the immortal horses that the gods gave as glorious gifts to Peleus.'),(5577,' And the son of Atreus, Menelaus, dear to Ares, failed not to mark that Patroclus had been slain in battle by the Trojans, '),(5578,'but fared amid the foremost fighters, harnessed in flaming bronze, and bestrode the dead, as over a calf standeth lowing plaintively its mother, that hath brought forth  her first-born, ere then knowing naught of motherhood;'),(5579,'even so over Patroclus strode fair-haired Menelaus, '),(5580,'and before him he held his spear and his shield that was well-balanced upon every side, eager to slay the man who should come to seize the corpse.'),(5581,'\nThen was Panthous\' son, of the good spear of ash, not unheedful  of the falling of peerless Patroclus, '),(5582,'but he took his stand hard by him, and spake to Menelaus, dear to Ares:'),(5583,'\n \"Menelaus, son of Atreus, fostered of Zeus, thou leader of hosts, give back, and leave the corpse, and let be the bloody spoils; '),(5584,'for before me no man of the Trojans and their famed allies smote  Patroclus with the spear in the fierce conflict; '),(5585,'wherefore suffer thou me to win goodly renown among the Trojans, lest I cast and smite thee, and rob thee of honey-sweet life.\"'),(5586,'Then, his heart mightily stirred, fair-haired Menelaus spake unto him:'),(5587,' \"O father Zeus, no good thing is it to boast overweeningly.'),(5588,'  Verily neither is the spirit of pard so high, nor of lion, nor of wild boar, of baneful mind, in whose breast the greatest fury exulteth exceedingly in might, as is the spirit of Panthous\' sons, of the good spear of ash. '),(5589,'Nay, but in sooth even the mighty Hyperenor, tamer of horses,  had no profit of his youth, when he made light of me and abode my coming, and deemed that among the Danaans I was the meanest warrior; '),(5590,'not on his own feet, I ween, did he fare home to make glad his dear wife and his worthy parents.'),(5591,' Even so, meseems, shall I loose thy might as well,  if thou stand to face me;'),(5592,'nay, of myself I bid thee get thee back into the throng, and stand not forth to face me, ere yet some evil befall thee; '),(5593,'when it is wrought even a fool getteth understanding.\"'),(5594,'\n but he answered, saying: '),(5595,'\n but he answered, saying: '),(5596,'\"Now in good sooth, Menelaus, nurtured of Zeus,  shalt thou verily pay the price for my brother whom thou slewest, and over whom thou speakest vauntingly; and thou madest his wife a widow in her new-built bridal chamber, and broughtest grief unspeakable and sorrow upon his parents.'),(5597,' Verily for them in their misery should I prove an assuaging of grief, if I but bring thy head and thy armour  and lay them in the hands of Panthous and queenly Phrontis.'),(5598,' Howbeit not for long shall the struggle be untried or unfought, be it for victory or for flight.\" '),(5599,'So saying, he smote upon his shield that was well-balanced upon every side;'),(5600,'howbeit the bronze brake not through,  but its point was bent back in the stout shield.'),(5601,'Then in turn did Atreus\' son, Menelaus, rush upon him with his spear, and made prayer to father Zeus;'),(5602,'and as he gave back, stabbed him at the base of the throat, and put his weight into the thrust, trusting in his heavy hand; '),(5603,'and clean out through the tender neck passed the point.  And he fell with a thud, and upon him his armour clanged.'),(5604,'In blood was his hair drenched, that was like the hair of the Graces, and his tresses that were braided with gold and silver.'),(5605,' And as a man reareth a lusty sapling of an olive in a lonely place, where water welleth up abundantly—  a goodly sapling and a fair-growing; '),(5606,'and the blasts of all the winds make it to quiver, and it burgeoneth out with white blossoms;'),(5607,'but suddenly cometh the wind with a mighty tempest, and teareth it out of its trench, and layeth it low upon the earth; '),(5608,'even in such wise did  Menelaus, son of Atreus, slay Panthous\' son, Euphorbus of the good ashen spear, and set him to spoil him of his armour.'),(5609,'And as when a mountain-nurtured lion, trusting in his might, hath seized from amid a grazing herd the heifer that is goodliest:'),(5610,' her neck he seizeth first in his strong jaws, and breaketh it, and thereafter devoureth the blood and all the inward parts in his fury; '),(5611,' and round about him hounds and herds-men folk clamour loudly from afar, but have no will to come against him, '),(5612,'for pale fear taketh hold on them;'),(5613,'even so dared not the heart in the breast of any Trojan go to face glorious Menelaus.'),(5614,'  Full easily then would Atreus\' son have borne off the glorious armour of the son of Panthous, but that Phoebus Apollo begrudged it him, and in the likeness of a man, even of Mentes, leader of the Cicones, aroused against him Hector, the peer of swift Ares.'),(5615,' And he spake and addressed him in winged words:'),(5616,'  \"Hector, now art thou hasting thus vainly after what thou mayest not attain, even the horses of the wise-hearted son of Aeacus; '),(5617,'but hard are they for mortal men to master or to drive, save only for Achilles, whom an immortal mother bare. '),(5618,'Meanwhile hath warlike Menelaus, son of Atreus,  bestridden Patroclus, and slain the best man of the Trojans, even Panthous\' son, Euphorbus, and hath made him cease from his furious valour.\" '),(5619,' \nSo spake he, and went back again, a god into the toil of men. But the soul of Hector was darkly clouded with dread sorrow, '),(5620,'and he glanced then along the lines, and forthwith was ware of the one  stripping off the glorious arms, and of the other lying on the ground; '),(5621,'and the blood was flowing down from the stricken wound.'),(5622,' Then strode he forth amid the foremost fighters, harnessed in flaming bronze, crying a shrill cry, in fashion like unto the flame of Hephaestus that none may quench.'),(5623,' Nor was his shrill cry unheard of the son of Atreus, '),(5624,' but sore troubled he spake to his own great-hearted spirit: '),(5625,' \"Ah, woe is me! If I leave behind the goodly arms, and Patroclus, that here lieth low for that he would get me recompense, I fear lest many a Danaan wax wroth against me, whosoever beholdeth it.'),(5626,' But if for very shame I, that am alone, do battle with Hector and the Trojans,  I fear lest haply they beset me round about, many against one; '),(5627,'for all the Trojans is Hector of the flashing helm leading hitherward.'),(5628,' But why doth my heart thus hold converse with me?'),(5629,' Whenso a warrior is minded against the will of heaven to fight with another whom a god honoureth, forthwith then upon him rolleth mighty woe.'),(5630,'  Therefore shall no man of the Danaans wax wroth against me, whoso shall mark me giving ground before Hector, seeing he fighteth with the help of heaven.'),(5631,' But if I might anywhere find Aias, good at the war-cry, then might we twain turn back and bethink us of fight, even were it against the will of heaven, in hope to save the dead  for Achilles, Peleus\' son: '),(5632,'of ills that were the best.”'),(5633,' \n While he pondered thus in mind and heart, meanwhile the ranks of the Trojans came on, and Hector led them.'),(5634,'and Hector led them.'),(5635,' Then Menelaus gave ground backward, and left the corpse, ever turning him about like a bearded lion  that dogs and men drive from a fold with spears and shouting;'),(5636,'and the valiant heart in his breast groweth chill, and sore loth he fareth from the farmstead; '),(5637,'even so from Patroclus went fair-haired Menelaus. '),(5638,'But he turned him about and stood, when he reached the throng of his comrades,  glancing this way and that for great Aias, son of Telamon. '),(5639,'Him he marked full quickly on the left of the whole battle, heartening his comrades, and urging them on to fight, '),(5640,'for wondrous fear had Phoebus Apollo cast upon them. '),(5641,'And he set him to run, and straightway came up to him, and spake, saying:'),(5642,'  \"Aias, come hither, good friend, let us hasten in defence of the dead Patroclus, if so be we may bear forth his corpse at least to Achilles—his naked corpse; '),(5643,' but his armour is held by Hector of the flashing helm.\"'),(5644,'\nSo spake he, and stirred the soul of wise-hearted Aias,'),(5645,'and he strode amid the foremost fighters, and with him fair-haired Menelaus.'),(5646,'  Now Hector, when he had stripped from Patroclus his glorious armour, sought to hale him away that he might cut the head from off his shoulders with the sharp bronze, and drag off the corpse, and give it to the dogs of Troy; '),(5647,'but Aias drew near, bearing his shield, that was like a city wall.'),(5648,' Then Hector gave ground backward into the throng of his comrades,  and leapt upon his chariot, '),(5649,'and gave the goodly armour to the Trojans to bear to the city, to be a great glory unto him.'),(5650,' But Aias covered the son of Menoetius round about with his broad shield, and stood as a lion over his whelps,  one that huntsmen have encountered in the forest as he leadeth his young; '),(5651,' then he exulteth in his strength, and draweth down all his brows to cover his eyes; '),(5652,' even so did Aias bestride the warrior Patroclus, '),(5653,'and hard by him stood the son of Atreus, Menelaus, dear to Ares, nursing great sorrow in his breast. '),(5654,' \n  And Glaucus, son of Hippolochus, leader of the Lycians, with an angry glance from beneath his brows, chid Hector with hard words, saying: '),(5655,'\"Hector, most fair to look upon, in battle art thou sorely lacking.'),(5656,'In good sooth \'tis but in vain that fair renown possesseth thee that art but a runagate. '),(5657,' Bethink thee now how by thyself thou mayest save thy city and home  aided only by the folk that were born in Ilios; '),(5658,' for of the Lycians at least will no man go forth to do battle with the Danaans for the city\'s sake, seeing there were to be no thanks, it seemeth, for warring against the foemen ever without respite. '),(5659,' How art thou like to save a meaner man amid the press of battle,  thou heartless one, when Sarpedon, that was at once thy guest and thy comrade, thou didst leave to the Argives to be their prey and spoil!—one that full often proved a boon to thee, to thy city and thine own self, while yet he lived;'),(5660,'  whereas now thou hadst not the courage to ward from him the dogs.'),(5661,'Wherefore now, if any one of the men of Lycia will hearken to me,  homeward will we go, and for Troy shall utter destruction be made plain. '),(5662,'Ah, that there were now in the Trojans dauntless courage, that knoweth naught of fear, such as cometh upon men that for their country\'s sake toil and strive with foemen; then forthwith should we hale Patroclus into Ilios.'),(5663,'  And if this man were to come, a corpse, to the great city of king Priam, and we should hale him forth from out the battle, straightway then would the Argives give back the goodly armour of Sarpedon, and we should bring his body into Ilios; '),(5664,' for such a man is he whose squire hath been slain, one that is far the best  of the Argives by the ships, himself and his squires that fight in close combat. '),(5665,'But thou hadst not the courage to stand before great-hearted Aias, facing him eye to eye amid the battle-cry of the foemen, nor to do battle against him, seeing he is a better man than thou.\"'),(5666,'\nThen with an angry glance from beneath his brows, spake to him Hector of the flashing helm:'),(5667,'\n  \"Glaucus, wherefore hast thou, being such a one as thou art, spoken an overweening word?'),(5668,' Good friend, in sooth I deemed that in wisdom thou wast above all others that dwell in deep-soiled Lycia;'),(5669,' but now have I altogether scorn of thy wits, that thou speakest thus, seeing thou sayest I stood not to face mighty Aias.'),(5670,'  I shudder not at battle, I tell thee, nor at the din of chariots,'),(5671,' but ever is the intent of Zeus that beareth the aegis strongest, for he driveth even a valiant man in rout, and robbeth him of victory full easily, and again of himself he rouseth men to fight. '),(5672,'Nay, come thou hither, good friend, take thy stand by my side, and behold my handiwork,  whether this whole day through I shall prove me a coward, as thou pratest, or shall stay many a one of the Danaans, how fierce soever for valorous deeds he be, from fighting in defence of the dead Patroclus.\" '),(5673,'So saying, he shouted aloud, and called to the Trojans:'),(5674,'  \"Ye Trojans, and Lycians, and Dardanians that fight in close combat,'),(5675,'  be men, my friends, and bethink you of furious valour, until I put upon me the armour of peerless Achilles, the goodly armour that I stripped from the mighty Patroclus, when I slew him.\"'),(5676,'\nWhen he had thus spoken, Hector of the flashing helm went forth from the fury of war, '),(5677,' and ran,  and speedily reached his comrades not yet far off, hastening after them with swift steps, even them that were bearing toward the city the glorious armour of the son of Peleus.'),(5678,' Then he halted apart from the tear-fraught battle, and changed his armour; '),(5679,' his own he gave to the war-loving Trojans to bear to sacred Ilios, but clad himself in the immortal armour  of Peleus\' son, Achilles, that the heavenly gods had given to his father '),(5680,'and that he had given to his son, when he himself waxed old;'),(5681,' howbeit in the armour of the father the son came not to old age.'),(5682,'\nBut when Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, beheld him from afar as he harnessed him in the battle-gear of the godlike son of Peleus,  he shook his head, and thus he spake unto his own heart: '),(5683,' \"Ah, poor wretch, death verily is not in thy thoughts, that yet draweth nigh thee; '),(5684,'but thou art putting upon thee the immortal armour of a princely man before whom others besides thee are wont to quail. '),(5685,'His comrade, kindly and valiant, hast thou slain,  and in unseemly wise hast stripped the armour from his head and shoulders.'),(5686,' Howbeit for this present will I vouch-safe thee great might, in recompense for this—that in no wise shalt thou return from out the battle for Andromache to receive from thee the glorious armour of the son of Peleus.\" '),(5687,' \nThe son of Cronos spake and bowed thereto with his dark brows, '),(5688,' and upon Hector\'s body he made the armour to fit, and there entered into him Ares, the dread Enyalius, and his limbs were filled within with valour and with might.'),(5689,' Then went he his way into the company of the famed allies,  crying a great cry, '),(5690,' and shewed himself before the eyes of all, flashing in the armour of the great-souled son of Peleus. '),(5691,'And going to and fro he spake and heartened each man, Mesthles and Glaucus and Medon and Thersilochus and Asteropaeus and Deisenor and Hippothous and Phorcys and Chroraius and Ennomus, the augur—'),(5692,'these he heartened, and spake to them winged words:'),(5693,'  \"Hear me, ye tribes uncounted of allies that dwell round about.'),(5694,' Not because I sought for numbers or had need thereof, did I gather each man of you from, your cities, but that with ready hearts ye might save the Trojans\' wives and their little children from the war-loving Achaeans.'),(5695,'  With this intent am I wasting the substance of mine own folk that ye may have gifts and food, and thereby I cause the strength of each one of you to wax.'),(5696,' Wherefore let every man turn straight against the foe and die haply, or live; '),(5697,'for this is the dalliance of war. '),(5698,'And whosoever shall hale Patroclus, dead though he be,  into the midst of the horse-taming Trojans, and make Aias to yield, the half of the spoils shall I render unto him, and the half shall I keep mine ownself; '),(5699,'and his glory shall be even as mine own.\"'),(5700,'\nSo spake he, and they charged straight against the Danaans with all their weight, holding their spears on high, '),(5701,'and their hearts within them  were full of hope to drag the corpse froma beneath Aias, son of Telamon—fools that they were!'),(5702,'\n Verily full many did he rob of life over that corpse.'),(5703,' Then spake Aias unto Menelaus, good at the war-cry,'),(5704,' \"Good Menelaus, fostered of Zeus, no more have I hope that we twain by ourselves alone shall win back from out the war.'),(5705,'  In no wise have I such dread for the corpse of Patroclus that shall presently glut the dogs and birds of the Trojans, as I have for mine own life, lest some evil befall, and for thine as well, for a cloud of war compasseth everything about, even Hector, and for us is utter destruction plain to see. '),(5706,'Howbeit, come thou, call upon the chieftains of the Danaans, if so be any may hear.”'),(5707,' \nSo spake he, and Menelaus, good at the war-cry, failed not to hearken, but uttered a piercing shout and called to the Danaans: '),(5708,'\"Friends, leaders and rulers of the Argives, ye that at the board of the sons of Atreus, Agamemnon and Menelaus,  drink at the common cost, and give commands each one to his folk—'),(5709,'ye upon whom attend honour and glory from Zeus—'),(5710,'hard is it for me to discern each man of the chieftains, '),(5711,'in such wise is the strife of war ablaze.'),(5712,' Nay, let every man go forth unbidden, and have shame at heart that  Patroclus should become the sport of the dogs of Troy.\"'),(5713,'So spake he, and swift Aias, son of Oileus, heard him clearly,'),(5714,' and was first to come running to meet him amid the battle, and after him Idomeneus and Idomeneus\' comrade, Meriones, the peer of Enyalius, slayer of men.'),(5715,'  But of the rest, what man of his own wit could name the names—of all that came after these and aroused the battle of the Achaeans?'),(5716,' and Hector led them.'),(5717,' and Hector led them.'),(5718,' And as when at the mouth of some heaven-fed river the mighty wave roareth against the stream,  and the headlands of the shore echo on either hand, as the salt-sea belloweth without; even with such din of shouting came on the Trojans.'),(5719,' But the Achaeans stood firm about the son of Menoetius with oneness of heart, fenced about with shields of bronze. '),(5720,' And the son of Cronos  shed thick darkness over their bright helms, for even aforetime was the son of Menoetius nowise hated of him, while he was yet alive and the squire of the son of Aeacus; '),(5721,'and now was Zeus full loath that he should become the sport of the dogs of his foemen, even them of Troy;'),(5722,' wherefore Zeus roused his comrades to defend him. '),(5723,' \nAnd first the Trojans drave back the bright-eyed Achaeans, '),(5724,' who left the corpse and shrank back before them; howbeit not a man did the Trojans high of heart slay with their spears, albeit they were fain, but they set them to hale the corpse.'),(5725,' Yet for but scant space were the Achaeans to hold back therefrom,'),(5726,' for full speedily did Aias rally them—Aias that in comeliness and in deeds of war was above  all the other Danaans next to the peerless son of Peleus. '),(5727,' Straight through the foremost fighters he strode, in might like a wild boar that, amid the mountains lightly scattereth hounds and lusty youths when he wheeleth upon them in the glades;'),(5728,'even so the son of lordly Telamon, glorious Aias,  when he had got among them lightly scattered the battalions of the Trojans, that had taken their stand above Patroclus, and were fain above all to hale him to their city, and get them glory.'),(5729,'\nNow Hippothous, the glorious son of Pelasgian Lethus, was dragging the corpse by the foot through the fierce conflict,  and had bound his baldric about the tendons of either ankle, doing pleasure unto Hector and the Trojans.'),(5730,'  But full swiftly upon him came evil that not one of them could ward off, how fain soever they were.'),(5731,' For the son of Telamon, darting upon him through the throng, smote him from close at hand through the helmet with cheek-pieces of bronze;'),(5732,' and the helm with horse-hair crest was cloven about the spear-point, smitten by the great spear and the strong hand; and the brain spurted forth from the wound along the socket of the spear all mingled with blood.'),(5733,' There then his strength was loosed, and from his hands he let fall  to lie upon the ground the foot of great-hearted Patroclus, '),(5734,'and hard thereby himself fell headlong upon the corpse, far from deep-soiled Larissa; nor paid he back to his dear parents the recompense of his upbringing, and but brief was the span of his life, for that he was laid low by the spear of great-souled Aias.'),(5735,' And Hector in turn cast at Aias with his bright spear, '),(5736,' but Aias, looking steadily at him, avoided the spear of bronze albeit by a little,'),(5737,'and Hector smote Schedius, son of great-souled Iphitus, far the best of the Phocians, that dwelt in a house in famous Panopeus, and was king over many men. Him Hector smote beneath the midst of the collar-bone, '),(5738,' and clean through passed the point of bronze, and came out beneath the base of the shoulder. '),(5739,'And he fell with a thud, and upon him his armour clanged. '),(5740,' And Aias in his turn smote wise-hearted Phorcys, son of Phaenops, full upon the belly as he bestrode Hippothous, '),(5741,'and he brake the plate of his corselet,  and the bronze let forth the bowels there-through; '),(5742,'and he fell in the dust and clutched the earth in his palm.'),(5743,' Thereat the foremost fighters and glorious Hector gave ground,'),(5744,' and the Argives shouted aloud, and drew off the dead, even Phorcys and Hippothous, and set them to strip the armour from their shoulders. '),(5745,' \nThen would the Trojans have been driven again by the Achaeans,  dear to Ares, up to Ilios, vanquished in their cowardice, and the Argives would have won glory even beyond the allotment of Zeus, by reason of their might and their strength, '),(5746,'had not Apollo himself aroused Aeneas, taking upon him the form of the herald, Periphas, son of Epytos, that in the house of his old father  had grown old in his heraldship, and withal was of kindly mind toward him.'),(5747,' In his likeness spake unto Aeneas the son of Zeus, Apollo:'),(5748,' \"Aeneas, how could ye ever guard steep Ilios, in defiance of a god?'),(5749,' In sooth I have seen other men that had trust in their strength and might, in their valour  and in their host, and that held their realm even in defiance of Zeus.'),(5750,'But for us Zeus willeth the victory far more than for the Danaans; '),(5751,'yet yourselves ye have measureless fear, and fight not.\"'),(5752,'So spake he, and Aeneas knew Apollo that smiteth afar, when he looked upon his face, and he called aloud, and spake to Hector:'),(5753,'  \"Hector, and ye other leaders of the Trojans and allies, shame verily were this, if before the Achaeans, dear to Ares, we be driven back to Ilios, vanquished in our cowardice.'),(5754,' Howbeit even yet, declareth one of the gods that stood by my side, is Zeus, the counsellor most high, our helper in the fight.'),(5755,'  Wherefore let us make straight for the Danaans, and let it not be at their ease that they bring to the ships the dead Patroclus.\"'),(5756,'\nSo spake he, and leapt forth far to the front of the foremost fighters, and there stood.'),(5757,' And they rallied, and took their stand with their faces toward the Achaeans.'),(5758,' Then Aeneas wounded with a thrust of his spear Leocritus,  son of Arisbas and valiant comrade of Lycomedes. '),(5759,'And as he fell Lycomedes, dear to Ares, had pity for him, and came and stood hard by and with a cast of his bright spear smote Apisaon, son of Hippasus, shepherd of the host, in the liver, below the midriff, and straightway loosed his knees—Apisaon  that was come from out of deep-soiled Paeonia, and next to Asteropaeus was preeminent above them all in fight.'),(5760,' But as he fell warlike Asteropaeus had pity for him, and he too rushed onward, fain to fight with the Danaans; '),(5761,'howbeit thereto could he no more avail, '),(5762,' for with shields were they fenced in on every side,  as they stood around Patroclus, and before them they held their spears.'),(5763,' For Aias ranged to and fro among them and straitly charged every man; '),(5764,'not one, he bade them, should give ground backward from the corpse, nor yet fight in front of the rest of the Achaeans as one pre-eminent above them all; but stand firm close beside the corpse and do battle hand to hand.'),(5765,'  Thus mighty Aias charged them, and the earth grew wet with dark blood, and the dead fell thick and fast alike of the Trojans and their mighty allies, and of the Danaans; '),(5766,'for these too fought not without shedding of blood, howbeit fewer of them by far were falling; '),(5767,'for they ever bethought them  to ward utter destruction from one another in the throng.'),(5768,' \n So fought they like unto blazing fire, nor wouldst thou have deemed that sun or moon yet abode, '),(5769,' for with darkness were they shrouded in the fight, all the chieftains that stood around the slain son of Menoetius.'),(5770,'  But the rest of the Trojans and the well-greaved Achaeans fought at their ease under clear air, and over them was spread the piercing brightness of the sun, and on all the earth and the mountains was no cloud seen;'),(5771,'and they fought resting themselves at times, avoiding one another\'s shafts, fraught with groaning,  and standing far apart. '),(5772,'But those in the midst suffered woes by reason of the darkness and the war, and were sore distressed with the pitiless bronze, even all they that were chieftains.'),(5773,' Howbeit two men that were famous warriors, even Thrasymedes and Antilochus, had not yet learned that peerless Patroclus was dead, but deemed that,  yet alive, he was fighting with the Trojans in the forefront of the throng. '),(5774,'And they twain, watching against the death and rout of their comrades, were warring in a place apart, for thus had Nestor bidden them, when he roused them forth to the battle from the black ships.'),(5775,'\nSo then the whole day through raged the great strife  of their cruel fray,'),(5776,'and with the sweat of toil were the knees and legs and feet of each man beneath him ever ceaselessly bedewed, and his arms and eyes, as the two hosts fought about the goodly squire of swift-footed Achilles.'),(5777,' And as when a man  giveth to his people the hide of a great bull for stretching, all drenched in fat, '),(5778,'and when they have taken it, they stand in a circle and stretch it, and forthwith its moisture goeth forth and the fat entereth in under the tugging of many hands, and all the hide is stretched to the uttermost; '),(5779,'even so they on this side and on that were haling the corpse hither and thither in scant space; '),(5780,'  and their hearts within them were full of hope, the Trojans that they might drag him to Ilios, but the Achaeans to the hollow ships; '),(5781,'and around him the battle waxed wild, '),(5782,'nor could even Ares, rouser of hosts, nor Athene, at sight of that strife have made light thereof, albeit their anger were exceeding great. '),(5783,' \n  Such evil toil of men and horses did Zeus on that day strain taut over Patroclus.'),(5784,' Nor as yet did goodly Achilles know aught of Patroclus\' death, '),(5785,'for afar from the swift ships were they fighting beneath the wall of the Trojans.'),(5786,' Wherefore Achilles never deemed in his heart  that he was dead, but that he would return alive, after he had reached even to the gates; nor yet thought he this in any wise, that Patroclus would sack the city without him, nay, nor with him, '),(5787,'for full often had he heard this from his mother, listening to her privily, whenso she brought him tidings of the purpose of great Zeus.'),(5788,'  Howbeit then his mother told him not how great an evil had been brought to pass, that his comrade, far the dearest, had been slain.'),(5789,'\nBut the others round about the corpse, with sharp spears in their hands, ever pressed on continually, and slew each other.'),(5790,' And thus would one of the brazen-coated Achaeans say:'),(5791,'  \"Friends, no fair fame verily were it for us to return back to the hollow ships; nay, even here let the black earth gape for us all.'),(5792,' That were for us straightway better far, if we are to yield this man to the Trojans, tamers of horses, to hale to their city, and win them glory.\" '),(5793,'  And thus in like manner would one of the great-hearted Trojans speak: '),(5794,' \"Friends, though it be our fate all together to be slain beside this man, yet let none give backward from the fight.\" '),(5795,' \nThus would one speak and arouse the might of each.'),(5796,' So they fought on,  and the iron din went up through the unresting air to the brazen heaven. '),(5797,' But the horses of the son of Aeacus being apart from the battle were weeping, since first they learned that their charioteer had fallen in the dust beneath the hands of man-slaying Hector.'),(5798,'In sooth Automedon, valiant son of Diores,  full often plied them with blows of the swift lash, and full often with gentle words bespake them, and oft with threatenings; '),(5799,'yet neither back to the ships to the broad Hellespont were the twain minded to go, not yet into the battle amid the Achaeans. Nay, as a pillar abideth firm that standeth on the tomb  of a dead man or woman, even so abode they immovably with the beauteous car, bowing their heads down to the earth.'),(5800,' And hot tears ever flowed from their eyes to the ground, as they wept in longing for their charioteer,'),(5801,'and their rich manes were befouled,  streaming from beneath the yoke-pad beside the yoke on this aide and on that.'),(5802,' And as they mourned, the son of Cronos had sight of them and was touched with pity, and he shook his head, and thus spake unto his own heart:'),(5803,' \"Ah unhappy pair, wherefore gave we you to king Peleus, to a mortal, while ye are ageless and immortal?'),(5804,'  Was it that among wretched men ye too should have sorrows? '),(5805,'For in sooth there is naught, I ween, more miserable than man among all things that breathe and move upon earth.'),(5806,' Yet verily not upon you and your car, richly-dight,  shall Hector, Priam\'s son, mount; '),(5807,'that will I not suffer.'),(5808,'Sufficeth it not that he hath the armour and therewithal vaunteth him vainly?'),(5809,' Nay, in your knees and in your heart will I put strength, to the end that ye may also bear Automedon safe out of the war to the hollow ships; '),(5810,'for still shall I vouchsafe glory to the Trojans, to slay and slay, until they come to the well-benched ships,  and the sun sets and sacred darkness cometh on.”'),(5811,' \nSo saying he breathed great might into the horses.'),(5812,' And the twain shook the dust from their manes to the ground, and fleetly bare the swift car amid the Trojans and Achaeans.'),(5813,' And behind them fought Automedon, albeit he sorrowed for his comrade, swooping  with his car as a vulture on a flock of geese, '),(5814,'for lightly would he flee from out the battle-din of the Trojans, and lightly charge, setting upon them through the great throng.'),(5815,' Howbeit no man might he slay as he hasted to pursue them,'),(5816,' for in no wise was it possible for him being alone in the sacred car,  to assail them with the spear, and withal to hold the swift horses.'),(5817,'  But at last a comrade espied him with his eyes, even Alcimedon, son of Laerces, son of Haemon, '),(5818,'and he halted behind the chariot and spake unto Automedon: '),(5819,'\"Automedon, what god  hath put in thy breast unprofitable counsel and taken from thee thy heart of understanding,'),(5820,'that thus in the foremost throng thou fightest with the Trojans, alone as thou art?'),(5821,' For thy comrade hath been slain, and his armour Hector weareth on his own shoulders, even the armour of the son of Aeacus, and glorieth therein.\"'),(5822,'To him then made answer Automedon, son of Diores:'),(5823,'  \"Alcimedon, what man beside of the Achaeans is of like worth to curb and guide the spirit of immortal steeds, save only Patroclus, the peer of the gods in counsel, while yet he lived?'),(5824,'But now death and fate have come upon him. '),(5825,' Howbeit  take thou the lash and the shining reins, and I will dismount to fight\"'),(5826,'So spake he, and Alcimedon leapt upon the car that was swift in battle, and quickly grasped in his hands the lash and reins; and Automedon leapt down.'),(5827,' And glorious Hector espied them, and forthwith spake to Aeneas, that was near:'),(5828,'  \"Aeneas, counsellor of the brazen-coated Trojans, yonder I espy the two horses of the swift-footed son of Aeacus coming forth to view into the battle with weakling charioteers.'),(5829,' These twain might I hope to take, if thou in thy heart art willing, seeing the men would not abide the oncoming of us two, '),(5830,' \nSo spake he, and the valiant son of Anchises failed not to hearken.'),(5831,' And the twain went straight forward, their shoulders clad with shields of bull\'s-hide, dry and tough, '),(5832,'and abundant bronze had been welded thereupon.'),(5833,' And with them went Chromius, and godlike Aretus both,'),(5834,' and their hearts within them were full of hope to slay the men and drive off the horses with high-arched necks—fools that they were! for not without shedding of blood were they to get them back from Automedon.'),(5835,' He made prayer to father Zeus, and his dark heart within him was filled with valour and strength;'),(5836,'  and forthwith he spake to Alcimedon, his trusty comrade: '),(5837,'\"Alcimedon, not afar from me do thou hold the horses, but let their breath smite upon my very back; '),(5838,'for I verily deem not that Hector, son of Priam, will be stayed from his fury until he mount behind the fair-maned horses of Achilles,  and have slain the two of us, and driven in rout the ranks of the Argive warriors, or haply himself be slain amid the foremost.\"'),(5839,'\nSo spake he, and called to the two Aiantes and to Menelaus: '),(5840,' \"Ye Aiantes twain, leaders of the Argives, and thou Menelaus, lo now, leave ye the corpse in charge of them that are bravest  to stand firm about it and to ward off the ranks of men; but from us twain that yet live ward ye off the pitiless day of doom, '),(5841,'for here are pressing hard in tearful war Hector and Aeneas, the best men of the Trojans.'),(5842,' Yet these things verily lie on the knees of the gods:'),(5843,'  I myself will cast; and Zeus will look after the issue.\''),(5844,' \nHe spake, and poised his far-shadowing spear and hurled it, and smote upon the shield of Aretus, that was well-balanced upon every side, '),(5845,'and this stayed not the spear, but the bronze passed clean through, and into the lower belly he drave it through the belt.'),(5846,'  And as when a strong man with sharp axe in hand smiteth behind the horns of an ox of the steading and cutteth clean through the sinew, and the ox leapeth forward and falleth; even so Aretus leapt forward and fell upon his back,'),(5847,'and the spear, exceeding sharp, fixed quivering in his entrails loosed his limbs.'),(5848,'  But Hector cast at Automedon with his bright spear,'),(5849,' howbeit he, looking steadily at him, avoided the spear of bronze, '),(5850,'for he stooped forward, and the long spear fixed itself in the ground behind him, and the butt of the spear quivered;'),(5851,' howbeit there at length did mighty Ares stay its fury.'),(5852,'  And now had they clashed with their swords in close fight but that the twain Aiantes parted them in their fury, for they came through the throng at the call of their comrade,'),(5853,' and seized with fear of them Hector and Aeneas and godlike Chromius gave ground again  and left Aretus lying there stricken to the death.'),(5854,' And Automedon, the peer of swift Ares, despoiled him of his armour, and exulted, saying:'),(5855,' \"Verily a little have I eased mine heart of grief for the death of Menoetius\' son, though it be but a worse man that I have slain.\"'),(5856,'\n  So saying, he took up the bloody spoils, and set them in the car, and himself mounted thereon, his feet and his hands above all bloody, even as a lion that hath devoured a bull. '),(5857,' \nThen again over Patroclus was strained taut the mighty conflict, dread and fraught with tears, and Athene roused the strife,  being come down from heaven; '),(5858,'for Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, had sent her to urge on the Danaans, '),(5859,'for lo, his mind was turned.'),(5860,' As Zeus stretcheth forth for mortals a lurid rainbow from out of heaven to be a portent whether of war or of chill storm that  maketh men to cease from their work upon the face of the earth, and vexeth the flocks; even so Athene, enwrapping herself in a lurid cloud, entered the throng of the Danaans, and urged on each man.'),(5861,' First to hearten him she spake to Atreus\' son, valiant Menelaus, '),(5862,'for he was nigh to her, '),(5863,' likening herself to Phoenix, in form and untiring voice: '),(5864,' \"To thee, verily, Menelaus, shall there be shame and a hanging of the head, if the trusty comrade of lordly Achilles he torn by swift dogs beneath the wall of the Trojans.'),(5865,' Nay, hold thy ground valiantly, and urge on all the host.\"'),(5866,' Then Menelaus, good at the war-cry, answered her:'),(5867,' \"Phoenix, old sire, my father of ancient days, would that Athene may give me strength and keep from me the onrush of darts.'),(5868,' So should I be full fain to stand by Patroclus\' side and succour him; '),(5869,'for in sooth his death hath touched me to the heart.'),(5870,'  Howbeit, Hector hath the dread fury of fire, and ceaseth not to make havoc with the bronze; '),(5871,'for it is to him that Zeus vouchsafeth glory.\" '),(5872,' \nSo spake he, and the goddess, flashing-eyed Athene, waxed glad, for that to her first of all the gods he made his prayer. '),(5873,'And she put strength into his shoulders and his knees,  and in his breast set the daring of the fly, that though it be driven away never so often from the skin of a man, ever persisteth in biting, and sweet to it is the blood of man; '),(5874,'even with such daring filled she his dark heart within him, and he stood over Patroclus and hurled with his bright spear.'),(5875,'  Now among the Trojans was one Podes, son of Eetion, a rich man and a valiant, '),(5876,'and Hector honoured him above all the people, for that he was his comrade, a welcome companion at the feast.'),(5877,' Him, fair-haired Menelaus smote upon the belt with a spear cast as he started to flee, and drave the bronze clean through; '),(5878,' and he fell with a thud.'),(5879,' But Menelaus, son of Atreus, dragged the dead body from amid the Trojans into the throng of his comrades.'),(5880,'\nThen unto Hector did Apollo draw nigh, and urged him on, in the likeness of Asius\' son Phaenops, that of all his guest-friends was dearest to him, and had his house at Abydus.'),(5881,' In his likeness Apollo that worketh afar spake unto Hector:'),(5882,' \"Hector, what man beside of the Achaeans will fear thee any more,'),(5883,' seeing thou hast thus quailed before Menelaus, who aforetime was a weakling warrior?'),(5884,' Now with none to aid him hath he taken the dead from out the ranks of the Trojans and is gone—aye, he hath slain thy trusty comrade,  a good man among the foremost fighters, even Podes, son of Eetion.\"'),(5885,'So spake he, and a black cloud of grief enwrapped Hector, and he strode amid the foremost fighters, harnessed in flaming bronze.'),(5886,'And then the son of Cronos took his tasselled aegis, all gleaming bright, and enfolded Ida with clouds,  and lightened and thundered mightily, and shook the aegis, giving victory to the Trojans, but the Achaeans he drave in rout. '),(5887,' \nFirst to begin the rout was Peneleos the Boeotian.'),(5888,' For as he abode ever facing the foe he was smitten on the surface of the shoulder with a spear, a grazing blow,'),(5889,'  but the spear-point of Polydamas cut even to the bone, '),(5890,'for he it was that cast at him from nigh at hand. '),(5891,' And Leitus again, the son of great-souled Alectryon, did Hector wound in close fight, on the hand at the wrist, and made him cease from fighting:'),(5892,' and casting an anxious glance about him he shrank back, seeing he no more had hope that bearing spear in hand he might do battle with the Trojans.'),(5893,'  And as Hector pursued after Leitus, Idomeneus smote him upon the corselet, on the breast beside the nipple; '),(5894,'but the long spear-shaft was broken in the socket, and the Trojans shouted aloud.'),(5895,' And Hector cast at Idomeneus, Deucalion\'s son, as he stood upon his car,'),(5896,'and missed him by but little; '),(5897,' howbeit he smote Coeranus the comrade and charioteer of Meriones that followed him from out of well-built Lyctus—'),(5898,'for on foot had Idomeneus come at the first from the curved ships, and would have yielded great victory to the Trojans, had not Coeranus speedily driven up the swift-footed horses.'),(5899,'  Thus to Idomeneus he came as a light of deliverance, and warded from him the pitiless day of doom, but him self lost his life at the hands of man-slaying Hector— '),(5900,'this Coeranus did Hector smite beneath the jaw under the ear, and the spear dashed out his teeth by the roots, and clave his tongue asunder in the midst; '),(5901,'and he fell from out the car, and let fall the reins down upon the ground.'),(5902,'  And Meriones stooped, and gathered them in his own hands from the earth, and spake to Idomeneus:'),(5903,' \"Ply now the lash, until thou be come to the swift ships.'),(5904,' Lo, even of thyself thou knowest that victory is no more with the Achaeans.\"'),(5905,'\nSo spake he, and Idomeneus lashed the fair-maned horses back  to the hollow ships; '),(5906,'for verily fear had fallen upon his soul.'),(5907,' \nNor were great-hearted Aias and Menelaus unaware how that Zeus was giving to the Trojans victory to turn the tide of battle; '),(5908,'and of them great Telamonian Aias was first to speak, saying:'),(5909,' \"Out upon it, now may any man, how foolish so ever he be,  know that father Zeus himself is succouring the Trojans. '),(5910,'For the missiles of all of them strike home, whosoever hurleth them, be he brave man or coward:'),(5911,' Zeus in any case guideth them all aright;'),(5912,'but for us the shafts of every man fall vainly to the ground.'),(5913,'Nay, come, let us of ourselves devise the counsel that is best,  whereby we may both hale away the corpse, and ourselves return home for the joy of our dear comrades, who methinks are sore distressed as they look hither-ward, and deem that the fury and the irresistible hands of man-slaying Hector will not be stayed, but will fall upon the black ships.'),(5914,'  But I would there were some comrade to bear word with all speed to the son of Peleus, for methinks he hath not even heard the woeful tale, that his dear comrade is slain.'),(5915,' Howbeit, nowhere can I see such a one among the Achaeans, '),(5916,'for in darkness are they all enwrapped, themselves and their horses withal.'),(5917,'  Father Zeus, deliver thou from the darkness the sons of the Achaeans, and make clear sky, and grant us to see with our eyes.'),(5918,' In the light do thou e\'en slay us, seeing such is thy good pleasure.\"'),(5919,'\nSo spake he, and the Father had pity on him as he wept,'),(5920,' and forthwith scattered the darkness and drave away the mist,  and the sun shone forth upon them and all the battle was made plain to view. '),(5921,' Then Aias spake unto Menelaus, good at the war-cry:'),(5922,' \"Look forth now, Menelaus, nurtured of Zeus, if so be thou mayest have sight of Antilochus yet alive, son of great-souled Nestor, and bestir thou him to go with speed unto Achilles, wise of heart,  to tell him that his comrade, far the dearest, is slain.”'),(5923,' \nSo spake he, and Menelaus, good at the war-cry, failed not to hearken, but went his way as a lion from a steading when he waxeth weary with vexing dogs and men that suffer him not to seize the fattest of the herd,  watching the whole night through;'),(5924,'but he in his lust for flesh goeth straight on, yet accomplisheth naught thereby, '),(5925,'for thick the darts fly to meet him, hurled by bold hands, and blazing brands withal, before which he quaileth, '),(5926,' how eager soever he be, and at dawn he departeth with sure heart; '),(5927,' even so from Patroclus departed Menelaus, good at the war-cry, sorely against his will; '),(5928,'for exceedingly did he fear lest the Achaeans in sorry rout should leave him to be a prey to the foemen.'),(5929,' And many a charge laid he on Meriones and the Aiantes, saying: '),(5930,'\"Ye Aiantes twain, leaders of the Argives, and thou, Meriones,  now let each man remember the kindliness of hapless Patroclus; '),(5931,'for to all was he ever gentle while yet he lived, '),(5932,'but now death and fate have come upon him.\"'),(5933,'So saying fair-haired Menelaus departed, glancing warily on every side as an eagle, which, men say, hath  the keenest sight of all winged things under heaven, of whom, though he be on high, the swift-footed hare is not unseen as he croucheth beneath a leafy bush, but the eagle swoopeth upon him and forthwith seizeth him, and robbeth him of life. '),(5934,'Even so then, Menelaus, nurtured of Zeus, did thy bright eyes  range everywhither over the throng of thy many comrades, if so be they niight have sight of Nestor\'s son yet alive.'),(5935,' Him he marked full quickly on the left of the whole battle, heartening his comrades and urging them on to fight. And drawing nigh fair-haired Menelaus spake to him, saying:'),(5936,'  \"Antilochus, up, come hither, thou nurtured of Zeus, that thou mayest learn woeful tidings, such as I would had never been.'),(5937,' Even now, I ween, thou knowest, for thine eyes behold it, how that a god rolleth ruin upon the Danaans, and that victory is with the men of Troy.'),(5938,' And slain is the best man of the Achaeans,  even Patroclus, and great longing for him is wrought for the Danaans.'),(5939,'But do thou with speed run to the ships of the Achaeans and bear word unto Achilles, in hope that he may forthwith bring safe to his ship the corpse—the naked corpse; '),(5940,'but his armour is held by Hector of the flashing helm.\" '),(5941,' \nSo spake he, and Antilochus had horror, as he heard that word.'),(5942,'  Long time was he speechless, and both his eyes were filled with tears, and the flow of his voice was checked.'),(5943,' Yet not even so was he neglectful of the bidding of Menelaus, but set him to run, and gave his armour to his peerless comrade Laodocus, that hard beside him was wheeling his single-hoofed horses.'),(5944,'\n  Him then as he wept his feet bare forth from out the battle to bear an evil tale to Peleus\' son Achilles.'),(5945,' Nor was thy heart, Menelaus, nurtured of Zeus, minded to bear aid to the sore-pressed comrades from whom Antilochus was departed, and great longing was wrought for the men of Pylos.'),(5946,'  Howbeit, for their aid he sent goodly Thrasymedes, and himself went again to bestride the warrior Patroclus; and he ran, and took his stand beside the Aiantes, and forthwith spake to them :'),(5947,' \"Yon man have I verily sent forth to the swift ships, to go to Achilles, fleet of foot.'),(5948,' Howbeit I deem not  that Achilles will come forth, how wroth soever he be against goodly Hector; '),(5949,' for in no wise may he fight against the Trojans unarmed as he is.'),(5950,' But let us of ourselves devise the counsel that is best, whereby we may both hale away the corpse, and ourselves escape death and fate amid the battle-din of the Trojans.\"'),(5951,'   Then great Telamonian Aias answered him: '),(5952,'\"All this hast thou spoken aright, most glorious Menelaus.'),(5953,' But do thou and Meriones stoop with all speed beneath the corpse, and raise him up, and bear him forth from out the toil of war;'),(5954,'but behind you we twain will do battle with the Trojans and goodly Hector,  one in heart as we are one in name, even we that aforetime have been wont to stand firm in fierce battle, abiding each by the other\'s side.\"'),(5955,'\nSo spake he, and the others took in their arms the dead from the ground, and lifted him on high in their great might; '),(5956,'and thereat the host of the Trojans behind them shouted aloud, when they beheld the Achaeans lifting the corpse.'),(5957,'  And they charged straight upon them like hounds that in front of hunting youths dart upon a wounded wild boar:'),(5958,' awhile they rush upon him fain to rend him asunder, but whenso he wheeleth among them trusting in his might, then they give ground and shrink in fear, one here, one there; '),(5959,' even so the Trojans for a time ever followed on in throngs, thrusting with swords and two-edged spears, '),(5960,'but whenso the twain Aiantes would wheel about and stand against them, then would their colour change, and no man dared dart forth and do battle for the dead. '),(5961,' \n  Thus the twain were hasting to bear the corpse forth from out the battle to the hollow ships, '),(5962,' and against them was strained a conflict fierce as fire that, rushing upon a city of men with sudden onset, setteth it aflame, and houses fall amid the mighty glare,'),(5963,'and the might of the wind driveth it roaring on.'),(5964,'  Even so against them as they went came ever the ceaseless din of chariots and of spearmen.'),(5965,' But as mules that, putting forth on either side their great strength, drag forth from the mountain down a rugged path a beam haply, or a great ship-timber, '),(5966,'and within them their hearts  as they strive are distressed with toil alike and sweat; '),(5967,' even so these hasted to bear forth the corpse.'),(5968,' And behind them the twain Aiantes held back the foe, as a ridge holdeth back a flood  —some wooded ridge that chanceth to lie all athwart a plain and that holdeth back even the dread streams of mighty rivers, and forthwith turneth the current of them all to wander over the plain,'),(5969,' neither doth the might of their flood avail to break through it; '),(5970,'even so the twain Aiantes ever kept back the battle of the Trojans, '),(5971,'but these ever followed after and two among them above all others, even Aeneas, Anchises\' son, and glorious Hector.'),(5972,'  And as flieth a cloud of starlings or of daws, shrieking cries of doom, when they see coming upon them a falcon that beareth death unto small birds; so before Aeneas and Hector fled the youths of the Achaeans, shrieking cries of doom, and forgat all fighting.'),(5973,'  And fair arms full many fell around and about the trench as the Danaans fled; '),(5974,'but there was no ceasing from war.'),(5975,' So fought they like unto blazing fire, but Antilochus, swift of foot, came to bear tidings to Achilles.'),(5976,' Him he found in front of his ships with upright horns, boding in his heart the thing that even now was brought to pass; '),(5977,' and sore troubled he spake unto his own great-hearted spirit: '),(5978,'\"Ah, woe is me, how is it that again the long-haired Achaeans are being driven toward the ships in rout over the plain?'),(5979,'Let it not be that the gods have brought to pass grievous woes for my soul, even as on a time my mother declared unto me, and said that  while yet I lived the best man of the Myrmidons should leave the light of the sun beneath the hands of the Trojans!'),(5980,' in good sooth the valiant son of Menoetius must now, be dead, foolhardy one.'),(5981,' Surely I bade him come back again to the ships when he had thrust off the consuming fire, and not to fight amain with Hector.\"'),(5982,'\n  While he pondered thus in mind and heart, there drew nigh unto him the son of lordly Nestor, shedding hot tears, and spake the grievous tidings:'),(5983,' \"Woe is me, thou son of wise-hearted Peleus, full grievous is the tidings thou must hear, such as I would had never been.'),(5984,'  Low lies Patroclus, and around his corpse are they fighting—his naked corpse; '),(5985,'but his armour is held by Hector of the flashing helm.\" '),(5986,' \nSo spake he, and a black cloud of grief enwrapped Achilles,'),(5987,'and with both his hands he took the dark dust  and strewed it over his head and defiled his fair face, '),(5988,'and on his fragrant tunic the black ashes fell. '),(5989,'And himself in the dust lay outstretched, mighty in his mightiness, and with his own hands he tore and marred his hair. '),(5990,'And the handmaidens, that Achilles and Patroclus had got them as booty, shrieked aloud in anguish of heart,  and ran forth around wise-hearted Achilles, and all beat their breasts with their hands, and the knees of each one were loosed be-neath her.'),(5991,' And over against them Antilochus wailed and shed tears, holding the hands of Achilles,'),(5992,'that in his noble heart was moaning mightily; '),(5993,'for he feared lest he should cut his throat asunder with the knife.'),(5994,'  Then terribly did Achilles groan aloud,'),(5995,' and his queenly mother heard him as she sat in the depths of the sea beside the old man her father. Thereat she uttered a shrill cry,'),(5996,' and the goddesses thronged about her, even all the daughters of Nereus that were in the deep of the sea.'),(5997,'There were Glauce and Thaleia and Cymodoce,  Nesaea and Speio and Thoë and ox-eyed Halië, and Cymothoë and Actaeä and Limnoreia, and Melite and Iaera and Amphithoe and Agave, Doto and Proto and Pherousa and Dynamene, and Dexamene and Amphinone and Callianeira,  Doris and Pynope and glorious Galatea, Nemertes and Apseudes and Callianassa,'),(5998,'and there were Clymene and Ianeira and Ianassa, Maera and Orithyia and fair-tressed Amatheia, and other Nereids that were in the deep of the sea.'),(5999,'  With these the bright cave was filled, '),(6000,'and they all alike beat their breasts, and Thetis was leader in their lamenting:'),(6001,' \"Listen, sister Nereids, that one and all ye may hear and know all the sorrows that are in my heart. '),(6002,' Ah, woe is me unhappy, woe is me that bare to my sorrow the best of men,  for after I had borne a son peerless and stalwart, pre-eminent among warriors, '),(6003,' and he shot up like a sapling; '),(6004,'then when I had reared him as a tree in a rich orchard plot, I sent him forth in the beaked ships to Ilios to war with the Trojans; '),(6005,'but never again shall I welcome him  back to his home, to the house of Peleus. '),(6006,'And while yet he liveth, and beholdeth the light of the sun, he hath sorrow, neither can I anywise help him, though I go to him.'),(6007,' Howbeit go I will, that I may behold my dear child, and hear what grief has come upon him while yet he abideth aloof from the war.\" '),(6008,' \n  So saying she left the cave,'),(6009,'and the nymphs went with her weeping, and around them the waves of the sea were cloven asunder.'),(6010,' And when they were come to the deep-soiled land of Troy they stepped forth upon the beach, one after the other, where the ships of the Myrmidons were drawn up in close lines round about swift Achilles.'),(6011,'  Then to his side, as he groaned heavily, came his queenly mother, and with a shrill cry she clasped the head of her son, and with wailing spake unto him winged words:'),(6012,'\n What sorrow hath come upon thy heart. '),(6013,'\n What sorrow hath come upon thy heart. '),(6014,'Speak out; hide it not. '),(6015,'Thy wish has verily been brought to pass for thee  by Zeus, as aforetime thou didst pray, stretching forth thy hands, even that one and all the sons of the Achaeans should be huddled at the sterns of the ships in sore need of thee, and should suffer cruel things.\"'),(6016,'\nThen groaning heavily swift-footed Achilles answered her:'),(6017,' \"My mother, these prayers verily hath the Olympian brought to pass for me, '),(6018,' but what pleasure have I therein, seeing my dear comrade is dead, even Patroclus, whom I honoured above all my comrades, even as mine own self?'),(6019,' Him have I lost, and his armour Hector that slew him hath stripped from him, that fair armour, huge of size, a wonder to behold, '),(6020,' that the gods gave as a glorious gift to Peleus  on the day when they laid thee in the bed of a mortal man. '),(6021,' Would thou hadst remained where thou wast amid the immortal maidens of the sea, and that Peleus had taken to his home a mortal bride.'),(6022,'But now—it was thus that thou too mightest have measureless grief at heart for thy dead son, whom thou shalt never again welcome  to his home; for neither doth my own heart bid me live on and abide among men, unless Hector first, smitten by my spear, shall lose his life, and pay back the price for that he made spoil of Patroclus, son of Menoetius.\"'),(6023,'\nThen Thetis again spake unto him, shedding tears the while:'),(6024,'  \"Doomed then to a speedy death, my child, shalt thou be, that thou spakest thus;'),(6025,' for straightway after Hector is thine own death ready at hand.\" '),(6026,' \nThen, mightily moved, swift-footed Achilles spake to her:'),(6027,' \"Straightway may I die, seeing I was not to bear aid to my comrade at his slaying.'),(6028,' Far, far from his own land  hath he fallen, and had need of me to be a warder off of ruin. '),(6029,' Now therefore, seeing I return not to my dear native land, neither proved anywise a light of deliverance to Patroclus nor to my other comrades, those many that have been slain by goodly Hector, but abide here by the ships. Profitless burden upon the earth—  I that in war am such as is none other of the brazen-coated Achaeans, '),(6030,' albeit in council there be others better— '),(6031,'so may strife perish from among gods and men, and anger that setteth a man on to grow wroth, how wise soever he be, and that sweeter far than trickling honey  waxeth like smoke in the breasts of men;'),(6032,' even as but now the king of men, Agamemnon, moved me to wrath.'),(6033,' Howbeit these things will we let be as past and done, for all our pain, curbing the heart in our breasts, because we must.'),(6034,' But now will I go forth that I may light on the slayer of the man I loved,  even on Hector; '),(6035,'for my fate, I will accept it whenso Zeus willeth to bring it to pass, and the other immortal gods.'),(6036,' For not even the mighty Heracles escaped death, albeit he was most dear to Zeus, son of Cronos, the king, '),(6037,'but fate overcame him, and the dread wrath of Hera.'),(6038,'  So also shall I, if a like fate hath been fashioned for me, lie low when I am dead.'),(6039,' But now let me win glorious renown, and set many a one among the deep-bosomed Trojan or Dardanian dames to wipe with both hands the tears from her tender cheeks, and ceaseless moaning;  and let them know that long in good sooth have I kept apart from the war.'),(6040,' thou shalt not persuade me.\" '),(6041,' thou shalt not persuade me.\" '),(6042,' \nThen answered him the goddess, silver-footed Thetis:'),(6043,' \"Aye, verily, as thou sayest, my child, it is in truth no ill thing to ward utter destruction from thy comrades, that are hard beset.'),(6044,'  But thy goodly armour is held among the Trojans, thine armour of bronze, all gleaming-bright.'),(6045,' This doth Hector of the flashing helm wear on his own shoulders, and exulteth therein.'),(6046,' Yet I deem that not for long shall he glory therein. seeing his own death is nigh at hand.'),(6047,' But do thou not enter into the turmoil of Ares  until thine eyes shall behold me again coming hither.'),(6048,'For in the morning will I return at the rising of the sun, bearing fair armour from the lord Hephaestus.\"'),(6049,'\nSo saying she turned her to go back from her son, and being turned she spake among her sisters of the sea:'),(6050,'  \"Do ye now plunge beneath the broad bosom of the deep, to visit the old man of the sea, and the halls of our father, and tell him all.'),(6051,' But I will get me to high Olympus to the house of Hephaestus, the famed craftsman, if so be he will give to my son glorious shining armour.\"'),(6052,'  So spake she, and they forthwith plunged beneath the surge of the sea,'),(6053,' while she, the goddess, silver-footed Thetis, went her way to Olympus, that she might bring glorious armour for her dear son. '),(6054,' \nHer then were her feet bearing to Olympus, '),(6055,'but the Achaeans fled with wondrous shouting from before man-slaying Hector,  and came to the ships and the Hellespont. '),(6056,'Howbeit Patroclus, the squire of Achilles, might the well-greaved Achaeans not draw forth from amid the darts; '),(6057,'for now again there overtook him the host and the chariots of Troy, and Hector, son of Priam, in might as it were a flame.'),(6058,'  Thrice from behind did glorious Hector seize him by the feet, fain to drag him away, and called mightily upon the Trojans, '),(6059,'and thrice did the two Aiantes, clothed in furious valour, hurl him back from the corpse.'),(6060,' But he, ever trusting in his might, would now charge upon them in the fray, and would now stand  and shout aloud; '),(6061,'but backward would he give never a whit.'),(6062,'And as shepherds of the steading avail not in any wise to drive from a carcase a tawny lion when he hungereth sore, even so the twain warrior Aiantes availed not to affright Hector, Priam\'s son, away from the corpse.'),(6063,'  And now would he have dragged away the body, and have won glory unspeakable, had not wind-footed, swift Iris speeding from Olympus with a message that he array him for battle, come to the son of Peleus, all unknown of Zeus and the other gods, '),(6064,' for Hera sent her forth.'),(6065,' And she drew nigh, and spake to him winged words:'),(6066,'  \"Rouse thee, son of Peleus, of all men most dread.'),(6067,' Bear thou aid to Patroclus, for whose sake is a dread strife afoot before the ships.'),(6068,' And men are slaying one another, these seeking to defend the corpse of the dead, while the Trojans charge on to drag him to windy Ilios; '),(6069,'and above all glorious Hector  is fain to drag him away; '),(6070,' and his heart biddeth him shear the head from the tender neck, and fix it on the stakes of the wall.'),(6071,' Nay, up then, lie here no more!'),(6072,' Let awe come upon thy soul that Patroclus should become the sport of the dogs of Troy. '),(6073,'  Thine were the shame, if anywise he come, a corpse despitefully entreated.”'),(6074,' \nThen swift-footed goodly Achilles answered her:'),(6075,' \"Goddess Iris, who of the gods sent thee a messenger to me?\"'),(6076,'\nAnd to him again spake wind-footed, swift Iris:'),(6077,' \"Hera sent me forth, the glorious wife of Zeus; '),(6078,' and the son of Cronos, throned on high, knoweth naught hereof, neither any other of the immortals that dwell upon snowy Olympus.\"'),(6079,'\nThen in answer to her spake Achilles, swift of foot: '),(6080,'They yonder hold my battle-gear;'),(6081,'They yonder hold my battle-gear;'),(6082,'and my dear mother forbade that I array me for the fight  until such time as mine eyes should behold her again coming hither; '),(6083,'for she pledged her to bring goodly armour from Hephaestus.'),(6084,' No other man know I whose glorious armour I might don, except it were the shield of Aias, son of Telamon.'),(6085,' Howbeit himself, I ween, hath dalliance amid the foremost fighters,  as he maketh havoc with his spear in defence of dead Patroclus.\"'),(6086,'And to him again spake wind-footed, swift Iris:'),(6087,' \"Well know we of ourselves that thy glorious armour is held of them; '),(6088,'but even as thou art go thou to the trench, and show thyself to the men of Troy, if so be that, seized with fear of thee,  the Trojans may desist from battle, and the warlike sons of the Achaeans may take breath, wearied as they are; '),(6089,'for scant is the breathing-space in war.\"'),(6090,'When she had thus spoken swift-footed Iris departed; but Achilles, dear to Zeus, roused him,'),(6091,'and round about his mighty shoulders Athene flung her tasselled aegis,  and around his head the fair goddess set thick a golden cloud, and forth from the man made blaze a gleaming fire.'),(6092,' And as when a smoke goeth up from a city and reacheth to heaven from afar, from an island that foes beleaguer, and the men thereof contend the whole day through in hateful war  from their city\'s walls,'),(6093,' and then at set of sun flame forth the beacon-fires one after another and high aloft darteth the glare thereof for dwellers round about to behold, if so be they may come in their ships to be warders off of bane; '),(6094,'even so from the head of Achilles went up the gleam toward heaven.'),(6095,'  Then strode he from the wall to the trench, and there took his stand, yet joined him not to the company of the Achaeans, '),(6096,'for he had regard to his mother\'s wise behest.'),(6097,' There stood he and shouted, and from afar Pallas Athene uttered her voice;  '),(6098,'but amid the Trojans he roused confusion unspeakable.'),(6099,' Clear as the trumpet\'s voice when it soundeth aloud  beneath the press of murderous foemen that beleaguer a city, so clear was then the voice of the son of Aeacus.'),(6100,' And when they heard the brazen voice of the son of Aeacus the hearts of all were dismayed; '),(6101,'and the fair-maned horses  turned their cars backward, '),(6102,'for their spirits boded bane. '),(6103,'And the charioteers were stricken with terror when they beheld the unwearied fire blaze in fearsome wise above the head of the great-souled son of Peleus; '),(6104,' for the goddess, flashing-eyed Athene, made it blaze.'),(6105,' Thrice over the trench shouted mightily the goodly Achilles, and thrice the Trojans and their famed allies were confounded.'),(6106,'  And there in that hour perished twelve men of their best amid their own chariots and their own spears.'),(6107,' But the Achaeans with gladness drew Patroclus forth from out the darts and laid him on a bier, '),(6108,' and his dear comrades thronged about him weeping; '),(6109,'and amid them followed swift-footed Achilles,  shedding hot tears, for that he beheld his trusty comrade lying on the bier, mangled by the sharp bronze. Him verily had he sent forth with horses and chariot into the war, but never again did he welcome his returning.'),(6110,'\nThen was the unwearying sun sent by ox-eyed, queenly Hera  to go his way, full loath, to the stream of Ocean. '),(6111,' So the sun set and the goodly Achaeans stayed them from the fierce strife and the evil war. '),(6112,' \nAnd on their side, the Trojans, when they were come back from the fierce conflict, loosed from beneath their cars their swift horses,  and gathered themselves in assembly or ever they bethought them to sup.'),(6113,' Upon their feet they stood while the gathering was held, neither had any man heart to sit;'),(6114,' for they all were holden of fear, seeing Achilles was come forth, albeit he had long kept him aloof from grievous battle.'),(6115,' Then among them wise Polydamas was first to speak,  the son of Panthous;'),(6116,' for he alone looked at once before and after.'),(6117,' Comrade was he of Hector, and in the one night were they born: howbeit in speech was one far the best, the other with the spear.'),(6118,' He with good intent addressed their gathering, and spake among them: '),(6119,'\"On both sides, my friends, bethink you well. '),(6120,' For my own part I bid you  return even now to the city, neither on the plain beside the ships await bright Dawn, '),(6121,' for afar from the wall are we.'),(6122,' As long as this man continued in wrath against goodly Agamemnon, even so long were the Achaeans easier to fight against; '),(6123,'aye, and I too was glad, when hard by the swift ships I spent the night,  in hope that we should take the curved ships.'),(6124,' But now do I wondrously fear the swift-footed son of Peleus; '),(6125,'so masterful is his spirit, he will not be minded to abide in the plain, where in the midst both Trojans and Achaeans share in the fury of Ares;  but it is for our city that he will fight, and for our wives.'),(6126,'for on this wise shall it be.'),(6127,'for on this wise shall it be.'),(6128,' For this present hath immortal night stayed the swift-footed son of Peleus,'),(6129,' but if on the morrow he shall come forth in harness and light on us yet abiding here, full well shall many a one come to know him; '),(6130,'for with joy shall he that escapeth win to sacred Ilios,  and many of the Trojans shall the dogs and vultures devour—'),(6131,'far from my ear be the tale thereof. '),(6132,' But and if we hearken to my words for all we be loath, this night shall we keep our forces in the place of gathering, and the city shall be guarded by the walls  and high gates and by the tall well-polished doors that are set therein, bolted fast.'),(6133,' But in the morning at the coming of Dawn arrayed in our armour will we make our stand upon the walls; '),(6134,'and the worse will it be for him, if he be minded to come forth from the ships and fight with us to win the wall.'),(6135,'  Back again to his ships shall he hie him, when he hath given his horses, with high-arched necks, surfeit of coursing to and fro, as he driveth vainly beneath the city.'),(6136,' But to force his way within will his heart not suffer him nor shall he lay it waste; '),(6137,'ere that shall the swift dogs devour him.\" '),(6138,' \nThen with an angry glance from beneath his brows spake to him Hector of the flashing helm:'),(6139,'  \"Polydamas, this that thou sayest is no longer to my pleasure, seeing thou biddest us go back and be pent within the city.'),(6140,' In good sooth have ye not yet had your fill of being pent within the walls?'),(6141,' Of old all mortal men were wont to tell of Priam\'s city, for its wealth of gold, its wealth of bronze; '),(6142,' but now are its goodly treasures perished from its homes, and lo, possessions full many have been sold away to Phrygia and lovely Maeonia, since great Zeus waxed wroth.'),(6143,' But now, when the son of crooked-counselling Cronos hath vouchsafed me to win glory at the ships, and to pen the Achaeans, beside the sea,  no longer, thou fool, do thou show forth counsels such as these among the folk.'),(6144,' I will not suffer it.'),(6145,' I will not suffer it.'),(6146,' Nay, come; even as I shall bid, let us all obey: '),(6147,'for this present take ye your supper throughout the host by companies, and take heed to keep watch, and be wakeful every man.'),(6148,'  And of the Trojans whoso is distressed beyond measure for his goods, let him gather them together and give them to the folk for them to feast thereon in common; '),(6149,' better were it that they have profit thereof than the Achaeans.'),(6150,'But in the morning, at the coming of Dawn, arrayed in our armour, let us arouse sharp battle at the hollow ships. '),(6151,'But if in deed and in truth goodly Achilles is arisen by the ships, the worse shall it be for him, if he so will it. '),(6152,'I verily will not flee from him out of dolorous war, but face to face will I stand against him, whether he shall win great victory, or haply I. '),(6153,'Alike to all is the god of war, and lo, he slayeth him that would slay.\"'),(6154,'So Hector addressed their gathering, and thereat the Trojans shouted aloud, fools that they were!'),(6155,' for from them Pallas Athene took away their wits.'),(6156,' To Hector they all gave praise in his ill advising, but Polydamas no man praised, albeit he devised counsel that was good.'),(6157,' So then they took supper throughout the host; '),(6158,'but the Achaeans  the whole night through made moan in lamentation for Patroclus. '),(6159,'And among them the son of Peleus began the vehement lamentation, laying his man-slaying hands upon the breast of his comrade and uttering many a groan, even as a bearded lion whose whelps some hunter of stags hath snatched away  from out the thick wood; '),(6160,' and the lion coming back thereafter grieveth sore, and through many a glen he rangeth on the track of the footsteps of the man, if so be he may anywhere find him; '),(6161,'for anger exceeding grim layeth hold of him.'),(6162,' Even so with heavy groaning spake Achilles among the Myrmidons: '),(6163,' \n\"Out upon it! Vain in sooth was the word I uttered on that day,  when I sought to hearten the warrior Menoetius in our halls; '),(6164,'and said that when I had sacked Ilios I would bring back to him unto Opoeis his glorious son with the share of the spoil that should fall to his lot.'),(6165,' But lo, Zeus fulfilleth not for men all their purposes; '),(6166,'for both of us twain are fated to redden the selfsame earth with our blood  here in the land of Troy; since neither shall I come back to be welcomed of the old knight Peleus in his halls, nor of my mother Thetis, but even here shall the earth hold me fast.'),(6167,' But now, Patroclus, seeing I shall after thee pass beneath the earth, I will not give thee burial till I have brought hither the armour and the head of Hector,  the slayer of thee, the great-souled; '),(6168,' and of twelve glorious sons of the Trojans will I cut the throats before thy pyre in my wrath at thy slaying. '),(6169,' Until then beside the beaked ships shalt thou lie, even as thou art, and round about thee shall deep-bosomed Trojan and Dardanian women  make lament night and day with shedding of tears, even they that we twain got us through toil by our might and our long spears, when we wasted rich cities of mortal men.\"'),(6170,'\nSo saying, goodly Achilles bade his comrades set upon the fire a great cauldron, that with speed  they might wash from Patroclus the bloody gore.'),(6171,'And they set upon the blazing fire the cauldron for filling the bath, and poured in water, and took billets of wood and kindled them beneath it.'),(6172,' Then the fire played about the belly of the cauldron, and the water grew warm. '),(6173,'But when the water boiled in the bright bronze,  then they washed him and anointed him richly with oil, filling his wounds with ointment of nine years old; '),(6174,' and they laid him upon his bed, and covered him with a soft linen cloth from head to foot, and thereover with a white robe.'),(6175,' So the whole night through around Achilles, swift of foot,  the Myrmidons made moan in lamentation for Patroclus; '),(6176,'but Zeus spake unto Hera, his sister and his wife:'),(6177,' \"Thou hast then had thy way, O ox-eyed, queenly Hera; thou hast aroused Achilles, swift of foot.'),(6178,' In good sooth must the long-haired Achaeans be children of thine own womb.\" '),(6179,' \n  Then made answer to him the ox-eyed, queenly Hera: '),(6180,' \"Most dread son of Cronos, what a word hast thou said.'),(6181,' Lo, even a man, I ween, is like to accomplish what he can for another man, one that is but mortal, and knoweth not all the wisdom that is mine. '),(6182,'How then was I, that avow me to be highest of goddesses  in twofold wise, for that I am eldest and am called thy wife, and thou art king among all the immortals—how was I not in my wrath against the Trojans to devise against them evil?\"'),(6183,'\nOn this wise spake they one to the other; '),(6184,'but silver-footed Thetis came unto the house of Hephaestus,  imperishable, decked with stars, preeminent among the houses of immortals, wrought all of bronze, that the crook-foot god himself had built him.'),(6185,' Him she found sweating with toil as he moved to and fro about his bellows in eager haste; '),(6186,'for he was fashioning tripods, twenty in all, to stand around the wall of his well-builded hall,  and golden wheels had he set beneath the base of each that of themselves they might enter the gathering of the gods at his wish and again return to his house, a wonder to behold.'),(6187,' Thus much were they fully wrought, that not yet were the cunningly fashioned ears set thereon; '),(6188,'these was he making ready, and was forging the rivets.'),(6189,'  And while he laboured thereat with cunning skill, meanwhile there drew nigh to him the goddess, silver-footed Thetis.'),(6190,' And Charis of the gleaming veil came forward and marked her—fair Charis, whom the famed god of the two strong arms had wedded.'),(6191,' And she clasped her by the hand, and spake, and addressed her:'),(6192,'  \"Wherefore, long-robed Thetis, art thou come to our house, an honoured guest, and a welcome?'),(6193,' Heretofore thou hast not been wont to come.'),(6194,' But follow me further, that I may set before thee entertainment.\" '),(6195,' \nSo saying the bright goddess led her on.'),(6196,' Then she made her to sit on a silver-studded chair,  a beautiful chair, richly-wrought, '),(6197,' and beneath was a footstool for the feet;'),(6198,'and she called to Hephaestus, the famed craftsman, and spake to him, saying:'),(6199,'Thetis hath need of thee.\"'),(6200,'Thetis hath need of thee.\"'),(6201,' And the famous god of the two strong arms answered her: '),(6202,'\"Verily then a dread and honoured goddess is within my halls,  even she that saved me when pain was come upon me after I had fallen afar through the will of my shameless mother, that was fain to hide me away by reason of my lameness.'),(6203,' Then had I suffered woes in heart, had not Eurynome and Thetis received me into their bosom—Eurynome, daughter of backward-flowing Oceanus.'),(6204,'  With them then for nine years\' space I forged much cunning handiwork, brooches, and spiral arm-bands, and rosettes and necklaces, within their hollow cave;'),(6205,'and round about me flowed, murmuring with foam, the stream of Oceanus, a flood unspeakable.'),(6206,' Neither did any other know thereof, either of gods or of mortal men,  but Thetis knew and Eurynome, even they that saved me.'),(6207,' And now is Thetis come to my house;'),(6208,' wherefore it verily behoveth me to pay unto fair-tressed Thetis the full price for the saving of my life.'),(6209,' But do thou set before her fair entertainment, while I put aside my bellows and all my tools.\"'),(6210,'\n  He spake, and from the anvil rose, a huge, panting bulk, halting the while,'),(6211,'but beneath him his slender legs moved nimbly.'),(6212,' The bellows he set away from the fire, and gathered all the tools wherewith he wrought into a silver chest; '),(6213,'and with a sponge wiped he his face and his two hands withal,  and his mighty neck and shaggy breast, and put upon him a tunic, and grasped a stout staff, and went forth halting;'),(6214,' but there moved swiftly to support their lord handmaidens wrought of gold in the semblance of living maids.'),(6215,' In them is understanding in their hearts, and in them speech  and strength, and they know cunning handiwork by gift of the immortal gods.'),(6216,' These busily moved to support their lord,'),(6217,' and he, limping nigh to where Thetis was, sat him down upon a shining chair; and he clasped her by the hand, and spake, and addressed her:'),(6218,' \"Wherefore, long-robed Thetis, art thou come to our house,  an honoured guest and a welcome? '),(6219,' Heretofore thou hast not been wont to come.'),(6220,' Speak what is in thy mind;'),(6221,' my heart bids me fulfill it, if fulfill it I can, and it is a thing that hath fulfillment.\" '),(6222,' \nAnd Thetis made answer to him, shedding tears the while: '),(6223,'\"Hephaestus, is there now any goddess, of all those that are in Olympus,  that hath endured so many grievous woes in her heart as are the sorrows that Zeus, son of Cronos, hath given me beyond all others?'),(6224,' Of all the daughters of the sea he subdued me alone to a mortal, even to Peleus, son of Aeacus, and I endured the bed of a mortal albeit sore against my will.'),(6225,'And lo, he lieth  in his halls fordone with grievous old age, but now other griefs are mine. A son he gave me to bear and to rear, pre-eminent among warriors,'),(6226,' and he shot up like a sapling; '),(6227,'then when I had reared him as a tree in a rich orchard plot, I sent him forth in the beaked ships to Ilios  to war with the Trojans; '),(6228,' but never again shall I welcome him back to his home, to the house of Peleus.'),(6229,' And while yet he liveth, and beholdeth the light of the sun, he hath sorrow, nor can I any wise help him, though I go to him.'),(6230,' The girl that the sons of the Achaeans chose out for him as a prize,  her hath the lord Agamemnon taken back from out his arms.'),(6231,' Verily in grief for her was he wasting his heart;'),(6232,' but the Achaeans were the Trojans penning at the sterns of the ships, and would not suffer them to go forth.'),(6233,' And to him the elders of the Argives made prayer, and named many glorious gifts.'),(6234,'  Then albeit he refused himself to ward from them ruin, yet clad he Patroclus in his own armour and sent him into the war, and added therewithal much people.'),(6235,' All day long they fought around the Scaean gates, '),(6236,'and on that selfsame day had laid the city waste, but that,  after the valiant son of Menoetius had wrought sore harm, Apollo slew him amid the foremost fighters and gave glory to Hector.'),(6237,' Therefore am I now come to thy knees, if so be thou wilt be minded to give my son, that is doomed to a speedy death, shield and helmet, and goodly greaves fitted with ankle-pieces,  and corselet. '),(6238,' For the harness that was his aforetime his trusty comrade lost, when he was slain by the Trojans; '),(6239,'and my son lieth on the ground in anguish of heart.\" '),(6240,' \nThen the famous god of the two strong arms answered her:'),(6241,'neither let these things distress thy heart. '),(6242,'neither let these things distress thy heart. '),(6243,'Would that I might so surely avail to hide him afar from dolorous death,  when dread fate cometh upon him, as verily goodly armour shall be his, such that in aftertime many a one among the multitude of men shall marvel, whosoever shall behold it.\"'),(6244,'\nSo saying he left her there and went unto his bellows, '),(6245,'and he turned these toward the fire and bade them work.'),(6246,'  And the bellows, twenty in all, blew upon the melting-vats, sending forth a ready blast of every force, now to further him as he laboured hard, and again in whatsoever way Hephaestus might wish and his work go on.'),(6247,' And on the fire he put stubborn bronze and tin  and precious gold and silver; '),(6248,'and thereafter he set on the anvil-block a great anvil, and took in one hand a massive hammer, and in the other took he the tongs.'),(6249,'\nFirst fashioned he a shield, great and sturdy, adorning it cunningly in every part, and round about it set a bright rim,  threefold and glittering, and therefrom made fast a silver baldric.'),(6250,' Five were the layers of the shield itself;'),(6251,' and on it he wrought many curious devices with cunning skill.'),(6252,'Therein he wrought the earth, therein the heavens therein the sea, and the unwearied sun, and the moon at the full,  and therein all the constellations wherewith heaven is crowned—the Pleiades, and the Hyades and the mighty Orion, and the Bear, that men call also the Wain, that circleth ever in her place, and watcheth Orion, and alone hath no part in the baths of Ocean. '),(6253,' \n  Therein fashioned he also two cities of mortal men exceeding fair.'),(6254,' In the one there were marriages and feastings, and by the light of the blazing torches they were leading the brides from their bowers through the city, and loud rose the bridal song.'),(6255,' And young men were whirling in the dance, and in their midst  flutes and lyres sounded continually;'),(6256,' and there the women stood each before her door and marvelled.'),(6257,' But the folk were gathered in the place of assembly; '),(6258,'for there a strife had arisen, and two men were striving about the blood-price of a man slain; '),(6259,'the one avowed that he had paid all,  declaring his cause to the people, but the other refused to accept aught; '),(6260,'and each was fain to win the issue on the word of a daysman.'),(6261,' Moreover, the folk were cheering both, shewing favour to this side and to that.'),(6262,' And heralds held back the folk,'),(6263,' and the elders were sitting upon polished stones in the sacred circle,  holding in their hands the staves of the loud-voiced heralds. '),(6264,'Therewith then would they spring up and give judgment, each in turn.'),(6265,' And in the midst lay two talents of gold, to be given to him whoso among them should utter the most righteous judgment.'),(6266,'But around the other city lay in leaguer two hosts of warriors  gleaming in armour. '),(6267,' And twofold plans found favour with them, either to lay waste the town or to divide in portions twain all the substance that the lovely city contained within. '),(6268,' Howbeit the besieged would nowise hearken thereto, but were arming to meet the foe in an ambush.'),(6269,'The wall were their dear wives and little children guarding,  as they stood thereon, and therewithal the men that were holden of old age; '),(6270,' but the rest were faring forth, '),(6271,' led of Ares and Pallas Athene, both fashioned in gold, and of gold was the raiment wherewith they were clad. Goodly were they and tall in their harness, as beseemeth gods, clear to view amid the rest,'),(6272,' and the folk at their feet were smaller.'),(6273,'  But when they were come to the place where it seemed good unto them to set their ambush, in a river-bed where was a watering-place for all herds alike, there they sate them down, clothed about with flaming bronze.'),(6274,' Thereafter were two scouts set by them apart from the host, waiting till they should have sight of the sheep and sleek cattle.'),(6275,'  And these came presently, and two herdsmen followed with them playing upon pipes; '),(6276,' and of the guile wist they not at all. '),(6277,' But the liers-in-wait, when they saw these coming on, rushed forth against them and speedily cut off the herds of cattle and fair flocks of white-fleeced sheep, and slew the herdsmen withal.'),(6278,'  But the besiegers, as they sat before the places of gathering and heard much tumult among the kine, mounted forthwith behind their high-stepping horses, and set out thitherward, and speedily came upon them.'),(6279,' Then set they their battle in array and fought beside the river banks, and were ever smiting one another with bronze-tipped spears.'),(6280,'  And amid them Strife and Tumult joined in the fray, and deadly Fate, grasping one man alive, fresh-wounded, another without a wound, and another she dragged dead through the mellay by the feet; '),(6281,'and the raiment that she had about her shoulders was red with the blood of men.'),(6282,' Even as living mortals joined they in the fray and fought;  and they were haling away each the bodies of the others\' slain.'),(6283,'Therein he set also soft fallow-land, rich tilth and wide, that was three times ploughed; '),(6284,'and ploughers full many therein were wheeling their yokes and driving them this way and that. '),(6285,'And whensoever after turning they came to the headland of the field,  then would a man come forth to each and give into his hands a cup of honey-sweet wine; '),(6286,' and the ploughmen would turn them in the furrows, eager to reach the headland of the deep tilth.'),(6287,' And the field grew black behind and seemed verily as it had been ploughed, for all that it was of gold; '),(6288,' herein was the great marvel of the work.'),(6289,'  Therein he set also a king\'s demesne-land,'),(6290,' wherein labourers were reaping, bearing sharp sickles in their hands.'),(6291,' Some handfuls were falling in rows to the ground along the swathe, while others the binders of sheaves were binding with twisted ropes of straw.'),(6292,' Three binders stood hard by them, '),(6293,' while behind them  boys would gather the handfuls, and bearing them in their arms would busily give them to the binders; '),(6294,'and among them the king, staff in hand, was standing in silence at the swathe, joying in his heart.'),(6295,' And heralds apart beneath an oak were making ready a feast, and were dressing a great ox they had slain for sacrifice;'),(6296,' and the women  sprinkled the flesh with white barley in abundance, for the workers\' mid-day meal.'),(6297,' \nTherein he set also a vineyard heavily laden with clusters, a vineyard fair and wrought of gold; '),(6298,'black were the grapes, and the vines were set up throughout on silver poles.'),(6299,' And around it he drave a trench of cyanus, and about that a fence of tin; '),(6300,'  and one single path led thereto, whereby the vintagers went and came, whensoever they gathered the vintage.'),(6301,' And maidens and youths in childish glee were bearing the honey-sweet fruit in wicker baskets. '),(6302,'And in their midst a boy made pleasant music with a clear-toned lyre,  and thereto sang sweetly the Linos-song with his delicate voice; '),(6303,'and his fellows beating the earth in unison therewith followed on with bounding feet mid dance and shoutings.'),(6304,'\nAnd therein he wrought a herd of straight-horned kine: '),(6305,'the kine were fashioned of gold and tin,  and with lowing hasted they forth from byre to pasture beside the sounding river, beside the waving reed.'),(6306,' And golden were the herdsmen that walked beside the kine, four in number, and nine dogs swift of foot followed after them.'),(6307,' But two dread lions amid the foremost kine  were holding a loud-lowing bull, '),(6308,'and he, bellowing mightily, was haled of them,'),(6309,'while after him pursued the dogs and young men.'),(6310,' The lions twain had rent the hide of the great bull, and were devouring the inward parts and the black blood, '),(6311,'while the herdsmen vainly sought to fright them, tarring on the swift hounds.'),(6312,'  Howbeit these shrank from fastening on the lions, but stood hard by and barked and sprang aside.'),(6313,'\nTherein also the famed god of the two strong arms wrought a pasture in a fair dell, a great pasture of white-fleeced sheep, and folds, and roofed huts, and pens. '),(6314,' \n  Therein furthermore the famed god of the two strong arms cunningly wrought a dancing-floor like unto that which in wide Cnosus Daedalus fashioned of old for fair-tressed Ariadne.'),(6315,' There were youths dancing and maidens of the price of many cattle, holding their hands upon the wrists one of the other.'),(6316,'  Of these the maidens were clad in fine linen, while the youths wore well-woven tunics faintly glistening with oil; '),(6317,'and the maidens had fair chaplets, and the youths had daggers of gold hanging from silver baldrics. '),(6318,'Now would they run round with cunning feet  exceeding lightly, as when a potter sitteth by his wheel that is fitted between his hands and maketh trial of it whether it will run; '),(6319,'and now again would they run in rows toward each other.'),(6320,' And a great company stood around the lovely dance, taking joy therein; '),(6321,' and two tumblers whirled up and down through the midst of them as leaders in the dance.'),(6322,'\nTherein he set also the great might of the river Oceanus, around the uttermost rim of the strongly-wrought shield.'),(6323,'\nBut when he had wrought the shield, great and sturdy,  then wrought he for him a corselet brighter than the blaze of fire, and he wrought for him a heavy helmet, fitted to his temples, a fair helm, richly-dight, and set thereon a crest of gold; and he wrought him greaves of pliant tin.'),(6324,'\nBut when the glorious god of the two strong arms had fashioned all the armour,  he took and laid it before the mother of Achilles. '),(6325,'\nAnd like a falcon she sprang down from snowy Olympus, bearing the flashing armour from Hephaestus.'),(6326,' Now Dawn the saffron-robed arose from the streams of Oceanus to bring light to immortals and to mortal men, '),(6327,'and Thetis came to the ships bearing gifts from the god.'),(6328,' And she found her dear son as he lay, clasping Patroclus,  and wailing aloud;'),(6329,'and in throngs round about him his comrades were weeping.'),(6330,' Then in the midst of them the bright goddess came to his side, and she clasped his hand, and spake and addressed him:\"'),(6331,'My child, this man must we let be, for all our sorrow, to lie as he is, seeing he hath been slain once for all by the will of the gods.'),(6332,'  But receive thou from Hephaestus glorious armour, exceeding fair, such as never yet a man bare upon his shoulders.\"'),(6333,'\nSo saying the goddess set down the arms in front of Achilles, '),(6334,'and they all rang aloud in their splendour.'),(6335,' Then trembling seized all the Myrmidons,  neither dared any man to look thereon, but they shrank in fear. '),(6336,'Howbeit, when Achilles saw the arms, then came wrath upon him yet the more, and his eyes blazed forth in terrible wise from beneath their lids, as it had been flame; '),(6337,' and he was glad as he held in his arms the glorious gifts of the god.'),(6338,' But when in his soul he had taken delight in gazing on the glory of them,  forthwith to his mother he spake winged words:'),(6339,'\"My mother, the arms that the god hath given are such as the works of immortals should fitly be, such as no mortal man could fashion.'),(6340,' Now therefore will I array me for battle; '),(6341,' yet am I sore afraid lest meantime flies enter the wounds that the bronze hath dealt on the corpse of the valiant son of Menoetius, and breed worms therein, and work shame upon his corpse—for the life is slain out of him—and so all his flesh shall rot.\"'),(6342,'\nThen the goddess, silver-footed Thetis, answered him:\"'),(6343,'My child, let not these things distress thy heart.'),(6344,'  From him will I essay to ward off the savage tribes, the flies that feed upon men slain in battle.'),(6345,' For even though he lie for the full course of a year, yet shall his flesh be sound continually, or better even than now it is.'),(6346,' But do thou call to the place of gathering the Achaean warriors,  and renounce thy wrath against Agamemnon, shepherd of the host, and then array thee with all speed for battle and clothe thee in thy might.\" '),(6347,' \nSo saying, she filled him with dauntless courage, and on Patroclus she shed ambrosia and ruddy nectar through his nostrils, that his flesh might be sound continually.'),(6348,'\n  But goodly Achilles strode along the shore of the sea, crying a terrible cry, and aroused the Achaean warriors. '),(6349,' And even they that aforetime were wont to abide in the gathering of the ships—they that were pilots and wielded the steering-oars of the ships, or were stewards that dealt out food—  even these came then to the place of gathering, because Achilles was come forth, albeit he had long kept him aloof from grievous war.'),(6350,' Twain there were, squires of Ares, that came limping, even Tydeus\' son, staunch in fight, and goodly Odysseus, leaning each on his spear, '),(6351,'for their wounds were grievous still; '),(6352,'  and they went and sat them down in the front of the gathering.'),(6353,' And last of all came the king of men, Agamemnon, burdened with his wound; '),(6354,'for him too in the fierce conflict had Coon, Antenor\'s son, wounded with a thrust of his bronze-shod spear.'),(6355,' But when all the Achaeans were gathered together,  Achilles, swift of foot, arose among them and said:'),(6356,'\"Son of Atreus, was this then the better for us twain, for thee and for me, what time with grief at heart we raged in soul-devouring strife for the sake of a girl?'),(6357,' Would that amid the ships Artemis had slain her with an arrow  on the day when I took her from out the spoil after I had laid waste Lyrnessus!'),(6358,'Then had not so many Achaeans bitten the vast earth with their teeth beneath the hands of the foemen, by reason of the fierceness of my wrath.'),(6359,' For Hector and the Trojans was this the better,'),(6360,'but long shall the Achaeans, methinks, remember the strife betwixt me and thee.'),(6361,'  Howbeit, these things will we let be as past and done, for all our pain, curbing the heart in our breasts because we must. '),(6362,'Now verily make I my wrath to cease: it beseemeth me not to be wroth for ever unrelentingly; '),(6363,'but come, rouse thou speedily to battle the long-haired Achaeans,  to the end that I may go forth against the Trojans and make trial of them yet again, whether they be fain to spend the night hard by the ships.'),(6364,' Nay, many a one of them, methinks, will be glad to bend his knees in rest, whosoever shall escape from the fury of war, and from my spear.\" '),(6365,' \nSo spake he, and the well-greaved Achaeans waxed glad, for that the great-souled son of Peleus  renounced his wrath. '),(6366,' And among them spake the king of men, Agamemnon, even from the place where he sat, not standing forth in their midst:'),(6367,' \"My friends, Danaan warriors, squires of Ares, meet is it to give ear to him that standeth to speak,  nor is it seemly to break in upon his words;'),(6368,' grievous were that even for one well-skilled. '),(6369,'And amid the uproar of many how should a man either hear or speak?'),(6370,' —hampered is he then, clear-voiced talker though he be.'),(6371,' To the son of Peleus will I declare my mind, '),(6372,'but do ye other Argives give heed, and mark well my words each man of you.'),(6373,'  Full often have the Achaeans spoken unto me this word, and were ever fain to chide me; '),(6374,'howbeit it is not I that am at fault, but Zeus and Fate and Erinys, that walketh in darkness, seeing that in the midst of the place of gathering they cast upon my soul fierce blindness on that day, when of mine own arrogance I took from Achilles his prize.'),(6375,'It is God that bringeth all things to their issue.'),(6376,'It is God that bringeth all things to their issue.'),(6377,' Eldest daughter of Zeus is Ate that blindeth all—a power fraught with bane;'),(6378,' delicate are her feet, '),(6379,'for it is not upon the ground that she fareth, but she walketh over the heads of men, bringing men to harm,'),(6380,'and this one or that she ensnareth.'),(6381,'  Aye, and on a time she blinded Zeus, albeit men say that he is the greatest among men and gods; '),(6382,' yet even him Hera, that was but a woman, beguiled in her craftiness on the day when Alcmene in fair-crowned Thebe was to bring forth the mighty Heracles.'),(6383,'  Zeus verily spake vauntingly among all the gods: '),(6384,'‘Hearken unto me, all ye gods and goddesses, that I may speak what the heart in my breast biddeth me.'),(6385,' This day shall Eileithyia, the goddess of childbirth, bring to the light a man that shall be the lord of all them that dwell round about,  even one of the race of those men who are of me by blood.’'),(6386,'But with crafty mind the queenly Hera spake unto him:'),(6387,'‘Thou wilt play the cheat, and not bring thy word to fulfillment.'),(6388,'Nay, come, Olympian, swear me now a mighty oath that in very truth that man shall be lord of all them that dwell round about,  whoso this day shall fall between a woman\'s feet, even one of those men who are of the blood of thy stock.'),(6389,'’ So spake she; '),(6390,'howbeit Zeus in no wise marked her craftiness, but sware a great oath, and therewithal was blinded sore.'),(6391,' But Hera darted down and left the peak of Olympus,  and swiftly came to Achaean Argos, where she knew was the stately wife of Sthenelus, son of Perseus, '),(6392,'that bare a son in her womb, and lo, the seventh month was come.'),(6393,' This child Hera brought forth to the light even before the full tale of the months, but stayed Alcmene\'s bearing, and held back the Eileithyiae.'),(6394,'  And herself spake to Zeus, son of Cronos, to bear him word:'),(6395,' ‘Father Zeus, lord of the bright lightning, a word will I speak for thy heeding.'),(6396,' Lo, even now, is born a valiant man that shall be lord over the Argives, even Eurystheus, son of Sthenelus, the son of Perseus, of thine own lineage;'),(6397,'not unmeet is it that he be lord over the Argives.'),(6398,'’  So spake she, and sharp pain smote him in the deep of his heart, '),(6399,'and forthwith he seized Ate by her bright-tressed head, wroth in his soul, and sware a mighty oath that never again unto Olympus and the starry heaven should Ate come, she that blindeth all.'),(6400,'  So said he, and whirling her in his hand flung her from the starry heaven,'),(6401,'and quickly she came to the tilled fields of men.'),(6402,' At thought of her would he ever groan, whenso he beheld his dear son in unseemly travail beneath Eurystheus\' tasks.'),(6403,'Even so I also, what time great Hector of the flashing helm  was making havoc of the Argives at the sterns of the ships, could not forget Ate, of whom at the first I was made blind.'),(6404,' Howbeit seeing I was blinded, and Zeus robbed me of my wits, fain am I to make amends and to give requital past counting.'),(6405,' Nay, rouse thee for battle, and rouse withal the rest of thy people.'),(6406,'  Gifts am I here ready to offer thee, even all that goodly Odysseus promised thee yesternight, when he had come to thy hut.'),(6407,' Or, if thou wilt, abide a while, eager though thou be for war, and the gifts shall squires take and bring thee from my ship, to the end that thou mayest see that I will give what will satisfy thy heart.\"'),(6408,'\nThen swift-footed Achilles answered him, and said:'),(6409,'  \"Most glorious son of Atreus, Agamemnon, king of men, for the gifts, to give them if thou wilt, as is but seemly, or to withhold them, rests with thee.'),(6410,' But now let us bethink us of battle with all speed; '),(6411,'it beseemeth not to dally here in talk,  neither to make delay, '),(6412,'for yet is a great work undone—'),(6413,'to the end that many a one may again behold Achilles amid the foremost laying waste with his spear of bronze the battalions of the men of Troy.'),(6414,' Thereon let each one of you take thought as he fighteth with his man.\" '),(6415,' \nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered him and said:'),(6416,'  \"Nay, valiant though thou art, godlike Achilles, urge not on this wise the sons of the Achaeans to go fasting against Ilios to do battle with the men of Troy, since not for a short space shall the battle last when once the ranks of men are met and the god breathes might into either host.'),(6417,'  But bid thou the Achaeans by their swift ships to taste of food and wine; '),(6418,'since therein is courage and strength. '),(6419,'For there is no man that shall be able the whole day long until set of sun to fight against the foe, fasting the while from food; '),(6420,'for though in his heart he be eager for battle,  yet his limbs wax heavy unawares and thirst cometh upon him and hunger withal, and his knees grow weary as he goeth.'),(6421,' But whoso, having had his fill of wine and food, fighteth the whole day long against the foemen, lo, his heart within him is of good cheer, and his limbs wax not weary  until all withdraw them from battle. '),(6422,' Come then, dismiss thou the host, and bid them make ready their meal.'),(6423,' And as touching the gifts, let Agamemnon, king of men, bring them forth into the midst of the place of gathering, that all the Achaeans may behold them with their eyes, and thou be made glad at heart. '),(6424,'And let him rise up in the midst of the Argives  and swear to thee an oath, that never hath he gone up into the woman\'s bed neither had dalliance with her, '),(6425,' as is the appointed way, O king, of men and of women; '),(6426,' and let the heart in thine own breast be open to appeasement.'),(6427,' Thereafter let him make amends to thee in his hut with a feast full rich,  that thou mayest have nothing lacking of thy due. '),(6428,'Son of Atreus, towards others also shalt thou be more righteous hereafter; '),(6429,'for in no wise is it blame for a king to make amends to another, if so be he wax wroth without a cause.\" '),(6430,' \nTo him then spake again the king of men, Agamemnon: '),(6431,' \n \"Glad am I, son of Laertes, to hear thy words, '),(6432,'for duly hast thou set forth the whole matter, and told the tale thereof.'),(6433,' This oath am I ready to swear, and my heart biddeth me thereto, nor shall I forswear myself before the god.'),(6434,' But let Achilles abide here the while, eager though he be for war, '),(6435,' and abide all ye others together, until the gifts be brought from my hut, and we make oaths of faith with sacrifice.'),(6436,' And to thine own self do I thus give charge and commandment:'),(6437,' Choose thee young men, princes of the host of the Achaeans, and bear from my ship the gifts  even all that we promised yesternight to give Achilles, and bring the women withal.'),(6438,'And let Talthybius forthwith make me ready a boar in the midst of the wide camp of the Achaeans, to sacrifice to Zeus and to the Sun.\"'),(6439,'\nBut swift-footed Achilles answered him, and said: '),(6440,'\"Most glorious son of Atreus, Agamemnon, king of men,  at some other time were it e\'en better that ye be busied thus, when haply there shall come between some pause in war, and the fury in my breast be not so great.'),(6441,' Now are they lying mangled, they that Hector, son of Priam, slew, Zeus vouch-safed him glory,  and ye twain are bidding us to meat! '),(6442,'Verily for mine own part would I even now bid the sons of the Achaeans do battle fasting and unfed, and at set of sun make them ready a mighty meal, when we shall have avenged the shame. '),(6443,'Till that shall be, down my throat, at least,  neither drink nor food shall pass, seeing my comrade is dead, who in my hut lieth mangled by the sharp bronze, his feet turned toward the door, while round about him our comrades mourn; '),(6444,'wherefore it is nowise on these things that my heart is set, but on slaying, and blood, and the grievous groanings of men.\" '),(6445,' \n  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(6446,'\"O Achilles, son of Peleus, far the mightiest of the Achaeans, better art thou than I and mightier not a little with the spear, howbeit in counsel might I surpass thee by far, seeing I am the elder-born and know the more; '),(6447,' wherefore let thine heart endure to hearken to my words.'),(6448,' \n Quickly have men surfeit of battle, wherein the bronze streweth most straw upon the ground, albeit the harvest is scantiest, whenso Zeus inclineth his balance, he that is for men the dispenser of battle. '),(6449,'  But with the belly may it nowise be that the Achaeans should mourn a corpse, '),(6450,'for full many are ever falling one after another day by day; '),(6451,' when then could one find respite from toil?'),(6452,' Nay, it behoveth to bury him that is slain, steeling our hearts and weeping but the one day\'s space; '),(6453,' but all they that are left alive from hateful war must needs bethink them of drink and of food, to the end that yet the more we may fight with the foemen ever incessantly, clothed about with stubborn bronze.'),(6454,' And let no man of all the host hold back awaiting other summons beside, '),(6455,' for the summons is this: Ill shall it be for him whoso is left at the ships of the Argives.'),(6456,' Nay, setting out in one throng let us rouse keen battle against the horse-taming Trojans.\" '),(6457,' \nHe spake, and took to him the sons of glorious Nestor, and Meges, son of Phyleus, and Thoas and Meriones and Lycomedes,  son of Creon, and Melanippus; '),(6458,'and they went their way to the hut of Agamemnon, son of Atreus.'),(6459,' Then straightway in the one moment was the word said, and the deed fulfilled.'),(6460,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 19.243-19.244'),(6461,' Seven tripods bare they from the hut, even as he promised him, and twenty gleaming cauldrons and twelve horses; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 243 to line 244'),(6462,' Then Odysseus weighed out ten talents of gold in all, and led the way and with him the other youths of the Achaeans bare the gifts.'),(6463,' These then they set in the midst of the place of gathering, and Agamemnon  rose up, '),(6464,'and Talthybius, whose voice was like a god\'s, took his stand by the side of the shepherd of the people, holding a boar in his hands.'),(6465,' And the son of Atreus drew forth with his hand the knife that ever hung beside the great sheath of his sword, and cut the firstling hairs from the boar, and lifting up his hands  made prayer to Zeus; '),(6466,'and all the Argives sat thereby in silence, hearkening as was meet unto the king.'),(6467,' And he spake in prayer, with a look up to the wide heaven: '),(6468,'\"Be Zeus my witness first, highest and best of gods, and Earth and Sun, and the Erinyes, that under earth  take vengeance on men, whosoever hath sworn a false oath, that never laid I hand upon the girl Briseis either by way of a lover\'s embrace or anywise else, '),(6469,' but she ever abode untouched in my huts.'),(6470,'And if aught of this oath be false, may the gods give me woes  full many, even all that they are wont to give to him whoso sinneth against them in his swearing.\"'),(6471,'He spake, and cut the boar\'s throat with the pitiless bronze,'),(6472,' and the body Talthybius whirled and flung into the great gulf of the grey sea, to be food for the fishes; '),(6473,' but Achilles uprose, and spake among the war-loving Argives:'),(6474,'\n  \"Father Zeus, great in good sooth is the blindness thou sendest upon men.'),(6475,' Never would the son of Atreus have utterly roused the wrath within my breast, nor led off the girl ruthlessly in my despite,'),(6476,' but mayhap it was the good pleasure of Zeus that on many of the Achaeans death should come. '),(6477,' But now go ye to your meal, that we may join in battle.”'),(6478,' \nSo spake he, and hastily brake up the gathering.'),(6479,' Then the others scattered, each to his own ship, but the great-hearted Myrmidons busied themselves about the gifts, and bare them forth to the ship of godlike Achilles.'),(6480,'  And they bestowed them in the huts, and set the women there, and the horses proud squires drave off to the herd.'),(6481,'\nBut Briseis, that was like unto golden Aphrodite, when she had sight of Patroclus mangled with the sharp bronze, flung herself about him and shrieked aloud,  and with her hands she tore her breast and tender neck and beautiful face.'),(6482,'And amid her wailing spake the woman like unto the goddesses:'),(6483,' \"Patroclus, dearest to my hapless heart, alive I left thee when I went from the hut, and now I find thee dead, thou leader of hosts,  as I return thereto:'),(6484,'thus for me doth evil ever follow hard on evil. '),(6485,' My husband, unto whom my father and queenly mother gave me, I beheld mangled with the sharp bronze before our city, and my three brethren whom mine own mother bare, brethren beloved, all these met their day of doom.'),(6486,'  But thou, when swift Achilles slew my husband, and laid waste the city of godlike Mynes, wouldst not even suffer me to weep, but saidest that thou wouldst make me the wedded wife of Achilles, and that he would bear me in his ships to Phthia, and make me a marriage-feast among the Myrmidons.'),(6487,'  Wherefore I wail for thee in thy death and know no ceasing, for thou wast ever kind.\"'),(6488,'\nSo spake she wailing, and thereto the women added their laments; Patroclus indeed they mourned, but therewithal each one her own sorrows.'),(6489,' But around Achilles gathered the elders of the Achaeans, beseeching him that he would eat; '),(6490,'but he refused them, moaning the while:'),(6491,'  \"I beseech you, if any of my dear comrades will hearken unto me, bid me not before the time sate my heart with food or drink, seeing dread grief is come upon me.'),(6492,' Till set of sun will I abide, and endure even as I am.\" '),(6493,' \nSo spake he, and sent from him the other chieftains,  but the two sons of Atreus abode, and goodly Odysseus, and Nestor and Idomeneus and the old man Phoenix, driver of chariots, seeking to comfort him in his exceeding sorrow; '),(6494,'but no whit would his heart be comforted until he entered the mouth of bloody war.'),(6495,' And as he thought thereon he heaved a heavy sigh and spake, saying:'),(6496,'  \"Ah verily of old, thou too, O hapless one, dearest of my comrades, thyself wast wont to set forth in our hut with nimble haste a savoury meal, whenso the Achaeans made haste to bring tearful war against the horse-taming Trojans. '),(6497,'But now thou liest here mangled, and my heart  will have naught of meat and drink, though they be here at hand, through yearning for thee.'),(6498,' Naught more grievous than this could I suffer, not though I should hear of the death of mine own father, who now haply in Phthia is shedding round tears for lack of a son like me, '),(6499,'while I in a land of alien folk  for the sake of abhorred Helen am warring with the men of Troy; '),(6500,' nay, nor though it were he that in Scyrus is reared for me, my son well-beloved —if so be godlike Neoptolemus still liveth. '),(6501,'For until now the heart in my breast had hope that I alone should perish far from horse-pasturing Argos,  here in the land of Troy, but that thou shouldest return to Phthia, that so thou mightest take my child in thy swift, black ship from Scyrus, and show him all things—my possessions, my slaves, and my great high-roofed house.'),(6502,'For by now I ween is Peleus either  dead and gone, or else, though haply he still liveth feebly, is sore distressed with hateful old age, and with waiting ever for woeful tidings of me, when he shall hear that I am dead.\"'),(6503,'\nSo spake he weeping, and thereto the elders added their laments, bethinking them each one of what he had left at home.'),(6504,'  And as they mourned the son of Cronos had sight of them, and was touched with pity; and forthwith he spake winged words unto Athene:'),(6505,'\n\"My child, lo thou forsakest utterly thine own warrior.'),(6506,' Is there then no place in thy thought any more for Achilles?'),(6507,' Yonder  he sitteth in front of his ships with upright horns, mourning for his dear comrade; '),(6508,'the others verily are gone to their meal but he fasteth and will have naught of food.'),(6509,' Nay go, shed thou into his breast nectar and pleasant ambrosia, that hunger-pangs come not upon him.\" '),(6510,' \nSo saying he urged on Athene, that was already eager:'),(6511,'  and she like a falcon, wide of wing and shrill of voice, leapt down upon him from out of heaven through the air.'),(6512,' Then while the Achaeans were arraying them speedily for battle throughout the camp, '),(6513,'into the breast of Achilles she shed nectar and pleasant ambrosia that grievous hunger-pangs should not come upon his limbs; '),(6514,' and then herself was gone to the stout-builded house of her mighty sire, and the Achaeans poured forth from the swift ships. '),(6515,'As when thick and fast the snowflakes flutter down from Zeus chill beneath the blast of the North Wind, born in the bright heaven; even so then thick and fast from the ships were borne the helms, bright-gleaming,  and the bossed shields, the corselets with massive plates, and the ashen spears.'),(6516,' And the gleam thereof went up to heaven, and all the earth round about laughed by reason of the flashing of bronze; '),(6517,'and there went up a din from beneath the feet of men;'),(6518,'and in their midst goodly Achilles arrayed him for battle.'),(6519,'  There was a gnashing of his teeth, and his two eyes blazed as it had been a flame of fire, and into his heart there entered grief that might not be borne.'),(6520,' Thus in fierce wrath against the Trojans he clad him in the gifts of the god, that Hephaestus had wrought for him with toil.'),(6521,' The greaves first he set about his legs:  beautiful they were, and fitted with silver ankle-pieces,'),(6522,'  and next he did on the corselet about his chest.'),(6523,' And about his shoulders he cast the silver-studded sword of bronze, '),(6524,'and thereafter grasped the shield great and sturdy, wherefrom went forth afar a gleam as of the moon.'),(6525,'  And as when forth ower the sea there appeareth to seamen the gleam of blazing fire, and it burneth high up in the mountains in a lonely steading—'),(6526,'but sore against their will the storm-winds bear them over the teeming deep afar from their friends; '),(6527,'even so from the shield of Achilles went up a gleam to heaven, from that shield  fair and richly-dight.'),(6528,' And he lifted the mighty helm and set it upon his head;'),(6529,' and it shone as it were a star—the helm with crest of horse-hair, and around it waved the plumes of gold, that Hephaestus had set thick about the crest.'),(6530,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 19.384-19.385'),(6531,' And goodly Achilles made proof of himself in his armour,  whether it fitted him, and his glorious limbs moved free; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 384 to line 385'),(6532,' And forth from its stand he drew his father\'s spear, heavy and huge and strong, '),(6533,'that none other of the Achaeans could wield, but Achilles alone was skilled to wield it, '),(6534,' even the Pelian spear of ash that Cheiron had given to his dear father from the peak of Pelion, to be for the slaying of warriors.'),(6535,' And Automedon and Alcinous set them busily to yoke the horses, '),(6536,'and about them they set the fair breast-straps, and cast bits within their jaws, and drew the reins  behind to the jointed car.'),(6537,' And Automedon grasped in his hand the bright lash, that fitted it well, and leapt upon the car;'),(6538,' and behind him stepped Achilles harnessed for fight, gleaming in his armour like the bright Hyperion. Then terribly he called aloud to the horses of his father:'),(6539,'\n  \"Xanthus and Balius, ye far-famed children of Podarge, in some other wise bethink you to bring your charioteer back safe to the host of the Danaans, when we have had our fill of war, and leave ye not him there dead, as ye did Patroclus.\"'),(6540,'\nThen from beneath the yoke spake to him the horse Xanthus, of the swift-glancing feet; '),(6541,' on a sudden he bowed his head, and all his mane streamed from beneath the yoke-pad beside the yoke, and touched the ground; '),(6542,' and the goddess, white-armed Hera, gave him speech:'),(6543,'\"Aye verily, yet for this time will we save thee, mighty Achilles,'),(6544,' albeit the day of doom is nigh thee, '),(6545,'nor shall we be the cause thereof,  but a mighty god and overpowering Fate. '),(6546,' For it was not through sloth or slackness of ours that the Trojans availed to strip the harness from the shoulders of Patroclus, '),(6547,' but one, far the best of gods, even he that fair-haired Leto bare, slew him amid the foremost fighters and gave glory to Hector.'),(6548,'  But for us twain, we could run swift as the blast of the West Wind, which, men say, is of all winds the fleetest; '),(6549,'nay, it is thine own self that art fated to be slain in fight by a god and a mortal.\"'),(6550,'\nWhen he had thus spoken, the Erinyes checked his voice.'),(6551,' Then, his heart mightily stirred, spake to him swift-footed Achilles:'),(6552,' Thou needest not at all.'),(6553,' Thou needest not at all.'),(6554,' Well know I even of myself that it is my fate to perish here, far from my father dear, and my mother;'),(6555,' howbeit even so will I not cease, until I have driven the Trojans to surfeit of war.\"'),(6556,'\nHe spake, and with a cry drave amid the foremost his single-hooved horses.'),(6557,' So by the beaked ships around thee, O son of Peleus, insatiate of fight, the Achaeans arrayed them for battle; and likewise the Trojans over against them on the rising ground of the plain.'),(6558,' But Zeus bade Themis summon the gods to the place of gathering from the  brow of many-ribbed Olympus; '),(6559,'and she sped everywhither, and bade them come to the house of Zeus.'),(6560,' There was no river that came not, save only Oceanus, nor any nymph, of all that haunt the fair copses, the springs that feed the rivers, and the grassy meadows.'),(6561,'  And being come to the house of Zeus they sate them down within the polished colonnades which for father Zeus Hephaestus had builded with cunning skill.'),(6562,'\nThus were they gathered within the house of Zeus; '),(6563,'nor did the Shaker of Earth fail to heed the call of the goddess, but came forth from the sea to join their company;  and he sate him in the midst, and made question concerning the purpose of Zeus:'),(6564,' \"Wherefore, thou lord of the bright lightning, hast thou called the gods to the place of gathering? '),(6565,'Is it that thou art pondering on somewhat concerning the Trojans and Achaeans? '),(6566,'for now is their battle and fighting kindled hard at hand.\"'),(6567,'Then Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, answered him, and said: '),(6568,' \"Thou knowest, O Shaker of Earth, the purpose in my breast, for the which I gathered you hither;'),(6569,' I have regard unto them, even though they die. '),(6570,'Yet verily, for myself will I abide here sitting in a fold of Olympus, wherefrom I will gaze and make glad my heart;'),(6571,' but do ye others all go forth till ye be come among the Trojans and Achaeans, and bear aid to this side or that, even as the mind of each may be.'),(6572,'  For if Achilles shall fight alone against the Trojans, not even for a little space will they hold back the swift-footed son of Peleus.'),(6573,' Nay, even aforetime were they wont to tremble as they looked upon him, '),(6574,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 20.29-20.30'),(6575,' \n  So spake the son of Cronos, and roused war unabating.'),(6576,' And the gods went their way into the battle, being divided in counsel:'),(6577,' Hera gat her to the gathering of the ships, and with her Pallas Athene, and Poseidon, the Shaker of Earth, and the helper Hermes, that was beyond all in the cunning of his mind; '),(6578,' and together with these went Hephaestus, exulting in his might, halting, but beneath him his slender legs moved nimbly;'),(6579,'but unto the Trojans went Ares, of the flashing helm, and with him Phoebus, of the unshorn locks, and Artemis, the archer,  and Leto and Xanthus and laughter-loving Aphrodite.'),(6580,'\nNow as long as the gods were afar from the mortal men, even for so long triumphed the Achaeans mightily, seeing Achilles was come forth, albeit he had long kept him aloof from grievous battle; '),(6581,'but upon the Trojans came dread trembling on the limbs of every man  in their terror, when they beheld the swift-footed son of Peleus, flaming in his harness, the peer of Ares, the bane of men.'),(6582,' But when the Olympians were come into the midst of the throng of men, then up leapt mighty Strife, the rouser of hosts, and Athene cried a1oud,—now would she stand beside the digged trench without the wall,  and now upon the loud-sounding shores would she utter her loud cry. '),(6583,'And over against her shouted Ares, dread as a dark whirlwind, calling with shrill tones to the Trojans from the topmost citadel, and now again as he sped by the shore of Simois over Callicolone. '),(6584,' \nThus did the blessed gods urge on the two hosts to  clash in battle, and amid them made grievous strife to burst forth.'),(6585,' Then terribly thundered the father of gods and men from on high;'),(6586,' and from beneath did Poseidon cause the vast earth to quake, and the steep crests of the mountains.'),(6587,' All the roots of many-fountained Ida were shaken,  and all her peaks, and the city of the Trojans, and the ships of the Achaeans. '),(6588,' And seized with fear in the world below was Aidoneus, lord of the shades, and in fear leapt he from his throne and cried aloud, lest above him the earth be cloven by Poseidon, the Shaker of Earth, and his abode be made plain to view for mortals and immortals-  the dread and dank abode, wherefor the very gods have loathing: '),(6589,'\n so great was the din that arose when the gods clashed in strife.'),(6590,' For against king Poseidon stood Phoebus Apollo with his winged arrows, and against Enyalius the goddess, flashing-eyed Athene;'),(6591,' against Hera stood forth the huntress of the golden arrows, and the echoing chase, even the archer Artemis, sister of the god that smiteth afar; '),(6592,' against Leto stood forth the strong helper, Hermes, and against Hephaestus the great, deep-eddying river, that god called Xanthus, and men Scamander.'),(6593,' Thus gods went forth to meet with gods.'),(6594,' But Achilles was fain to meet with Hector, Priam\'s son, above all others in the throng,'),(6595,'for with his blood as with that of none other did his spirit bid him glut Ares, the warrior with tough shield of hide.'),(6596,' Howbeit Aeneas did Apollo, rouser of hosts, make to go forth  to face the son of Peleus, and he put into him great might: '),(6597,'and he likened his own voice to that of Lycaon, son of Priam.'),(6598,' In his likeness spake unto Aeneas the son of Zeus, Apollo:\"'),(6599,'Aeneas, counsellor of the Trojans, where be now thy threats, wherewith thou wast wont to declare unto the princes of the Trojans over thy wine,  that thou wouldst do battle man to man against Achilles, son of Peleus?”'),(6600,' \nThen Aeneas answered him, and said:'),(6601,' \"Son of Priam, why on this wise do thou bid me face in fight the son of Peleus, high of heart, though I be not minded thereto?'),(6602,'  Not now for the first time shall I stand forth against swift-footed Achilles; nay, once ere now he drave me with his spear from Ida, when he had come forth against our kine, and laid Lyrnessus waste and Pedasus withal; '),(6603,'howbeit Zeus saved me, who roused my strength and made swift my knees. '),(6604,'Else had I been slain beneath the hands of Achilles and of Athene,  who ever went before him and set there a light of deliverance, and bade him slay Leleges and Trojans with spear of bronze.'),(6605,' Wherefore may it not be that any man face Achilles in fight,'),(6606,' for that ever by his side is some god, that wardeth from him ruin.'),(6607,' Aye, and of itself his spear flieth straight, and ceaseth not  till it have pierced through the flesh of man.'),(6608,'Howbeit were a god to stretch with even hand the issue of war, then not lightly should he vanquish me, nay, not though he vaunt him to be wholly wrought of bronze.\"'),(6609,'\nThen in answer to him spake the prince Apollo, son of Zeus:'),(6610,' \"Nay, warrior, come, pray thou also  to the gods that are for ever; '),(6611,'for of thee too men say that thou wast born of Aphrodite, daughter of Zeus, while he is sprung from a lesser goddess.'),(6612,' For thy mother is daughter of Zeus, and his of the old man of the sea.'),(6613,' Nay, bear thou straight against him thy stubborn bronze, nor let him anywise turn thee back with words of contempt and with threatenings.\" '),(6614,' \n  So saying he breathed great might into the shepherd of the host, and he strode amid the foremost fighters, harnessed in flaming bronze.'),(6615,' Nor was the son of Anchises unseen of white-armed Hera, as he went forth to face the son of Peleus amid the throng of men,'),(6616,'but she gathered the gods together, and spake among them, saying:'),(6617,'  \"Consider within your hearts, ye twain, O Poseidon and Athene, how these things are to be.'),(6618,' Lo, here is Aeneas, gone forth, harnessed in flaming bronze, to face the son of Peleus, and it is Phoebus Apollo that hath set him on.'),(6619,'  Come ye then, let us turn him back forthwith; or else thereafter let one of us stand likewise by Achilles\' side, and give him great might, and suffer not the heart in his breast anywise to fail; to the end that he may know that they that love him are the best of the immortals, and those are worthless as wind, that hitherto have warded from thie Trojans war and battle.'),(6620,'  All we are come down from Olympus to mingle in this battle, that Achilles take no hurt among the Trojans for this days\' space; '),(6621,' but thereafter shall he suffer whatever Fate spun for him with her thread at his birth, when his mother bare him.'),(6622,'But if Achilles learn not this from some voice of the gods,  he shall have dread hereafter when some god shall come against him in battle; '),(6623,'for hard are the gods to look upon when they appear in manifest presence.\"'),(6624,'Then Poseidon, the Shaker of Earth, answered her:'),(6625,'thou needest not at all.'),(6626,'thou needest not at all.'),(6627,' I verily were not fain to make gods chash  with gods in strife, since indeed we are far too strong for them.'),(6628,'Nay, for our part let us rather go apart from the track unto some place of outlook, and sit us there, and war shall be for men.'),(6629,'But if so be Ares or Phoebus Apollo shall make beginning of fight, or shall keep Achilles in check and suffer him not to do battle,  then forthwith from us likewise shall the strife of war arise; '),(6630,'and right soon, methinks, shall they separate them from the battle and hie them back to Olympus, to the gathering of the other gods, vanquished beneath our hands perforce.\" '),(6631,' \nSo saying, the dark-haired god led the way  to the heaped-up wall of godlike Heracles, the high wall that the Trojans and Pallas Athene had builded for him, to the end that he might flee thither and escape from the monster of the deep, whenso the monster drave him from the seashore to the plain.'),(6632,' There Poseidon and the other gods sate them down,  and clothed their shoulders round about with a cloud that might not be rent; '),(6633,'and they of the other part sat over against them on the brows of Callicolone, round about thee, O archer Phoebus, and Ares, sacker of cities.'),(6634,' So sat they on either side devising counsels,'),(6635,' but to make beginning of grievous war  both sides were loath, albeit Zeus, that sitteth on high, had bidden them.'),(6636,'Howbeit the whole plain was filled with men and horses, and aflame with bronze,'),(6637,' and the earth resounded beneath their feet as they rushed together;'),(6638,'and two warriors best by far of all came one against the other into the space between the two hosts, eager to do battle,  even Aeneas, Anchises\' son, and goodly Achilles.'),(6639,' Aeneas first strode forth with threatening mien, his heavy hem nodding above him; '),(6640,'his valorous shield he held before his breast, and he brandished a spear of bronze. '),(6641,' And on the other side the son of Peleus rushed against him him like a lion,  a ravening lion that men are fain to slay, even a whole folk that be gathered together;'),(6642,'and he at the first recking naught of them goeth his way, but when one of the youths swift in battle hath smitten him with a spear-cast, then he gathereth himself open-mouthed, and foam cometh forth about his teeth, and in his heart his valiant spirit groaneth,  and with his tail he lasheth his ribs and his flanks on this side and on that, and rouseth himself to fight, and with glaring eyes he rusheth straight on in his fury, whether he slay some man or himself be slain in the foremost throng; '),(6643,' even so was Achilles driven by his fury,  and his lordly spirit to go forth to face great-hearted Aeneas.'),(6644,' And when they were come near, as they advanced one against the other, then first unto Aeneas spake swift-footed goodly Achilles:'),(6645,' \"Aeneas, wherefore hast thou sallied thus far forth from the throng to stand and face me? '),(6646,' Is it that thy heart biddeth thee fight with me  in hope that thou shalt be master of Priam\'s sovreignty amid the horse-taming Trojans?'),(6647,' Nay, but though thou slayest me, not for that shall Priam place his kingship in thy hands, '),(6648,' for he hath sons, and withal is sound and nowise flighty of mind.'),(6649,'  Or have the Trojans meted out for thee a demesne pre-eminent above all, a fair tract of orchard and of plough-land, that thou mayest possess it, if so be thou slayest me?'),(6650,' Hard, methinks, wilt thou find that deed.'),(6651,' Aye, for on another day ere now methinks I drave thee before my, spear.'),(6652,' Dost thou not remember when thou wast alone and I made thee run from the kine down with swift steps from Ida\'s hills  in headlong haste?'),(6653,' On that day didst thou not once look behind thee in thy flight. '),(6654,'Thence thou fleddest forth to Lyrnessus, '),(6655,'but I laid it waste, assailing it with the aid of Athene and father Zeus, and the women I led captive and took from them the day of freedom;'),(6656,'  but thyself thou wast saved by Zeus and the other gods.'),(6657,'Howbeit not this day, methinks, shall he save thee,  as thou deemest in thy heart;'),(6658,' nay, of myself I bid thee get thee back into the throng and stand not forth to face me, ere yet some evil befall thee; '),(6659,'when it is wrought even a fool getteth understanding.\" '),(6660,' \nThen Aeneas answered him and said:'),(6661,'  \"Son of Peleus, think not with words to afright me, as I were a child, seeing I know well of myself to utter taunts and withal speech that is seemly.'),(6662,' We know each other\'s lineage, and each other\'s parents, for we have heard the tales told in olden days by mortal men;'),(6663,' but with sight of eyes hast thou never seen my parents nor I thine. '),(6664,'Men say that thou art son of peerless Peleus, and that thy mother was fair-tressed Thetis, a daughter of the sea; '),(6665,'but for me, I declare that I am son of great-hearted Anchises, and my mother is Aphrodite.'),(6666,'  Of these shall one pair or the other mourn a dear son this day; '),(6667,'for verily not with childish words, I deem, shall we twain thus part one from the other and return from out the battle.'),(6668,' Howbeit, if thou wilt, hear this also, that thou mayest know well my lineage, and many there be that know it:'),(6669,'  at the first Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, begat Dardanus, and he founded Dardania, for not yet was sacred Ilios builded in the plain to be a city of mortal men, but they still dwelt upon the slopes of many-fountained Ida.'),(6670,' And Dardanus in turn begat a son, king Erichthonius,  who became richest of mortal men. '),(6671,'Three thousand steeds had he that pastured in the marsh-land; mares were they. rejoicing in their tender foals.'),(6672,' Of these as they grazed the North Wind became enamoured, and he likened himself to a dark-maned stallion and covered them; '),(6673,' and they conceived, and bare twelve fillies. '),(6674,'These, when they bounded over the earth, the giver of grain, would course over the topmost ears of ripened corn and break them not, '),(6675,'and whenso they bounded over the broad back of the sea, would course over the topmost breakers of the hoary brine.'),(6676,'   And Erichthonius begat Tros to be king among the Trojans, '),(6677,'and from Tros again three peerless sons were born, Ilus, and Assaracus, and godlike Ganymedes that was born the fairest of mortal men; '),(6678,'wherefore the gods caught him up on high to be cupbearer to Zeus by reason of his beauty, that he might dwell with the immortals.'),(6679,'  And Ilus again begat a son, peerless Laomedon, '),(6680,'and Laomedon begat Tithonus and Priam and Clytius, and Hicetaon, scion of Ares.'),(6681,' And Assaracus begat Capys, and he Anchises; '),(6682,'but Anchises begat me and Priam goodly Hector.'),(6683,'  This then is the lineage amid the blood wherefrom I avow me sprung. '),(6684,' But as for valour, it is Zeus that increaseth it for men or minisheth it, even as himself willeth, '),(6685,'seeing he is mightiest of all.'),(6686,' But come, no longer let us talk thus like children,  as we twain stand in the midst of the strife of battle. '),(6687,'Revilings are there for both of us to utter, revilings full many; a ship of an hundred benches would not bear the load thereof.'),(6688,' Glib is the tongue of mortals, and words there be therein many and manifold, and of speech the range is wide on this side and on that.'),(6689,'  Whatsoever word thou speakest, such shalt thou also hear.'),(6690,' But what need have we twain to bandy strifes and wranglings one with the other like women, that when they have waxed wroth in soul-devouring strife go forth into the midst of the street  and wrangle one against the other with words true and false; '),(6691,'for even these wrath biddeth them speak.'),(6692,' But from battle, seeing I am eager therefor, shalt thou not by words turn me till we have fought with the bronze man to man;'),(6693,' nay, come, let us forthwith make trial each of the other with bronze-tipped spears.'),(6694,'\nHe spake, and let drive his mighty spear against the other\'s dread and wondrous shield,'),(6695,'and loud rang the shield about the spear-point.'),(6696,'  And the son of Peleus held the shield from him with his stout hand, being seized with dread; '),(6697,'for he deemed that the far-shadowing spear of great-hearted Aeneas would lightly pierce it through—  fool that he was, nor knew in his mind and heart that not easy are the glorious gifts of the gods for mortal men to master or that they give place withal.'),(6698,' Nor did the mighty spear of wise-hearted Aeneas then break through the shield, '),(6699,'for the gold stayed it, the gift of the god.'),(6700,'Howbeit through two folds he drave it, yet were there still three,  for five layers had the crook-foot god welded, two of bronze, and two within of tin, and one of gold, in which the spear of ash was stayed. '),(6701,' \nThen Achilles in his turn hurled his far-shadowing spear and smote upon Aeneas\' shield that was well-balanced upon every side,  beneath the outermost rim where the bronze ran thinnest, and thinnest was the backing of bull\'s-hide; and the shield rang beneath the blow.'),(6702,' The Pelian ash spear crashed clean through it there, and the shield cried out as it went through.'),(6703,' And Aeneas cringed and held from him the shield, being seized with fear; '),(6704,' and the spear passed over his back and was stayed in the ground  for all its fury, albeit it tore asunder two circles of the sheltering shield.'),(6705,' And having escaped the long spear he stood up, and over his eyes measureless grief was shed, and fear came over him for that the spear was planted so nigh.'),(6706,' But Achilles drew his sharp sword and leapt upon him furiously,  crying a terrible cry;'),(6707,'and Aeneas grasped in his hand a stone—a mighty deed—one that not two mortals could bear, such as men are now; '),(6708,' yet lightly did he wield it even alone.'),(6709,'Then would Aeneas have smitten him with the stone, as he rushed upon him, either on helm or on the shield that had warded from him woeful destruction,  and the son of Peleus in close combat would with his sword have robbed Aeneas of life, had not Poseidon, the Shaker of Earth, been quick to see.'),(6710,' And forthwith he spake among the immortal gods, saying: '),(6711,' \"Now look you, verily have I grief for great-hearted Aeneas, who anon shall go down to the house of Hades,  slain by the son of Peleus, for that he listened to the bidding of Apollo that smiteth afar—fool that he was! nor will the god in any wise ward from him woeful destruction. '),(6712,'But wherefore should he, a guiltless man, suffer woes vainly by reason of sorrows that are not his own?—whereas he ever giveth acceptable gifts to the gods that hold broad heaven.'),(6713,'  Nay, come, let us head him forth from out of death, lest the son of Cronos be anywise wroth, if so be Achilles slay him; '),(6714,'for it is ordained unto him to escape, that the race of Dardanus perish not without seed and be seen no more—of Dardanus whom the son of Cronos loved above all the children born to him  from mortal women.'),(6715,' For at length hath the son of Cronos come to hate the race of Priam;'),(6716,' and now verily shall the mighty Aeneas be king among the Trojans, and his sons\' sons that shall be born in days to come.\" '),(6717,' \nThen made answer to him the ox-eyed, queenly Hera:'),(6718,'  \"Shaker of Earth, of thine own self take counsel in thine heart as touching Aeneas, whether thou wilt save him or suffer him to be slain for all his valour by Achilles, Peleus\' son.'),(6719,' We twain verily, even Pallas Athene and I,  have sworn oaths full many among the immortals never to ward off from the Trojans the day of evil, nay, not when all Troy shall burn in the burning of consuming fire, and the warlike sons of the Achaeans shall be the burners thereof.\"'),(6720,'\nNow when Poseidon, the Shaker of Earth, heard this, he went his way amid the battle and the hurtling of spears,  and came to the place where Aeneas was and glorious Achilles.'),(6721,' Forthwith then he shed a mist over the eyes of Achilles, Peleus\' son, '),(6722,'and the ashen spear, well-shod with bronze, he drew forth from the shield of the great-hearted Aeneas '),(6723,' and set it before the feet of Achilles,  but Aeneas he lifted up and swung him on high from off the ground. '),(6724,'Over many ranks of warriors and amny of chariots sprang Aeneas, soaring from the hand of the god, and came to the uttermost verge of the furious battle, where the Caucones were arraying them for the fight. '),(6725,' Then close to his side came Poseidon, the Shaker of Earth,  and he spake, and addressed him with winged words:'),(6726,'\n\"Aeneas, what god is it that thus biddeth thee in blindness of heart do battle man to man with the high-hearted son of Peleus, seeing he is a better man than thou, and therewithal dearer to the immortals?'),(6727,' Nay, draw thou back, whensoever thou fallest in with him, lest even beyond thy doom thou enter the house of Hades.'),(6728,' But when it shall be that Achilles hath met his death and fate, then take thou courage to fight among the foremost, '),(6729,'for there is none other of the Achaeans that shall slay thee.\" '),(6730,' \n  So saying he left him there, when he had told him all. '),(6731,'Then quickly from Achilles\' eyes he scattered the wondrous mist; '),(6732,'and he stared hard with his eyes, and mightily moved spake unto his own great-hearted spirit:'),(6733,' \"Now look you, verily a great marvel is this that mine eyes behold.'),(6734,'  My spear lieth here upon the ground, yet the man may I nowise see at whom I hurled it, eager to slay him.'),(6735,' Verily, it seemeth, Aeneas likewise is dear to the immortal gods, '),(6736,'albeit I deemed that his boasting was idle and vain. '),(6737,'Let him go his way! '),(6738,'no heart shall he find to make trial of me again,  seeing that now he is glad to have escaped from death. '),(6739,'But come, I will call to the war-loving Danaans and go forth against the other Trojans to make trial of them.\"'),(6740,'\nHe spake, and leapt along the ranks, and called to each man:\"'),(6741,'No longer now stand ye afar from the Trojans, ye goodly Achaeans,  but come, let man go forth against man and be eager for the fray.'),(6742,' Hard is it for me, how mighty soever I be, to deal with men so many, and to fight them all; '),(6743,'not even Ares, for all he is an immortal god, nor Athene could control by dint of toil the jaws of such a fray.'),(6744,'  Howbeit so far as I avail with hands and feet and might, in no wise, methiinks, shall I be slack, nay, not a whit; but straight through their line will I go, nor deem I that any of the Trojans will be glad, whosoever shall draw nigh my spear.\"'),(6745,'\nSo spake he, urging them on; '),(6746,' and to the Trojans glorious Hector  ca11ed with a shout, and declared that he would go forth to face Achilles:'),(6747,' \"Ye Trojans, high of heart, fear not the son of Peleus.'),(6748,' I too with words could fight even the immortals, but with the spear it were hard, for they are mightier far, '),(6749,' Neither shall Achilles bring to fulfillment all his words,  but a part thereof will he fulfill, and a part leave incomplete. '),(6750,'Against him will I go forth, though his hands be even as fire, though his hands be as fire and his fury as the flashing steel.\" '),(6751,' \nSo spake he, urging them on; and the Trojans with their faces toward the foe lifted their spears on high, '),(6752,'and the fury of both sides clashed confusedly, and the battle cry arose.'),(6753,' Then Phoebus Apollo drew nigh to Hector, and spake, saying:'),(6754,' \"Hector, no longer do thou anywise stand forth as a champion against Achilles, but in the throng await thou him and from amid the din of conflict, lest so be he smite thee with a cast of his spear or with his sword in close combat.\"'),(6755,'So spake he, and Hector fell back again into the throng of men,  seized with fear, when he heard the voice of the god as he spoke.'),(6756,'But Achilles leapt among the Trojans, his heart clothed about in might, crying a terrible cry, and first he slew Iphition, the valiant son of Otrynteus, the leader of a great host, whom a Naiad nymph bare to Otrynteus, sacker of cities,  beneath snowy Timolus in the rich land of Hyde. '),(6757,'Him, as he rushed straight upon him, goodly Achilles smote with a cast of his spear full upon the head,'),(6758,' and his head was wholly choven asunder. And he fell with a thud, and goodly Achilles exulted over him:\"'),(6759,'Low thou liest, Otrynteus, of all men most dread; '),(6760,' here is thy death, albeit thy birth was by the Gygaean lake, where is the demesne of thy fathers, even by Hyllus, that teems with fish, and eddying Hermus.\"'),(6761,'So spake he vauntingly, but darkness enfolded the other\'s eyes. '),(6762,'Him the chariots of the Achaeans tore asunder  with their tires in the forefront of the fray, '),(6763,'and over him Demoleon, Antenor\'s son, a valiant warder of battle, did Achilles pierce in the temple through the helmet with cheek-pieces of bronze.'),(6764,' Nor did the bronze helm stay the spear, but through it sped the spear-point and brake asunder the bone; and all the brain  was scattered about within; '),(6765,'so stayed he him in his fury. '),(6766,'Hippodamas thereafter, as he leapt down from his car and fled before him, he smote upon the back with a thrust of his spear.'),(6767,' And as he breathed forth his spirit he gave a bellowing cry, even as a bull that is dragged belloweth, when young men drag him about the altar of the lord of Helice; '),(6768,' for in such doth the Shaker of Earth delight;'),(6769,'even so bellowed Hippodamas, as his lordly spirit left his bones.'),(6770,' But Achilles with his spear went on after godlike Polydorus, son of Priam. '),(6771,'Him would his father nowise suffer to fight, for that among his children he was the youngest born  and was dearest in his eyes; and in swiftness of foot he surpassed all. And lo, now in his folly, making show of his fleetness of foot, he was rushing through the foremost fighters, until he lost his life.'),(6772,' Him swift-footed goodly Achilles smote full upon the back with a cast of his spear, as he darted past, even where the golden clasps of the belt  were fastened, and the corselet overlapped;'),(6773,'through this straight on its way beside the navel passed the spear-point, and he fell to his knees with a groan and a cloud of darkness enfolded him, and as he sank he clasped his bowels to him with his hands. '),(6774,' \nBut when Hector beheld his brother Polydorus,  clasping his bowels in his hand and sinking to earth, down over his eyes a mist was shed, '),(6775,'nor might he longer endure to range apart, but strode against Achilles, brandishing his sharp spear, in fashion like a flame.'),(6776,' But when Achilles beheld him, even then sprang he up and spake vauntingly:'),(6777,'  \"Lo, nigh is the man, that above all hath stricken me to the heart, for that he slew the comrade I honoured.'),(6778,' Not for long shall we any more shrink one from the other along the dykes of war.\"'),(6779,'\nHe said, and with an angry glance from beneath his brows spake unto goodly Hector:\"'),(6780,'Draw nigh, that thou mayest the sooner enter the toils of destruction.\"'),(6781,'  But with no touch of fear, spake to him Hector of the flashing helm:'),(6782,'\n\"Son of Peleus, think not with words to affright me, as I were a child, seeing I know well of myself to utter taunts and withal speech that is seemly.'),(6783,' I know that thou art valiant, and I am weaker far than thou.'),(6784,'  Yet these things verily lie on the knees of the gods, whether I,albeit the weaker, shall rob thee of life with a cast of my spear; for my missile too hath been found keen ere now.\"'),(6785,'\nHe spake, and poised his spear and hurled it, but Athene with a breath turned it back from glorious Achilles,  breathing full lightly;'),(6786,'and it came back to goodly Hector, and fell there before his feet.'),(6787,' But Achilles leapt upon him furiously, fain to slay him, crying a terrible cry.'),(6788,' But Apollo snatched up Hector full easily, as a god may, and shrouded him in thick mist.'),(6789,'  Thrice then did swift-footed, goodly Achilles heap upon him with spear of bronze, and thrice he smote the thick mist.'),(6790,' But when for the fourth time he rushed upon him like a god, then with a terrible cry he spake to him winged words:\"'),(6791,'Now again, thou dog, art thou escaped from death, '),(6792,' though verily  thy bane came nigh thee; '),(6793,'but once more hath Phoebus Apollo saved thee, to whom of a surety thou must make prayer, whenso thou goest amid the hurtling of spears.'),(6794,' Verily I will yet make an end of thee, when I meet thee hereafter, if so be any god is helper to me likewise.'),(6795,' But now will I make after others, whomsoever I may light upon.\" '),(6796,' \n  So saying he smote Dryops full upon the neck with a thrust of his spear, '),(6797,' and he fell down before his feet.'),(6798,' But he left him there, and stayed from fight Demuchus, Philetor\'s son, a valiant man and tall, striking him upon the knee with a cast of his spear; '),(6799,'and thereafter he smote him with his great sword, and took away his life.'),(6800,'  Then setting upon Laogonus and Dardanus, sons twain of Bias, he thrust them both from their chariot to the ground, smiting the one with a cast of his spear and the other with his sword in close fight. '),(6801,'Then Tros, Alastor\'s son—he came to clasp his knees, if so be he would spare him, by taking him captive, and let him go alive,  and slay him not, having pity on one of like age, fool that he was! nor knew, he this, that with him was to be no hearkening; '),(6802,' for nowise soft of heart or gentle of mind was the man, but exceeding fierce— '),(6803,'he sought to clasp Achilles\' knees with his hands, fain to make his prayer; but he smote him upon the liver with his sword'),(6804,'and forth the liver slipped,  and the dark blood welling forth therefrom filled his bosom; '),(6805,'and darkness enfolded his eyes, as he swooned.'),(6806,'Then with his spear Achilles drew nigh unto Mulius and smote him upon the ear, '),(6807,' and clean through the other ear passed the spear-point of bronze. '),(6808,'Then smote he Agenor\'s son Echeclus  full upon the head with his hilted sword, and all the blade grew warm with his blood, '),(6809,' and down over his eyes came dark death and mighty fate.'),(6810,' Thereafter Deucalion, at the point where the sinews of the elbow join, even there pierced he him through the arm  with spear-point of bronze; '),(6811,'and he abode his oncoming with arm weighed down, beholding death before him;'),(6812,'but Achilles, smiting him with the sword upon his neck, hurled afar his head and therewithal his helmet; '),(6813,' and the marrow spurted forth from the spine, and the corpse lay stretched upon the ground.'),(6814,' Then went he on after the peerless son of Peires,  even Rhigmus, that had come from deep-soiled Thrace. '),(6815,' Him he smote in the middle with a cast of his spear, and the bronze was fixed in his belly; and he fell forth from out his car.'),(6816,' And Areithous, his squire, as he was turning round the horses, did Achilles pierce in the back with his sharp spear, and thrust him from the car;  '),(6817,'and the horses ran wild. '),(6818,' \n  As through the deep glens of a parched mountainside rageth wondrous-blazing fire, and the deep forest burneth, and the wind as it driveth it on whirleth the flame everywhither, even so raged he everywhither with his spear, like some god, ever pressing hard upon them that he slew; '),(6819,' and the black earth ran with blood.'),(6820,'  And as a man yoketh bulls broad of brow to tread white barley in a well-ordered threshing-floor, and quickly is the grain trodden out beneath the feet of the loud-bellowing bulls; even so beneath great-souled Achilles his single-hooved horses trampled alike on the dead and on the shields; '),(6821,' and with blood  was all the axle sprinkled beneath, and the rims round about the car, for drops smote upon them from the horses\" hooves and from the tires.'),(6822,' But the son of Peleus pressed on to win him glory, and with gore were his invincible hands bespattered.'),(6823,' But when they were now come to the ford of the fair-flowing river, even eddying Xanthus that immortal Zeus begat, there Achilles cleft them asunder, and the one part he drave to the plain toward the city, even where the Achaeans were fleeing in rout  the day before, what time glorious Hector was raging—'),(6824,'thitherward poured forth some in rout, and Hera spread before them a thick mist to hinder them; '),(6825,'but the half of them were pent into the deep-flowing river with its silver eddies. Therein they flung themselves with a great din, and the sheer-falling streams resounded,  and the banks round about rang loudly; '),(6826,' and with noise of shouting swam they this way and that, whirled about in the eddies.'),(6827,' And as when beneath the onrush of fire locusts take wing to flee unto a river,'),(6828,' and the unwearied fire burneth them with its sudden oncoming, and they shrink down into the water; '),(6829,' even so before Achilles was the sounding stream of deep-eddying Xanthus filled confusedly with chariots and with men.'),(6830,'\nBut the Zeus-begotten left there his spear upon the bank, leaning against the tamarisk bushes, and himself leapt in like a god with naught but his sword; and grim was the work he purposed in his heart, and turning him this way  and that he smote and smote; '),(6831,'and from them uprose hideous groaning as they were anchorage in their terror, and the water was reddened with blood.'),(6832,'As before a huge-gaping dolphin the other fishes escaping cram the corners of a deepwater harbour in fear, '),(6833,' for greedily doth he devour whatsoever one he catcheth; '),(6834,' even so cowered the Trojans in the streams of the dread river beneath the steep banks.'),(6835,' And he, when his hands grew weary of slaying, chose twelve youths alive from out the river as blood-price for dead Patroclus, son of Menoetius. '),(6836,'These led he forth dazed like fawns,  and bound their hands behind them with shapely thongs, which they themselves wore about their pliant tunics, and gave them to his comrades to lead to the hollow ships.'),(6837,' Then himself he sprang back again, full eager to slay. '),(6838,' \nThere met he a son of Dardanian Priam  fleeing forth from the river, even Lycaon, whom on a time he had himself taken and brought sore against his will, from his father\'s orchard being come forth in the night; '),(6839,'he was cutting with the sharp bronze the young shoots of a wild fig-tree, to be the rims of a chariot; '),(6840,' but upon him, an unlooked-for bane, came goodly Achilles.'),(6841,'  For that time had he sold him into well-built Lemnos, bearing him thither on his ships, and the son of Jason had given a price for him; '),(6842,' but from thence a guest-friend had ransomed him— and a great price he gave—even Eetion of Imbros, and had sent him unto goodly Arisbe; '),(6843,'whence he had fled forth secretly and come to the house of his fathers.'),(6844,'  For eleven days\' space had he joy amid his friends, being come forth from Lemnos; '),(6845,'but on the twelfth a god cast him once more into the hands of Achilles, who was to send him to the house of Hades, loath though he was to go. '),(6846,'When the swift-footed, goodly Achilles was ware of him,  all unarmed, without helm or shield, nor had he a spear, but had thrown all these from him to the ground; '),(6847,'for the sweat vexed him as he sought to flee from out the river, and weariness overmastered his knees beneath him; '),(6848,'then, mightily moved, Achilles spake unto his own great-hearted spirit:'),(6849,'\"Now look you, verily a great marvel is this that mine eyes behold!'),(6850,'  In good sooth the great-hearted Trojans that I have slain will rise up again from beneath the murky darkness, seeing this man is thus come back and hath escaped the pitiless day of doom, albeit he was sold into sacred Lemnos; '),(6851,'neither hath the deep of the grey sea stayed him, that holdeth back full many against their will.'),(6852,'  Nay, but come, of the point of our spear also shall he taste, that I may see and know in heart whether in like manner he will come back even from beneath, or whether the life-giving earth will hold him fast, she that holdeth even him that is strong.\" '),(6853,' \nSo pondered he, and abode;'),(6854,' but the other drew nigh him, dazed,  eager to touch his knees, and exceeding fain of heart was he to escape from evil death and black fate.'),(6855,' Then goodly Achilles lifted on high his long spear, eager to smite him, but Lycaon stooped and ran thereunder, and clasped his knees; '),(6856,'and the spear passed over his back and was stayed in the ground,  albeit fain to glut itself with the flesh of man. '),(6857,'Then Lycaon besought him, with the one hand clasping his knees while with the other he held the sharp spear, and would not let it go; '),(6858,'and he spake and addressed him with winged words:'),(6859,'and do thou respect me and have pity; '),(6860,'and do thou respect me and have pity; '),(6861,'in thine eyes, O thou  nurtured of Zeus, am I even as a sacred suppliant,'),(6862,'for at thy table first did I eat of the grain of Demeter on the day when thou didst take me captive in the well-ordered orchard, and didst lead me afar from father and from friends, and sell me into sacred Lemnos; and I fetched thee the price of an hundred oxen.'),(6863,'  Lo, now have I bought my freedom by paying thrice as much,'),(6864,' and this is my twelfth morn since I came to Ilios, after many sufferings; '),(6865,' and now again has deadly fate put me in thy hands; '),(6866,'surely it must be that I am hated of father Zeus, seeing he hath given me unto thee again;'),(6867,' and to a brief span of life did my mother bear me, even Laothoe, daughter of the old man Altes,—Altes that is lord over the war-loving Leleges, holding steep Pedasus on the Satnioeis.'),(6868,' His daughter Priam had to wife, and therewithal many another, '),(6869,' and of her we twain were born, and thou wilt butcher us both. Him thou didst lay low amid the foremost foot-men, even godlike Polydorus, when thou hadst smitten him with a cast of thy sharp spear,'),(6870,' and now even here shall evil come upon me; '),(6871,'for I deem not that I shall escape thy hands, seeing a god hath brought me nigh thee.'),(6872,' Yet another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart:'),(6873,'  slay me not; since I am not sprung from the same womb as Hector, who slew thy comrade the kindly and valiant.\" '),(6874,' \nSo spake to him the glorious son of Priam with words of entreaty, but all ungentle was the voice he heard:'),(6875,' \"Fool, tender not ransom to me, neither make harangue.'),(6876,'  Until Patroclus met his day of fate, even till then was it more pleasing to me to spare the Trojans, and full many I took alive and sold oversea; '),(6877,' but now is there not one that shall escape death, whomsoever before the walls of Ilios God shall deliver into my hands—  aye, not one among all the Trojans, and least of all among the sons of Priam.'),(6878,' why lamentest thou thus?'),(6879,' why lamentest thou thus?'),(6880,'Patroclus also died, who was better far than thou. '),(6881,'And seest thou not what manner of man am I, how comely and how tall?'),(6882,' A good man was my father, and a goddess the mother that bare me; '),(6883,'yet over me too hang death and mighty fate.'),(6884,'  There shall come a dawn or eve or mid-day, when my life too shall some man take in battle, whether he smite me with cast of the spear, or with an arrow from the string.\"'),(6885,'\nSo spake he, and the other\'s knees were loosened where he was and his heart was melted.'),(6886,'  The spear he let go, but crouched with both hands outstretched.'),(6887,' But Achilles drew his sharp sword and smote him upon the collar-bone beside the neck, and all the two-edged sword sank in; '),(6888,'and prone upon the earth he lay outstretched, and the dark blood flowed forth and wetted the ground.'),(6889,'  Him then Achilles seized by the foot and flung into the river to go his way, and vaunting over him he spake winged words:'),(6890,'\n\"Lie there now among the fishes that shall lick the blood from thy wound, nor reck aught of thee, '),(6891,'neither shall thy mother lay thee on a bier and make lament;  nay, eddying Scamander shall bear thee into the broad gulf of the sea. '),(6892,' Many a fish as he leapeth amid the waves, shall dart up beneath the black ripple to eat the white fat of Lycaon.'),(6893,' So perish ye, till we be come to the city of sacred Ilios, ye in flight, and I making havoc in your rear.'),(6894,'  Not even the fair-flowing river with his silver eddies shall aught avail you, albeit to him, I ween, ye have long time been wont to sacrifice bulls full many, and to cast single-hooved horses while yet they lived into his eddies.'),(6895,' Howbeit even so shall ye perish by an evil fate till ye have all paid the price for the slaying of Patroclus and for the woe of the Achaeans,  whom by the swift ships ye slew while I tarried afar.”'),(6896,' \nSo spake he, and the river waxed the more wroth at heart, and pondered in mind how he should stay goodly Achilles from his labour and ward off ruin from the Trojans. '),(6897,' Meanwhile the son of Peleus bearing his far-shadowing spear leapt, eager to slay him,  upon Asteropaeus, son of Pelegon, '),(6898,'that was begotten of wide-flowing Axius and Periboea, eldest of the daughters of Acessamenus; '),(6899,'for with her lay the deep-eddying River. '),(6900,'Upon him rushed Achilles, and Asteropaeus  stood forth from the river to face him, holding two spears; '),(6901,'and courage was set in his heart by Xanthus, being wroth because of the youths slain in battle, of whom Achilles was making havoc along the stream and had no pity.'),(6902,' But when they were come near, as they advanced one against the other, then finst unto Asteropaeus spake swift-footed, goodly Achilles:'),(6903,'  \"Who among men art thou, and from whence, that thou darest come forth against me?'),(6904,' Unhappy are they whose children face my might.\"'),(6905,'Then spake unto him the glorious son of Pelegon:'),(6906,'\n \"Great-souled son of Peleus, wherefore enquirest thou of my lineage?'),(6907,' I come from deep-soiled Paeonia, a land afar,  leading the Paeonians with their long spears, '),(6908,'and this is now my eleventh morn, since I came to Ilios.'),(6909,' But my lineage is from wide-flowing Axius—Axius, the water whereof flows the fairest over the face of the earth—who begat Pelegon famed for his spear,  '),(6910,' and he, men say,  was my father. '),(6911,' Now let us do battle, glorious Achilles.”'),(6912,' \nSo spake he threatening, but goodly Achilles raised on high the spear of Pelian ash; '),(6913,' howbeit the warrior Asteropaeus hurled with both spears at once, for he was one that could use both hands alike.'),(6914,' With the one spear he smote the shield,  but it brake not through,'),(6915,'for the gold stayed it, '),(6916,'the gift of the god and with the other he smote the right forearm of Achilles a grazing blow, and the black blood gushed forth; '),(6917,'but the spear-point passed above him and fixed itself in the earth, fain to glut itself with flesh.'),(6918,' Then Achilles in his turn hurled  at Asteropaeus his straight-flying spear of ash, '),(6919,'eager to slay him but missed the man and struck the high bank and up to half its length he fixed in the bank the spear of ash.'),(6920,' But the son of Peleus, drawing his sharp sword from beside his thigh, leapt upon him furiously, '),(6921,' and the other availed not to draw in his stout hand the ashen spear of Achilles forth from out the bank.'),(6922,' Thrice he made it quiver in his eagerness to draw it, and thrice he gave up his effort;'),(6923,' but the fourth time his heart was fain to bend and break the ashen spear of the son of Aeacus; howbeit ere that might be Achilles drew nigh and robbed him of life with his sword.'),(6924,'  In the belly he smote him beside the navel, and forth upon the ground gushed all his bowels, '),(6925,'and darkness enfolded his eyes as he lay gasping.'),(6926,' And Achilles leapt upon his breast and despoiled him of his arms, and exulted saying:'),(6927,' \"Lie as thou art! '),(6928,'Hard is it  to strive with the children of the mighty son of Cronos, albeit for one begotten of a River. '),(6929,'Thou verily declarest that thy birth is from the wide-flowing River, whereas I avow me to be of the lineage of great Zeus.'),(6930,' The father that begat me is one that is lord among the many Myrmidons, even Peleus, son of Aeacus; '),(6931,'and Aeacus was begotten of Zeus.'),(6932,'  Wherefore as Zeus is mightier than rivers that murmur seaward, so mightier too is the seed of Zeus than the seed of a river.'),(6933,' For lo, hard beside thee is a great River, if so be he can avail thee aught; '),(6934,'but it may not be that one should fight with Zeus the son of Cronos. With him doth not even king Achelous vie,  nor the great might of deep-flowing Ocean, from whom all rivers flow and every sea, and all the springs and deep wells;'),(6935,'howbeit even he hath fear of the lightning of great Zeus, and his dread thunder, whenso it crasheth from heaven.\" '),(6936,' \n  He spake, and drew forth from the bank his spear of bronze, and left Asteropaeus where he was, when he had robbed him of his life, lying in the sands; and the dark water wetted him.'),(6937,' With him then the eels and fishes dealt, plucking and tearing the fat about his kidneys; '),(6938,' but Achilles went his way after the Paeonians, lords of chariots, who were still huddled in rout along the eddying river, when they saw their best man mightily vanquished in the fierce conflict beneath the hands and sword of the son of Peleus.'),(6939,' There slew he Thersilochus and Mydon and Astypylus  and Mnesus and Thrasius and Aenius and Ophelestes; '),(6940,'and yet more of the Paeonians would swift Achilles have slain, had not the deep-eddying River waxed wroth and called to him in the semblance of a man, sending forth a voice from out the deep eddy:\"'),(6941,'O Achilles, beyond men art thou in might, and beyond men doest deeds of evil;'),(6942,' for ever do the very gods give thee aid. '),(6943,'If so be the son of Cronos hath granted thee to slay all the men of Troy, forth out of my stream at least do thou drive them, and work thy direful work on the plain.'),(6944,' Lo, full are my lovely streams with dead men, nor can I anywise avail to pour my waters forth into the bright sea,  being choked with dead, while thou ever slayest ruthlessly.'),(6945,' amazement holds me, thou leader of hosts.\"'),(6946,' amazement holds me, thou leader of hosts.\"'),(6947,'\nThen swift-footed Achilles answered him, saying:'),(6948,' \"Thus shall it be, Scamander, nurtured of Zeus, even as thou biddest.'),(6949,'Howbeit the proud Trojan will I not cease to slay  until I have pent them in their city, and have made trial of Hector, man to man, whether he shall slay me or I him.\"'),(6950,'So saying he leapt upon the Trojans like a god. '),(6951,' Then unto Apollo spake the deep-eddying River:'),(6952,'\"Out upon it, thou lord of the silver bow, child of Zeus, thou verily hast not kept the commandment  of the son of Cronos, who straitly charged thee to stand by the side of the Trojans and to succour them, until the late-setting star of even shall have come forth and darkened the deep-soiled earth.\" '),(6953,' \nHe spake, and Achilles, famed for his spear, sprang from the bank and leapt into his midst;'),(6954,'but the River rushed upon him with surging flood, and roused all his streams tumultuously, and swept along the many dead  that lay thick within his bed, slain by Achilles; these lie cast forth to the land, bellowing the while like a bull, '),(6955,' and the living he saved under his fair streams, hiding them in eddies deep and wide.'),(6956,'  In terrible wise about Achilles towered the tumultuous wave, and the stream as it beat upon his shield thrust him backward, '),(6957,'nor might he avail to stand firm upon his feet.'),(6958,' Then grasped he an elm, shapely and tall, '),(6959,' but it fell uprooted and tore away all the bank, and stretched over the fair streams  with its thick branches, and dammed the River himself, falling all within him; '),(6960,' but Achilles, springing forth from the eddy hasted to fly with swift feet over the plain, for he was seized with fear.'),(6961,' Howbeit the great god ceased not, but rushed upon him with dark-crested wave, that he might stay  goodly Achilles from his labour, and ward off ruin from the Trojans. '),(6962,'But the son of Peleus rushed back as far as a spear-cast with the swoop of a black eagle, the mighty hunter, that is alike the strongest and swiftest of winged things; '),(6963,'like him he darted, and upon his breast  the bronze rang terribly, '),(6964,' while he swerved from beneath the flood and fled ever onward, and the River followed after, flowing with a mighty roar.'),(6965,' As when a man that guideth its flow leadeth from a dusky spring a stream of water amid his plants and garden-lots a mattock in his hands and cleareth away the dams from the channel— '),(6966,' and as it floweth all the pebbles beneath are swept along therewith, '),(6967,'and it glideth swiftly onward with murmuring sound down a sloping place and outstrippeth even him that guideth it;'),(6968,'—even thus did the flood of the River  ever overtake Achilles for all he was fleet of foot; '),(6969,'for the gods are mightier than men. '),(6970,'And oft as swift-footed, goodly Achilles strove to make stand against him and to learn if all the immortals that hold broad heaven were driving him in rout, so often would the great flood of the heaven-fed River beat upon his shoulders from above;'),(6971,' and he would spring on high with his feet  in vexation of spirit, '),(6972,'and the River was ever tiring his knees with its violent flow beneath, and was snatching away the ground from under his feet. '),(6973,' Then the son of Peleus uttered a bitter cry, with a look at the broad heaven:\"'),(6974,'Father Zeus, how is it that no one of the gods taketh it upon him in my pitiless plight to save me from out the River!'),(6975,' thereafter let come upon me what may.'),(6976,'  None other of the heavenly gods do I blame so much, but only my dear mother, that beguiled me with false words,'),(6977,'saying that beneath the wall of the mail-clad Trojans I should perish by the swift missiles of Apollo.'),(6978,' Would that Hector had slain me, the best of the men bred here; '),(6979,' then had a brave man been the slayer, and a brave man had he slain. '),(6980,'But now by a miserable death was it appointed me to be cut off, pent in the great river, like a swine-herd boy whom a torrent sweepeth away as he maketh essay to cross it in winter.\"'),(6981,'So spake he, and forthwith Poseidon and Pallas Athene  drew nigh and stood by his side, being likened in form to mortal men, and they clasped his hand in theirs and pledged him in words.'),(6982,' And among them Poseidon, the Shaker of Earth, was first to speak:\"'),(6983,'Son of Peleus, tremble not thou overmuch, neither be anywise afraid, '),(6984,'such helpers twain are we from the gods—  and Zeus approveth thereof —even I and Pallas Athene. '),(6985,'Therefore is it not thy doom to be vanquished by a river; nay, he shall soon give respite, and thou of thyself shalt know it.'),(6986,' But we will give thee wise counsel, if so be thou wilt hearken.'),(6987,'Make not thine hands to cease from evil battle  until within the famed walls of Ilios thou hast pent the Trojan host, whosoever escapeth.'),(6988,' But for thyself, when thou hast bereft Hector of life, come thou back to the ships; '),(6989,'lo, we grant thee to win glory.\" '),(6990,' \nWhen the twain had thus spoken, they departed to the immortals,'),(6991,'but he went on  toward the plain, or mightily did the bidding of the gods arouse him; '),(6992,' and the whole plain was filled with a flood of water, and many goodly arms and corpses of youths slain in battle were floating there.'),(6993,' But on high leapt his knees, as he rushed straight on against the flood, nor might the wide-flowing River stay him; '),(6994,'for Athene put in him great strength.'),(6995,'  Nor yet would Scamander abate his fury, but was even more wroth against the son of Peleus, and raising himself on high he made the surge of his flood into a crest, and he called with a shout to Simois:'),(6996,' \"Dear brother, the might of this man let us stay, though it need the two of us, seeing presently he will lay waste the great city of king Priam,  neither will the Trojans abide him in battle. '),(6997,' Nay, bear thou aid with speed, and fill thy streams with water from thy springs, and arouse all thy torrents; raise thou a great wave, and stir thou a mighty din of tree-trunks and stones, that we may check this fierce man  that now prevaileth, and is minded to vie even with the gods. '),(6998,'For I deem that his strength shall naught avail him, neither anywise his comeliness, nor yet that goodly armour, which, I ween, deep beneath the mere shall lie covered over with slime;'),(6999,'and himself will I enwrap in sands and shed over him great store of shingle  past all measuring; nor shall the Achaeans know where to gather his bones, '),(7000,' with such a depth of silt shall I enshroud him.'),(7001,' Even here shall be his sepulchre, nor shall he have need of a heaped-up mound, when the Achaeans make his funeral.\" '),(7002,' \nHe spake, and rushed tumultuously upon Achilles, raging on high  and seething with foam and blood and dead men. '),(7003,'And the dark flood of the heaven-fed River rose towering above him, and was at point to overwhelm the son of Peleus.'),(7004,' But Hera called aloud, seized with fear for Achilles, lest the great deep-eddying River should sweep him away.  And forthwith she spake unto Hephaestus, her dear son:'),(7005,' \"Rouse thee, Crook-foot, my child!'),(7006,' for it was against thee that we deemed eddying Xanthus to be matched in fight.'),(7007,' Nay, bear thou aid with speed, and put forth thy flames unstintedly.'),(7008,'  But I will hasten and rouse from the sea a fierce blast of the West Wind and the white South, that shall utterly consume the dead Trojans and their battle gear, ever driving on the evil flame; '),(7009,'and do thou along the banks of Xanthus burn up his trees, and beset him about with fire,'),(7010,' nor let him anywise turn thee back with soft words or with threatenings; '),(7011,'  neither stay thou thy fury, save only when I call to thee with a shout; then do thou stay thy unwearied fire.\"'),(7012,'\nSo spake she, and Hephaestus made ready wondrous-blazing fire.'),(7013,' First on the plain was the fire kindled, and burned the dead, the many dead that lay thick therein, slain by Achilles; '),(7014,' and all the plain was parched, and the bright water was stayed. '),(7015,' And as when in harvest-time the North Wind quickly parcheth again a freshly-watered orchard,'),(7016,'and glad is he that tilleth it; '),(7017,'so was the whole plain parched, and the dead he utterly consumed; '),(7018,' and then against the River he turned his gleaming flame.'),(7019,'  Burned were the elms and the willows and the tamarisks, burned the lotus and the rushes and the galingale, that round the fair streams of the river grew abundantly;'),(7020,'tormented were the eels and the fishes in the eddies, and in the fair streams they plunged this way and that,  sore distressed by the blast of Hephaestus of many wiles.'),(7021,' Burned too was the mighty River, and he spake and addressed the god:'),(7022,'\"Hephaestus, there is none of the gods that can vie with thee, nor will I fight thee, ablaze with fire as thou art.'),(7023,' Cease thou from strife,, and as touching the Trojans, let goodly Achilles forthwith  drive them forth from out their city; '),(7024,'what part have I in strife or in bearing aid?”'),(7025,' \nSo spake he, burning the while with fire, and his fair streams were seething.'),(7026,' And as a cauldron boileth within, when the fierce flame setteth upon it, while it melteth the lard of a fatted hog, and it bubbleth in every part, and dry faggots are set thereunder;  so burned in fire his fair streams, and the water boiled; '),(7027,'nor had he any mind to flow further onward, but was stayed; '),(7028,' for the blast of the might of wise-hearted Hephaestus distressed him.'),(7029,' Then with instant prayer he spake winged words unto Hera:'),(7030,' \"Hera, wherefore hath thy son beset my stream to afflict it  beyond all others? '),(7031,'I verily am not so much at fault in thine eyes, as are all those others that are helpers of the Trojans.'),(7032,' Howbeit I will refrain me, if so thou biddest, and let him also refrain. '),(7033,' And I will furthermore swear this oath, never to ward off from the Trojans the day of evil,  nay, not when all Troy shall burn with the burning of consuming fire, and the warlike sons of the Achaeans shall be the burners thereof.\"'),(7034,'\nBut when the goddess, white-armed Hera, heard this plea, forthwith she spake unto Hephaestus, her dear son:\"'),(7035,'Hephaestus, withhold thee, my glorious son; '),(7036,'it is nowise seemly  thus to smite an immortal god for mortals\' sake.\"'),(7037,'So spake she, and Hephaestus quenched his wondrous-blazing fire, and once more in the fair river-bed the flood rushed down.'),(7038,'\nBut when the fury of Xanthus was quelled, the twain thereafter ceased, for Hera stayed them, albeit she was wroth; '),(7039,' but upon the other gods fell strife heavy and grievous, and in diverse ways the spirit in their breasts was blown.'),(7040,' Together then they clashed with a mighty din and the wide earth rang, and round about great heaven pealed as with a trumpet.'),(7041,' And Zeus heard it where he sat upon Olympus,'),(7042,'and the heart within him laughed aloud  in joy as he beheld the gods joining in strife.'),(7043,' Then no more held they long aloof,'),(7044,' for Ares, piercer of shields, began the fray, and first leapt upon Athene, brazen spear in hand, and spake a word of reviling:'),(7045,' \"Wherefore now again, thou dog-fly,  art thou making gods to clash with gods in strife, in the fierceness of thy daring, as thy proud spirit sets thee on? '),(7046,'Rememberest thou not what time thou movedst Diomedes, Tydeus\' son, to wound me, and thyself in the sight of all didst grasp the spear and let drive straight at me, and didst rend my fair flesh?'),(7047,' Therefore shalt thou now methinks, pay the full price of all that thou hast wrought.\" '),(7048,' \n  So saying he smote upon her tasselled aegis—the awful aegis against which not even the lightning of Zeus can prevail—'),(7049,'thereon blood-stained Ares smote with his long spear.'),(7050,' But she gave ground, and seized with her stout hand a stone that lay upon the plain, black and jagged and great,  that men of former days had set to be the boundary mark of a field. '),(7051,'Therewith she smote furious Ares on the neck, and loosed his limbs.'),(7052,' Over seven roods he stretched in his fall, and befouled his hair with dust, and about him his armour clanged.'),(7053,' But Pallas Athene broke into a laugh, and vaunting over him she spake winged words:'),(7054,'  \"Fool, not even yet hast thou learned how much mightier than thou I avow me to be, that thou matchest thy strength with mine.'),(7055,' On this wise shalt thou satisfy to the full the Avengers invoked of thy mother, who in her wrath deviseth evil against thee, for that thou hast deserted the Achaeans and bearest aid to the overweening Trojans.\"'),(7056,' When she had thus spoken, she turned from Ares her bright eyes.'),(7057,'Him then the daughter of Zeus, Aphrodite, took by the hand, and sought to lead away, as he uttered many a moan, '),(7058,'and hardly could he gather back to him his spirit.'),(7059,' But when the goddess, white-armed Hera, was ware of her, forthwith she spake winged words to Athene:'),(7060,'  \"Out upon it, thou child of Zeus that beareth the aegis, unwearied one, lo, there again the dog-fly is leading Ares, the bane of mortals, forth from the fury of war amid the throng;'),(7061,' nay, have after her.\"'),(7062,'\nSo spake she, and Athene sped in pursuit, glad at heart, and rushing upon her she smote Aphrodite on the breast with her stout hand; '),(7063,' and her knees were loosened where she stood, and her heart melted. '),(7064,' So the twain lay upon the bounteous earth, and vaunting over them Athene spake winged words: '),(7065,'\"In such plight let all now be that are aiders of the Trojans when they fight against the mail-clad Argives,  and on this wise bold and stalwart, even as Aphrodite came to bear aid to Ares, and braved my might.'),(7066,' Then long ere this should we have ceased from war, having sacked Ilios, that well-peopled city.\" '),(7067,' \nSo spake she, and the goddess, white-armed Hera smiled thereat. '),(7068,'  But unto Apollo spake the lord Poseidon, the Shaker of Earth:'),(7069,' \"Phoebus, wherefore do we twain stand aloof?'),(7070,' It beseemeth not, seeing others have begun.'),(7071,' Nay, it were the more shameful, if without fighting we should fare back to Olympus, to the house of Zeus with threshold of bronze.'),(7072,'since thou art the younger; '),(7073,'since thou art the younger; '),(7074,'  it were not meet for me, seeing I am the elder-born and know the more.'),(7075,' Fool, how witless is the heart thou hast!'),(7076,' Neither rememberest thou all the woes that we twain alone of all the gods endured at Ilios, what time we came  at the bidding of Zeus and served the lordly Laomedon for a year\'s space at a fixed wage, '),(7077,'and he was our taskmaster and laid on us his commands.'),(7078,' I verily built for the Trojans round about their city a wall, wide and exceeding fair, that the city might never be broken;'),(7079,' and thou, Phoebus, didst herd the sleek kine of shambling gait amid the spurs of wooded Ida, the many-ridged.'),(7080,'  But when at length the glad seasons were bringing to its end the term of our hire, then did dread Laomedon defraud us twain of all hire, and send us away with a threatening word.'),(7081,' He threatened that he would bind together our feet and our hands above, and would sell us into isles that lie afar.'),(7082,' Aye, and he made as if he would lop off with the bronze the ears of us both.'),(7083,' So we twain fared aback with angry hearts, wroth for the hire he promised but gave us not. '),(7084,'It is to his folk now that thou showest favour, neither seekest thou with us that the overweening Trojans may perish miserably  in utter ruin with their children and their honoured wives.\"\nThen spake unto him lord Apollo, that worketh afar: '),(7085,'\"Shaker of Earth, as nowise sound of mind wouldest thou count me, if I should war with thee for the sake of mortals, pitiful creatures, that like unto leaves  are now full of flaming life, eating the fruit of the field, and now again pine away and perish.'),(7086,' Nay, with speed let us cease from strife, '),(7087,' and let them do battle by themselves.\" '),(7088,' \nSo saying he turned him back, '),(7089,'  for he had shame to deal in blows with his father\'s brother.'),(7090,'  But his sister railed at him hotly, even the queen of the wild beasts, Artemis of the wild wood, and spake a word of reviling:\"'),(7091,'Lo, thou fleest, thou god that workest afar, and to Poseidon hast thou utterly yielded the victory, and given him glory for naught!'),(7092,' Fool, why bearest thou a bow thus worthless as wind?'),(7093,'  Let me no more hear thee in the halls of our father boasting as of old among the immortal gods that thou wouldest do battle in open combat with Poseidon.\"'),(7094,' \nSo spake she, but Apollo, that worketh afar, answered her not. Howbeit the revered wife of Zeus waxed wroth, and chid the archer queen with words of reviling:'),(7095,'  \"How now art thou fain, thou bold and shameless thing, to stand forth against me?'),(7096,' No easy foe I tell thee, am I, that thou shouldst vie with me in might, albeit thou bearest the bow, since it was against women that Zeus made thee a lion, and granted thee to slay whomsoever of them thou wilt.'),(7097,'  In good sooth it is better on the mountains to be slaying beasts and wild deer than to fight amain with those mightier than thou. '),(7098,'Howbeit if thou wilt, learn thou of war, that thou mayest know full well how much mightier am I, seeing thou matchest thy strength with mine.\"'),(7099,'Therewith she caught both the other\'s hands by the wrist  with her left hand, and with her right took the bow and its gear from her shoulders, and with these self-same weapons, smiling the while, she beat her about the ears, as she turned this way and that;'),(7100,'and the swift arrows fell from out the quiver.'),(7101,' Then weeping the goddess fled from before her even as a dove that from before a falcon flieth into a hollow rock,  a cleft—'),(7102,'nor is it her lot to be taken;'),(7103,'even so fled Artemis weeping, and left her bow and arrows where they lay.'),(7104,' But unto Leto spake the messenger Argeiphontes:'),(7105,' \"Leto, it is not I that will anywise fight with thee; '),(7106,'a hard thing were it to bandy blows with the wives of Zeus, the cloud-gatherer; '),(7107,' nay, with a right ready heart boast thou among the immortal gods that thou didst vanquish me with thy great might.\" '),(7108,' \nSo spake he, and Leto gathered up the curved bow and the arrows that had fallen hither and thither amid the whirl of dust.'),(7109,' She then, when she had taken her daughter\'s bow and arrows, went back; '),(7110,' but the maiden came to Olympus, to the house of Zeus with threshold of bronze, and sat down weeping upon her father\'s knees, while about her the fragrant robe quivered; '),(7111,'and her father, the son of Cronos, clasped her to him, and asked of her, laughing gently:'),(7112,' \"Who now of the sons of heaven, dear child, hath entreated thee  thus wantonly as though thou wert working some evil before the face of all?\"'),(7113,'Then answered him the fair-crowned huntress of the echoing chase:\"'),(7114,'Thy wife it was that buffeted me, father, even white-armed Hera, from whom strife and contention have been made fast upon the immortals.\"'),(7115,'\nOn this wise spake they one to the other; '),(7116,' but Phoebus Apollo entered into sacred Ilios, '),(7117,'for he was troubled for the wall of the well-builded city, lest the Danaans beyond what was ordained should lay it waste on that day.'),(7118,' But the other gods that are for ever went unto Olympus, some of them in wrath and some exulting greatly,'),(7119,'  and they sate them down beside the Father, the lord of the dark clouds. '),(7120,'But Achilles was still slaying alike the Trojans themselves and their single-hooved horses.'),(7121,' And as when smoke riseth and reacheth the wide heaven from a city that burneth, and the wrath of the gods driveth it on—it causeth toil to all and upon many doth it let loose woes—  even so caused Achilles toil and woes for the Trojans.'),(7122,'And the old man Priam stood upon the heaven-built wall, and was ware of monstrous Achilles, '),(7123,'and how before him the Trojans were being driven in headlong rout; and help there was none.'),(7124,' Then with a groan he gat him down to the ground from the wall,  calling the while to the glorious keepers of the gate along the wall:\"'),(7125,'Wide open hold ye the gates with your hands until the folk shall come to the city in their rout, '),(7126,'for lo, here at hand is Achilles, as he driveth them on; '),(7127,'now methinks shall there be sorry work.'),(7128,' But whenso they have found respite, being gathered within the wall,  then close ye again the double doors, close fitted; '),(7129,'for I am adread lest yon baneful man leap within the wall.\" '),(7130,' \nSo spake he, and they undid the gates and thrust back the bars;'),(7131,'and the gates being flung wide wrought deliverance.'),(7132,' But Apollo leapt forth to face Achilles, that so he might ward off ruin from the Trojans.'),(7133,'  And they, the while, were fleeing straight for the city and the high wall, parched with thirst, and begrimed with dust from the plain, '),(7134,' while Achilles pressed upon them furiously with his spear; for fierce madness ever possessed his heart, and he was eager to win him glory.'),(7135,'Then would the sons of the Achaeans have taken high-gated Troy,  had not Phoebus Apollo aroused goodly Agenor, Antenor\'s son, a peerless warrior and a stalwart.'),(7136,' In his heart he put courage, and himself stood by his side, that he might ward from him the heavy hands of death; against the oak he leaned,'),(7137,'and he was enfolded in deep mist.'),(7138,'  So when Agenor was ware of Achilles, sacker of cities, he halted, and many things did his heart darkly ponder as he abode; '),(7139,'and mightily moved he spake unto his own great-hearted spirit:'),(7140,'\"Ah, woe is me;'),(7141,' if I flee before mighty Achilles, there where the rest are being driven in rout,  even so shall he overtake and butcher me in my cowardice.'),(7142,'But what if I leave these to be driven before Achilles, son of Peleus, and with my feet flee from the wall elsewhither, toward the Ilean plain, until I be come to the glens and the spurs of Ida, and hide me in the thickets?'),(7143,'  Then at even, when I have bathed me in the river and cooled me of my sweat, I might get me back to Ilios.'),(7144,' But why doth my heart thus hold converse with me?'),(7145,' Let it not be that he mark me as I turn away from the city toward the plain, and darting after me overtake me by his fleetness of foot.'),(7146,'  Then will it no more be possible to escape death and the fates, '),(7147,'for exceeding mighty is he above all mortal men.'),(7148,' What then if in front of the city I go forth to meet him?'),(7149,' Even his flesh too, I ween, may be pierced with the sharp bronze, and in him is but one life, and mortal do men deem him  to be; '),(7150,'howbeit Zeus, son of Cronos, giveth him glory.”'),(7151,' \nSo saying he gathered himself together to abide Achilles\' oncoming, and within him his valiant heart was fain to war and to do battle.'),(7152,' Even as a pard goeth forth from a deep thicket before the face of a huntsman,  neither is anywise afraid at heart, nor fleeth when she heareth the baying of the hounds; '),(7153,'for though the man be beforehand with her and smite her with thrust or with dart, yet even pierced through with the spear she ceaseth not from her fury until she grapple with him or be slain; '),(7154,'even so lordly Antenor\'s son, goodly Agenor,  refused to flee till he should make trial of Achilles, '),(7155,'but held before him his shield that was well-balanced upon every side, and aimed at Achilles with his spear, and shouted aloud:'),(7156,' \"Verily, I ween, thou hopest in thy heart, glorious Achilles,  on this day to sack the city of the lordly Trojans. '),(7157,'Thou fool! in sooth many be the woes that shall yet be wrought because of her.'),(7158,' Within her are we, many men and valiant, that in front of our dear parents and wives and sons guard Ilios; '),(7159,'nay, it is thou that shalt here meet thy doom, for all thou art so dread and so bold a man of war.\"'),(7160,'\n  He spake, and hurled the sharp spear from his heavy hand, and smote him on the shin below the knee, and missed him not; '),(7161,'and the greave of new-wrought tin rang terribly upon him; '),(7162,' but back from him it smote leapt the bronze, and pierced not through, for the gift of the god stayed it.'),(7163,'  And the son of Peleus in his turn set upon godlike Agenor; '),(7164,'howbeit Apollo suffered him not to win glory, but snatched away Agenor, and shrouded him in thick mist, and sent him forth from the war to go his way in peace.'),(7165,'  But Apollo by craft kept the son of Peleus away from the folk,'),(7166,'for likened in all things to Agenor\'s self the god that worketh afar took his stand before his feet; and Achilles rushed upon him swiftly to pursue him.'),(7167,' And while he pursued him over the wheat-bearing plain, turning him toward the river, deep-eddying Scamander, as he by but little outran him—'),(7168,'for by craft did Apollo beguile him,  that he ever hoped to overtake him in his running—'),(7169,'meanwhile the rest of the Trojans that were fleeing in rout came crowding gladly toward the city, and the town was filled with the throng of them.'),(7170,' Neither dared they longer to await one another outside the city and wall, and to know who perchance was escaped and  who had been slain in the fight; '),(7171,' but with eager haste they poured into the city, whomsoever of them his feet and knees might save.'),(7172,' So they throughout the city, huddled in rout like fawns, were cooling their sweat and drinking and quenching their thirst, as they rested on the fair battlements; '),(7173,'while the Achaeans drew near the wall leaning their shields against their shoulders.'),(7174,'  But Hector did deadly fate ensnare to abide there where he was in front of Ilios and the Scaean gates.'),(7175,' Then unto the son of Peleus spake Phoebus Apollo:'),(7176,' \"Wherefore, son of Peleus, dost thou pursue me with swift feet, thyself a mortal, while I am an immortal god?'),(7177,'  Not even yet hast thou known me that I am a god, but thou ragest incessantly!'),(7178,' Hast thou in good sooth no care for thy toil regarding the Trojans whom thou dravest in rout, who now are gathered into the city, while thou hast turned thee aside hitherward?'),(7179,' Thou shalt never slay me, for lo, I am not one that is appointed to die.\"'),(7180,'Then with a mighty burst of anger spake to him swift-footed Achilles:'),(7181,'  \"Thou hast foiled me, thou god that workest afar, most cruel of all gods in that thou hast now turned me hither from the wall;'),(7182,'else had many a man yet bitten the ground or ever they came into Ilios.'),(7183,' Now hast thou robbed me of great glory, aud them hast thou saved full easily, seeing thou hadst no fear of vengeance in the aftertime.'),(7184,'  Verily I would avenge me on thee, had I but the power.\"'),(7185,'So spake he, and was gone toward the city in pride of heart, speeding as speedeth with a chariot a horse that is winner of prizes, one that lightly courseth at full speed over the plain;'),(7186,' even so swiftly plied Achilles his feet and knees.'),(7187,'\n  Him the old man Priam was first to behold with his eyes, as he sped all-gleaming over the plain, like to the star that cometh forth at harvest-time, and brightly do his rays shine amid the host of stars in the darkness of night, the star that men call by name the Dog of Orion.'),(7188,'  Brightest of all is he, yet withal is he a sign of evil, and bringeth much fever upon wretched mortals.'),(7189,' Even in such wise did the bronze gleam upon the breast of Achilles as he ran.'),(7190,' And the old man uttered a groan, and beat upon his head with his hands, lifting them up on high, and with a groan he called aloud,  beseeching his dear son, '),(7191,'that was standing before the gates furiously eager to do battle with Achilles.'),(7192,' To him the old man spake piteously, stretching forth his arms: '),(7193,' \n\"Hector, my dear child, abide not, I pray thee, yon man, alone with none to aid thee, lest forthwith thou meet thy doom,  slain by the son of Peleus, since verily he is far the mightier— cruel that he is.'),(7194,' I would that he were loved by the gods even as by me!'),(7195,' Then would the dogs and vuhtures speedily devour him as he lay unburied; '),(7196,' so would dread sorrow depart from my soul, '),(7197,' seeing he hath made me bereft of sons many and valiant,  slaying them and selling them into isles that hie afar. '),(7198,'For even now there be twain of my sons, Lycaon and Polydorus, that I cannot see amid the Trojans that are gathered into the city, even they that Laothoe bare me, a princess among women.'),(7199,' But if they be yet alive in the camp of the foe, then verily  will we ransom them with bronze and gold, seeing there is store thereof in my house; '),(7200,'for gifts full many did the old Altes, of glorious name, give to his daughter.'),(7201,' But and if they be even now dead and in the house of Hades, then shall there be sorrow to my heart and to their mother, to us that gave them birth; '),(7202,'but to the rest of the host a briefer sorrow,  if so be thou die not as well, slain by Achilles. '),(7203,' Nay, enter within the walls, my child, that thou mayest save the Trojan men and Trojan women, and that thou give not great glory to the son of Peleus, and be thyself reft of thy dear life. '),(7204,'Furthermore, have thou compassion on me that yet can feel —  on wretched me whom the father, son of Cronos, will shay by a grievous fate on the threshold of old age, when I have beheld ills full many, my sons perishing and my daughters haled away, and my treasure chambers laid waste, and little children hurled to the ground in the dread conflict, and my sons\" wives  being haled away beneath the deadly hands of the Achaeans.'),(7205,'Myself then last of all at the entering in of my door shall ravening dogs rend, when some man by thrust or cast of the sharp bronze hath reft my limbs of life—even the dogs that in my halls I reared at my table to guard my door,  which then having drunk my blood in the madness of their hearts, shall lie there in the gateway.'),(7206,' A young man it beseemeth wholly, when he is slain in battle, that he lie mangled by the sharp bronze;'),(7207,'dead though he be, all is honourable whatsoever be seen.'),(7208,' But when dogs work shame upon the hoary head and hoary beard  and on the nakedness of an old man slain, lo, this is the most piteous thing that cometh upon wretched mortals.\" '),(7209,' \nThus spake the old man, and with his hands he plucked and tore the hoary hairs from his head;'),(7210,'but he could not persuade the heart of Hector.'),(7211,' And over against him the mother in her turn wailed and shed tears,  loosening the folds of her robe, while with the other hand she showed her breast, '),(7212,' and amid shedding of tears she spake unto him winged words:'),(7213,' \"Hector, my child, have thou respect unto this and pity me, if ever I gave thee the breast to lull thy pain. '),(7214,'Think thereon, dear child, and ward off yon foemen  from within the wall, neither stand thou forth to face him. Cruel is he;'),(7215,' for if so be he shay thee, never shall I lay thee on a bier and bewail thee, dear plant, born of mine own self, nay, nor shall thy bounteous wife; '),(7216,'but far away from us by the ships of the Argives shall swift dogs devour thee.\"'),(7217,'\n  So the twain with weeping spake unto their dear son, beseeching him instantly; '),(7218,'howbeit they could not persuade the heart of Hector, but he abode Achilles as he drew nigh in his mightiness.'),(7219,' And as a serpent of the mountain awaiteth a man at his lair, having fed upon evil herbs, and dread wrath hath entered into him,  and terribly he glareth as he coileth him about within his lair; '),(7220,'even so Hector in his courage unquenchable would not give ground, leaning his bright shield against the jutting wall.'),(7221,' Then, mightily moved, he spake unto his own great-hearted spirit: '),(7222,'\"Ah, woe is me, if I go within the gates and the walls  Polydamas will be the first to put reproach upon me, for that he bade me lead the Trojans to the city during this fatal night, when goodly Achilles arose.'),(7223,'verily it had been better far! '),(7224,'verily it had been better far! '),(7225,'But now, seeing I have brought the host to ruin in my blind folly,  I have shame of the Trojans, and the Trojans\' wives with trailing robes, lest haply some other baser man may say:'),(7226,' ‘Hector, trusting in his own might, brought ruin on the host.’'),(7227,' So will they say; '),(7228,'but for me it were better far to meet Achilles man to man and shay him, and so get me home,  or myself perish gloriously before the city. ”'),(7229,' Or what if I lay down my bossed shield and my heavy helm, and leaning my spear against the wall, go myself to meet peerless Achilles, and promise him that Helen,  and with her all the store of treasure that Alexander brought in his hollow ships to Troy —the which was the beginning of strife—will we give to the sons of Atreus to take away, and furthermore and separate therefrom will make due division with the Achaeans of all that this city holdeth; '),(7230,'and if thereafter I take from the Trojans an oath sworn by the elders  that they will hide nothing, but will divide all in twain, even all the treasure that the lovely city holdeth within?'),(7231,'But why doth my heart thus hold converse with me? '),(7232,'Let it not be that I go and draw nigh him, but he then pity me not nor anywise have reverence unto me, but slay me out of hand all unarmed,  as I were a woman, when I have put from me mine armour.'),(7233,'In no wise may I now from oak-tree or from rock hold dalliance with him, even as youth and maiden—youth and maiden! —hold dalliance one with the other.'),(7234,' Better were it to clash in strife with all speed; '),(7235,' let us know to which of us twain the Olympian will vouchsafe glory.”'),(7236,' \nSo he pondered as he abode, and nigh to him came Achilles, the peer of Enyalius, warrior of the waving helm, brandishing over his right shoulder the Pelian ash, his terrible spear; '),(7237,'and all round about the bronze flashed like the gleam  of blazing fire or of the sun as he riseth.'),(7238,' But trembling gat hold of Hector when he was ware of him,'),(7239,' neither dared he any more abide where he was, but left the gates behind him, and fled in fear; '),(7240,'and the son of Peleus rushed after him, trusting in his fleetness of foot. '),(7241,'As a falcon in the mountains, swiftest of winged things,  swoopeth lightly after a trembling dove: she fleeth before him, and he hard at hand darteth ever at her with shrill cries, and his heart biddeth him seize her; '),(7242,'even so Achilles in his fury sped straight on, and Hector fled beneath the wall of the Trojans, and plied his limbs swiftly.'),(7243,'  Past the place of watch, and the wind-waved wild fig-tree they sped, ever away from under the wall along the waggon-track, and came to the two fair-flowing fountains,'),(7244,'where well up the two springs that feed eddying Scamander.'),(7245,' The one floweth with warm water, and round about a smoke  goeth up therefrom as it were from a blazing fire,'),(7246,' while the other even in summer floweth forth cold as hail or chill snow or ice that water formeth. '),(7247,'And there hard by the selfsame springs are broad washing-tanks, fair and wrought of stone,  where the wives and fair daughters of the Trojans were wont to wash bright raiment of old in the time of peace, before the sons of the Achaeans came.'),(7248,' Thereby they ran, one fleeing, and one pursuing. '),(7249,' In front a good man fled, but one mightier far pursued him swiftly; for it was not for beast of sacrifice or for bull\'s hide  that they strove, such as are men\'s prizes for swiftness of foot, but it was for the life of horse-taming Hector that they ran.'),(7250,' And as when single-hooved horses that are winners of prizes course swiftly about the turning-points,'),(7251,' and some — great prize is set forth, a tripod haply or a woman, in honour of a warrior that is dead; '),(7252,' even so these twain circled thrice with swift feet about the city of Priam; '),(7253,'and all the gods gazed upon them.'),(7254,' Then among these the father of men and gods was first to speak:\"'),(7255,'Look you now, in sooth a well-loved man do mine eyes behold pursued around the wall; '),(7256,'and my heart hath sorrow  for Hector, who hath burned for me many thighs of oxen on the crests of many-ridged Ida, and at other times on the topmost citadel;'),(7257,' but now again is goodly Achilles pursuing him with swift feet around the city of Priam. '),(7258,' Nay then, come, ye gods, bethink you and take counsel  whether we shall save him from death, or now at length shall slay him, good man though he be, by the hand of Achilles, son of Peleus.\" '),(7259,' \nThen spake unto him the goddess, flashing-eyed Athene:\"'),(7260,'O Father, Lord of the bright lightning and of the dark cloud, what a word hast thou said!'),(7261,' A man that is mortal, doomed long since by fate, art thou minded  to deliver again from dolorous death?'),(7262,' but be sure that we other gods assent not all thereto.\"'),(7263,' but be sure that we other gods assent not all thereto.\"'),(7264,'\nThen in answer to her spake Zeus, the cloud-gatherer:'),(7265,' \"Be of good cheer, Tritogeneia, dear child.'),(7266,' In no wise do I speak with full purpose of heart, but am minded to be kindly to thee.'),(7267,' Do as thy pleasure is and hold thee back no more.\"'),(7268,' So saying he urged on Athene that was already eager,'),(7269,' and down from the peaks of Olympus she went darting.'),(7270,'\nBut hard upon Hector pressed swift Achilles in ceaseless pursuit.'),(7271,' And as when on the mountains a hound  rouseth from his covert the fawn of a deer and chaseth him through glens and glades,'),(7272,'and though he escape for a time, cowering beneath a thicket, yet doth the hound track him out and run ever on until he find him; '),(7273,' even so Hector escaped not the swift-footed son of Peleus.'),(7274,'Oft as he strove to rush straight for the Dardanian gates  to gain the shelter of the well-built walls, if so be his fellows from above might succour him with missiles, so oft would Achilles be beforehand with him and turn him back toward the plain, '),(7275,'but himself sped on by the city\'s walls.'),(7276,' And as in a dream a man availeth not to pursue one that fleeth before him— '),(7277,' the one availeth not to flee, nor the other to pursue—'),(7278,'even so Achilles availed not to overtake Hector in his fleetness, neither Hector to escape.'),(7279,' And how had Hector escaped the fates of death, but that Apollo, albeit for the last and latest time, drew nigh him to rouse his strength and make swift his knees?'),(7280,'  And to his folk goodly Achilles made sign with a nod of his head, and would not suffer them to hurl at Hector their bitter darts, lest another might smite him and win glory, and himself come too late.'),(7281,'But when for the fourth time they were come to the springs, lo then the Father lifted on high his golden scales,  and set therein two fates of grievous death, one for Achilles, and one for horse-taming Hector; then he grasped the balance by the midst and raised it; '),(7282,'and down sank the day of doom of Hector, and departed unto Hades; and Phoebus Apollo left him.'),(7283,' But unto Peleus\' son came the goddess, flashing-eyed Athene,  and drawing nigh she spake to him winged words: '),(7284,' \"Now in good sooth, glorious Achilles, dear to Zeus, have I hope that to the ships we twain shall bear off great glory for the Achaeans, having slain Hector, insatiate of battle though he be; '),(7285,' for now is it no more possible for him to escape us,  nay, not though Apollo, that worketh afar, should travail sore, grovelling before Father Zeus, that beareth the aegis.'),(7286,' But do thou now stand, and get thy breath; myself will I go and persuade yon warrior to do battle with thee man to man.\"'),(7287,' So spake Athene, and he obeyed and was glad at heart,  and stood leaning upon his bronze-barbed spear of ash. '),(7288,'But she left him, and came to goodly Hector in the likeness of Deiphobus both in form and untiring voice; '),(7289,'and drawing nigh she spake to him winged words: '),(7290,'\"Dear brother, full surely fleet Achilles doeth violence unto thee,  chasing thee with swift feet around the city of Priam. '),(7291,'But come, let us stand, and abiding here ward off his onset.\"'),(7292,' Then spake to her great Hector of the flashing helm:'),(7293,'\"Deiphobus, verily in time past thou wast far the dearest of my brethren, that were born of Hecabe and Priam, '),(7294,' but now I deem that I shall honour thee in my heart even more, seeing thou hast dared for my sake, when thine eyes beheld me, to come forth from out the wall, while the others abide within.\"'),(7295,' To him then spake again the goddess, flashing-eyed Athene:'),(7296,'\"Dear brother, in sooth my father and queenly mother, yea, and my comrades round about me,  besought me much, entreating me each in turn that I should abide there,'),(7297,' in such wise do they all tremble before Achilles; '),(7298,' but my heart within me was sore distressed with bitter grief.'),(7299,'Howbeit now let us charge straight at him and do battle, neither let there be anywise a sparing of spears, to the end that we may know whether Achilles  shall slay us twain, and bear our bloody spoils to the hollow ships, or whether he shall haply be vanquished by thy spear.\"'),(7300,'\nBy such words and by guile Athene led him on.'),(7301,' And when they were come near as they advanced one against the other, then first unto Achilles spake great Hector of the glancing helm:'),(7302,'  \"No longer, son of Peleus, will I flee from thee, as before I thrice fled around the great city of Priam, nor ever had the heart to abide thy onset;'),(7303,'but now again my spirit biddeth me stand and face thee, '),(7304,' whether I slay or be slain.'),(7305,' But come hither, let us call the gods to witness,'),(7306,'for they shall be the best  witnesses and guardians of our covenant: '),(7307,'I will do unto thee no foul despite, if Zeus grant me strength to outstay thee, and I take thy life; '),(7308,'  but when I have stripped from thee thy glorious armour, Achilles, I will give thy dead body back to the Achaeans; '),(7309,' and so too do thou.\" '),(7310,' \n  Then with an angry glance from beneath his brows spake unto him Achilles, swift of foot: '),(7311,'\"Hector, talk not to me, thou madman, of covenants. '),(7312,' As between lions and men there are no oaths of faith, nor do wolves and lambs have hearts of concord but are evil-minded continually one against the other,  even so is it not possible for thee and me to be friends, neither shall there be oaths between us till one or the other shall have fallen, and glutted with his blood Ares, the warrior with tough shield of hide.'),(7313,' Bethink thee of all manner of valour: '),(7314,'now in good sooth it behoveth thee to quit thee as a spearman and a dauntless warrior.'),(7315,'No more is there any escape for thee, but forthwith shall Pallas Athene  lay thee low by my spear. '),(7316,'Now shalt thou pay back the full price of all my sorrows for my comrades, whom thou didst slay when raging with thy spear.\"'),(7317,'He spake, and poised his far-shadowing spear, and hurled it; '),(7318,' howbeit glorious Hector, looking steadily at him, avoided it; '),(7319,'  for he was ware of it in time and crouched, and the spear of bronze flew over, and fixed itself in the earth; '),(7320,' but Pallas Athene caught it up, and gave it back to Achilles, unseen of Hector, shepherd of the host.'),(7321,'And Hector spake unto the peerless son of Peleus:'),(7322,'\"Thou hast missed, neither in any wise, as it seemeth, O Achilles like to the gods, hast thou yet known from Zeus of my doom, though  verily thou thoughtest it. '),(7323,'Howbeit thou wast but glib of tongue and a cunning knave in speech, to the end that seized with fear of thee I might be forgetful of my might and my valour.'),(7324,' Not as I flee shalt thou plant thy spear in my back; nay, as I charge upon thee drive thou it straight through my breast,  if a god hath vouchsafed thee this.'),(7325,' Now in turn avoid thou my spear of bronze.'),(7326,' Would that thou mightest take it all into thy flesh!'),(7327,' So would war be lighter for the Trojans, if thou wert but dead;  '),(7328,'for thou art their greatest bane.\" '),(7329,' \nHe spake, and poised his far-shadowing spear and hurled it,  and smote full upon the shield of the son of Peleus, and missed him not; '),(7330,'but far from the shield the spear leapt back.'),(7331,' And Hector waxed wroth for that the swift shaft had flown vainly from his hand, and he stood confounded, for he had no second spear of ash.'),(7332,' Then he shouted aloud, and called to Deiphobus of the white shield, '),(7333,' but he was nowise nigh. '),(7334,' but he was nowise nigh. '),(7335,' And Hector knew all in his heart, and spake, saying:'),(7336,' \"Out upon it, in good sooth have the gods called me to my death.'),(7337,' For I deemed that the warrior Deiphobus was at hand, '),(7338,'but lo, he is within the wall, and Athene hath beguiled me.'),(7339,'  Now of a surety is evil death nigh at hand, and no more afar from me, neither is there way of escape.'),(7340,' So I ween from of old was the good pleasure of Zeus, and of the son of Zeus, the god that smiteth afar, even of them that aforetime were wont to succour me with ready hearts; '),(7341,'but now again is my doom come upon me.'),(7342,' Nay, but not without a struggle let me die, neither ingloriously,  but in the working of some great deed for the hearing of men that are yet to be.\"'),(7343,'So saying, he drew his sharp sword that hung beside his flank, a great sword and a mighty, and gathering himself together swooped like an eagle of lofty flight that darteth to the plain through the dark clouds to seize a tender lamb or a cowering hare; '),(7344,' even so Hector swooped, brandishing his sharp sword.'),(7345,' And Achilles rushed upon him, his heart full of savage wrath, and before his breast he made a covering of his shield, fair and richly-dight, and tossed his bright  four-horned helm;'),(7346,' and fair about it waved the plumes wrought of gold, that Hephaestus had set thick about the crest. '),(7347,'As a star goeth forth amid stars in the darkness of night, the star of evening, that is set in heaven as the fairest of all; even so went forth a gleam from the keen spear that Achilles poised in his right hand,  as he devised evil for goodly Hector, looking the while upon his fair flesh to find where it was most open to a blow.'),(7348,' Now all the rest of his flesh was covered by the armour of bronze, the goodly armour that he had stripped from mighty Patroclus when he slew him;'),(7349,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 22.324-22.325'),(7350,'but there was an opening where the collar bones part the neck and shoulders, even the gullet,  where destruction of life cometh most speedily; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 324 to line 325'),(7351,' Howbeit the ashen spear, heavy with bronze, clave not the windpipe, to the end that he might yet make answer and speak unto his foe.'),(7352,' and goodly Achilles exulted over him;'),(7353,' and goodly Achilles exulted over him;'),(7354,'\"Hector, thou thoughtest, I ween, whilst thou wast spoiling Patroclus, that thou wouldest be safe, and hadst no thought of me that was afar, thou fool.'),(7355,' Far from him a helper, mightier far, was left behind at the hollow ships,  even I, that have loosed thy knees.'),(7356,' Thee shall dogs and birds rend in unseemly wise, but to him shall the Achaeans give burial.\" '),(7357,' \nThen, his strength all spent, spake to him Hector of the flashing helm:'),(7358,'\"I implore thee by thy life and knees and parents, suffer me not to be devoured of dogs by the ships of the Achaeans;  nay, take thou store of bronze and gold, gifts that my fathec and queenly mother shall give thee, but my bodv give thou back to my home, that the Trojans and the Trojans\' wives may give me my due meed of fire in my death.\"'),(7359,'\nThen with an angry glance from beneath his brows spake unto him Achilhes swift of foot:'),(7360,'  \"Implore me not, dog, by knees or parents.'),(7361,' Would that in any wise wrath and fury might bid me carve thy flesh and myself eat it raw, because of what thou hast wrought, as surely as there lives no man that shall ward off the dogs from thy head; nay, not though they should bring hither and weigh out ransom ten-fold, aye, twenty-fold,  and should promise yet more; nay, not though Priam, son of Dardanus, should bid pay thy weight in gold;'),(7362,'not even so shall thy queenly mother lay thee on a bier and make lament for thee, the son herself did bear, but dogs and birds shall devour thee utterly.\"'),(7363,'  Then even in dying spake unto him Hector of the flashing helm:'),(7364,' \"Verily I know thee well, and forbode what shall be, neither was it to be that I should persuade thee;'),(7365,' of a truth the heart in thy breast is of iron.'),(7366,' Bethink thee now lest haply I bring the wrath of the gods upon thee on the day when Paris and Phoebus Apollo shall slay thee,  valorous though thou art, at the Scaean gate.\"'),(7367,'Even as he thus spake the end of death enfolded him and his soul fleeting from his limbs was gone to Hades, bewailing her fate, leaving manliness and youth.'),(7368,' And to him even in his death spake goodly Achilles:'),(7369,'  \"Lie thou dead;'),(7370,' my fate will I accept whenso Zeus willeth to bring it to pass and the other immortal gods.\" '),(7371,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 22.367-22.369'),(7372,' \nHe spake, and from the corpse drew forth his spear of bronze and laid it aside, and set him to strip from the shoulders the blood-stained armour. ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 367 to line 369'),(7373,'neither did any draw nigh but dealt him a wound.'),(7374,' And thus would one speak, with a look at his neighbour:\"'),(7375,'Look you, in good sooth softer is Hector for the handling now than when he burned the ships with blazing fire.\"'),(7376,' Thus would one speak, and drawing nigh would deal a wound.'),(7377,'  But when goodly Achilles, swift of foot, had despoiled him, then stood he up among the Achaeans and spake winged words:'),(7378,'\"My friends, leaders and rulers of the Argives, seeing the gods have vouchsafed us to slay this man,  that hath wrought much evil beyond all the host of the others, come, let us make trial in arms about the city, to the end that we may yet further know what purpose the Trojans have in mind, whether they will leave their high city now that this man is fallen, or whether they are minded to abide, even though Hector be no more.'),(7379,'  But why doth my heart thus hold converse with me?'),(7380,' There lieth by the ships a dead man unwept, unburied, even Patroclus; '),(7381,'him will I not forget so long as I abide among the living, and my knees are quick.'),(7382,'Nay, if even in the house of Hades men forget their dead,  yet will I even there remember my dear comrade. '),(7383,' But come, singing our song of victory, ye sons of the Achaeans, let us go back to the hollow ships and bring thither this corpse.'),(7384,' We have won us great glory; '),(7385,' we have slain goodly Hector, to whom the Trojans made prayer throughout their city, as unto a god.\"'),(7386,' He spake, and devised foul entreatment for goodly Hector. '),(7387,'The tendons of both his feet behind he pierced from heel to ankle, and made fast therethrough thongs of oxhide, and bound them to his chariot, but left the head to trail.'),(7388,' Then when he had mounted his car and had lifted therein the glorious armour,  he touched the horses with the lash to start thiem, and nothing loath the pair sped onward.'),(7389,' And from Hector as he was dragged the dust rose up, and on either side his dark hair flowed outspread, and all in the dust lay the head that was before so fair;'),(7390,' but now had Zeus given him over to his foes to suffer foul entreatment in his own native land. '),(7391,' \n  So was his head all befouled with dust; '),(7392,'  but his mother tore her hair and from her flung far her gleaming veil and uttered a cry exceeding loud at sight of her son.'),(7393,' And a piteous groan did his father utter, and around them the folk was holden of wailing and groaning throughout the city.'),(7394,'  Most like to this was it as though all beetling Ilios were utterly burning with fire.'),(7395,' And the folk had much ado to hold back the old man in his frenzy, fain as he was to go forth from the Dardanian gates.'),(7396,' To all he made prayer, grovelling the while in the filth,  and calling on each man by name:'),(7397,'\"Withhold, my friends, and suffer me for all your love to go forth from the city alone, and hie me to the ships of the Achaeans.'),(7398,' I will make prayer to yon ruthless man, yon worker of violence, if so be he may have shame before his fellows and have pity on my old age.'),(7399,'  He too, I ween, hath a father such as I am, even Peleus, that begat him and reared him to be a bane to Trojans;'),(7400,' but above all others hath he brought woe upon me,'),(7401,'  so many sons of mine hath he slain in their prime.'),(7402,'Yet for them all I mourn not so much, despite my grief,  as for one only, sharp grief for whom will bring me down to the house of Hades—even for Hector.'),(7403,' Ah, would he had died in my arms; '),(7404,'then had we taken our fill of weeping and wailing, the mother that bare him to her sorrow, and myself.\"'),(7405,'\nSo spake he weeping, and thereto the townsfolk added their laments. '),(7406,' And among the women of Troy Hecabe led the vehement lamentation: '),(7407,' \"My child, ah woe is me!'),(7408,' How shall I live in my sore anguish, now thou art dead?'),(7409,'—thou that wast my boast night and day in the city, and a blessing to all, both to the men and women of Troy throughout the town, who ever greeted thee as a god; '),(7410,' for verily thou wast to them a glory exceeding great, while yet thou livedst;'),(7411,'but now death and fate are come upon thee.\" '),(7412,' \nSo spake she weeping; but the wife knew naught as yet the wife of Hector—'),(7413,' for no true messenger had come to tell her that her husband abode without the gates;  but she was weaving a web in the innermost part of the lofty house, a purple web of double fold, and therein was broidering flowers of varied hue. '),(7414,' And she called to her fair-tressed handmaids through the house to set a great tripod on the fire,to the end that there should be a hot bath for Hector whenso he returned from out the battle—unwitting one,  neither wist she anywise that far from all baths flashing-eyed Athene had laid him low by the hand of Achilles.'),(7415,' But the shrieks she heard and the groanings from the wall, '),(7416,'and her limbs reeled, and from her hand the shuttle fell to earth.'),(7417,' Then she spake again among her fair-tressed handmaids:'),(7418,'  \"Come hither two of you, and follow me, let me see what deeds have been wrought.'),(7419,'It was the voice of my husband\'s honoured mother that I heard, and in mine own breast my heart leapeth to my mouth, and beneath me my knees are numbed;'),(7420,'  verily hard at hand is some evil thing for the children of Priam.'),(7421,' Far from my ear be the word, '),(7422,' but sorely am I afraid lest to my sorrow goodly Achilles may have cut off from the city bold Hector by himself alone, and have driven him to the plain, aye, and have by now made him to cease from the baneful valour that possessed him; seeing he would never abide in the throng of men, but would ever charge far to the front, yielding to no man in his might.\"'),(7423,'\n  So saying she hasted through the hall with throbbing heart as one beside herself, '),(7424,'and with her went her handmaidens. But when she was come to the wall and the throng of men, then on the wall she stopped and looked, and was ware of him as he was dragged before the city;'),(7425,'and swift horses  were dragging him ruthlessly toward the hollow ships of the Achaeans. '),(7426,' Then down over her eyes came the darkness of night, and enfolded her, and she fell backward and gasped forth her spirit. '),(7427,'Far from off her head she cast the bright attiring thereof, the frontlet and coif and kerchief and woven band,  and the veil that golden Aphrodite had given her on the day when Hector of the flashing helm hed her as his bride forth from the house of Eetion, after he had brought bride-gifts past counting.\n '),(7428,' And round about her came thronging ber husband\'s sisters and his brothers\' wives, who bare her up in their midst, distraught even unto death.'),(7429,'  But when she revived, and her spirit was returned into her breast,then she lifted up her voice in wailing, and spake among the women of Troy:\"'),(7430,'Ah Hector, woe is me! '),(7431,'to one fate, it seemeth, were we born, both of us twain, thou in Troy in the house of Priam, and I in Thebe beneath wooded Placus  in the house of Eetion, who reared me when I was a babe, hapless father of a cruel-fated child; '),(7432,' would God he had never begotten me.'),(7433,' Now thou unto the house of Hades beneath the deeps of earth art departing, but me thou leavest in bitter grief, a widow in thy halls, '),(7434,'  and thy son is still a mere babe, the son born of thee and me in our haplessness; '),(7435,'nor shalt thou be any profit to him, Hector, seeing thou art dead, neither he to thee.'),(7436,' For even though he escape the woeful war of the Achaeans, yet shall his portion be labour and sorrow in the aftertime,'),(7437,' for others will take away his lands.'),(7438,'  The day of orphanhood cutteth a child off from the friends of his youth;'),(7439,' ever is his head bowed how, and his cheeks are bathed in tears, and in his need the child hieth him to his father\'s friends, plucking one by the cloak and another by the tunic; '),(7440,'and of them that are touched with pity, one holdeth forth his cup for a moment:'),(7441,' his hips he wetteth, but his palate he wetteth not.'),(7442,'  And one whose father and mother yet live thrusteth him from the feast with smiting of the hand, and chideth him with words of reviling:'),(7443,' No father of thine feasteth in our company.’'),(7444,' No father of thine feasteth in our company.’'),(7445,'Then in tears unto his widowed mother cometh back the child—  Astyanax, that aforetime on his father\'s knees ate only marrow and the rich fat of sheep; '),(7446,' and when sleep came upon him and he ceased from his childish play, then would he slumber on a couch in the arms of his nurse in his soft bed, his heart satisfied with good things.'),(7447,'  But now, seeing he has lost his dear father, he will suffer ills full many—my Astyanax, whom the Troians call by this name '),(7448,'for that thou alone didst save their gates and their high walls.'),(7449,' But now by the beaked ships far from thy parents shall writhing worms devour thee, when the dogs have had their fill, as thou liest a naked corpse; '),(7450,' yet in thy halls lieth raiment, finely-woven and fair, wrought by the hands of women.'),(7451,' Howbeit all these things will I verily burn in blazing fire—in no wise a profit unto thee, seeing thou shalt not lie therein, but to be an honour unto thee from the men and women of Troy.\"'),(7452,'  So spake she weeping, and thereto the women added their laments.'),(7453,' Thus they made lamentation throughout the city; '),(7454,'but the Achaeans, when they were come to the ships and the Hellespont, scattered each man to his own ship; howbeit the Myrmidons would Achilles nowise suffer to be scattered,  but spake among his war-loving comrades, saying: '),(7455,'\"Ye Myrmidons of fleet steeds, my trusty comrades, let us not yet loose our single-hooved horses from their cars, but with horses and chariots let us draw nigh and mourn Patroclus; '),(7456,'for that is the due of the dead.'),(7457,'  Then when we have taken our fill of dire lamenting, we will unyoke our horses and sup here all together.\"'),(7458,' So spake he, and they raised the voice of wailing all with one accord, and Achilles was leader thereof.'),(7459,'Then thrice about the corpse they drave their fair-maned steeds, mourning the while; '),(7460,'and among them Thetis roused desire of wailing.'),(7461,'  Wetted were the sands and wetted the armour of the warriors with their tears; '),(7462,'so mighty a deviser of rout was he for whom they mourned.'),(7463,' And among them the son of Peleus was leader in the vehement lamentation; laying his man-slaying hands upon the breast of his comrade:'),(7464,' \"Hail, I bid thee, O Patroclus, even in the house of Hades, '),(7465,'  for even now I am bringing to fulfillment all that aforetime I promised thee: that I would drag Hector hither and give him raw unto dogs to devour, and of twelve glorious sons of the Trojans would I cut the throats before thy pyre, in my wrath at thy slaying.\"'),(7466,'He spake, and devised foul entreatment for goodly Hector,  stretching him on his face in the dust before the bier of the son of Menoetius.'),(7467,' And they put off, each man of them, their shining harnesses of bronze, and loosed their loud-neighing horses, and themselves sat down beside the ship of the swift-footed son of Aeacus, a countless host; '),(7468,'and he made them a funeral feast to satisfy their hearts.'),(7469,'  Many sleek bulls bellowed about the knife, as they were slaughtered, many sheep and bleating goats, '),(7470,'and many white-tusked swine, rich with fat, were stretched to singe over the flame of Hephaestus;'),(7471,'and everywhere about the corpse the blood ran so that one might dip cups therein. '),(7472,' \n  But the prince, the swiftfooted son of Peleus, was led unto goodly Agamemnon by the chiefs of the Achaeans, that had much ado to persuade him thereto, so wroth at heart was he for his comrade. '),(7473,' But when, as they went, they were come to the hut of Agamemnon, forthwith they bade clear-voiced heralds  set upon the fire a great cauldron, if so be they might persuade the son of Peleus to wash from him the bloody gore.'),(7474,' But he steadfastly denied them, and swore an oath thereto: '),(7475,'\"Nay, verily by Zeus, that is highest and best of gods, it may not be that water should come nigh my head,  until such time as I have laid Patroclus on the fire, and have heaped him a barrow, and shorn my hair withal, since never more shall a second grief thus reach my heart, while yet I abide among the living.'),(7476,' Howbeit for this present let us yield us to the banquet we needs must loathe; '),(7477,'but in the morning rouse thou the folk, king of men Agamemnon,  to bring wood, and to make ready all that it beseemeth a dead man to have, whenso he goeth beneath the murky darkness, to the end that unwearied fire may burn him quickly from sight, and the host betake it to its tasks.\" '),(7478,' \nSo spake he, and they readily hearkened to him and obeyed, '),(7479,'  and speedily making ready each man his meal they supped, nor did their hearts lack aught of the equal feast. '),(7480,'But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, they went each man to his hut to take his rest; but the son of Peleus upon the shore of the loud-resounding sea  lay groaning heavily amid the host of the Myrmidons, in an open space where the waves splashed upon the shore.'),(7481,' And when sleep seized him, loosenlng the cares of his heart, being shed in sweetness round about him — '),(7482,'for sore weary were his glorious limbs with speeding after Hector unto windy Ilios— '),(7483,' then there came to him the spirit of hapless Patroclus, in all things like his very self, in stature and fair eyes and in voice, and in like raiment was he clad withal; '),(7484,'and he stood above Achilles\' head and spake to him, saying:'),(7485,'\"Thou sleepest, and hast forgotten me, Achilles.'),(7486,'  Not in my life wast thou unmindful of me, but now in my death!'),(7487,' Bury me with all speed, that I pass within the gates of Hades.'),(7488,' Afar do the spirits keep me aloof, the phantoms of men that have done with toils, neither suffer they me to join myself to them beyond the River, but vainly I wander through the wide-gated house of Hades.'),(7489,'  And give me thy hand,'),(7490,' I pitifully entreat thee, for never more again shall I come back from out of Hades, when once ye have given me my due of fire.'),(7491,' Never more in life shall we sit apart from our dear comrades and take counsel together, but for me hath loathly fate  opened its maw, the fate that was appointed me even from my birth. '),(7492,'Aye, and thou thyself also, Achilles like to the gods, art doomed to be brought low beneath the wall of the wealthy Trojans.'),(7493,' And another thing will I speak, and charge thee, if so be thou wilt hearken.'),(7494,' Lay not my bones apart from thine, Achilles, but let them lie together, even as we were reared in your house,  when Menoetius brought me, being yet a little lad, from Opoeis to your country, by reason of grievous man-slaying, on the day when I slew Amphidamus\' son in my folly, though I willed it not, in wrath over the dice.'),(7495,' Then the knight Peleus received me into his house  and reared me with kindly care and named me thy squire; '),(7496,'even so let one coffer enfold our bones, a golden coffer with handles twain, the which thy queenly mother gave thee.\" '),(7497,' \nThen in answer spake to him Achilles, swift of foot:\"'),(7498,'Wherefore, O head beloved, art thou come hither,  and thus givest me charge about each thing? '),(7499,' Nay, verily I will fulfill thee all, and will hearken even as thou biddest.'),(7500,' But, I pray thee, draw thou nigher; '),(7501,'though it be but for a little space let us clasp our arms one about the other, and take our fill of dire lamenting.\"'),(7502,'\nSo saying he reached forth with his hands,  yet clasped him not; '),(7503,' but the spirit like a vapour was gone beneath the earth, gibbering faintly.'),(7504,' And seized with amazement Achilles sprang up, and smote his hands together, and spake a word of wailing:\"'),(7505,'Look you now, even in the house of Hades is the spirit and phantom somewhat, albeit the mind be not anywise therein; '),(7506,' for the whole night long hath the spirit of hapless Patroclus stood over me, weeping and wailing, and gave me charge concerning each thing, and was wondrously like his very self.\"'),(7507,'\nSo spake he, and in them all aroused the desire of lament, '),(7508,'and rosy-fingered Dawn shone forth upon them  while yet they wailed around the piteous corpse. '),(7509,'But the lord Agamemnon sent forth mules and men from all sides from out the huts to fetch wood'),(7510,'and a man of valour watched thereover, even Meriones, squire of kindly Idomeneus.'),(7511,' And they went forth bearing in their hands axes for the cutting of wood  and well-woven ropes, '),(7512,'and before them went the mules: '),(7513,' and ever upward, downward, sideward, and aslant they fared.'),(7514,' But when they were come to the spurs of many-fountained Ida, forthwith they set them to fill high-crested oaks with the long-edged bronze in busy haste '),(7515,'and with a mighty crash the trees kept falling.'),(7516,'  Then the Achaeans split the trunks asunder and bound them behind the mules,'),(7517,'and these tore up the earth with their feet as they hasted toward the plain through the thick underbrush.'),(7518,' And all the woodcutters bare logs; '),(7519,'for so were they bidden of Meriones, squire of kindly Idomeneus.'),(7520,'  Then down upon the shore they cast these, man after man, where Achilles planned a great barrow for Patroclus and for himself.'),(7521,' But when on all sides they had cast down the measureless wood, they sate them down there and abode, all in one throng. '),(7522,'And Achilles straightway bade the war-loving Myrmidons  gird them about with bronze, and yoke each man his horses to his car.'),(7523,' And they arose and did on their armour and mounted their chariots, warriors and charioteers alike. In front fared the men in chariots, and thereafter followed a cloud of footmen, a host past counting '),(7524,'and in the midst his comrades bare Patroclus.'),(7525,'  And as with a garment they wholly covered the corpse with their hair that they shore off and cast thereon; '),(7526,'and behind them goodly Achilles clasped the head, sorrowing the while; '),(7527,' for peerless was the comrade whom he was speeding to the house of Hades. '),(7528,' \nBut when they were come to the place that Achilles had appointed unto them, they set down the dead, and swiftly heaped up for him abundant store of wood.'),(7529,'  Then again swift-footed goodly Achilles took other counsel; '),(7530,'he took his stand apart from the fire and shore off a golden lock, the rich growth whereof he had nursed for the river Spercheüs, '),(7531,'and his heart mightily moved, he spake, with a look over the wine-dark sea:\"'),(7532,'Spercheüs, to no purpose did my father Peleus vow to thee  that when I had come home thither to my dear native land, I would shear my hair to thee and offer a holy hecatomb, and on the selfsame spot would sacrifice fifty rams, males without blemish, into thy waters, where is thy demesne and thy fragrant altar.'),(7533,' So vowed that old man, but thou didst not fulfill for him his desire.'),(7534,'  Now, therefore, seeing I go not home to my dear native land, I would fain give unto the warrior Patroclus this lock to fare with him.\"'),(7535,'\nHe spake and set the lock in the hands of his dear comrade, and in them all aroused the desire of lament.'),(7536,' And now would the light of the sun have gone down upon their weeping,  had not Achilles drawn nigh to Agamemnon\'s side and said:'),(7537,'\"Son of Atreus—for to thy words as to those of none other will the host of the Achaeans give heed— of lamenting they may verily take their fill, but for this present disperse them from the pyre, and bid them make ready their meal;'),(7538,'for all things here we to whom the dead is nearest and dearest will take due care; '),(7539,' and with us let the chieftains also abide.”'),(7540,' \nThen when the king of men Agamemnon heard this word, he forthwith dispersed the folk amid the shapely ships, but they that were neareat and dearest to the dead abode there, and heaped up the wood, and made a pyre of an hundred feet this way and that,  and on the topmost part thereof they set the dead man, their hearts sorrow-laden.'),(7541,' And many goodly sheep and many sleek kine of shambling gait they flayed and dressed before the pyre;'),(7542,' and from them all great-souled Achilles gathered the fat, and enfolded the dead therein from head to foot, and about him heaped the flayed bodies.'),(7543,'  And thereon he set two-handled jars of honey and oil, leaning them against the bier; '),(7544,' and four horses with high arched neeks he cast swiftly upon the pyre, groaning aloud the while.'),(7545,' Nine dogs had the prince, that fed beneath his table, and of these did Achilles cut the throats of twain, and cast them upon the pyre. And twelve valiant sons of the great-souled Trojans slew he with the bronze—'),(7546,'and grim was the work he purposed in his heart '),(7547,'and thereto he set the iron might of fire, to range at large.'),(7548,' Then he uttered a groan, and called on his dear comrade by name:'),(7549,' \"Hail, I bid thee, O Patroclus, even in the house of Hades, '),(7550,' for now am I bringing all to pass, which afore-time I promised thee. Twelve valiant sons of the great-souled Trojans, lo all these together with thee the flame devoureth; '),(7551,'but Hector, son of Priam, will I nowise give to the fire to feed upon, but to dogs.\"'),(7552,'\nSo spake he threatening,'),(7553,' but with Hector might no dogs deal;  nay, the daughter of Zeus, Aphrodite, kept dogs from him by day alike and by night, and with oil anointed she him, rose-sweet, ambrosial, to the end that Achilles might not tear him as he dragged him. '),(7554,'And over him Phoebus Apollo drew a dark cloud from heaven to the plain, and covered all the place  whereon the dead man lay, lest ere the time the might of the sun should shrivel his flesh round about on his sinews and limbs. '),(7555,' \nHowbeit the pyre of dead Patroclus kindled not.'),(7556,' Then again did swift footed goodly Achilles take other counsel; '),(7557,'he took his stand apart from the pyre, and made prayer to the two winds,  to the North Wind and the West Wind, and promised fair offerings, '),(7558,' and full earnestly, as he poured libations from a cup of gold, he besought them to come, to the end that the corpses might speedily blaze with fire, and the wood make haste to be kindled.'),(7559,' Then forthwith Iris heard his prayer, and hied her with the message to the winds.'),(7560,'  They in the house of the fierce-blowing West Wind were feasting all together at the banquet '),(7561,'and Iris halted from her running on the threshold of stone.'),(7562,' Soon as their eyes beheld her, they all sprang up and called her each one to himself.'),(7563,' But she refused to sit, and spake saying:'),(7564,'  \"I may not sit,'),(7565,' for I must go back unto the streams of Oceanus, unto the land of the Ethiopians, where they are sacrificing hecatombs to the immortals, that I too may share in the sacred feast. '),(7566,' But Achilles prayeth the North Wind and the noisy West Wind to come, and promiseth them fair offerings, that so ye may rouse the pyre to burn whereon lieth  Patroclus, for whom all the Achaeans groan aloud.\"'),(7567,'\nWhen she had thus departed, and they arose with a wondrous din, driving the clouds tumultuously before them.'),(7568,' And swiftly they came to the sea to blow thereon, and the wave swelled  beneath the shrill blast; '),(7569,'and they came to deep-soiled Troyland, and fell upon the pyre, and mightily roared the wordrous blazing fire.'),(7570,' So the whole night long as with one blast they beat upon the flame of the pyre, blowing shrill;'),(7571,'and the whole night long swift Achilles, taking a two-handled cup in hand,  drew wine from a golden howl and poured it upon the earth, and wetted the ground, calling ever upon the spirit of hapless Patroclus.'),(7572,' As a father waileth for his son, as he burneth his bones, a son newly wed whose death has brought woe to his hapless parents, even so wailed Achilles for his comrade as he burned his bones,  going heavily about the pyre with ceaseless groaning.'),(7573,' \nBut at the hour when the star of morning goeth forth to herald light over the face of the earth—the star after which followeth saffron-robed Dawn and spreadeth over the sea—even then grew the burning faint, and the flame thereof died down.'),(7574,' And the winds went back again to return to their home  over the Thracian sea,'),(7575,' and it roared with surging flood.'),(7576,' Then the son of Peleus withdrew apart from the burning pyre, and laid him down sore-wearied; and sweet sleep leapt upon him.'),(7577,'But they that were with the son of Atreus gathered in a throng, '),(7578,' and the noise and din of their oncoming aroused him;  and he sat upright and spake to them saying:'),(7579,'\"Son of Atreus, and ye other princes of the hosts of Achaea, first quench ye with flaming wine the burning pyre, even all whereon the might of the fire hath come,'),(7580,' and thereafter let us gather the bones of Patroclus, Menoetius\' son, singling them out well from the rest; '),(7581,' and easy they are to discern, '),(7582,'for he lay in the midst of the pyre, while the others burned apart on the edges thereof, horses and men mingled together.'),(7583,' Then let us place the bones in a golden urn wrapped in a double layer of fat until such time as I myself be hidden in Hades.'),(7584,'  Howbeit no huge barrow do I bid you rear with toil for him, but such a one only as beseemeth; '),(7585,'but in aftertime do ye Achaeans build it broad and high, ye that shall be left amid the benched ships when I am gone.\"'),(7586,'\nSo spake he, and they hearkened to the swift-footed son of Peleus.'),(7587,'  First they quenched with flaming wine the pyre, so far as the flame had come upon it, and the ash had settled deep; '),(7588,'and with weeping they gathered up the white bones of their gentle comrade into a golden urn, and wrapped them in a double layer of fat, and placing the urn in the hut they covered it with a soft linen cloth.'),(7589,'  Then they traced the compass of the barrow and set forth the foundations thereof round about the pyre, '),(7590,' and forthwith they piled the up-piled earth.And when they had piled the barrow, they set them to go back again.'),(7591,'But Achilles stayed the folk even where they were, and made them to sit in a wide gathering; and from his ships brought forth prizes; cauldrons and tripods  and horses and mules and strong oxen and fair-girdled women and grey iron. '),(7592,' \nFor swift charioteers first he set forth goodly prizes, a woman to lead away, one skilled in goodly handiwork, and an eared tripod of two and twenty measures  for him that should be first;'),(7593,' and for the second he appointed a mare of six years, unbroken, with a mule foal in her womb; '),(7594,'and for the third he set forth a cauldron untouched of fire, a fair cauldron that held four measures, white even as the first;'),(7595,'and for the fourth he appointed two talents of gold;  and for the fifth a two-handled urn, yet untouched of fire. '),(7596,'Then he stood up, and spake among the Argives, saying:'),(7597,'\n\"Son of Atreus, and ye other well-greaved Achaeans, for the charioteers these prizes lie waiting in the lists.'),(7598,' If for some other\'s honour we Achaeans were now holding contests,  surely it were I that should win the first prize, and bear it to my hut; '),(7599,'for ye know how far my horses twain surpass in excellence,'),(7600,'seeing they are immortal, and it was Poseidon that gave them to my father Peleus, and he gave them to me.'),(7601,' Howbeit I verily will abide, I and my single-hooved horses, '),(7602,' so valiant and glorious a charioteer have they lost, and one so kind, who full often would pour upon their manes soft soil when he had washed them in bright water.'),(7603,' For him they stand and mourn, and on the ground their manes are trailing, and the twain stand there, grieving at heart.'),(7604,'  But do ye others make yourselves ready throughout the host, whosoever of the Achaeans hath trust in his horses and his jointed car.\" '),(7605,' \nSo spake the son of Peleus, and the swift charioteers bestirred them.'),(7606,' Upsprang, for the first, Eumelus, king of men, Admetus\' dear son, a man well-skilled in horsemanship  '),(7607,' and after him upsprang Tydeus\' son, mighty Diomedes, and led beneath the yoke the horses of Tros, even them that on a time he had taken from Aeneas, albeit Apollo snatched away Aeneas\' self; '),(7608,' and after him uprose Atreus\' son, fair-haired Menelaus, sprung from Zeus, and led beneath the yoke swift steeds, Aethe, Agamemnon\'s mare, and his own horse Podargus.'),(7609,'  The mare had Anchises\' son Echepolus given to Agamemnon without price, to the end that he might not follow him to windy Ilios, but might abide at home and take his joy;'),(7610,'for great wealth had Zeus given him, and he dwelt in spaclous Sicyon:'),(7611,'  her Menelaus led beneath the yoke, and exceeding fain was she of the race.'),(7612,' And fourth Antilochus made ready his fair-maned horses, he the peerless son of Nestor, the king high of heart, the son of Neleus; '),(7613,'and bred at Pylos were the swift-footed horses that drew his car.'),(7614,' And his father drew nigh and gave counsel  to him for his profit — a wise man to one that himself had knowledge.'),(7615,'\"Antilochus, for all thou art young, yet have Zeus and Poseidon loved thee and taught thee all manner of horsemanship; '),(7616,' wherefore to teach thee is no great need, '),(7617,' for thou knowest well how to wheel about the turning-post; '),(7618,' yet are thy horses slowest in the race:'),(7619,' therefore I deem there will be sorry work for thee.'),(7620,' The horses of the others are swifter, but the men know not how to devise more cunning counsel than thine own self.'),(7621,' Wherefore come, dear son, lay thou up in thy mind cunning of every sort, to the end that the prizes escape thee not.'),(7622,'  By cunning, thou knowest, is a woodman far better than by might; '),(7623,'by cunning too doth a helmsman on the wine-dark deep guide aright a swift ship that is buffeted by winds; '),(7624,'and by cunning doth charioteer prove better than charioteer. '),(7625,'  Another man, trusting in his horses and car,  heedlessly wheeleth wide to this side and that, and his horses roam over the course, neither keepeth he them in hand; '),(7626,' whereas he that hath crafty mind, albeit he drive worse horses, keepeth his eye ever on the turning-post and wheeleth close thereby, neither is unmindful how at the first to force his horses with the oxhide reins,  but keepeth them ever in hand, and watcheth the man that leadeth him in the race.'),(7627,' Now will I tell thee a manifest sign that will not escape thee.'),(7628,' There standeth, as it were a fathom\'s height above the ground, a dry stump, whether of oak or of pine, '),(7629,' which rotteth not in the rain, and two white stones on either side  thereof are firmly set against it at the joinings of the course, and about it is smooth ground for driving. Haply it is a monnment of some man long ago dead, or haply was made the turning-post of a race in days of men of old; and now hath switft-footed goodly Achilles appointed it his turningpost. '),(7630,' Pressing hard thereon do thou drive close thy chariot and horses, and thyself lean in thy well-plaited  car a little to the left of the pair, '),(7631,'and to the off horse do thou give the goad, calling to him with a shout, and give him rein from thy hand.'),(7632,' But to the post let the near horse draw close, that the nave of the well-wrought wheel seem to graze the surface thereof— '),(7633,' but be thou ware of touching the stone, lest haply thou wound thy horses and wreck thy car;'),(7634,'so should there be joy for the rest, but reproach it for thyself.'),(7635,' Nay, dear son, be thou wise and on thy guard; '),(7636,'for if at the turning-post thou shalt drive past the rest in thy course,  there is no man that shall catch thee by a burst of speed, neither pass thee by, nay, not though in pursuit he were driving goodly Arion, the swift horse of Adrastus, that was of heavenly stock, or those of Laomedon, the goodly breed of this land.\"'),(7637,'\nSo saying Nestor, son of Neleus, sate him down again in his place,  when he had told his son the sum of every matter.'),(7638,' \nAnd fifth Meriones made ready his fair-maned horses.'),(7639,' Then they mounted their cars, and cast in the lots; '),(7640,'and Achilles shook them, and forth leapt the lot of Nestor\'s son, Antilochus; '),(7641,'after him had the lord Eumelus a place, '),(7642,' and next to him Atreus\' son, Menelaus, famed for his spear, and next to him Meriones drew his place; '),(7643,' and last of all the son of Tydeus, albeit far the best, drew a place for his chariot.'),(7644,' Then took they their places in a row, and Achilles shewed them the turning-post afar off in the smooth plain; '),(7645,'and thereby he set as an umpire  godlike Phoenix, his father\'s follower, that he might mark the running and tell the truth thereof.'),(7646,'\nThen they all at one moment lifted the lash each above his yoke of horses, and smote them with the reins, and called to them with words, '),(7647,'full eagerly and forthwith they sped swiftly over the plain  away from the ships '),(7648,'and beneath their breasts the dust arose and stood, as it were a cloud or a whirlwind, and their manes streamed on the blasts of the wind.'),(7649,' And the chariots would now course over the bounteous earth, and now again would bound on high; '),(7650,' and they that drave  stood in the cars, and each man\'s heart was athrob as they strove for victory; '),(7651,' and they called every man to his horses, that flew in the dust over the plain.'),(7652,'\nBut when now the swift horses were fulfilling the last stretch of the course, back toward the grey sea, then verily was made manifest the worth of each,  and the pace of their horses was forced to the uttermost.'),(7653,'And forthwith the swift-footed mares of the son of Pheres shot to the front,'),(7654,' and after them Diomedes\' stallions of the breed of Tros; not far behind were they, but close behind,'),(7655,' for they seemed ever like to mount upon  Eumelus\' car, and with their breath his back waxed warm and his broad shoulders, '),(7656,'for right over him did they lean their heads as they flew along.'),(7657,' And now would Tydeus\' son have passed him by or left the issue in doubt, had not Phoebus Apollo waxed wroth with him and smitten from his hand the shining lash.'),(7658,'  Then from his eyes ran tears in his wrath for that he saw the mares coursing even far swiftlier still than before, while his own horses were hampered, as running without goad.\n '),(7659,' But Athene was not unaware of Apollo\'s cheating of the son of Tydeus, and right swiftly sped she after the shepherd of the host,  and gave him back the lash and put strength into his horses.'),(7660,' Then in wrath was she gone after the son of Admetus, and the goddess brake the yoke of his steeds, '),(7661,'and to his cost the mares swerved to this side and that of the course, and the pole was swung to the earth; '),(7662,' and Eumelus himself was hurled from out the car beside the wheel,  and from his elbows and his mouth and nose the skin was stripped, and his forehead above his brows was bruised; '),(7663,' and both his eyes were filled with tears and the flow of his voice was checked.'),(7664,' Then Tydeus\' son turned his single-hooved horses aside and drave on, darting out far in advance of the rest;'),(7665,' for Athene  put strength in his horses and gave glory to himself.'),(7666,' And after him drave the son of Atreus, fair-haired Menelaus.'),(7667,' But Antilochus called to the horses of his father:'),(7668,' strain to your utmost speed.'),(7669,' strain to your utmost speed.'),(7670,'With yon steeds verily I nowise bid you strive,  with the horses of wise-hearted Tydeus to the which Athene hath now given speed and vouchsafed glory to him that driveth them.'),(7671,' But the horses of the son of Atreus do ye overtake with speed, and be not outstripped of them, lest shame be shed on you by Aethe that is but a mare.'),(7672,' Why are ye outstripped, good steeds?'),(7673,'  For thus will I speak out to you, and verily it shall be brought to pass:'),(7674,' no tendance shall there be for you twain with Nestor, the shepherd of the host, but forthwith will he slay you with the sharp bronze, if through your heedlessness we win but a worse prize.'),(7675,' Nay, have after them with all speed ye may, '),(7676,' and this will I myself contrive and plan, that we slip past them in the narrow way; it shall not escape me.\"'),(7677,'So spake he, and they, seized with fear at the rebuke of their master, ran swiftlier on for a little time,'),(7678,' and then quickly did Antilochus, staunch in fight, espy a narrow place in the hollow road.'),(7679,'  A rift there was in the ground, where the water, swollen by winter rains, had broken away a part of the road and had hollowed all the place.'),(7680,' There drave Menelaus in hope that none other might drive abreast of him.'),(7681,' But Antilochus turned aside his single-hooved horses, and drave on outside the track, and followed after him, a little at one side.'),(7682,'  And the son of Atreus was seized with fear, and shouted to Antilochus:'),(7683,'\"Antilochus, thou art driving recklessly; nay, rein in thy horses!'),(7684,' Here is the way straitened, but presently it will be wider for passing;  '),(7685,' lest haply thou work harm to us both by fouling my car.\" '),(7686,' \nSo spake he, but Antilochus drave on even the more hotly,  and plied the goad, as he were one that heard not.'),(7687,' And far is the range of a discus swung from the shoulder, which a young man hurleth, making trial of his strength, even so far ran they on;'),(7688,' but the mares of the son of Atreus gave back, '),(7689,'for of his own will he forbare to urge them,  lest haply the single-hooved horses should clash together in the track, and overturn the well-plaited cars, and themselves be hurled in the dust in their eager haste for victory.'),(7690,' Then fair-haired Menelaus chid Antilochus, and said:\"'),(7691,'Antilochus, than thou is none other of mortals more malicious. '),(7692,' Go, and perdition take thee, since falsely did we Achaeans deem thee wise.'),(7693,'Howbeit even so shalt thou not bear off the prize without an oath.\"'),(7694,'\nSo said he, and called to his horses, saying:'),(7695,' \"Hold not back, I bid you, neither stand ye still with grief at heart.'),(7696,' Their feet and knees will grow weary  before yours, '),(7697,'for they both are lacking in youth.\"'),(7698,'So spake be, and they, seized with fear at the rebuke of their master, ran swiftlier on, and quickly came close anigh the others.'),(7699,'\nBut the Argives sitting in the place of gathering were gazing at the horses, '),(7700,'that flew amid the dust over the plain.'),(7701,'  And the first to mark them was Idomeneus, leader of the Cretans,'),(7702,' for he sat without the gathering, the highest of all, in a place of outlook, '),(7703,' and when he heard the voice of him that shouted, albeit afar off, he knew it; and he was ware of a horse, shewing clear to view in front, one that was a bay all the rest of him, but on his forehead was  a white spot round like the moon.'),(7704,' And he stood up, and spake among the Argives saying:\"'),(7705,'My friends, leaders and rulers of the Argives, is it I alone that discern the horses, or do ye as well?'),(7706,' Other are they, meseemeth, that be now in front,  and other is the charioteer that appeareth; '),(7707,'and the mares will have come to harm out yonder on the plain, they that were in front on the outward course.'),(7708,' For in truth I marked them sweeping first about the turning-post, but now can I nowhere spy them, '),(7709,'though mine eyes glance everywhither over the Trojan plain, as I gaze.'),(7710,'  Did the reins haply slip from the charioteer, and was he unable to guide the course aright about the post, and did he fail in the turn?'),(7711,' Even there, methinks, must he have been hurled to earth, and have wrecked his car, and the mares must have swerved from the course in wild terror of heart.'),(7712,' Howbeit stand ye up also, and look; '),(7713,'for myself  I discern not clearly, '),(7714,'but the man seemeth to me to be an Aetolian by race, and is king among the Argives, even the son of horse-taming Tydeus, mighty Diomedes.\" '),(7715,' \nThen shamefully chid him swift Aias, son of Oïleus:\"'),(7716,'Idomeneus, why art thou a braggart from of old?'),(7717,' Nay, still afar off are  the high-stepping mares speeding over the wide plain. '),(7718,' Neither art thou so far the youngest among the Argives, nor do thine eyes look forth from thy head so far the keenliest '),(7719,'yet thou ever pratest loudly.'),(7720,' It beseemeth thee not to be loud of speech, '),(7721,' for here be others better than thou.'),(7722,'  The selfsame mares are in the lead, that led of old, even they of Eumelus, and himself he standeth firmly in the car and holdeth the reins.\"'),(7723,'\nThen the leader of the Cretans waxed wroth, and spake in answer:\"'),(7724,'Aias, thou master of railing, witless in counsel, in all things else thou fallest behind the other Argives, for thy mind is stubborn.'),(7725,'  Come now, let us wager a tripod or a cauldron, and as umpire betwixt us twain let us choose Atreus\' son Agamemnon, as to which mares are in the lead — that thou mayst learn by paying the price.\"'),(7726,'\nSo spake he, and forthwith uprose in wrath swift Aias, son of Oïleus, to answer him with angry words; '),(7727,' and yet furthur would the strife between the twain have gone, had not Achilles himself stood up, and spoken, saying:\"'),(7728,'No longer now, O Aias and Idomeneus, answer ye one another with angry words, with evil words, for that were unseemly.'),(7729,' Ye have indignation with another, whoso should act thus.'),(7730,'  Nay, sit ye down in the place of gathering, and watch ye the horses; '),(7731,'full soon in their eager haste for victory will they come hither,'),(7732,'and then shall ye know, each man of you, the horses of the Argives, which be behind, and which in the lead.\"'),(7733,'\nSo spake he, and Tydeus\' son came hard anigh as he drave,  and with his lash dealt many a stroke down from the shoulder; '),(7734,'and his horses leapt on high as they swiftly sped on their way.'),(7735,' And ever did flakes of dust smite the charioteer, and his chariot overlaid with gold and tin ran on behind the swift-footed horses,'),(7736,' and small trace there was  of the wheel tires behind in the light dust,'),(7737,'  as the twain flew speeding on.'),(7738,'Then he drew up in the midst of the place of gathering, and in streams the sweat flowed from the necks and chests of the horses to the ground.'),(7739,' And Diomedes himself leapt to the ground from his gleaming car,  and leaned the goad against the yoke.'),(7740,' Neither did mighty Sthenelus anywise tarry, but speedily took the prize, and gave to his comrades, high of heart, the woman and the eared tripod to bear away;'),(7741,'and himself loosed the horses from beneath the yoke. '),(7742,' \nAnd next after him Antilochus of the stock of Neleus drave his horses,  for that by guile, and nowise by speed, had he outstripped Menelaus; '),(7743,' howbeit even so Menelaus guided his swift horses close behind.'),(7744,' Far as a horse is from the wheel, a horse that draweth his master over the plain,and straineth at the car—'),(7745,'the tire thereof do the hindmost hairs of his tail touch, '),(7746,'  for it runneth close behind, and but scant space is there between, as he courseth over the wide plain—'),(7747,'even by so much was Menelaus behind peerless Antilochus, '),(7748,'though at the first he was behind far as a man hurleth the discus; howbeit quickly was he overtaking Antilochus, '),(7749,'for the goodly mettle  of the mare of Agamemnon, fair-maned Aethe, waxed ever higher. '),(7750,'And if the course had been yet longer for the twain, then had he passed him by, neither left the issue in doubt.'),(7751,' But Meriones, valiant squire of Idomeneus, was a spear-cast behind glorious Menelaus,'),(7752,' for slowest of all were his fair-maned horses, and himself least skilled to drive a chariot in the race.'),(7753,' And the son of Admetus came in last, behind all the rest, dragging his fair chariot and driving his horses before him.'),(7754,' And at sight of him swift-footed, goodly Achilles had pity  and he stood up amid the Argives, and spake winged words:'),(7755,'\"Lo, in the last place driveth his single-hooved horses the man that is far the best.'),(7756,' But come, let us give him a prize, as is meet, a prize for the second place;'),(7757,'but the first let the son of Tydeus bear away.\"'),(7758,'\nSo spake he, and they all assented even as he bade.'),(7759,'  And now would he have given him the mare —for the Achaeans assented thereto —but that Antilochus, son of great-souled Nestor, uprose and answered Achilles, son of Peleus, to claim his due:'),(7760,' \"Achilles, sore wroth shall I be with thee if thou fulfill this word, '),(7761,'for thou art minded to rob me of my prize,  bethinking thee of this, how his chariot and his swift honses came to harm, and himself withal, good man though he be.'),(7762,' Nay, he should have made prayer to the immortals,'),(7763,' then had he nowise come in last of all in the race.'),(7764,' But if so be thou pitiest him, and he be dear to thy heart, lo, in thy hut is great store of gold, and bronze is there  and sheep, aye, and handmaids too, and single-hooved horses.'),(7765,'Thereof do thou hereafter take and give him even a goodlier prize, or even now forthwith, that the Achaeans may applaud thee.'),(7766,' But the mare will not yield; '),(7767,'for her let any man that will, essay to do battle with me by might of hand.\" '),(7768,' \n  So spake he , and swift-footed, goodly Achilles smiled, having joy in Antilochus, for that he was his dear comrade; '),(7769,'and he made answer, and spake to him winged words:\"'),(7770,'Antilochus, if thou wilt have men give to Eumelus some other thing from out my house as a further prize, even this will I do.'),(7771,'  I will give him the corselet that I took from Asteropaeus; of bronze is it, and thereon is set in circles a casting of bright tin, '),(7772,'and it shall be to him a thing of great worth.\"'),(7773,'\nHe spake, and bade his dear comrade Automedon bring it from the hut '),(7774,'and he went and brought it,  and placed it in Eumelus\' hands '),(7775,'and he received it gladly.'),(7776,'\nThen among them uprose also Menelaus, sore vexed at heart, furiously wroth at Antilochus; '),(7777,'and a herald gave the staff into his hand, and proclaimed silence among the Argives;'),(7778,' and thereafter spake among them the godlike man:'),(7779,' \"Antilochus, thou that aforetime wast wise, what a thing hast thou wrought!'),(7780,'Thou hast put my skill to shame and hast thwarted my horses, thrusting to the front thine own that were worser far.'),(7781,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.perseus-grc1 - 23.573-23.575'),(7782,' Come now, ye leaders and rulers of the Argives, judge ye aright betwixt us twain, neither have regard unto either,  lest in aftertime some one of the brazen-coated Achaeans shall say: ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 573 to line 575'),(7783,'’ Nay, but I will myself declare the right, and I deem that  none other of the Danaans shall reproach me, '),(7784,'for my judgement shall be just.'),(7785,' Antilochus, fostered of Zeus, up, come thou hither and, as is the appointed way, stand thou before thy horses and chariot, and take in hand the slender lash with which aforetimethou wast wont to drive, and laying thy hand on thy horses swear by him that holdeth and shaketh the earth  that not of thine own will didst thou hinder my chariot by guile.”'),(7786,' \nThen in turn wise Antilochus answered him:'),(7787,' \"Bear with me, now, '),(7788,'for far younger am I than thou, king Menelaus, and thou art the elder and the better man.'),(7789,' Thou knowest of what sort are the transgressions of a man that he is young, '),(7790,' for hasty is he of purpose and but slender is his wit.'),(7791,' Wherefore let thy heart be patient;'),(7792,' the mare that I have won will I give thee of my self.'),(7793,' Aye, and if thou shouldst ask some other goodlier thing from out my house, forthwith were I fain to give it thee out of hand, rather than all my days be cast out of thy heart, thou nurtured of Zeus,  and be a sinner in the eyes of the gods.\"'),(7794,'So spake the son of great-souled Nestor, and led up the mare, and gave her into the hands of Menelaus.'),(7795,' And his heart was gladdened even as the corn when with the dew upon the ears it waxeth ripe, what time the fields are bristling. '),(7796,' In such wise, Menelaus, was thy heart gladdened in thy breast. '),(7797,'Then he spake winged words unto Antilochos, saying:'),(7798,' \"Antilochus, lo now, I of myself cease from mine anger against thee, since nowise flighty or light of wit wast thou of old, '),(7799,'albeit now hath thy youth got the better of thy reason.'),(7800,'  Another time seek not to outwit thy betters.'),(7801,' Verily not soon should another of the Achaeans have persuaded me, '),(7802,'but thou hast suffered greatly and toiled greatly, thou and thy brave father and thy brother, for my sake; '),(7803,'wherefore I will hearken to thy prayer, aye,  and will give unto thee the mare, for all she is mine own, to the end that these too may know that my heart is never over-haughty neither unbending.\"'),(7804,'\nHe spake, and gave the mare unto Nosmon, the comrade of Antilochus, to lead away, '),(7805,' and himself thereafter took the shining cauldron.'),(7806,'And Meriones took up the two talents of gold in the fourth place,  even as he drave; '),(7807,'but the fifth prize was left unclaimed, even the two-handled urn.'),(7808,' Unto Nestor Achilles gave this, bearing it through the gathering of the Argives; and he came to his side, and said'),(7809,'\"Take this now, old sire, and let it be treasure for thee, a memorial of Patroclus\' burying; '),(7810,'for nevermore shalt thou behold him  among the Argives.'),(7811,' Lo, I give thee this prize unwon;'),(7812,' for not in boxing shalt thou contend, neither in wrestling, nor shalt thou enter the lists for the casting of javelins, neither run upon thy feet; '),(7813,'for now grievous old age weigheth heavy upon thee.\"'),(7814,' \nSo saying he placed the urn in his arms, '),(7815,' and Nestor received it gladly,  and spake, and addressed him with winged words:'),(7816,'\"Aye, verily, my son, all this hast thou spoken aright, '),(7817,'for my limbs, even my feet, are no more firm, O my friend, as of old, nor do my arms as of old dart out lightly from my shoulders on either side. '),(7818,'Would that I were young, and my strength were firm  as on the day when the Epeians were burying lord Amarynceus at Buprasium, and his sons appointed prizes in honour of the king.'),(7819,' Then was there no man that proved himself my peer, neither of the Epeians nor of Pylians themselves nor of the great-souled Aetolians.'),(7820,' In boxing I overcame Clytomedes, son of Enops,  and in wrestling Ancaeus of Pleuron, who stood up against me; '),(7821,'Iphiclus I outran in the foot-race, good man though he was; and in casting the spear I outthrew Phyleus and Polydorus.'),(7822,' In the chariot race alone the twain sons of Actor outstripped me by force of numbers crowding their horses to the front, being exceeding jealous for victory,  for that the goodliest prize abode yet there in the lists. '),(7823,' Twin brethren were they— '),(7824,' the one drave with sure hand, drave with sure hand, while the other plied the goad.'),(7825,'Thus was I on a time,'),(7826,'but now let men that be younger face such-like tasks; '),(7827,'me it behoveth to yield to grievous old age,  but then was I pre-eminent among warriors. '),(7828,'But come, for thy comrade too hold thou funeral rites with contests.'),(7829,' For this gift, I receive it wlth gladness, and my heart rejoiceth that thou rememberest me, thy friend, neither am I forgotten of thee, and the honour wherewith it beseemeth that I be honoured among the Achaeans.'),(7830,'  And to thee may the gods in requital thereof grant grace to satisfy thy heart.\"'),(7831,'\nSo spake he, and the son of Peleus went his way through the great throng of the Achaeans, when he had hearkened to all the praise of the son of Neleus.'),(7832,' Then set he forth prizes for grievous boxing.'),(7833,' A sturdy mule he brought and tethered in the place of gathering,  a mule of six years, unbroken, the which is hardest of all to break; '),(7834,'and for him that should be worsted he appointed a two-handled cup.'),(7835,' Then he stood up, and spake among the Argives, saying:'),(7836,' \"Son of Atreus, and ye other well-greaved Achaeans, for these prizes we invite warriors twain, the best there are, to lift up their hands and box amain.'),(7837,'  Let him to whom Apollo shall grant strength to endure, and all the Achaeans have knowledge thereof, go his way to his hut leading the sturdy muIe;'),(7838,'but he that is worsted shall bear as his prize the two-handled cup.\" '),(7839,' \nSo spake he, and forthwith uprose a man valiant and tall,  well-skilled in boxing, even Epeius, son of Panopeus; and he laid hold of the sturdy mule, and spake, saying:\"'),(7840,'Let him draw nigh, whoso is to bear as his prize the two-handled cup :'),(7841,' the mule I deem that none other of the Achaeans shall lead away, by worsting me with his fists, for I avow me to be the best man.'),(7842,'  Sufficeth it not that I fall short in battle?'),(7843,' One may not, meseemeth, prove him a man of skill in every work.'),(7844,' For thus will I speak, and verily this thing shall be brought to pass :'),(7845,' utterly will I rend his flesh and crush his bones.'),(7846,' Wherefore let them that be next of kin abide here in a throng,  that they may bear him forth when worsted by my hands.\"'),(7847,'So spake he, and they all became hushed in silence.'),(7848,' Euryalus alone uprose to face him, a godlike man, son of king Mecisteus, son of Talaus, who on a time had come to Thebes for the burial of Oedipus,  when he had fallen,'),(7849,' and there had worsted all the sons of Cadmus. '),(7850,'And Tydeus\' son, famed for his spear, made Euryalus ready, heartening him with words, and much he wished for him victory.'),(7851,' A girdle first he cast about him, and thereafter gave him well-cut thongs of the hide of an ox of the field.'),(7852,'  So the twain, when they had girded themselves, stepped into the midst of the place of gathering, and lifting their mighty hands on high one against the other, fell to, and their hands clashed together in heavy blows.'),(7853,' Dread then was the grinding of their teeth, and the sweat flowed on every side from off their limbs'),(7854,'But upon him goodly Epeius rushed  as he peered for an opening,and smote him on the cheek, '),(7855,'nor after that, methinks, did he long stand upright, '),(7856,'for even there did his glorious limbs sink beneath him. '),(7857,'And as when beneath the ripple of the North Wind a fish leapeth up on the tangle-strewn sand of a shallow, and then the black wave hideth it, even so leapt up Euryalus when he was smitten.'),(7858,' But great-souled Epeius  took him in his hands and set him on his feet,'),(7859,' and his dear comrades thronged about him and led him through the place of gathering with trailing feet, spitting out clotted blood and letting his head hang to one side; '),(7860,'and they brought him wandering in his wits and set him down in the midst of their company, and themselves went and fetched the two-handled cup. '),(7861,' \n  Then the son of Peleus forthwith ordained in the sight of the Danaans other prizes for a third contest, even for toilsome wrestling — for him that should win, a great tripod to stand upon the fire, that the Achaeans prized amongst them at the worth of twelve oxen; '),(7862,'and for him that should be worsted he set in the midst a woman  of manifold skill in handiwork, and they prized her at the worth of four oxen. '),(7863,'And he stood up and spake among the Argives saying:'),(7864,' \"Up now, ye twain that will make essay likewise in this contest.\"'),(7865,'So spake he, and thereat arose great Telamonian Aias, and up stood Odysseus of many wiles, he of guileful mind.'),(7866,'  Then the twain, when they had girded themselves, stepped into the midst of the place of gathering, and laid hold each of the other in close grip with their mighty hands, even as the gable-rafters of a high house, which some famous craftsman joineth together, that he may have shelter from the might of the winds.'),(7867,' And their backs creaked beneath the violent tugging of bold hands, '),(7868,' and the sweat flowed down in streams; and many a weal, red with blood, sprang up along their ribs and shoulders; '),(7869,'and ever they strove amain for victory, to win the fashioned tripod.'),(7870,' Neither might Odysseus avail to trip Aias and throw him to the ground,  nor Aias him, for the mighty strength of Odysseus held firm. '),(7871,'But when at the last they were like to weary the well-greaved Achaeans, then unto Odysseus spake great Telamonian Aias, saying:\"'),(7872,'Zeus-born, son of Laertes, Odysseus of many wiles, lift thou me, or let me lift thee; '),(7873,' but the issue shall rest with Zeus.\"'),(7874,' but Odysseus forgat not his guile.'),(7875,' but Odysseus forgat not his guile.'),(7876,'\n He smote with a sure blow the hollow of Aias\' knee from behind, and loosed his limbs, so that he was thrown backward,'),(7877,' and Odysseus fell upon his chest; '),(7878,' and the people gazed thereon and were seized with wonder.'),(7879,'Then in his turn the much-enduring goodly Odysseus essayed to lift,  and moved him a little from the ground, but lifted him not, howbeit he crooked his knee within that of Aias, '),(7880,'and upon the ground the twain fell one hard by the other, and were befouled with dust.'),(7881,' And now would they have sprung up again for the third time and have wrestled, but that Achilles himself uprose, and held them back:'),(7882,'  \"No longer strain ye now, neither be worn with pain.'),(7883,' Victory is with you both; '),(7884,'take then equa1 prizes and go your ways, that other Achaeans too may strive.\"'),(7885,'\nSo spake he, and they readily hearkened to him and obeyed, and wiping from their bodies the dust they put upon them their tunics. '),(7886,' \n  Then the son of Peleus straightway set forth other prizes for fleetness of foot: a mixingbowl of silver, richly wrought; '),(7887,'six measures it held, and in beauty it was far the goodliest in all the earth, seeing that Sidonians, well skilled in deft handiwork, had wrought it cunningly, and men of the Phoenicians brought it over the murky deep, and landed it in harbour,  and gave it as a gift to Thoas; '),(7888,'and as a ransom for Lycaon, son of Priam, Jason\'s son Euneos gave it to the warrior Patroclus.'),(7889,' This bowl did Achilles set forth as a prize in honourof his comrade, even for him whoso should prove fleetest in speed of foot.'),(7890,'  For the second again he set an ox great and rich with fat; and a half-talent in gold he appointed for the last.'),(7891,' And he stood up, and spake among the Argives saying:'),(7892,' \"Up now, ye that will make essay likewise in this contest.\" '),(7893,'So spake he, and forthwith uprose swift Aias, son of Oïleus,  and Odysseus of many wiles, and after them Antilochus, Nestor\'s son, '),(7894,'for he surpassed all the youths in swiftness of foot.'),(7895,'and Achilles showed them the goal, '),(7896,'and Achilles showed them the goal, '),(7897,'and a course was marked out for them from the turning-point.'),(7898,' Then speedily the son of Oïleus forged to the front, '),(7899,' and close after him sped goodly Odysseus;  close as is the weaving-rod to the breast of a fair-girdled woman, when she deftly draweth it in her hands, pulling the spool past the warp, and holdeth the rod nigh to her breast; '),(7900,'even so close behind ran Odysseus,  and his feet trod in the footsteps of Aias or ever the dust had settled therein, '),(7901,'and down upon his head beat the breath of goodly Odysseus, as he ran ever swiftly on; '),(7902,'and all the Achaeans shouted to further him as he struggled for victory, and called to him as he strained to the utmost.'),(7903,' But when now they were running the last part of the course, straightway Odysseus made prayer in his heart to flashing-eyed Athene:'),(7904,'  \"Hear me, goddess, and come a goodly helper to my feet.\"'),(7905,' So spake he in prayer, '),(7906,'and Pallas Athene heard him, and made his limbs light, his feet and his hands above. '),(7907,' But when they were now about to dart forth to win the prize, then Aias slipped as he ran—for Athene hampered him—  where was strewn the filth from the slaying of the loud bellowing bulls that swift-footed Achilles had slain in honour of Patroclus; '),(7908,'and with the filth of the bulls were his mouth and nostrils filled.'),(7909,' So then much-enduring, goodly Odysseus took up the bowl, seeing he came in the first, '),(7910,' and glorious Aias took the ox.'),(7911,'  And he stood holding in his hands the horn of the ox of the field, spewing forth the filth; and he spake among the Argives:'),(7912,' \"Out upon it, lo, the goddess hampered me in my running, she that standeth ever by Odysseus\' side like a mother, and helpeth him.\" '),(7913,' \nSo spake he, but they all laughed merrily at him.'),(7914,'  Then Antilochus bare away the last prize, smiling the while, and spake among the Argives, saying:'),(7915,' \"Among you all that know it well, will I declare, my friends, that even to this day the immortals shew honour to older men.'),(7916,' For Aias is but a little older than I,  whereas Odysseus is of an earlier generation and of earlier men—'),(7917,'a green old age is his, men say—'),(7918,'yet hard were he for any other Achaean to contend with in running, save only for Achilles.\"'),(7919,'\nSo spake he,and gave glory to the son of Peleus, swift of foot.'),(7920,' And Achilles made answer, and spake to him, saying:'),(7921,'  \"Antilochus, not in vain shall thy word of praise be spoken; nay, I will add to thy prize a half-talent of gold.\"'),(7922,'\nSo saying, he set it in his hands, and Antilochus received it gladly.'),(7923,' But the son of Peleus brought and set in the place of gathering a far-shadowing spear, and therewith a shield and helmet,  the battlegear of Sarpedon, that Patroclus stripped from him; '),(7924,'and he stood up, and spake among the Argives, saying:\"'),(7925,'To win these prizes invite we warriors twain, the best there are, to clothe them in their armour and take bronze that cleaveth the flesh, and so make trial each of the other before the host.'),(7926,'  Whoso of the twain shall first reach the other\'s fair flesh, and touch the inward parts through armour and dark blood, to him will I give this silver-studded sword—a goodly Thracian sword which I took from Asteropaeus; '),(7927,'  and these arms let the twain bear away to hold in common; '),(7928,' and a goodly banquet shall we set before them in our huts.\"'),(7929,'So spake he, and thereat arose great Telamonian Aias, and up rose the son of Tydeus, stalwart Diomedes.'),(7930,' So when they had armed them on either side of the throng, into the midst strode the twain, eager for battle,  glaring terribly;'),(7931,' and amazement held all the Achaeans. '),(7932,'But when they were come near as they advance done against the other, thrice they set upon each other, and thrice they clashed together.'),(7933,' Then Aias thrust upon the shield, that was well-balanced upon every side, but reached not the flesh, '),(7934,' for the corselet within kept off the spear.'),(7935,'  But Tydeus\' son over the great shield sought ever to reach the neck with the point of his shining spear, '),(7936,'Then verily the Achaeans, seized with fear for Aias, bade them cease and take up equal prizes.'),(7937,' Howbeit to Tydeus\' son the warrior gave the great sword,  bringing it with its scabbard and its well-cut baldric.'),(7938,' \nThen the son of Peleus set forth a mass of rough-cast iron, which of old the mighty strength of Eëtion was wont to hurl; '),(7939,'but him had swift-footed goodly Achilles slain, and bare this away on his ships with his other possessions.'),(7940,'  And he stood up, and spake among the Argives, saying :'),(7941,'\"Up now, ye that will make essay likewise in this contest.'),(7942,' Though his rich fields lie very far remote, the winner hereof will have it five revolving years to serve his need; '),(7943,' for not through lack of iron will his shepherd or ploughman  fare to the city; nay, this will supply them.\" '),(7944,'So spake he, and thereat arose Polypoetes, staunch in fight, and the mighty strength of godlike Leonteus, and Aias, son of Telamon, and goodly Epeius.'),(7945,' Then they took their places in order, and goodly Epeius grasped the mass, and whirled and flung it; '),(7946,'and all the Achaeans laughed aloud thereat.'),(7947,' Then in turn Leonteus, scion of Ares, made a cast; '),(7948,'and thirdly great Telamonian Aias hurled it from his strong hand, and sent it past the marks of all. '),(7949,'But when Polypoetes, staunch in fight,  grasped the mass, far as a herdsman flings his crook, and it flieth whirling over the herds of kine, even so far cast he it beyond all the gathering; '),(7950,' and the folk shouted aloud.'),(7951,'And the comrades of strong Polypoetes rose up and bare to the hollow ships the prize of the king.'),(7952,'\n  Then for the archers he set forth as a prize dark iron—ten double axes laid he down, and ten single; and he set up the mast of a dark-prowed ship far off in the sands, and with a slender cord made fast thereto by the foot a timorous dove, and bade shoot thereat.'),(7953,'  \"Whoso shall hit the timorous dove let him take up all the double axes and bear them home,'),(7954,' and whoso shall hit the cord, albeit he miss the bird: lo, his is the worser shot; he shall bear as his prize the single axes.\" '),(7955,' \nSo spake he, and there arose the might of the prince Teucer,  and Meriones the valiant squire of Idomeneus. '),(7956,'Then took they the lots and shook them in a helmet of bronze, and Teucer drew by lot the first place.'),(7957,' Forthwith he let fly an arrow with might, howbeit he vowed not that he would sacrifice to the king a glorious hecatomb of firstling lambs. '),(7958,'for Apollo grudged him that, '),(7959,'for Apollo grudged him that, '),(7960,'but hit the cord beside its foot wherewith the bird was tied, '),(7961,'and clean away the bitter arrow cut the cord.'),(7962,' Then the dove darted skyward, and the cord hung loose toward earth; '),(7963,'and the Achaeans shouted aloud.'),(7964,'  But Meriones speedily snatched the bow from Teucer\'s hand—'),(7965,'an arrow had he long been holding while Teucer aimed—'),(7966,'and vowed forthwith that he would sacrifice to Apollo that smiteth afar a glorious hecatomb of firstling lambs.'),(7967,' High up beneath the cloud he spied the timorous dove;'),(7968,' there as she circled round he struck her in the midst beneath the wing, and clean through passed the shaft, '),(7969,' and fell again and fixed itself in the ground before the foot of Meriones;'),(7970,'but the dove, lighting on the mast of the dark-prowed ship, hung down her head, and her thick plumage drooped.'),(7971,'  Swiftly the life fled from her limbs, and she fell far from the mast; '),(7972,'and the people gazed thereon and were seized with wonder.'),(7973,' And Meriones took up all ten double axes, and Teucer bare the single to the hollow ships.'),(7974,'Then the son of Peleus brought and set in the place of gathering a far-shadowing spear  and a cauldron, that the fire had not yet touched, of an ox\'s worth, embossed with flowers; '),(7975,'and men that were hurlers of javelins arose.'),(7976,' Up rose the son of Atreus, wide-ruling Agamemnon and Meriones, the valiant squire of Idomeneus.'),(7977,' But among them spake swift-footed, goodly Achilles:'),(7978,'  \"Son of Atreus,'),(7979,' we know how far thou excellest all, and how far thou art the best in might and in the casting of the spear; '),(7980,'nay, take thou this prize and go thy way to the hollow ships; but the spear let us give to the warrior Meriones, if thy heart consenteth thereto:'),(7981,' so at least would I have it:\"'),(7982,'  So spake he, and the king of men, Agamemnon, failed not to hearken.'),(7983,' Then to Meriones he gave the spear of bronze, '),(7984,'but the warrior handed to the herald Talthybius the beauteous prize.'),(7985,' Then was the gathering broken up, and the folk scattered, each man to go to his own ship.'),(7986,' The rest bethought them of supper and of sweet sleep, to take their fill thereof;'),(7987,'but Achilles wept, ever remembering his dear comrade, neither might sleep,  that mastereth all, lay hold of him, but he turned him ever to this side or to that, yearning for the man-hood and valorous might of Patroclus, thinking on all he had wrought with him and all the woes he had borne, passing though wars of men and the grievous waves. '),(7988,'Thinking thereon he would shed big tears,  lying now upon his side, now upon his back, and now upon his face; '),(7989,'and then again he would rise upon his feet and roam distraught along the shore of the sea.'),(7990,' Neither would he fail to mark the Dawn, as she shone over the sea and the sea-beaches, '),(7991,'but would yoke beneath the car his swift horses,  and bind Hector behind the chariot to drag him withal; and when he had haled him thrice about the barrow of the dead son of Menoetius, he would rest again in his hut, but would leave Hector outstretched on his face in the dust.'),(7992,' Howbeit Apollo kept all defacement from his flesh, pitying the warrior  even in death, '),(7993,'and with the golden aegis he covered him wholly, that Achilles might not tear his body as he dragged him. '),(7994,' \nThus Achilles in his fury did foul despite unto goodly Hector; '),(7995,'but the blessed gods had pity on him as they beheld him, and bestirred the keen-sighted Argeiphontes to steal away the corpse.'),(7996,'  And the thing was pleasing unto all the rest, yet not unto Hera or Poseidon or the flashing-eyed maiden, but they continued even as when at the first sacred Ilios became hateful in their eyes and Priam and his folk, by reason of the sin of Alexander, for that he put reproach upon those goddesses when they came to his steading,  and gave precedence to her who furthered his fatal lustfulness. '),(7997,'But when at length the twelfth morn thereafter was come, then among the immortals spake Phoebus Apollo:\"'),(7998,'Cruel are ye, O ye gods, and workers of bane.'),(7999,' Hath Hector then never burned for you thighs of bulls and goats without blemish?'),(8000,'  Him now have ye not the heart to save, a corpse though he be, for his wife to look upon and his mother and his child, and his father Priam and his people, who would forthwith burn him in the fire and pay him funeral rites. '),(8001,' Nay, it is the ruthless Achilles, O ye gods, that ye are fain to succour,  him whose mind is nowise right, neither the purpose in his breast one that may be bent; but his heart is set on cruelty, even as a lion that at the bidding of his great might and lordly spirit goeth forth against the flocks of men to win him a feast;'),(8002,'even so hath Achilles lost all pity, neither is shame in his heart,  the which harmeth men greatly and profiteth them withal.'),(8003,' Lo, it may be that a man hath lost one dearer even than was this—a brother, that the selfsame mother bare, or haply a son;'),(8004,' yet verily when he hath wept and wailed for him he maketh an end; '),(8005,'for an enduring soul have the Fates given unto men.'),(8006,'  But this man, when he hath reft goodly Hector of life, bindeth him behind his chariot and draggeth him about the barrow of his dear comrade; '),(8007,'in sooth neither honour nor profit shall he have therefrom. '),(8008,' Let him beware lest we wax wroth with him, good man though he be; '),(8009,' for lo, in his fury he doth foul despite unto senseless clay.\"'),(8010,'  Then stirred to anger spake to him white-armed Hera:'),(8011,'\"Even this might be as thou sayest, Lord of the silver bow, if indeed ye gods will vouchsafe like honour to Achilles and to Hector.'),(8012,' Hector is but mortal and was suckled at a woman\'s breast, '),(8013,'but Achilles is the child of a goddess that I mine own self  fostered and reared, and gave to a warrior to be his wife, even to Peleus, who was heartily dear to the immortals.'),(8014,' And all of you, O ye gods, came to her marriage,  '),(8015,'and among them thyself too didst sit at the feast, thy lyre in thy hand, O thou friend of evil-doers, faithless ever.\" '),(8016,' \nThen Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, answered her, and said:'),(8017,'  \"Hera, be not thou utterly wroth against the gods;'),(8018,' the honour of these twain shall not be as one; '),(8019,'howbeit Hector too was dearest to the gods of all mortals that are in Ilios.'),(8020,' So was he to me at least, for nowise failed he of acceptable gifts.'),(8021,' For never was my altar in lack of the equal feast,  the drink-offiering and the savour of burnt-offering,'),(8022,'  even the worship that is our due. '),(8023,' Howbeit of the stealing away of bold Hector will we naught; it may not be but that Achilles would be ware thereof; '),(8024,' for verily his mother cometh ever to his side alike by night and day.'),(8025,'But I would that one of the gods would call Thetis to come unto me,  that I may speak to her a word of wisdom, to the end that Achilles may accept gifts from Priam, and give Hector back.\"'),(8026,'\n So spake he, and storm-footed Iris hasted to bear his message, and midway between Samos and rugged Imbros she leapt into the dark sea, '),(8027,'and the waters sounded loud above her.'),(8028,'  Down sped she to the depths hike a plummet of lead, the which, set upon the horn of an ox of the field, goeth down bearing death to the ravenous fishes.'),(8029,' And she found Thetis in the hollow cave, and round about her other goddesses of the sea sat in a throng, ');
INSERT INTO `Sentence_Translation` VALUES (8030,' and she in their midst  was wailing for the fate of her peerless son, who to her sorrow was to perish in deep-soiled Troy, far from his native land.'),(8031,' And swift-footed Iris drew near, and spake to her:\"'),(8032,'Zeus, whose counsels are everlasting, calleth thee.\"'),(8033,'Zeus, whose counsels are everlasting, calleth thee.\"'),(8034,' Then spake in answer Thetis, the silver-footed goddess:'),(8035,'  \"Wherefore summoneth me that mighty god?'),(8036,' I have shame to mingle in the company of the immortals, seeing I have measurehess griefs at heart.'),(8037,' Howbeit I will go, neither shall his word be vain, whatsoever he shall speak.\" '),(8038,' \nSo saying, the fair goddess took a dark-hued veil, than which was no raiment more black, '),(8039,' and set out to go, and before her wind-footed swift Iris led the way; '),(8040,' and about them the surge of the sea parted asunder.'),(8041,'And when they had stepped forth upon the beach they sped unto heaven; and they found the son of Cronos, whose voice is borne afar, and around him sat gathered together all the other blessed gods that are for ever.'),(8042,'  Then she sate her down beside father Zeus, and Athene gave place.'),(8043,' And Hera set in her hand a fair golden cup, and spake words of cheer.'),(8044,'; and Thetis drank, and gave back the cup.'),(8045,' Then among them the father of men and gods was first to speak:\"'),(8046,'Thou art come to Olympus, 0, goddess Thetis,  for all thy sorrow, though thou hast comfortless grief at heart; '),(8047,' I know it of myself; '),(8048,'yet even so will I tell thee wherefore I called thee hither.'),(8049,' For nine days\' space hath strife arisen among the immortals as touching the corpse of Hector and Achilles, sacker of cities.'),(8050,' They are for bestirring the keen-sighted Argeiphontes to steal the body away,'),(8051,' yet herein do I accord honour unto Achilles; for I would fain keep in time to come thy worship and thy love.'),(8052,' Haste thee with all speed to the host and declare unto thy son my bidding. '),(8053,'Say unto him that the gods are angered with him, and that I above all immortals am filled with wrath, for that in the fury of his heart  he holdeth Hector at the beaked ships and gave him not back, if so be he may be seized with fear of me and give Hector back.'),(8054,' But I will send forth Iris unto great-hearted Priam, to bid him go to the ships of the Achaeans to ransom his dear son, and to bear gifts unto Achilles which shall make glad his heart.\" '),(8055,' \n  So spake he, and the goddess, silver-footed Thetis, failed not to hearken, but went darting down from the peaks of Olympus, and came to the hut of her son.'),(8056,' There she found him groaning ceaselessly, '),(8057,'and round about him his dear comrades with busy haste were making ready their early meal,'),(8058,' and in the hut a ram, great and shaggy, lay slaughtered for them. '),(8059,'Then she, his queenly mother, sate her down close by his side and stroked him with her hand, and spake, and called him by name:\"'),(8060,'My child, how long wilt thou devour thine heart with weeping and sorrowing, and wilt take no thought of food,  neither of the couch? '),(8061,'Good were it for thee even to have dalliance in a woman\'s embrace.'),(8062,' For, I tell thee, thou shalt not thyself be long in life, but even now doth death stand hard by thee and mighty fate.'),(8063,' But hearken thou forthwith unto me, for I am a messenger unto thee from Zeus. '),(8064,'He declareth that that the gods are angered with thee,  and that himself above all immortals is filled with wrath, for that in the fury of thine heart thou holdest Hector at the beaked ships, and gavest him not back.'),(8065,' Nay come, give him up, and take ransom for the dead.\"'),(8066,'Then in answer to her spake Achilles, swift of foot:'),(8067,' \"So let it be;'),(8068,'whoso bringeth ransom, let him bear away the dead,  if verily with full purpose of heart the Olympian himself so biddeth.\"'),(8069,'On this wise amid the gathering of the ships mother and son spake many winged words one to the other,'),(8070,' but the son of Cronos sent forth Iris to sacred Ilios:'),(8071,'\"Up, go, swift Iris; leave thou the abode of Olympus  and bear tidings within Ilios unto great-hearted Priam that he go to the ships of the Achaeans to ransom his dear son, and that he bear gifts unto Achilles which shall make glad his heart; alone let him go, neither let any man beside of the Trojans go with him.'),(8072,'A herald may attend him, an elder man,  to guide the mules and the light-running waggon, and to carry back to the city the dead, even him that Achilles slew.'),(8073,' Let not death be in his thoughts. neither any fear;'),(8074,' such a guide will we give him, even Argeiphontes, who shall lead him, until in his leading he bring him nigh to Achilles.'),(8075,'  And when he shall have led him into the hut, neither shall Achilles himself slay him nor suffer any other to slay; '),(8076,'for not without wisdom is he, neither without purpose, nor yet hardened in sin; nay, with all kindliness will he spare a suppliant man.\" '),(8077,' \nSo spake he, and storm-footed Iris hasted to bear his message.'),(8078,' She came to the house of Priam, and found therein clamour and wailing.'),(8079,' His sons sat about their father within the court sullying their garments with their tears, and in their midst was the old king close-wrapped in his mantle; '),(8080,' and upon the old man\'s head and neck was filth in abundance,  which he had gathered in his hands as he grovelled on the earth. '),(8081,'And his daughters and his sons\' wives were wailing throughout the house, bethinking them of the warriors many and valiant who were lying low, slain by the hands of the Argives.'),(8082,' And the messenger of Zeus drew nigh to Priam, and spake to him;  softly she uttered her voice, '),(8083,'yet trembling gat hold of his himbs:'),(8084,'\"Be of good courage, O Priam, son of Dardanus, and fear thou not at all.'),(8085,' Not to forbode any evil to thee am I come hither, but with good intent.'),(8086,' I am a messenger to thee from Zeus, who far away though he be, hath exceeding care for thee and pity.'),(8087,'  The Olympian biddeth thee ransom goodly Hector, and bear gifts to Achilles which shall make glad his heart; alone do thou go, neither let any man beside of the Trojans go with thee.'),(8088,' A herald may attend thee, an elder man, to guide the mules and the light-running waggon,  and to carry back to the city the dead, even him that Achilles slew.'),(8089,' Let not death be in thy thoughts, neither any fear;'),(8090,'such a guide shall go with thee, even Argeiphontes, who shall lead thee, until in his heading he bring thee nigh to Achilles.'),(8091,' And when he shall have led thee into the hut,  neither shall Achilles himself slay thee nor suffer any other to slay; '),(8092,'for not without wisdom is he, neither without purpose, nor yet hardened in sin; nay, with all kindliness will he spare a suppliant man.\"'),(8093,'When she had thus spoken swift-footed Iris departed; but the king bade his sons  make ready the running mule waggon, and bind the wicker box thereon.'),(8094,' And himself he went down to the vaulted treasure-chamber, fragrant of cedar wood and high of roof, that held jewels full many:'),(8095,' and he called to him Hecabe his wife, and spake:'),(8096,'\"Lady, from Zeus hath an Olympian messenger come to me,  that I go to the ships of the Achaeans to ransom my dear son, and that I bear gifts to Achilles which shall make glad his heart.'),(8097,' But come, tell me this, how seemeth it to thy mind?'),(8098,' For as touching mine own self, wondrously doth the desire of my heart bid me go thither to the ships, into the wide camp of the Achaeans.\" '),(8099,' \n  So spake he, but his wife uttered a shrill cry, and spake in answer:'),(8100,'\"Ah, woe is me, whither now is gone the wisdom for the which of old thou wast famed among stranger folk and among them thou rulest?'),(8101,' How art thou fain to go alone to the ships of the Achaeans to meet the eyes of the man who  hath slain thy sons, many and valiant?'),(8102,'Of iron verily is thy heart.'),(8103,'For if so be he get thee in his power and his eyes behold thee, so savage and faithless is the man, he will neither pity thee nor anywise have reverence.'),(8104,' Nay, let us now make our lament afar from him we mourn, abiding here in the hall. '),(8105,'On this wise for him did mighty Fate spin  with her thread at his birth, when myself did bear him, that he should glut swift-footed dogs far from his parents, in the abode of a violent man, in whose inmost heart I were fain to fix my teeth and feed thereon; '),(8106,'then haply might deeds of requital be wrought for my son, seeing in no wise while playing the dastard was he slain of him,  but while standing forth in defence of the men and deep-bosomed women of Troy, with no thought of shelter or of flight.\"'),(8107,'\nThen in answer spake unto her the old man, god-like Priam:\"'),(8108,'Seek not to stay me that am fain to go, neither be thyself a bird of ill-boding in my halls; '),(8109,'thou shalt not persuade me.'),(8110,'  For if any other of the men that are upon the face of the earth had bidden me this, whether of seers that divine from sacrifice or of priests, a false thing might we deem it, and turn away therefrom the more; '),(8111,'but now—for myself I heard the voice of the goddess and looked upon her face—I will go forth, neither shall her word be vain. '),(8112,'And if it be my fate  to lie dead by the ships of the brazen-coated Achaeans, so would I have it; '),(8113,'forthwith let Achilles slay me, when once I have clasped in my arms my son, and have put from me the desire for wailing.\" '),(8114,' \nHe spake, and opened the goodly lids of chests, '),(8115,'wherefrom he took twelve beauteous robes  and twelve cloaks of single fold, and as many coverlets, and as many white mantles, and therewithal as many tunics.'),(8116,' And of gold he weighed out and bare forth talents, ten in all, and two gleaming tripods, and four cauldrons, and a cup exceeding fair, that the men of Thrace had given him  when he went thither on an embassage, a great treasure;'),(8117,' not even this did the old man spare in his halls, for he was exceeding fain to ransom his dear son.'),(8118,' Then drave he all the Trojans from out the portico, and chid them with words of reviling:\"'),(8119,'Get ye hence, wretches, ye that work me shame!'),(8120,'  Have ye not also lamentation at home, that ye come hither to vex me?'),(8121,' Count ye it not enough that Zeus, son of Cronos, hath brought this sorrow upon me, that I should lose my son the best of all?'),(8122,' Nay, but yourselves too shall know it,'),(8123,' for easier shall ye be, now he is dead, for the Achaeans to slay.'),(8124,'  But for me, or ever mine eyes behold the city sacked and laid waste, may I go down into the house of Hades.\"'),(8125,'He spake, and plying his staff went among the men,'),(8126,'\n and they went forth from before the old man in his haste. '),(8127,' Then called he aloud to his sons, chiding Helenus and Paris and goodly Agathon  and Pammon and Antiphonus and Polites, good at the war-cry, and Deiphobus and Hippothous and lordly Dius.'),(8128,' To these nine the old man called aloud, and gave command:\"'),(8129,'Haste ye, base children that are my shame;'),(8130,' would that ye all together in Hector\'s stead had been slain at the swift ships!'),(8131,'  Woe is me, that am all unblest, seeing that I begat sons the best in the broad land of Troy, yet of them I avow that not one is left, not godlike Nestor, not Troilus the warrior charioteer, not Hector that was a god among men, neither seemed he as the son of a mortal man, but of a god:'),(8132,'  all them hath Ares slain, yet these things of shame are all left me, false of tongue, nimble of foot, peerless at beating the floor in the dance, robbers of lambs and kids from your own folk.'),(8133,' Will ye not make me ready a waggon, and that with speed, and lay all these things therein, that we may get forward on our way?\" '),(8134,' \n  So spake he, and they, seized with fear of the rebuke of their father, brought forth the light-running waggon drawn of mules, fair and newly-wrought, and bound upon it the wicker box; and down from its peg they took the mule-yoke, a box-wood yoke with a knob thereon, well-fitted with guiding-rings; '),(8135,' and they brought forth the yoke-band of nine cubits, and therewithal the yoke. '),(8136,'The yoke they set with care upon the polished pole at the upturned end thereof, and cast the ring upon the thole; and they bound it fast to the knob with three turns to left and right, and thereafter made it fast to the post, and bent the hook thereunder.'),(8137,'  Then they brought forth from the treasure-chamber and heaped upon the polished waggon the countless ransom for Hector\'s head, and yoked the strong-hooved mules that toil in harness, which on a time the Mysians had given to Priam, a splendid gift.'),(8138,' And for Priam they led beneath the yoke horses that the old king  kept for his own and reared at the polished stall.'),(8139,'Thus were the twain letting yoke their cars, in the high palace, even the herald and Priam, with thoughts of wisdom in their hearts,'),(8140,'when nigh to them came Hecabe, her heart sore stricken, bearing in her right hand honey-hearted wine in a cup of gold, that they might make libation ere they went.'),(8141,'  And she stood before the horses, and spake, saying:'),(8142,' \"Take now, pour libation to father Zeus, and pray that thou mayest come back home from the midst of the foemen, seeing thy heart sendeth thee forth to the ships, albeit I am fain thou shouldst not go, '),(8143,' Thereafter make thou prayer unto the son of Cronos, lord of the dark chouds, the god of Ida, that looketh down upon all the land of Troy, and ask of him a bird of omen, even the swift messenger that to himself is dearest of birds and is mightiest in strength; let him appear upon thy right hand, to the end that marking the sign with thine own eyes,  thou mayest have trust therein, and go thy way to the ships of the Danaans of fleet steeds. '),(8144,'But if so be Zeus whose voice is borne afar grant thee not his own messenger, then I of a surety should not urge thee on and bid thee go to the ships of the Argives, how eager soever thou be.\" '),(8145,' \nThen in answer spake unto her godlike Priam:'),(8146,' \n  \"Wife, I will not disregard this hest of thine;'),(8147,' for good is it to lift up hands to Zeus, if so be he will have pity.\"'),(8148,'\nThus spake the old man, and bade the housewife that attended pour over his hands water undefiled;'),(8149,'and the handmaid drew nigh bearing in her hands alike basin and ewer.'),(8150,'  Then, when he had washed his hands, he took the cup from his wife '),(8151,'and then made prayer, standing in the midst of thie court, and poured forth the wine, with a look toward heaven, and spake ahoud, saying:'),(8152,'\"Father Zeus, that rulest from Ida, most glorious, most great, grant that I may come unto Achilles\' hut as one to be welcomed and to be pitied;  and send a bird of omen, even the swift messenger that to thyself is dearest of birds and is mightiest in strength; let him appear upon my right hand, to the end that, marking the sign with mine own eyes, I may have trust therein, and go my way to the ships of the Danaans of fleet steeds.\"'),(8153,'So spake he in prayer, and Zeus the Counsellor heard him.  Forthwith he sent an eagle, surest of omen among winged birds, the dusky eagle, even the hunter, that men call also the black eagle.'),(8154,' Wide as is the door of some rich man\'s high-roofed treasure-chamber, a door well fitted with bolts, even so wide spread his wings to this side and to that; '),(8155,'and he appeared to them on the right,  darting across the city.'),(8156,' And at sight of him they waxed glad, and the hearts in the breasts of all were cheered.'),(8157,'Then the old man made haste and stepped upon his car, and drave forth from the gateway and the echoing portico.'),(8158,' In front the mules drew the four-wheeled waggon,  driven of wise-hearted Idaeus, '),(8159,'and behind came the horses that the old man ever plying the lash drave swiftly through the city;'),(8160,' and his kinsfolk all followed wailing aloud as for one faring to his death.'),(8161,'But when they had gone down from the city and were come to the plain,  back then to Ilios turned his sons and his daughters\' husbands; howbeit the twain were not unseen of Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, as they came forth upon the plain, '),(8162,'but as he saw the old man he had pity, and forthwith spake to Hermes, his dear son:'),(8163,'\"Hermes, seeing thou lovest above all others to companion a man,  and thou givest ear to whomsoever thou art minded up, go and guide Priam unto the hollow ships of the Achaeans in such wise that no man may see him or be ware of him among all the Damans, until he be come to the son of Pe1eus.\" '),(8164,' \nSo spake he, and the messenger, Argeiphontes, failed not to hearken.'),(8165,'  Straightway he bound beneath his feet his beautiful sandals, immortal, golden, which were wont to bear him over the waters of the sea and over the boundless land swift as the blasts of the wind.'),(8166,' And he took the wand wherewith he lulls to sleep the eyes of whom he will, while others again he awakens even out of slumber.'),(8167,'  With this in his hand the strong Argeiphontes flew,'),(8168,' and quickly came to Troy-land and the Hellespont. Then went he his way in the likeness of a young man that is a prince, with the first down upon his lip, in whom the charm of youth is fairest.'),(8169,'Now when the others had driven past the great barrow of Ilus,  they halted the mules and the horses in the river to drink; '),(8170,'for darkness was by now come down over the earth.'),(8171,' Then the herald looked and was ware of Hermes hard at hand, and he spake to Priam, saying:\"'),(8172,'  here is somewhat that calls for prudent thought.'),(8173,'  here is somewhat that calls for prudent thought.'),(8174,' I see a man, and anon methinks shall we be cut to pieces. '),(8175,'Come, let us flee in thie chariot, or at least clasp his knees and entreat him, if so be he will have pity.\"'),(8176,'\nSo spake he, and the old man\'s mind was confounded and he was sore afraid, and up stood the hair on his pliant limbs,  and he stood in a daze. '),(8177,'But of himself the Helper drew nigh, and took the ohd man\'s hand, and made question of him, saying:'),(8178,' \"Whither, Father, dost thou thus guide horses and mules through the immortal night when other mortals are sleeping?'),(8179,' Art thou untouched by fear of the fury-breathing Achaeans,  hostile men and ruthless that are hard anigh thee? '),(8180,'If one of them should espy thee bearing such store of treasure through the swift bhack night, what were thy counsel then?'),(8181,' Thou art not young thyself, and thy companion here is old, that ye should defend you against a man, when one waxes wroth without a cause.'),(8182,'  But as for me, I will nowise harm thee, nay, I will even defend thee against another; '),(8183,'for like unto my dear father art thou in mine eyes.\" '),(8184,' \nThen the old man, godlike Priam, answered him: '),(8185,'\"Even so, dear son, are all these things as thou dost say.'),(8186,' Howbeit still hath some god stretched out his hand even over me,  seeing he hath sent a way-farer such as thou to meet me, a bringer of blessing, so wondrous in form and comeliness, and withal thou art wise of heart; blessed parents are they from whom thou art sprung.\"'),(8187,'\nThen again the messenger, Argeiphontes, spake to him:\"'),(8188,'Yea verily, old sire, all this hast thou spoken according to right.'),(8189,'  But come, tell me this, and declare it truly, whether thou art bearing forth these many treasures and goodly unto some foreign folk, where they may abide for thee in safety, or whether by now ye are all forsaking holy Ilios in fear; '),(8190,' so great a warrior, the noblest of all, hath perished,  even thy son; '),(8191,'for never held he back from warring with the Achaeans.\"'),(8192,'And the old man, godlike Priam, answered him:'),(8193,' \"Who art thou, noble youth, and from what parents art thou sprung,'),(8194,'seeing thou speakest thus fitly of the fate of my hapless son?\"'),(8195,'\nThen again the messenger, Argeiphontes, spake to him:'),(8196,'  \"Thou wouldest make trial of me, old sire, in asking me of goodly Hector. '),(8197,'Him have mine eyes full often seen in battle, where men win glory, and when after driving the Argives to the ships he would slay them in havoc with the sharp bronze; '),(8198,'and we stood there and marvelled, '),(8199,' for Achilles would not suffer us to fight, being filled with wrath against the son of Atreus. '),(8200,'His squire am I, and the selfsame well-wrought ship brought us hither.'),(8201,' Of the Myrmidons am I one, and my father is Polyctor.'),(8202,' Rich in substance is he, and an old man even as thou, and six sons hath he, and myself the seventh.'),(8203,' From these by the casting of lots was I chosen to fare hitherward.'),(8204,' And now am I come to the plain from the ships; '),(8205,'for at dawn the bright-eyed Achaeans will set the battle in array about the city.'),(8206,' For it irketh them that they sit idle here, nor can the kings of the Achaeans avail to hold them back in their eagerness for war.\" '),(8207,' \n  And the old man, godlike Priam, answered him: '),(8208,'\"If thou art indeed a squire of Peleus\' son Achilles, come now, tell me all the truth, whether my son is even yet by the ships or whether by now Achilles hath hewn him limb from limb and cast him before his dogs.\"'),(8209,'   Then again the messenger Argeiphontes spake to him:'),(8210,'\"Old sire, not yet have dogs and birds devoured him, but still he lieth there beside the ship of Achilles amid the huts as he was at the first; '),(8211,'and this is now the twelfth day that he lieth there, yet his flesh decayeth not at all,  neither do worms consume it, such as devour men that be slain in fight. '),(8212,'Truly Achilles draggeth him ruthlessly about the barrow of his dear comrade, so oft as sacred Dawn appeareth, howbeit he marreth him not; '),(8213,'thou wouldst thyself marvel, wert thou to come and see how dewy-fresh he lieth, and is washen clean of blood,  neither hath anywhere pollution;'),(8214,'and all the wounds are closed wherewith he was stricken,'),(8215,'  for many there were that drave the bronze into his flesh.'),(8216,'In such wise do the blessed gods care for thy son, a corpse though he be, seeing he was dear unto their hearts.\"'),(8217,'So spake he, and the old man waxed glad, and answered, saying:'),(8218,'  \"My child, a good thing is it in sooth e\'en to give to the immortals such gifts as be due; for never did my son—as sure as ever such a one there was—forget in our halls the gods that hold Olympus; '),(8219,'wherefore they have remembered this for him, even though he be in the doom of death.'),(8220,'But come, take thou from me this fair goblet,  and guard me myself, and guide me with the speeding of the gods, until I be come unto the hut of the son of Peleus.\"'),(8221,'And again the messenger, Argeiphontes, spake to him:'),(8222,'Thou dost make trial of me, old sire, that am younger than thou; but thou shalt not prevail upon me, seeing thou biddest me take gifts from thee while Achilles knoweth naught thereof.'),(8223,'  Of him have I fear and awe at heart, that I should defraud him, lest haply some evil befall me hereafter.'),(8224,' Howbeit as thy guide would I go even unto glorious Argos, attending thee with kindly care in a swift ship or on foot; '),(8225,'nor would any man make light of thy guide and set upon thee.\" '),(8226,' \n  So spake the Helper, and leaping upon the chariot behind the horses quickly grasped in his hands the lash and reins, and breathed great might into the horses and mules.'),(8227,' But when they were come to the walls and the trench that guarded the ships, even as the watchers were but now busying them about their supper,  upon all of these the messenger Argeiphontes shed sleep, and forthwith opened the gates, and thrust back the bars, and brought within Priam, and the splendid gifts upon the wain.'),(8228,' But when they were come to the hut of Peleus\' son, the lofty hut which the Myrmidons had builded for their king,  hewing therefor beams of fir —'),(8229,'and they had roofed it over with downy thatch, gathered from the meadows; '),(8230,'and round it they reared for him, their king, a great court with thick-set pales; '),(8231,'and the door thereof was held by one single bar of fir that  three Achaeans were wont to drive home, and three to draw back the great bolt of the door （three of the rest, '),(8232,'but Achilles would drive it home even of himself）—'),(8233,'then verily the helper Hermes opened the door for the old man, and brought in the glorious gifts for the swift-footed son of Peleus; and from the chariot he stepped down to the ground and spake, saying:'),(8234,'  \"Old sire, I that am come to thee am immortal god, even Hermes; '),(8235,'for the Father sent me to guide thee on thy way.'),(8236,' But now verily will I go back, neither come within Achilles\' sight; '),(8237,'good cause for wrath would it be that an immortal god should thus openly be entertained of mortals.'),(8238,'  But go thou in, and clasp the knees of the son of Peleus and entreat him by his father and his fair-haired mother and his child, that thou mayest stir his soul.\" '),(8239,' \nSo spake Hermes, and departed unto high Olympus; '),(8240,'and Priam leapt from his chariot to the ground,  and left there Idaeus,'),(8241,'  who abode holding the horses and mules;'),(8242,'but the old man went straight toward the house where Achilles, dear to Zeus, was wont to sit.'),(8243,' Therein he found Achilles, but his comrades sat apart:'),(8244,' two only, the warrior Automedon and Alcimus, scion of Ares,  waited busily upon him; '),(8245,'and he was newly ceased from meat, even from eating and drinking, '),(8246,'and the table yet stood by his side.'),(8247,' Unseen of these great Priam entered in, and coming close to Achilles, clasped in his hands his knees, and kissed his hands, the terrible, man-slaying hands that had slain his many sons.'),(8248,'  And as when sore blindness of heart cometh upon a man, that in his own country slayeth another and escapeth to a land of strangers, to the house of some man of substance, and wonder holdeth them that look upon him; even so was Achilles seized with wonder at sight of godlike Priam, '),(8249,' and seized with wonder were the others likewise, and they glanced one at the other.'),(8250,'  But Priam made entreaty, and spake to him, saying: '),(8251,'\"Remember thy father, O Achilles like to the gods, whose years are even as mine, on the grievous threshold of old age.'),(8252,' Him full likely the dwellers that be round about are entreating evilly, neither is there any to ward from him ruin and bane.'),(8253,'  Howbeit, while he heareth of thee as yet alive he hath joy at heart, and therewithal hopeth day by day that he shall see his dear son returning from Troy-land.'),(8254,' But I—I am utterly unblest, seeing I begat sons the best in the broad land of Troy, yet of them I avow that not one is left.'),(8255,'  Fifty I had, when the sons of the Achaeans came;'),(8256,' nineteen were born to me of the self-same womb, and the others women of the palace bare.'),(8257,' Of these, many as they were, furious Ares hath loosed the knees, '),(8258,'and he that alone was left me, that by himself guarded the city and the men,  him thou slewest but now as he fought for his country, even Hector.'),(8259,' For his sake am I now come to the ships of the Achaeans to win him back from thee, and I bear with me ransom past counting.'),(8260,' Nay, have thou awe of the gods, Achilles, and take pity on me, remembering thine own father.'),(8261,' Lo, I am more piteous far than he,  and have endured what no other mortal on the face of earth hath yet endured, to reach forth my hand to the face of him that hath slain my sons.\" '),(8262,' \nSo spake he, and in Achilles he roused desire to weep for his father; '),(8263,'and he took the old man by the hand, and gently put him from him. '),(8264,'So the twain bethought them of their dead, and wept; the one for man-slaying Hector wept sore,  the while he grovelled at Achilles\' feet, but Achilles wept for his own father, and now again for Patroclus; '),(8265,'and the sound of their moaning went up through the house. '),(8266,'But when goodly Achilles had had his fill of lamenting, and the longing therefor had departed from his heart and limbs,  forthwith then he sprang from his seat, and raised the old man by his hand, pitying his hoary head and hoary beard; and he spake and addressed him with winged words:\"'),(8267,' Ah, unhappy man, full many in good sooth are the evils thou hast endured in thy soul. '),(8268,'How hadst thou the heart to come alone to the ships of the Achaeans,  to meet the eyes of me that have slain thy sons many and valiant?'),(8269,' Of iron verily is thy heart.'),(8270,'But come, sit thou upon a seat, and our sorrows will we suffer to lie quiet in our hearts, despite our pain;'),(8271,' for no profit cometh of chill lament.'),(8272,'  For on this wise have the gods spun the thread for wretched mortals, that they should live in pain; '),(8273,'and themselves are sorrowless.'),(8274,' For two urns are set upon the floor of Zeus of gifts that he giveth, the one of ills, the other of blessings.'),(8275,' To whomsoever Zeus, that hurleth the thunderbolt, giveth a mingled lot,  that man meeteth now with evil, now with good; '),(8276,'but to whomsoever he giveth but of the baneful, him he maketh to be reviled of man, and direful madness driveth him over the face of the sacred earth, and he wandereth honoured neither of gods nor mortals.'),(8277,' Even so unto Peleus did the gods give glorious gifts  from his birth; '),(8278,'for he excelled all men in good estate and in wealth, and was king over the Myrmidons, and to him that was but a mortal the gods gave a goddess to be his wife.'),(8279,'  Howbeit even upon him the gods brought evil, in that there nowise sprang up in his halls offspring of princely sons, but he begat one only son, doomed to an untimely fate. '),(8280,'Neither may I tend him as he groweth old, seeing that far, far from mine own country I abide in the land of Troy, vexing thee and thy children.'),(8281,' And of thee, old sire, we hear that of old thou wast blest; '),(8282,'how of all that toward the sea Lesbos, the seat of Macar, encloseth,  and Phrygia in the upland, and the boundless Hellespont, over all these folk, men say, thou, old sire, wast preeminent by reason of thy wealth and thy sons.'),(8283,' Howbeit from the time when the heavenly gods brought upon thee this bane, ever around thy city are battles and slayings of men.'),(8284,' Bear thou up, neither wail ever ceaselessly in thy heart; '),(8285,'for naught wilt thou avail by grieving for thy son,  neither wilt thou bring him back to life; ere that shalt thou suffer some other ill.\" '),(8286,' \n And the old man, godlike Priam, answered him:'),(8287,' \"Seat me not anywise upon a chair, O thou fostered of Zeus, so long as Hector lieth uncared-for amid the huts;  nay, give him back with speed, that mine eyes may behold him; '),(8288,'and do thou accept the ransom, the great ransom, that we bring.'),(8289,' So mayest thou have joy thereof, and come to thy native land, seeing that from the first thou hast spared me.\"'),(8290,'\nThen with an angry glance from beneath his brows spake to him Achilles swift of foot:'),(8291,' \"Provoke me no more, old sir;'),(8292,' I am minded even of myself to give Hector back to thee; for from Zeus there came to me a messenger, even the mother that bare me, daughter of the old man of the sea.'),(8293,' And of thee, Priam, do I know in my heart—it nowise escapeth me—that some god led thee to the swift ships of the Achaeans.'),(8294,'  For no mortal man, were he never so young and strong, would dare to come amid the host; '),(8295,'neither could he then escape the watch, nor easily thrust back the bar of our doors.'),(8296,' Wherefore now stir my heart no more amid my sorrows, lest, old sire, I spare not even thee within the huts,  my suppliant though thou art, and so sin against the behest of Zeus.\"'),(8297,'So spake he, and the old man was seized with fear, and hearkened to his word. '),(8298,' But like a lion the son of Peleus sprang forth from the houses—not alone, for with him went two squires as well, even the warrior Automedon and Alcimus,  they that Achilles honoured above all his comrades, after the dead Patroclus. These then loosed from beneath the yoke the horses and mules, and led within the herald, the crier of the old king, and set him on a chair;'),(8299,' and from the wain of goodly felloes they took the countless ransom for Hector\'s head.'),(8300,'  But they left there two robes and a fair-woven tunic, to the end that Achilles might enwrap the dead therein and so give him to be borne to his home. '),(8301,'Then Achilles called forth the hand-maids and bade them wash and anoint him, bearing him to a place apart that Priam might not have sight of his son, lest in grief of heart he should not restrain his wrath,  whenso he had sight of his son, and Achilles\' own spirit be stirred to anger, and he slay him, and so sin against the behest of Zeus.'),(8302,' So when the handmaids had washed the body and anointed it with oil, and had cast about it a fair cloak and a tunic, then Achilles himself lifted it and set it upon a bier,  and his comrades with him lifted it upon the polished waggon.'),(8303,' Then he uttered a groan, and called by name upon his dear comrade:'),(8304,'\"Be not thou wroth with me, Patroclus, if thou hearest even in the house of Hades that I have given back goodly Hector to his dear father, seeing that not unseemly is the ransom he hath given me. '),(8305,'  And unto thee shall I render even of this all that is thy due.” '),(8306,' \nSo spake goodly Achilles, and went back within the hut and on the richly-wrought chair wherefrom he had risen sate him down by the opposite wall, and he spake unto Priam, saying:\"'),(8307,'Thy son, old sire, is given back according to thy wish,  and lieth upon a bier;'),(8308,' and at break of day thou shalt thyself behold him, as thou bearest him hence;'),(8309,'but for this present let us bethink us of supper.'),(8310,' For even the fair-haired Niobe bethought her of meat, albeit twelve children perished in her halls, six daughters and six lusty sons.'),(8311,'  The sons Apollo slew with shafts from his silver bow, being wroth against Niobe, and the daughters the archer Artemis, for that Niobe had matched her with fair-cheeked Leto, '),(8312,'saying that the goddess had borne but twain, while herself was mother to many;'),(8313,'wherefore they, for all they were but twain, destroyed them all.'),(8314,'  For nine days\' space they lay in their blood, nor was there any to bury them, for the son of Cronos turned the folk to stones;'),(8315,'howbeit on the tenth day the gods of heaven buried them; '),(8316,'and Niobe bethought her of meat, for she was wearied with the shedding of tears.'),(8317,'And now somewhere amid the rocks, on the lonely mountains,  on Sipylus, where, men say, are the couching-places of goddesses, even of the nymphs that range swiftly in the dance about Achelous, there, albeit a stone, she broodeth over her woes sent by the gods.'),(8318,' But come, let us twain likewise, noble old sire, bethink us of meat;'),(8319,' and thereafter shalt thou make lament over thy dear son,  when thou hast borne him into Ilios; '),(8320,'mourned shall he be of thee many tears.\"'),(8321,'Therewith swift Achilles sprang up, and slew a white-fleeced sheep,'),(8322,' and his comrades flayed it and made it ready well and duly, and sliced it cunningly and spitted the morsels, and roasted them carefully and drew all off the spits.'),(8323,'  And Automedon took bread and dealt it forth on the table in fair baskets, '),(8324,'while Achilles dealt the meat.'),(8325,'So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them.'),(8326,'  But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, then verily Priam, son of Dardanus, marvelled at Achilles, how tall he was and how comely;'),(8327,'  for he was like the gods to look upon.'),(8328,' And a son of Dardanus, did Achilles marvel, beholding his goodly aspect and hearkening to his words.'),(8329,' But when they had had their fill of gazing one upon the other, then the old man, godlike Priam, was first to speak, saying:'),(8330,'  \"Show me now my bed with speed, O thou nurtured of Zeus, that lulled at length by sweet sleep we may rest and take our joy; '),(8331,' for never yet have mine eyes closed beneath mine eyelids since at thy hands my son lost his life, but ever do I wail and brood over my countless sorrows,  grovelling in the filth in the closed spaces of the court.'),(8332,' But now have I tasted of meat, and have let flaming wine pass down my throat;'),(8333,' whereas till now had I tasted naught.\" '),(8334,' \nHe spake, and Achilles bade his comrades and the handmaids set bedsteads beneath the portico,  and to lay on them fair purple blankets, and to spread thereover coverlets, and on these to put fleecy cloaks for clothing.'),(8335,' So the maids went forth from the hall with torches in their hands, and straightway spread two beds in busy haste.'),(8336,' Then mockingly spake unto Priam Achilles, swift of foot:'),(8337,'  \"Without do thou lay thee down, dear old sire, lest there come hither one of the counsellors of the Achaeans, that ever sit by my side and take counsel, as is meet.'),(8338,' If one of these were to have sight of thee through the swift black night, forthwith might he haply tell it to Agamemnon, shepherd of the host,  and so should there arise delay in the giving back of the body.'),(8339,' But come, tell me this, and declare it truly: for how many days\' space thou art minded to make funeral for goodly Hector, to the end that for so long I may myself abide, and may keep back the host.\"'),(8340,'\nAnd the old man, godlike Priam, answered him: saying:'),(8341,'  \"If thou indeed art willing that I accomplish for goodly Hector his burial, then in doing on this wise, O Achilles, wilt thou do according to my wish.'),(8342,' Thou knowest how we are pent within the city, and far is it to fetch wood from the mountain, and the Trojans are sore afraid.'),(8343,'  For nine days\' space will we wail for him in our halls, and on the tenth will we make his funeral, and the folk shall feast, and on the eleventh will we heap a barrow over him, and on the twelfth will we do battle, if so be we must.\"'),(8344,'\nThen spake to him in answer swift-footed, goodly Achilles:\"'),(8345,'Thus shall this also be aged Priam, even as thou wouldest have it; '),(8346,' for I will hold back the battle for such time as thou dost bid.\"'),(8347,'When he had thus spoken he clasped the old man\'s right hand by the wrist, lest his heart should any wise wax fearful.'),(8348,' So they laid them to sleep there in the fore-hall of the house, the herald and Priam, with hearts of wisdom in their breasts;  but Achilles slept in the innermost part of the well-builded hut, '),(8349,'and by his side lay fair-cheeked Briseis. '),(8350,' \nNow all the other gods and men, lords of chariots, slumbered the whole night through, overcome of soft sleep; '),(8351,'but not upon the helper Hermes might sleep lay hold,  as he pondered in mind how he should guide king Priam forth from the ships unmarked of the strong keepers of the gate.'),(8352,' He took his stand above his head and spake to him, saying:\"'),(8353,'Old sire, no thought then hast thou of any evil, that thou still sleepest thus amid foemen, for that Achilles has spared thee.'),(8354,'  Now verily hast thou ransomed thy son, and a great price thou gavest. '),(8355,'But for thine own life must the sons thou hast, they that be left behind, give ransorn thrice so great, if so be Agamemnon, Atreus\' son, have knowledge of thee, or the host of the Achaeans have knowledge.\"'),(8356,'\nSo spake he, and the old man was seized with fear, and made the herald to arise.'),(8357,'  And Hermes yoked for them the horses and mules, and himself lightly drave them through the camp, neither had any man knowledge thereof.'),(8358,'\nBut when they were now come to the ford of the fair-flowing river, even eddying Xanthus, that immortal Zeus begat, then Hermes departed to high Olympus,  and Dawn, the saffron-robed, was spreading over the face of all the earth. So they with moaning and wailing drave the horses to the city, and the mules bare the dead. '),(8359,' Neither was any other ware of them, whether man or fair-girdled woman; but in truth Cassandra, peer of golden Aphrodite,  having gone up upon Pergamus, marked her dear father as he stood in the car, and the herald, the city\'s crier; '),(8360,'and she had sight of that other lying on the bier in the waggon drawn of the mules.'),(8361,' Thereat she uttered a shrill cry, and called throughout all the town:'),(8362,'\"Come ye, men and women of Troy, and behold Hector,  if ever while yet he lived ye had joy of his coming back from battle; since great joy was he to the city and to all the folk.\" '),(8363,' \nSo spake she, nor was any man left there within the city, neither any woman, '),(8364,' \nfor upon all had come grief that might not be borne; '),(8365,'  and hard by the gates they met Priam, as he bare home the dead.'),(8366,'  First Hector\'s dear wife and queenly mother flung themselves upon the light-running waggon, and clasping his head the while, wailed and tore their hair;'),(8367,'and the folk thronged about and wept.'),(8368,' And now the whole day long until set of sun had they made lament for Hector with shedding of tears there without the gates,  had not the old man spoken amid the folk from out the car:\"'),(8369,'Make me way for the mules to pass through;'),(8370,' thereafter shall ye take your fill of wailing, when I have brought him to the house.\"'),(8371,'\nSo spake he, and they stood apart and made way for the waggon.'),(8372,'But the others, when they had brought him to the glorious house,  laid him on a corded bedstead, and by his side set singers, leaders of the dirge, who led the song of lamentation—they chanted the dirge, and thereat the women made lament.'),(8373,' And amid these white-armed Andromache led the wailing, holding in her arms the while the head of man-slaying Hector:'),(8374,'  \"Husband, perished from out of life art thou, yet in thy youth, and leavest me a widow in thy halls; '),(8375,' and thy son is still but a babe, the son born of thee and me in our haplessness; neither do I deem that he will come to manhood, '),(8376,' for ere that shall this city be wasted utterly.'),(8377,'For thou hast perished that didst watch thereover,  thou that didst guard it, and keep safe its noble wives and little children. These, I ween, shall soon be riding upon the hollow ships, and I among them; '),(8378,'and thou, my child, shalt follow with me to a place where thou shalt labour at unseemly tasks, toiling before the face of some ungentle master, or else some Achaean shall seize thee by the arm  and hurl thee from the wall, a woeful death, being wroth for that Hector slew his brother haply, or his father, or his son, seeing that full many Achaeans at the hands of Hector have bitten the vast earth with their teeth; '),(8379,'for nowise gentle was thy father in woeful war.'),(8380,'  Therefore the folk wail for him throughout the city, and grief unspeakable and sorrow hast thou brought upon thy parents, Hector;'),(8381,'and for me beyond all others shall grievous woes be left.'),(8382,' For at thy death thou didst neither stretch out thy hands to me from thy bed, nor speak to me any word of wisdom whereon  I might have pondered night and day with shedding of tears.” '),(8383,' \nSo spake she wailing, and thereat the women made lament.'),(8384,' And among them Hecabe in turns led the vehement wailing:\"'),(8385,'Hector, far dearest to my heart of all my children, lo, when thou livedst thou wast dear to the gods, '),(8386,'  and therefore have they had care of thee for all thou art in the doom of death.'),(8387,'For of other sons of mine whomsoever he took would swift-footed Achilles sell beyond the unresting sea, unto Samos and Imbros and Lemnos, shrouded in smoke, '),(8388,' but, when from thee he had taken away thy life with the long-edged bronze  oft would he drag thee about the barrow of his comrade, Patroclus, whom thou didst slay; '),(8389,'howbeit even so might he not raise him up.'),(8390,' all dewy-fresh thou liest in my halls as wert thou g newly slain, like as one whom Apollo of the silver bow assaileth with his gentle shafts and slayeth.\"'),(8391,'  So spake she wailing, and roused unabating lament.'),(8392,' And thereafter Helen was the third to lead the wailing:\"'),(8393,'Hector, far dearest to my heart of all my husband\'s brethren! In sooth my husband is godlike Alexander, that brought me to Troy-land —'),(8394,'would I died ere then!'),(8395,'  For this is now the twentieth year from the time when I went from thence and am gone from my native land, '),(8396,'but never yet heard I evil or despiteful word from thee; '),(8397,'nay, if so be any other spake reproachfully of me in the halls, a brother of thine or a sister, or brother\'s fair-robed wife,  or thy mother—but thy father was ever gentle as he had been mine own—yet wouldst thou turn them with speech and restrain them by the gentleness of thy spirit and thy gentle words.'),(8398,' Wherefore I wail alike for thee and for my hapless self with grief at heart;  '),(8399,'for no longer have I anyone beside in broad Troy  that is gentle to me or kind; but all men shudder at me.”'),(8400,' \nSo spake she wailing, and thereat the countless throng made moan.'),(8401,' But the old man Priam spake among the folk, saying:\"'),(8402,'Bring wood now, ye men of Troy, unto the city, neither have ye anywise fear at heart of a cunning ambush of the Argives; '),(8403,'for verily Achilles laid upon me this word  when he sent me forth from the black ships, that he would do us no hurt until the twelfth dawn be come.\"'),(8404,'\nSo spake he, and they yoked oxen and mules to waggons, and speedily thereafter gathered together before the city.'),(8405,' For nine days\' space they brought in measureless store of wood,'),(8406,' but when the tenth Dawn arose, giving light unto mortals, then bare they forth bold Hector, shedding tears the while, and on the topmost pyre they laid the dead man, and cast fire thereon.'),(8407,'\nBut soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, then gathered the folk about the pyre of glorious Hector.'),(8408,'  And when they were assembled and met together, first they quenched with flaming wine all the pyre, so far as the fire\'s might had come upon it,'),(8409,' and thereafter his brethren and his comrades gathered the white bones, mourning, and big tears flowed ever down their cheeks.'),(8410,'  The bones they took and placed in a golden urn, covering them over with soft purple robes, '),(8411,'and quickly laid the urn in a hollow grave, and covered it over with great close-set stones.'),(8412,' Then with speed heaped they the mound, and round about were watchers set on every side,  lest the well-greaved Achaeans should set upon them before the time.'),(8413,' And when they had piled the barrow they went back,'),(8414,' and gathering together duly feasted a glorious feast in the palace of Priam, the king fostered of Zeus.'),(8415,'\nOn this wise held they funeral for horse-taming Hector.'),(8416,' Tell me, O Muse, of the man of many devices, who wandered full many ways after he had sacked the sacred citadel of Troy.'),(8417,' Many were the men whose cities he saw and whose mind he learned, aye, and many the woes he suffered in his heart upon the sea,  seeking to win his own life and the return of his comrades.'),(8418,'Yet even so he saved not his comrades, though he desired it sore,'),(8419,' for through their own blind folly they perished—fools, who devoured the kine of Helios Hyperion;'),(8420,'but he took from them the day of their returning.'),(8421,'  Of these things, goddess, daughter of Zeus, beginning where thou wilt, tell thou even unto us.'),(8422,'Now all the rest, as many as had escaped sheer destruction, were at home, safe from both war and sea,'),(8423,'but Odysseus alone, filled with longing for his return and for his wife, did the queenly nymph Calypso, that bright goddess,  keep back in her hollow caves, yearning that he should be her husband.'),(8424,'But when, as the seasons revolved, the year came in which the gods had ordained that he should return home to Ithaca, not even there was he free from toils, even among his own folk.'),(8425,' And all the gods pitied him  save Poseidon; '),(8426,'but he continued to rage unceasingly against godlike Odysseus until at length he reached his own land.'),(8427,'Howbeit Poseidon had gone among the far-off Ethiopians—the Ethiopians who dwell sundered in twain, the farthermost of men, some where Hyperion sets and some where he rises,  there to receive a hecatomb of bulls and rams,'),(8428,'and there he was taking his joy, sitting at the feast;'),(8429,'but the other gods were gathered together in the halls of Olympian Zeus.'),(8430,'Among them the father of gods and men was first to speak,'),(8431,'for in his heart he thought of noble Aegisthus,  whom far-famed Orestes, Agamemnon\'s son, had slain.'),(8432,'Thinking on him he spoke among the immortals, and said:'),(8433,' “Look you now, how ready mortals are to blame the gods.'),(8434,' It is from us, they say, that evils come, but they even of themselves, through their own blind folly, have sorrows beyond that which is ordained. Even as now Aegisthus, beyond that which was ordained, took to himself the wedded wife of the son of Atreus, and slew him on his return, though well he knew of sheer destruction, seeing that we spake to him before, sending Hermes, the keen-sighted Argeiphontes, that he should neither slay the man nor woo his wife;'),(8435,'  for from Orestes shall come vengeance for the son of Atreus when once he has come to manhood and longs for his own land.'),(8436,' So Hermes spoke, but for all his good intent he prevailed not upon the heart of Aegisthus; '),(8437,'and now he has paid the full price of all.” '),(8438,' \nThen the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(8439,'  “Father of us all, thou son of Cronos, high above all lords, aye, verily that man lies low in a destruction that is his due;'),(8440,' so, too, may any other also be destroyed who does such deeds.'),(8441,' But my heart is torn for wise Odysseus, hapless man, who far from his friends has long been suffering woes  in a sea-girt isle, where is the navel of the sea.'),(8442,'\'Tis a wooded isle, and therein dwells a goddess, daughter of Atlas of baneful mind, who knows the depths of every sea, and himself holds the tall pillars which keep earth and heaven apart.'),(8443,'  His daughter it is that keeps back that wretched, sorrowing man; and ever with soft and wheedling words she beguiles him that he may forget Ithaca.'),(8444,' But Odysseus, in his longing to see were it but the smoke leaping up from his own land, yearns to die.'),(8445,' Yet thy  heart doth not regard it, Olympian.'),(8446,' Did not Odysseus beside the ships of the Argives offer thee sacrifice without stint in the broad land of Troy?'),(8447,' Wherefore then didst thou conceive such wrath against him, O Zeus?\"'),(8448,'Then Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, answered her and said:'),(8449,' “My child, what a word has escaped the barrier of thy teeth?'),(8450,'  How should I, then, forget godlike Odysseus, who is beyond all mortals in wisdom, and beyond all has paid sacrifice to the immortal gods, who hold broad heaven?'),(8451,' Nay, it is Poseidon, the earth-enfolder, who is ever filled with stubborn wrath because of the Cyclops, whom Odysseus blinded of his eye—  even the godlike Polyphemus, whose might is greatest among all the Cyclopes;'),(8452,' and the nymph Thoosa bore him, daughter of Phorcys who rules over the unresting sea; for in the hollow caves she lay with Poseidon.'),(8453,' From that time forth Poseidon, the earth-shaker,  does not indeed slay Odysseus, but makes him a wanderer from his native land.'),(8454,'But come, let us who are here all take thought of his return, that he may come home;'),(8455,' and Poseidon will let go his anger,'),(8456,'for he will in no wise be able, against all the immortal gods and in their despite, to contend alone.” '),(8457,' \n  Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(8458,' “Father of us all, thou son of Cronos, high above all lords, if indeed this is now well pleasing to the blessed gods, that the wise Odysseus should return to his own home, let us send forth Hermes, the messenger, Argeiphontes,  to the isle Ogygia, that with all speed he may declare to the fair-tressed nymph our fixed resolve, even the return of Odysseus of the steadfast heart, that he may come home.'),(8459,' But, as for me, I will go to Ithaca, that I may the more arouse his son, and set courage in his heart  to call to an assembly the long-haired Achaeans, and speak out his word to all the wooers, who are ever slaying his thronging sheep and his sleek kine of shambling gait.'),(8460,' And I will guide him to Sparta and to sandy Pylos, to seek tidings of the return of his dear father, if haply he may hear of it,  that good report may be his among men.”'),(8461,'So she spoke, and bound beneath her feet her beautiful sandals, immortal, golden, which were wont to bear her both over the waters of the sea and over the boundless land swift as the blasts of the wind.'),(8462,' And she took her mighty spear, tipped with sharp bronze,  heavy and huge and strong, wherewith she vanquishes the ranks of men—of warriors, with whom she is wroth, she, the daughter of the mighty sire.'),(8463,' Then she went darting down from the heights of Olympus, and took her stand in the land of Ithaca at the outer gate of Odysseus, on the threshold of the court.'),(8464,' In her hand she held the spear of bronze,  and she was in the likeness of a stranger, Mentes, the leader of the Taphians.'),(8465,' There she found the proud wooers.'),(8466,' They were taking their pleasure at draughts in front of the doors, sitting on the hides of oxen which they themselves had slain;'),(8467,' and of the heralds and busy squires,  some were mixing wine and water for them in bowls, others again were washing the tables with porous sponges and setting them forth, while still others were portioning out meats in abundance.'),(8468,'Her the godlike Telemachus was far the first to see, for he was sitting among the wooers, sad at heart,  seeing in thought his noble father, should he perchance come from somewhere and make a scattering of the wooers in the palace, and himself win honor and rule over his own house.'),(8469,' As he thought of these things, sitting among the wooers, he beheld Athena,'),(8470,' and he went straight to the outer door; for in his heart he counted it shame  that a stranger should stand long at the gates. '),(8471,' So, drawing near, he clasped her right hand, and took from her the spear of bronze; and he spoke, and addressed her with winged words:'),(8472,'“Hail, stranger; in our house thou shalt find entertainment '),(8473,'and then, when thou hast tasted food, thou shalt tell of what thou hast need.” '),(8474,' \n  So saying, he led the way, and Pallas Athena followed.'),(8475,' And when they were within the lofty house, he bore the spear and set it against a tall pillar in a polished spear-rack, where were set many spears besides, even those of Odysseus of the steadfast heart.  Athena herself he led and seated on a chair, spreading a linen cloth beneath—a beautiful chair, richly-wrought,'),(8476,' and below was a footstool for the feet.'),(8477,' Beside it he placed for himself an inlaid seat, apart from the others, the wooers, lest the stranger, vexed by their din, should loathe the meal, seeing that he was in the company of overweening men;  and also that he might ask him about his father that was gone.'),(8478,'Then a handmaid brought water for the hands in a fair pitcher of gold, and poured it over a silver basin for them to wash,'),(8479,' and beside them drew up a polished table.'),(8480,' And the grave housewife brought and set before them bread,  and therewith dainties in abundance, giving freely of her store.'),(8481,'And a carver lifted up and placed before them platters of all manner of meats, and set by them golden goblets,'),(8482,' while a herald ever walked to and fro pouring them wine.'),(8483,'\nThen in came the proud wooers,'),(8484,'and thereafter  sat them down in rows on chairs and high seats. Heralds poured water over their hands, and maid-servants heaped by them bread in baskets, and youths filled the bowls brim full of drink; '),(8485,' and they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them.'),(8486,'  Now after the wooers had put from them the desire of food and drink, their hearts turned to other things, to song and to dance; '),(8487,'for these things are the crown of a feast.'),(8488,' And a herald put the beautiful lyre in the hands of Phemius, who sang perforce among the wooers; '),(8489,' and he struck the chords in prelude to his sweet lay.'),(8490,'But Telemachus spoke to flashing-eyed Athena, holding his head close, that the others might not hear: '),(8491,'“Dear stranger, wilt thou be wroth with me for the word that I shall say?'),(8492,' These men care for things like these, the lyre and song,  full easily, seeing that without atonement they devour the livelihood of another, of a man whose white bones, it may be, rot in the rain as they lie upon the mainland, or the wave rolls them in the sea.'),(8493,' Were they to see him returned to Ithaca, they would all pray to be swifter of foot,  rather than richer in gold and in raiment. '),(8494,' But now he has thus perished by an evil doom, nor for us is there any comfort, no, not though any one of men upon the earth should say that he will come;'),(8495,' gone is the day of his returning.'),(8496,' But come, tell me this, and declare it truly.'),(8497,'Where is thy city and where thy parents?'),(8498,'Where is thy city and where thy parents?'),(8499,' On what manner of ship didst thou come,'),(8500,' and how did sailors bring thee to Ithaca? '),(8501,' Who did they declare themselves to be? '),(8502,' For nowise, methinks, didst thou come hither on foot.'),(8503,'And tell me this also truly, that I may know full well,  whether this is thy first coming hither, or whether thou art indeed a friend of my father\'s house. For many were the men who came to our house as strangers, since he, too, had gone to and fro among men.” '),(8504,' \nThen the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(8505,' “Therefore of a truth will I frankly tell thee all.'),(8506,'  I declare that I am Mentes, the son of wise Anchialus, and I am lord over the oar-loving Taphians.'),(8507,' And now have I put in here, as thou seest, with ship and crew, while sailing over the wine-dark sea to men of strange speech, on my way to Temese for copper; and I bear with me shining iron.'),(8508,'  My ship lies yonder beside the fields away from the city, in the harbor of Rheithron, under woody Neion. '),(8509,' Friends of one another do we declare ourselves to be, even as our fathers were, friends from of old. Nay, if thou wilt, go and ask the old warrior Laertes, who, they say,  comes no more to the city, but afar in the fields suffers woes attended by an aged woman as his handmaid, who sets before him food and drink, after weariness has laid hold of his limbs, as he creeps along the slope of his vineyard plot.'),(8510,' And now am I come,'),(8511,' for of a truth men said that he,  thy father, was among his people; '),(8512,' but lo, the gods are thwarting him of his return. '),(8513,' For not yet has goodly Odysseus perished on the earth, but still, I ween, he lives and is held back on the broad sea in a sea-girt isle, and cruel men keep him, a savage folk, that constrain him, haply sore against his will.'),(8514,'  Nay, I will now prophesy to thee, as the immortals put it in my heart, and as I think it shall be brought to pass, though I am in no wise a soothsayer, nor one versed in the signs of birds.'),(8515,' Not much longer shall he be absent from his dear native land, no, not though bonds of iron hold him.'),(8516,'  He will contrive a way to return, for he is a man of many devices.'),(8517,' But come, tell me this and declare it truly, whether indeed, tall as thou art, thou art the son of Odysseus himself.'),(8518,' Wondrously like his are thy head and beautiful eyes; for full often did we consort with one another  before he embarked for the land of Troy, whither others, too, the bravest of the Argives, went in their hollow ships.'),(8519,' But since that day neither have I seen Odysseus, nor he me.\"'),(8520,'Then wise Telemachus answered her:'),(8521,' “Therefore of a truth, stranger, will I frankly tell thee all.'),(8522,'  My mother says that I am his child; but I know not, '),(8523,' for never yet did any man of himself know his own parentage.'),(8524,' Ah, would that I had been the son of some blest man, whom old age overtook among his own possessions.'),(8525,' But now of him who was the most ill-fated of mortal men  they say that I am sprung, since thou askest me of this.”'),(8526,'Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(8527,' “Surely, then, no nameless lineage have the gods appointed for thee in time to come, seeing that Penelope bore thee such as thou art.'),(8528,' But come, tell me this and declare it truly.'),(8529,' What need hast thou of it?'),(8530,' What need hast thou of it?'),(8531,' For this plainly is no meal to which each brings his portion, '),(8532,' For this plainly is no meal to which each brings his portion, '),(8533,' with such outrage and overweening do they seem to me to be feasting in thy halls.'),(8534,' Angered would a man be at seeing all these shameful acts, any man of sense who should come among them.” '),(8535,' \n  Then wise Telemachus answered her:'),(8536,' “Stranger, since indeed thou dost ask and question me of this, our house once bade fair to be rich and honorable, so long as that man was still among his people.'),(8537,' But now the gods have willed otherwise in their evil devising,  seeing that they have caused him to pass from sight as they have no other man. For I should not so grieve for his death, if he had been slain among his comrades in the land of the Trojans, or had died in the arms of his friends, when he had wound up the skein of war.'),(8538,' Then would the whole host of the Achaeans have made him a tomb,  and for his son, too, he would have won great glory in days to come.'),(8539,' But as it is, the spirits of the storm have swept him away and left no tidings:'),(8540,' he is gone out of sight, out of hearing, and for me he has left anguish and weeping;'),(8541,' nor do I in any wise mourn and wail for him alone, seeing that the gods have brought upon me other sore troubles.'),(8542,'  For all the princes who hold sway over the islands—Dulichium and Same and wooded Zacynthus—and those who lord it over rocky Ithaca, all these woo my mother and lay waste my house.'),(8543,' And she neither refuses the hateful marriage,  nor is she able to make an end;'),(8544,' but they with feasting consume my substance:'),(8545,' ere long they will bring me, too, to ruin.\"'),(8546,'Then, stirred to anger, Pallas Athena spoke to him:'),(8547,' “Out on it! Thou hast of a truth sore need of Odysseus that is gone, that he might put forth his hands upon the shameless wooers.'),(8548,'  Would that he might come now and take his stand at the outer gate of the house, with helmet and shield and two spears, such a man as he was when I first saw him in our house drinking and making merry, on his way back from Ephyre, from the house of Ilus, son of Mermerus.  For thither, too, went Odysseus in his swift ship in search of a deadly drug, that he might have wherewith to smear his bronze-tipped arrows; '),(8549,' yet Ilus gave it not to him, for he stood in awe of the gods that are forever; but my father gave it, '),(8550,' for he held him strangely dear. Would, I say, that in such strength Odysseus might come amongst the wooers;'),(8551,' then should they all find swift destruction and bitterness in their wooing.'),(8552,' Yet these things verily lie on the knees of the gods, whether he shall return and wreak vengeance in his halls, or whether he shall not; '),(8553,' but for thyself, I bid thee take thought  how thou mayest thrust forth the wooers from the hall. '),(8554,' Come now, give ear, and hearken to my words.'),(8555,' On the morrow call to an assembly the Achaean lords, and speak out thy word to all, and let the gods be thy witnesses. '),(8556,' As for the wooers, bid them scatter, each to his own;  and for thy mother, if her heart bids her marry, let her go back to the hall of her mighty father, '),(8557,' and there they will prepare a wedding feast, and make ready the gifts full many—aye, all that should follow after a well-loved daughter.'),(8558,' And to thyself will I give wise counsel, if thou wilt hearken. '),(8559,'   Man with twenty rowers the best ship thou hast, and go to seek tidings of thy father, that has long been gone, if haply any mortal may tell thee, or thou mayest hear a voice from Zeus, which oftenest brings tidings to men.'),(8560,' First go to Pylos and question goodly Nestor,  and from thence to Sparta to fair-haired Menelaus; '),(8561,' for he was the last to reach home of the brazen-coated Achaeans.'),(8562,' If so be thou shalt hear that thy father is alive and coming home, then verily, though thou art sore afflicted, thou couldst endure for yet a year.'),(8563,' But if thou shalt hear that he is dead and gone,  then return to thy dear native land and heap up a mound for him, and over it pay funeral rites, full many as is due, and give thy mother to a husband. '),(8564,'Then when thou hast done all this and brought it to an end, thereafter take thought in mind and heart  how thou mayest slay the wooers in thy halls whether by guile or openly;'),(8565,' for it beseems thee not to practise childish ways, since thou art no longer of such an age.'),(8566,' Or hast thou not heard what fame the goodly Orestes won among all mankind when he slew his father\'s murderer,  the guileful Aegisthus, for that he slew his glorious father?'),(8567,' Thou too, my friend, for I see that thou art comely and tall, be thou valiant, that many an one of men yet to be born may praise thee.'),(8568,' But now I will go down to my swift ship and my comrades, who, methinks, are chafing much at waiting for me.'),(8569,'  For thyself, give heed and have regard to my words.”'),(8570,'Then wise Telemachus answered her: '),(8571,' “Stranger, in truth thou speakest these things with kindly thought, as a father to his son, and never will I forget them. '),(8572,' But come now, tarry, eager though thou art to be gone,  in order that when thou hast bathed and satisfied thy heart to the full, thou mayest go to thy ship glad in spirit, and bearing a gift costly and very beautiful, which shall be to thee an heirloom from me, even such a gift as dear friends give to friends.\"'),(8573,'Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(8574,' “Stay me now no longer, when I am eager to be gone,'),(8575,' and whatsoever gift thy heart bids thee give me, give it when I come back, to bear to my home, choosing a right beautiful one; '),(8576,' it shall bring thee its worth in return.\"'),(8577,'So spoke the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, and departed,  flying upward as a bird; '),(8578,'and in his heart she put strength and courage, and made him think of his father even more than aforetime.'),(8579,' And in his mind he marked her and marvelled, '),(8580,' for he deemed that she was a god; '),(8581,' and straightway he went among the wooers, a godlike man. '),(8582,' \n  For them the famous minstrel was singing, and they sat in silence listening;'),(8583,' and he sang of the return of the Achaeans—the woeful return from Troy which Pallas Athena laid upon them.'),(8584,' And from her upper chamber the daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope, heard his wondrous song,'),(8585,'  and she went down the high stairway from her chamber, not alone, for two handmaids attended her.'),(8586,' Now when the fair lady had come to the wooers, she stood by the door-post of the well-built hall, holding before her face her shining veil; '),(8587,'  and a faithful handmaid stood on either side of her. '),(8588,' Then she burst into tears, and spoke to the divine minstrel:'),(8589,'\n“Phemius, many other things thou knowest to charm mortals, deeds of men and gods which minstrels make famous.'),(8590,' Sing them one of these, as thou sittest here,  and let them drink their wine in silence. '),(8591,' But cease from this woeful song which ever harrows the heart in my breast, for upon me above all women has come a sorrow not to be forgotten.'),(8592,' So dear a head do I ever remember with longing, even my husband, whose fame is wide through Hellas and mid-Argos.\"'),(8593,'  Then wise Telemachus answered her: '),(8594,' “My mother, why dost thou begrudge the good minstrel to give pleasure in whatever way his heart is moved?'),(8595,' It is not minstrels that are to blame, but Zeus, I ween, is to blame, who gives to men that live by toil, to each one as he will. '),(8596,'  With this man no one can be wroth if he sings of the evil doom of the Danaans; '),(8597,'for men praise that song the most which comes the newest to their ears.'),(8598,' For thyself, let thy heart and soul endure to listen;'),(8599,'for not Odysseus alone lost  in Troy the day of his return, but many others likewise perished.'),(8600,' Nay, go to thy chamber, and busy thyself with thine own tasks, the loom and the distaff, and bid thy handmaids ply their tasks;'),(8601,' but speech shall be for men, for all, but most of all for me; '),(8602,' since mine is the authority in the house.\"'),(8603,' She then, seized with wonder, went back to her chamber,'),(8604,'for she laid to heart the wise saying of her son.'),(8605,' Up to her upper chamber she went with her handmaids, and then bewailed Odysseus, her dear husband until flashing-eyed Athena cast sweet sleep upon her eyelids. '),(8606,' \n  But the wooers broke into uproar throughout the shadowy halls, and all prayed, each that he might lie by her side.'),(8607,' And among them wise Telemachus was the first to speak:'),(8608,'“Wooers of my mother, overweening in your insolence, for the present let us make merry with feasting,  but let there be no brawling; for this is a goodly thing, to listen to a minstrel such as this man is, like to the gods in voice.'),(8609,' But in the morning let us go to the assembly and take our seats, one and all, that I may declare my word to you outright that you depart from these halls.'),(8610,' Prepare you other feasts,  eating your own substance and changing from house to house. '),(8611,' But if this seems in your eyes to be a better and more profitable thing, that one man\'s livelihood should be ruined without atonement, waste ye it.'),(8612,' But I will call upon the gods that are forever, if haply Zeus may grant that deeds of requital may be wrought.'),(8613,'  Without atonement, then, should ye perish within my halls.”'),(8614,'So he spoke, and they all bit their lips and marvelled at Telemachus, for that he spoke boldly.'),(8615,'Then Antinous, son of Eupeithes, answered him:'),(8616,'“Telemachus, verily the gods themselves are teaching thee  to be a man of vaunting tongue, and to speak with boldness.'),(8617,'May the son of Cronos never make thee king in sea-girt Ithaca, which thing is by birth thy heritage.\"'),(8618,' Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(8619,'“Antinous, wilt thou be wroth with me for the word that I shall say?'),(8620,'  Even this should I be glad to accept from the hand of Zeus.'),(8621,' Thinkest thou indeed that this is the worst fate among men?'),(8622,' Nay, it is no bad thing to be a king.'),(8623,' Straightway one\'s house grows rich and oneself is held in greater honor. '),(8624,' However, there are other kings of the Achaeans  full many in seagirt Ithaca, both young and old. One of these haply may have this place, since goodly Odysseus is dead.'),(8625,' But I will be lord of our own house and of the slaves that goodly Odysseus won for me.\"'),(8626,'Then Eurymachus, son of Polybus, answered him:'),(8627,'  “Telemachus, this matter verily lies on the knees of the gods, who of the Achaeans shall be king in sea-girt Ithaca; '),(8628,' but as for thy possessions, thou mayest keep them thyself, and be lord in thine own house.'),(8629,' Never may that man come who by violence and against thy will shall wrest thy possessions from thee, while men yet live in Ithaca.'),(8630,' Where are his kinsmen and his native fields? '),(8631,' Does he bring some tidings of thy father\'s coming, or came he hither in furtherance of some matter of his own?'),(8632,'  How he started up, and was straightway gone! Nor did he wait to be known;'),(8633,' and yet he seemed no base man to look upon.\"'),(8634,' Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(8635,'“Eurymachus, surely my father\'s home-coming is lost and gone.'),(8636,'No longer do I put trust in tidings, whencesoever they may come,  nor reck I of any prophecy which my mother haply may learn of a seer, when she has called him to the hall.'),(8637,' But this stranger is a friend of my father\'s house from Taphos. He declares that he is Mentes, son of wise Anchialus, and he is lord over the oar-loving Taphians.\"'),(8638,'So spoke Telemachus, but in his heart he knew the immortal goddess.'),(8639,'Now the wooers turned to the dance and to gladsome song, and made them merry, and waited till evening should come; '),(8640,' and as they made merry dark evening came upon them.'),(8641,' Then they went, each man to his house, to take their rest.'),(8642,'  But Telemachus, where his chamber was built in the beautiful court, high, in a place of wide outlook, thither went to his bed, pondering many things in mind; '),(8643,' and with him, bearing blazing torches, went true-hearted Eurycleia, daughter of Ops, son of Peisenor.  Her long ago Laertes had bought with his wealth, when she was in her first youth, and gave for her the price of twenty oxen; and he honored her even as he honored his faithful wife in his halls, but he never lay with her in love, for he shunned the wrath of his wife.'),(8644,' She it was who bore for Telemachus the blazing torches;  for she of all the handmaids loved him most, and had nursed him when he was a child. '),(8645,'  He opened the doors of the well-built chamber, sat down on the bed, and took off his soft tunic '),(8646,' and laid it in the wise old woman\'s hands.'),(8647,' And she folded and smoothed the tunic  and hung it on a peg beside the corded bedstead, and then went forth from the chamber, drawing the door to by its silver handle, and driving the bolt home with the thong.'),(8648,' So there, the night through, wrapped in a fleece of wool, he pondered in his mind upon the journey which Athena had shewn him.'),(8649,' Soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, up from his bed arose the dear son of Odysseus and put on his clothing. About his shoulder he slung his sharp sword, and beneath his shining feet bound his fair sandals,  and went forth from his chamber like a god to look upon. '),(8650,' Straightway he bade the clear-voiced heralds to summon to the assembly the long-haired Achaeans.'),(8651,' And the heralds made the summons, and the Achaeans assembled full quickly. '),(8652,' Now when they were assembled and met together,  Telemachus went his way to the place of assembly, holding in his hand a spear of bronze—not alone, for along with him two swift hounds followed;'),(8653,' and wondrous was the grace that Athena shed upon him, '),(8654,' and all the people marvelled at him as he came.'),(8655,' But he sat down in his father\'s seat, and the elders gave place.'),(8656,'\n  Then among them the lord Aegyptius was the first to speak, a man bowed with age and wise with wisdom untold. '),(8657,' Now he spoke, because his dear son had gone in the hollow ships to Ilius, famed for its horses, in the company of godlike Odysseus, even the warrior Antiphus.'),(8658,' But him the savage Cyclops had slain  in his hollow cave, and made of him his latest meal. '),(8659,' Three others there were; one, Eurynomus, consorted with the wooers, and two ever kept their father\'s farm.'),(8660,' Yet, even so, he could not forget that other, mourning and sorrowing; '),(8661,' and weeping for him he addressed the assembly, and spoke among them:'),(8662,'  “Hearken now to me, men of Ithaca, to the word that I shall say.'),(8663,' Never have we held assembly or session since the day when goodly Odysseus departed in the hollow ships.'),(8664,' And now who has called us together? '),(8665,' On whom has such need come either of the young men or of those who are older?'),(8666,'  Has he heard some tidings of the army\'s return, which he might tell us plainly, seeing that he has first learned of it himself? '),(8667,' Or is there some other public matter on which he is to speak and address us? '),(8668,' A good man he seems in my eyes, a blessed man.'),(8669,' May Zeus fulfil unto him himself some good, even whatsoever he desires in his heart.”'),(8670,'  So he spoke, and the dear son of Odysseus rejoiced at the word of omen; nor did he thereafter remain seated, but was fain to speak. So he took his stand in the midst of the assembly,'),(8671,'and the staff was placed in his hands by the herald Peisenor, wise in counsel. '),(8672,' Then he spoke, addressing first the old man:'),(8673,'\n  “Old man, not far off, as thou shalt soon learn thyself, is that man who has called the host together—even I;'),(8674,'for on me above all others has sorrow come. '),(8675,'I have neither heard any tidings of the army\'s return, which I might tell you plainly, seeing that I had first learned of it myself, nor is there any other public matter on which I am to speak and address you.  Nay, it is mine own need, for that evil has fallen upon my house in two-fold wise.'),(8676,'First, I have lost my noble sire who was once king among you here, and was gentle as a father; '),(8677,' and now there is come an evil yet greater far, which will presently altogether destroy my house and ruin all my livelihood.'),(8678,'  My mother have wooers beset against her will, the sons of those men who are here the noblest. They shrink from going to the house of her father, Icarius, that he may himself exact the bride-gifts for his daughter, and give her to whom he will, even to him who meets his favour,'),(8679,' but thronging our house day after day they slay our oxen and sheep and fat goats, and keep revel, and drink the sparkling wine recklessly;'),(8680,' and havoc is made of all this wealth.'),(8681,' For there is no man here, such as Odysseus was, to ward off ruin from the house.'),(8682,'  As for me, I am no-wise such as he to ward it off.'),(8683,' Nay verily, even if I try I shall be found a weakling and one knowing naught of valor.'),(8684,' Yet truly I would defend myself, if I had but the power;'),(8685,' for now deeds past all enduring have been wrought, and past all that is seemly has my house been destroyed. '),(8686,' Take shame upon yourselves,  and have regard to your neighbors who dwell roundabout,'),(8687,' and fear the wrath of the gods, lest haply they turn against you in anger at your evil deeds.'),(8688,' I pray you by Olympian Zeus, and by Themis who looses and gathers the assemblies of men, '),(8689,'  forbear, my friends, and leave me alone to pine in bitter grief—unless indeed my father, goodly Odysseus, despitefully wrought the well-greaved Achaeans woe, in requital whereof ye work me woe despitefully by urging these men on.'),(8690,' For me it were better  that ye should yourselves eat up my treasures and my flocks.'),(8691,' If ye were to devour them, recompense would haply be made some day; '),(8692,' for just so long should we go up and down the city, pressing our suit and asking back our goods, until all was given back.'),(8693,' But now past cure are the woes ye put upon my heart.”'),(8694,'  Thus he spoke in wrath, and dashed the staff down upon the ground, bursting into tears; '),(8695,'and pity fell upon all the people.'),(8696,' Then all the others kept silent, and no man had the heart to answer Telemachus with angry words. '),(8697,' Antinous alone answered him, and said:'),(8698,'\n  “Telemachus, thou braggart, unrestrained in daring, what a thing hast thou said, putting us to shame, '),(8699,'\nand wouldest fain fasten reproach upon us!'),(8700,' Nay, I tell thee, it is not the Achaean wooers who are anywise at fault, but thine own mother, for she is crafty above all women.'),(8701,' For it is now the third year and the fourth will soon pass,  since she has been deceiving the hearts of the Achaeans in their breasts.'),(8702,' To all she offers hopes, and has promises for each man, sending them messages, but her mind is set on other things.'),(8703,' And she devised in her heart this guileful thing also:'),(8704,' she set up in her halls a great web, and fell to weaving—  fine of thread was the web and very wide;'),(8705,'  and straightway she spoke among us:'),(8706,'“‘Young men, my wooers, since goodly Odysseus is dead, be patient, though eager for my marriage, until I finish this robe—I would not that my spinning should come to naught—a shroud for the lord Laertes, against the time when  the fell fate of grievous death shall strike him down; lest any of the Achaean women in the land should be wroth with me,'),(8707,'if he, who had won great possessions, were to lie without a shroud.\'\"'),(8708,'So she spoke, and our proud hearts consented.'),(8709,' Then day by day she would weave at the great web,  but by night would unravel it, when she had let place torches by her.'),(8710,'Thus for three years she by her craft kept the Achaeans from knowing, and beguiled them;'),(8711,'but when the fourth year came as the seasons rolled on, even then one of her women who knew all told us, and we caught her unravelling the splendid web.'),(8712,' So she finished it against her will, perforce.'),(8713,' Therefore to thee the wooers make answer thus, that thou mayest thyself know it in thine heart, and that all the Achaeans may know.'),(8714,' Send away thy mother, and command her to wed whomsoever her father bids, and whoso is pleasing to her.'),(8715,'  But if she shall continue long time to vex the sons of the Achaeans, mindful in her heart of this, that Athena has endowed her above other women with knowledge of fair handiwork and an understanding heart, and wiles, such as we have never yet heard that any even of the women of old knew, of those who long ago were fair-tressed Achaean women—  Tyro and Alcmene and Mycene of the fair crown - '),(8716,' of whom not one was like Penelope in shrewd device;'),(8717,' yet this at least she devised not aright.'),(8718,' For so long shall men devour thy livelihood and thy possessions, even as long as she shall keep the counsel which  the gods now put in her heart.'),(8719,' Great fame she brings on herself, but on thee regret for thy much substance.'),(8720,' For us, we will go neither to our lands nor else whither, until she marries that one of the Achaeans whom she will.” '),(8721,' \nThen wise Telemachus answered him, and said:'),(8722,'  “Antinous, in no wise may I thrust forth from the house against her will her that bore me and reared me; '),(8723,' and, as for my father, he is in some other land, whether he be alive or dead.'),(8724,' An evil thing it were for me to pay back a great price to Icarius, as I must, if of my own will I send my mother away. '),(8725,' For from her father\'s hand shall I suffer evil, and heaven  will send other ills besides, for my mother as she leaves the house will invoke the dread Avengers;'),(8726,' and I shall have blame, too, from men.'),(8727,' Therefore will I never speak this word.'),(8728,' And for you, if your own heart is wroth here at, get you forth from my halls and prepare you other feasts,  eating your own substance and changing from house to house. '),(8729,' But if this seems in your eyes to be a better and more profitable thing, that one man\'s livelihood should be ruined without atonement, waste ye it.'),(8730,' But I will call upon the gods that are forever, if haply Zeus may grant that deeds of requital may be wrought.'),(8731,' Without atonement then should ye perish within my halls.”'),(8732,'So spoke Telemachus, and in answer Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, sent forth two eagles, flying from on high, from a mountain peak.'),(8733,' For a time they flew swift as the blasts of the wind side by side with wings outspread; '),(8734,'  but when they reached the middle of the many-voiced assembly, then they wheeled about, flapping their wings rapidly, and down on the heads of all they looked, and death was in their glare.'),(8735,' Then they tore with their talons one another\'s cheeks and necks on either side, and darted away to the right across the houses and the city of the men.'),(8736,' But they were seized with wonder at the birds when their eyes beheld them,'),(8737,' and pondered in their hearts on what was to come to pass.'),(8738,' Then among them spoke the old lord Halitherses, son of Mastor, '),(8739,'for he surpassed all men of his day in knowledge of birds and in uttering words of fate.'),(8740,'  He with good intent addressed their assembly, and spoke among them:'),(8741,'“Hearken now to me, men of Ithaca, to the word that I shall say; '),(8742,'and to the wooers especially do I declare and announce these things,'),(8743,' since on them a great woe is rolling. '),(8744,' For Odysseus shall not long be away from his friends, but even now, methinks,  he is near, and is sowing death and fate for these men, one and all.'),(8745,' Aye, and to many others of us also who dwell in clear-seen Ithaca will he be a bane.'),(8746,' But long ere that let us take thought how we may make an end of this—'),(8747,' or rather let them of themselves make an end, '),(8748,'for this is straightway the better course for them.'),(8749,' Not as one untried do I prophesy, but with sure knowledge.'),(8750,'  For unto Odysseus I declare that all things are fulfilled even as I told him, when the Argives embarked for Ilios and with them went Odysseus of many wiles. '),(8751,'I declared that after suffering many ills and losing all his comrades he would come home in the twentieth year  unknown to all; '),(8752,'and lo, all this is now being brought to pass.” '),(8753,' \nThen Eurymachus, son of Polybus, answered him, and said:'),(8754,' “Old man, up now, get thee home and prophesy to thy children, lest haply in days to come they suffer ill.'),(8755,' In this matter I am better far than thou to prophesy.'),(8756,' Many birds there are that fare to and fro under the rays of the sun, and not all are fateful.'),(8757,' As for Odysseus, he has perished far away, as I would that thou hadst likewise perished with him. '),(8758,' Then wouldst thou not prate so much in thy reading of signs,  or be urging Telemachus on in his wrath, hoping for some gift for thy house, if haply he shall give it.'),(8759,' But I will speak out to thee, and this word shall verily be brought to pass. '),(8760,' If thou, wise in the wisdom of old, shalt beguile with thy talk a younger man, and set him on to be wroth,  for him in the first place it shall be the more grievous, and he will in no case be able to do aught because of these men here,'),(8761,'and on thee, old man, will we lay a fine which it will grieve thy soul to pay,'),(8762,'and bitter shall be thy sorrow.'),(8763,' And to Telemachus I myself, here among all, will offer this counsel.'),(8764,' His mother let him bid to go back to the house of her father,'),(8765,'  and they will prepare a wedding feast and make ready the gifts full many,—aye, all that should follow after a well-loved daughter. '),(8766,'For ere that, methinks, the sons of the Achaeans will not cease from their grievous wooing, since in any case we fear no man,—  no, not Telemachus for all his many words,—nor do we reck of any soothsaying which thou, old man, mayest declare; it will fail of fulfillment, and thou shalt be hated the more.'),(8767,' Aye, and his possessions shall be devoured in evil wise, nor shall requital ever be made, so long as she shall put off the Achaeans  in the matter of her marriage. '),(8768,' And we on our part waiting here day after day are rivals by reason of her excellence, and go not after other women, whom each one might fitly wed.\"'),(8769,'Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(8770,'“Eurymachus and all ye other lordly wooers,  in this matter I entreat you no longer nor speak thereof, '),(8771,'for now the gods know it, and all the Achaeans.'),(8772,' But come, give me a swift ship and twenty comrades who will accomplish my journey for me to and fro.'),(8773,'For I shall go to Sparta and to sandy Pylos  to seek tidings of the return of my father that has long been gone, if haply any mortal man may tell me, or I may hear a voice from Zeus, which oftenest brings tidings to men.'),(8774,'  If so be I shall hear that my father is alive and coming home, then verily, though I am sore afflicted, I could endure for yet a year. '),(8775,'But if I shall hear that he is dead and gone, then I will return to my dear native land and heap up a mound for him, and over it pay funeral rites, full many, as is due, and give my mother to a husband.” '),(8776,' \nSo saying he sat down, and among them rose  Mentor, who was a comrade of noble Odysseus. To him, on departing with his ships, Odysseus had given all his house in charge, that it should obey the old man and that he should keep all things safe.'),(8777,' He with good intent addressed their assembly, and spoke among them:'),(8778,'\n“Hearken now to me, men of Ithaca, to the word that I shall say.'),(8779,'  Never henceforth let sceptred king with a ready heart be kind and gentle, nor let him heed righteousness in his heart, but let him ever be harsh and work unrighteousness, '),(8780,' seeing that no one remembers divine Odysseus of the people whose lord he was; yet gentle was he as a father.'),(8781,'  But of a truth I begrudge not the proud wooers that they work deeds of violence in the evil contrivings of their minds, '),(8782,' for it is at the hazard of their own lives that they violently devour the house of Odysseus, who, they say, will no more return. '),(8783,' Nay, rather it is with the rest of the folk that I am wroth, that ye all  sit thus in silence, and utter no word of rebuke to make the wooers cease, though ye are many and they but few.\"'),(8784,'Then Leocritus, son of Euenor, answered him:'),(8785,'“Mentor, thou mischief-maker, thou wanderer in thy wits, what hast thou said, bidding men make us cease?'),(8786,' Nay, it were a hard thing  to fight about a feast with men that moreover outnumber you. '),(8787,'For if Ithacan Odysseus himself were to come and be eager at heart to drive out from his hall the lordly wooers who are feasting in his house, then should his wife have no joy  at his coming, though sorely she longed for him, but right here would he meet a shameful death, if he fought with men that outnumbered him.'),(8788,' Thou hast not spoken aright. '),(8789,' But come now, ye people, scatter, each one of you to his own lands. As for this fellow, Mentor and Halitherses will speed his journey, for they are friends of his father\'s house from of old.'),(8790,'  But methinks he will long abide here and get his tidings in Ithaca, and never accomplish this journey.\"'),(8791,'So he spoke, and hastily broke up the assembly.'),(8792,'They then scattered, each one to his own house; and the wooers went to the house of divine Odysseus.'),(8793,'\n  But Telemachus went apart to the shore of the sea, and having washed his hands in the grey seawater, prayed to Athena:'),(8794,' “Hear me, thou who didst come yesterday as a god to our house, and didst bid me go in a ship over the misty deep to seek tidings of the return of my father, that has long been gone.'),(8795,'  Lo, all this the Achaeans hinder, but the wooers most of all in their evil insolence.” '),(8796,' \nSo he spoke in prayer, and Athena drew near to him in the likeness of Mentor, both in form and invoice; and she spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(8797,'\n  “Telemachus, neither hereafter shalt thou be a base man or a witless, if aught of thy father\'s goodly spirit has been instilled into thee, such a man was he to fulfil both deed and word.'),(8798,' So then shall this journey of thine be neither vain nor unfulfilled.'),(8799,' But if thou art not the son of him and of Penelope,  then I have no hope that thou wilt accomplish thy desire. '),(8800,'Few sons indeed are like their fathers; most are worse, few better than their fathers.'),(8801,' But since neither hereafter shalt thou be a base man or a witless, nor has the wisdom of Odysseus wholly failed thee,  there is therefore hope that thou wilt accomplish this work.'),(8802,' Now then let be the will and counsel of the wooers—fools, for they are in no wise either prudent or just,'),(8803,' nor do they know aught of death or black fate, which verily is near at hand for them, that they shall all perish in a day.'),(8804,' But for thyself, the journey on which thy heart is set shall not be long delayed,'),(8805,'  so true a friend of thy father\'s house am I, who will equip for thee a swift ship, and myself go with thee.'),(8806,' But go thou now to the house and join the company of the wooers; make ready stores, and bestow all in vessels—  wine in jars, and barley meal, the marrow of men, in stout skins;'),(8807,' —but I, going through the town, will quickly gather comrades that go willingly.'),(8808,' And ships there are full many in sea-girt Ithaca, both new and old; '),(8809,' of these will I choose out for thee the one that is best,  and quickly will we make her ready and launch her on the broad deep.\"'),(8810,'So spoke Athena, daughter of Zeus,'),(8811,' nor did Telemachus tarry long after he had heard the voice of the goddess,'),(8812,'but went his way to the house, his heart heavy within him. He found there the proud wooers in the halls,  flaying goats and singeing swine in the court.'),(8813,' And Antinous with a laugh came straight to Telemachus, and clasped his hand, and spoke, and addressed him:'),(8814,'  Nay, I bid thee, eat and drink even as before. All these things the Achaeans will surely provide for thee—the ship and chosen oarsmen—that with speed thou mayest go to sacred Pylos to seek for tidings of thy noble father.” '),(8815,'  Nay, I bid thee, eat and drink even as before. All these things the Achaeans will surely provide for thee—the ship and chosen oarsmen—that with speed thou mayest go to sacred Pylos to seek for tidings of thy noble father.” '),(8816,' \nThen wise Telemachus answered him:'),(8817,'  “Antinous, in no wise is it possible for me in your overweening company to sit at meat quietly and to make merry with an easy mind.'),(8818,' Is it not enough, ye wooers, that in time past ye wasted many goodly possessions of mine, while I was still a child? '),(8819,'But now that I am grown,  and gain knowledge by hearing the words of others, yea and my spirit waxes within me, I will try how I may hurl forth upon your evil fates, either going to Pylos or here in this land.'),(8820,' For go I will, nor shall the journey be in vain whereof I speak, '),(8821,' though I voyage in another\'s ship, since I may not be master of ship or oarsmen.'),(8822,'  So, I ween, it seemed to you to be more to your profit.\"'),(8823,' He spoke, and snatched his hand from the hand of Antinous without more ado,'),(8824,' and the wooers were busy with the feast throughout the hall.'),(8825,' They mocked and jeered at him in their talk;'),(8826,'and thus would one of the proud youths speak:'),(8827,' “Aye, verily Telemachus is planning our murder.'),(8828,' He will bring men to aid him from sandy Pylos or even from Sparta, so terribly is he set upon it.'),(8829,' Or he means to go to Ephyre, that rich land, to bring from thence deadly drugs,  that he may cast them in the wine-bowl, and destroy us all.”'),(8830,'And again another of the proud youths would say:'),(8831,' “Who knows but he himself as he goes on the hollow ship may perish wandering far from his friends, even as Odysseus did?'),(8832,' So would he cause us yet more labour;'),(8833,' for we should have to divide all his possessions, and his house we should give to his mother to possess, and to him who should wed her.\"'),(8834,'So they spoke, but Telemachus went down to the high-roofed treasure-chamber of his father, a wide room where gold and bronze lay piled, and raiment in chests, and stores of fragrant oil.'),(8835,'  There, too, stood great jars of wine, old and sweet, holding within them an unmixed divine drink, and ranged in order along the wall, if ever Odysseus should return home even after many grievous toils.'),(8836,' Shut were  the double doors, close-fitted; '),(8837,' and there both night and day a stewardess abode, who guarded all in wisdom of mind, Eurycleia, daughter of Ops, son of Peisenor.'),(8838,' To her now Telemachus, when he had called her to the treasure-chamber, spoke, and said:'),(8839,'“Nurse, draw me off wine in jars,  sweet wine that is the choicest next to that which thou guardest ever thinking upon that ill-fated one, if haply Zeus-born Odysseus may come I know not whence, having escaped from death and the fates.'),(8840,' Fill twelve jars and fit them all with covers,'),(8841,'and pour me barley meal into well-sewn skins,'),(8842,' and let there be twenty measures of ground barley meal.'),(8843,'and have all these things brought together; '),(8844,'and have all these things brought together; '),(8845,'for at evening I will fetch them, when my mother goes to her upper chamber and bethinks her of her rest.'),(8846,' For I am going to Sparta and to sandy Pylos  to seek tidings of the return of my dear father, if haply I may hear any.”'),(8847,' \nSo he spoke, and the dear nurse, Eurycleia, uttered a shrill cry, and weeping spoke to him winged words:'),(8848,'“Ah, dear child, how has this thought come into thy mind?'),(8849,' Whither art thou minded to go over the wide earth,  thou who art an only son and well-beloved? '),(8850,' But he hath perished far from his country, the Zeus-born Odysseus, in a strange land; '),(8851,'and these men, so soon as thou art gone, will devise evil for thee hereafter, that thou mayest perish by guile, and themselves divide all these possessions.'),(8852,'Nay, abide here in charge of what is thine;'),(8853,'thou hast no need  to suffer ills and go a wanderer over the unresting sea.”'),(8854,'Then wise Telemachus answered her:'),(8855,' “Take heart, nurse, for not without a god\'s warrant is this my plan. '),(8856,'But swear to tell naught of this to my dear mother until the eleventh or twelfth day shall come,  or until she shall herself miss me and hear that I am gone, that she may not mar her fair flesh with weeping.\"'),(8857,'So he spoke, and the old woman swore a great oath by the gods to say naught.'),(8858,' But when she had sworn and made an end of the oath, straightway she drew for him wine in jars,  and poured barley meal into well-sewn skins; '),(8859,'and Telemachus went to the hall and joined the company of the wooers.'),(8860,'\nThen the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, took other counsel.'),(8861,' In the likeness of Telemachus she went everywhere throughout the city, and to each of the men she drew near and spoke her word,  bidding them gather at even beside the swift ship. '),(8862,'Furthermore, of Noemon, the glorious son of Phronius, she asked a swift ship, '),(8863,'and he promised it to her with a ready heart. '),(8864,' \nNow the sun set and all the ways grew dark. Then she drew the swift ship to the sea and  put in it all the gear that well-benched ships carry.'),(8865,' \nAnd she moored it at the mouth of the harbor, and round about it the goodly company was gathered together,'),(8866,' and the goddess heartened each man.'),(8867,'\nThen again the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, took other counsel.'),(8868,' She went her way to the house of divine Odysseus, '),(8869,' and there began to shed sweet sleep upon the wooers and made them to wander in their drinking, and from their hands she cast the cups.'),(8870,' But they rose to go to their rest throughout the city, and remained no long time seated, for sleep was falling upon their eyelids. '),(8871,'But to Telemachus spoke flashing-eyed Athena,  calling him forth before the stately hall, having likened herself to Mentor both in form and in voice:'),(8872,'\n“Telemachus, already thy well-greaved comrades sit at the oar and await thy setting out.'),(8873,' Come, let us go, that we may not long delay their journey.”'),(8874,'  So saying, Pallas Athena led the way quickly,'),(8875,' and he followed in the footsteps of the goddess.'),(8876,' Now when they had come down to the ship and to the sea, they found on the shore their long-haired comrades, '),(8877,'and the strong and mighty Telemachus spoke among them:'),(8878,'  “Come, friends, let us fetch the stores,'),(8879,'for all are now gathered together in the hall.'),(8880,' My mother knows naught hereof, nor the handmaids either: one only heard my word.\"'),(8881,'Thus saying, he led the way, and they went along with him.'),(8882,' So they brought and  stowed everything in the well-benched ship, as the dear son of Odysseus bade. '),(8883,'Then on board the ship stepped Telemachus, and Athena went before him and sat down in the stern of the ship, '),(8884,' and near her sat Telemachus, '),(8885,' while the men loosed the stern cables and themselves stepped on board, and sat down upon the benches.'),(8886,'  And flashing-eyed Athena sent them a favorable wind, a strong-blowing West wind that sang over the wine-dark sea.'),(8887,' And Telemachus called to his men, and bade them lay hold of the tackling,'),(8888,' and they hearkened to his call.'),(8889,' The mast of fir  they raised and set in the hollow socket, and made it fast with fore-stays, and hauled up the white sail with twisted thongs of ox-hide.'),(8890,' So the wind filled the belly of the sail, and the dark wave sang loudly about the stem of the ship as she went, '),(8891,' and she sped over the wave accomplishing her way.'),(8892,'  Then, when they had made the tackling fast in the swift black ship, they set forth bowls brim full of wine, and poured libations to the immortal gods that are forever, and chiefest of all to the flashing-eyed daughter of Zeus.'),(8893,' So all night long and through the dawn the ship cleft her way.'),(8894,' And now the sun, leaving the beauteous mere, sprang up into the brazen heaven to give light to the immortals and to mortal men on the earth, the giver of grain; '),(8895,'and they came to Pylos, the well-built citadel of Neleus.'),(8896,'  Here the townsfolk on the shore of the sea were offering sacrifice of black bulls to the dark-haired Earth-shaker.'),(8897,' Nine companies there were, and five hundred men sat in each, and in each they held nine bulls ready for sacrifice. '),(8898,'Now when they had tasted the inner parts and were burning the thigh-pieces to the god,  the others put straight in to the shore, and hauled up and furled the sail of the shapely ship, and moored her, and themselves stepped forth.'),(8899,'Forth too from the ship stepped Telemachus, and Athena led the way.'),(8900,' And the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, spake first to him, and said:'),(8901,'“Telemachus, no longer hast thou need to feel shame, no, not a whit. '),(8902,' For to this end hast thou sailed over the sea, that thou mightest seek tidings of thy father,—where the earth covered him, and what fate he met.'),(8903,' But come now, go straightway to Nestor, tamer of horses;'),(8904,'let us learn what counsel he keepeth hid in his breast.'),(8905,' And do thou beseech him thyself that he may tell thee the very truth.'),(8906,'for he is wise indeed.\"'),(8907,'for he is wise indeed.\"'),(8908,'Then wise Telemachus answered her:'),(8909,'and how shall I greet him?'),(8910,'and how shall I greet him?'),(8911,'I am as yet all unversed in subtle speech,'),(8912,' and moreover a young man has shame to question an elder.\"'),(8913,' Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(8914,'“Telemachus, somewhat thou wilt of thyself devise in thy breast, and somewhat heaven too will prompt thee.'),(8915,' For, methinks, not without the favour of the gods hast thou been born and reared.\"'),(8916,'So spake Pallas Athena, and led the way  quickly;'),(8917,' but he followed in the footsteps of the goddess; '),(8918,' There Nestor sat with his sons, and round about his people, making ready the feast, were roasting some of the meat and putting other pieces on spits. '),(8919,' But when they saw the strangers they all came thronging about them,  and clasped their hands in welcome, and bade them sit down. '),(8920,'First Nestor\'s son Peisistratus came near and took both by the hand, and made them to sit down at the feast on soft fleeces upon the sand of the sea, beside his brother Thrasymedes and his father.'),(8921,'  Thereupon he gave them portions of the inner meat and poured wine in a golden cup, '),(8922,'and, pledging her, he spoke to Pallas Athena, daughter of Zeus who bears the aegis:'),(8923,'“Pray now, stranger, to the lord Poseidon,'),(8924,' for his is the feast whereon you have chanced in coming hither.'),(8925,'  And when thou hast poured libations and hast prayed, as is fitting, then give thy friend also the cup of honey-sweet wine that he may pour, since he too, I ween, prays to the immortals;'),(8926,'for all men have need of the gods.'),(8927,' Howbeit he is the younger, of like age with myself, '),(8928,' wherefore to thee first will I give the golden cup.”'),(8929,' \nSo he spake, and placed in her hand the cup of sweet wine.'),(8930,' But Pallas Athena rejoiced at the man\'s wisdom and judgment, in that to her first he gave the golden cup; '),(8931,'and straightway she prayed earnestly to the lord Poseidon:'),(8932,'\n  “Hear me, Poseidon, thou Earth-enfolder, and grudge not in answer to our prayer to bring these deeds to fulfillment.'),(8933,' To Nestor, first of all, and to his sons vouchsafe renown, and then do thou grant to the rest gracious requital for this glorious hecatomb, even to all the men of Pylos; '),(8934,'  and grant furthermore that Telemachus and I may return when we have accomplished all that for which we came hither with our swift black ship.\"'),(8935,'Thus she prayed, and was herself fulfilling all.'),(8936,' Then she gave Telemachus the fair two-handled cup, '),(8937,'and in like manner the dear son of Odysseus prayed.'),(8938,'  Then when they had roasted the outer flesh and drawn it off the spits, they divided the portions and feasted a glorious feast.'),(8939,' But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, spoke first among them:'),(8940,'\n“Now verily is it seemlier to ask and enquire  of the strangers who they are, since now they have had their joy of food.'),(8941,'Whence do ye sail over the watery ways? '),(8942,'Whence do ye sail over the watery ways? '),(8943,' Is it on some business, or do ye wander at random over the sea, even as pirates, who wander hazarding their lives and bringing evil to men of other lands?”'),(8944,'  Then wise Telemachus took courage, and made answer,'),(8945,'for Athena herself put courage in his heart, that he might ask about his father that was gone, and that good report might be his among men:'),(8946,'\n“Nestor, son of Neleus, great glory of the Achaeans,  thou askest whence we are, '),(8947,' and I will surely tell thee.'),(8948,' We have come from Ithaca that is below Neion; '),(8949,' but this business whereof I speak is mine own, and concerns not the people.'),(8950,' I come after the wide-spread rumor of my father, if haply I may hear of it, even of goodly Odysseus of the steadfast heart, who once, men say,  fought by thy side and sacked the city of the Trojans. '),(8951,' For of all men else, as many as warred with the Trojans, we learn where each man died a woeful death, but of him the son of Cronos has made even the death to be past learning; '),(8952,'for no man can tell surely where he hath died,—  whether he was overcome by foes on the mainland, or on the deep among the waves of Amphitrite.'),(8953,' Therefore am I now come to thy knees, if perchance thou wilt be willing to tell me of his woeful death, whether thou sawest it haply with thine own eyes, or didst hear from some other the story  of his wanderings; '),(8954,'for beyond all men did his mother bear him to sorrow. '),(8955,' And do thou nowise out of ruth or pity for me speak soothing words, but tell me truly how thou didst come to behold him. '),(8956,'I beseech thee, if ever my father, noble Odysseus, promised aught to thee of word or deed and fulfilled it  in the land of the Trojans, where you Achaeans suffered woes, be mindful of it now, I pray thee, and tell me the very truth.” '),(8957,' \nThen the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, answered him:'),(8958,'“My friend, since thou hast recalled to my mind the sorrow which we endured in that land, we sons of the Achaeans, unrestrained in daring,—  all that we endured on shipboard, as we roamed after booty over the misty deep whithersoever Achilles led; and all our fightings around the great city of king Priam;'),(8959,'—lo, there all our best were slain.'),(8960,' There lies warlike Aias, there Achilles,  there Patroclus, the peer of the gods in counsel; and there my own dear son, strong alike and peerless, Antilochus, pre-eminent in speed of foot and as a warrior.'),(8961,' Aye, and many other ills we suffered besides these; '),(8962,' who of mortal men could tell them all?'),(8963,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 3.115-3.116'),(8964,'  Nay, if for five years\' space or six years\' space thou wert to abide here, and ask of all the woes which the goodly Achaeans endured there, ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 115 to line 117'),(8965,' For nine years\' space were we busied plotting their ruin with all manner of wiles; and hardly did the son of Cronos bring it to pass.'),(8966,'  There no man ventured to vie with him in counsel, since goodly Odysseus far excelled in all manner of wiles,—thy father, if indeed thou art his son.'),(8967,' Amazement holds me as I look on thee, '),(8968,'for verily thy speech is like his; nor would one think  that a younger man would speak so like him. '),(8969,'Now all the time that we were there goodly Odysseus and I never spoke at variance either in the assembly or in the council, but being of one mind advised the Argives with wisdom and shrewd counsel how all might be for the best.'),(8970,'  But when we had sacked the lofty city of Priam, and had gone away in our ships, and a god had scattered the Achaeans, then, even then, Zeus planned in his heart a woeful return for the Argives, for in no wise prudent or just were all.'),(8971,' Wherefore many of them met an evil fate  through the fell wrath of the flashing-eyed goddess, the daughter of the mighty sire, '),(8972,'for she caused strife between the two sons of Atreus.'),(8973,' Now these two called to an assembly all the Achaeans, recklessly and in no due order, at set of sun—and they came heavy with wine, the sons of the Achaeans,—  and they spoke their word, and told wherefore they had gathered the host together.'),(8974,' \nThen in truth Menelaus bade all the Achaeans think of their return over the broad back of the sea, but in no wise did he please Agamemnon, '),(8975,' for he was fain to hold back the host and to offer holy hecatombs,  that he might appease the dread wrath of Athena,—fool! nor knew he this, that with her was to be no hearkening;'),(8976,' for the mind of the gods that are forever is not quickly turned.'),(8977,' So these two stood bandying harsh words; '),(8978,' but the well-greaved Achaeans sprang up  with a wondrous din, and two-fold plans found favour with them.'),(8979,' That night we rested, each side pondering hard thoughts against the other,'),(8980,' for Zeus was bringing upon us an evil doom, '),(8981,'but in the morning some of us launched our ships upon the bright sea, and put on board our goods and the low-girdled women.'),(8982,'  Half, indeed, of the host held back and remained there with Agamemnon, son of Atreus, shepherd of the host, '),(8983,'but half of us embarked and rowed away; '),(8984,'and swiftly the ships sailed, for a god made smooth the cavernous sea.'),(8985,' But when we came to Tenedos, we offered sacrifice to the gods,  being eager to reach our homes, '),(8986,'howbeit Zeus did not yet purpose our return, stubborn god, who roused evil strife again a second time.'),(8987,' Then some turned back their curved ships and departed, even the lord Odysseus, the wise and crafty-minded, with his company, once more showing favour to Agamemnon, son of Atreus; '),(8988,' but I with the full company of ships that followed me fled on, for I knew that the god was devising evil.'),(8989,' And the warlike son of Tydeus fled and urged on his men; '),(8990,'and late upon our track came fair-haired Menelaus, and overtook us in Lesbos, as we were debating the long voyage,  whether we should sail to sea-ward of rugged Chios, toward the isle Psyria, keeping Chios itself on our left, or to land-ward of Chios past windy Mimas.'),(8991,' So we asked the god to shew us a sign, '),(8992,' and he shewed it us, and bade us cleave through the midst of the sea to Euboea,  that we might the soonest escape from misery.'),(8993,'And a shrill wind sprang up to blow,'),(8994,' and the ships ran swiftly over the teeming ways, and at night put in to Geraestus.'),(8995,' There on the altar of Poseidon we laid many thighs of bulls, thankful to have traversed the great sea.'),(8996,'  It was the fourth day when in Argos the company of Diomedes, son of Tydeus, tamer of horses, stayed their shapely ships; '),(8997,'but I held on toward Pylos, and the wind was not once quenched from the time when the god first sent it forth to blow. '),(8998,' \n“Thus I came, dear child, without tidings, nor know I aught  of those others, who of the Achaeans were saved, and who were lost. '),(8999,'But what tidings I have heard as I abide in our halls thou shalt hear, as is right, nor will I hide it from thee.'),(9000,' Safely, they say, came the Myrmidons that rage with the spear, whom the famous son of great-hearted Achilles led;  and safely Philoctetes, the glorious son of Poias. '),(9001,'All his company, too, did Idomeneus bring to Crete, all who escaped the war, and the sea robbed him of none.'),(9002,' But of the son of Atreus you have yourselves heard, far off though you are, how he came, and how Aegisthus devised for him a woeful doom.'),(9003,'  Yet verily he paid the reckoning therefor in terrible wise,'),(9004,' so good a thing is it that a son be left behind a man at his death, since that son took vengeance on his father\'s slayer, the guileful Aegisthus, for that he slew his glorious father.'),(9005,' Thou, too, friend, for I see thou art a comely man and tall,  be thou valiant, that many an one among men yet to be born may praise thee.\"'),(9006,'Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(9007,' “Nestor, son of Neleus, great glory of the Achaeans, yea verily that son took vengeance, and the Achaeans shall spread his fame abroad, that men who are yet to be may hear thereof.'),(9008,'  O that the gods would clothe me with such strength, that I might take vengeance on the wooers for their grievous sin, who in wantonness devise mischief against me. '),(9009,'But lo, the gods have spun for me no such happiness, for me or for my father; '),(9010,'and now I must in any case endure.”'),(9011,'  Then the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, answered him: '),(9012,'“Friend, since thou calledst this to my mind and didst speak of it, they say that many wooers for the hand of thy mother devise evils in thy halls in thy despite.'),(9013,' Tell me, art thou willingly thus oppressed, or do the people  throughout the land hate thee, following the voice of a god? '),(9014,'Who knows but Odysseus may some day come and take vengeance on them for their violent deeds,—he alone, it may be, or even all the host of the Achaeans? '),(9015,'Ah, would that flashing-eyed Athena might choose to love thee even as then she cared exceedingly for glorious Odysseus  in the land of the Trojans, where we Achaeans suffered woes. For never yet have I seen the gods so manifestly shewing love, as Pallas Athena did to him, standing manifest by his side. If she would be pleased to love thee in such wise and would care for thee at heart, then would many a one of them utterly forget marriage.\"'),(9016,' Then wise Telemachus answered him: '),(9017,' “Old man, in no wise do I deem that this word will be brought to pass.'),(9018,'amazement holds me.'),(9019,'amazement holds me.'),(9020,' No hope have I that this will come to pass, no, not though the gods should so will it.” '),(9021,' \nThen the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, spoke to him, and said: '),(9022,' \n “Telemachus, what a word has escaped the barrier of thy teeth! '),(9023,' \nEasily might a god who willed it bring a man safe home, even from afar.'),(9024,' But for myself, I had rather endure many grievous toils ere I reached home and saw the day of my returning, than after my return be slain at my hearth, as Agamemnon  was slain by the guile of Aegisthus and of his own wife. '),(9025,'But of a truth death that is common to all the gods themselves cannot ward from a man they love, when the fell fate of grievous death shall strike him down.\"'),(9026,'Then wise Telemachus answered her: '),(9027,' “Mentor, no longer let us tell of these things despite our grief. '),(9028,' For him no return can ever more be brought to pass; nay, ere this the immortals have devised for him death and black fate.'),(9029,' But now I would make enquiry and ask Nestor regarding another matter, since beyond all others he knows judgments and wisdom; '),(9030,' for thrice, men say, has he been king for a generation of men, '),(9031,'and like unto an immortal he seems to me to look upon.'),(9032,' Nestor, son of Neleus, do thou tell me truly:'),(9033,' how was the son of Atreus, wide-ruling Agamemnon, slain?'),(9034,' Where was Menelaus?'),(9035,' What death did  guileful Aegisthus plan for the king, since he slew a man mightier far than himself? '),(9036,'Was Menelaus not in Achaean Argos, but wandering elsewhere among men, so that Aegisthus took heart and did the murderous deed?\"'),(9037,'Then the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, answered him:'),(9038,' “Then verily, my child, will I tell thee all the truth.'),(9039,'  Lo, of thine own self thou dost guess how this matter would have fallen out, if the son of Atreus, fair-haired Menelaus, on his return from Troy had found Aegisthus in his halls alive. '),(9040,' Then for him not even in death would they have piled the up-piled earth, but the dogs and birds would have torn him  as he lay on the plain far from the city, nor would any of the Achaean women have bewailed him; '),(9041,'for monstrous was the deed he devised.'),(9042,' We on our part abode there in Troy fulfilling our many toils; '),(9043,'but he, at ease in a nook of horse-pasturing Argos, ever sought to beguile with words the wife of Agamemnon.'),(9044,'  Now at the first she put from her the unseemly deed, the beautiful Clytemnestra, '),(9045,'for she had an understanding heart; '),(9046,'and with her was furthermore a minstrel whom the son of Atreus straitly charged, when he set forth for the land of Troy, to guard his wife. '),(9047,'But when at length the doom of the gods bound her that she should be overcome,  then verily Aegisthus took the minstrel to a desert isle and left him to be the prey and spoil of birds; and her, willing as he was willing, he led to his own house.'),(9048,' And many thigh-pieces he burned upon the holy altars of the gods, and many offerings he hung up, woven stuffs and gold,  since he had accomplished a mighty deed beyond all his heart had hoped.'),(9049,' \n“Now we were sailing together on our way from Troy, the son of Atreus and I, in all friendship; '),(9050,'but when we came to holy Sunium, the cape of Athens, there Phoebus Apollo  assailed with his gentle shafts and slew the helmsman of Menelaus, as he held in his hands the steering-oar of the speeding ship, even Phrontis, son of Onetor, who excelled the tribes of men in piloting a ship when the storm winds blow strong.'),(9051,' So Menelaus tarried there, though eager for his journey,  that he might bury his comrade and over him pay funeral rites.'),(9052,'But when he in his turn, as he passed over the wine-dark sea in the hollow ships, reached in swift course the steep height of Malea, then verily Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, planned for him a hateful path and poured upon him the blasts of shrill winds,  and the waves were swollen to huge size, like unto mountains. '),(9053,'Then, parting his ships in twain, he brought some to Crete, where the Cydonians dwelt about the streams of Iardanus.'),(9054,' Now there is a smooth cliff, sheer towards the sea, on the border of Gortyn in the misty deep, '),(9055,' where the Southwest Wind drives the great wave against the headland on the left toward Phaestus, and a little rock holds back a great wave.'),(9056,' Thither came some of his ships, and the men with much ado escaped destruction, howbeit the ships the waves dashed to pieces against the reef.'),(9057,' But the five other dark-prowed ships  the wind, as it bore them, and the wave brought to Egypt.'),(9058,' So he was wandering there with his ships among men of strange speech, gathering much livelihood and gold;'),(9059,' but meanwhile Aegisthus devised this woeful work at home.'),(9060,'  Seven years he reigned over Mycenae, rich in gold, after slaying the son of Atreus, and the people were subdued under him;'),(9061,' but in the eighth came as his bane the goodly Orestes back from Athens, and slew his father\'s murderer,  the guileful Aegisthus, for that he had slain his glorious father. '),(9062,' Now when he had slain him, he made a funeral feast for the Argives over his hateful mother and the craven Aegisthus; '),(9063,'and on the self-same day there came to him Menelaus, good at the war-cry, bringing much treasure, even all the burden that his ships could bear.'),(9064,'“So do not thou, my friend, wander long far from home, leaving thy wealth behind thee and men in thy house  so insolent, lest they divide and devour all thy wealth, and thou shalt have gone on a fruitless journey.'),(9065,' But to Menelaus I bid and command thee to go, '),(9066,'for he has but lately come from a strange land, from a folk whence no one would hope in his heart  to return, whom the storms had once driven astray into a sea so great, whence the very birds do not fare in the space of a year, so great is it and terrible.'),(9067,' But now go thy way with thy ship and thy comrades, '),(9068,' or, if thou wilt go by land, here are chariot and horses at hand for thee,  and here at thy service are my sons, who will be thy guides to goodly Lacedaemon, where lives fair-haired Menelaus.'),(9069,' And do thou beseech him thyself that he may tell thee the very truth.'),(9070,' for he is wise indeed.” '),(9071,' for he is wise indeed.” '),(9072,' \nSo he spoke, and the sun set, and darkness came on. '),(9073,' \n Then among them spoke the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena: '),(9074,' \n“Old man, of a truth thou hast told this tale aright.'),(9075,' But come, cut out the tongues of the victims and mix the wine, that when we have poured libations to Poseidon and the other immortals, we may bethink us of sleep; '),(9076,'for it is the time thereto.'),(9077,'  Even now has the light gone down beneath the darkness,'),(9078,' and it is not fitting to sit long at the feast of the gods, but to go our way.\"'),(9079,'So spoke the daughter of Zeus, and they hearkenened to her voice.'),(9080,' Heralds poured water over their hands, and youths filled the bowls brim full of drink,  and served out to all, pouring first drops for libation into the cups.'),(9081,' Then they cast the tongues upon the fire, and, rising up, poured libations upon them.'),(9082,' But when they had poured libations and had drunk to their heart\'s content, then verily Athena and godlike Telemachus were both fain to return to the hollow ship; '),(9083,' but Nestor on his part sought to stay them, and he spoke to them, saying:'),(9084,'“This may Zeus forbid, and the other immortal gods, that ye should go from my house to your swift ship as from one utterly without raiment and poor, who has not cloaks and blankets in plenty in his house,  whereon both he and his guests may sleep softly.'),(9085,' Nay, in my house there are cloaks and fair blankets.'),(9086,' Never surely shall the dear son of this man Odysseus lie down upon the deck of a ship, while I yet live and children after me are left in my halls  to entertain strangers, even whosoever shall come to my house.\"'),(9087,'Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(9088,' “Well indeed hast thou spoken in this, old friend,'),(9089,' and it were fitting for Telemachus to hearken to thee, since it is far better thus.'),(9090,' But while he shall now follow with thee, that he may sleep  in thy halls, '),(9091,' I for my part will go to the black ship, that I may hearten my comrades and tell them all.'),(9092,' For alone among them I declare that I am an older man;'),(9093,' the others are younger who follow in friendship, all of them of like age with great-hearted Telemachus.'),(9094,'  There will I lay me down by the hollow black ship this night, '),(9095,'but in the morning I will go to the great-hearted Cauconians, where a debt is owing to me, in no wise new or small.'),(9096,' But do thou send this man on his way with a chariot and with thy son, since he has come to thy house,'),(9097,' and give him horses,  the fleetest thou host in running and the best in strength.”'),(9098,' \nSo spoke the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, and she departed in the likeness of a sea-eagle; '),(9099,' \nand amazement fell upon all at the sight, '),(9100,'and the old man marvelled, when his eyes beheld it.'),(9101,' And he grasped the hand of Telemachus, and spoke, and addressed him:'),(9102,'\n  “Friend, in no wise do I think that thou wilt prove a base man or a craven, if verily when thou art so young the gods follow thee to be thy guides.'),(9103,' For truly this is none other of those that have their dwellings on Olympus but the daughter of Zeus, Tritogeneia, the maid most glorious, she that honored also thy noble father among the Argives.'),(9104,'  Nay, O Queen, be gracious, and grant to me fair renown, to me and to my sons and to my revered wife; '),(9105,'and to thee in return will I sacrifice a sleek heifer, broad of brow, unbroken, which no man hath yet led beneath the yoke.'),(9106,' Her will I sacrifice, and I will overlay her horns with gold.\"'),(9107,' So he spoke in prayer, and Pallas Athena heard him. '),(9108,'Then the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, led them, his sons and the husbands of his daughters, to his beautiful palace.'),(9109,' And when they reached the glorious palace of the king, they sat down in rows on the chairs and high seats; '),(9110,' and on their coming the old man mixed for them a bowl of sweet wine, which now in the eleventh year the housewife opened, when she had loosed the string that held the lid.'),(9111,' Thereof the old man bade mix a bowl, and earnestly he prayed, as he poured libations, to Athena, the daughter of Zeus who bears the aegis.'),(9112,'\n  But when they had poured libations, and had drunk to their heart\'s content, they went, each to his home, to take their rest. But the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, bade Telemachus, the dear son of divine Odysseus, to sleep there on a corded bedstead under the echoing portico,  and by him Peisistratus, of the good ashen spear, a leader of men, who among his sons was still unwed in the palace.'),(9113,' But he himself slept in the inmost chamber of the lofty house, and beside him lay the lady his wife, who had strewn the couch. '),(9114,' \nSoon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered,  up from his bed rose the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, and went forth and sat down on the polished stones which were before his lofty doors, white and glistening as with oil.'),(9115,' On these of old was wont to sit Neleus, the peer of the gods in counsel; '),(9116,' but he ere this had been stricken by fate and had gone to the house of Hades, and now there sat upon them in his turn Nestor of Gerenia, the warder of the Achaeans, holding a sceptre in his hands.'),(9117,' About him his sons gathered in a throng as they came forth from their chambers, Echephron and Stratius and Perseus and Aretus and godlike Thrasymedes; '),(9118,' and to these thereafter came as the sixth the lord Peisistratus. And they led godlike Telemachus and made him sit beside them;'),(9119,' and the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, was first to speak among them:'),(9120,'\n“Quickly, my dear children, fulfil my desire, that first of all the gods I may propitiate Athena,  who came to me in manifest presence to the rich feast of the god. '),(9121,'Come now, let one go to the plain for a heifer, that she may come speedily, and that the neat herd may drive her; '),(9122,'and let one go to the black ship of great-hearted Telemachus and bring all his comrades, and let him leave two men only; '),(9123,' and let one again bid the goldsmith Laerces come hither, that he may overlay the heifer\'s horns with gold. '),(9124,'And do ye others abide here together; and bid the handmaids within to make ready a feast throughout our glorious halls, to fetch seats, and logs to set on either side of the altar, and to bring clear water.\"'),(9125,'  So he spoke, and they all set busily to work. '),(9126,'The heifer came from the plain and from the swift, shapely ship came the comrades of great-hearted Telemachus; the smith came, bearing in his hands his tools of bronze, the implements of his craft, anvil and hammer and well-made tongs,  wherewith he wrought the gold; '),(9127,' and Athena came to accept the sacrifice.'),(9128,' Then the old man, Nestor, the driver of chariots, gave gold,  '),(9129,' and the smith prepared it, and overlaid therewith the horns of the heifer, that the goddess might rejoice when she beheld the offering.'),(9130,' And Stratius and goodly Echephron led the heifer by the horns, '),(9131,'  and Aretus came from the chamber, bringing them water for the hands in a basin embossed with flowers, and in the other hand he held barley grains in a basket; and Thrasymedes, steadfast in fight, stood by, holding in his hands a sharp axe, to fell the heifer; '),(9132,' and Perseus held the bowl for the blood. '),(9133,'Then the old man, Nestor, driver of chariots,  began the opening rite of hand-washing and sprinkling with barley grains, and earnestly he prayed to Athena, cutting off as first offering the hair from the head, and casting it into the fire. '),(9134,' \nNow when they had prayed, and had strewn the barley grains, straightway the son of Nestor, Thrasymedes, high of heart, came near and dealt the blow; '),(9135,'and the axe cut through the sinews  of the neck, and loosened the strength of the heifer. '),(9136,'Then the women raised the sacred cry, the daughters and the sons\' wives and the revered wife of Nestor, Eurydice, the eldest of the daughters of Clymenus, '),(9137,' and the men raised the heifer\'s head from the broad-wayed earth and held it,'),(9138,' and Peisistratus, leader of men, cut the throat.'),(9139,'  And when the black blood had flowed from her and the life had left the bones, at once they cut up the body and straightway cut out the thigh-pieces all in due order, and covered them with a double layer of fat, and laid raw flesh upon them.'),(9140,' Then the old man burned them on billets of wood, and poured over them sparkling wine,'),(9141,'  and beside him the young men held in their hands the five-pronged forks. '),(9142,'But when the thigh-pieces were wholly burned, and they had tasted the inner parts, they cut up the rest and spitted and roasted it, holding the pointed spits in their hands.'),(9143,'\nMeanwhile the fair Polycaste,  the youngest daughter of Nestor, son of Neleus, bathed Telemachus.'),(9144,' And when she had bathed him and anointed him richly with oil, and had cast about him a fair cloak and a tunic, forth from the bath he came in form like unto the immortals;'),(9145,' and he went and sat down by Nestor, the shepherd of the people.'),(9146,' Now when they had roasted the outer flesh and had drawn it off the spits, they sat down and feasted, '),(9147,' and worthy men waited on them, pouring wine into golden cups.'),(9148,' But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, was first to speak, saying:'),(9149,'\n  “My sons, up, yoke for Telemachus horses with beautiful mane beneath the car, that he may get forward on his journey.\"'),(9150,'So he spoke, and they readily hearkened and obeyed; and quickly they yoked beneath the car the swift horses.'),(9151,' And the housewife placed in the car bread and wine  and dainties, such as kings, fostered of Zeus, are wont to eat.'),(9152,' Then Telemachus mounted the beautiful car,'),(9153,' and Peisistratus, son of Nestor, a leader of men, mounted beside him, and took the reins in his hands. He touched the horses with the whip to start them, and nothing loath the pair sped on  to the plain, and left the steep citadel of Pylos.'),(9154,'So all day long they shook the yoke which they bore about their necks.'),(9155,' Now the sun set and all the ways grew dark. And they came to Pherae, to the house of Diocles, son of Ortilochus, whom Alpheus begot.'),(9156,'   There they spent the night, and before them he set the entertainment due to strangers.'),(9157,'So soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, they yoked the horses and mounted the inlaid car, '),(9158,'and drove forth from the gateway and the echoing portico.'),(9159,' Then Peisistratus touched the horses with the whip to start them, and nothing loath the pair sped onward.'),(9160,'  So they came to the wheat-bearing plain, and thereafter pressed on toward their journey\'s end,'),(9161,'so well did their swift horses bear them on.'),(9162,' And the sun set and all the ways grew dark.'),(9163,' And they came to the hollow land of Lacedaemon with its many ravines, and drove to the palace of glorious Menelaus.'),(9164,' Him they found giving a marriage feast to his many kinsfolk for his noble son and daughter within his house.'),(9165,' His daughter he was sending to the son of Achilles, breaker of the ranks of men,'),(9166,'for in the land of Troy he first had promised and pledged that he would give her, and now the gods were bringing their marriage to pass.'),(9167,' Her then he was sending forth with horses and chariots to go her way to the glorious city of the Myrmidons, over whom her lord was king; '),(9168,' but for his son he was bringing to his home from Sparta the daughter of Alector, even for the stalwart Megapenthes, who was his son well-beloved, born of a slave woman;'),(9169,' for to Helen the gods vouchsafed issue no more after that she had at the first borne her lovely child, Hermione, who had the beauty of golden Aphrodite. '),(9170,' So they were feasting in the great high-roofed hall, the neighbors and kinsfolk of glorious Menelaus, and making merry;'),(9171,'and among them a divine minstrel was singing to the lyre, and two tumblers whirled up and down through the midst of them, as he began his song.'),(9172,' Then the two, the prince Telemachus and the glorious son of Nestor, halted at the gateway of the palace, they and their two horses.'),(9173,'And the lord Eteoneus came forth and saw them, the busy squire of glorious Menelaus; and he went through the hall to bear the tidings to the shepherd of the people.  So he came near and spoke to him winged words:'),(9174,'“Here are two strangers, Menelaus, fostered of Zeus, two men that are like the seed of great Zeus.'),(9175,' But tell me, shall we unyoke for them their swift horses, or send them on their way to some other host, who will give them entertainment?”'),(9176,' Then, stirred to sore displeasure, fair-haired Menelaus spoke to him:'),(9177,'“Aforetime thou was not wont to be a fool, Eteoneus, son of Boethous,'),(9178,'but now like a child thou talkest folly.'),(9179,' Surely we two ate full often hospitable cheer of other men, ere we came hither in the hope that Zeus  would hereafter grant us respite from sorrow.'),(9180,'Nay, unyoke the strangers\' horses, and lead the men forward into the house, that they may feast.”'),(9181,'So he spoke, and the other hastened through the hall, and called to the other busy squires to follow along with him. '),(9182,'They loosed the sweating horses from beneath the yoke  and tied them at the stalls of the horses, and flung before them spelt, and mixed therewith white barley. Then they tilted the chariot against the bright entrance walls, and led the men into the divine palace.'),(9183,' But at the sight they marvelled as they passed through the palace of the king, fostered of Zeus;'),(9184,' for there was a gleam as of sun or moon over the high-roofed house of glorious Menelaus.'),(9185,'But when they had satisfied their eyes with gazing they went into the polished baths and bathed. '),(9186,' And when the maids had bathed them and anointed them with oil,  and had cast about them fleecy cloaks and tunics, they sat down on chairs beside Menelaus, son of Atreus.'),(9187,' Then a handmaid brought water for the hands in a fair pitcher of gold, and poured it over a silver basin for them to wash,'),(9188,' and beside them drew up a polished table.'),(9189,'  And the grave housewife brought and set before them bread, and therewith dainties in abundance, giving freely of her store.'),(9190,'And a carver lifted up and placed before them platters of all manner of meats, and set by them golden goblets. '),(9191,'Then fair-haired Menelaus greeted the two and said:'),(9192,' “Take of the food, and be glad,'),(9193,'and then when you have supped, we will ask you who among men you are;'),(9194,'for in you two the breed of your sires is not lost, but ye are of the breed of men that are sceptred kings, fostered of Zeus; for base churls could not beget such sons as you.”'),(9195,' So saying he took in his hands roast meat and set it before them, even the fat ox-chine which they had set before himself as a mess of honor.'),(9196,' So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them.'),(9197,' But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, lo, then Telemachus spoke to the son of Nestor,  holding his head close to him, that the others might not hear:'),(9198,'“Son of Nestor, dear to this heart of mine, mark the flashing of bronze throughout the echoing halls, and the flashing of gold, of electrum, of silver, and of ivory.'),(9199,' Of such sort, methinks, is the court of Olympian Zeus within,  such untold wealth is here; '),(9200,'amazement holds me as I look.”'),(9201,'Now as he spoke fair-haired Menelaus heard him, and he spoke and addressed them with winged words:'),(9202,'“Dear children, with Zeus verily no mortal man could vie,'),(9203,' for everlasting are his halls and his possessions;'),(9204,' but of men another might vie with me in wealth or haply might not.'),(9205,' For of a truth after many woes and wide wanderings I brought my wealth home in my ships and came in the eighth year. Over Cyprus and Phoenicia I wandered, and Egypt, and I came to the Ethiopians and the Sidonians and the Erembi,  and to Libya, where the lambs are horned from their birth.'),(9206,' For there the ewes bear their young thrice within the full course of the year; '),(9207,'there neither master nor shepherd has any lack of cheese or of meat or of sweet milk, but the flocks ever yield milk to the milking the year through.'),(9208,'  While I wandered in those lands gathering much livelihood, meanwhile another slew my brother by stealth and at unawares, by the guile of his accursed wife.'),(9209,' Thus, thou mayest see, I have no joy in being lord of this wealth;'),(9210,'and you may well have heard of this from your fathers, whosoever they  may be, for full much did I suffer, and let fall into ruin a stately house and one stored with much goodly treasure.'),(9211,'Would that I dwelt in my halls with but a third part of this wealth, and that those men were safe who then perished in the broad land of Troy far from horse-pasturing Argos. '),(9212,' And yet, though I often sit in my halls weeping and sorrowing for them all—one moment indeed I ease my heart with weeping, and then again I cease,'),(9213,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 4.103'),(9214,'yet for them all I mourn not so much, despite my grief,  as for one only, who makes me to loathe both sleep and food, when I think of him; for no one of the Achaeans toiled so much as Odysseus toiled and endured. '),(9215,'But to himself, as it seems, his portion was to be but woe, and for me there is sorrow never to be forgotten for him, in that he is gone so long, nor do we know aught  whether he be alive or dead.'),(9216,' Mourned is he, I ween, by the old man Laertes, and by constant Penelope, and by Telemachus, whom he left a new-born child in his house.”'),(9217,'So he spoke, and in Telemachus he roused the desire to weep for his father.'),(9218,' Tears from his eyelids he let fall upon the ground, when he heard his father\'s name,  and with both hands held up his purple cloak before his eyes.'),(9219,'And Menelaus noted him, and debated in mind and heart whether he should leave him to speak of his father himself, or whether he should first question him and prove him in each thing.'),(9220,' While he pondered thus in mind and heart, forth then from her fragrant high-roofed chamber came Helen, like Artemis of the golden arrows;'),(9221,'and with her came Adraste, and placed for her a chair, beautifully wrought, and Alcippe brought a rug of soft wool  and Phylo a silver basket, which Alcandre had given her, the wife of Polybus, who dwelt in Thebes of Egypt, where greatest store of wealth is laid up in men\'s houses.'),(9222,' He gave to Menelaus two silver baths and two tripods and ten talents of gold. '),(9223,' And besides these, his wife gave to Helen also beautiful gifts,—'),(9224,'a golden distaff and a basket with wheels beneath did she give, a basket of silver, and with gold were the rims thereof gilded.'),(9225,' This then the handmaid, Phylo, brought and placed beside her, filled with finely-spun yarn,'),(9226,'and across it  was laid the distaff laden with violet-dark wool.'),(9227,'So Helen sat down upon the chair, and below was a footstool for the feet;'),(9228,' and at once she questioned her husband on each matter, and said:'),(9229,'“Do we know, Menelaus, fostered of Zeus, who these men declare themselves to be who have come to our house? '),(9230,' Nay, my heart bids me speak.'),(9231,' Nay, my heart bids me speak.'),(9232,' For never yet, I declare, saw I one so like another, whether man or woman—amazement holds me, as I look—as this man is like the son of great-hearted Odysseus, even Telemachus, whom that warrior left a new-born child in his house, when for the sake of shameless me ye Achaeans came up under the walls of Troy, pondering in your hearts fierce war.” '),(9233,' \nThen fair-haired Menelaus answered her:'),(9234,' “Even so do I myself now note it, wife, as thou markest the likeness.'),(9235,'Such were his feet, such his hands,  and the glances of his eyes, and his head and hair above.'),(9236,'And verily but now, as I made mention of Odysseus and was telling of all the woe and toil he endured for my sake, this youth let fall a bitter tear from beneath his brows, holding up his purple cloak before his eyes.”'),(9237,' Then Peisistratus, son of Nestor, answered him:'),(9238,'“Menelaus, son of Atreus, fostered of Zeus, leader of hosts, his son indeed this youth is, as thou sayest.'),(9239,'But he is of prudent mind and feels shame at heart thus on his first coming to make a show of forward words  in the presence of thee, in whose voice we both take delight as in a god\'s. '),(9240,'But the horseman, Nestor of Gerenia, sent me forth to go with him as his guide,'),(9241,'for he was eager to see thee, that thou mightest put in his heart some word or some deed. '),(9242,'For many sorrows has a son  in his halls when his father is gone, when there are none other to be his helpers, even as it is now with Telemachus; his father is gone, and there are no others among the people who might ward off ruin.”'),(9243,'Then fair-haired Menelaus answered him and said: '),(9244,'“Lo now, verily is there come to my house the son of a man well-beloved,  who for my sake endured many toils. '),(9245,'And I thought that if he came back I should give him welcome beyond all the other Argives, if Olympian Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, had granted to us two a return in our swift ships over the sea. '),(9246,'And in Argos I would have given him a city to dwell in, and would have built him a house,  when I had brought him from Ithaca with his goods and his son and all his people, driving out the dwellers of some one city among those that lie round about and obey me myself as their lord.'),(9247,'Then, living here, should we ofttimes have met together,'),(9248,'nor would aught have parted us, loving and joying in one another,  until the black cloud of death enfolded us.'),(9249,'Howbeit of this, methinks, the god himself must have been jealous, who to that hapless man alone vouchsafed no return.” '),(9250,'So he spoke, and in them all aroused the desire of lament.'),(9251,' Argive Helen wept, the daughter of Zeus,  Telemachus wept, and Menelaus, son of Atreus, nor could the son of Nestor keep his eyes tearless.'),(9252,' For he thought in his heart of peerless Antilochus, whom the glorious son of the bright Dawn had slain.'),(9253,'Thinking of him, he spoke winged words:'),(9254,' “Son of Atreus, old Nestor used ever to say that thou wast wise above all men, whenever we made mention of thee in his halls and questioned one another.'),(9255,'And now, if it may in any wise be, hearken to me, '),(9256,'for I take no joy in weeping at supper time,—and moreover  early dawn will soon be here. '),(9257,'I count it indeed no blame to weep for any mortal who has died and met his fate.'),(9258,'Yea, this is the only due we pay to miserable mortals, to cut the hair and let a tear fall from the cheeks.'),(9259,'For a brother of mine, too, is dead, nowise the meanest  of the Argives,'),(9260,'and thou mayest well have known him.'),(9261,'As for me, I never met him nor saw him;'),(9262,'but men say that Antilochus was above all others pre-eminent in speed of foot and as a warrior.”'),(9263,'Then fair-haired Menelaus answered him and said:'),(9264,' “My friend, truly thou hast said all that a wise man  might say or do, even one that was older than thou;'),(9265,' for from such a father art thou sprung, wherefore thou dost even speak wisely. Easily known is the seed of that man for whom the son of Cronos spins the thread of good fortune at marriage and at birth, even as now he has granted to Nestor throughout all his days continually that  he should himself reach a sleek old age in his halls, and that his sons in their turn should be wise and most valiant with the spear.'),(9266,'But we will cease the weeping which but now was made, and let us once more think of our supper, and let them pour water over our hands.'),(9267,' Tales there will be in the morning also  for Telemachus and me to tell to one another to the full.”'),(9268,'So he spoke, and Asphalion poured water over their hands, the busy squire of glorious Menelaus.'),(9269,'And they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them. '),(9270,' \nThen Helen, daughter of Zeus, took other counsel.'),(9271,' Straightway she cast into the wine of which they were drinking a drug to quiet all pain and strife, and bring forgetfulness of every ill. '),(9272,'Whoso should drink this down, when it is mingled in the bowl, would not in the course of that day let a tear fall down over his cheeks,  no, not though his mother and father should lie there dead, or though before his face men should slay with the sword his brother or dear son, and his own eyes beheld it.'),(9273,'Such cunning drugs had the daughter of Zeus, drugs of healing, which Polydamna, the wife of Thon, had given her, a woman of Egypt, for there the earth, the giver of grain, bears greatest store  of drugs, many that are healing when mixed, and many that are baneful;'),(9274,'there every man is a physician, wise above human kind;'),(9275,'for they are of the race of Paeeon.'),(9276,'Now when she had cast in the drug, and had bidden pour forth the wine, again she made answer, and said:'),(9277,' “Menelaus, son of Atreus, fostered of Zeus, and ye that are here, sons of noble men—'),(9278,'though now to one and now to another Zeus gives good and ill,'),(9279,'for he can do all things,—'),(9280,'now verily sit ye in the halls and feast, and take ye joy in telling tales,'),(9281,'for I will tell what fitteth the time.'),(9282,' All things I cannot tell or recount, even all the labours of Odysseus of the steadfast heart;'),(9283,'but what a thing was this which that mighty man wrought and endured in the land of the Trojans, where you Achaens suffered woes!'),(9284,'Marring his own body with cruel blows,  and flinging a wretched garment about his shoulders, in the fashion of a slave he entered the broad-wayed city of the foe,'),(9285,'and he hid himself under the likeness of another, a beggar, he who was in no wise such an one at the ships of the Achaeans.'),(9286,'In this likeness he entered the city of the Trojans, and all of them were but as babes.'),(9287,'  I alone recognized him in this disguise, and questioned him,'),(9288,'but he in his cunning sought to avoid me. '),(9289,'Howbeit when I was bathing him and anointing him with oil, and had put on him raiment, and sworn a mighty oath not to make him known among the Trojans as Odysseus  before that he reached the swift ships and the huts, then at length he told me all the purpose of the Achaeans.'),(9290,'And when he had slain many of the Trojans with the long sword, he returned to the company of the Argives and brought back plentiful tidings. '),(9291,'Then the other Trojan women wailed aloud,'),(9292,'but my soul  was glad, for already my heart was turned to go back to my home, and I groaned for the blindness that Aphrodite gave me, when she led me thither from my dear native land, forsaking my child and my bridal chamber, and my husband, a man who lacked nothing, whether in wisdom or in comeliness.” '),(9293,' Then fair-haired Menelaus answered her and said:'),(9294,'“Aye verily, all this, wife, hast thou spoken aright.'),(9295,'Ere now have I come to know the counsel and the mind of many warriors, and have travelled over the wide earth,'),(9296,'but never yet have mine eyes beheld such an one  as was Odysseus of the steadfast heart.'),(9297,'What a thing was this, too, which that mighty man wrought and endured in the carven horse, wherein all we chiefs of the Argives were sitting, bearing to the Trojans death and fate!'),(9298,'Then thou camest thither,'),(9299,'and it must be that thou wast bidden  by some god, who wished to grant glory to the Trojans,'),(9300,'and godlike Deiphobus followed thee on thy way. '),(9301,'Thrice didst thou go about the hollow ambush, trying it with thy touch, and thou didst name aloud the chieftains of the Danaans by their names, likening thy voice to the voices of the wives of all the Argives.'),(9302,' Now I and the son of Tydeus and goodly Odysseus sat there in the midst and heard how thou didst call,'),(9303,'and we two were eager to rise up and come forth, or else to answer straightway from within,'),(9304,'but Odysseus held us back and stayed us, despite our eagerness.'),(9305,' Then all the other sons of the Achaeans held their peace, but Anticlus alone was fain to speak and answer thee;'),(9306,'but Odysseus firmly closed his mouth with strong hands, and saved all the Achaeans,'),(9307,'and held him thus until Pallas Athena led thee away.”'),(9308,' Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(9309,'“Menelaus, son of Atreus, fostered of Zeus, leader of hosts, all the more grievous is it;'),(9310,'for in no wise did this ward off from him woeful destruction, nay, not though the heart within him had been of iron.'),(9311,'But come, send us to bed, that lulled now  by sweet sleep we may rest and take our joy.”'),(9312,'Thus he spoke, and Argive Helen bade her handmaids place bedsteads beneath the portico, and to lay on them fair purple blankets, and to spread there over coverlets, and on these to put fleecy cloaks for clothing.'),(9313,' But the maids went forth from the hall with torches in their hands and strewed the couch,'),(9314,'and a herald led forth the guests.'),(9315,'So they slept there in the fore-hall of the palace, the prince Telemachus and the glorious son of Nestor;'),(9316,'but the son of Atreus slept in the inmost chamber of the lofty house,  and beside him lay long-robed Helen, peerless among women.'),(9317,'So soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, up from his bed arose Menelaus, good at the war-cry, and put on his clothing. About his shoulders he slung his sharp sword, and beneath his shining feet bound his fair sandals,  and went forth from his chamber like unto a god to look upon. Then he sat down beside Telemachus, and spoke, and addressed him:'),(9318,'“What need has brought thee hither, prince Telemachus, to goodly Lacedaemon over the broad back of the sea?'),(9319,'Tell me the truth of this.” '),(9320,'Tell me the truth of this.” '),(9321,' Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(9322,'“Menelaus, son of Atreus, fostered of Zeus, leader of hosts, I came if haply thou mightest tell me some tidings of my father.'),(9323,'My home is being devoured and my rich lands are ruined; with men that are foes my house is filled, who are ever  slaying my thronging sheep and my sleek kine of shambling gait, even the wooers of my mother, overweening in their insolence.'),(9324,'Therefore am I now come to thy knees, if perchance thou wilt be willing to tell me of his woeful death, whether thou sawest it haply with thine own eyes, or didst hear from some other the story  of his wanderings;'),(9325,'for beyond all men did his mother bear him to sorrow.'),(9326,'And do thou no wise out of ruth or pity for me speak soothing words, but tell me truly how thou didst come to behold him.'),(9327,'I beseech thee, if ever my father, noble Odysseus, promised aught to thee of word or deed and fulfilled it  in the land of the Trojans, where you Achaeans suffered woes, be mindful of it now, I pray thee, and tell me the truth.”'),(9328,'Then, stirred to sore displeasure, fair-haired Menelaus spoke to him:'),(9329,'“Out upon them, for verily in the bed of a man of valiant heart were they fain to lie, who are themselves cravens.'),(9330,' Even as when in the thicket-lair of a mighty lion a hind has laid to sleep her new-born suckling fawns, and roams over the mountain slopes and grassy vales seeking pasture, and then the lion comes to his lair and upon the two lets loose a cruel doom,  so will Odysseus let loose a cruel doom upon these men.'),(9331,'I would, O father Zeus and Athena and Apollo, that in such strength as when once in fair-stablished Lesbos he rose up and wrestled a match with Philomeleides and threw him mightily, and all the Achaeans rejoiced,  even in such strength Odysseus might come among the wooers;'),(9332,'then should they all find swift destruction and bitterness in their wooing. '),(9333,'But in this matter of which thou dost ask and beseech me, verily I will not swerve aside to speak of other things, nor will I deceive thee; but of all that the unerring old man of the sea told me. '),(9334,'“In Egypt, eager though I was to journey hither, the gods still held me back, because I offered not to them hecatombs that bring fulfillment,'),(9335,'and the gods ever wished that men should be mindful of their commands.'),(9336,'Now there is an island in the surging sea  in front of Egypt, and men call it Pharos, distant as far as a hollow ship runs in a whole day when the shrill wind blows fair behind her.'),(9337,'Therein is a harbor with good anchorage, whence men launch the shapely ships into the sea, when they have drawn supplies of black water.'),(9338,' There for twenty days the gods kept me, nor ever did the winds that blow over the deep spring up, which speed men\'s ships over the broad back of the sea.'),(9339,'And now would all my stores have been spent and the strength of my men, had not one of the gods taken pity on me and saved me, even Eidothea,  daughter of mighty Proteus, the old man of the sea; '),(9340,'for her heart above all others had I moved.'),(9341,'She met me as I wandered alone apart from my comrades,'),(9342,'who were ever roaming about the island, fishing with bent hooks, for hunger pinched their bellies;'),(9343,' and she came close to me, and spoke, and said:'),(9344,'“‘Art thou so very foolish, stranger, and slack of wit, or art thou of thine own will remiss, and hast pleasure in suffering woes?'),(9345,'So long art thou pent in the isle and canst find no sign of deliverance and the heart of thy comrades grows faint.’'),(9346,' “So she spoke, and I made answer and said: '),(9347,'‘I will speak out and tell thee, whosoever among goddesses thou art, that in no wise am I pent here of mine own will, but it must be that I have sinned against the immortals, who hold broad heaven.'),(9348,'But do thou tell me—for the gods know all things—  who of the immortals fetters me here, and has hindered me from my path, and tell me of my return, how I may go over the teeming deep.’'),(9349,'“So I spoke, and the beautiful goddess straightway made answer:'),(9350,'‘Then verily, stranger, will I frankly tell thee all. '),(9351,'There is wont to come hither the unerring old man of the sea,  immortal Proteus of Egypt, who knows the depths of every sea, and is the servant of Poseidon.'),(9352,'He, they say, is my father that begat me. '),(9353,'If thou couldst in any wise lie in wait and catch him, he will tell thee thy way and the measure of thy path,  and of thy return, how thou mayest go over the teeming deep.'),(9354,'Aye, and he will tell thee, thou fostered of Zeus, if so thou wilt, what evil and what good has been wrought in thy halls, while thou hast been gone on thy long and grievous way.’'),(9355,'“So she spoke, and I made answer and said: '),(9356,' ‘Do thou thyself now devise a means of lying in wait for the divine old man, lest haply he see me beforehand and being ware of my purpose avoid me.'),(9357,' For hard is a god for a mortal man to master.’ '),(9358,' \n“So I spoke, and the beautiful goddess straightway made answer:'),(9359,' ‘Then verily, stranger, will I frankly tell thee all.'),(9360,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 4.400-4.403'),(9361,'and around him the seals, the brood of the fair daughter of the sea,  sleep in a herd, coming forth from the gray water, and bitter is the smell they breathe of the depths of the sea.'),(9362,'Thither will I lead thee at break of day and lay you all in a row;'),(9363,'for do thou choose carefully three of thy companions, who are the best thou hast in thy well-benched ships.'),(9364,' And I will tell thee all the wizard wiles of that old man. '),(9365,'First he will count the seals, and go over them;'),(9366,'but when he has told them all off by fives, and beheld them, he will lay himself down in their midst, as a shepherd among his flocks of sheep.'),(9367,'Now so soon as you see him laid to rest,  thereafter let your hearts be filled with strength and courage, and do you hold him there despite his striving and struggling to escape.'),(9368,'For try he will, and will assume all manner of shapes of all things that move upon the earth, and of water, and of wondrous blazing fire.'),(9369,'Yet do ye hold him unflinchingly and grip him yet the more. '),(9370,' But when at length of his own will he speaks and questions thee in that shape in which you saw him laid to rest, then, hero, stay thy might, and set the old man free, and ask him who of the gods is wroth with thee, and of thy return, how thou mayest go over the teeming deep.’'),(9371,' “So saying she plunged beneath the surging sea,'),(9372,'but I went to my ships, where they stood on the sand,'),(9373,'and many things did my heart darkly ponder as I went.'),(9374,'But when I had come down to the ship and to the sea, and we had made ready our supper, and immortal night had come on,'),(9375,' then we lay down to rest on the shore of the sea.'),(9376,'And as soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, I went along the shore of the broad-wayed sea, praying earnestly to the gods; '),(9377,'and I took with me three of my comrades, in whom I trusted most for every adventure. '),(9378,' “She meanwhile had plunged beneath the broad bosom of the sea, and had brought forth from the deep the skins of four seals,'),(9379,'and she devised a plot against her father.'),(9380,'and she devised a plot against her father.'),(9381,'She had scooped out lairs in the sand of the sea, and sat waiting;'),(9382,'and we came very near to her, '),(9383,' and she made us to lie down in a row, and cast a skin over each.'),(9384,'Then would our ambush have proved most terrible,'),(9385,'for terribly did the deadly stench of the brine-bred seals distress us—'),(9386,' who would lay him down by a beast of the sea?—'),(9387,'but she of herself delivered us, and devised a great boon; '),(9388,' she brought and placed ambrosia of a very sweet fragrance beneath each man\'s nose, and destroyed the stench of the beast.'),(9389,'So all the morning we waited with steadfast heart,'),(9390,'and the seals came forth from the sea in throngs.'),(9391,'These then laid them down in rows along the shore of the sea,'),(9392,' and at noon the old man came forth from the sea and found the fatted seals; and he went over all, and counted their number.'),(9393,'Among the creatures he counted us first, nor did his heart guess that there was guile;'),(9394,'and then he too laid him down. '),(9395,'Thereat we rushed upon him with a shout, and  threw our arms about him,'),(9396,'nor did that old man forget his crafty wiles. Nay, at the first he turned into a bearded lion, and then into a serpent, and a leopard, and a huge boar; '),(9397,'then he turned into flowing water, and into a tree, high and leafy;'),(9398,'but we held on unflinchingly with steadfast heart.'),(9399,' But when at last that old man, skilled in wizard arts, grew weary, then he questioned me, and spoke, and said:'),(9400,'“‘Who of the gods, son of Atreus, took counsel with thee that thou mightest lie in wait for me, and take me against my will?'),(9401,'Of what hast thou need?’'),(9402,'“So he spoke, and I made answer, and said:'),(9403,'  ‘Thou knowest, old man—why dost thou seek to put me off with this question?—'),(9404,'how long a time I am pent in this isle, and can find no sign of deliverance, and my heart grows faint within me.'),(9405,' But do thou tell me—for the gods know all things—who of the immortals fetters me here, and has hindered me from my path, and tell me  of my return, how I may go over the teeming deep.’'),(9406,'“So I spoke, and he straightway made answer, and said:'),(9407,' ‘Nay, surely thou oughtest to have made fair offerings to Zeus and the other gods before embarking, that with greatest speed thou mightest have come to thy country, sailing over the wine-dark sea.'),(9408,'  For it is not thy fate to see thy friends, and reach thy well-built house and thy native land, before that thou hast once more gone to the waters of Aegyptus, the heaven-fed river,'),(9409,' and hast offered holy hecatombs to the immortal gods who hold broad heaven. '),(9410,' \n“So he spoke, and my spirit was broken within me, for that he bade me go again over the misty deep to Aegyptus, a long and weary way.'),(9411,' Yet even so I made answer, and said:'),(9412,' “‘All this will I perform, old man, even as thou dost bid.'),(9413,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 4.486-4.490'),(9414,'“So I spoke, and he straightway made answer, and said: '),(9415,'‘Son of Atreus, why dost thou question me of this?'),(9416,'In no wise does it behove thee to know, or to learn my mind;'),(9417,'nor, methinks, wilt thou long be free from tears, when thou hast heard all aright.'),(9418,' For many of them were slain, and many were left;'),(9419,'but two chieftains alone of the brazen-coated Achaeans perished on their homeward way '),(9420,'（ as for the fighting, thou thyself wast there）,'),(9421,'and one, I ween, still lives, and is held back on the broad deep.'),(9422,'“‘Aias truly was lost amid his long-oared ships.'),(9423,' Upon the great rocks of Gyrae Poseidon at first drove him, but saved him from the sea;'),(9424,'and he would have escaped his doom, hated of Athena though he was, had he not uttered a boastful word in great blindness of heart.'),(9425,'He declared that it was in spite of the gods that he had escaped the great gulf of the sea; '),(9426,' and Poseidon heard his boastful speech,'),(9427,'and straightway took his trident in his mighty hands, and smote the rock of Gyrae and clove it in sunder.'),(9428,'And one part abode in its place, but the sundered part fell into the sea, even that on which Aias sat at the first when his heart was greatly blinded,'),(9429,' and it bore him down into the boundless surging deep.'),(9430,'So there he perished, when he had drunk the salt water. '),(9431,' \n“‘But thy brother escaped, indeed, the fates and shunned them with his hollow ships,'),(9432,'for queenly Hera saved him.'),(9433,'But when he was now about  to reach the steep height of Malea, then the storm-wind caught him up and bore him over the teeming deep, groaning heavily, to the border of the land, where aforetime Thyestes dwelt, but where now dwelt Thyestes\' son Aegisthus.'),(9434,'But when from hence too a safe return was shewed him,  and the gods changed the course of the wind that it blew fair, and they reached home, then verily with rejoicing did Agamemnon set foot on his native land, and he clasped his land and kissed it,'),(9435,'and many were the hot tears that streamed from his eyes, for welcome to him was the sight of his land.'),(9436,'Now from his place of watch a watchman saw him, whom  guileful Aegisthus took and set there, promising him as a reward two talents of gold;'),(9437,'and he had been keeping guard for a year, lest Agamemnon should pass by him unseen, and be mindful of his furious might.'),(9438,'So he went to the palace to bear the tidings to the shepherd of the people,'),(9439,'and Aegisthus straightway planned a treacherous device.'),(9440,' He chose out twenty men, the best in the land, and set them to lie in wait, but on the further side of the hall he bade prepare a feast. '),(9441,'Then he went with chariot and horses to summon Agamemnon, shepherd of the people, his mind pondering a dastardly deed.'),(9442,'So he brought him up all unaware of his doom,  and when he had feasted him he slew him, as one slays an ox at the stall.'),(9443,'And not one of the comrades of the son of Atreus was left, of all that followed him, nor one of the men of Aegisthus, but they were all slain in the halls.’'),(9444,'“So he spoke, and my spirit was broken within me, and I wept, as I sat on the sands, nor had my heart  any longer desire to live and to behold the light of the sun.'),(9445,'But when I had had my fill of weeping and writhing, then the unerring old man of the sea said to me:'),(9446,'“‘No more, son of Atreus, do thou weep long time thus without ceasing, for in it we shall find no help.'),(9447,'Nay, rather, with all the speed thou canst,  strive that thou mayest come to thy native land, '),(9448,'for either thou wilt find Aegisthus alive, or haply Orestes may have forestalled thee and slain him, and thou mayest chance upon his funeral feast.’'),(9449,'“So he spoke, and my heart and spirit were again warmed with comfort in my breast despite my grief,  and I spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(9450,'“‘Of these men now I know,'),(9451,'but do thou name the third, who he is that still lives, and is held back upon the broad sea, or is haply dead. '),(9452,' Fain would I hear, despite my grief.’ '),(9453,' \n“So I spoke, and he straightway made answer, and said:'),(9454,'  ‘It is the son of Laertes, whose home is in Ithaca.'),(9455,'Him I saw in an island, shedding big tears, in the halls of the nymph Calypso, who keeps him there perforce,'),(9456,'and he cannot come to his native land,'),(9457,'for he has at hand no ships with oars and no comrades  to send him on his way over the broad back of the sea.'),(9458,'But for thyself, Menelaus, fostered of Zeus, it is not ordained that thou shouldst die and meet thy fate in horse-pasturing Argos, but to the Elysian plain and the bounds of the earth will the immortals convey thee, where dwells fair-haired Rhadamanthus,  and where life is easiest for men.'),(9459,'No snow is there, nor heavy storm, nor ever rain, but ever does Ocean send up blasts of the shrill-blowing West Wind that they may give cooling to men;'),(9460,'for thou hast Helen to wife, and art in their eyes the husband of the daughter of Zeus.’'),(9461,' “So saying he plunged beneath the surging sea, '),(9462,'but I went to my ships with my god like comrades, and many things did my heart darkly ponder as I went. '),(9463,'But when I had come down to the ship and to the sea, and we had made ready our supper, and immortal night had come on,  then we lay down to rest on the shore of the sea.'),(9464,'And as soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, our ships first of all we drew down to the bright sea, and set the masts and the sails in the shapely ships, and the men, too, went on board and sat down upon the benches,'),(9465,' and sitting well in order smote the grey sea with their oars.'),(9466,'So back again to the waters of Aegyptus, the heaven-fed river, I sailed, and there moored my ships and offered hecatombs that bring fulfillment. '),(9467,'But when I had stayed the wrath of the gods that are forever, I heaped up a mound to Agamemnon, that his fame might be unquenchable.'),(9468,' Then, when I had made an end of this, I set out for home, and the immortals gave me a fair wind, and brought me swiftly to my dear native land.'),(9469,'But come now, tarry in my halls until the eleventh or the twelfth day be come.'),(9470,'Then will I send thee forth with honor and give thee splendid gifts,  three horses and a well-polished car;'),(9471,'and besides I will give thee a beautiful cup, that thou mayest pour libations to the immortal gods, and remember me all thy days.” '),(9472,' \nThen wise Telemachus answered him:'),(9473,' “Son of Atreus, keep me no long time here,  '),(9474,' for verily for a year would I be content to sit in thy house, nor would desire for home or parents come upon me; '),(9475,'for wondrous is the pleasure I take in listening to thy tales and thy speech.'),(9476,' But even now my comrades are chafing in sacred Pylos, '),(9477,'and thou art keeping me long time here.'),(9478,' And whatsoever gift thou wouldest give me, let it be some treasure;'),(9479,'but horses will I not take to Ithaca, but will leave them here for thyself to delight in, '),(9480,' for thou art lord of a wide plain, wherein is lotus in abundance, and galingale and wheat and spelt, and broad-eared white barley.'),(9481,'  But in Ithaca there are no widespread courses nor aught of meadow-land.'),(9482,'It is a pasture-land of goats and pleasanter than one that pastures horses.'),(9483,'For not one of the islands that lean upon the sea is fit for driving horses, or rich in meadows,'),(9484,' and Ithaca least of all.”'),(9485,'So he spoke, and Menelaus, good at the war-cry, smiled,  and stroked him with his hand, and spoke, and addressed him:'),(9486,'“Thou art of noble blood, dear child, that thou speakest thus.'),(9487,'for well I may.'),(9488,'for well I may.'),(9489,'Of all the gifts that lie stored as treasures in my house, I will give thee that one which is fairest and costliest.'),(9490,' I will give thee a well-wrought mixing bowl.'),(9491,'All of silver it is, and with gold are the rims thereof gilded, the work of Hephaestus;'),(9492,'and the warrior Phaedimus, king of the Sidonians, gave it me, when his house sheltered me as I came thither, '),(9493,'and now I am minded to give it to thee.”'),(9494,' Thus they spoke to one another, and meanwhile the banqueters came to the palace of the divine king.'),(9495,'They drove up sheep, and brought strengthening wine,'),(9496,' and their wives with beautiful veils sent them bread.'),(9497,'Thus they were busied about the feast in the halls. '),(9498,' \n  \n\n\n======================================================================\nk1k1\n======================================================================\n But the wooers in front of the palace of Odysseus were making merry, throwing the discus and the javelin in a levelled place, as their wont was, in insolence of heart;'),(9499,'and Antinous and godlike Eurymachus were sitting there, the leaders of the wooers, who in valiance were far the best of all. '),(9500,' To them Noemon, son of Phronius, drew near, and he questioned Antinous, and spoke, and said:'),(9501,'“Antinous, know we at all in our hearts, or know we not, when Telemachus will return from sandy Pylos?'),(9502,'He is gone, taking a ship of mine,'),(9503,' and I have need of her  to cross over to spacious Elis, where I have twelve brood mares, and at the teat sturdy mules as yet unbroken.'),(9504,'Of these I would fain drive one off and break him in.”'),(9505,'So he spoke, and they marvelled at heart,'),(9506,'for they did not deem that Telemachus had gone to Neleian Pylos, but that he was somewhere there  on his lands, among the flocks or with the swineherd.'),(9507,'Then Antinous, son of Eupeithes, spoke to him, saying: '),(9508,'“Tell me the truth; when did he go, and what youths went with him?'),(9509,'Were they chosen youths of Ithaca, or hirelings and slaves of his own?'),(9510,'Able would he be to accomplish even that.'),(9511,' And tell me this truly, that I may know full well. Was it perforce and against thy will that he took from thee the black ship? or didst thou give it him freely of thine own will, because he besought thee?”'),(9512,'Then Noemon, son of Phronius, answered him:'),(9513,'“I myself freely gave it him.'),(9514,'What else could any man do,  when a man like him, his heart laden with care, makes entreaty?'),(9515,'Hard it were to deny the gift.'),(9516,'The youths that are the noblest in the land after ourselves, even these have gone with him;'),(9517,'and among them I noted one going on board as their leader, Mentor, or a god, who was in all things like unto Mentor.'),(9518,' But at this I marvel. '),(9519,'I saw goodly Mentor here yesterday at early dawn; but at that time he embarked for Pylos.”'),(9520,'So saying he departed to his father\'s house, but of those two the proud hearts were angered.'),(9521,'The wooers they straightway made to sit down and cease from their games;'),(9522,' and among them spoke Antinous, son of Eupeithes, in displeasure;'),(9523,'and with rage was his black heart wholly filled, and his eyes were like blazing fire.'),(9524,'“Out upon him, verily a proud deed has been insolently brought to pass by Telemachus, even this journey,'),(9525,' and we deemed that he would never see it accomplished.'),(9526,' Forth in despite of all of us here the lad is gone without more ado, launching a ship, and choosing the best men in the land. and we deemed that he would never see it accomplished.'),(9527,' He will begin by and by to be our bane; '),(9528,'but to his own undoing may Zeus destroy his might before ever he reaches the measure of manhood.'),(9529,'But come, give me a swift ship and twenty men,  that I may watch in ambush for him as he passes in the strait between Ithaca and rugged Samos. Thus shall his voyaging in search of his father come to a sorry end.”'),(9530,'So he spoke, and they all praised his words, and bade him act.'),(9531,' And straightway they rose up and went to the house of Odysseus. '),(9532,' Now Penelope was no long time without knowledge of the plans which the wooers were plotting in the deep of their hearts; '),(9533,'for the herald Medon told her, who heard their counsel as he stood without the court '),(9534,'and they within were weaving their plot.'),(9535,'So he went through the hall to bear the tidings to Penelope;'),(9536,' and as he stepped across the threshold Penelope spoke to him and said:'),(9537,'“Herald, why have the lordly wooers sent thee forth?'),(9538,'Was it to tell the handmaids of divine Odysseus to cease from their tasks, and make ready a feast for them?'),(9539,'Never wooing any more, nor consorting together elsewhere,  may they now feast here their latest and their last—'),(9540,'even ye who are ever thronging here and wasting much livelihood, the wealth of wise Telemachus.'),(9541,' Surely ye hearkened not at all in olden days, when ye were children, when your fathers told what manner of man Odysseus was among them that begat you,  in that he wrought no wrong in deed or word to any man in the land, as the wont is of divine kings—'),(9542,'one man they hate and another they love.'),(9543,'Yet he never wrought iniquity at all to any man.'),(9544,'But your mind and your unseemly deeds  are plain to see, nor is there in after days any gratitude for good deeds done.”'),(9545,'Then Medon, wise of heart, answered her: '),(9546,'“I would, O queen, that this were the greatest evil.'),(9547,'But another greater far and more grievous are the wooers planning, which I pray that the son of Cronos may never bring to pass. '),(9548,'  They are minded to slay Telemachus with the sharp sword on his homeward way;'),(9549,'for he went in quest of tidings of his father to sacred Pylos and to goodly Lacedaemon.”'),(9550,'So he spoke, and her knees were loosened where she sat, and her heart melted. Long time she was speechless,'),(9551,'and both her eyes  were filled with tears, and the flow of her voice was checked.'),(9552,'But at last she made answer, and said to him:'),(9553,'“Herald, why is my son gone? '),(9554,'He had no need to go on board swift-faring ships, which serve men as horses of the deep, and cross over the wide waters of the sea.'),(9555,' Was it that not even his name should be left among men?”'),(9556,'Then Medon, wise of heart, answered her: '),(9557,'“I know not whether some god impelled him, or whether his own heart was moved to go to Pylos, that he might learn either of his father\'s return or what fate he had met.” '),(9558,' So he spoke, and departed through the house of Odysseus,'),(9559,'and on her fell a cloud of soul-consuming grief, and she had no more the heart to sit upon one of the many seats that were in the room, but down upon the threshold of her fair-wrought chamber she sank, moaning piteously,'),(9560,'and round about her wailed her handmaids,  even all that were in the house, both young and old.'),(9561,'Among these with sobs of lamentation spoke Penelope:'),(9562,'“Hear me, my friends,'),(9563,'for to me the Olympian has given sorrow above all the women who were bred and born with me.'),(9564,'For long since I lost my noble husband of the lion heart,  pre-eminent in all manner of worth among the Danaans, my noble husband, whose fame is wide through Hellas and mid-Argos.'),(9565,'And now again my well-loved son have the storm-winds swept away from our halls without tidings, nor did I hear of his setting forth. '),(9566,'Cruel, that ye are! Not even you took thought, any one of you,  to rouse me from my couch, though in your hearts ye knew full well when he went on board the hollow black ship. '),(9567,'For had I learned that he was pondering this journey, he should verily have stayed here, how eager soever to be gone, or he should have left me dead in the halls.'),(9568,' But now let one hasten to call hither the aged Dolius, my servant, whom my father gave me or ever I came hither, and who keeps my garden of many trees, that he may straightway go and sit by Laertes, and tell him of all these things. So haply may Laertes weave some plan in his heart,  and go forth and with weeping make his plea to the people, who are minded to destroy his race and that of godlike Odysseus.”'),(9569,'Then the good nurse Eurycleia answered her:'),(9570,'“Dear lady, thou mayest verily slay me with the pitiless sword or let me abide in the house, '),(9571,'yet will I not hide my word from thee. '),(9572,' I knew all this, and gave him whatever he bade me, bread and sweet wine. '),(9573,'But he took from me a mighty oath not to tell thee until at least the twelfth day should come, or thou shouldst thyself miss him and hear that he was gone, that thou mightest not mar thy fair flesh with weeping. '),(9574,' But now bathe thyself, and take clean raiment for thy body, and then go up to thy upper chamber with thy handmaids and pray to Athena, the daughter of Zeus who bears the aegis;'),(9575,'for she may then save him even from death.'),(9576,'And trouble not a troubled old man;'),(9577,'for  the race of the son of Arceisius is not, methinks, utterly hated by the blessed gods, but there shall still be one, I ween, to hold the high-roofed halls and the rich fields far away.” '),(9578,'So she spoke, and lulled Penelope\'s laments, and made her eyes to cease from weeping.'),(9579,' She then bathed, and took clean raiment for her body,  and went up to her upper chamber with her handmaids, and placing barley grains in a basket prayed to Athena:'),(9580,'\n“Hear me, child of Zeus who bears the aegis, unwearied one. If ever Odysseus, of many wiles, burnt to thee in his halls fat thigh-pieces of heifer or ewe,  remember these things now, I pray thee, and save my dear son, and ward off from him the wooers in their evil insolence.”'),(9581,'\nSo saying she raised the sacred cry, and the goddess heard her prayer. '),(9582,'\nBut the wooers broke into uproar throughout the shadowy halls,'),(9583,'and thus would one of the proud youths speak:'),(9584,' “Aye, verily the queen, wooed of many, is preparing our marriage, nor does she know at all that death has been made ready for her son.”'),(9585,'So would one of them speak; but they knew not how these things were to be. '),(9586,'And Antinous addressed their company, and said:'),(9587,'“Good sirs, shun haughty speech  of every kind alike, lest someone report your speech even within the house. '),(9588,'Nay come, in silence thus let us arise and put into effect our plan which pleased us one and all at heart.”'),(9589,'So he spoke, and chose twenty men that were best, and they went their way to the swift ship and the shore of the sea.'),(9590,' The ship first of all they drew down to the deep water, and set the mast and sail in the black ship, and fitted the oars in the leathern thole-straps, all in due order, and spread the white sail.'),(9591,'And proud squires brought them their weapons.'),(9592,' Well out in the roadstead they moored the ship, and themselves disembarked.'),(9593,'There then they took supper, and waited till evening should come.'),(9594,'But she, the wise Penelope, lay there in her upper chamber, touching no food, tasting neither meat nor drink, pondering whether her peerless son would escape death,  or be slain by the insolent wooers.'),(9595,'And even as a lion is seized with fear and broods amid a throng of men, when they draw their crafty ring about him, so was she pondering when sweet sleep came upon her.'),(9596,'And she sank back and slept, and all her joints relaxed. '),(9597,' Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, took other counsel. '),(9598,'She made a phantom, and likened it in form to a woman, Iphthime, daughter of great-hearted Icarius, whom Eumelus wedded, whose home was in Pherae.'),(9599,'And she sent it to the house of divine Odysseus,  to Penelope in the midst of her wailing and lamenting, to bid her cease from weeping and tearful lamentation.'),(9600,'So into the chamber it passed by the thong of the bolt, and stood above her head, and spoke to her, and said:'),(9601,'“Sleepest thou, Penelope, thy heart sore stricken? '),(9602,' Nay, the gods that live at ease suffer thee not to weep or be distressed, seeing that thy son is yet to return;'),(9603,'for in no wise is he a sinner in the eyes of the gods.”'),(9604,'Then wise Penelope answered her, as she slumbered very sweetly at the gates of dreams:'),(9605,' “Why, sister, art thou come hither? '),(9606,'Thou hast not heretofore been wont to come, for thou dwellest in a home far away.'),(9607,'And thou biddest me cease from my grief and the many pains that distress me in mind and heart. Long since I lost my noble husband of the lion heart,  pre-eminent in all manner of worth among the Danaans, my noble husband whose fame is wide in Hellas and mid-Argos.'),(9608,'And now again my well-loved son is gone forth in a hollow ship, a mere child, knowing naught of toils and the gatherings of men.'),(9609,'For him I sorrow even more than for that other,'),(9610,' and tremble for him, and fear lest aught befall him, whether it be in the land of the men to whom he is gone, or on the sea.'),(9611,'For many foes are plotting against him, eager to slay him before he comes back to his native land.”'),(9612,'Then the dim phantom answered her, and said:'),(9613,' “Take heart, and be not in thy mind too sore afraid;'),(9614,'since such a guide goes with him as men have full often besought to stand by their side, for she has power,—even Pallas Athena.'),(9615,'And she pities thee in thy sorrow,'),(9616,'for she it is that has sent me forth to tell thee this.”'),(9617,' Then again wise Penelope answered her:'),(9618,' “If thou art indeed a god, and hast listened to the voice of a god, come, tell me, I pray thee, also of that hapless one, whether he still lives and beholds the light of the sun, or whether he is already dead and in the house of Hades.”'),(9619,' And the dim phantom answered her, and said:'),(9620,'“Nay, of him I may not speak at length, whether he be alive or dead;'),(9621,'it is an ill thing to speak words vain as wind.”'),(9622,'So saying the phantom glided away by the bolt of the door into the breath of the winds. '),(9623,'And  the daughter of Icarius started up from sleep,'),(9624,'and her heart was warmed with comfort, that so clear a vision had sped to her in the darkness of night.'),(9625,'But the wooers embarked, and sailed over the watery ways, pondering in their hearts utter murder for Telemachus. '),(9626,'There is a rocky isle in the midst of the sea,  midway between Ithaca and rugged Samos, Asteris, of no great size,'),(9627,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 4.846-4'),(9628,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 4'),(9629,' Now Dawn arose from her couch from beside lordly Tithonus, to bear light to the immortals and to mortal men.'),(9630,' And the gods were sitting down to council, and among them Zeus, who thunders on high, whose might is supreme.'),(9631,'  To them Athena was recounting the many woes of Odysseus, as she called them to mind; '),(9632,'for it troubled her that he abode in the dwelling of the nymph:'),(9633,'\n“Father Zeus, and ye other blessed gods that are forever, never henceforward let sceptred king with a ready heart be kind and gentle, nor let him heed righteousness in his mind;  but let him ever be harsh, and work unrighteousness,'),(9634,'seeing that no one remembers divine Odysseus of the people whose lord he was; yet gentle was he as a father.'),(9635,' He verily abides in an island suffering grievous pains, in the halls of the nymph Calypso, who  keeps him perforce; '),(9636,' and he cannot return to his own land, '),(9637,'for he has at hand no ships with oars and no comrades to send him on his way over the broad back of the sea.'),(9638,' And now again they are minded to slay his well-loved son on his homeward way; '),(9639,'for he went in quest of tidings of his father  to sacred Pylos and to goodly Lacedaemon.”'),(9640,'Then Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, answered her, and said:'),(9641,' “My child, what a word has escaped the barrier of thy teeth!'),(9642,' Didst thou not thyself devise this plan, that verily Odysseus might take vengeance on these men at his coming?'),(9643,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 5.25-5.27'),(9644,'  But concerning Telemachus, do thou guide him in thy wisdom, for thou canst, that all unscathed he may reach his native land, and the wooers may come back in their ship ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 25 to line 27'),(9645,'He spoke, and said to Hermes, his dear son:'),(9646,'“Hermes, do thou now, seeing that thou art at other times our messenger,  declare to the fair-tressed nymph our fixed resolve, even the return of Odysseus of the steadfast heart, that he may return with guidance neither of gods nor of mortal men, '),(9647,' but that on a stoutly-bound raft, suffering woes, he may come on the twentieth day to deep-soiled Scheria,  the land of the Phaeacians, who are near of kin to the gods. These shall heartily shew him all honor, as if he were a god, and shall send him in a ship to his dear native land, after giving him stores of bronze and gold and raiment, more than Odysseus would ever have won for himself from Troy,  if he had returned unscathed with his due share of the spoil. '),(9648,'For in this wise it is his fate to see his friends, and reach his high-roofed house and his native land.”'),(9649,'So he spoke, and the messenger, Argeiphontes, failed not to hearken.  '),(9650,'Straightway he bound beneath his feet his beautiful sandals,  immortal, golden, which were wont to bear him over the waters of the sea and over the boundless land swift as the blasts of the wind.'),(9651,' And he took the wand wherewith he lulls to sleep the eyes of whom he will, while others again he awakens even out of slumber.'),(9652,' With this in his hand the strong Argeiphontes flew. '),(9653,'   On to Pieria he stepped from the upper air, and swooped down upon the sea, '),(9654,'and then sped over the wave like a bird, the cormorant, which in quest of fish over the dread gulfs of the unresting sea wets its thick plumage in the brine.'),(9655,' In such wise did Hermes ride upon the multitudinous waves.'),(9656,'  But when he had reached the island which lay afar, then forth from the violet sea he came to land, and went his way until he came to a great cave, wherein dwelt the fair-tressed nymph; '),(9657,'and he found her within.'),(9658,' A great fire was burning on the hearth, and from afar over the isle there was a fragrance  of cleft cedar and juniper, as they burned; '),(9659,'but she within was singing with a sweet voice as she went to and fro before the loom, weaving with a golden shuttle.'),(9660,' Round about the cave grew a luxuriant wood, alder and poplar and sweet-smelling cypress, '),(9661,' wherein birds long of wing were wont to nest, owls and falcons and sea-crows with chattering tongues, who ply their business on the sea.'),(9662,' And right there about the hollow cave ran trailing a garden vine, in pride of its prime, richly laden with clusters.'),(9663,'  And fountains four in a row were flowing with bright water hard by one another, turned one this way, one that.'),(9664,' And round about soft meadows of violets and parsley were blooming.'),(9665,' There even an immortal, who chanced to come, might gaze and marvel, and delight his soul; '),(9666,' and there the messenger Argeiphontes stood and marvelled.'),(9667,' But when he had marvelled in his heart at all things, straightway he went into the wide cave;'),(9668,' nor did Calypso, the beautiful goddess, fail to know him, when she saw him face to face; '),(9669,'for not unknown are  the immortal gods to one another, even though one dwells in a home far away. '),(9670,'But the great-hearted Odysseus he found not within; for he sat weeping on the shore, as his wont had been, racking his soul with tears and groans and griefs, '),(9671,'and he would look over the unresting sea, shedding tears.'),(9672,'  And Calypso, the beautiful goddess, questioned Hermes, when she had made him sit on a bright shining chair:'),(9673,'\n“Why, pray, Hermes of the golden wand, hast thou come, an honorable guest and welcome?'),(9674,' heretofore thou hast not been wont to come.'),(9675,' Speak what is in thy mind; '),(9676,'my heart bids me fulfil it,  if fulfil it I can, and it is a thing that hath fulfillment.'),(9677,'But follow me further, that I may set before thee entertainment.” '),(9678,' \nSo saying, the goddess set before him a table laden with ambrosia, and mixed the ruddy nectar.'),(9679,' So he drank and ate, the messenger Argeiphontes.'),(9680,'  But when he had dined and satisfied his soul with food, then he made answer, and addressed her, saying:'),(9681,'\n“Thou, a goddess, dost question me, a god, upon my coming, '),(9682,'\nand I will speak my word truly,'),(9683,' since thou biddest me.'),(9684,' It was Zeus who bade me come hither against my will.'),(9685,'  Who of his own will would speed over so great space of salt sea-water, great past telling?'),(9686,' Nor is there at hand any city of mortals who offer to the gods sacrifice and choice hecatombs.'),(9687,' But it is in no wise possible for any other god to evade or make void the will of Zeus, who bears the aegis.'),(9688,'  He says that there is here with thee a man most wretched above all those warriors who around the city of Priam fought for nine years, and in the tenth year sacked the city and departed homeward.'),(9689,' But on the way they sinned against Athena, and she sent upon them an evil wind and long waves.'),(9690,'  There all the rest of his goodly comrades perished, but as for him, the wind and the wave, as they bore him, brought him hither.'),(9691,' Him now Zeus bids thee to send on his way with all speed, '),(9692,'for it is not his fate to perish here far from his friends, but it is still his lot to see his friends and reach  his high-roofed house and his native land.”'),(9693,'So he spoke, and Calypso, the beautiful goddess, shuddered, and she spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(9694,' “Cruel are ye, O ye gods, and quick to envy above all others, seeing that ye begrudge goddesses that they should mate with men  openly, if any takes a mortal as her dear bed-fellow. '),(9695,'Thus, when rosy-fingered Dawn took to herself Orion, ye gods that live at ease begrudged her, till in Ortygia chaste Artemis of the golden throne assailed him with her gentle shafts and slew him.'),(9696,'  Thus too, when fair-tressed Demeter, yielding to her passion, lay in love with Iasion in the thrice-ploughed fallow land, '),(9697,'Zeus was not long without knowledge thereof, but smote him with his bright thunder-bolt and slew him.'),(9698,' And even so again do ye now begrudge me, O ye gods, that a mortal man should abide with me.'),(9699,'  Him I saved when he was bestriding the keel and all alone, for Zeus had smitten his swift ship with his bright thunder-bolt, and had shattered it in the midst of the wine-dark sea.'),(9700,' There all the rest of his goodly comrades perished, but as for him, the wind and the wave, as they bore him, brought him hither.'),(9701,'  Him I welcomed kindly and gave him food, and said that I would make him immortal and ageless all his days.'),(9702,' But since it is in no wise possible for any other god to evade or make void the will of Zeus who bears the aegis, let him go his way, if Zeus thus orders and commands,  over the unresting sea. '),(9703,' But it is not I that shall give him convoy, '),(9704,'for I have at hand no ships with oars and no men to send him on his way over the broad back of the sea.'),(9705,' But with a ready heart will I give him counsel, and will hide naught, that all unscathed he may return to his native land.” '),(9706,' \n  Then again the messenger Argeiphontes answered her: '),(9707,'“Even so send him forth now, and beware of the wrath of Zeus, lest haply he wax wroth and visit his anger upon thee hereafter.\"'),(9708,'So saying, the strong Argeiphontes departed, '),(9709,' and the queenly nymph went to the great-hearted Odysseus,  when she had heard the message of Zeus.'),(9710,'Him she found sitting on the shore,'),(9711,' and his eyes were never dry of tears, and his sweet life was ebbing away, as he longed mournfully for his return, for the nymph was no longer pleasing in his sight.'),(9712,' By night indeed he would sleep by her side perforce  in the hollow caves, unwilling beside the willing nymph, '),(9713,'but by day he would sit on the rocks and the sands, racking his soul with tears and groans and griefs, and he would look over the unresting sea, shedding tears.'),(9714,' Then coming close to him, the beautiful goddess addressed him:'),(9715,'\n  “Unhappy man, sorrow no longer here, I pray thee, nor let thy life pine away; '),(9716,'\nfor even now with a ready heart will I send thee on thy way.'),(9717,' Nay, come, hew with the axe long beams, and make a broad raft, '),(9718,'and fasten upon it cross-planks for a deck well above it, that it may bear thee over the misty deep.'),(9719,'  And I will place therein bread and water and red wine to satisfy thy heart, to keep hunger from thee. And I will clothe thee with raiment,'),(9720,'  and will send a fair wind behind thee, that all unscathed thou mayest return to thy native land, if it be the will of the gods who hold broad heaven;  for they are mightier than I both to purpose and to fulfil.”'),(9721,'\nSo she spoke, and much-enduring goodly Odysseus shuddered, and he spoke, and addressed her with winged words:'),(9722,' “Some other thing, goddess, art thou planning in this, and not my sending, seeing that thou biddest me cross on a raft the great gulf of the sea,  dread and grievous, '),(9723,' over which not even the shapely, swift-faring ships pass, rejoicing in the wind of Zeus.'),(9724,' But I will not set foot on a raft in thy despite, unless thou, goddess, wilt bring thyself to swear a mighty oath that thou wilt not plot against me any fresh mischief to my hurt.”'),(9725,'  So he spoke, but Calypso, the beautiful goddess, smiled, and stroked him with her hand, and spoke, and addressed him:'),(9726,' “Verily thou art a knave, and not stunted in wit, that thou hast bethought thee to utter such a word. '),(9727,'Now therefore let earth be witness to this, and the broad heaven above,  and the down-flowing water of the Styx, which is the greatest and most dread oath for the blessed gods, that I will not plot against thee any fresh mischief to thy hurt.'),(9728,' Nay, I have such thoughts in mind, and will give such counsel, as I should devise for mine own self, if such need should come on me.'),(9729,'  For I too have a mind that is righteous, and the heart in this breast of mine is not of iron, but hath compassion.” '),(9730,' \nSo saying, the beautiful goddess led the way quickly, '),(9731,' \nand he followed in the footsteps of the goddess.'),(9732,' And they came to the hollow cave, the goddess and the man,  and he sat down upon the chair from which Hermes had arisen, and the nymph set before him all manner of food to eat and drink, of such sort as mortal men eat.'),(9733,' But she herself sat over against divine Odysseus, and before her the handmaids set ambrosia and nectar.'),(9734,' So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them. '),(9735,' But when they had their fill of food and drink, Calypso, the beautiful goddess, was the first to speak, and said:'),(9736,'\n“Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices,  would\'st thou then fare now forthwith home to thy dear native land! '),(9737,'Yet, even so fare thee well. '),(9738,'Howbeit if in thy heart thou knewest all the measure of woe it is thy fate to fulfil before thou comest to thy native land thou wouldest abide here and keep this house with me, and wouldest be immortal, for all thy desire to see  thy wife for whom thou longest day by day.'),(9739,'Surely not inferior to her do I declare myself to be either in form or stature, for in no wise is it seemly that mortal women should vie with immortals in form or comeliness.\"'),(9740,'\nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said:'),(9741,'  “Mighty goddess, be not wroth with me for this. '),(9742,'I know full well of myself that wise Penelope is meaner to look upon than thou in comeliness and in stature, '),(9743,'for she is a mortal, while thou art immortal and ageless.'),(9744,' But even so I wish and long day by day  to reach my home, and to see the day of my return. '),(9745,'And if again some god shall smite me on the wine-dark sea, I will endure it, having in my breast a heart that endures affliction.'),(9746,' For ere this I have suffered much and toiled much amid the waves and in war; '),(9747,'let this also be added unto that.\"'),(9748,'  So he spoke, and the sun set and darkness came on. '),(9749,'And the two went into the innermost recess of the hollow cave, and took their joy of love, abiding each by the other\'s side. '),(9750,' \nAs soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, straightway Odysseus put on a cloak and a tunic,  and the nymph clothed herself in a long white robe, finely woven and beautiful, and about her waist she cast a fair girdle of gold, and on her head a veil above.'),(9751,' Then she set herself to plan the sending of the great-hearted Odysseus.'),(9752,' She gave him a great axe, well fitted to his hands,  an axe of bronze, sharpened on both sides; '),(9753,'and in it was a beautiful handle of olive wood, securely fastened;'),(9754,'and thereafter she gave him a polished adze.'),(9755,' Then she led the way to the borders of the island where tall trees were standing, alder and popular and fir, reaching to the skies,  long dry and well-seasoned, which would float for him lightly. '),(9756,'But when she had shewn him where the tall trees grew, Calypso, the beautiful goddess, returned homewards, but he fell to cutting timbers, '),(9757,'and his work went forward apace.'),(9758,' Twenty trees in all did he fell, and trimmed them with the axe;  then he cunningly smoothed them all and made them straight to the line.'),(9759,' Meanwhile Calypso, the beautiful goddess, brought him augers;'),(9760,' and he bored all the pieces and fitted them to one another, and with pegs and morticings did he hammer it together. '),(9761,' Wide as a man well-skilled in carpentry marks out the curve of the hull of a freight-ship,  broad of beam, even so wide did Odysseus make his raft.'),(9762,' And he set up the deck-beams, bolting them to the close-set ribs, and laboured on; '),(9763,'and he finished the raft with long gunwales.'),(9764,' In it he set a mast and a yard-arm, fitted to it, '),(9765,' and furthermore made him a steering-oar, wherewith to steer.'),(9766,' Then he fenced in the whole from stem to stern with willow withes to be a defence against the wave,'),(9767,' and strewed much brush thereon.'),(9768,' Meanwhile Calypso, the beautiful goddess, brought him cloth to make him a sail,'),(9769,'and he fashioned that too with skill.'),(9770,'  And he made fast in the raft braces and halyards and sheets, and then with levers forced it down into the bright sea. '),(9771,' \nNow the fourth day came and all his work was done.'),(9772,' And on the fifth the beautiful Calypso sent him on his way from the island after she had bathed him and clothed him in fragrant raiment.'),(9773,'  On the raft the goddess put a skin of dark wine, and another, a great one, of water, and provisions, too, in a wallet.'),(9774,'Therein she put abundance of dainties to satisfy his heart,'),(9775,'  and she sent forth a gentle wind and warm.'),(9776,' Gladly then did goodly Odysseus spread his sail to the breeze; '),(9777,' and he sat and guided his raft skilfully with the steering-oar, nor did sleep fall upon his eyelids, as he watched the Pleiads, and late-setting Bootes, and the Bear, which men also call the Wain, which ever circles where it is and watches Orion,  and alone has no part in the baths of Ocean. '),(9778,' For this star Calypso, the beautiful goddess, had bidden him to keep on the left hand as he sailed over the sea.'),(9779,' For seventeen days then he sailed over the sea, and on the eighteenth appeared the shadowy mountains  of the land of the Phaeacians, where it lay nearest to him; '),(9780,'and it shewed like unto a shield in the misty deep.'),(9781,'\nBut the glorious Earth-shaker, as he came back from the Ethiopians, beheld him from afar, from the mountains of the Solymi:'),(9782,'for Odysseus was seen of him sailing over the sea;'),(9783,' and he waxed the more wroth in spirit,  and shook his head, and thus he spoke to his own heart:'),(9784,'\n“Out on it! Surely the gods have changed their purpose regarding Odysseus, while I was among the Ethiopians. And lo, he is near to the land of the Phaeacians, where it is his fate to escape from the great bonds of the woe which has come upon him.'),(9785,'  Aye, but even yet, methinks, I shall drive him to surfeit of evil.\"'),(9786,'So saying, he gathered the clouds, and seizing his trident in his hands troubled the sea,'),(9787,' and roused all blasts of all manner of winds, and hid with clouds land and sea alike; '),(9788,' and night rushed down from heaven. '),(9789,'  Together the East Wind and the South Wind dashed, and the fierce-blowing West Wind and the North Wind, born in the bright heaven, rolling before him a mighty wave. '),(9790,'Then were the knees of Odysseus loosened and his heart melted, and deeply moved he spoke to his own mighty spirit:'),(9791,'“Ah me, wretched that I am!  What is to befall me at the last?'),(9792,'  I fear me that verily all that the goddess said was true, when she declared that on the sea, before ever I came to my native land, I should fill up my measure of woes; '),(9793,'and lo, all this now is being brought to pass.'),(9794,' In such wise does Zeus overcast the broad heaven with clouds, and has stirred up the sea, and the blasts  of all manner of winds sweep upon me; '),(9795,'now is my utter destruction sure.'),(9796,' Thrice blessed those Danaans, aye, four times blessed, who of old perished in the wide land of Troy, doing the pleasure of the sons of Atreus.'),(9797,' Even so would that I had died and met my fate on that day when the throngs  of the Trojans hurled upon me bronze-tipped spears, fighting around the body of the dead son of Peleus. '),(9798,' Then should I have got funeral rites, and the Achaeans would have spread my fame, '),(9799,'but now by a miserable death was it appointed me to be cut off.” '),(9800,' \nEven as thus he spoke the great wave smote him from on high, rushing upon him with terrible might, and around it whirled his raft.'),(9801,'  Far from the raft he fell, and let fall the steering-oar from his hand; '),(9802,' but his mast was broken in the midst by the fierce blast of tumultuous winds that came upon it, and far in the sea sail and yardarm fell.'),(9803,' As for him, long time did the wave hold him in the depths, nor could he  rise at once from beneath the onrush of the mighty wave, '),(9804,'for the garments which beautiful Calypso had given him weighed him down.'),(9805,' At length, however, he came up, and spat forth from his mouth the bitter brine which flowed in streams from his head. '),(9806,'Yet even so he did not forget his raft, in evil case though he was,  but sprang after it amid the waves, and laid hold of it, and sat down in the midst of it, seeking to escape the doom of death; '),(9807,'and a great wave ever bore him this way and that along its course.'),(9808,' As when in autumn the North Wind bears the thistle-tufts over the plain, and close they cling to one another,  so did the winds bear the raft this way and that over the sea. '),(9809,'Now the South Wind would fling it to the North Wind to be driven on, and now again the East Wind would yield it to the West Wind to drive.'),(9810,'\nBut the daughter of Cadmus, Ino of the fair ankles, saw him, even Leucothea, who of old was a mortal of human speech,  but now in the deeps of the sea has won a share of honor from the gods. '),(9811,'\nShe was touched with pity for Odysseus, as he wandered and was in sore travail, and she rose up from the deep like a sea-mew on the wing, and sat on the stoutly-bound raft, and spoke, saying:'),(9812,'\n“Unhappy man, how is it that Poseidon, the earth-shaker,  has conceived such furious wrath against thee, that he is sowing for thee the seeds of many evils?'),(9813,'Yet verily he shall not utterly destroy thee for all his rage.'),(9814,'  Nay, do thou thus; and methinks thou dost not lack understanding.'),(9815,' Strip off these garments, and leave thy raft to be driven by the winds, but do thou swim with thy hands and so strive to reach  the land of the Phaeacians, where it is thy fate to escape.'),(9816,' Come, take this veil, and stretch it beneath thy breast.'),(9817,'It is immortal; there is no fear that thou shalt suffer aught or perish.'),(9818,'there is no fear that thou shalt suffer aught or perish. But when with thy hands thou hast laid hold of the land, loose it from thee, and cast it into the wine-dark sea  far from the land, and thyself turn away.”'),(9819,'\nSo saying, the goddess gave him the veil, and herself plunged again into the surging deep, like a sea-mew; '),(9820,'and the dark wave hid her.'),(9821,' Then the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus pondered,  and deeply moved he spoke to his own mighty spirit:'),(9822,'“Woe is me! Let it not be that some one of the immortals is again weaving a snare for me, that she bids me leave my raft.'),(9823,' Nay, but verily I will not yet obey, for afar off mine eyes beheld the land, where she said I was to escape.'),(9824,' But this will I do, and meseems that this is best: '),(9825,' as long as the timbers hold firm in their fastenings, so long will I remain here and endure to suffer affliction; '),(9826,'but when the wave shall have shattered the raft to pieces, I will swim, seeing that there is naught better to devise.” '),(9827,' \n  While he pondered thus in mind and heart, Poseidon, the earth-shaker, made to rise up a great wave, dread and grievous, arching over from above, and drove it upon him.'),(9828,' And as when a strong wind tosses a heap of straw that is dry,'),(9829,'and some it scatters here, some there, '),(9830,' even so the wave scattered the long timbers of the raft. '),(9831,'But Odysseus bestrode one plank, as though he were riding a horse, and stripped off the garments which beautiful Calypso had given him.'),(9832,' Then straightway he stretched the veil beneath his breast, and flung himself headlong into the sea with hands outstretched,  ready to swim.'),(9833,' And the lord, the earth-shaker, saw him, and he shook his head, and thus he spoke to his own heart:'),(9834,'\n“So now, after thou hast suffered many ills, go wandering over the deep, till thou comest among the folk fostered of Zeus.'),(9835,' Yet even so, methinks, thou shalt not make any mock at thy suffering.”'),(9836,'\n  So saying, he lashed his fair-maned horses, and came to Aegae, where is his glorious palace.'),(9837,'\nBut Athena, daughter of Zeus, took other counsel.'),(9838,' She stayed the paths of the other winds, and bade them all cease and be lulled to rest; '),(9839,' but she roused the swift North Wind, and broke the waves before him, to the end that Zeus-born Odysseus might come among the Phaeacians, lovers of the oar, escaping from death and the fates.'),(9840,'\nThen for two nights and two days he was driven about over the swollen waves, and full often his heart forboded destruction.'),(9841,'  But when fair-tressed Dawn brought to its birth the third day, then the wind ceased and there was a windless calm, '),(9842,' and he caught sight of the shore close at hand, casting a quick glance forward, as he was raised up by a great wave.'),(9843,'And even as when most welcome to his children appears the life  of a father who lies in sickness, bearing grievous pains, long while wasting away, and some cruel god assails him, but then to their joy the gods free him from his woe, so to Odysseus did the land and the wood seem welcome; and he swam on, eager to set foot on the land.'),(9844,'  But when he was as far away as a man\'s voice carries when he shouts, and heard the boom of the sea upon the reefs—'),(9845,'for the great wave thundered against the dry land, belching upon it in terrible fashion, and all things were wrapped in the foam of the sea; '),(9846,'for there were neither harbors where ships might ride, nor road-steads, '),(9847,' but projecting headlands, and reefs, and cliffs—'),(9848,'then the knees of Odysseus were loosened and his heart melted, and deeply moved he spoke to his own mighty spirit: '),(9849,' \n“Ah me, when Zeus has at length granted me to see the land beyond my hopes, and lo, I have prevailed to cleave my way and to cross this gulf,  nowhere doth there appear a way to come forth from the grey sea. '),(9850,'For without are sharp crags, and around them the wave roars foaming, and the rock runs up sheer, and the water is deep close in shore, so that in no wise is it possible to plant both feet firmly and escape ruin.'),(9851,'  Haply were I to seek to land, a great wave may seize me and dash me against the jagged rock, '),(9852,'and so shall my striving be in vain.'),(9853,' But if I swim on yet further in hope to find shelving beaches and harbors of the sea, I fear me lest the storm-wind may catch me up again,  and bear me, groaning heavily, over the teeming deep; or lest some god may even send forth upon me some great monster from out the sea—and many such does glorious Amphitrite breed.'),(9854,' For I know that the glorious Earth-shaker is filled with wrath against me.\"'),(9855,'While he pondered thus in mind and heart,  a great wave bore him against the rugged shore. '),(9856,'There would his skin have been stripped off and his bones broken, had not the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, put a thought in his mind.'),(9857,' On he rushed and seized the rock with both hands, and clung to it, groaning, until the great wave went by.'),(9858,'  Thus then did he escape this wave, but in its backward flow it once more rushed upon him and smote him, and flung him far out in the sea.'),(9859,' And just as, when a cuttlefish is dragged from its hole, many pebbles cling to its suckers, even so from his strong hands  were bits of skin stripped off against the rocks;'),(9860,'and the great wave covered him. '),(9861,'Then verily would hapless Odysseus have perished beyond his fate, had not flashing-eyed Athena given him prudence.'),(9862,' Making his way forth from the surge where it belched upon the shore, he swam outside, looking ever toward the land in hope to find  shelving beaches and harbors of the sea.'),(9863,' But when, as he swam, he came to the mouth of a fair-flowing river, where seemed to him the best place, since it was smooth of stones, and besides there was shelter from the wind, he knew the river as he flowed forth, and prayed to him in his heart:'),(9864,' “Hear me, O king, whosoever thou art.'),(9865,'As to one greatly longed-for do I come to thee, seeking to escape from out the sea from the threats of Poseidon.'),(9866,' Reverend even in the eyes of the immortal gods is that man who comes as a wanderer, even as I have now come to thy stream and to thy knees, after many toils. '),(9867,'for I declare that I am thy suppliant.”'),(9868,'for I declare that I am thy suppliant.”'),(9869,' \nSo he spoke, and the god straightway stayed his stream, and checked the waves, and made a calm before him, and brought him safely to the mouth of the river.'),(9870,' And he let his two knees bend and his strong hands fall, '),(9871,'for his spirit was crushed by the sea.'),(9872,'  And all his flesh was swollen, and sea water flowed in streams up through his mouth and nostrils.'),(9873,' So he lay breathless and speechless, with scarce strength to move; for terrible weariness had come upon him.'),(9874,' But when he revived, and his spirit returned again into his breast, then he loosed from him the veil of the goddess'),(9875,'and let it fall into the river that murmured seaward;  and the great wave bore it back down the stream, and straightway Ino received it in her hands.'),(9876,' But Odysseus, going back from the river, sank down in the reeds and kissed the earth, the giver of grain; '),(9877,'and deeply moved he spoke to his own mighty spirit:'),(9878,'What will happen to me at the last? '),(9879,'What will happen to me at the last? '),(9880,'\nIf here in the river bed I keep watch throughout the weary night, I fear that together the bitter frost and the fresh dew may overcome me, when from feebleness I have breathed forth my spirit; '),(9881,'and the breeze from the river blows cold in the early morning.'),(9882,'  But if I climb up the slope to the shady wood and lie down to rest in the thick brushwood, in the hope that the cold and weariness might leave me, and if sweet sleep comes over me, I fear me lest I become a prey and spoil to wild beasts.\"'),(9883,'Then, as he pondered, this thing seemed to him the better:'),(9884,' he went his way to the wood'),(9885,'  and found it near the water in a clear space; '),(9886,'and he crept beneath two bushes that grew from the same spot, '),(9887,'one of thorn and one of olive.'),(9888,' Through these the strength of the wet winds could never blow, nor the rays of the bright sun beat,  nor could the rain pierce through them, '),(9889,' so closely did they grow, intertwining one with the other.'),(9890,'Beneath these Odysseus crept'),(9891,'  and straightway gathered with his hands a broad bed, '),(9892,'for fallen leaves were there in plenty, enough to shelter two men or three  in winter-time, however bitter the weather. '),(9893,'And the much-enduring goodly Odysseus saw it, and was glad, and he lay down in the midst, and heaped over him the fallen leaves. '),(9894,'And as a man hides a brand beneath the dark embers in an outlying farm, a man who has no neighbors,  and so saves a seed of fire, that he may not have to kindle it from some other source, so Odysseus covered himself with leaves.'),(9895,' And Athena shed sleep upon his eyes, that it might enfold his lids and speedily free him from toilsome weariness.'),(9896,' So he lay there asleep, the much-enduring goodly Odysseus, overcome with sleep and weariness; '),(9897,'but Athena went to the land and city of the Phaeacians. These dwelt of old in spacious Hypereia  hard by the Cyclopes, men overweening in pride who plundered them continually and were mightier than they.'),(9898,' From thence Nausithous, the godlike, had removed them, and led and settled them in Scheria far from men that live by toil. About the city he had drawn a wall, he had built houses  and made temples for the gods, and divided the ploughlands;'),(9899,'but he, ere now, had been stricken by fate and had gone to the house of Hades, and Alcinous was now king, made wise in counsel by the gods.'),(9900,' To his house went the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, to contrive the return of great-hearted Odysseus.'),(9901,'  She went to a chamber, richly wrought, wherein slept a maiden like the immortal goddesses in form and comeliness, Nausicaa, the daughter of great-hearted Alcinous; hard by slept two hand-maidens, gifted with beauty by the Graces, one on either side of the door-posts,'),(9902,'and the bright doors were shut.'),(9903,'\n  But like a breath of air the goddess sped to the couch of the maiden, and stood above her head, and spoke to her, taking the form of the daughter of Dymas, famed for his ships, a girl who was of like age with Nausicaa, and was dear to her heart.'),(9904,' Likening herself to her, the flashing-eyed Athena spoke and said:'),(9905,'  “Nausicaa, how comes it that thy mother bore thee so heedless? '),(9906,'Thy bright raiment is lying uncared for; yet thy marriage is near at hand, when thou must needs thyself be clad in fair garments, and give other such to those who escort thee.'),(9907,' It is from things like these, thou knowest, that good report goeth up among men,  and the father and honored mother rejoice.'),(9908,' Nay, come, let us go to wash them at break of day, '),(9909,'for I will follow with thee to aid thee, that thou mayest with speed make thee ready; for thou shalt not long remain a maiden.'),(9910,' Even now thou hast suitors in the land, the noblest  of all the Phaeacians, from whom is thine own lineage. '),(9911,'Nay, come, bestir thy noble father early this morning that he make ready mules and a wagon for thee, to bear the girdles and robes and bright coverlets.'),(9912,' And for thyself, too, it is far more seemly  to go thus than on foot, '),(9913,'for the washing tanks are far from the city.”'),(9914,'So saying, the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, departed to Olympus, where, they say, is the abode of the gods that stands fast forever.'),(9915,' Neither is it shaken by winds nor ever wet with rain, nor does snow fall upon it, but the air  is outspread clear and cloudless, and over it hovers a radiant whiteness.'),(9916,' Therein the blessed gods are glad all their days,'),(9917,' and thither went the flashing-eyed one, when she had spoken all her word to the maiden. '),(9918,' \nAt once then came fair-throned Dawn and awakened Nausicaa of the beautiful robes, '),(9919,'and straightway she marvelled at her dream,  and went through the house to tell her parents, her father dear and her mother; '),(9920,'and she found them both within.'),(9921,' The mother sat at the hearth with her handmaidens, spinning the yarn of purple dye, '),(9922,'and her father she met as he was going forth to join the glorious kings  in the place of council, to which the lordly Phaeacians called him. '),(9923,' But she came up close to her dear father, and said:'),(9924,'\n“Papa dear, wilt thou not make ready for me a wagon, high and stout of wheel, that I may take to the river for washing the goodly raiment of mine which is lying here soiled?'),(9925,'  Moreover for thyself it is seemly that when thou art at council with the princes'),(9926,' thou shouldst have clean raiment upon thee; '),(9927,'and thou hast five sons living in thy halls—two are wedded, but three are sturdy bachelors—'),(9928,'and these ever wish to put on them freshly-washed raiment,  when they go to the dance. '),(9929,'Of all this must I take thought.\"'),(9930,'So she spoke,'),(9931,'for she was ashamed to name gladsome marriage to her father; '),(9932,'but he understood all, and answered, saying:'),(9933,' “Neither the mules do I begrudge thee, my child, nor aught beside.'),(9934,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 6.69'),(9935,'the slaves shall make ready for thee the wagon,  high and stout of wheel and fitted with a box above.”'),(9936,'With this he called to the slaves, and they hearkened.'),(9937,' Outside the palace they made ready the light-running mule wagon, and led up the mules and yoked them to it; '),(9938,'and the maiden brought from her chamber the bright raiment, '),(9939,' and placed it upon the polished car, while her mother put in a chest food of all sorts to satisfy the heart. Therein she put dainties, and poured wine in a goat-skin flask; '),(9940,'and the maiden mounted upon the wagon.'),(9941,' Her mother gave her also soft olive oil in a flask of gold,  that she and her maidens might have it for the bath. '),(9942,'Then Nausicaa took the whip and the bright reins, and smote the mules to start them; '),(9943,' and there was a clatter of the mules '),(9944,'as they sped on a main, bearing the raiment and the maiden; neither went she alone, for with her went her handmaids as well. '),(9945,' \n  Now when they came to the beautiful streams of the river, where were the washing tanks that never failed—for abundant clear water welled up from beneath and flowed over, to cleanse garments however soiled—there they loosed the mules from under the wagon '),(9946,'and drove them along the eddying river  to graze on the honey-sweet water-grass, '),(9947,' and themselves took in their arms the raiment from the wagon, and bore it into the dark water, and trampled it in the trenches, busily vying each with each.'),(9948,' Now when they had washed the garments, and had cleansed them of all the stains, they spread them out in rows on the shore of the sea where  the waves dashing against the land washed the pebbles cleanest; '),(9949,'and they, after they had bathed and anointed themselves richly with oil, took their meal on the river\'s banks, and waited for the clothing to dry in the bright sunshine.'),(9950,' Then when they had had their joy of food, she and her handmaids,  they threw off their head-gear and fell to playing at ball,'),(9951,'and white-armed Nausicaa was leader in the song.'),(9952,' And even as Artemis, the archer, roves over the mountains, along the ridges of lofty Taygetus or Erymanthus, joying in the pursuit of boars and swift deer, '),(9953,' and with her sport the wood-nymphs, the daughters of Zeus who bears the aegis, and Leto is glad at heart—'),(9954,'high above them all Artemis holds her head and brows, and easily may she be known, though all are fair—'),(9955,'so amid her handmaidens shone the maid unwed.'),(9956,'\n  But when she was about to yoke the mules, and fold the fair raiment, in order to return homeward, then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, took other counsel, that Odysseus might awake and see the fair-faced maid, who should lead him to the city of the Phaeacians.'),(9957,' So then the princess tossed the ball to one of her maidens;'),(9958,'  the maiden indeed she missed, but cast it into a deep eddy, '),(9959,'and thereat they cried aloud, '),(9960,'and goodly Odysseus awoke, and sat up, and thus he pondered in mind and heart:'),(9961,'\n“Woe is me! to the land of what mortals am I now come?'),(9962,'  Are they cruel, and wild, and unjust? or do they love strangers and fear the gods in their thoughts?'),(9963,' There rang in my ears a cry as of maidens, '),(9964,'of nymphs who haunt the towering peaks of the mountains, the springs that feed the rivers, and the grassy meadows! '),(9965,'  Can it be that I am somewhere near men of human speech? '),(9966,'Nay, I will myself make trial and see.” '),(9967,' \nSo saying the goodly Odysseus came forth from beneath the bushes, and with his stout hand he broke from the thick wood a leafy branch, that he might hold it about him and hide therewith his nakedness.'),(9968,'  Forth he came like a mountain-nurtured lion trusting in his might, who goes forth, beaten with rain and wind, but his two eyes are ablaze:'),(9969,' into the midst of the kine he goes, or of the sheep, or on the track of the wild deer, '),(9970,' and his belly bids him go even into the close-built fold, to make an attack upon the flocks.'),(9971,'  Even so Odysseus was about to enter the company of the fair-tressed maidens, naked though he was, '),(9972,' for need had come upon him.'),(9973,' But terrible did he seem to them, all befouled with brine, and they shrank in fear, one here, one there, along the jutting sand-spits.'),(9974,' Alone the daughter of Alcinous kept her place, '),(9975,'for  in her heart Athena put courage, and took fear from her limbs.'),(9976,' She fled not, but stood and faced him;'),(9977,' and Odysseus pondered whether he should clasp the knees of the fair-faced maid, and make his prayer, or whether, standing apart as he was, he should beseech her with gentle words, in hope that she might show him the city and give him raiment.'),(9978,'  And, as he pondered, it seemed to him better to stand apart and beseech her with gentle words, lest the maiden\'s heart should be wroth with him if he clasped her knees; '),(9979,' so straightway he spoke a gentle word and crafty:'),(9980,'\na goddess art thou, or art thou mortal?'),(9981,'\na goddess art thou, or art thou mortal?'),(9982,'  If thou art a goddess, one of those who hold broad heaven, to Artemis, the daughter of great Zeus, do I liken thee most nearly in comeliness and in stature and in form.'),(9983,' But if thou art one of mortals who dwell upon the earth, thrice-blessed then are thy father and thy honored mother,  and thrice-blessed thy brethren. '),(9984,'Full well, I ween, are their hearts ever warmed with joy because of thee, as they see thee entering the dance, a plant so fair.'),(9985,' But he again is blessed in heart above all others, who shall prevail with his gifts of wooing and lead thee to his home.'),(9986,'  For never yet have mine eyes looked upon a mortal such as thou, whether man or woman; '),(9987,'amazement holds me as I look on thee. '),(9988,' Of a truth in Delos once I saw such a thing, a young shoot of a palm springing up beside the altar of Apollo—'),(9989,'for thither, too, I went, and much people followed with me,  on that journey on which evil woes were to be my portion;'),(9990,';—even so, when I saw that, I marvelled long at heart, for never yet did such a tree spring up from the earth. And in like manner, lady, do I marvel at thee, and am amazed, and fear greatly to touch thy knees;'),(9991,'but sore grief has come upon me.'),(9992,'  Yesterday, on the twentieth day, I escaped from the wine-dark sea,'),(9993,' but ever until then the wave and the swift winds bore me from the island of Ogygia;'),(9994,'and now fate has cast me ashore here, that here too, haply, I may suffer some ill.'),(9995,' For not yet, methinks, will my troubles cease, but the gods ere that will bring many to pass.'),(9996,'  Nay, O queen, have pity;'),(9997,'for it is to thee first that I am come after many grievous toils, and of the others who possess this city and land I know not one. '),(9998,'Shew me the city, and give me some rag to throw about me, if thou hadst any wrapping for the clothes when thou camest hither.'),(9999,' And for thyself, may the gods grant thee all that thy heart desires; a husband and a home may they grant thee, and oneness of heart—a goodly gift.'),(10000,' For nothing is greater or better than this, when man and wife dwell in a home in one accord, '),(10001,'a great grief to their foes  and a joy to their friends; but they know it best themselves.\"'),(10002,'Then white-armed Nausicaa answered him:'),(10003,'“Stranger, since thou seemest to be neither an evil man nor a witless,'),(10004,' and it is Zeus himself, the Olympian, that gives happy fortune to men, both to the good and the evil, to each man as he will;'),(10005,'  so to thee, I ween, he has given this lot, and thou must in any case endure it.'),(10006,' But now, since thou hast come to our city and land, thou shalt not lack clothing or aught else of those things which befit a sore-tried suppliant when he cometh in the way.'),(10007,' The city will I shew thee, and will tell thee the name of the people.'),(10008,'  The Phaeacians possess this city and land, and I am the daughter of great-hearted Alcinous, upon whom depend the might and power of the Phaeacians.\"'),(10009,'She spoke, and called to her fair-tressed handmaids:'),(10010,' Whither do ye flee at the sight of a man?'),(10011,' Whither do ye flee at the sight of a man?'),(10012,'  Ye do not think, surely, that he is an enemy?'),(10013,' That mortal man lives not, or exists nor shall ever be born who shall come to the land of the Phaeacians as a foeman, '),(10014,'for we are very dear to the immortals.'),(10015,'Far off we dwell in the surging sea,  the furthermost of men, and no other mortals have dealings with us.'),(10016,' Nay, this is some hapless wanderer that has come hither. Him must we now tend;'),(10017,' for from Zeus are all strangers and beggars, and a gift, though small, is welcome.'),(10018,' Come, then, my maidens, give to the stranger food and drink,  and bathe him in the river in a spot where there is shelter from the wind.”'),(10019,' \nSo she spoke, and they halted and called to each other. Then they set Odysseus in a sheltered place, as Nausicaa, the daughter of great-hearted Alcinous, bade, '),(10020,' and beside him they put a cloak and a tunic for raiment,  and gave him soft olive oil in the flask of gold, and bade him bathe in the streams of the river.'),(10021,' Then among the maidens spoke goodly Odysseus:'),(10022,' “Maidens, stand yonder apart, that by myself I may wash the brine from my shoulders, and  anoint myself with olive oil; '),(10023,'for of a truth it is long since oil came near my skin.'),(10024,'But in your presence will I not bathe,'),(10025,'  for I am ashamed to make me naked in the midst of fair-tressed maidens.\"'),(10026,'So he said, and they went apart and told the princess. '),(10027,'But with water from the river goodly Odysseus washed from his skin  the brine which clothed his back and broad shoulders, and from his head he wiped the scurf of the unresting sea. '),(10028,'But when he had washed his whole body and anointed himself with oil, and had put on him the raiment which the unwedded maid had given him, then Athena, the daughter of Zeus, made him  taller to look upon and mightier, and from his head she made the locks to flow in curls like unto the hyacinth flower.'),(10029,' And as when a man overlays silver with gold, a cunning workman whom Hephaestus and Pallas Athena have taught all manner of craft, and full of grace is the work he produces,  even so the goddess shed grace upon his head and shoulders.'),(10030,'Then he went apart and sat down on the shore of the sea, gleaming with beauty and grace;'),(10031,' and the damsel marvelled at him, '),(10032,'and spoke to her fair-tressed handmaids, saying:'),(10033,'\n“Listen, white-armed maidens, that I may say somewhat.'),(10034,'  Not without the will of all the gods who hold Olympus does this man come among the godlike Phaeacians.'),(10035,' Before he seemed to me uncouth, but now he is like the gods, who hold broad heaven.'),(10036,' Would that a man such as he might be called my husband,  dwelling here, and that it might please him here to remain.'),(10037,'But come, my maidens; give to the stranger food and drink.”'),(10038,'So she spoke, and they readily hearkened and obeyed, and set before Odysseus food and drink.'),(10039,' Then verily did the much-enduring goodly Odysseus drink and eat, ravenously;'),(10040,'for long had he been without taste of food.'),(10041,' \nBut the white-armed Nausicaa took other counsel.'),(10042,' She folded the raiment and put it in the fair wagon, and yoked the stout-hoofed mules, and mounted the car herself. Then she hailed Odysseus, and spoke and addressed him:'),(10043,'  “Rouse thee now, stranger, to go to the city, that I may escort thee to the house of my wise father, where, I tell thee, thou shalt come to know all the noblest of the Phaeacians.'),(10044,' Only do thou thus, and, methinks, thou dost not lack understanding: '),(10045,'so long as we are passing through the country and the tilled fields of men go thou quickly  with the handmaids behind the mules and the wagon, '),(10046,'and I will lead the way.'),(10047,' But when we are about to enter the city, around which runs a lofty wall,—a fair harbor lies on either side of the city and the entrance is narrow, '),(10048,'and curved ships  are drawn up along the road, '),(10049,'for they all have stations for their ships, each man one for himself. '),(10050,'There, too, is their place of assembly about the fair temple of Poseidon, fitted with huge stones set deep in the earth.'),(10051,' Here the men are busied with the tackle of their black ships, with cables and sails, and here they shape the thin oar-blades.'),(10052,'   For the Phaeacians care not for bow or quiver, but for masts and oars of ships, and for the shapely ships, rejoicing in which they cross over the grey sea.'),(10053,'It is their ungentle speech that I shun, lest hereafter some man should taunt me, '),(10054,' for indeed there are insolent folk in the land, '),(10055,' and thus might some baser fellow say, shall he meet us:'),(10056,' ‘Who is this that follows Nausicaa, a comely man and tall, a stranger?'),(10057,' He will doubtless be a husband for her. '),(10058,' He will doubtless be a husband for her. '),(10059,'Haply she has brought from his ship some wanderer of a folk that dwell afar—for none are near us—'),(10060,' or some god, long prayed-for, has come down from heaven in answer to her prayers, and she will have him as her husband all her days. '),(10061,'Better so, even if she has herself gone forth and found a husband from another people; '),(10062,' for of a truth she scorns the Phaeacians here in the land, where she has wooers many and noble!’ '),(10063,' So will they say, and this would become a reproach to me. '),(10064,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 6.286-6.288'),(10065,' Nay, stranger, do thou quickly hearken to my words, that with all speed  thou mayest win from my father an escort and a return to thy land. '),(10066,'Thou wilt find a goodly grove of Athena hard by the road, a grove of poplar trees.'),(10067,' In it a spring wells up, and round about is a meadow.'),(10068,' There is my father\'s park and fruitful vineyard, as far from the city as a man\'s voice carries when he shouts.'),(10069,'  Sit thou down there, and wait for a time, until we come to the city and reach the house of my father.'),(10070,' But when thou thinkest that we have reached the house, then do thou go to the city of the Phaeacians and ask for the house of my father, great-hearted Alcinous.'),(10071,'  Easily may it be known, and a child could guide thee, a mere babe; '),(10072,'for the houses of the Phaeacians are no wise built of such sort as is the palace of the lord Alcinous.'),(10073,' But when the house and the court enclose thee, pass quickly through the great hall, till thou comest  to my mother, '),(10074,' who sits at the hearth in the light of the fire, spinning the purple yarn, a wonder to behold, leaning against a pillar, '),(10075,'and her handmaids sit behind her.'),(10076,' There, too, leaning against the selfsame pillar, is set the throne of my father, whereon he sits and quaffs his wine, like unto an immortal.'),(10077,'  Him pass thou by, and cast thy hands about my mother\'s knees, that thou mayest quickly see with rejoicing the day of thy return, though thou art come from never so far.'),(10078,' If in her sight thou dost win favour, then there is hope that thou wilt see thy friends, and return  to thy well-built house and unto thy native land.\"'),(10079,'So saying, she smote the mules with the shining whip, '),(10080,'and they quickly left the streams of the river.'),(10081,' Well did they trot, well did they ply their ambling feet,  '),(10082,'and she drove with care that  the maidens and Odysseus might follow on foot, and with judgment did she ply the lash.'),(10083,'Then the sun set, and they came to the glorious grove, sacred to Athena. There Odysseus sat him down,'),(10084,'and straightway prayed to the daughter of great Zeus: '),(10085,'“Hear me, child of aegis-bearing Zeus, unwearied one.'),(10086,'Hearken now to my prayer, since aforetime thou didst not hearken when I was smitten, what time the glorious Earth-shaker smote me.'),(10087,'Grant that I may come to the Phaeacians as one to be welcomed and to be pitied.”'),(10088,'So he spoke in prayer, and Pallas Athena heard him;'),(10089,'but she did not yet appear to him face to face,'),(10090,'for she feared  her father\'s brother;'),(10091,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 6.330-631'),(10092,' So he prayed there, the much-enduring goodly Odysseus, while the two strong mules bore the maiden to the city. '),(10093,'But when she had come to the glorious palace of her father, she halted the mules at the outer gate, and her brothers  thronged about her, men like the immortals, and loosed the mules from the wagon, and bore the raiment within; '),(10094,'and she herself went to her chamber.'),(10095,' There a fire was kindled for her by her waiting-woman, Eurymedusa, an aged dame from Apeire. Long ago the curved ships had brought her from Apeire, '),(10096,' and men had chosen her from the spoil as a gift of honor for Alcinous, for that he was king over all the Phaeacians, and the people hearkened to him as to a god.'),(10097,' She it was who had reared the white-armed Nausicaa in the palace,'),(10098,'and she it was who kindled the fire for her, and made ready her supper in the chamber.'),(10099,'\nThen Odysseus roused himself to go to the city,'),(10100,'and Athena,  with kindly purpose, cast about him a thick mist, that no one of the great-hearted Phaeacians, meeting him, should speak mockingly to him, and ask him who he was.'),(10101,' But when he was about to enter the lovely city, then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, met him  in the guise of a young maiden carrying a pitcher, '),(10102,'and she stood before him; and goodly Odysseus questioned her, saying:'),(10103,'\n“My child, couldst thou not guide me to the house of him they call Alcinous, who is lord among the people here?'),(10104,' For I am come hither a stranger sore-tried  from afar, from a distant country; '),(10105,'wherefore I know no one of the people who possess this city and land.\"'),(10106,'Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(10107,' “Then verily, Sir stranger, I will shew thee the palace as thou dost bid me, for it lies hard by the house of my own noble father.'),(10108,'  Only go thou quietly, and I will lead the way.  But turn not thine eyes upon any man nor question any,'),(10109,' for the men here endure not stranger-folk, nor do they give kindly welcome to him who comes from another land.'),(10110,' They, indeed, trusting in the speed of their swift ships,  cross over the great gulf of the sea, for this the Earth-shaker has granted them; '),(10111,'and their ships are swift as a bird on the wing or as a thought.” '),(10112,' \nSo speaking, Pallas Athena led the way quickly, '),(10113,' and he followed in the footsteps of the goddess. '),(10114,' And as he went through the city in the midst of them, the Phaeacians, famed for their ships, took no heed of him, '),(10115,'for fair-tressed Athena, the dread goddess, would not suffer it, but shed about him a wondrous mist, for her heart was kind toward him.'),(10116,' And Odysseus marvelled at the harbors and the stately ships, at the meeting-places where the heroes themselves gathered, and the walls, long and  high and crowned with palisades, a wonder to behold. '),(10117,' But when they had come to the glorious palace of the king, the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, was the first to speak, saying:'),(10118,'“Here, Sir stranger, is the house which thou didst bid me shew to thee,'),(10119,' and thou wilt find the kings, fostered of Zeus,  feasting at the banquet.'),(10120,' Go thou within, and let thy heart fear nothing;'),(10121,' for a bold man is better in all things, though he be a stranger from another land.'),(10122,'The queen shalt thou approach first in the palace;'),(10123,'  Arete is the name by which she is called,  and she is sprung from the same line as is the king Alcinous. '),(10124,'Nausithous at the first was born from the earth-shaker Poseidon and Periboea, the comeliest of women, youngest daughter of great-hearted Eurymedon, who once was king over the insolent Giants.'),(10125,'  But he brought destruction on his froward people, and was himself destroyed.'),(10126,' But with Periboea lay Poseidon and begat a son, great-hearted Nausithous, who ruled over the Phaeacians; '),(10127,'and Nausithous begat Rhexenor and Alcinous.'),(10128,' Rhexenor, when as yet he had no son, Apollo of the silver bow smote  in his hall, a bridegroom though he was, and he left only one daughter, Arete.'),(10129,' Her Alcinous made his wife, and honored her as no other woman on earth is honored, of all those who in these days direct their households in subjection to their husbands;'),(10130,'so heartily is she honored,  and has ever been, by her children and by Alcinous himself and by the people, who look upon her as upon a goddess, and greet her as she goes through the city.'),(10131,'For she of herself is no wise lacking in good understanding,'),(10132,'  and for the women to whom she has good will she makes an end of strife even among their husbands. '),(10133,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 7.75-7.77'),(10134,' \nSo saying, flashing-eyed Athena departed over the unresting sea, and left lovely Scheria.  She came to Marathon and broad-wayed Athens, and entered the well-built house of Erectheus; '),(10135,'but Odysseus went to the glorious palace of Alcinous.'),(10136,' There he stood, and his heart pondered much before he reached the threshold of bronze;'),(10137,'for there was a gleam as of sun or moon  over the high-roofed house of great-hearted Alcinous. '),(10138,'Of bronze were the walls that stretched this way and that from the threshold to the innermost chamber, and around was a cornice of cyanus.'),(10139,' Golden were the doors that shut in the well-built house, '),(10140,'and doorposts of silver were set in a threshold of bronze. Of silver was the lintel above, and of gold the handle.'),(10141,'  On either side of the door there stood gold and silver dogs, which Hephaestus had fashioned with cunning skill to guard the palace of great-hearted Alcinous; immortal were they and ageless all their days.'),(10142,'  Within, seats were fixed along the wall on either hand, from the threshold to the innermost chamber, and on them were thrown robes of soft fabric, cunningly woven, the handiwork of women.'),(10143,' On these the leaders of the Phaeacians were wont to sit drinking and eating,'),(10144,'for they had unfailing store.'),(10145,'  And golden youths stood on well-built pedestals, holding lighted torches in their hands to give light by night to the banqueters in the hall. '),(10146,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 7.103-7.106'),(10147,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 7.107'),(10148,' For as the Phaeacian men are skilled above all others in speeding a swift ship upon the sea, so are the women  cunning workers at the loom, '),(10149,'for Athena has given to them above all others skill in fair handiwork, and an understanding heart.'),(10150,' But without the courtyard, hard by the door, is a great orchard of four acres, '),(10151,' and a hedge runs about it on either side. '),(10152,'Therein grow trees, tall and luxuriant,  pears and pomegranates and apple-trees with their bright fruit, and sweet figs, and luxuriant olives.'),(10153,' Of these the fruit perishes not nor fails in winter or in summer, but lasts throughout the year; '),(10154,'and ever does the west wind, as it blows, quicken to life some fruits, and ripen others; '),(10155,' pear upon pear waxes ripe, apple upon apple, cluster upon cluster, and fig upon fig.'),(10156,' There, too, is his fruitful vineyard planted, one part of which, a warm spot on level ground, is being dried in the sun, while other grapes men are gathering,  and others, too, they are treading; '),(10157,'but in front are unripe grapes that are shedding the blossom, and others that are turning purple.'),(10158,' There again, by the last row of the vines, grow trim garden beds of every sort, blooming the year through, '),(10159,'and therein are two springs, one of which sends its water throughout all the garden,  while the other, over against it, flows beneath the threshold of the court toward the high house; from this the townsfolk drew their water. '),(10160,'Such were the glorious gifts of the gods in the palace of Alcinous.'),(10161,' There the much-enduring goodly Odysseus stood and gazed. '),(10162,'But when he had marvelled in his heart at all things,  he passed quickly over the threshold into the house. '),(10163,'There he found the leaders and counsellors of the Phaeacians pouring libations from their cups to the keen-sighted Argeiphontes, to whom they were wont to pour the wine last of all, when they were minded to go to their rest. '),(10164,'But the much-enduring goodly Odysseus went through the hall,  wrapped in the thick mist which Athena had shed about him, till he came to Arete and to Alcinous the king.'),(10165,' About the knees of Arete Odysseus cast his hands, and straightway the wondrous mist melted from him, '),(10166,' and a hush fell upon all that were in the room at sight of the man, '),(10167,'But Odysseus made his prayer:'),(10168,'But Odysseus made his prayer:'),(10169,'“Arete, daughter of godlike Rhexenor, to thy husband and to thy knees am I come after many toils,—aye and to these banqueters, '),(10170,'to whom may the gods grant happiness in life, and may each of them hand down to his children  the wealth in his halls, and the dues of honor which the people have given him. But for me do ye speed my sending, that I may come to my native land, and that quickly; for long time have I been suffering woes far from my friends.” '),(10171,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 7.151-7.152'),(10172,' \nSo saying he sat down on the hearth in the ashes by the fire, '),(10173,'and they were all hushed in silence.'),(10174,'  But at length there spoke among them the old lord Echeneus, who was an elder among the Phaeacians, well skilled in speech, and understanding all the wisdom of old.'),(10175,' He with good intent addressed the assembly, and said: '),(10176,'“Alcinous, lo, this is not the better way, nor is it seemly,  that a stranger should sit upon the ground on the hearth in the ashes; but these others hold back waiting for thy word.'),(10177,' Come, make the stranger to arise, and set him upon a silver-studded chair, and bid the heralds mix wine,  that we may pour libations also to Zeus, who hurls the thunderbolt; for he ever attends upon reverend suppliants. '),(10178,' And let the housewife give supper to the stranger of the store that is in the house.”'),(10179,'When the strong and mighty Alcinous heard this, he took by the hand Odysseus, the wise and crafty-minded, and raised him from the hearth, and set him upon a bright chair  from which he bade his son, the kindly Laodamas, to rise; for he sat next to him, and was his best beloved.'),(10180,' Then a handmaid brought water for the hands in a fair pitcher of gold, and poured it over a silver basin, for him to wash, '),(10181,'and beside him drew up a polished table.'),(10182,'  And the grave housewife brought and set before him bread, and therewith dainties in abundance, giving freely of her store.'),(10183,' So the much-enduring goodly Odysseus drank and ate; '),(10184,'and then the mighty Alcinous spoke to the herald, and said:'),(10185,'“Pontonous, mix the bowl, and serve wine  to all in the hall, that we may pour libations also to Zeus, who hurls the thunderbolt; for he ever attends upon reverend suppliants.\"'),(10186,'He spoke, and Pontonous mixed the honey-hearted wine, and served out to all, pouring first drops for libation into the cups.'),(10187,' But when they had poured libations, and had drunk to their heart\'s content,  Alcinous addressed the assembly, and spoke among them:'),(10188,'“Hearken to me, leaders and counsellors of the Phaeacians, that I may say what the heart in my breast bids me.'),(10189,' Now that ye have finished your feast, go each of you to his house to rest. '),(10190,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 7.189-7.196'),(10191,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 7.196-7.198'),(10192,' But if he is one of the immortals come down from heaven,  then is this some new thing which the gods are planning; '),(10193,'for ever heretofore have they been wont to appear to us in manifest form, when we sacrifice to them glorious hecatombs, and they feast among us, sitting even where we sit. '),(10194,'Aye, and if one of us as a lone wayfarer meets them,  they use no concealment, for we are of near kin to them, as are the Cyclopes and the wild tribes of the Giants.\"'),(10195,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(10196,' “Alcinous, far from thee be that thought; '),(10197,'for I am not like the immortals, who hold broad heaven,  either in stature or in form, but like mortal men. '),(10198,'Whomsoever ye know among men who bear greatest burden of woe, to them might I liken myself in my sorrows.'),(10199,' Yea, and I could tell a yet longer tale of all the evils which I have endured by the will of the gods.'),(10200,'  But as for me, suffer me now to eat, despite my grief; '),(10201,'for there is nothing more shameless than a hateful belly, which bids a man perforce take thought thereof, be he never so sore distressed and laden with grief at heart, even as I, too, am laden with grief at heart, yet ever does my belly  bid me eat and drink, and makes me forget all that I have suffered, and commands me to eat my fill.'),(10202,' But do ye make haste at break of day, that ye may set me, hapless one, on the soil of my native land, even after my many woes.'),(10203,' Yea, let life leave me, when I have seen once more  my possessions, my slaves, and my great high-roofed house.”'),(10204,'So he spoke, and they all praised his words, and bade send the stranger on his way, since he had spoken fittingly. '),(10205,'Then when they had poured libations, and had drunk to their heart\'s content, they went each man to his home, to take their rest,  and goodly Odysseus was left behind in the hall, and beside him sat Arete and godlike Alcinous; '),(10206,'and the handmaids cleared away the dishes of the feast.'),(10207,' Then white-armed Arete was the first to speak; '),(10208,' for, as she saw it, she knew his  fair raiment, the mantle and tunic, which she herself had wrought with her handmaids. '),(10209,' And she spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(10210,'\n“Stranger, this question will I myself ask thee first.'),(10211,' Who gave thee this raiment?'),(10212,' Who gave thee this raiment?'),(10213,' Didst thou not say that thou camest hither wandering over the sea?” '),(10214,' Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said: '),(10215,' “Hard were it, O queen, to tell to the end the tale of my woes, since full many have the heavenly gods given me.'),(10216,' But this will I tell thee, of which thou dost ask and enquire.'),(10217,' There is an isle, Ogygia, which lies far off in the sea.'),(10218,'  Therein dwells the fair-tressed daughter of Atlas, guileful Calypso, a dread goddess, '),(10219,' and with her no one either of gods or mortals hath aught to do; '),(10220,'but me in my wretchedness did fate bring to her hearth alone, for Zeus had smitten my swift ship with his bright thunderbolt,  and had shattered it in the midst of the wine-dark sea. '),(10221,' There all the rest of my trusty comrades perished, but I clasped in my arms the keel of my curved ship and was borne drifting for nine days, '),(10222,'and on the tenth black night the gods brought me to the isle, Ogygia, where  the fair-tressed Calypso dwells, a dread goddess. She took me to her home with kindly welcome, and gave me food, and said that she would make me immortal and ageless all my days;'),(10223,' but she could never persuade the heart in my breast.'),(10224,' There for seven years\' space I remained continually, and ever  with my tears would I wet the immortal raiment which Calypso gave me. '),(10225,'But when the eight year came in circling course, then she roused me and bade me go, either because of some message from Zeus, or because her own mind was turned. '),(10226,' And she sent me on my way on a raft, stoutly bound, and gave me abundant store  of bread and sweet wine, and clad me in immortal raiment, and sent forth a gentle wind and warm.'),(10227,' So for seventeen days I sailed over the sea, and on the eighteenth appeared the shadowy mountains of your land; and my heart was glad,  ill-starred that I was;'),(10228,'for verily I was yet to have fellowship with great woe, which Poseidon, the earth-shaker, sent upon me. For he stirred up the winds against me and stayed my course, and wondrously roused the sea, nor would the wave suffer me to be borne upon my raft, as I groaned ceaselessly.'),(10229,' My raft indeed the storm shattered,'),(10230,' but by swimming I clove my way through yon gulf of the sea, until the wind and the waves, as they bore me, brought me to your shores.'),(10231,' There, had I sought to land, the waves would have hurled me upon the shore, and dashed me against the great crags and a cheerless place, '),(10232,' but I gave way, and swam back until I came to a river, where seemed to me the best place, since it was smooth of rocks, and besides there was shelter from the wind.'),(10233,' Forth then I staggered, and sank down, gasping for breath, and immortal night came on. '),(10234,'Then I went forth from the heaven-fed river,  and lay down to sleep in the bushes, gathering leaves about me; '),(10235,' and a god shed over me infinite sleep. '),(10236,' So there among the leaves I slept, my heart sore stricken, the whole night through, until the morning and until midday; '),(10237,'and the sun turned to his setting ere sweet sleep released me.'),(10238,'  Then I saw the handmaids of thy daughter on the shore at play, and amid them was she, fair as the goddesses.'),(10239,'To her I made my prayer;'),(10240,' and she in no wise failed in good understanding, to do as thou wouldst not deem that one of younger years would do on meeting thee; '),(10241,'for younger folk are ever thoughtless.'),(10242,'  She gave bread in plenty and sparkling wine, and bathed me in the river, and gave me this raiment.'),(10243,' In this, for all my sorrows, have I told thee the truth.”'),(10244,'\nThen in turn Alcinous answered him, and said:'),(10245,'“Stranger, verily my daughter was not minded aright in this,  that she did not bring thee to our house with her maidens. Yet it was to her first that thou didst make thy prayer.”'),(10246,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(10247,' “Prince, rebuke not for this, I pray thee, thy blameless daughter. '),(10248,'She did indeed bid me follow with her maidens,  but I would not for fear and shame, lest haply thy heart should darken with wrath as thou sawest it; '),(10249,'for we are quick to anger, we tribes of men upon the earth.\"'),(10250,'And again Alcinous answered him, and said:'),(10251,'“Stranger, not such is the heart in my breast,  to be filled with wrath without a cause. '),(10252,' Better is due measure in all things.'),(10253,'I would, O father Zeus, and Athena and Apollo, that thou, so goodly a man, and like-minded with me, wouldst have my daughter to wife, and be called my son, and abide here; '),(10254,'a house and possessions would I give thee,  if thou shouldst choose to remain, '),(10255,'but against thy will shall no one of the Phaeacians keep thee; '),(10256,'let not that be the will of father Zeus. '),(10257,' But as for thy sending, that thou mayest know it surely, I appoint a time thereto, even the morrow. '),(10258,'Then shalt thou lie down, overcome by sleep, and they shall row thee over the calm sea until thou comest  to thy country and thy house, or to whatsoever place thou wilt, aye though it be even far beyond Euboea, which those of our people who saw it, when they carried fair-haired Rhadamanthus to visit Tityus, the son of Gaea, say is the furthest of lands.'),(10259,'  Thither they went, and without toil accomplished their journey, and on the selfsame day came back home.'),(10260,' So shalt thou, too, know for thyself how far my ships are the best, and my youths at tossing the brine with the oar-blade.\"'),(10261,'So said he, and the much-enduring goodly Odysseus was glad;  and he spoke in prayer, and said: '),(10262,'“Father Zeus, grant that Alcinous may bring to pass all that he has said.'),(10263,' So shall his fame be unquenchable over the earth, the giver of grain, and I shall reach my native land.\"'),(10264,'Thus they spoke to one another, '),(10265,' and white-armed Arete bade her maidens place a bedstead under cover of the portico, and to lay on it fair blankets of purple, and to spread there over coverlets, and on these to put fleecy cloaks for clothing.'),(10266,' So they went forth from the hall with torches in their hands.'),(10267,'  But when they had busily spread the stout-built bedstead, they came to Odysseus, and called to him, and said:'),(10268,'thy bed is made.”'),(10269,'thy bed is made.”'),(10270,'Thus they spoke, and welcome did it seem to him to lay him down to sleep.'),(10271,' So there he slept, the much-enduring goodly Odysseus,  on the corded bedstead under the echoing portico. '),(10272,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 7.346-7.347'),(10273,' As soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, the strong and mighty Alcinous rose from his couch, and up rose also Zeus-born Odysseus, the sacker of cities.'),(10274,' And the strong and mighty Alcinous led the way  to the place of assembly of the Phaeacians, which was builded for them hard by their ships.'),(10275,'Thither they came and sat down on the polished stones close by one another;'),(10276,' and Pallas Athena went throughout the city, in the likeness of the herald of wise Alcinous, devising a return for great-hearted Odysseus.  To each man\'s side she came, and spoke and said:'),(10277,'“Hither now, leaders and counsellors of the Phaeacians, come to the place of assembly, that you may learn of the stranger who has newly come to the palace of wise Alcinous after his wanderings over the sea, and in form is like unto the immortals.\"'),(10278,'  So saying she roused the spirit and heart of each man,'),(10279,' and speedily the place of assembly and the seats were filled with men that gathered.'),(10280,' And many marvelled at the sight of the wise son of Laertes, '),(10281,'for wondrous was the grace that Athena shed upon his head and shoulders;  and she made him taller and sturdier to behold, that he might be welcomed by all the Phaeacians, and win awe and reverence, and might accomplish the many feats wherein the Phaeacians made trial of Odysseus.'),(10282,' Now when they were assembled and met together,  Alcinous addressed their assembly and spoke among them:'),(10283,'“Hearken to me, leaders and counsellors of the Phaeacians, that I may speak what the heart in my breast bids me.'),(10284,' This stranger—I know not who he is—has come to my house in his wanderings, whether from men of the east or of the west.'),(10285,'  He urges that he be sent on his way, and prays for assurance,'),(10286,' and let us on our part, as of old we were wont, speed on his sending; '),(10287,' for verily no man soever who comes to my house, abides here long in sorrow for lack of sending. '),(10288,'Nay come, let us draw a black ship down to the bright sea  for her first voyage, and let men choose two and fifty youths from out the people, even those that have heretofore been the best.'),(10289,' And when you have all duly lashed the oars to the thole-pins, go ashore,'),(10290,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 8.38-8.39'),(10291,' and then go your way to my house, and prepare a feast with speed; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 38 to line 39'),(10292,' To the youths this is my command,'),(10293,' but do you others, the sceptred kings, come to my fair palace, that we may entertain yon stranger in the halls; and let no man say me nay.'),(10294,' And summon hither the divine minstrel, Demodocus; '),(10295,'for to him above all others has the god granted skill in song,  to give delight in whatever way his spirit prompts him to sing.”'),(10296,' \nSo saying, he led the way, and the sceptred kings followed him, '),(10297,'while a herald went for the divine minstrel.'),(10298,' And chosen youths, two and fifty, went, as he bade, to the shore of the unresting sea.'),(10299,'  And when they had come down to the ship and to the sea, they drew the black ship down to the deep water, and placed the mast and sail in the black ship, and fitted the oars in the leathern thole-straps, all in due order, and spread the white sail.'),(10300,' Well out in the roadstead they moored the ship,'),(10301,'  and then went their way to the great palace of the wise Alcinous.'),(10302,' Filled were the porticoes and courts and rooms with the men that gathered, '),(10303,' for many there were, both young and old.'),(10304,'For them Alcinous slaughtered twelve sheep,  and eight white-tusked boars, and two oxen of shambling gait. '),(10305,'These they flayed and dressed, and made ready a goodly feast.'),(10306,'\nThen the herald drew near, leading the good minstrel, whom the Muse loved above all other men, and gave him both good and evil; '),(10307,'of his sight she deprived him, but gave him the gift of sweet song.'),(10308,'  For him Pontonous, the herald, set a silver-studded chair in the midst of the banqueters, leaning it against a tall pillar, '),(10309,' and he hung the clear-toned lyre from a peg close above his head, and showed him how to reach it with his hands. '),(10310,'And beside him he placed a basket and a beautiful table,  and a cup of wine, to drink when his heart should bid him.'),(10311,'So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them. '),(10312,' But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, the Muse moved the minstrel to sing of the glorious deeds of warriors, from that lay the fame whereof had then reached broad heaven,  even the quarrel of Odysseus and Achilles, son of Peleus, how once they strove with furious words at a rich feast of the gods, and Agamemnon, king of men, was glad at heart that the best of the Achaeans were quarrelling;'),(10313,'for thus Phoebus Apollo, in giving his response, had told him that it should be,  in sacred Pytho, when he passed over the threshold of stone to enquire of the oracle.'),(10314,' For then the beginning of woe was rolling upon Trojans and Danaans through the will of great Zeus. '),(10315,' \nThis song the famous minstrel sang; '),(10316,'but Odysseus grasped his great purple cloak with his stout hands,  and drew it down over his head, and hid his comely face; '),(10317,'for he had shame of the Phaeacians as he let fall tears from beneath his eyebrows.'),(10318,' Yea, and as often as the divine minstrel ceased his singing, Odysseus would wipe away his tears and draw the cloak from off his head, and taking the two-handled cup would pour libations to the gods.'),(10319,'  But as often as he began again, and the nobles of the Phaeacians bade him sing, because they took pleasure in his lay, Odysseus would again cover his head and moan.'),(10320,' Now from all the rest he concealed the tears that he shed, but Alcinous alone marked him and took heed,  for he sat by him, and heard him groaning heavily.'),(10321,' And straightway he spoke among the Phaeacians, lovers of the oar:'),(10322,'“Hear me, ye leaders and counsellors of the Phaeacians, '),(10323,'already have we satisfied our hearts with the equal banquet and with the lyre, which is the companion of the rich feast.'),(10324,'  But now let us go forth, and make trial of all manner of games, that yon stranger may tell his friends, when he returns home, how far we excel other men in boxing and wrestling and leaping and in speed of foot.\"'),(10325,'So saying, he led the way, and they followed him.'),(10326,'  From the peg the herald hung the clear-toned lyre, and took Demodocus by the hand, and led him forth from the hall, '),(10327,'guiding him by the self-same road by which the others, the nobles of the Phaeacians, had gone to gaze upon the games.'),(10328,'They went their way to the place of assembly, and with them went a great throng,  past counting; '),(10329,' and up rose many noble youths.'),(10330,'There rose Acroneus, and Ocyalus, and Elatreus, and Nauteus, and Prymneus, and Anchialus, and Eretmeus, and Ponteus, and Proreus, Thoon and Anabesineus,  and Amphialus, son of Polyneus, son of Tecton; '),(10331,'and up rose also Euryalus, the peer of man-destroying Ares, the son of Naubolus, who in comeliness and form was the best of all the Phaeacians after peerless Laodamas; '),(10332,'and up rose the three sons of noble Alcinous, Laodamas, and Halius, and godlike Clytoneus. '),(10333,' These then first made trial in the foot-race.'),(10334,' A course was marked out for them from the turning point,'),(10335,' and they all sped swiftly, raising the dust of the plain; '),(10336,'but among them noble Clytoneus was far the best at running,'),(10337,'and by as far as is the range of a team of mules in fallow land,  by so far he shot to the front and reached the host, and the others were left behind.'),(10338,' Then they made trial of toilsome wrestling,'),(10339,' and here in turn Euryalus excelled all the princes.'),(10340,'And in leaping Amphialus was best of all,'),(10341,'  and with the discus again far the best of all was Elatreus,  and in boxing Laodamas, the good son of Alcinous.'),(10342,'But when the hearts of all had taken pleasure in the contests, Laodamas, the son of Alcinous, spoke among them:'),(10343,'\n“Come, friends, let us ask yon stranger whether he knows and has learned any contests. '),(10344,'In build, surely, he is no mean man,  in thighs and calves, and in his two arms above, his stout neck, and his great might.'),(10345,' In no wise does he lack aught of the strength of youth, but he has been broken by many troubles.'),(10346,' For to my mind there is naught worse than the sea to confound a man, be he never so strong.\"'),(10347,'  And Euryalus in turn answered him, and said:'),(10348,'“Laodamas, this word of thine is right fitly spoken.'),(10349,' Go now thyself and challenge him, and make known thy word.\"'),(10350,'Now when the good son of Alcinous heard this he came and took his stand in the midst and spoke to Odysseus:'),(10351,'  “Come, Sir stranger, do thou, too, make trial of the contests, if thou knowest any;'),(10352,'and it must be that thou knowest contests, '),(10353,'for there is no greater glory for a man so long as he lives than that which he achieves by his own hands and his feet.'),(10354,' Nay, come, make trial, and cast away care from thy heart.'),(10355,'  Thy journey shall no more be long delayed, nay, even now thy ship is launched and the crew is ready.”'),(10356,' Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(10357,' “Laodamas, why do ye mock me with this challenge? '),(10358,'Sorrow is in my mind far more than contests,  seeing that in time past I have suffered much and toiled much, and now I sit in the midst of your assembly, longing for my return home, and making my prayer to the king and to all the people.”'),(10359,' Then again Euryalus made answer and taunted him to his face:'),(10360,'“Nay verily, stranger, for I do not liken thee to a man that is skilled  in contests, such as abound among men, but to one who, faring to and fro with his benched ship, is a captain of sailors who are merchantmen, one who is mindful of his freight, and has charge of a home-borne cargo, and the gains of his greed.'),(10361,' Thou dost not look like an athlete.” '),(10362,' \n  Then with an angry glance from beneath his brows Odysseus of many wiles answered him:'),(10363,' thou art as one blind with folly.'),(10364,' thou art as one blind with folly.'),(10365,' So true is it that the gods do not give gracious gifts to all alike, not form nor mind nor eloquence. '),(10366,'For one man is inferior in comeliness,  but the god sets a crown of beauty upon his words, and men look upon him with delight, '),(10367,' and he speaks on unfalteringly with sweet modesty, and is conspicuous among the gathered people, and as he goes through the city men gaze upon him as upon a god.'),(10368,'Another again is in comeliness like the immortals,  but no crown of grace is set about his words. So, in thy case, thy comeliness is preeminent, nor could a god himself mend it, but in mind thou art stunted. '),(10369,' Thou hast stirred the spirit in my breast by speaking thus unmannerly.'),(10370,'I am not unskilled in sports  as thou pratest, nay, methinks I was among the first so long as I trusted in my youth and in my hands.'),(10371,' But now I am bound by suffering and pains; '),(10372,' for much have I endured in passing through wars of men and the grievous waves.'),(10373,'But even so, though I have suffered much, I will make trial of the contests, '),(10374,' for thy word has stung me to the heart, and thou hast provoked me with thy speech.”'),(10375,'He spoke, and, leaping up with his cloak about him as it was, seized a discus larger than the rest and thick, no little heavier than those with which the Phaeacians were wont to contend one with another.'),(10376,' This with a whirl he sent from his stout hand,  and the stone hummed as it flew; '),(10377,'and down they crouched to the earth, the Phaeacians of the long oars, men famed for their ships, beneath the rush of the stone.'),(10378,' Past the marks of all it flew, speeding lightly from his hand, '),(10379,'and Athena, in the likeness of a man, set the mark, and she spoke and addressed him:'),(10380,'\n  “Even a blind man, stranger, could distinguish this mark, groping for it with his hands, for it is in nowise confused with the throng of the others, but is far the first.'),(10381,' Be thou of good cheer for this bout at least:'),(10382,' no one of the Phaeacians will reach this, or cast beyond it.” '),(10383,' \nSo she spoke, and the much-enduring goodly Odysseus was glad,  rejoicing that he saw a true friend in the lists. '),(10384,'  Then with a lighter heart he spoke among the Phaeacians:'),(10385,'\n“Reach this now, young men; '),(10386,'and presently, methinks, I will send another after it, as far or even further. '),(10387,' Of the rest, if any man\'s heart and spirit bid him,  let him come hither and make trial—for ye have greatly angered me—be it in boxing or in wrestling, aye, or in running, I care not; let any one come of all the Phaeacians, save Laodamas alone.'),(10388,' and who would quarrel with one that entertains him? '),(10389,' and who would quarrel with one that entertains him? '),(10390,'Foolish is that man and worthless,  who challenges to a contest the host who receives him in a strange land; '),(10391,'he does but mar his own fortunes.'),(10392,' But of all the rest I refuse none, and make light of none, but am fain to know them, and make trial of them man to man.'),(10393,' For in all things I am no weakling, even in all the contests that are practised among men.'),(10394,'  Well do I know how to handle the polished bow,'),(10395,' and ever would I be the first to shoot and smite my man in the throng of the foe, even though many comrades stood by me and were shooting at the men.'),(10396,' Only Philoctetes excelled me with the bow  in the land of the Trojans, when we Achaeans shot. '),(10397,' But of all others I declare that I am best by far, of all mortals that are now upon the earth and eat bread.'),(10398,' Yet with men of former days I will not seek to vie, with Heracles or with Eurytus of Oechalia,  who strove even with the immortals in archery. '),(10399,' Wherefore great Eurytus died soon, nor did old age come upon him in his halls, '),(10400,'for Apollo waxed wroth and slew him, because he had challenged him to a contest with the bow.'),(10401,' And with the spear I throw farther than any other man can shoot with an arrow.'),(10402,'  In the foot race alone I fear that someone of the Phaeacians may out strip me, '),(10403,'for cruelly have I been broken amid the many waves, since there was in my ship no lasting store of provisions; '),(10404,'therefore my limbs are loosened.\"'),(10405,'So he spoke and they were all hushed in silence; '),(10406,'  but Alcinous alone answered him and said:'),(10407,'“Stranger, since not ungraciously dost thou speak thus in our midst, but art minded to shew forth the prowess which waits upon thee, in anger that yonder man came up to thee in the lists and taunted thee in a way in which no mortal would make light of thy prowess,  who knew in his heart how to speak fitly; '),(10408,'come, now, hearken to my words, that thou mayest tell to another hero, when in thy halls thou art feasting with thy wife and children, and rememberest our skill, what feats  Zeus has vouchsafed to us from our fathers\' days even until now. '),(10409,'For we are not faultless boxers or wrestlers, but in the foot race we run swiftly, and we are the best seamen; and ever to us is the banquet dear, and the lyre, and the dance, and changes of raiment, and warm baths, and the couch. '),(10410,'   But come now, all ye that are the best dancers of the Phaeacians, make sport, that the stranger may tell his friends on reaching home how far we surpass others in seamanship and in fleetness of foot, and in the dance and in song.'),(10411,' And let one go straightway  and fetch for Demodocus the clear-toned lyre which lies somewhere in our halls.”'),(10412,'So spoke Alcinous the godlike, and the herald rose to fetch the hollow lyre from the palace of the king.'),(10413,' Then stood up masters of the lists, nine in all, men chosen from out the people, who in their gatherings were wont to order all things aright.  They levelled a place for the dance, and marked out a fair wide ring,'),(10414,' and the herald came near, bearing the clear-toned lyre for Demodocus.'),(10415,' He then moved into the midst, '),(10416,'and around him stood boys in the first bloom of youth, well skilled in the dance, and they smote the goodly dancing floor with their feet.'),(10417,' And Odysseus  gazed at the twinklings of their feet and marvelled in spirit.'),(10418,'But the minstrel struck the chords in prelude to his sweet lay and sang of the love of Ares and Aphrodite of the fair crown, how first they lay together in the house of Hephaestus secretly; and Ares gave her many gifts, and shamed the bed  of the lord Hephaestus.'),(10419,' But straightway one came to him with tidings, even Helius, who had marked them as they lay together in love.'),(10420,' And when Hephaestus heard the grievous tale, he went his way to his smithy, pondering evil in the deep of his heart, and set on the anvil block the great anvil and forged bonds  which might not be broken or loosed, that the lovers might bide fast where they were. '),(10421,' But when he had fashioned the snare in his wrath against Ares, he went to his chamber where lay his bed, and everywhere round about the bed-posts he spread the bonds, '),(10422,'and many too were hung from above, from the roof-beams,  fine as spiders\' webs, so that no one even of the blessed gods could see them, '),(10423,'so exceeding craftily were they fashioned.'),(10424,' But when he had spread all his snare about the couch, he made as though he would go to Lemnos, that well-built citadel, which is in his eyes far the dearest of all lands.'),(10425,'  And no blind watch did Ares of the golden rein keep, when he saw Hephaestus, famed for his handicraft, departing, '),(10426,'but he went his way to the house of famous Hephaestus, eager for the love of Cytherea of the fair crown.'),(10427,' Now she had but newly come from the presence of her father, the mighty son of Cronos,  and had sat her down.'),(10428,'And Ares came into the house and clasped her hand and spoke and addressed her:'),(10429,'\n“Come, love, let us to bed and take our joy, couched together.'),(10430,' For Hephaestus is no longer here in the land, but has now gone, I ween, to Lemnos, to visit the Sintians of savage speech.” '),(10431,'  So he spoke, and a welcome thing it seemed to her to lie with him.'),(10432,'So they two went to the couch, and lay them down to sleep,'),(10433,'and about them clung the cunning bonds of the wise Hephaestus, nor could they in any wise stir their limbs or raise them up.'),(10434,' Then at length they learned that there was no more escaping.'),(10435,'  And near to them came the famous god of the two strong arms, having turned back before he reached the land of Lemnos; '),(10436,'for Helius had kept watch for him and had brought him word.'),(10437,' So he went to his house with a heavy heart, '),(10438,'and stood at the gateway, and fierce anger seized him.'),(10439,' And terribly he cried out and called to all the gods:'),(10440,'\n“Father Zeus, and ye other blessed gods that are forever, come hither that ye may see a laughable matter and a monstrous, even how Aphrodite, daughter of Zeus, scorns me for that I am lame and loves destructive Ares  because he is comely and strong of limb, whereas I was born misshapen.'),(10441,' Yet for this is none other to blame but my two parents—would they had never begotten me!'),(10442,' But ye shall see where these two have gone up into my bed and sleep together in love; and I am troubled at the sight.'),(10443,'  Yet, methinks, they will not wish to lie longer thus, no, not for a moment, how loving soever they are.'),(10444,' Soon shall both lose their desire to sleep;'),(10445,'but the snare and the bonds shall hold them until her father pays back to me all the gifts of wooing that I gave him for the sake of his shameless girl;  for his daughter is fair but bridles not her passion.”'),(10446,'So he spoke and the gods gathered to the house of the brazen floor.'),(10447,' Poseidon came, the earth-enfolder, and the helper Hermes came, and the lord Apollo, the archer god.'),(10448,' Now the goddesses abode for shame each in her own house, '),(10449,' but the gods, the givers of good things, stood in the gateway; '),(10450,'and unquenchable laughter arose among the blessed gods as they saw the craft of wise Hephaestus.'),(10451,' And thus would one speak, with a glance at his neighbor:'),(10452,'\n“Ill deeds thrive not. '),(10453,' The slow catches the swift;  even as now Hephaestus, slow though he is, has out-stripped Ares for all that he is the swiftest of the gods who hold Olympus. Lame though he is, he has caught him by craft,'),(10454,'wherefore Ares owes the fine of the adulterer.\"'),(10455,'Thus they spoke to one another.'),(10456,' But to Hermes the lord Apollo, son of Zeus, said:'),(10457,'\n  “Hermes, son of Zeus, messenger, giver of good things, wouldst thou in sooth be willing, even though ensnared with strong bonds, to lie on a couch by the side of golden Aphrodite?\"'),(10458,'Then the messenger, Argeiphontes, answered him:'),(10459,'“Would that this might befall, lord Apollo, thou archer god— '),(10460,' that thrice as many bonds inextricable might clasp me about and ye gods, aye, and all the goddesses too might be looking on, but that I might sleep by the side of golden Aphrodite.” '),(10461,' \nSo he spoke and laughter arose among the immortal gods.'),(10462,' Yet Poseidon laughed not, but ever besought  Hephaestus, the famous craftsman, to set Ares free; '),(10463,'and he spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(10464,'“Loose him,'),(10465,'and I promise, as thou biddest me, that he shall himself pay thee all that is right in the presence of the immortal gods.\"'),(10466,'Then the famous god of the two strong arms answered him:'),(10467,' “Ask not this of me, Poseidon, thou earth-enfolder.'),(10468,' A sorry thing to be sure of is the surety for a sorry knave.'),(10469,' How could I put thee in bonds among the immortal gods, if Ares should avoid both the debt and the bonds and depart?\"'),(10470,'Then again Poseidon, the earth-shaker, answered him:'),(10471,'  “Hephaestus, even if Ares shall avoid the debt and flee away, I will myself pay thee this.\"'),(10472,'Then the famous god of the two strong arms answered him:'),(10473,' “It may not be that I should say thee nay, nor were it seemly.\"'),(10474,'So saying the mighty Hephaestus loosed the bonds '),(10475,' and the two, when they were freed from that bond so strong, sprang up straightway. And Ares departed to Thrace, but she, the laughter-loving Aphrodite, went to Cyprus, to Paphos,'),(10476,'  where is her demesne and fragrant altar.'),(10477,'There the Graces bathed her and anointed her with  immortal oil, such as gleams upon the gods that are forever.'),(10478,' And they clothed her in lovely raiment, a wonder to behold.'),(10479,'\nThis song the famous minstrel sang; and Odysseus was glad at heart as he listened, and so too were the Phaeacians of the long oars, men famed for their ships.'),(10480,'\n  Then Alcinous bade Halius and Laodamas dance alone, for no one could vie with them. '),(10481,'And when they had taken in their hands the beautiful ball of purple, which wise Polybus had made for them, the one  would lean backward and toss it toward the shadowy clouds, and the other would leap up from the earth and skilfully catch it before his feet touched the ground again.'),(10482,' But when they had tried their skill in throwing the ball straight up, the two fell to dancing on the bounteous earth, ever tossing the ball to and fro, '),(10483,' and the other youths  stood in the lists and beat time, and thereat a great din arose.'),(10484,'Then to Alcinous spoke goodly Odysseus:'),(10485,' “Lord Alcinous, renowned above all men, thou didst boast that thy dancers were the best, and lo, thy words are made good; '),(10486,'amazement holds me as I look on them.” '),(10487,' \n  So he spoke, and the strong and mighty Alcinous was glad; and straightway he spoke among the Phaeacians, lovers of the oar:'),(10488,'\n“Hear me, leaders and counsellors of the Phaeacians.'),(10489,' This stranger verily seems to me a man of understanding.'),(10490,' Come then, let us give him a gift of friendship, as is fitting; '),(10491,' for twelve glorious kings bear sway in our land as rulers, and I myself am the thirteenth.'),(10492,' Now do you, each of the twelve, bring a newly washed cloak and tunic, and a talent of precious gold, '),(10493,'and let us straightway bring all together,  that the stranger with our gifts in his hands may go to his supper glad at heart. '),(10494,'And let Euryalus make amends to the stranger himself with words and with a gift, for the word that he spoke was in no wise seemly.\"'),(10495,'So he spoke, and they all praised his words and bade that so it should be, and sent forth every man a herald to fetch the gifts.'),(10496,' And Euryalus in turn made answer, and said:'),(10497,'“Lord Alcinous, renowned above all men, I will indeed make amends to the stranger, as thou biddest me.'),(10498,' I will give him this sword, all of bronze, whereon is a hilt of silver, and a scabbard of new-sawn ivory  is wrought about it; '),(10499,'and it shall be to him a thing of great worth.”'),(10500,'So saying, he put into his hands the silver-studded sword, and spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(10501,' “Hail, Sir stranger; '),(10502,'but if any word has been spoken that was harsh, may the storm-winds straightway snatch it and bear it away.'),(10503,'  And for thyself, may the gods grant thee to see thy wife, and to come to thy native land, for long time hast thou been suffering woes far from thy friends.\"'),(10504,'And Odysseus of many wiles answered him:'),(10505,' “All hail to thee, too, friend; and may the gods grant thee happiness, '),(10506,'and mayest thou never hereafter miss  this sword which thou hast given me, making amends with gentle speech.”'),(10507,'He spoke, and about his shoulders hung the silver-studded sword.'),(10508,' And the sun set, and the glorious gifts were brought him.'),(10509,' These the lordly heralds bore to the palace of Alcinous, '),(10510,'and the sons of peerless Alcinous  took the beautiful gifts and set them before their honored mother. '),(10511,'And the strong and mighty Alcinous led the way, and they came in and sat down on the high seats.'),(10512,' Then to Arete spoke the mighty Alcinous:'),(10513,'\n“Bring hither, wife, a goodly chest, the best thou hast, '),(10514,' and thyself place in it a newly-washed cloak and tunic; '),(10515,'and do ye heat for the stranger a cauldron on the fire, and warm water, that when he has bathed and has seen well bestowed all the gifts which the noble Phaeacians have brought hither, he may take pleasure in the feast, and in hearing the strains of the song.'),(10516,'  And I will give him this beautiful cup of mine, wrought of gold, that he may remember me all his days as he pours libations in his halls to Zeus and to the other gods.” '),(10517,' \nSo he spoke, and Arete bade her handmaids to set a great cauldron on the fire with all speed.'),(10518,'  And they set on the blazing fire the cauldron for filling the bath, and poured in water, and took billets of wood and kindled them beneath it.'),(10519,' Then the fire played about the belly of the cauldron, and the water grew warm;'),(10520,'but meanwhile Arete brought forth for the stranger a beautiful chest from the treasure chamber, and placed in it the goodly gifts,  the raiment and the gold, which the Phaeacians gave. '),(10521,'And therein she herself placed a cloak and a fair tunic; and she spoke and addressed Odysseus with winged words:'),(10522,'\n“Look now thyself to the lid, and quickly cast a cord upon it, lest some one despoil thee of thy goods on the way, when later on  thou art lying in sweet sleep, as thou farest in the black ship.”'),(10523,'Now when the much-enduring goodly Odysseus heard these words, he straightway fitted on the lid, and quickly cast a cord upon it—a cunning knot, which queenly Circe once had taught him.'),(10524,' Then forthwith the housewife bade him  go to the bath and bathe; '),(10525,'and his heart was glad when he saw the warm bath, for he had not been wont to have such tendance from the time that he left the house of faired-haired Calypso, '),(10526,'but until then he had tendance continually as a god.'),(10527,'Now when the handmaids had bathed him and anointed him with oil,  and had cast about him a fair cloak and a tunic, he came forth from the bath, and went to join the men at their wine.'),(10528,' And Nausicaa, gifted with beauty by the gods, stood by the door-post of the well-built hall, and she marvelled at Odysseus, as her eyes beheld him,  and she spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(10529,'“Farewell, stranger, and hereafter even in thy own native land mayest thou remember me, for to me first thou owest the price of thy life.\"'),(10530,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her:'),(10531,'“Nausicaa, daughter of great-hearted Alcinous,  so may Zeus grant, the loud-thundering lord of Here, that I may reach my home and see the day of my returning.'),(10532,' Then will I even there pray to thee as to a god all my days, '),(10533,'for thou, maiden, hast given me life.\"'),(10534,' \nHe spoke, and sat down on a chair beside king Alcinous.'),(10535,' And now they were serving out portions and mixing the wine.'),(10536,' Then the herald came near, leading the good minstrel, Demodocus, held in honor by the people, '),(10537,' and seated him in the midst of the banqueters, leaning his chair against a high pillar.'),(10538,'Then to the herald said Odysseus of many wiles,  cutting off a portion of the chine of a white-tusked boar, whereof yet more was left, and there was rich fat on either side:'),(10539,'\n“Herald, take and give this portion to Demodocus, that he may eat, '),(10540,' and I will greet him, despite my grief. '),(10541,'For among all men that are upon the earth minstrels  win honor and reverence, for that the Muse has taught them the paths of song, and loves the tribe of minstrels.\"'),(10542,'So he spoke, and the herald bore the portion and placed it in the hands of the lord Demodocus,'),(10543,' and he took it and was glad at heart.'),(10544,' So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them.'),(10545,'  But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, then to Demodocus said Odysseus of many wiles:'),(10546,'\n“Demodocus, verily above all mortal men do I praise thee, '),(10547,'whether it was the Muse, the daughter of Zeus, that taught thee, or Apollo; '),(10548,'for well and truly dost thou sing of the fate of the Achaeans,  all that they wrought and suffered, and all the toils they endured, as though haply thou hadst thyself been present, or hadst heard the tale from another.'),(10549,' But come now, change thy theme, and sing of the building of the horse of wood, which Epeius made with Athena\'s help, the horse which once Odysseus led up into the citadel as a thing of guile,  when he had filled it with the men who sacked Ilios. '),(10550,' If thou dost indeed tell me this tale aright, I will declare to all mankind that the god has of a ready heart granted thee the gift of divine song.”'),(10551,'So he spoke, and the minstrel, moved by the god, began, and let his song be heard,  taking up the tale where the Argives had embarked on their benched ships and were sailing away, after casting fire on their huts, while those others led by glorious Odysseus were now sitting in the place of assembly of the Trojans, hidden in the horse; '),(10552,'for the Trojans had themselves dragged it to the citadel.'),(10553,'  So there it stood, while the people talked long as they sat about it, and could form no resolve.'),(10554,' Nay, in three ways did counsel find favour in their minds: either to cleave the hollow timber with the pitiless bronze, or to drag it to the height and cast it down the rocks, or to let it stand as a great offering to propitiate the gods,  even as in the end it was to be brought to pass; '),(10555,'for it was their fate to perish when their city should enclose the great horse of wood, wherein were sitting all the best of the Argives, bearing to the Trojans death and fate.'),(10556,' And he sang how the sons of the Achaeans  poured forth from the horse and, leaving their hollow ambush, sacked the city. '),(10557,'Of the others he sang how in divers ways they wasted the lofty city, but of Odysseus, how he went like Ares to the house of Deiphobus together with godlike Menelaus.'),(10558,' There it was, he said, that Odysseus braved the most terrible fight  and in the end conquered by the aid of great-hearted Athena.'),(10559,' \nThis song the famous minstrel sang.'),(10560,' But the heart of Odysseus was melted and tears wet his cheeks beneath his eyelids.'),(10561,' And as a woman wails and flings herself about her dear husband, who has fallen in front of his city and his people,  seeking toward off from his city and his children the pitiless day; '),(10562,'and as she beholds him dying and gasping for breath, she clings to him and shrieks aloud, '),(10563,'while the foe behind her smite her back and shoulders with their spears, and lead her away to captivity to bear toil and woe,'),(10564,' while with most pitiful grief her cheeks are wasted: '),(10565,'even so did Odysseus let fall pitiful tears from beneath his brows.'),(10566,' Now from all the rest he concealed the tears that he shed, but Alcinous alone marked him and took heed,  for he sat by him and heard him groaning heavily. '),(10567,'And straightway he spoke among the Phaeacians, lovers of the oar:'),(10568,'“Hear me, leaders and counsellors of the Phaeacians, and let Demodocus now check his clear-toned lyre, '),(10569,' for in no wise to all alike does he give pleasure with this song.'),(10570,'Ever since we began to sup and the divine minstrel was moved to sing,  from that time yon stranger has never ceased from sorrowful lamentation; '),(10571,'surely, methinks, grief has encompassed his heart.'),(10572,' Nay, let the minstrel cease, that we may all make merry, hosts and guest alike, since it is better thus.'),(10573,' Lo, for the sake of the honored stranger all these things have been made ready,  his sending and the gifts of friendship which we give him of our love. '),(10574,' Dear as a brother is the stranger and the suppliant to a man whose wits have never so short a range.'),(10575,' Therefore do not thou longer hide with crafty thought whatever I shall ask thee;'),(10576,'to speak out plainly is the better course. '),(10577,'  \n  Tell me the name by which they were wont to call thee in thy home, even thy mother and thy father and other folk besides, thy townsmen and the dwellers round about.'),(10578,' For there is no one of all mankind who is nameless, be he base man or noble, when once he has been born, but parents bestow names on all when they give them birth.'),(10579,'  And tell me thy country,'),(10580,'thy people, and thy city, that our ships may convey thee thither, discerning the course by their wits.'),(10581,' For the Phaeacians have no pilots, nor steering-oars such as other ships have, '),(10582,'but their ships of themselves understand the thoughts and minds of men,  and they know the cities and rich fields of all peoples, and most swiftly do they cross over the gulf of the sea, hidden in mist and cloud, '),(10583,' nor ever have they fear of harm or ruin.'),(10584,'Yet this story I once heard thus told by my father  Nausithous, who was wont to say that Poseidon was wroth with us because we give safe convoy to all men.'),(10585,' He said that someday, as a well-built ship of the Phaeacians was returning from a convoy over the misty deep, Poseidon would smite her and would fling a great mountain about our city.'),(10586,'  So that old man spoke,'),(10587,' and these things the god will haply bring to pass, or will leave unfulfilled, as may be his good pleasure. '),(10588,'But come, now, tell me this and declare it truly: whither thou hast wandered and to what countries of men thou hast come; tell me of the people and of their well-built cities,  both of those who are cruel and wild and unjust, and of those who love strangers and fear the gods in their thoughts.'),(10589,' And tell me why thou dost weep and wail in spirit as thou hearest the doom of the Argive Danaans and of Ilios.'),(10590,' This the gods wrought, and spun the skein of ruin  for men, that there might be a song for those yet to be born. '),(10591,'Did some kinsman of thine fall before Ilios, some good, true man, thy daughter\'s husband or thy wife\'s father, such as are nearest to one after one\'s own kin and blood?'),(10592,' Or was it haply some comrade dear to thy heart,  some good, true man? '),(10593,'For no whit worse than a brother is a comrade who has an understanding heart.”'),(10594,' Then Odysseus, of many wiles, answered him, and said:'),(10595,' “Lord Alcinous, renowned above all men, verily this is a good thing, to listen to a minstrel such as this man is, like unto the gods in voice.'),(10596,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 9.11'),(10597,' But thy heart is turned to ask of my grievous woes, that I may weep and groan the more.'),(10598,' What, then, shall I tell thee first, what last?'),(10599,' for woes full many have the heavenly gods given me.'),(10600,'First now will I tell my name, that ye, too, may know it, and that I hereafter, when I have escaped from the pitiless day of doom, may be your host, though I dwell in a home that is afar.'),(10601,' I am Odysseus, son of Laertes, who  am known among men for all manner of wiles, and my fame reaches unto heaven.'),(10602,'But I dwell in clear-seen Ithaca,'),(10603,' wherein is a mountain, Neriton, covered with waving forests, conspicuous from afar; '),(10604,'and round it lie many isles hard by one another, Dulichium, and Same, and wooded Zacynthus.'),(10605,'  Ithaca itself lies close in to the mainland the furthest toward the gloom, but the others lie apart toward the Dawn and the sun—a rugged isle, but a good nurse of young men; '),(10606,' and for myself no other thing can I see sweeter than one\'s own land.'),(10607,' Of a truth Calypso, the beautiful goddess, sought to keep me by her  in her hollow caves, yearning that I should be her husband; '),(10608,'and in like manner Circe would fain have held me back in her halls, the guileful lady of Aeaea, yearning that I should be her husband; '),(10609,' but they could never persuade the heart within my breast.'),(10610,'So true is it that naught is sweeter than a man\'s own land and his parents,  even though it be in a rich house that he dwells afar in a foreign land away from his parents.'),(10611,' But come, let me tell thee also of my woeful home-coming, which Zeus laid upon me as I came from Troy.'),(10612,'\n“From Ilios the wind bore me and brought me to the Cicones,  to Ismarus. '),(10613,'There I sacked the city and slew the men; '),(10614,'and from the city we took their wives and great store of treasure, and divided them among us, that so far as lay in me no man might go defrauded of an equal share.'),(10615,' Then verily I gave command that we should flee with swift foot, but the others in their great folly did not hearken.'),(10616,'  But there much wine was drunk, and many sheep they slew by the shore, and sleek kine of shambling gait. '),(10617,' Meanwhile the Cicones went and called to other Cicones who were their neighbors, at once more numerous and braver than they—men that dwelt inland and were skilled  at fighting with their foes from chariots, and, if need were, on foot.'),(10618,'So they came in the morning, as thick as leaves or flowers spring up in their season; '),(10619,'and then it was that an evil fate from Zeus beset us luckless men, that we might suffer woes full many.'),(10620,' They set their battle in array and fought by the swift ships,   and each side hurled at the other with bronze-tipped spears.'),(10621,'Now as long as it was morn and the sacred day was waxing, so long we held our ground and beat them off, though they were more than we.'),(10622,' But when the sun turned to the time for the unyoking of oxen, then the Cicones prevailed and routed the Achaeans,'),(10623,'  and six of my well-greaved comrades perished from each ship; '),(10624,'but the rest of us escaped death and fate.'),(10625,'“Thence we sailed on, grieved at heart, glad to have escaped from death, though we had lost our dear comrades; '),(10626,'nor did I let my curved ships pass on  till we had called thrice on each of those hapless comrades of ours who died on the plain, cut down by the Cicones.'),(10627,' But against our ships Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, roused the North Wind with a wondrous tempest, and hid with clouds the land and the sea alike, '),(10628,'and night rushed down from heaven.'),(10629,'  Then the ships were driven headlong, and their sails were torn to shreds by the violence of the wind.'),(10630,' So we lowered the sails and stowed them aboard, in fear of death, and rowed the ships hurriedly toward the land.'),(10631,' There for two nights and two days continuously  we lay, eating our hearts for weariness and sorrow.'),(10632,'But when now fair-tressed Dawn brought to its birth the third day, we set up the masts and hoisted the white sails, and took our seats, and the wind and the helmsmen steered the ships.'),(10633,' And now all unscathed should I have reached my native land, '),(10634,' but the wave and the current and the North Wind beat me back as I was rounding Malea, and drove me from my course past Cythera. '),(10635,' “Thence for nine days\' space I was borne by direful winds over the teeming deep; '),(10636,'but on the tenth we set foot on the land of the Lotus-eaters, who eat a flowery food.'),(10637,'  There we went on shore and drew water, and straightway my comrades took their meal by the swift ships.'),(10638,' But when we had tasted food and drink, I sent forth some of my comrades to go and learn who the men were, who here ate bread upon the earth;  two men I chose, sending with them a third as a herald. '),(10639,'So they went straightway and mingled with the Lotus-eaters,'),(10640,' and the Lotus-eaters did not plan death for my comrades, but gave them of the lotus to taste. '),(10641,'And whosoever of them ate of the honey-sweet fruit of the lotus,  had no longer any wish to bring back word or to return, but there they were fain to abide among the Lotus-eaters, feeding on the lotus, and forgetful of their homeward way.'),(10642,' These men, therefore, I brought back perforce to the ships, weeping, and dragged them beneath the benches and bound them fast in the hollow ships; '),(10643,' and I bade the rest of my trusty comrades to embark with speed on the swift ships, lest perchance anyone should eat of the lotus and forget his homeward way.'),(10644,' So they went on board straightway and sat down upon the benches, and sitting well in order smote the grey sea with their oars.'),(10645,' “Thence we sailed on, grieved at heart, '),(10646,'and we came to the land of the Cyclopes, an overweening and lawless folk, who, trusting in the immortal gods, plant nothing with their hands nor plough; but all these things spring up for them without sowing or ploughing,  wheat, and barley, and vines, which bear the rich clusters of wine, and the rain of Zeus gives them increase.'),(10647,' Neither assemblies for council have they, nor appointed laws, but they dwell on the peaks of lofty mountains in hollow caves, and each one is lawgiver  to his children and his wives, and they reck nothing one of another.'),(10648,' \n“Now there is a level isle that stretches aslant outside the harbor, neither close to the shore of the land of the Cyclopes, nor yet far off, a wooded isle.'),(10649,' Therein live wild goats innumerable, '),(10650,'for the tread of men scares them not away,  nor are hunters wont to come thither, men who endure toils in the woodland as they course over the peaks of the mountains.'),(10651,' Neither with flocks is it held, nor with ploughed lands, but unsown and untilled all the days it knows naught of men, but feeds the bleating goats.'),(10652,'  For the Cyclopes have at hand no ships with vermilion cheeks, nor are there ship-wrights in their land who might build them well-benched ships, which should perform all their wants, passing to the cities of other folk, as men often cross the sea in ships to visit one another— '),(10653,' craftsmen, who would have made of this isle also a fair settlement.'),(10654,' For the isle is nowise poor, but would bear all things in season.'),(10655,'In it are meadows by the shores of the grey sea, well-watered meadows and soft,'),(10656,'where vines would never fail,'),(10657,'and in it level ploughland, '),(10658,'whence  they might reap from season to season harvests exceeding deep, so rich is the soil beneath;'),(10659,'and in it, too, is a harbor giving safe anchorage, where there is no need of moorings, either to throw out anchor-stones or to make fast stern cables, but one may beach one\'s ship and wait until the sailors\' minds bid them put out, and the breezes blow fair.'),(10660,'  Now at the head of the harbor a spring of bright water flows forth from beneath a cave, '),(10661,'and round about it poplars grow.'),(10662,'Thither we sailed in, and some god guided us through the murky night; for there was no light to see, '),(10663,' but a mist lay deep about the ships and the moon  showed no light from heaven, but was shut in by clouds.'),(10664,' Then no man\'s eyes beheld that island, nor did we see the long waves rolling on the beach, until we ran our well-benched ships on shore.'),(10665,' And when we had beached the ships we lowered all the sails  and ourselves went forth on the shore of the sea, '),(10666,'and there we fell asleep and waited for the bright Dawn.'),(10667,'“As soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, we roamed throughout the isle marvelling at it;'),(10668,' and the nymphs, the daughters of Zeus who bears the aegis, roused  the mountain goats, that my comrades might have whereof to make their meal.'),(10669,'Straightway we took from the ships our curved bows and long javelins, and arrayed in three bands we fell to smiting;'),(10670,'  and the god soon gave us game to satisfy our hearts.'),(10671,' The ships that followed me were twelve, and to each  nine goats fell by lot, '),(10672,'but for me alone they chose out ten.'),(10673,' \n“So then all day long till set of sun we sat feasting on abundant flesh and sweet wine.'),(10674,' For not yet was the red wine spent from out our ships, but some was still left; '),(10675,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 9.164-9.165'),(10676,'for abundant store  had we drawn in jars for each crew ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 164 to line 165'),(10677,'And we looked across to the land of the Cyclopes, who dwelt close at hand, and marked the smoke, and the voice of men, and of the sheep, and of the goats.'),(10678,' But when the sun set and darkness came on, then we lay down to rest on the shore of the sea.'),(10679,'  And as soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, I called my men together and spoke among them all:'),(10680,'\n“‘Remain here now, all the rest of you, my trusty comrades, '),(10681,'but I with my own ship and my own company will go and make trial of yonder men, to learn who they are,  whether they are cruel, and wild, and unjust, or whether they love strangers and fear the gods in their thoughts.\'\"'),(10682,'So saying, I went on board the ship and bade my comrades themselves to embark, and to loose the stern cables.'),(10683,' So they went on board straightway and sat down upon the benches,  and sitting well in order smote the grey sea with their oars.  '),(10684,' But when we had reached the place, which lay close at hand, there on the land\'s edge hard by the sea we saw a high cave, roofed over with laurels, '),(10685,'and there many flocks, sheep and goats alike, were wont to sleep.'),(10686,' Round about it  a high court was built with stones set deep in the earth, and with tall pines and high-crested oaks.'),(10687,' There a monstrous man was wont to sleep, who shepherded his flocks alone and afar, '),(10688,'and mingled not with others, but lived apart, with his heart set on lawlessness.'),(10689,'  For he was fashioned a wondrous monster, and was not like a man that lives by bread, but like a wooded peak of lofty mountains, which stands out to view alone, apart from the rest. '),(10690,' \n“Then I bade the rest of my trusty comrades to remain there by the ship and to guard the ship,  but I chose twelve of the best of my comrades and went my way.'),(10691,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 9.196-9.200'),(10692,' With me I had a goat-skin of the dark, sweet wine, which Maro, son of Euanthes, had given me, the priest of Apollo, the god who used to watch over Ismarus. And he had given it me because we had protected him with his child and wife  out of reverence; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 196 to line 200'),(10693,'And he gave me splendid gifts: '),(10694,'of well-wrought gold he gave me seven talents, and he gave me a mixing-bowl all of silver; and besides these, wine, wherewith he filled twelve jars in all,  wine sweet and unmixed, a drink divine. '),(10695,'Not one of his slaves nor of the maids in his halls knew thereof, but himself and his dear wife, and one house-dame only. '),(10696,' And as often as they drank that honey-sweet red wine he would fill one cup and pour it into twenty measures of water,  and a smell would rise from the mixing-bowl marvellously sweet; '),(10697,'then verily would one not choose to hold back.'),(10698,' With this wine I filled and took with me a great skin, and also provision in a scrip;'),(10699,'for my proud spirit had a foreboding that presently a man would come to me clothed in great might,  a savage man that knew naught of justice or of law.'),(10700,'“Speedily we came to the cave, nor did we find him within, but he was pasturing his fat flocks in the fields.'),(10701,' So we entered the cave and gazed in wonder at all things there.'),(10702,' The crates were laden with cheeses, and the pens were crowded  with lambs and kids. '),(10703,' Each kind was penned separately: by themselves the firstlings, by themselves the later lambs, and by themselves again the newly weaned.'),(10704,' And with whey were swimming all the well-wrought vessels, the milk-pails and the bowls into which he milked. '),(10705,'Then my comrades spoke and besought me first of all  to take of the cheeses and depart, and thereafter speedily to drive to the swift ship the kids and lambs from out the pens, and to sail over the salt water.'),(10706,' But I did not listen to them—verily it would have been better far—to the end that I might see the man himself, and whether he would give me gifts of entertainment. '),(10707,' Yet, as it fell, his appearing was not to prove a joy to my comrades.'),(10708,' \n“Then we kindled a fire and offered sacrifice, and ourselves, too, took of the cheeses and ate, and thus we sat in the cave and waited for him until he came back, herding his flocks.'),(10709,' He bore a mighty weight of dry wood to serve him at supper time,  and flung it down with a crash inside the cave, '),(10710,'but we, seized with terror, shrank back into a recess of the cave.'),(10711,' But he drove his fat flocks into the wide cavern—all those that he milked; but the males—the rams and the goats—he left without in the deep court.'),(10712,'  Then he lifted on high and set in place the great door-stone, a mighty rock; '),(10713,' two and twenty stout four-wheeled wagons could not lift it from the ground, '),(10714,' such a towering mass of rock he set in the doorway.'),(10715,' Thereafter he sat down and milked the ewes and bleating goats  all in turn, and beneath each dam he placed her young. '),(10716,' Then presently he curdled half the white milk, and gathered it in wicker baskets and laid it away, and the other half he set in vessels that he might have it to take and drink, and that it might serve him for supper.'),(10717,'  But when he had busily performed his tasks, then he rekindled the fire, and caught sight of us, and asked:'),(10718,'Whence do ye sail over the watery ways? '),(10719,'Whence do ye sail over the watery ways? '),(10720,' Is it on some business, or do ye wander at random over the sea, even as pirates, who wander,  hazarding their lives and bringing evil to men of other lands?\"'),(10721,'So he spoke, and in our breasts our spirit was broken for terror of his deep voice and monstrous self;'),(10722,' yet even so I made answer and spoke to him, saying:'),(10723,'“‘We, thou must know, are from Troy, Achaeans, driven wandering  by all manner of winds over the great gulf of the sea. Seeking our home, we have come by another way, by other paths;'),(10724,'  so, I ween, Zeus was pleased to devise.'),(10725,' And we declare that we are the men of Agamemnon, son of Atreus, whose fame is now mightiest under heaven, '),(10726,'  so great a city did he sack, and slew many people; '),(10727,'but we on our part, thus visiting thee, have come as suppliants to thy knees, in the hope that thou wilt give us entertainment, or in other wise make some present, as is the due of strangers.'),(10728,' Nay, mightiest one, reverence the gods; '),(10729,'we are thy suppliants;  and Zeus is the avenger of suppliants and strangers—Zeus, the strangers\' god—who ever attends upon reverend strangers.\'\"'),(10730,'So I spoke, and he straightway made answer with pitiless heart:'),(10731,' ‘A fool art thou, stranger, or art come from afar, seeing that thou biddest me either to fear or to shun the gods.'),(10732,'  For the Cyclopes reck not of Zeus, who bears the aegis, nor of the blessed gods, since verily we are better far than they.'),(10733,' Nor would I, to shun the wrath of Zeus, spare either thee or thy comrades, unless my own heart should bid me.'),(10734,' But tell me where thou didst moor thy well-wrought ship on thy coming.  Was it haply at a remote part of the land, or close by? I fain would know.’'),(10735,' \n“So he spoke, tempting me, but he trapped me not because of my great cunning; and I made answer again in crafty words:'),(10736,'\n“‘My ship Poseidon, the earth-shaker, dashed to pieces, casting her upon the rocks at the border of your land;  for he brought her close to the headland,'),(10737,'and the wind drove her in from the sea. '),(10738,'But I, with these men here, escaped utter destruction.\"'),(10739,'So I spoke, but from his pitiless heart he made no answer, but sprang up and put forth his hands upon my comrades. Two of them at once he seized and dashed to the earth like puppies,'),(10740,'   and the brain flowed forth upon the ground and wetted the earth.'),(10741,' Then he cut them limb from limb and made ready his supper,'),(10742,' and ate them as a mountain-nurtured lion, leaving naught—ate the entrails, and the flesh, and the marrowy bones.'),(10743,' And we with wailing held up our hands to Zeus,  beholding his cruel deeds; and helplessness possessed our souls. '),(10744,'But when the Cyclops had filled his huge maw by eating human flesh and thereafter drinking pure milk, he lay down within the cave, stretched out among the sheep.'),(10745,'And I formed a plan in my great heart  to steal near him, and draw my sharp sword from beside my thigh and smite him in the breast, where the midriff holds the liver, feeling for the place with my hand.'),(10746,' But a second thought checked me, '),(10747,'for right there should we, too, have perished in utter ruin.'),(10748,'for right there should we, too, have perished in utter ruin. For we should not have been able  to thrust back with our hands from the high door the mighty stone which he had set there. '),(10749,' So then, with wailing, we waited for the bright Dawn.'),(10750,'\n“As soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, he rekindled the fire and milked his goodly flocks all in turn, and beneath each dam placed her young.'),(10751,'  Then, when he had busily performed his tasks, again he seized two men at once and made ready his meal.'),(10752,' And when he had made his meal he drove his fat flocks forth from the cave, easily moving away the great door-stone;'),(10753,'and then he put it in place again, as one might set the lid upon a quiver.'),(10754,'  Then with loud whistling the Cyclops turned his fat flocks toward the mountain, '),(10755,'and I was left there, devising evil in the deep of my heart, if in any way I might take vengeance on him, and Athena grant me glory. '),(10756,' \n“Now this seemed to my mind the best plan.'),(10757,' There lay beside a sheep-pen a great club of the Cyclops,  a staff of green olive-wood, '),(10758,'which he had cut to carry with him when dry; '),(10759,'and as we looked at it we thought it as large as is the mast of a black ship of twenty oars, a merchantman, broad of beam, which crosses over the great gulf; '),(10760,'so huge it was in length and in breadth to look upon.'),(10761,'  To this I came, and cut off therefrom about a fathom\'s length and handed it to my comrades, bidding them dress it down; '),(10762,'and they made it smooth,'),(10763,'and I, standing by, sharpened it at the point, and then straightway took it and hardened it in the blazing fire.'),(10764,' Then I laid it carefully away, hiding it beneath the dung,  which lay in great heaps throughout the cave. '),(10765,'And I bade my comrades cast lots among them, which of them should have the hardihood with me to lift the stake and grind it into his eye when sweet sleep should come upon him.'),(10766,' And the lot fell upon those whom I myself would fain have chosen;  four they were, and I was numbered with them as the fifth.'),(10767,' At even then he came, herding his flocks of goodly fleece,'),(10768,' and straightway drove into the wide cave his fat flocks one and all, and left not one without in the deep court, either from some foreboding or because a god so bade him.'),(10769,'  Then he lifted on high and set in place the great door-stone, and sitting down he milked the ewes and bleating goats all in turn, and beneath each dam he placed her young.'),(10770,' But when he had busily performed his tasks, again he seized two men at once and made ready his supper.'),(10771,'  Then I drew near and spoke to the Cyclops, holding in my hands an ivy bowl of the dark wine:'),(10772,' “‘Cyclops, take and drink wine after thy meal of human flesh, that thou mayest know what manner of drink this is which our ship contained.'),(10773,'It was to thee that I was bringing it as a drink offering, in the hope that, touched with pity,  thou mightest send me on my way home; '),(10774,'but thou ragest in a way that is past all bearing.'),(10775,'Cruel man, how shall any one of all the multitudes of men ever come to thee again hereafter, seeing that thou hast wrought lawlessness?\"'),(10776,'So I spoke, and he took the cup and drained it, '),(10777,'and was wondrously pleased as he drank the sweet draught, and asked me for it again a second time:'),(10778,'\n  “‘Give it me again with a ready heart, and tell me thy name straightway, that I may give thee a stranger\'s gift whereat thou mayest be glad.'),(10779,' For among the Cyclopes the earth, the giver of grain, bears the rich clusters of wine, and the rain of Zeus gives them increase; '),(10780,'but this is a streamlet of ambrosia and nectar.'),(10781,' \n  “So he spoke, and again I handed him the flaming wine.'),(10782,'Thrice I brought and gave it him, and thrice he drained it in his folly.'),(10783,' But when the wine had stolen about the wits of the Cyclops, then I spoke to him with gentle words:'),(10784,'\n“‘Cyclops, thou askest me of my glorious name, and I  will tell it thee;'),(10785,' and do thou give me a stranger\'s gift, even as thou didst promise.'),(10786,'Noman is my name,'),(10787,'  Noman do they call me—my mother and my father, and all my comrades as well.\"'),(10788,'So I spoke, and he straightway answered me with pitiless heart:'),(10789,' ‘Noman will I eat last among his comrades,  and the others before him; '),(10790,'this shall be thy gift.’'),(10791,'“He spoke, and reeling fell upon his back, and lay there with his thick neck bent aslant, and sleep, that conquers all, laid hold on him.'),(10792,' And from his gullet came forth wine and bits of human flesh, '),(10793,'and he vomited in his drunken sleep.'),(10794,'  Then verily I thrust in the stake under the deep ashes until it should grow hot, '),(10795,' and heartened all my comrades with cheering words, that I might see no man flinch through fear.'),(10796,'But when presently that stake of olive-wood was about to catch fire, green though it was, and began to glow terribly,  then verily I drew nigh, bringing the stake from the fire, and my comrades stood round me '),(10797,'and a god breathed into us great courage.'),(10798,' They took the stake of olive-wood, sharp at the point, and thrust it into his eye, '),(10799,'while I, throwing my weight upon it from above, whirled it round, as when a man bores a ship\'s timber  with a drill, while those below keep it spinning with the thong, which they lay hold of by either end, and the drill runs around unceasingly.'),(10800,' Even so we took the fiery-pointed stake and whirled it around in his eye, and the blood flowed around the heated thing.'),(10801,' And his eyelids wholly and his brows round about did the flame singe  as the eyeball burned, and its roots crackled in the fire.'),(10802,' And as when a smith dips a great axe or an adze in cold water amid loud hissing to temper it—'),(10803,'for therefrom comes the strength of iron—even so did his eye hiss round the stake of olive-wood.'),(10804,'  Terribly then did he cry aloud, and the rock rang around; and we, seized with terror, shrank back, '),(10805,'while he wrenched from his eye the stake, all befouled with blood, '),(10806,' and flung it from him, wildly waving his arms. Then he called aloud to the Cyclopes, who  dwelt round about him in caves among the windy heights, '),(10807,'and they heard his cry and came thronging from every side, and standing around the cave asked him what ailed him:'),(10808,'\n“‘What so sore distress is thine, Polyphemus, that thou criest out thus through the immortal night, and makest us sleepless?'),(10809,'  Can it be that some mortal man is driving off thy flocks against thy will,'),(10810,' or slaying thee thyself by guile or by might?\"'),(10811,'Then from out the cave the mighty Polyphemus answered them:'),(10812,' ‘My friends, it is Noman that is slaying me by guile and not by force.\"'),(10813,' ‘My friends, it is Noman that is slaying me by guile and not by force.\"'),(10814,' \n“And they made answer and addressed him with winged words:'),(10815,'  ‘If, then, no man does violence to thee in thy loneliness, sickness which comes from great Zeus thou mayest in no wise escape. Nay, do thou pray to our father, the lord Poseidon.\"'),(10816,'So they spoke and went their way; and my heart laughed within me that my name and cunning device had so beguiled.'),(10817,'  But the Cyclops, groaning and travailing in anguish, groped with his hands and took away the stone from the door, and himself sat in the doorway with arms outstretched in the hope of catching anyone who sought to go forth with the sheep—'),(10818,'so witless, forsooth, he thought in his heart to find me.'),(10819,'  But I took counsel how all might be the very best, if I might haply find some way of escape from death for my comrades and for myself.'),(10820,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 9.422-9.423'),(10821,' And I wove all manner of wiles and counsel, as a man will in a matter of life and death; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 422 to line 423'),(10822,' And this seemed to my mind the best plan.'),(10823,'  Rams there were, well-fed and thick of fleece, fine beasts and large, with wool dark as the violet.'),(10824,' These I silently bound together with twisted withes on which the Cyclops, that monster with his heart set on lawlessness, was wont to sleep. Three at a time I took.'),(10825,' The one in the middle in each case bore a man,  and the other two went, one on either side, saving my comrades. '),(10826,' Thus every three sheep bore a man.'),(10827,' But as for me—there was a ram, far the best of all the flock; him I grasped by the back, and curled beneath his shaggy belly, '),(10828,'lay there face upwards  with steadfast heart, clinging fast with my hands to his wondrous fleece. '),(10829,'So then, with wailing, we waited for the bright dawn.'),(10830,'\n“As soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, then the males of the flock hastened forth to pasture and the females bleated unmilked about the pens, '),(10831,' for their udders were bursting.'),(10832,'And their master, distressed with grievous pains, felt along the backs of all the sheep as they stood up before him,'),(10833,'  but in his folly he marked not this, that my men were bound beneath the breasts of his fleecy sheep.'),(10834,' Last of all the flock the ram went forth,  burdened with the weight of his fleece and my cunning self. '),(10835,'And mighty Polyphemus, as he felt along his back, spoke to him, saying:'),(10836,'\n“‘Good ram, why pray is it that thou goest forth thus through the cave the last of the flock?'),(10837,'Thou hast not heretofore been wont to lag behind the sheep, but wast ever far the first to feed on the tender bloom of the grass,  moving with long strides, and ever the first didst reach the streams of the river, and the first didst long to return to the fold at evening.'),(10838,' But now thou art last of all.'),(10839,'Surely thou art sorrowing for the eye of thy master, which an evil man blinded along with his miserable fellows, when he had overpowered my wits with wine,  even Noman, who, I tell thee, has not yet escaped destruction.'),(10840,' If only thou couldst feel as I do, and couldst get thee power of speech to tell me where he skulks away from my wrath, '),(10841,'then should his brains be dashed on the ground here and there throughout the cave, when I had smitten him, and my heart  should be lightened of the woes which good-for-naught Noman has brought me.’'),(10842,' \n“So saying, he sent the ram forth from him.'),(10843,' And when we had gone a little way from the cave and the court, I first loosed myself from under the ram and set my comrades free. '),(10844,' Speedily then we drove off those long-shanked sheep, rich with fat,  turning full often to look about until we came to the ship.'),(10845,' And welcome to our dear comrades was the sight of us who had escaped death, but for the others they wept and wailed; '),(10846,' yet I would not suffer them to weep, but with a frown forbade each man. Rather I bade them  to fling on board with speed the many sheep of goodly fleece, and sail over the salt water. '),(10847,'So they went on board straightway and sat down upon the benches, and sitting well in order smote the grey sea with their oars.'),(10848,' But when I was as far away as a man\'s voice carries when he shouts, then I spoke to the Cyclops with mocking words:'),(10849,'\n  “‘Cyclops, that man, it seems, was no weakling, whose comrades thou wast minded to devour by brutal strength in thy hollow cave.'),(10850,' Full surely were thy evil deeds to fall on thine own head, thou cruel wretch, who didst not shrink from eating thy guests in thine own house.'),(10851,' Therefore has Zeus taken vengeance on thee, and the other gods.’'),(10852,'  “So I spoke, and he waxed the more wroth at heart, and broke off the peak of a high mountain and hurled it at us, and cast it in front of the dark-prowed ship. And the sea surged beneath the stone as it fell, '),(10853,' and the backward flow, like a flood from the deep, bore the ship swiftly landwards and drove it upon the shore.'),(10854,' But I seized a long pole in my hands and shoved the ship off and along the shore,  and with a nod of my head I roused my comrades, and bade them fall to their oars that we might escape out of our evil plight.'),(10855,' And they bent to their oars and rowed. '),(10856,' But when, as we fared over the sea, we were twice as far distant, then was I fain to call to the Cyclops, '),(10857,'though round about me my comrades, one after another, sought to check me with gentle words:'),(10858,'\n“‘Reckless one, why wilt thou provoke to wrath a savage man, '),(10859,' who but now hurled his missile into the deep and drove our ship back to the land, and verily we thought that we had perished there?'),(10860,' And had he heard one of us uttering a sound or speaking, he would have hurled a jagged rock and crushed our heads and the timbers of our ship, '),(10861,'so mightily does he throw.\"'),(10862,' \n  “So they spoke, but they could not persuade my great-hearted spirit; and I answered him again with angry heart:'),(10863,'\n“‘Cyclops, if any one of mortal men shall ask thee about the shameful blinding of thine eye, say that Odysseus, the sacker of cities, blinded it,  even the son of Laertes, whose home is in Ithaca.’'),(10864,'\n“So I spoke, and he groaned and said in answer:'),(10865,'‘Lo now, verily a prophecy uttered long ago is come upon me.'),(10866,' There lived here a soothsayer, a good man and tall, Telemus, son of Eurymus, who excelled all men in soothsaying,  and grew old as a seer among the Cyclopes.'),(10867,' He told me that all these things should be brought to pass in days to come, that by the hands of Odysseus I should lose my sight.'),(10868,' But I ever looked for some tall and comely man to come hither, clothed in great might, '),(10869,' but now one that is puny, a man of naught and a weakling, has blinded me of my eye when he had overpowered me with wine.'),(10870,' Yet come hither, Odysseus, that I may set before thee gifts of entertainment, and may speed thy sending hence, that the glorious Earth-shaker may grant it thee.'),(10871,' For I am his son, and he declares himself my father; '),(10872,'  and he himself will heal me, if it be his good pleasure, but none other either of the blessed gods or of mortal men.’'),(10873,' \n“So he spoke in prayer, and the dark-haired god heard him.'),(10874,' But the Cyclops lifted on high again a far greater stone, and swung and hurled it, putting into the throw measureless strength. He cast it  a little behind the dark-prowed ship, and barely missed the end of the steering-oar. '),(10875,'And the sea surged beneath the stone as it fell, '),(10876,' and the wave bore the ship onward and drove it to the shore.'),(10877,'\n“Now when we had come to the island, where our other well-benched ships lay all together, and round about them our comrades,  ever expecting us, sat weeping, then, on coming thither, we beached our ship on the sands, and ourselves went forth upon the shore of the sea.'),(10878,' Then we took from out the hollow ship the flocks of the Cyclops, and divided them, that so far as in me lay no man might go defrauded of an equal share.'),(10879,'  But the ram my well-greaved comrades gave to me alone, when the flocks were divided, as a gift apart; '),(10880,'and on the shore I sacrificed him to Zeus, son of Cronos, god of the dark clouds, who is lord of all, and burned the thigh-pieces.'),(10881,' Howbeit he heeded not my sacrifice, but was planning how all  my well-benched ships might perish and my trusty comrades.'),(10882,'“So, then, all day long till set of sun we sat feasting on abundant flesh and sweet wine; '),(10883,'but when the sun set and darkness came on, then we lay down to rest on the shore of the sea.'),(10884,'  And as soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, I roused my comrades, and bade them themselves to embark and to loose the stern cables.'),(10885,' So they went on board straightway and sat down upon the benches, and sitting well in order smote the grey sea with their oars.'),(10886,'\n  “Thence we sailed on, grieved at heart, glad to have escaped death, though we had lost our dear comrades.'),(10887,' “Then to the Aeolian isle we came, '),(10888,' where dwelt Aeolus, son of Hippotas, dear to the immortal gods, in a floating island, '),(10889,'and all around it is a wall of unbreakable bronze, and the cliff runs up sheer.'),(10890,'  Twelve children of his, too, there are in the halls, six daughters and six sturdy sons, '),(10891,' and he gave his daughters to his sons to wife. '),(10892,' These, then, feast continually by their dear father and good mother, and before them lies boundless good cheer.  And the house, filled with the savour of feasting, resounds all about even in the outer court by day,'),(10893,' and by night again they sleep beside their chaste wives on blankets and on corded bedsteads.'),(10894,' To their city, then, and fair palace did we come, '),(10895,'and for a full month he made me welcome and questioned me about each thing,  about Ilios, and the ships of the Argives, and the return of the Achaeans. '),(10896,'And I told him all the tale in due order.'),(10897,' But when I, on my part, asked him that I might depart and bade him send me on my way, he, too, denied me nothing, but furthered my sending.'),(10898,' He gave me a wallet, made of the hide of an ox nine years old, which he flayed,  and therein he bound the paths of the blustering winds; '),(10899,'for the son of Cronos had made him keeper of the winds, both to still and to rouse whatever one he will.'),(10900,' And in my hollow ship he bound it fast with a bright cord of silver, that not a breath might escape, were it never so slight.'),(10901,'  But for my furtherance he sent forth the breath of the West Wind to blow, that it might bear on their way both ships and men.'),(10902,' Yet this he was not to bring to pass,'),(10903,' for we were lost through our own folly.'),(10904,'\n“For nine days we sailed, night and day alike, and now on the tenth our native land came in sight,  and lo, we were so near that we saw men tending the beacon fires. '),(10905,' Then upon me came sweet sleep in my weariness, for I had ever kept in hand the sheet of the ship, and had yielded it to none other of my comrades, that we might the sooner come to our native land. '),(10906,' But my comrades meanwhile began to speak one to another,  and said that I was bringing home for myself gold and silver as gifts from Aeolus, the great-hearted son of Hippotas.'),(10907,'And thus would one speak, with a glance at his neighbor:'),(10908,' \n“‘Out on it, how beloved and honored this man is by all men, to whose city and land soever he comes!'),(10909,'  Much goodly treasure is he carrying with him from the land of Troy from out the spoil, while we, who have accomplished the same journey as he, are returning, bearing with us empty hands.'),(10910,' And now Aeolus has given him these gifts, granting them freely of his love.'),(10911,' Nay, come, let us quickly see what is here,   what store of gold and silver is in the wallet.\"'),(10912,' \nSo they spoke, and the evil counsel of my comrades prevailed.'),(10913,' They loosed the wallet, and all the winds leapt forth, '),(10914,'and swiftly the storm-wind seized them and bore them weeping out to sea away from their native land; '),(10915,'but as for me,  I awoke, and pondered in my goodly heart whether I should fling myself from the ship and perish in the sea, or endure in silence and still remain among the living.'),(10916,' However, I endured and abode, and covering my head lay down in the ship.'),(10917,' But the ships were borne by an evil blast of wind  back to the Aeolian isle; and my comrades groaned.'),(10918,'\n“There we went ashore and drew water, and straightway my comrades took their meal by the swift ships.'),(10919,' But when we had tasted of food and drink, I took with me a herald and one companion  and went to the glorious palace of Aeolus, '),(10920,' and I found him feasting beside his wife and his children.'),(10921,' So we entered the house and sat down by the doorposts on the threshold, '),(10922,'and they were amazed at heart, and questioned us:'),(10923,'What cruel god assailed thee?'),(10924,'What cruel god assailed thee?'),(10925,'  Surely we sent thee forth with kindly care, that thou mightest reach thy native land and thy home, and whatever place thou wouldest.\"'),(10926,'So said they, but I with a sorrowing heart spoke among them and said:'),(10927,' ‘Bane did my evil comrades work me, and therewith sleep accursed; '),(10928,'for with you is the power.’'),(10929,'for with you is the power.’'),(10930,'  “So I spoke and addressed them with gentle words, but they were silent.'),(10931,' Then their father answered and said:'),(10932,'\n“‘Begone from our island with speed, thou vilest of all that live.'),(10933,' In no wise may I help or send upon his way that man who is hated of the blessed gods.  '),(10934,' Begone, for thou comest hither as one hated of the immortals.’'),(10935,'“So saying, he sent me forth from the house, groaning heavily. '),(10936,' Thence we sailed on, grieved at heart.'),(10937,'And worn was the spirit of the men by the grievous rowing, because of our own folly, for no longer appeared any breeze to bear us on our way.'),(10938,'  So for six days we sailed, night and day alike, and on the seventh we came to the lofty citadel of Lamus, even to Telepylus of the Laestrygonians, where herdsman calls to herdsman as he drives in his flock, and the other answers as he drives his forth.'),(10939,' There a man who never slept could have earned a double wage,  one by herding cattle, and one by pasturing white sheep; '),(10940,'for the out goings of the night and of the day are close together.  '),(10941,' \nWhen we had come thither into the goodly harbor, about which on both sides a sheer cliff runs continuously, and projecting headlands opposite to one another  stretch out at the mouth, and the entrance is narrow, then all the rest steered their curved ships in, '),(10942,'and the ships were moored within the hollow harbor close together; '),(10943,'for therein no wave ever swelled, great or small, but all about was a bright calm.'),(10944,'  But I alone moored my black ship outside, there on the border of the land, making the cables fast to the rock.'),(10945,' Then I climbed to a rugged height, a point of outlook, and there took my stand; '),(10946,'from thence no works of oxen or of men appeared; smoke alone we saw springing up from the land.'),(10947,'  So then I sent forth some of my comrades to go and learn who the men were, who here ate bread upon the earth—two men I chose, and sent with them a third as a herald. '),(10948,' Now when they had gone ashore, they went along a smooth road by which wagons were wont to bring wood down to the city from the high mountains. And before the city they met a maiden drawing water, the goodly daughter of Laestrygonian Antiphates, '),(10949,' who had come down to the fair-flowing spring Artacia, '),(10950,'from whence they were wont to bear water to the town.'),(10951,'So they came up to her and spoke to her,  and asked her who was king of this folk, and who they were of whom he was lord. '),(10952,'And she showed them forth with the high-roofed house of her father. '),(10953,' Now when they had entered the glorious house, they found there his wife, huge as the peak of a mountain, and they were aghast at her.'),(10954,'At once she called from the place of assembly the glorious Antiphates,  her husband, and he devised for them woeful destruction. '),(10955,'Straightway he seized one of my comrades and made ready his meal, '),(10956,' but the other two sprang up and came in flight to the ships.'),(10957,'Then he raised a cry throughout the city, '),(10958,'and as they heard it the mighty Laestrygonians came thronging from all sides,  a host past counting, not like men but like the Giants.'),(10959,' They hurled at us from the cliffs with rocks huge as a man could lift,'),(10960,' and at once there rose throughout the ships a dreadful din, alike from men that were dying and from ships that were being crushed.'),(10961,' And spearing them like fishes they bore them home, a loathly meal.'),(10962,'  Now while they were slaying those within the deep harbor, I meanwhile drew my sharp sword from beside my thigh, and cut therewith the cables of my dark-prowed ship; '),(10963,'and quickly calling to my comrades bade them fall to their oars, that we might escape from out our evil plight.'),(10964,'  And they all tossed the sea with their oar-blades in fear of death,'),(10965,' and joyfully seaward, away from the beetling cliffs, my ship sped on;'),(10966,'but all those other ships were lost together there. '),(10967,' \n“Thence we sailed on, grieved at heart, glad to have escaped death, though we had lost our dear comrades; '),(10968,' and we came to the isle of Aeaea, '),(10969,' where dwelt fair-tressed Circe, a dread goddess of human speech, own sister to Aeetes of baneful mind; '),(10970,'and both are sprung from Helius, who gives light to mortals, and from Perse, their mother, whom Oceanus begot.'),(10971,'  Here we put in to shore with our ship in silence, into a harbor where ships may lie, and some god guided us.'),(10972,' Then we disembarked, and lay there for two days and two nights, eating our hearts for weariness and sorrow. '),(10973,' But when fair-tressed Dawn brought to its birth the third day,  then I took my spear and my sharp sword, and quickly went up from the ship to a place of wide prospect, in the hope that I might see the works of men, and hear their voice.'),(10974,' So I climbed to a rugged height, a place of outlook, and there took my stand, and I saw smoke rising from the broad-wayed earth  in the halls of Circe, through the thick brush and the wood. '),(10975,' And I debated in mind and heart, whether I should go and make search, when I had seen the flaming smoke.'),(10976,' And as I pondered, this seemed to me to be the better way, to go first to the swift ship and the shore of the sea,  and give my comrades their meal, and send them forth to make search. '),(10977,' But when, as I went, I was near to the curved ship, then some god took pity on me in my loneliness, and sent a great, high-horned stag into my very path.'),(10978,' He was coming down to the river from his pasture in the wood  to drink, '),(10979,'for the might of the sun oppressed him; '),(10980,'and as he came out I struck him on the spine in the middle of the back, '),(10981,'and the bronze spear passed right through him, and down he fell in the dust with a moan, and his spirit flew from him.'),(10982,' Then I planted my foot upon him,  and drew the bronze spear forth from the wound,'),(10983,'and left it there to lie on the ground. '),(10984,' But for myself, I plucked twigs and osiers, and weaving a rope as it were a fathom in length, well twisted from end to end, I bound together the feet of the monstrous beast, and went my way to the black ship, bearing him across my back and  leaning on my spear, since in no wise could I hold him on my shoulder with one hand, '),(10985,' for he was a very mighty beast.'),(10986,' Down I flung him before the ship, and heartened my comrades with gentle words, coming up to each man in turn:'),(10987,'\n“‘Friends, not yet shall we go down  to the house of Hades, despite our sorrows, before the day of fate comes upon us. '),(10988,'Nay, come, while there is yet food and drink in our swift ship, let us bethink us of food, that we pine not with hunger.\''),(10989,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 10.177'),(10990,' \n“So I spoke, and they quickly hearkened to my words. From their faces they drew their cloaks,  and marvelled at the stag on the shore of the unresting sea, '),(10991,'for he was a very mighty beast.'),(10992,'But when they had satisfied their eyes with gazing, they washed their hands, and made ready a glorious feast.'),(10993,' So then all day long till set of sun we sat feasting on abundant flesh and sweet wine.'),(10994,'  But when the sun set and darkness came on, then we lay down to rest on the shore of the sea.'),(10995,' And as soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, I called my men together, and spoke among them all:'),(10996,'\n“‘Hearken to my words, comrades, for all your evil plight.'),(10997,'  My friends, we know not where the darkness is or where the dawn, neither where the sun, who give light to mortals, goes beneath the earth, nor where he rises;'),(10998,' but let us straightway take thought if any device be still left us.'),(10999,' As for me I think not that there is.'),(11000,' For I climbed to a rugged point of outlook, and beheld  the island, about which is set as a crown the boundless deep.'),(11001,' The isle itself lies low, '),(11002,'and in the midst of it my eyes saw smoke through the thick brush and the wood.\"'),(11003,'So I spoke, and their spirit was broken within them, as they remembered the deeds of the Laestrygonian, Antiphates,  and the violence of the great-hearted Cyclops, the man-eater.'),(11004,'And they wailed aloud, and shed big tears.'),(11005,'  But no good came of their mourning.'),(11006,'\n“Then I told off in two bands all my well-greaved comrades, and appointed a leader for each band.'),(11007,' Of the one I took command, and of the other godlike Eurylochus.'),(11008,' Quickly then we shook lots in a brazen helmet,'),(11009,'  and out leapt the lot of great-hearted Eurylochus. '),(11010,' So he set out, and with him went two-and-twenty comrades, all weeping; '),(11011,'and they left us behind, lamenting.'),(11012,'  Within the forest glades they found the house of Circe, built of polished stone in a place of wide outlook, '),(11013,' and round about it were mountain wolves and lions, whom Circe herself had bewitched; for she gave them evil drugs.'),(11014,' Yet these beasts did not rush upon my men,  but pranced about them fawningly, wagging their long tails.'),(11015,' And as when hounds fawn around their master as he comes from a feast, for he ever brings them bits to soothe their temper, so about them fawned the stout-clawed wolves and lions;'),(11016,' but they were seized with fear, as they saw the dread monsters.'),(11017,'  So they stood in the gateway of the fair-tressed goddess, and within they heard Circe singing with sweet voice, as she went to and fro before a great imperishable web, such as is the handiwork of goddesses, finely-woven and beautiful, and glorious.'),(11018,' Then among them spoke Polites, a leader of men,  dearest to me of my comrades, and trustiest:'),(11019,'“‘Friends, within someone goes to and fro before a great web, singing sweetly, so that all the floor echoes; some goddess it is, or some woman. '),(11020,'Come, let us quickly call to her.'),(11021,'“So he spoke, and they cried aloud, and called to her. '),(11022,' And she straightway came forth and opened the bright doors, and bade them in; '),(11023,' and all went with her in their folly.'),(11024,'Only Eurylochus remained behind, for he suspected that there was a snare.'),(11025,' She brought them in and made them sit on chairs and seats, and made for them a potion of cheese and barley meal and yellow honey  with Pramnian wine; '),(11026,'but in the food she mixed baneful drugs, that they might utterly forget their native land.'),(11027,' Now when she had given them the potion, and they had drunk it off, then she presently smote them with her wand, and penned them in the sties.'),(11028,' And they had the heads, and voice, and bristles,  and shape of swine, but their minds remained unchanged even as before. '),(11029,'So they were penned there weeping, and before them Circe flung mast and acorns, and the fruit of the cornel tree, to eat, such things as wallowing swine are wont to feed upon.'),(11030,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 10.244-10.245'),(11031,'\n“But Eurylochus came back straightway to the swift, black ship,  to bring tiding of his comrades and their shameful doom. ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 244 to line 245'),(11032,'and his eyes were filled with tears, and his spirit was set on lamentation.'),(11033,' But when we questioned him in amazement,  then he told the fate of the others, his comrades.'),(11034,'“‘We went through the thickets, as thou badest, noble Odysseus.'),(11035,' We found in the forest glades a fair palace, built of polished stones, in a place of wide outlook.'),(11036,' There someone was going to and fro before a great web, and singing with clear voice,  some goddess or some woman, '),(11037,' and they cried aloud, and called to her.'),(11038,'And she came forth straightway, and opened the bright doors, and bade them in;'),(11039,' and they all went with her in their folly.'),(11040,'  But I remained behind, for I suspected that there was a snare.'),(11041,'Then they all vanished together, nor did one of them  appear again, '),(11042,' though I sat long and watched.’'),(11043,' \n“So he spoke, and I cast my silver-studded sword about my shoulders, a great sword of bronze, and slung my bow about me, '),(11044,'and bade him lead me back by the self-same road.'),(11045,' But he clasped me with both hands, and be sought me by my knees,  and with wailing he spoke to me winged words:'),(11046,'“‘Lead me not thither against my will, O thou fostered of Zeus, but leave me here.'),(11047,' For I know that thou wilt neither come back thyself, nor bring anyone of thy comrades.'),(11048,' Nay, with these that are here let us flee with all speed, '),(11049,'for still we may haply escape the evil day.'),(11050,'  “So he spoke, but I answered him, and said:'),(11051,'‘Eurylochus, do thou stay here in this place, eating and drinking by the hollow, black ship; '),(11052,' but I will go, for strong necessity is laid upon me.\''),(11053,'\n“So saying, I went up from the ship and the sea.'),(11054,'  But when, as I went through the sacred glades, I was about to come to the great house of the sorceress, Circe, then Hermes, of the golden wand, met me as I went toward the house, in the likeness of a young man with the first down upon his lip, in whom the charm of youth is fairest.'),(11055,'  He clasped my hand, and spoke, and addressed me:'),(11056,'\n“‘Whither now again, hapless man, dost thou go alone through the hills, knowing naught of the country?'),(11057,' Lo, thy comrades yonder in the house of Circe are penned like swine in close-barred sties. '),(11058,' And art thou come to release them?'),(11059,'Nay, I tell thee, thou shalt not  thyself return, but shalt remain there with the others. '),(11060,'But come, I will free thee from harm, and save thee.'),(11061,' Here, take this potent herb, and go to the house of Circe, and it shall ward off from thy head the evil day.'),(11062,' And I will tell thee all the baneful wiles of Circe.'),(11063,'  She will mix thee a potion, and cast drugs into the food;'),(11064,' but even so she shall not be able to bewitch thee, '),(11065,' for the potent herb that I shall give thee will not suffer it. And I will tell thee all.'),(11066,' When Circe shall smite thee with her long wand, then do thou draw thy sharp sword from beside thy thigh,  and rush upon Circe, as though thou wouldst slay her. '),(11067,' And she will be seized with fear, and will bid thee lie with her.'),(11068,' Then do not thou thereafter refuse the couch of the goddess, that she may set free thy comrades, and give entertainment to thee. '),(11069,'But bid her swear a great oath by the blessed gods,  that she will not plot against thee any fresh mischief to thy hurt, lest when she has thee stripped she may render thee a weakling and unmanned.’ '),(11070,' \n“So saying, Argeiphontes gave me the herb, drawing it from the ground, and showed me its nature.'),(11071,' At the root it was black, but its flower was like milk.'),(11072,'  Moly the gods call it,'),(11073,' and it is hard for mortal men to dig; but with the gods all things are possible.'),(11074,' Hermes then departed to high Olympus through the wooded isle, and I went my way to the house of Circe, and many things did my heart darkly ponder as I went.'),(11075,'  So I stood at the gates of the fair-tressed goddess.'),(11076,' There I stood and called, and the goddess heard my voice.'),(11077,' Straightway then she came forth, and opened the bright doors, and bade me in; '),(11078,' and I went with her, my heart sore troubled.'),(11079,'She brought me in and made me sit on a silver-studded chair,  a beautiful chair, richly wrought, '),(11080,'and beneath was a foot-stool for the feet. '),(11081,'And she prepared me a potion in a golden cup, that I might drink, and put therein a drug, with evil purpose in her heart.'),(11082,' But when she had given it me, and I had drunk it off, yet was not bewitched, she smote me with her wand, and spoke, and addressed me:'),(11083,'  ‘Begone now to the sty, and lie with the rest of thy comrades.’'),(11084,'“So she spoke, but I, drawing my sharp sword from beside my thigh, rushed upon Circe, as though I would slay her.'),(11085,' But she, with a loud cry, ran beneath, and clasped my knees, and with wailing she spoke to me winged words:'),(11086,' Where is thy city, and where thy parents?'),(11087,' Where is thy city, and where thy parents?'),(11088,'Amazement holds me that thou hast drunk this charm and wast in no wise bewitched.'),(11089,'  For no man else soever hath withstood this charm, when once he has drunk it, and it has passed the barrier of his teeth.'),(11090,' Nay, but the mind in thy breast is one not to be beguiled.'),(11091,'  Surely thou art Odysseus, the man of ready device, who Argeiphontes of the golden wand ever said to me would come hither on his way home from Troy with his swift, black ship.'),(11092,' Nay, come, put up thy sword in its sheath, and let us two then go up into my bed, that couched together  in love we may put trust in each other.’'),(11093,'“So she spoke, but I answered her, and said:'),(11094,'‘Circe, how canst thou bid me be gentle to thee, who hast turned my comrades into swine in thy halls, and now keepest me here, and with guileful purpose biddest me  go to thy chamber, and go up into thy bed, that when thou hast me stripped thou mayest render me a weakling and unmanned?'),(11095,' Nay, verily, it is not I that shall be fain to go up into thy bed, unless thou, goddess, wilt consent to swear a mighty oath that thou wilt not plot against me any fresh mischief to my hurt.’ '),(11096,' \n  “So I spoke, and she straightway swore the oath to do me no harm, as I bade her. '),(11097,'But when she had sworn, and made an end of the oath, then I went up to the beautiful bed of Circe.'),(11098,'\n“But her handmaids meanwhile were busied in the halls, four maidens who are her serving-women in the house.'),(11099,'  Children are they of the springs and groves, and of the sacred rivers that flow forth to the sea, '),(11100,'and of them one threw upon chairs fair rugs of purple above, and spread beneath them a linen cloth;'),(11101,'another drew up before the chairs tables  of silver, and set upon them golden baskets; '),(11102,' and the third mixed sweet, honey-hearted wine in a bowl of silver, and served out golden cups; '),(11103,' and the fourth brought water, and kindled a great fire beneath a large cauldron, '),(11104,'and the water grew warm.'),(11105,'  But when the water boiled in the bright bronze, she set me in a bath, and bathed me with water from out the great cauldron, mixing it to my liking, and pouring it over my head and shoulders, till she took from my limbs soul-consuming weariness. '),(11106,'But when she had bathed me, and anointed me richly with oil,  and had cast about me a fair cloak and a tunic, she brought me into the hall, and made me sit upon a silver-studded chair—a beautiful chair, richly wrought, and beneath was a foot-stool for the feet.'),(11107,' Then a handmaid brought water for the hands in a fair pitcher of gold, and poured it over a silver basin  for me to wash, '),(11108,' and beside me drew up a polished table.'),(11109,'And the grave housewife brought and set before me bread, and therewith meats in abundance, granting freely of her store.'),(11110,' Then she bade me eat,'),(11111,'  but my heart inclined not thereto. Rather, I sat with other thoughts, and my spirit boded ill.'),(11112,'\n  “Now when Circe noted that I sat thus, and did not put forth my hands to the food, but was burdened with sore grief, she came close to me, and spoke winged words:'),(11113,'\n“‘Why, Odysseus, dost thou sit thus like one that is dumb, eating thy heart, and dost not touch food or drink?'),(11114,'  Dost thou haply forbode some other guile?'),(11115,'Nay, thou needest in no wise fear,'),(11116,'  for already have I sworn a mighty oath to do thee no harm.\''),(11117,'“So she spoke, but I answered her, and said:'),(11118,'‘Circe, what man that is right-minded could bring himself to taste of food or drink,  ere yet he had won freedom for his comrades, and beheld them before his face? '),(11119,' But if thou of a ready heart dost bid me eat and drink, set them free, that mine eyes may behold my trusty comrades.’ '),(11120,' \n“So I spoke, and Circe went forth through the hall holding her wand in her hand, and opened the doors of the sty,  and drove them out in the form of swine of nine years old. '),(11121,'  So they stood there before her, and she went through the midst of them, and anointed each man with another charm.'),(11122,' Then from their limbs the bristles fell away which the baneful drug that queenly Circe gave them had before made to grow, '),(11123,' and they became men again, younger than they were before, and far comelier and taller to look upon.'),(11124,' They knew me, and clung to my hands, each man of them, '),(11125,'and upon them all came a passionate sobbing, and the house about them rang wondrously, '),(11126,'and the goddess herself was moved to pity.'),(11127,'  “Then the beautiful goddess drew near me, and said: '),(11128,'\n ‘Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, go now to thy swift ship and to the shore of the sea.'),(11129,' First of all do ye draw the ship up on the land, and store your goods and all the tackling in caves.'),(11130,'  Then come back thyself, and bring thy trusty comrades.’'),(11131,'\n“So she spoke, and my proud heart consented. I went my way to the swift ship and the shore of the sea,'),(11132,' and there I found my trusty comrades by the swift ship, wailing piteously, shedding big tears.'),(11133,'  And as when calves in a farmstead sport about the droves of cows returning to the yard, when they have had their fill of grazing—all together they frisk before them, '),(11134,'and the pens no longer hold them, but with constant lowing they run about their '),(11135,'mothers-'),(11136,'so those men, when their eyes beheld me,  thronged about me weeping, '),(11137,' and it seemed to their hearts as though they had got to their native land, and the very city of rugged Ithaca, where they were bred and born.'),(11138,' And with wailing they spoke to me winged words:'),(11139,'\n“‘At thy return, O thou fostered of Zeus, we are as glad  as though we had returned to Ithaca, our native land.'),(11140,' But come, tell the fate of the others, our comrades.'),(11141,'“So they spoke, and I answered them with gentle words: '),(11142,'‘First of all let us draw the ship up on the land, and store our goods and all the tackling in caves.'),(11143,'  Then haste you, one and all, to go with me that you may see your comrades in the sacred halls of Circe, drinking and eating, '),(11144,'for they have unfailing store.’ '),(11145,' \n“So I spoke, and they quickly hearkened to my words.'),(11146,' Eurylochus alone sought to hold back all my comrades, '),(11147,'   and he spoke, and addressed them with winged words:'),(11148,' Why are you so enamoured of these woes,'),(11149,' Why are you so enamoured of these woes,'),(11150,'as to go down to the house of Circe, who will change us all to swine, or wolves, or lions, that so we may guard her great house perforce?  Even so did the Cyclops, when our comrades went to his fold, and with them went this reckless Odysseus.'),(11151,' For it was through this man\'s folly that they too perished.\''),(11152,'“So he spoke, and I pondered in heart, whether to draw my long sword from beside my stout thigh,  and therewith strike off his head, and bring it to the ground, near kinsman of mine by marriage though he was; '),(11153,'but my comrades one after another sought to check me with gentle words:'),(11154,'“‘O thou sprung from Zeus, as for this man, we will leave him, if thou so biddest, to abide here by the ship, and to guard the ship,'),(11155,' but as for us, do thou lead us to the sacred house of Circe.’'),(11156,'“So saying, they went up from the ship and the sea.'),(11157,' Nor was Eurylochus left beside the hollow ship, but he went with us, '),(11158,'for he feared my dread reproof.'),(11159,'“Meanwhile in her halls Circe  bathed the rest of my comrades with kindly care, and anointed them richly with oil, and cast about them fleecy cloaks and tunics; '),(11160,' and we found them all feasting bountifully in the halls.'),(11161,'But when they saw and recognized one another, face to face, they wept and wailed, and the house rang around.'),(11162,' Then the beautiful goddess drew near me, and said:'),(11163,'“‘No longer now do ye rouse this plenteous lamenting.'),(11164,' Of myself I know both all the woes you have suffered on the teeming deep, and all the wrong that cruel men have done you on the land.'),(11165,'  Nay, come, eat food and drink wine, until you once more get spirit in your breasts such as when at the first you left your native land of rugged Ithaca; '),(11166,' but now ye are withered and spiritless, ever thinking of your weary wanderings, nor are your  hearts ever joyful, for verily ye have suffered much.’'),(11167,'“So she spoke, and our proud hearts consented. '),(11168,' So there day after day for a full year we abode, feasting on abundant flesh and sweet wine.'),(11169,'But when a year was gone and the seasons turned,  as the months waned and the long days were brought in their course, then my trusty comrades called me forth, and said:'),(11170,'“‘Strange man, bethink thee now at last of thy native land, if it is fated for thee to be saved, and to reach thy high-roofed house and thy native land.'),(11171,' \n  “So they spoke, and my proud heart consented. '),(11172,'So then all day long till set of sun we sat feasting on abundant flesh and sweet wine.'),(11173,' But when the sun set and darkness came on, they lay down to sleep throughout the shadowy halls, '),(11174,'but I went up to the beautiful bed of Circe, and besought her by her knees; and the goddess heard my voice, '),(11175,'and I spoke, and addressed her with winged words:'),(11176,'\n“‘Circe, fulfil for me the promise which thou gavest to send me home; '),(11177,'for my spirit is now eager to be gone,  and the spirit of my comrades, who make my heart to pine, as they sit about me mourning, whensoever thou haply art not at hand.\''),(11178,'“So I spoke, and the beautiful goddess straightway made answer:'),(11179,' ‘Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, abide ye now no longer in my house against your will; '),(11180,' but you must first complete another journey, and come to the house of Hades and dread Persephone, to seek soothsaying of the spirit of Theban Teiresias, the blind seer, whose mind abides steadfast.'),(11181,' To him even in death Persephone has granted reason,  that he alone should have understanding; but the others flit about as shadows.'),(11182,'“So she spoke, and my spirit was broken within me,'),(11183,' and I wept as I sat on the bed, nor had my heart any longer desire to live and behold the light of the sun. '),(11184,'But when I had my fill of weeping and writhing,  then I made answer, and addressed her, saying:'),(11185,'“‘O Circe, who will guide us on this journey?'),(11186,' To Hades no man ever yet went in a black ship.’ '),(11187,' \n“So I spoke, and the beautiful goddess straightway made answer: '),(11188,'‘Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices,  let there be in thy mind no concern for a pilot to guide thy ship, but set up thy mast, and spread the white sail, and sit thee down; '),(11189,' and the breath of the North Wind will bear her onward.'),(11190,'But when in thy ship thou hast now crossed the stream of Oceanus, where is a level shore and the groves of Persephone—  tall poplars, and willows that shed their fruit—there do thou beach thy ship by the deep eddying Oceanus, but go thyself to the dank house of Hades.'),(11191,' There into Acheron flow Periphlegethon and Cocytus, which is a branch of the water of the Styx;  and there is a rock, and the meeting place of the two roaring rivers.'),(11192,'Thither, prince, do thou draw nigh, as I bid thee, and dig a pit of a cubit\'s length this way and that, and around it pour a libation to all the dead, first with milk and honey, thereafter with sweet wine,  and in the third place with water,'),(11193,'  and sprinkle thereon white barley meal. '),(11194,' And do thou earnestly entreat the powerless heads of the dead, vowing that when thou comest to Ithaca thou wilt sacrifice in thy halls a barren heifer, the best thou hast, and wilt fill the altar with rich gifts; and that to Teiresias alone thou wilt sacrifice separately a ram,  wholly black, the goodliest of thy flock. '),(11195,'But when with prayers thou hast made supplication to the glorious tribes of the dead, then sacrifice a ram and a black ewe, turning their heads toward Erebus but thyself turning backward, and setting thy face towards the streams of the river.'),(11196,' Then many  ghosts of men that are dead will come forth. '),(11197,' But do thou thereafter call to thy comrades, and bid them flay and burn the sheep that lie there, slain by the pitiless bronze, and make prayer to the gods, to mighty Hades and to dread Persephone.'),(11198,'  And do thou thyself draw thy sharp sword from beside thy thigh, and sit there, not suffering the powerless heads of the dead to draw near to the blood, till thou hast enquired of Teiresias.'),(11199,' Then the seer will presently come to thee, leader of men, and he will tell thee thy way and the measures of thy path,  and of thy return, how thou mayest go over the teeming deep.\''),(11200,' “So she spoke, and straightway came golden-throned Dawn.'),(11201,'Round about me then she cast a cloak and tunic as raiment,'),(11202,'  and the nymph clothed herself in a long white robe, finely-woven and beautiful, and about her waist she cast  a fair girdle of gold, and upon her head she put a veil.'),(11203,' But I went through the halls, and roused my men with gentle words, coming up to each man in turn.'),(11204,' “‘No longer now sleep ye, and drowse in sweet slumber, but let us go; lo!'),(11205,'queenly Circe has told me all.’'),(11206,' \n  “So I spoke, and their proud hearts consented.'),(11207,' But not even from thence could I lead my men unscathed.'),(11208,' There was one, Elpenor, the youngest of all, not over valiant in war nor sound of understanding, '),(11209,'who had laid him down apart from his comrades in the sacred house of Circe,  seeking the cool air, for he was heavy with wine.'),(11210,' He heard the noise and the bustle of his comrades as they moved about, and suddenly sprang up, and forgot to go to the long ladder that he might come down again, but fell headlong from the roof,'),(11211,' and his neck  was broken away from the spine, and his spirit went down to the house of Hades.'),(11212,'“But as my men were going on their way I spoke among them, saying:'),(11213,'‘Ye think, forsooth, that ye are going to your dear native land;'),(11214,'  but Circe has pointed out for us another journey, even to the house of Hades and dread Persephone,  to consult the spirit of Theban Teiresias.\''),(11215,'“So I spoke, and their spirit was broken within them, and sitting down right where they were, they wept and tore their hair. '),(11216,'But no good came of their lamenting.'),(11217,'\n“But when we were on our way to the swift ship and the shore of the sea,  sorrowing and shedding big tears, meanwhile Circe had gone forth and made fast beside the black ship a ram and a black ewe, for easily had she passed us by.'),(11218,' Who with his eyes could behold a god against his will, whether going to or fro?'),(11219,' “But when we had come down to the ship and to the sea, first of all we drew the ship down to the bright sea, and set the mast and sail in the black ship, and took the sheep and put them aboard,  and ourselves embarked, sorrowing, and shedding big tears.'),(11220,' And for our aid in the wake of our dark-prowed ship a fair wind that filled the sail, a goodly comrade, was sent by fair-tressed Circe, dread goddess of human speech.'),(11221,' So when we had made fast all the tackling throughout the ship,  we sat down, '),(11222,' and the wind and the helms man made straight her course.'),(11223,' All the day long her sail was stretched as she sped over the sea; '),(11224,'and the sun set and all the ways grew dark.'),(11225,'“She came to deep-flowing Oceanus, that bounds the Earth,'),(11226,'where is the land and city of the Cimmerians,  wrapped in mist and cloud.'),(11227,' Never does the bright sun look down on them with his rays either when he mounts the starry heaven or when he turns again to earth from heaven, but baneful night is spread over wretched mortals.'),(11228,'  Thither we came and beached our ship, and took out the sheep,'),(11229,' and ourselves went beside the stream of Oceanus until we came to the place of which Circe had told us.'),(11230,'\n“Here Perimedes and Eurylochus held the victims, '),(11231,'while I drew my sharp sword from beside my thigh,  and dug a pit of a cubit\'s length this way and that, and around it poured a libation to all the dead, first with milk and honey, thereafter with sweet wine, and in the third place with water, '),(11232,' and I sprinkled thereon white barley meal.'),(11233,'And I earnestly entreated the powerless heads of the dead,  vowing that when I came to Ithaca I would sacrifice in my halls a barren heifer, the best I had, and pile the altar with goodly gifts, and to Teiresias alone would sacrifice separately a ram, wholly black, the goodliest of my flocks. '),(11234,'But when with vows and prayers  I had made supplication to the tribes of the dead, I took the sheep and cut their throats over the pit, and the dark blood ran forth.'),(11235,' Then there gathered from out of Erebus the spirits of those that are dead,'),(11236,'brides, and unwedded youths, and toil-worn old men, and tender maidens with hearts yet new to sorrow,  and many, too, that had been wounded with bronze-tipped spears, men slain in fight, wearing their blood-stained armour.'),(11237,' These came thronging in crowds about the pit from every side, with a wondrous cry;'),(11238,' and pale fear seized me. '),(11239,' Then I called to my comrades and bade them flay and burn  the sheep that lay there slain with the pitiless bronze, and to make prayer to the gods, to mighty Hades and dread Persephone.'),(11240,' And I myself drew my sharp sword from beside my thigh and sat there, and would not suffer the powerless heads of the dead  to draw near to the blood until I had enquired of Teiresias.'),(11241,' \n“The first to come was the spirit of my comrade Elpenor.'),(11242,' Not yet had he been buried beneath the broad-wayed earth,'),(11243,' we had left his corpse behind us in the hall of Circe, unwept and unburied, since another task was then urging us on.'),(11244,'  When I saw him I wept, and my heart had compassion on him; and I spoke and addressed him with winged words:'),(11245,'\n“‘Elpenor, how didst thou come beneath the murky darkness?'),(11246,' Thou coming on foot hast out-stripped me in my black ship.\''),(11247,'\n“So I spoke, and with a groan he answered me and said:'),(11248,'  ‘Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, an evil doom of some god was my undoing, and measureless wine.'),(11249,' When I had lain down to sleep in the house of Circe I did not think to go to the long ladder that I might come down again, but fell headlong from the roof, '),(11250,' and my neck  was broken away from the spine and my spirit went down to the house of Hades. '),(11251,'Now I beseech thee by those whom we left behind, who are not present with us, by thy wife and thy father who reared thee when a babe, and by Telemachus whom thou didst leave an only son in thy halls; '),(11252,'for I know that as thou goest hence from the house of Hades  thou wilt touch at the Aeaean isle with thy well-built ship. '),(11253,' There, then, O prince, I bid thee remember me. '),(11254,' Leave me not behind thee unwept and unburied as thou goest thence, and turn not away from me, lest haply I bring the wrath of the gods upon thee. Nay, burn me with my armour, all that is mine,  and heap up a mound for me on the shore of the grey sea, in memory of an unhappy man, that men yet to be may learn of me.'),(11255,' Fulfil this my prayer, and fix upon the mound my oar wherewith I rowed in life when I was among my comrades.\''),(11256,'“So he spoke, and I made answer and said:'),(11257,'  ‘All this, unhappy man, will I perform and do.’'),(11258,'\n“Thus we two sat and held sad converse one with the other, I on one side holding my sword over the blood, while on the other side the phantom of my comrade spoke at large.'),(11259,'\n“Then there came up the spirit of my dead mother,  Anticleia, the daughter of great-hearted Autolycus, whom I had left alive when I departed for sacred Ilios.'),(11260,' At sight of her I wept, and my heart had compassion on her, '),(11261,'but even so I would not suffer her to come near the blood, for all my great sorrow, until I had enquired of Teiresias.'),(11262,'\n  “Then there came up the spirit of the Theban Teiresias, bearing his golden staff in his hand, and he knew me and spoke to me:'),(11263,' ‘Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, what now, hapless man? Why hast thou left the light of the sun and come hither to behold the dead and a region where is no joy?'),(11264,'  Nay, give place from the pit and draw back thy sharp sword, that I may drink of the blood and tell thee sooth.’ '),(11265,' \n“So he spoke, and I gave place and thrust my silver-studded sword into its sheath,'),(11266,'  and when he had drunk the dark blood, then the blameless seer spoke to me and said:'),(11267,' “‘Thou askest of thy honey-sweet return, glorious Odysseus,'),(11268,'\n  but this shall a god make grievous unto thee; '),(11269,'for I think not that thou shalt elude the Earth-shaker, seeing that he has laid up wrath in his heart against thee, angered that thou didst blind his dear son. '),(11270,'Yet even so ye may reach home, though in evil plight,  if thou wilt curb thine own spirit and that of thy comrades, as soon as thou shalt bring thy well-built ship to the island Thrinacia, escaping from the violet sea, and ye find grazing there the kine and goodly flocks of Helios, who over sees and overhears all things.'),(11271,'  If thou leavest these unharmed and heedest thy homeward way, verily ye may yet reach Ithaca, though in evil plight.'),(11272,' But if thou harmest them, then I foresee ruin for thy ship and thy comrades, '),(11273,'and even if thou shalt thyself escape, late shalt thou come home and in evil case, after losing all thy comrades,  in a ship that is another\'s, '),(11274,' and thou shalt find woes in thy house—proud men that devour thy livelihood, wooing thy godlike wife, and offering wooers\' gifts.'),(11275,' Yet verily on their violent deeds shalt thou take vengeance when thou comest. '),(11276,'But when thou hast slain the wooers in thy halls,  whether by guile or openly with the sharp sword, then do thou go forth, taking a shapely oar, until thou comest to men that know naught of the sea and eat not of food mingled with salt,'),(11277,' aye, and they know naught of ships with purple cheeks,  or of shapely oars that are as wings unto ships. '),(11278,' And I will tell thee a sign right manifest, which will not escape thee. '),(11279,'When another wayfarer, on meeting thee, shall say that thou hast a winnowing-fan on thy stout shoulder, then do thou fix in the earth thy shapely oar  and make goodly offerings to lord Poseidon—a ram, and a bull, and a boar that mates with sows—and depart for thy home and offer sacred hecatombs to the immortal gods who hold broad heaven, to each one in due order. '),(11280,'And death shall come to thee thyself far from the sea,  a death so gentle, that shall lay thee low when thou art overcome with sleek old age, '),(11281,'and thy people shall dwell in prosperity around thee.'),(11282,' In this have I told thee sooth.’ '),(11283,' \n“So he spoke, and I made answer and said:'),(11284,' ‘Teiresias, of all this, I ween, the gods themselves have spun the thread.'),(11285,'  But come, tell me this, and declare it truly.'),(11286,' I see here the spirit of my dead mother;'),(11287,' she sits in silence near the blood, and deigns not to look upon the face of her own son or to speak to him. '),(11288,'Tell me, prince, how she may recognize that I am he?\''),(11289,'  “So I spoke, and he straightway made answer, and said: '),(11290,'‘Easy is the word that I shall say and put in thy mind.'),(11291,' Whomsoever of those that are dead and gone thou shalt suffer to draw near the blood, he will tell thee sooth; '),(11292,'but whomsoever thou refusest, he surely will go back again.’'),(11293,'  “So saying the spirit of the prince, Teiresias, went back into the house of Hades, when he had declared his prophecies; '),(11294,' but I remained there steadfastly until my mother came up and drank the dark blood.'),(11295,'At once then she knew me, and with wailing she spoke to me winged words:'),(11296,'\n  “‘My child, how didst thou come beneath the murky darkness, being still alive?'),(11297,' Hard is it for those that live to behold these realms, '),(11298,' for between are great rivers and dread streams; Oceanus first, which one may in no wise cross on foot, but only if one have a well-built ship.'),(11299,'  Art thou but now come hither from Troy after long wanderings with thy ship and thy companions? '),(11300,'and hast thou not yet reached Ithaca, nor seen thy wife in thy halls?’'),(11301,' “So she spoke, and I made answer and said:'),(11302,' “So she spoke, and I made answer and said:‘My mother, necessity brought me down to the house of Hades,  to seek soothsaying of the spirit of Theban Teiresias. '),(11303,'For not yet have I come near to the shore of Achaea, nor have I as yet set foot on my own land, but have ever been wandering, laden with woe, from the day when first I went with goodly Agamemnon to Ilios, famed for its horses, to fight with the Trojans.'),(11304,'  But come, tell me this, and declare it truly.'),(11305,' What fate of grievous death overcame thee?'),(11306,' Was it long disease, or did the archer, Artemis, assail thee with her gentle shafts, and slay thee? '),(11307,'And tell me of my father and my son, whom I left behind me.  Does the honor that was mine still abide with them, or does some other man now possess it, and do they say that I shall no more return?'),(11308,' And tell me of my wedded wife, of her purpose and of her mind. Does she abide with her son, and keep all things safe? or has one already wedded her, whosoever is best of the Achaeans?’ '),(11309,' \n  “So I spoke, and my honored mother straightway answered: '),(11310,'‘Aye verily she abides with steadfast heart in thy halls, '),(11311,' and ever sorrowfully for her do the nights and the days wane, as she weeps.'),(11312,'But the fair honor that was thine no man yet possesses,  but Telemachus holds thy demesne unharassed, and feasts a equal banquets, such as it is fitting that one who deals judgment should share, '),(11313,'for all men invite him.'),(11314,' But thy father abides there in the tilled land, and comes not to the city, '),(11315,' nor has he, for bedding, bed and cloaks and bright coverlets,  but through the winter he sleeps in the house, where the slaves sleep, in the ashes by the fire, and wears upon his body mean raiment.'),(11316,' But when summer comes and rich autumn, then all about the slope of his vineyard plot are strewn his lowly beds of fallen leaves.'),(11317,'  There he lies sorrowing, and nurses his great grief in his heart, in longing for thy return, and heavy old age has come upon him.'),(11318,' Even so did I too perish and meet my fate.'),(11319,' Neither did the keen-sighted archer goddess assail me in my halls with her gentle shafts, and slay me,  nor did any disease come upon me, such as oftenest through grievous wasting takes the spirit from the limbs; '),(11320,'nay, it was longing for thee, and for thy counsels, glorious Odysseus, and for thy tender-heartedness, that robbed me of honey-sweet life.\''),(11321,'“So she spoke, and I pondered in heart, and was fain  to clasp the spirit of my dead mother. '),(11322,'Thrice I sprang towards her, and my heart bade me clasp her, and thrice she flitted from my arms like a shadow or a dream, '),(11323,' and pain grew ever sharper at my heart. And I spoke and addressed her with winged words:'),(11324,'\n  “‘My mother, why dost thou not stay for me, who am eager to clasp thee, that even in the house of Hades we two may cast our arms each about the other, and take our fill of chill lamenting.'),(11325,' Is this but a phantom that august Persephone has sent me, that I may lament and groan the more?\''),(11326,'  “So I spoke, and my honored mother straightway answered: '),(11327,'‘Ah me, my child, ill-fated above all men, in no wise does Persephone, the daughter of Zeus, deceive thee, but this is the appointed way with mortals when one dies. '),(11328,' For the sinews no longer hold the flesh and the bones together,  but the strong might of blazing fire destroys these, as soon as the life leaves the white bones, and the spirit, like a dream, flits away, and hovers to and fro.'),(11329,' But haste thee to the light with what speed thou mayest, '),(11330,'and bear all these things in mind, that thou mayest hereafter tell them to thy wife.’ '),(11331,' \n  “Thus we two talked with one another; and the women came, for august Persephone sent them forth, even all those that had been the wives and the daughters of chieftains.'),(11332,' These flocked in throngs about the dark blood, and I considered how I might question each; '),(11333,' and this seemed to my mind the best counsel. '),(11334,'I drew my long sword from beside my stout thigh, and would not suffer them to drink of the dark blood all at one time.'),(11335,' So they drew near, one after the other, and each declared her birth, '),(11336,'and I questioned them all.'),(11337,'\n  “Then verily the first that I saw was high-born Tyro, who said that she was the daughter of noble Salmoneus, and declared herself to be the wife of Cretheus, son of Aeolus.'),(11338,' She became enamoured of the river, divine Enipeus, who is far the fairest of rivers that send forth their streams upon the earth,  and she was wont to resort to the fair waters of Enipeus. '),(11339,'But the Enfolder and Shaker of the earth took his form, and lay with her at the mouths of the eddying river.'),(11340,' And the dark wave stood about them like a mountain, vaulted-over, and hid the god and the mortal woman.'),(11341,' And he loosed her maiden girdle, and shed sleep upon her.'),(11342,'  But when the god had ended his work of love, he clasped her hand, and spoke, and addressed her:'),(11343,'“‘Be glad, woman, in our love,'),(11344,' and as the year goes on its course thou shalt bear glorious children, for not weak are the embraces  of a god.'),(11345,' These do thou tend and rear.'),(11346,'  But now go to thy house, and hold thy peace, and tell no man;'),(11347,' but know that I am Poseidon, the shaker of the earth.\''),(11348,'“So saying, he plunged beneath the surging sea.'),(11349,' But she conceived and bore Pelias and Neleus,  who both became strong servants of great Zeus;'),(11350,'and Pelias dwelt in spacious Iolcus, and was rich in flocks, and the other dwelt in sandy Pylos.'),(11351,' But her other children she, the queenly among women, bore to Cretheus, even Aeson, and Pheres, and Amythaon, who fought from chariots.'),(11352,'\n  “And after her I saw Antiope, daughter of Asopus, who boasted that she had slept even in the arms of Zeus, and she bore two sons, Amphion and Zethus, who first established the seat of seven-gated Thebe, and fenced it in with walls, for they could not  dwell in spacious Thebe unfenced, how mighty soever they were.'),(11353,'\n“And after her I saw Alcmene, wife of Amphitryon, who lay in the arms of great Zeus, and bore Heracles, staunch in fight, the lion-hearted.'),(11354,' And Megara I saw, daughter of Creon, high-of-heart, whom the son of Amphitryon, ever stubborn in might, had to wife.'),(11355,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 11.271-11.273'),(11356,' \n“And I saw the mother of Oedipodes, fair Epicaste, who wrought a monstrous deed in ignorance of mind, in that she wedded her own son, ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 271 to line 273'),(11357,'and straightway the gods made these things known among men.'),(11358,'  Howbeit he abode as lord of the Cadmeans in lovely Thebe, suffering woes through the baneful counsels of the gods, '),(11359,' but she went down to the house of Hades, the strong warder. She made fast a noose on high from a lofty beam, overpowered by her sorrow,'),(11360,'  but for him she left behind woes  full many, even all that the Avengers of a mother bring to pass.'),(11361,'“And I saw beauteous Chloris, whom once Neleus wedded because of her beauty, when he had brought countless gifts of wooing. Youngest daughter was she of Amphion, son of Iasus, who once ruled mightily in Orchomenus of the Minyae.'),(11362,'  And she was queen of Pylos, and bore to her husband glorious children, Nestor, and Chromius, and lordly Periclymenus, '),(11363,' and besides these she bore noble Pero, a wonder to men. Her all that dwelt about sought in marriage, '),(11364,' but Neleus would give her to no man, save to him who  should drive from Phylace the kine of mighty Iphicles, sleek and broad of brow; and hard they were to drive.'),(11365,' These the blameless seer alone undertook to drive off;'),(11366,' but a grievous fate of the gods ensnared him, even hard bonds and the herdsmen of the field.'),(11367,'  Howbeit when at length the months and the days were being brought to fulfillment, as the year rolled round, and the seasons came on, then verily mighty Iphicles released him, when he had told all the oracles; '),(11368,'and the will of Zeus was fulfilled.'),(11369,'“And I saw Lede, the wife of Tyndareus, who bore to Tyndareus two sons, stout of heart,  Castor the tamer of horses, and the boxer Polydeuces. These two the earth, the giver of life, covers, albeit alive,'),(11370,'and even in the world below they have honor from Zeus. One day they live in turn, and one day they are dead;'),(11371,'   and they have won honor like unto that of the gods.'),(11372,'  “And after her I saw Iphimedeia, wife of Aloeus, who declared that she had lain with Poseidon. She bore two sons, but short of life were they, godlike Otus, and far-famed Ephialtes—men whom the earth, the giver of grain, reared as the tallest,  and far the comeliest, after the famous Orion.'),(11373,' For at nine years they were nine cubits in breadth and in height nine fathoms.'),(11374,' Yea, and they threatened to raise the din of furious war against the immortals in Olympus.'),(11375,'  They were fain to pile Ossa on Olympus, and Pelion, with its waving forests, on Ossa, that so heaven might be scaled.'),(11376,' And this they would have accomplished, if they had reached the measure of manhood;'),(11377,' but the son of Zeus, whom fair-haired Leto bore, slew them both before  the down blossomed beneath their temples and covered their chins with a full growth of beard.'),(11378,' \n“And Phaedra and Procris I saw, and fair Ariadne, the daughter of Minos of baneful mind, whom once Theseus was fain to bear from Crete to the hill of sacred Athens; but he had no joy of her, '),(11379,'for ere that Artemis slew her  in sea-girt Dia because of the witness of Dionysus.'),(11380,'\n“And Maera and Clymene I saw, and hateful Eriphyle, who took precious gold as the price of the life of her own lord.'),(11381,' But I cannot tell or name all the wives and daughters of heroes that I saw; '),(11382,' ere that immortal night would wane. '),(11383,'Nay, it is now time to sleep, either when I have gone to the swift ship and the crew, or here.'),(11384,' My sending shall rest with the gods, and with you.\"'),(11385,'\nSo he spoke, and they were all hushed in silence, and were held spell-bound throughout the shadowy halls.'),(11386,'  Then among them white-armed Arete was the first to speak:'),(11387,'\n“Phaeacians, how seems this man to you for comeliness and stature, and for the balanced spirit within him?'),(11388,' And moreover he is my guest, though each of you has a share in this honor.'),(11389,' Wherefore be not in haste to send him away, nor  stint your gifts to one in such need; '),(11390,'for many are the treasures which lie stored in your halls by the favour of the gods.\"'),(11391,'Then among them spoke also the old lord Echeneus, who was an elder among the Phaeacians:'),(11392,'“Friends, verily not wide of the mark or of our own thought  are the words of our wise queen.'),(11393,' Nay, do you give heed to them. '),(11394,'Yet it is on Alcinous here that deed and word depend.\"'),(11395,'Then again Alcinous answered him and said:'),(11396,'“This word of hers shall verily hold, as surely as I live and am lord over the Phaeacians, lovers of the oar.'),(11397,'  But let our guest, for all his great longing to return, nevertheless endure to remain until tomorrow, till I shall make all our gift complete.'),(11398,' His sending shall rest with the men, with all, but most of all with me; '),(11399,'for mine is the control in the land.\"'),(11400,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him and said:'),(11401,'  “Lord Alcinous, renowned above all men, if you should bid me abide here even for a year, and should further my sending, and give glorious gifts, even that would I choose; and it would be better far to come with a fuller hand to my dear native land. '),(11402,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 11.360-11.361'),(11403,' \nThen again Alcinous made answer and said:'),(11404,'“Odysseus, in no wise as we look on thee do we deem this of thee, that thou art a cheat and a dissembler, such as are many  whom the dark earth breeds scattered far and wide, men that fashion lies out of what no man can even see.'),(11405,' But upon thee is grace of words, and within thee is a heart of wisdom, '),(11406,' and thy tale thou hast told with skill, as doth a minstrel, even the grievous woes of all the Argives and of thine own self.'),(11407,'  But come, tell me this, and declare it truly, whether thou sawest any of thy godlike comrades, who went to Ilios together with thee, and there met their fate.'),(11408,' The night is before us, long, aye, wondrous long, '),(11409,' and it is not yet the time for sleep in the hall. Tell on, I pray thee, the tale of these wondrous deeds.'),(11410,'  Verily I could abide until bright dawn, so thou wouldest be willing to tell in the hall of these woes of thine.\"'),(11411,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him and said:'),(11412,' “Lord Alcinous, renowned above all men, there is a time for many words and there is a time also for sleep.'),(11413,'  But if thou art fain still to listen, I would not begrudge to tell thee of other things more pitiful still than these, even the woes of my comrades, who perished afterward, who escaped from the dread battle-cry of the Trojans, but perished on their return through the will of an evil woman.'),(11414,'\n  “When then holy Persephone had scattered this way and that the spirits of the women, there came up the spirit of Agamemnon, son of Atreus, sorrowing; '),(11415,' and round about him others were gathered, spirits of all those who were slain with him in the house of Aegisthus, and met their fate.'),(11416,'  He knew me straightway, when he had drunk the dark blood,'),(11417,' and he wept aloud, and shed big tears, and stretched forth his hands toward me eager to reach me.'),(11418,' But no longer had he aught of strength or might remaining such as of old was in his supple limbs.'),(11419,'\n  “When I saw him I wept, and my heart had compassion on him, and I spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(11420,' ‘Most glorious son of Atreus, king of men, Agamemnon, what fate of grievous death overcame thee?'),(11421,' Did Poseidon smite thee on board thy ships,  when he had roused a furious blast of cruel winds? '),(11422,' Or did foemen work thee harm on the land, while thou wast cutting off their cattle and fair flocks of sheep, or wast fighting to win their city and their women?’ '),(11423,' \n“So I spoke, and he straightway made answer and said:'),(11424,'  ‘Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, neither did Poseidon smite me on board my ships, when he had roused a furious blast of cruel winds, nor did foemen work me harm on the land, but Aegisthus wrought for me death and fate,  and slew me with the aid of my accursed wife, when he had bidden me to his house and made me a feast, even as one slays an ox at the stall.'),(11425,' So I died by a most pitiful death, '),(11426,' and round about me the rest of my comrades were slain unceasingly like white-tusked swine, which are slaughtered in the house of a rich man of great might  at a marriage feast, or a joint meal, or a rich drinking-bout.'),(11427,'Ere now thou hast been present at the slaying of many men, killed in single combat or in the press of the fight,'),(11428,'  but in heart thou wouldst have felt most pity hadst thou seen that sight, how about the mixing bowl and the laden tables  we lay in the hall, and the floor all swam with blood. '),(11429,' But the most piteous cry that I heard was that of the daughter of Priam, Cassandra, whom guileful Clytemnestra slew by my side. And I sought to raise my hands and smite down the murderess, dying though I was, pierced through with the sword. '),(11430,' But she, the shameless one,  turned her back upon me, and even though I was going to the house of Hades deigned neither to draw down my eyelids with her fingers nor to close my mouth.'),(11431,' So true is it that there is nothing more dread or more shameless than a woman who puts into her heart such deeds, '),(11432,' even as she too devised a monstrous thing,  contriving death for her wedded husband.'),(11433,' Verily I thought that I should come home welcome to my children and to my slaves;'),(11434,' but she, with her heart set on utter wickedness, has shed shame on herself and on women yet to be, even upon her that doeth uprightly.\''),(11435,' “So he spoke, and I made answer and said: '),(11436,' ‘Ah, verily has Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, visited wondrous hatred on the race of Atreus from the first because of the counsels of women.'),(11437,' For Helen\'s sake many of us perished, and against thee Clytemnestra spread a snare whilst thou wast afar.’ '),(11438,' \n  “So I spoke, and he straightway made answer and said: '),(11439,' ‘Wherefore in thine own case be thou never gentle even to thy wife.'),(11440,' Declare not to her all the thoughts of thy heart, but tell her somewhat, and let somewhat also be hidden.'),(11441,' Yet not upon thee, Odysseus, shall death come from thy wife, '),(11442,' for very prudent and of an understanding heart is the daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope.'),(11443,' Verily we left her a bride newly wed, when we went to the war,'),(11444,'and a boy was at her breast, a babe, who now, I ween, sits in the ranks of men, '),(11445,'  happy in that his dear father will behold him when he comes, and he will greet his father as is meet. '),(11446,' But my wife did not let me sate my eyes even with sight of my own son. '),(11447,' Nay, ere that she slew even me, her husband. '),(11448,'And another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart:'),(11449,'  in secret and not openly do thou bring thy ship to the shore of thy dear native land; '),(11450,' for no longer is there faith in women.'),(11451,'But, come, tell me this, and declare it truly, whether haply ye hear of my son as yet alive in Orchomenus it may be, or in sandy Pylos,  or yet with Menelaus in wide Sparta; '),(11452,'for not yet has goodly Orestes perished on the earth.’'),(11453,'“So he spoke, and I made answer and said: '),(11454,'Son of Atreus, wherefore dost thou question me of this? '),(11455,'I know not at all whether he be alive or dead, '),(11456,' and it is an ill thing to speak words vain as wind.’'),(11457,'\n  “Thus we two stood and held sad converse with one another, sorrowing and shedding big tears; '),(11458,'and there came up the spirit of Achilles, son of Peleus, and those of Patroclus and of peerless Antilochus and of Aias, who in comeliness and form was the goodliest  of all the Danaans after the peerless son of Peleus. '),(11459,' And the spirit of the swift-footed son of Aeacus recognized me, and weeping, spoke to me winged words:'),(11460,'\n“Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, rash man, what deed yet greater than this wilt thou devise in thy heart?'),(11461,'  How didst thou dare to come down to Hades, where dwell the unheeding dead, the phantoms of men outworn.’'),(11462,'“‘So he spoke, and I made answer and said:'),(11463,'‘Achilles, son of Peleus, far the mightiest of the Achaeans, I came through need of Teiresias, if haply  he would tell me some plan whereby I might reach rugged Ithaca. '),(11464,'For not yet have I come near to the land of Achaea, nor have I as yet set foot on my own country, but am ever suffering woes;'),(11465,' whereas than thou, Achilles, no man aforetime was more blessed nor shall ever be hereafter. '),(11466,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 11.484-11.486'),(11467,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 11.486'),(11468,' \n“So I spoke, and he straightway made answer and said:'),(11469,' ‘Nay, seek not to speak soothingly to me of death, glorious Odysseus.'),(11470,' I should choose, so I might live on earth, to serve as the hireling of another,  of some portionless man whose livelihood was but small, rather than to be lord over all the dead that have perished.'),(11471,' But come, tell me tidings of my son, that lordly youth, whether or not he followed to the war to be a leader. '),(11472,'And tell me of noble Peleus, if thou hast heard aught,  whether he still has honor among the host of the Myrmidons, or whether men do him dishonor throughout Hellas and Phthia, because old age binds him hand and foot.'),(11473,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 11.498-11.500'),(11474,' If but in such strength I could come, were it but for an hour, to my father\'s house, '),(11475,'I would give many a one of those who do him violence and keep him from his honor, cause to rue my strength and my invincible hands.\''),(11476,'“So he spoke, and I made answer and said:'),(11477,'  ‘Verily of noble Peleus have I heard naught, but as touching thy dear son, Neoptolemus, I will tell thee all the truth, as thou biddest me.'),(11478,' I it was, myself, who brought him from Scyros in my shapely, hollow ship to join the host of the well-greaved Archaeans.'),(11479,'  And verily, as often as we took counsel around the city of Troy, he was ever the first to speak, and made no miss of words; '),(11480,' godlike Nestor and I alone surpassed him.'),(11481,'But as often as we fought with the bronze on the Trojan plain, he would never remain behind in the throng or press of men,  but would ever run forth far to the front, yielding to none in his might; and many men he slew in dread combat. '),(11482,'All of them I could not tell or name, all the host that he slew in defence of the Argives; but what a warrior was that son of Telephus whom he slew with the sword,  the prince Eurypylus! Aye, and many of his comrades, the Ceteians, were slain about him, because of gifts a woman craved.'),(11483,' He verily was the comeliest man I saw, next to goodly Memnon.'),(11484,'And again, when we, the best of the Argives, were about to go down into the horse which Epeus made, and the command of all was laid upon me,  both to open and to close the door of our stout-built ambush, then the other leaders and counsellors of the Danaans would wipe away tears from their eyes, and each man\'s limbs shook beneath him, '),(11485,' but never did my eyes see his fair face grow pale at all, nor see him  wiping tears from his cheeks;'),(11486,' but he earnestly besought me to let him go forth from the horse, and kept handling his sword-hilt and his spear heavy with bronze, and was eager to work harm to the Trojans.'),(11487,' But after we had sacked the lofty city of Priam, he went on board his ship with his share of the spoil and a goodly prize—  all unscathed he was, neither smitten with the sharp spear nor wounded in close fight, as often befalls in war; '),(11488,'for Ares rages confusedly.’ '),(11489,' \n“So I spoke, and the spirit of the son of Aeacus departed with long strides over the field of asphodel,  joyful in that I said that his son was preeminent.'),(11490,'\n“And other spirits of those dead and gone stood sorrowing, and each asked of those dear to him.'),(11491,'Alone of them all the spirit of Aias, son of Telamon, stood apart, still full of wrath for the victory  that I had won over him in the contest by the ships for the arms of Achilles, '),(11492,' whose honored mother had set them for a prize; '),(11493,' and the judges were the sons of the Trojans and Pallas Athena.'),(11494,' I would that I had never won in the contest for such a prize, '),(11495,'over so noble a head did the earth close because of those arms,  even over Aias, who in comeliness and in deeds of war was above all the other Achaeans, next to the peerless son of Peleus.'),(11496,' To him I spoke with soothing words:'),(11497,'\n“‘Aias, son of peerless Telamon, wast thou then not even in death to forget thy wrath against me because of  those accursed arms?'),(11498,'Surely the gods set them to be a bane to the Argives: such a tower of strength was lost to them in thee;'),(11499,'  and for thee in death we Achaeans sorrow unceasingly, even as for the life of Achilles, son of Peleus.'),(11500,' Yet no other is to blame but Zeus,  who bore terrible hatred against the host of Danaan spearmen, and brought on thee thy doom.'),(11501,' Nay, come hither, prince, that thou mayest hear my word and my speech; '),(11502,'and subdue thy wrath and thy proud spirit.\''),(11503,'“So I spoke, but he answered me not a word, but went his way to Erebus to join the other spirits of those dead and gone. '),(11504,'  Then would he nevertheless have spoken to me for all his wrath, or I to him, '),(11505,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 11.566-11.567'),(11506,' \n“There then I saw Minos, the glorious son of Zeus, golden sceptre in hand, giving judgment to the dead  from his seat, while they sat and stood about the king through the wide-gated house of Hades, and asked of him judgment.'),(11507,'\n“And after him I marked huge Orion driving together over the field of asphodel wild beasts which he himself had slain on the lonely hills,  and in his hands he held a club all of bronze, ever unbroken.'),(11508,'\n“And I saw Tityos, son of glorious Gaea, lying on the ground.'),(11509,' Over nine roods he stretched, and two vultures sat, one on either side, and tore his liver, plunging their beaks into his bowels, nor could he beat them off with his hands.'),(11510,'  For he had offered violence to Leto, the glorious wife of Zeus, as she went toward Pytho through Panopeus with its lovely lawns.'),(11511,'\n“Aye, and I saw Tantalus in violent torment, standing in a pool, '),(11512,'\nand the water came nigh unto his chin.'),(11513,' He seemed as one athirst, but could not take and drink; '),(11514,' for as often as that old man stooped down, eager to drink, so often would the water be swallowed up and vanish away, and at his feet the black earth would appear, for some god made all dry.'),(11515,' And trees, high and leafy, let stream their fruits above his head, pears, and pomegranates, and apple trees with their bright fruit,  and sweet figs, and luxuriant olives. '),(11516,'But as often as that old man would reach out toward these, to clutch them with his hands, the wind would toss them to the shadowy clouds.'),(11517,'\n“Aye, and I saw Sisyphus in violent torment, seeking to raise a monstrous stone with both his hands.'),(11518,'  Verily he would brace himself with hands and feet, and thrust the stone toward the crest of a hill, '),(11519,' but as often as he was about to heave it over the top, the weight would turn it back, '),(11520,'and then down again to the plain would come rolling the ruthless stone.'),(11521,' But he would strain again and thrust it back, and the sweat  flowed down from his limbs, and dust rose up from his head.'),(11522,' \n“And after him I marked the mighty Heracles—his phantom; '),(11523,'for he himself among the immortal gods takes his joy in the feast, and has to wife Hebe, of the fair ankles, daughter of great Zeus and of Here, of the golden sandals.'),(11524,'  About him rose a clamor from the dead, as of birds flying everywhere in terror; '),(11525,' and he like dark night, with his bow bare and with arrow on the string, glared about him terribly, like one in act to shoot.'),(11526,'Awful was the belt about his breast,  a baldric of gold, whereon wondrous things were fashioned, bears and wild boars, and lions with flashing eyes, and conflicts, and battles, and murders, and slayings of men.'),(11527,' May he never have designed, or hereafter design such another, even he who stored up in his craft the device of that belt.'),(11528,'  He in turn knew me when his eyes beheld me, and weeping spoke to me winged words:'),(11529,'\n“‘Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, ah, wretched man, dost thou, too, drag out an evil lot such as I once bore beneath the rays of the sun?'),(11530,'  I was the son of Zeus, son of Cronos, but I had woe beyond measure; '),(11531,' for to a man far worse than I was I made subject, and he laid on me hard labours.'),(11532,' Yea, he once sent me hither to fetch the hound of Hades, '),(11533,' for he could devise for me no other task mightier than this.'),(11534,'  The hound I carried off and led forth from the house of Hades;'),(11535,' and Hermes was my guide, and flashing-eyed Athena.\''),(11536,'“So saying, he went his way again into the house of Hades, but I abode there steadfastly, in the hope that some other haply might still come forth of the warrior heroes who died in the days of old.'),(11537,'  And I should have seen yet others of the men of former time, whom I was fain to behold, even Theseus and Peirithous, glorious children of the gods, '),(11538,' but ere that the myriad tribes of the dead came thronging up with a wondrous cry, '),(11539,' and pale fear seized me, lest  august Persephone might send forth upon me from out the house of Hades the head of the Gorgon, that awful monster.'),(11540,'“Straightway then I went to the ship and bade my comrades themselves to embark, and to loose the stern cables.'),(11541,' So they went on board quickly and sat down upon the benches.'),(11542,' And the ship was borne down the stream Oceanus by the swelling flood,  first with our rowing, and afterwards the wind was fair.'),(11543,' “Now after our ship had left the stream of the river Oceanus and had come to the wave of the broad sea, and the Aeaean isle, where is the dwelling of early Dawn and her dancing-lawns, and the risings of the sun,  there on our coming we beached our ship on the sands, and ourselves went forth upon the shore of the sea, '),(11544,' and there we fell asleep, and waited for the bright Dawn.'),(11545,'\n“As soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, then I sent forth my comrades to the house of Circe  to fetch the body of the dead Elpenor. '),(11546,'Straightway then we cut billets of wood and gave him burial where the headland runs furthest out to sea, sorrowing and shedding big tears.'),(11547,' But when the dead man was burned, and the armour of the dead, we heaped up a mound and dragged on to it a pillar,  and on the top of the mound we planted his shapely oar.'),(11548,'“We then were busied with these several tasks,'),(11549,'\n howbeit Circe was not unaware of our coming forth from the house of Hades, but speedily she arrayed herself and came, '),(11550,'and her handmaids brought with her bread and meat in abundance and flaming red wine.'),(11551,'  And the beautiful goddess stood in our midst, and spoke among us, saying:'),(11552,'\n“‘Rash men, who have gone down alive to the house of Hades to meet death twice, while other men die but once.'),(11553,' Nay, come, eat food and drink wine here this whole day through;'),(11554,' but at the coming of Dawn  ye shall set sail, '),(11555,'and I will point out the way and declare to you each thing, in order that ye may not suffer pain and woes through wretched ill-contriving either by sea or on land.\''),(11556,'“So she spoke, and our proud hearts consented.'),(11557,' So then all day long till set of sun  we sat feasting on abundant flesh and sweet wine. '),(11558,'But when the sun set and darkness came on, they lay down to rest beside the stern cables of the ship; but Circe took me by the hand, and leading me apart from my dear comrades, made me to sit, and herself lay down close at hand and asked me all the tale. '),(11559,' And I told her all in due order.'),(11560,' Then queenly Circe spoke to me and said:'),(11561,'\n“All these things have thus found an end; but do thou hearken as I shall tell thee, and a god shall himself bring it to thy mind.'),(11562,' To the Sirens first shalt thou come, who  beguile all men whosoever comes to them. '),(11563,' Whoso in ignorance draws near to them and hears the Sirens\' voice, he nevermore returns, that his wife and little children may stand at his side rejoicing, but the Sirens beguile him with their clear-toned song,  as they sit in a meadow, and about them is a great heap of bones of mouldering men, and round the bones the skin is shrivelling.'),(11564,' But do thou row past them, and anoint the ears of thy comrades with sweet wax, which thou hast kneaded, lest any of the rest may hear. '),(11565,' But if thou thyself hast a will to listen,  let them bind thee in the swift ship hand and foot upright in the step of the mast, and let the ropes be made fast at the ends to the mast itself, that with delight thou mayest listen to the voice of the two Sirens.'),(11566,' And if thou shalt implore and bid thy comrades to loose thee, then let them bind thee with yet more bonds.'),(11567,'  But when thy comrades shall have rowed past these, thereafter I shall not fully say on which side thy course is to lie, but do thou thyself ponder it in mind, '),(11568,'and I will tell thee of both ways.'),(11569,' For on the one hand are beetling crags, and against them  roars the great wave of dark-eyed Amphitrite;'),(11570,'the Planctae do the blessed gods call these.'),(11571,' Thereby not even winged things may pass, no, not the timorous doves that bear ambrosia to father Zeus, but the smooth rock ever snatches away one even of these, '),(11572,' and the father sends in another to make up the tale. '),(11573,'And thereby has no ship of men ever yet escaped that has come thither, but the planks of ships and bodies of men are whirled confusedly by the waves of the sea and the blasts of baneful fire.'),(11574,' One seafaring ship alone has passed thereby,  that Argo famed of all, on her voyage from Aeetes, '),(11575,'and even her the wave would speedily have dashed there against the great crags, had not Here sent her through, for that Jason was dear to her. '),(11576,' \n“‘Now on the other path are two cliffs, one of which reaches with its sharp peak to the broad heaven, and a dark cloud surrounds it.'),(11577,'  This never melts away, nor does clear sky ever surround that peak in summer or in harvest time.'),(11578,' No mortal man could scale it or set foot upon the top, not though he had twenty hands and feet; '),(11579,'for the rock is smooth, as if it were polished.'),(11580,'  And in the midst of the cliff is a dim cave, turned to the West, toward Erebus, even where you shall steer your hollow ship, glorious Odysseus.'),(11581,' Not even a man of might could shoot an arrow from the hollow ship so as to reach into that vaulted cave.'),(11582,'  Therein dwells Scylla, yelping terribly.'),(11583,'Her voice is indeed but as the voice of a new-born whelp, but she herself is an evil monster,'),(11584,'  nor would anyone be glad at sight of her, no, not though it were a god that met her. '),(11585,' Verily she has twelve feet, all misshapen,  and six necks, exceeding long, and on each one an awful head, and therein three rows of teeth, thick and close, and full of black death.'),(11586,' Up to her middle she is hidden in the hollow cave, but she holds her head out beyond the dread chasm,  and fishes there, eagerly searching around the rock for dolphins and sea-dogs and whatever greater beast she may haply catch, such creatures as deep-moaning Amphitrite rears in multitudes past counting.'),(11587,' By her no sailors yet may boast that they have fled unscathed in their ship,'),(11588,' for with each head she carries off  a man, snatching him from the dark-prowed ship.'),(11589,'“‘But the other cliff, thou wilt note, Odysseus, is lower—'),(11590,' thou couldst even shoot an arrow across—'),(11591,' thou couldst even shoot an arrow across—'),(11592,'and on it is a great fig tree with rich foliage, '),(11593,' but beneath this divine Charybdis sucks down the black water.'),(11594,'  Thrice a day she belches it forth, and thrice she sucks it down terribly.'),(11595,'Mayest thou not be there when she sucks it down,'),(11596,'  for no one could save thee from ruin, no, not the Earth-shaker.'),(11597,' Nay, draw very close to Scylla\'s cliff, and drive thy ship past quickly; for it is better far   to mourn six comrades in thy ship than all together.’ '),(11598,' \n“So she spoke, but I made answer and said:'),(11599,' ‘Come, I pray thee, goddess, tell me this thing truly, if in any wise I might escape from fell Charybids, and ward off that other, when she works harm to my comrades.’'),(11600,'\n  “So I spoke, and the beautiful goddess answered and said: '),(11601,' ‘Rash man, lo, now again thy heart is set on the deeds of war and on toil.'),(11602,'  Wilt thou not yield even to the immortal gods?'),(11603,'  She is not mortal, but an immortal bane, dread, and dire, and fierce, and not to be fought with; '),(11604,'  there is no defence; '),(11605,' to flee from her is bravest. '),(11606,' For if thou tarriest to arm thyself by the cliff, I fear lest she may again dart forth and attack thee with as many heads and seize as many men as before.'),(11607,' Nay, row past with all thy might, and call upon Crataiis,  the mother of Scylla, who bore her for a bane to mortals. '),(11608,' Then will she keep her from darting forth again.'),(11609,' “‘And thou wilt come to the isle Thrinacia. '),(11610,'There in great numbers feed the kine of Helios and his goodly flocks, seven herds of kine and as many fair flocks of sheep,  and fifty in each. '),(11611,' These bear no young, nor do they ever die, '),(11612,' and goddesses are their shepherds, fair-tressed nymphs, Phaethusa and Lampetie, whom beautiful Neaera bore to Helios Hyperion. '),(11613,'These their honored mother, when she had borne and reared them,  sent to the isle Thrinacia to dwell afar, and keep the flocks of their father and his sleek kine. '),(11614,' If thou leavest these unharmed and heedest thy homeward way, verily ye may yet reach Ithaca, though in evil plight.'),(11615,' But if thou harmest them, then I foretell ruin  for thy ship and for thy comrades,'),(11616,'and even if thou shalt thyself escape, late shalt thou come home and in evil case, after losing all thy comrades.’'),(11617,' “So she spoke, and presently came golden-throned Dawn. '),(11618,'Then the beautiful goddess departed up the island,'),(11619,' but I went to the ship and roused my comrades  themselves to embark and to loose the stern cables. '),(11620,' So they went on board straightway and sat down upon the benches, '),(11621,'and sitting well in order smote the grey sea with their oars. '),(11622,' And for our aid in the wake of our dark-prowed ship a fair wind that filled the sail, a goodly comrade, was sent  by fair-tressed Circe, dread goddess of human speech.'),(11623,' So when we had straightway made fast all the tackling throughout the ship we sat down,'),(11624,' but the wind and the helmsman guided the ship. '),(11625,' \n“Then verily I spoke among my comrades, grieved at heart:'),(11626,' ‘Friends, since it is not right that one or two alone should know  the oracles that Circe, the beautiful goddess, told me, '),(11627,'therefore will I tell them, in order that knowing them we may either die or, shunning death and fate, escape.'),(11628,' First she bade us avoid the voice of the wondrous Sirens, and their flowery meadow.'),(11629,'  Me alone she bade to listen to their voice;'),(11630,' but do ye bind me with grievous bonds, that I may abide fast where I am, upright in the step of the mast, and let the ropes be made fast at the ends to the mast itself; '),(11631,'and if I implore and bid you to loose me, then do ye tie me fast with yet more bonds.\''),(11632,' “Thus I rehearsed all these things and told them to my comrades. '),(11633,'Meanwhile the well-built ship speedily came to the isle of the two Sirens, '),(11634,'for a fair and gentle wind bore her on.'),(11635,' Then presently the wind ceased and there was a windless calm, and a god lulled the waves to sleep.'),(11636,'  But my comrades rose up and furled the sail and stowed it in the hollow ship, and thereafter sat at the oars and made the water white with their polished oars of fir.'),(11637,' But I with my sharp sword cut into small bits a great round cake of wax, and kneaded it with my strong hands, '),(11638,' and soon the wax grew warm, forced by the strong pressure and the rays of the lord Helios Hyperion.'),(11639,' Then I anointed with this the ears of all my comrades in turn; '),(11640,'and they bound me in the ship hand and foot, upright in the step of the mast, and made the ropes fast at the ends to the mast itself; '),(11641,' and themselves sitting down smote the grey sea with their oars. '),(11642,'But when we were as far distant as a man can make himself heard when he shouts, driving swiftly on our way, the Sirens failed not to note the swift ship as it drew near, and they raised their clear-toned song:'),(11643,'\n“‘Come hither, as thou farest, renowned Odysseus, great glory of the Achaeans;  stay thy ship that thou mayest listen to the voice of us two. '),(11644,' For never yet has any man rowed past this isle in his black ship until he has heard the sweet voice from our lips. Nay, he has joy of it, and goes his way a wiser man. '),(11645,'For we know all the toils that in wide Troy  the Argives and Trojans endured through the will of the gods, and we know all things that come to pass upon the fruitful earth.’ '),(11646,' \n“So they spoke, sending forth their beautiful voice, '),(11647,' and my heart was fain to listen, and I bade my comrades loose me, nodding to them with my brows; '),(11648,'but they fell to their oars and rowed on.'),(11649,'  And presently Perimedes and Eurylochus arose and bound me with yet more bonds and drew them tighter.'),(11650,' But when they had rowed past the Sirens, and we could no more hear their voice or their song, then straightway my trusty comrades took away the  wax with which I had anointed their ears and loosed me from my bonds.'),(11651,'“But when we had left the island, I presently saw smoke and a great billow, and heard a booming.'),(11652,' Then from the hands of my men in their terror the oars flew, and splashed one and all in the swirl, '),(11653,'and  the ship stood still where it was, when they no longer plied with their hands the tapering oars.'),(11654,' But I went through the ship and cheered my men with gentle words, coming up to each man in turn:'),(11655,'\n“‘Friends, hitherto we have been in no wise ignorant of sorrow; '),(11656,'surely this evil that besets us now is no greater than when the Cyclops  penned us in his hollow cave by brutal strength; '),(11657,' yet even thence we made our escape through my valor and counsel and wit; these dangers, too, methinks we shall some day remember.'),(11658,' But now come, as I bid, let us all obey.'),(11659,' Do you keep your seats on the benches  and smite with your oars the deep surf of the sea, in the hope that Zeus may grant us to escape and avoid this death.'),(11660,'  And to thee, steersman, I give this command,'),(11661,' and do thou lay it to heart, since thou wieldest the steering oar of the hollow ship.'),(11662,' From this smoke and surf keep  the ship well away and hug the cliff, lest, ere thou know it, the ship swerve off to the other side and thou cast us into destruction.\''),(11663,'“So I spoke, and they quickly hearkened to my words.'),(11664,'But of Scylla I went not on to speak, a cureless bane, lest haply my comrades, seized with fear, should cease  from rowing and huddle together in the hold.'),(11665,' Then verily I forgot the hard command of Circe, whereas she bade me in no wise to arm myself;'),(11666,' but when I had put on my glorious armour and grasped in my hand two long spears, I went to the fore-deck of the ship, '),(11667,'  whence I deemed that Scylla of the rock would first be seen, who was to bring ruin upon my comrades.'),(11668,' But nowhere could I descry her, and my eyes grew weary as I gazed everywhere toward the misty rock. '),(11669,' \n“We then sailed on up the narrow strait with wailing.'),(11670,'  For on one side lay Scylla and on the other divine Charybdis terribly sucked down the salt water of the sea.'),(11671,' Verily whenever she belched it forth, like a cauldron on a great fire she would seethe and bubble in utter turmoil, and high over head the spray would fall on the tops of both the cliffs.'),(11672,'  But as often as she sucked down the salt water of the sea, within she could all be seen in utter turmoil, and round about the rock roared terribly, while beneath the earth appeared black with sand;'),(11673,' and pale fear seized my men.'),(11674,' So we looked toward her and feared destruction; '),(11675,' but meanwhile Scylla seized from out the hollow ship six of my comrades who were the best in strength and in might.'),(11676,' Turning my eyes to the swift ship and to the company of my men, even then I noted above me their feet and hands as they were raised aloft.'),(11677,' To me they cried aloud, calling upon me  by name for that last time in anguish of heart. '),(11678,' And as a fisher on a jutting rock, when he casts in his baits as a snare to the little fishes, with his long pole lets down into the sea the horn of an ox of the steading, and then as he catches a fish flings it writhing ashore,  even so were they drawn writhing up towards the cliffs. '),(11679,'Then at her doors she devoured them shrieking and stretching out their hands toward me in their awful death-struggle.'),(11680,' Most piteous did mine eyes behold that thing of all that I bore while I explored the paths of the sea.'),(11681,'\n  “Now when we had escaped the rocks, and dread Charybdis and Scylla, presently then we came to the goodly island of the god,'),(11682,' where were the fair kine, broad of brow, and the many goodly flocks of Helios Hyperion. '),(11683,'Then while I was still out at sea in my black ship,  I heard the lowing of the cattle that were being stalled and the bleating of the sheep, '),(11684,'and upon my mind fell the words of the blind seer, Theban Teiresias, and of Aeaean Circe, who very straitly charged me to shun the island of Helios, who gives joy to mortals.'),(11685,' Then verily I spoke among my comrades, grieved at heart:'),(11686,' \n“‘Hear my words, comrades, for all your evil plight, that I may tell you the oracles of Teiresias and of Aeaean Circe, who very straitly charged me to shun the island of Helios, who gives joy to mortals; '),(11687,' for there, she said, was our most terrible bane. '),(11688,' Nay, row the black ship out past the island.’ '),(11689,' \n“So I spoke, but their spirit was broken within them, '),(11690,' \nand straightway Eurylochus answered me with hateful words:'),(11691,'\n“‘Hardy art thou, Odysseus; '),(11692,'\nthou hast strength beyond that of other men and thy limbs never  grow weary. '),(11693,' Verily thou art wholly wrought of iron, seeing that thou sufferest not thy comrades, worn out with toil and drowsiness, to set foot on shore, where on this sea-girt isle we might once more make ready a savoury supper; but thou biddest us even as we are to wander on through the swift night,  driven away from the island over the misty deep.'),(11694,'It is from the night that fierce winds are born, wreckers of ships.'),(11695,'  How could one escape utter destruction, if haply there should suddenly come a blast of the South Wind or the blustering West Wind, which oftenest  wreck ships in despite of the sovereign gods? '),(11696,'Nay, verily for this time let us yield to black night and make ready our supper, remaining by the swift ship, and in the morning we will go aboard, and put out into the broad sea.\''),(11697,'“So spoke Eurylochus, and the rest of my comrades gave assent.'),(11698,'  Then verily I knew that some god was assuredly devising ill, and I spoke and addressed him with winged words:'),(11699,'“‘Eurylochus, verily ye constrain me, who stand alone.'),(11700,'\n But come now, do ye all swear to me a mighty oath, '),(11701,'to the end that, if we haply find a herd of kine or a great flock of sheep,  no man may slay either cow or sheep in the blind folly of his mind; '),(11702,' but be content to eat the food which immortal Circe gave.\''),(11703,'\n“So I spoke; and they straightway swore that they would not, even as I bade them. '),(11704,'But when they had sworn and made an end of the oath,  we moored our well-built ship in the hollow harbor near a spring of sweet water, and my comrades went forth from the ship and skilfully made ready their supper.'),(11705,' But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, then they fell to weeping, as they remembered their dear comrades  whom Scylla had snatched from out the hollow ship and devoured;'),(11706,' and sweet sleep came upon them as they wept.'),(11707,' But when it was the third watch of the night, and the stars had turned their course, Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, roused against us a fierce wind with a wondrous tempest, and hid with clouds  the land and sea alike,'),(11708,'and night rushed down from heaven. '),(11709,' And as soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, we dragged our ship, and made her fast in a hollow cave, '),(11710,' where were the fair dancing-floors and seats of the nymphs.'),(11711,' Then I called my men together and spoke among them:'),(11712,'\n  “‘Friends, in our swift ship is meat and drink; let us therefore keep our hands from those kine lest we come to harm, '),(11713,'for these are the cows and goodly sheep of a dread god, even of Helios, who oversees all things and overhears all things.\''),(11714,'“So I spoke, and their proud hearts consented.'),(11715,'  Then for a full month the South Wind blew unceasingly, nor did any other wind arise except the East and the South. '),(11716,' \n“Now so long as my men had grain and red wine they kept their hands from the kine, for they were eager to save their lives.'),(11717,'But when all the stores had been consumed from out the ship,  and now they must needs roam about in search of game, fishes, and fowl, and whatever might come to their hands—fishing with bent hooks, for hunger pinched their bellies—'),(11718,'then I went apart up the island that I might pray to the gods in the hope that one of them might show me a way to go.'),(11719,'  And when, as I went through the island, I had got away from my comrades, I washed my hands in a place where there was shelter from the wind, and prayed to all the gods that hold Olympus; '),(11720,'but they shed sweet sleep upon my eyelids.'),(11721,' And meanwhile Eurylochus began to give evil counsel to my comrades:'),(11722,'  “‘Hear my words, comrades, for all your evil plight.'),(11723,'All forms of death are hateful to wretched mortals, but to die of hunger, and so meet one\'s doom, is the most pitiful.'),(11724,' Nay, come, let us drive off the best of the kine of Helios and offer sacrifice to the immortals who hold broad heaven.'),(11725,'   And if we ever reach Ithaca, our native land, we will straightway build a rich temple to Helios Hyperion and put therein many goodly offerings. '),(11726,' And if haply he be wroth at all because of his straight-horned kine, and be minded to destroy our ship, and the other gods consent,  rather would I lose my life once for all with a gulp at the wave, than pine slowly away in a desert isle.\''),(11727,'“So spoke Eurylochus, and the rest of my comrades gave assent.'),(11728,' Straightway they drove off the best of the kine of Helios from near at hand, for not far from the dark-prowed ship  were grazing the fair, sleek kine, broad of brow. '),(11729,'Around these, then, they stood and made prayer to the gods, plucking the tender leaves from off a high-crested oak; '),(11730,' for they had no white barley on board the well-benched ship.'),(11731,'Now when they had prayed and had cut the throats of the kine and flayed them,  they cut out the thigh-pieces and covered them with a double layer of fat and laid raw flesh upon them.'),(11732,' They had no wine to pour over the blazing sacrifice, but they made libations with water, and roasted all the entrails over the fire.  '),(11733,' Now when the thighs were wholly burned and they had tasted the inner parts,  they cut up the rest and spitted it. '),(11734,'Then it was that sweet sleep fled from my eyelids, and I went my way to the swift ship and the shore of the sea.'),(11735,' But when, as I went, I drew near to the curved ship, then verily the hot savour of the fat was wafted about me,'),(11736,' and I groaned and cried aloud to the immortal gods:'),(11737,'\n“‘Father Zeus and ye other blessed gods that are for ever, verily it was for my ruin that ye lulled me in pitiless sleep, '),(11738,' while my comrades remaining behind have contrived a monstrous deed.\''),(11739,'\n“Swiftly then to Helios Hyperion came  Lampetie of the long robes, bearing tidings that we had slain his kine; '),(11740,'and straightway he spoke among the immortals, wroth at heart:'),(11741,'\n“‘Father Zeus and ye other blessed gods that are for ever, take vengeance now on the comrades of Odysseus, son of Laertes, who have insolently slain my kine, in which I  ever took delight, when I went toward the starry heaven and when I turned back again to earth from heaven.'),(11742,' If they do not pay me fit atonement for the kine I will go down to Hades and shine among the dead.\''),(11743,'\n“Then Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, answered him and said:'),(11744,'  ‘Helios, do thou verily shine on among the immortals and among mortal men upon the earth, the giver of grain.'),(11745,' As for these men I will soon smite their swift ship with my bright thunder-bolt, and shatter it to pieces in the midst of the wine-dark sea.\''),(11746,'“This I heard from fair-haired Calypso, '),(11747,' and she said that she herself had heard it from the messenger Hermes.'),(11748,'“But when I had come down to the ship and to the sea I upbraided my men, coming up to each in turn, but we could find no remedy—the kine were already dead.'),(11749,' For my men, then, the gods straightway shewed forth portents.'),(11750,'  The hides crawled, the flesh, both roast and raw, bellowed upon the spits, and there was a lowing as of kine. '),(11751,' \n“For six days, then, my trusty comrades feasted on the best of the kine of Helios which they had driven off. '),(11752,' \nBut when Zeus, the son of Cronos, brought upon us the seventh day,  then the wind ceased to blow tempestuously, and we straightway went on board, and put out into the broad sea when we had set up the mast and hoisted the white sail.'),(11753,' \n“But when we had left that island and no other land appeared, but only sky and sea,  then verily the son of Cronos set a black cloud above the hollow ship, and the sea grew dark beneath it.'),(11754,' She ran on for no long time, '),(11755,' for straightway came the shrieking West Wind, blowing with a furious tempest, and the blast of the wind snapped both the fore-stays of the mast, '),(11756,' so that the mast fell backward and all its tackling was strewn in the bilge.'),(11757,' On the stern of the ship the mast struck the head of the pilot and crushed all the bones of his skull together, '),(11758,'and like a diver he fell from the deck and his proud spirit left his bones.  '),(11759,' Therewith Zeus thundered and hurled his bolt upon the ship,'),(11760,'and she quivered from stem to stern, smitten by the bolt of Zeus, and was filled with sulphurous smoke, and my comrades fell from out the ship.'),(11761,' Like sea-crows they were borne on the waves about the black ship, and the god took from them their returning.'),(11762,'  But I kept pacing up and down the ship till the surge tore the sides from the keel, and the wave bore her on dismantled and snapped the mast off at the keel; '),(11763,' but over the mast had been flung the back-stay fashioned of ox-hide; '),(11764,'with this I lashed the two together, both keel and mast,  and sitting on these was borne by the direful winds.'),(11765,' \n“Then verily the West Wind ceased to blow tempestuously, and swiftly the South Wind came, bringing sorrow to my heart, that I might traverse again the way to baneful Charybdis.'),(11766,' All night long was I borne, and at the rising of the sun  I came to the cliff of Scylla and to dread Charybdis.'),(11767,'She verily sucked down the salt water of the sea,'),(11768,' but I, springing up to the tall fig-tree, laid hold of it, and clung to it like a bat.'),(11769,' Yet I could in no wise plant my feet firmly or climb upon the tree, '),(11770,'  for its roots spread far below and its branches hung out of reach above, long and great, and overshadowed Charybdis.'),(11771,' There I clung steadfastly until she should vomit forth mast and keel again, '),(11772,' and to my joy they came at length. '),(11773,' At the hour when a man rises from the assembly for his supper,  one that decides the many quarrels of young men that seek judgment, even at that hour those spars appeared from out Charybdis.'),(11774,' And I let go hands and feet from above and plunged down into the waters out beyond the long spars, and sitting on these I rowed onward with my hands.'),(11775,'  But as for Scylla, the father of gods and men did not suffer her again to catch sight of me, '),(11776,' else should I never have escaped utter destruction.'),(11777,'\n“Thence for nine days was I borne, and on the tenth night the gods brought me to Ogygia, where the fair-tressed Calypso dwells, dread goddess of human speech,  who gave me welcome and tendance. '),(11778,'But why should I tell thee this tale?'),(11779,'For it was but yesterday that I told it in thy hall to thyself and to thy noble wife.'),(11780,' It is an irksome thing, meseems, to tell again a plain-told tale.”'),(11781,' So he spoke, and they were all hushed in silence, and were spellbound throughout the shadowy halls.'),(11782,' And Alcinous again answered him, and said:'),(11783,'“Odysseus, since thou hast come to my  high-roofed house with floor of brass, thou shalt not, methinks, be driven back, and return with baffled purpose, even though thou hast suffered much.'),(11784,' And to each man of you that in my halls are ever wont to drink the flaming wine of the elders, and to listen to the minstrel, I speak, and give this charge.'),(11785,'  Raiment for the stranger lies already stored in the polished chest, with gold curiously wrought and all the other gifts which the counsellors of the Phaeacians brought hither.'),(11786,' But, come now, let us give him a great tripod and a cauldron, each man of us,'),(11787,'and we in turn will gather the cost from among the people,  and repay ourselves. '),(11788,' It were hard for one man to give freely, without requital.”'),(11789,'So spake Alcinous, and his word was pleasing to them.'),(11790,' They then went, each man to his house, to take their rest; but as soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, they hastened to the ship and brought the bronze, that gives strength to men.'),(11791,'  And the strong and mighty Alcinous went himself throughout the ship, and carefully stowed the gifts beneath the benches, that they might not hinder any of the crew at their rowing, when they busily plied the oars. '),(11792,'Then they went to the house of Alcinous, and prepared a feast.'),(11793,'And for them the strong and mighty Alcinous sacrificed a bull  to Zeus, son of Cronos, god of the dark clouds, who is lord of all.'),(11794,' Then, when they had burned the thigh-pieces, they feasted a glorious feast, and made merry,'),(11795,' and among them the divine minstrel Demodocus, held in honor by the people, sang to the lyre.'),(11796,' But Odysseus would ever turn his head toward the blazing sun,  eager to see it set, '),(11797,'for verily he was eager to return home.'),(11798,'And as a man longs for supper, for whom all day long a yoke of wine-dark oxen has drawn the jointed plough through fallow land,'),(11799,'  and gladly for him does the light of the sun sink, that he may busy him with his supper, and his knees grow weary as he goes; '),(11800,' even so gladly for Odysseus did the light of the sun sink. '),(11801,'Straightway then he spoke among the Phaeacians, lovers of the oar, and to Alcinous above all he declared his word, and said:'),(11802,'\n“Lord Alcinous, renowned above all men, pour libations now, and send ye me on my way in peace; and yourselves too—Farewell!'),(11803,'  For now all that my heart desired has been brought to pass: a convoy, and gifts of friendship.  May the gods of heaven bless them to me,'),(11804,' and on my return may I find in my home my peerless wife with those I love unscathed; '),(11805,' and may you again, remaining here, make glad  your wedded wives and children;'),(11806,'and may the gods grant you prosperity of every sort, and may no evil come upon your people.” '),(11807,' \nSo he spoke, and they all praised his words, and bade send the stranger on his way, since he had spoken fittingly.'),(11808,' Then the mighty Alcinous spoke to the herald, saying:'),(11809,'  “Pontonous, mix the bowl, and serve out wine to all in the hall, in order that, when we have made prayer to father Zeus, we may send forth the stranger to his own native land.\"'),(11810,'So he spoke, and Pontonous mixed the honey hearted wine and served out to all, coming up to each in turn; '),(11811,' and they poured libations to the blessed gods, who hold broad heaven, from where they sat.'),(11812,' But goodly Odysseus arose, and placed in the hand of Arete the two-handled cup, and spoke, and addressed her with winged words:'),(11813,'\n“Fare thee well, O queen, throughout all the years, till old age  and death come, which are the lot of mortals.'),(11814,' As for me, I go my way,'),(11815,' but do thou in this house have joy of thy children and thy people and Alcinous the king.\"'),(11816,'So the goodly Odysseus spake and passed over the threshold. And with him the mighty Alcinous sent forth a herald  to lead him to the swift ship and the shore of the sea. '),(11817,' And Arete sent with him slave women, one bearing a newly washed cloak and a tunic, and another again she bade follow to bear the strong chest, '),(11818,'and yet another bore bread and red wine.'),(11819,'\n  But when they had come down to the ship and to the sea, straightway the lordly youths that were his escort took these things, and stowed them in the hollow ship, even all the food and drink.'),(11820,' Then for Odysseus they spread a rug and a linen sheet on the deck of the hollow ship  at the stern, that he might sleep soundly; '),(11821,' and he too went aboard, and laid him down in silence.'),(11822,' Then they sat down on the benches, each in order, and loosed the hawser from the pierced stone.'),(11823,' And as soon as they leaned back, and tossed the brine with their oarblades, sweet sleep fell upon his eyelids,  an unawakening sleep, most sweet, and most like to death.'),(11824,'And as on a plain four yoked stallions spring forward all together beneath the strokes of the lash, and leaping on high swiftly accomplish their way, even so the stern of that ship leapt on high, and in her wake  the dark wave of the loud-sounding sea foamed mightily, '),(11825,' and she sped safely and surely on her way; '),(11826,' not even the circling hawk, the swiftest of winged things, could have kept pace with her.'),(11827,' Thus she sped on swiftly and clove the waves of the sea, bearing a man the peer of the gods in counsel,'),(11828,'  one who in time past had suffered many griefs at heart in passing through wars of men and the grievous waves; but now he slept in peace, forgetful of all that he had suffered. '),(11829,' \nNow when that brightest of stars rose which ever comes to herald the light of early Dawn,  even then the seafaring ship drew near to the island.'),(11830,'\nThere is in the land of Ithaca a certain harbor of Phorcys, the old man of the sea, '),(11831,' and at its mouth two projecting headlands sheer to seaward, but sloping down on the side toward the harbor.These keep back the great waves raised by heavy winds  without, '),(11832,'but within the benched ships lie unmoored when they have reached the point of anchorage.'),(11833,' At the head of the harbor is a long-leafed olive tree, and near it a pleasant, shadowy cave sacred to the nymphs that are called Naiads.'),(11834,'  Therein are mixing bowls and jars of stone, '),(11835,' and there too the bees store honey.'),(11836,'And in the cave are long looms of stone, at which the nymphs weave webs of purple dye, a wonder to behold; '),(11837,' and therein are also ever-flowing springs.'),(11838,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 13.109-13.111'),(11839,'Two doors there are to the cave,  one toward the North Wind, by which men go down, but that toward the South Wind is sacred, ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 109 to line 111'),(11840,'\nHere they rowed in, knowing the place of old; '),(11841,' and the ship ran full half her length on the shore  in her swift course,'),(11842,' at such pace was she driven by the arms of the rowers.'),(11843,'Then they stepped forth from the benched ship upon the land, and first they lifted Odysseus out of the hollow ship, with the linen sheet and bright rug as they were, and laid him down on the sand, still overpowered by sleep.  And they lifted out the goods which the lordly Phaeacians had given him, as he set out for home, through the favour of great-hearted Athena.'),(11844,' These they set all together by the trunk of the olive tree, out of the path, lest haply some wayfarer, before Odysseus awoke, might come upon them and spoil them.'),(11845,'  Then they themselves returned home again.'),(11846,' But the Shaker of the Earth did not forget the threats wherewith at the first he had threatened godlike Odysseus, and he thus enquired of the purpose of Zeus:'),(11847,'\n“Father Zeus, no longer shall I, even I, be held in honor among the immortal gods, seeing that mortals honor me not a whit—  even the Phaeacians, who, thou knowest, are of my own lineage.'),(11848,' For I but now declared that Odysseus should suffer many woes ere he reached his home,'),(11849,' though I did not wholly rob him of his return when once thou hadst promised it and confirmed it with thy nod; '),(11850,' yet in his sleep these men have borne him in a swift ship over the sea  and set him down in Ithaca, and have given him gifts past telling, stores of bronze and gold and woven raiment, more than Odysseus would ever have won for himself from Troy, if he had returned unscathed with his due share of the spoil.” '),(11851,' \nThen Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, answered him, and said: '),(11852,' \n “Ah me, thou shaker of the earth, wide of sway, what a thing hast thou said!'),(11853,' The gods do thee no dishonor;'),(11854,' hard indeed would it be to assail with dishonor our eldest and best.'),(11855,' But as for men, if any one, yielding to his might and strength, fails to do thee honor in aught, '),(11856,'thou mayest ever take vengeance, even thereafter.'),(11857,' Do as thou wilt, and as is thy good pleasure.”'),(11858,'Then Poseidon, the earth-shaker, answered him:'),(11859,' “Straightway should I have done as thou sayest, thou god of the dark clouds,'),(11860,' but I ever dread and avoid thy wrath.'),(11861,'But now I am minded to smite the fair ship of the Phaeacians,  as she comes back from his convoy on the misty deep, that hereafter they may desist and cease from giving convoy to men, and to fling a great mountain about their city.\"'),(11862,'Then Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, answered him and said: '),(11863,' “Lazy one, hear what seems best in my sight. When all the people are looking forth from the city upon her as she speeds on her way, then do thou turn her to stone hard by the land—a stone in the shape of a swift ship, that all men may marvel; and do thou fling a great mountain about their city.\"'),(11864,'Now when Poseidon, the earth-shaker, heard this  he went his way to Scheria, where the Phaeacians dwell, '),(11865,'and there he waited.'),(11866,' And she drew close to shore, the seafaring ship, speeding swiftly on her way.'),(11867,' Then near her came the Earth-shaker and turned her to stone, and rooted her fast beneath by a blow of the flat of his hand, and then he was gone.'),(11868,'and then he was gone.'),(11869,'\n  But they spoke winged words to one another, the Phaeacians of the long oars, men famed for their ships.'),(11870,' And thus would one speak, with a glance at his neighbor:'),(11871,'\n“Ah me, who has now bound our swift ship on the sea as she sped homeward?'),(11872,' Lo, she was in plain sight.\"'),(11873,'but they knew not how these things were to be. '),(11874,'but they knew not how these things were to be. '),(11875,'Then Alcinous addressed their company and said:'),(11876,'\n“Lo now, verily the oracles of my father, uttered long ago, have come upon me. He was wont to say that Poseidon was wroth with us because we give safe convoy to all men.'),(11877,'  He said that some day, as a beautiful ship of the Phaeacians was returning from a convoy over the misty deep, Poseidon would smite her, and would fling a great mountain about our town.'),(11878,' and lo, now all this is being brought to pass.'),(11879,' and lo, now all this is being brought to pass.'),(11880,' But now come, as I bid let us all obey.'),(11881,'  Cease ye to give convoy to mortals, when anyone comes to our city, '),(11882,'and let us sacrifice to Poseidon twelve choice bulls, if haply he may take pity, and not fling a lofty mountain about our town.” '),(11883,' \nSo he spoke, and they were seized with fear and made ready the bulls.'),(11884,'  Thus they were praying to the lord Poseidon, the leaders and counsellors of the land of the Phaeacians, as they stood about the altar, '),(11885,' but Odysseus awoke out of his sleep in his native land. Yet he knew it not after his long absence,'),(11886,'for about him the goddess had shed a mist,  even Pallas Athena, daughter of Zeus, that she might render him unknown, and tell him all things, so that his wife might not know him, nor his townsfolk, nor his friends, until the wooers had paid the full price of all their transgressions.'),(11887,' Therefore all things seemed strange to their lord,  the long paths, the bays offering safe anchorage, the sheer cliffs, and the luxuriant trees.'),(11888,' So he sprang up and stood and looked upon his native land, '),(11889,' and then he groaned and smote both of his thighs with the flat of his hands, and mournfully spoke, and said:'),(11890,'  “Woe is me, to the land of what mortals am I now come?'),(11891,' Are they cruel, and wild, and unjust, or do they love strangers and fear the gods in their thoughts?'),(11892,' Whither shall I bear all this wealth, '),(11893,' or whither shall I myself go wandering on? '),(11894,'Would that I had remained there among the Phaeacians, '),(11895,' and had then come to some other of the mighty kings, who would have entertained me and sent me on my homeward way.'),(11896,' But now I know not where to bestow this wealth; yet here will I not leave it, lest haply it become the spoil of others to my cost.'),(11897,' Out upon them; not wholly wise, it seems, nor just  were the leaders and counsellors of the Phaeacians who have brought me to a strange land. Verily they said that they would bring me to clear-seen Ithaca, but they have not made good their word.'),(11898,' May Zeus, the suppliant\'s god, requite them, who watches over all men, and punishes him that sins.'),(11899,'  But come, I will number the goods, and go over them, lest to my cost these men have carried off aught with them in the hollow ship.” '),(11900,' \nSo he spake, and set him to count the beautiful tripods, and the cauldrons, and the gold, and the fair woven raiment, '),(11901,' and of these he missed nothing. '),(11902,'Then, mournfully longing for his native land,  he paced by the shore of the loud-sounding sea, uttering many a moan.'),(11903,' And Athena drew near him in the form of a young man, a herdsman of sheep, one most delicate, as are the sons of princes. In a double fold about her shoulders she wore a well-wrought cloak,'),(11904,'  and beneath her shining feet she had sandals, and in her hands a spear. '),(11905,' Then Odysseus was glad at sight of her, and came to meet her, and he spoke, and addressed her with winged words:'),(11906,'\n“Friend, since thou art the first to whom I have come in this land, hail to thee, and mayst thou meet me with no evil mind.  Nay, save this treasure, and save me;'),(11907,'  for to thee do I pray, as to a god, and am come to thy dear knees.'),(11908,' And tell me this also truly, that I may know full well.'),(11909,' What land, what people is this? What men dwell here?'),(11910,' Is it some clear-seen island, or a shore  of the deep-soiled mainland that lies resting on the sea?”'),(11911,'\nThen the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(11912,' “A fool art thou, stranger, or art come from far, if indeed thou askest of this land.'),(11913,' Surely it is no wise so nameless, '),(11914,'but full many know it,  both all those who dwell toward the dawn and the sun, and all those that are behind toward the murky darkness.'),(11915,' It is a rugged isle, not fit for driving horses, yet it is not utterly poor, though it be but narrow.'),(11916,' Therein grows corn beyond measure, and the wine-grape as well,'),(11917,' and the rain never fails it, nor the rich dew.'),(11918,' It is a good land for pasturing goats and kine;'),(11919,' there are trees of every sort, and in it also pools for watering that fail not the year through.'),(11920,' Therefore, stranger, the name of Ithaca has reached even to the land of Troy which, they say, is far from this land of Achaea.” '),(11921,' \n  So she spake, and the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus was glad, and rejoiced in his land, the land of his fathers, as he heard the word of Pallas Athena, daughter of Zeus, who bears the aegis; '),(11922,'  and he spoke, and addressed her with winged words; '),(11923,' yet he spoke not the truth, but checked the word ere it was uttered,  ever revolving in his breast thoughts of great cunning:'),(11924,'“I heard of Ithaca, even in broad Crete, far over the sea;'),(11925,'\n and now have I myself come hither with these my goods. '),(11926,'And I left as much more with my children, when I fled the land, after I had slain the dear son of Idomeneus,  Orsilochus, swift of foot, who in broad Crete surpassed in fleetness all men that live by toil. Now he would have robbed me of all that booty of Troy, for which I had borne grief of heart, passing through wars of men and the grievous waves,  for that I would not shew favour to his father, and serve as his squire in the land of the Trojans, but commanded other men of my own.'),(11927,' So I smote him with my bronze-tipped spear as he came home from the field, lying in wait for him with one of my men by the roadside.'),(11928,' A dark night covered the heavens, and no  man was ware of us, but unseen I took away his life.'),(11929,' Now when I had slain him with the sharp bronze, I went straightway to a ship, and made prayer to the lordly Phoenicians, giving them booty to satisfy their hearts.'),(11930,' I bade them take me aboard and land me at Pylos,  or at goodly Elis, where the Epeans hold sway. '),(11931,'Yet verily the force of the wind thrust them away from thence, sore against their will, nor did they purpose to play me false; '),(11932,' but driven wandering from thence we came hither by night.'),(11933,'With eager haste we rowed on into the harbor, nor had we any  thought of supper, sore as was our need of it, but even as we were we went forth from the ship and lay down, one and all.'),(11934,' Then upon me came sweet sleep in my weariness, but they took my goods out of the hollow ship and set them where I myself lay on the sands.'),(11935,'  And they went on board, and departed for the well-peopled land of Sidon; '),(11936,'but I was left here, my heart sore troubled.” '),(11937,' \nSo he spoke, and the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, smiled, and stroked him with her hand, '),(11938,'and changed herself to the form of a woman, comely and tall, and skilled in glorious handiwork.'),(11939,'  And she spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(11940,'\n“Cunning must he be and knavish, who would go beyond thee in all manner of guile, aye, though it were a god that met thee.'),(11941,' Bold man, crafty in counsel, insatiate in deceit, not even in thine own land, it seems, wast thou to cease from guile  and deceitful tales, which thou lovest from the bottom of thine heart. '),(11942,' But come, let us no longer talk of this, being both well versed in craft, since thou art far the best of all men in counsel and in speech, and I among all the gods am famed for wisdom and craft.'),(11943,' Yet thou didst not know  Pallas Athena, daughter of Zeus, even me, who ever stand by thy side, and guard thee in all toils. Aye, and I made thee beloved by all the Phaeacians. And now am I come hither to weave a plan with thee, and to hide all the treasure, which the lordly Phaeacians  gave thee by my counsel and will, when thou didst set out for home; and to tell thee all the measure of woe it is thy fate to fulfil in thy well-built house.'),(11944,' But do thou be strong, for bear it thou must, and tell no man of them all nor any woman that thou hast come back from thy wanderings, but in silence  endure thy many griefs, and submit to the violence of men.”'),(11945,'\nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said:'),(11946,' “Hard is it, goddess, for a mortal man to know thee when he meets thee, how wise soever he be, '),(11947,'for thou takest what shape thou wilt.'),(11948,' But this I know well, that of old thou wast kindly toward me,  so long as we sons of the Achaeans were warring in the land of Troy.'),(11949,'But after we had sacked the lofty city of Priam, and had gone away in our ships, and a god had scattered the Achaeans, never since then have I seen thee, daughter of Zeus, nor marked thee coming on board my ship, that thou mightest ward off sorrow from me.'),(11950,'  Nay, I ever wandered on, bearing in my breast a stricken heart, till the gods delivered me from evil,'),(11951,'  even until in the rich land of the Phaeacians thou didst cheer me with thy words, and thyself lead me to their city.'),(11952,' But now I beseech thee by thy father—for I think not  that I am come to clear-seen Ithaca; nay, it is some other land over which I roam, '),(11953,'and thou, methinks, dost speak thus in mockery to beguile my mind—tell me whether in very truth I am come to my dear native land.” '),(11954,' \nThen the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(11955,'  “Ever such is the thought in thy breast,'),(11956,' and therefore it is that I cannot leave thee in thy sorrow, for thou art soft of speech, keen of wit, and prudent.'),(11957,' Eagerly would another man on his return from wanderings have hastened to behold in his halls his children and his wife;'),(11958,' but thou art not yet minded to know or learn of aught, till thou hast furthermore proved thy wife, who abides as of old in her halls, and ever sorrowfully for her the nights and days wane, as she weeps.'),(11959,' But as for me, I never doubted of this, but in my heart  knew it well, that thou wouldest come home after losing all thy comrades. '),(11960,'Yet, thou must know, I was not minded to strive against Poseidon, my father\'s brother, who laid up wrath in his heart against thee, angered that thou didst blind his dear son.'),(11961,' But come, I will shew thee the land of Ithaca, that thou mayest be sure.'),(11962,'  This is the harbor of Phorcys, the old man of the sea, and here at the head of the harbor is the long-leafed olive tree, '),(11963,'and near it is the pleasant, shadowy cave, sacred to the nymphs that are called Naiads.'),(11964,' This, thou must know, is the vaulted cave in which thou  wast wont to offer to the nymphs many hecatombs that bring fulfillment; '),(11965,'and yonder is Mount Neriton, clothed with its forests.\"'),(11966,'So spake the goddess, and scattered the mist, and the land appeared.'),(11967,' Glad then was the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus, rejoicing in his own land, and he kissed the earth, the giver of grain.'),(11968,'  And straightway he prayed to the nymphs with upstretched hands:'),(11969,'“Ye Naiad Nymphs, daughters of Zeus, never did I think to behold you again,'),(11970,' but now I hail you with loving prayers. '),(11971,'Aye, and gifts too will I give, as aforetime, if the daughter of Zeus, she that drives the spoil, shall graciously grant me  to live, and shall bring to manhood my dear son.\"'),(11972,'Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him again:'),(11973,' “Be of good cheer, and let not these things distress thy heart.'),(11974,' But let us now forthwith set thy goods in the innermost recess of the wondrous cave, where they may abide for thee in safety, '),(11975,'  and let us ourselves take thought how all may be far the best.”'),(11976,' \nSo saying, the goddess entered the shadowy cave and searched out its hiding-places.'),(11977,' And Odysseus brought all the treasure thither, the gold and the stubborn bronze and the finely-wrought raiment, which the Phaeacians gave him.'),(11978,'  These things he carefully laid away, and Pallas Athena, daughter of Zeus, who bears the aegis, set a stone at the door.'),(11979,' Then the two sat them down by the trunk of the sacred olive tree, and devised death for the insolent wooers.'),(11980,' And the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, was the first to speak, saying:'),(11981,'\n  “Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, take thought how thou mayest put forth thy hands on the shameless wooers, who now for three years have been lording it in thy halls, wooing thy godlike wife, and offering wooers\' gifts. '),(11982,' And she, as she mournfully looks for thy coming,  offers hopes to all, and has promises for each man, sending them messages, but her mind is set on other things.\"'),(11983,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said:'),(11984,' “Lo now, of a surety I was like to have perished in my halls by the evil fate of Agamemnon, son of Atreus,  hadst not thou, goddess, duly told me all.'),(11985,'  But come, weave some plan by which I may requite them;'),(11986,' and stand thyself by my side, and endue me with dauntless courage, even as when we loosed the bright diadem of Troy. '),(11987,' Wouldest thou but stand by my side, thou flashing-eyed one, as eager as thou wast then,  I would fight even against three hundred men, with thee, mighty goddess, if with a ready heart thou wouldest give me aid.\"'),(11988,'Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(11989,' “Yea verily, I will be with thee, and will not forget thee, when we are busied with this work; '),(11990,'and methinks many a one  of the wooers that devour thy substance shall bespatter the vast earth with his blood and brains.'),(11991,' But come, I will make thee unknown to all mortals. '),(11992,' I will shrivel the fair skin on thy supple limbs, and destroy the flaxen hair from off thy head, and clothe thee in a ragged garment,  such that one would shudder to see a man clad therein. And I will dim thy two eyes that were before so beautiful, that thou mayest appear mean in the sight of all the wooers, and of thy wife, and of thy son, whom thou didst leave in thy halls. '),(11993,'And for thyself, do thou go first of all  to the swineherd who keeps thy swine, and withal has a kindly heart towards thee, and loves thy son and constant Penelope.'),(11994,'Thou wilt find him abiding by the swine,'),(11995,'  and they are feeding by the rock of Corax and the spring Arethusa, eating acorns to their heart\'s content and  drinking the black water, things which cause the rich flesh of swine to wax fat. '),(11996,'There do thou stay, and sitting by his side question him of all things, while I go to Sparta, the land of fair women, to summon thence Telemachus, thy dear son, Odysseus, '),(11997,' who went to spacious Lacedaemon to the house of Menelaus,  to seek tidings of thee, if thou wast still anywhere alive.”'),(11998,' \nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered her:'),(11999,' “Why then, I pray thee, didst thou not tell him, thou whose mind knows all things?'),(12000,' Nay, was it haply that he too might suffer woes, wandering over the unresting sea, '),(12001,' and that others might devour his substance?\"'),(12002,'  Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him: '),(12003,' “Nay verily, not for him be thy heart overmuch troubled.'),(12004,' It was I that guided him, that he might win good report by going thither, '),(12005,' and he has no toil, but sits in peace in the palace of the son of Atreus, and good cheer past telling is before him.'),(12006,'  Truly young men in a black ship lie in wait for him, eager to slay him before he comes to his native land, '),(12007,' but methinks this shall not be. Ere that shall the earth cover many a one of the wooers that devour thy substance.\"'),(12008,'So saying, Athena touched him with her wand.'),(12009,'  She withered the fair flesh on his supple limbs, and destroyed the flaxen hair from off his head, and about all his limbs she put the skin of an aged old man. And she dimmed his two eyes that were before so beautiful,'),(12010,'  and clothed him in other raiment,  a vile ragged cloak and a tunic, tattered garments and foul, begrimed with filthy smoke.'),(12011,'And about him she cast the great skin of a swift hind, stripped of the hair,'),(12012,'  and she gave him a staff, and a miserable wallet, full of holes, '),(12013,'slung by a twisted cord.'),(12014,'\nSo when the two had thus taken counsel together, they parted; '),(12015,'and thereupon the goddess went to goodly Lacedaemon to fetch the son of Odysseus.'),(12016,' But Odysseus went forth from the harbor by the rough path up over the woodland and through the heights to the place where Athena had shewed him that he should find the goodly swineherd, who cared for his substance above all the slaves that goodly Odysseus had gotten.'),(12017,'\n  He found him sitting in the fore-hall of his house, where his court was built high in a place of wide outlook, a great and goodly court with an open space around it.'),(12018,' This the swineherd had himself built for the swine of his master, that was gone, without the knowledge of his mistress and the old man Laertes. With huge stones had he built it, and set on it a coping of thorn.'),(12019,'  Without he had driven stakes the whole length, this way and that, huge stakes, set close together, which he had made by splitting an oak to the black core;'),(12020,' and within the court he had made twelve sties close by one another, as beds for the swine, '),(12021,' and in each one  were penned fifty wallowing swine, females for breeding; '),(12022,'but the boars slept without. These were far fewer in numbers,'),(12023,'for on them the godlike wooers feasted, and lessened them, for the swineherd ever sent in the best of all the fatted hogs,'),(12024,'for on them the godlike wooers feasted, and lessened them, for the swineherd ever sent in the best of all the fatted hogs,'),(12025,' By these ever slept four dogs, savage as wild beasts, which the swineherd had reared, a leader of men.'),(12026,' But he himself was fitting boots about his feet, cutting an ox-hide of good color, '),(12027,'while the others  had gone, three of them, one here one there, with the droves of swine;'),(12028,'and the fourth he had sent to the city to drive perforce a boar to the insolent wooers, that they might slay it and satisfy their souls with meat.'),(12029,'\nSuddenly then the baying hounds caught sight of Odysseus, '),(12030,' and rushed upon him with loud barking, '),(12031,' but Odysseus sat down in his cunning, and the staff fell from his hand.'),(12032,' Then even in his own farmstead would he have suffered cruel hurt,'),(12033,'but the swineherd with swift steps followed after them, and hastened through the gateway, and the hide fell from his hand.'),(12034,'  He called aloud to the dogs, and drove them this way and that with a shower of stones, '),(12035,' and spoke to his master, and said:'),(12036,'\n“Old man, verily the dogs were like to have torn thee to pieces all of a sudden, and on me thou wouldest have shed reproach.'),(12037,' Aye, and the gods have given me other griefs and sorrow.'),(12038,'  It is for a godlike master that I mourn and grieve, as I abide here, and rear fat swine for other men to eat,'),(12039,'while he haply in want of food wanders over the land and city of men of strange speech, if indeed he still lives and sees the light of the sun.'),(12040,'  But come with me, let us go to the hut, old man, that when thou hast satisfied thy heart with food and wine, thou too mayest tell whence thou art, and all the woes thou hast endured.” '),(12041,' \nSo saying, the goodly swineherd led him to the hut, and brought him in, and made him sit, strowing beneath thick brushwood,  and thereon spreading the skin of a shaggy wild goat, large and hairy, on which he was himself wont to sleep.'),(12042,' And Odysseus was glad that he gave him such welcome, and spoke, and addressed him:'),(12043,'\n“Stranger, may Zeus and the other immortal gods grant thee what most thou desirest, since thou with a ready heart hast given me welcome.\"'),(12044,'  To him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say:'),(12045,'“Nay, stranger, it were not right for me, even though one meaner than thou were to come, to slight a stranger:'),(12046,' for from Zeus are all strangers and beggars,'),(12047,'  and a gift, though small, is welcome from such as we; '),(12048,'since this is the lot of slaves,  ever in fear when over them as lords their masters hold sway—young masters such as ours.'),(12049,'For verily the gods have stayed the return of him who would have loved me with all kindness, and would have given me possessions of my own, a house and a bit of land, and a wife, sought of many wooers, even such things as a kindly master gives to his thrall  who has toiled much for him, and whose labour the god makes to prosper, even as this work of mine prospers, to which I give heed.'),(12050,' Therefore would my master have richly rewarded me, if he had grown old here at home:'),(12051,' Therefore would my master have richly rewarded me, if he had grown old here at home:'),(12052,'  For he too went forth to win recompense for Agamemnon to Ilios, famed for its horses, that he might fight with the Trojans.” '),(12053,' \nSo saying, he quickly bound up his tunic with his belt, and went to the sties, where the tribes of swine were penned.'),(12054,' Choosing two from thence, he brought them in and slew them both,  and singed, and cut them up, and spitted them. '),(12055,'Then, when he had roasted all, he brought and set it before Odysseus, hot upon the spits, '),(12056,' and sprinkled over it white barley meal.'),(12057,' Then in a bowl of ivy wood he mixed honey-sweet wine, and himself sat down over against Odysseus, and bade him to his food, and said:'),(12058,'\n  “Eat now, stranger, such food as slaves have to offer, meat of young pigs;'),(12059,'the fatted hogs the wooers eat, who reck not in their hearts of the wrath of the gods, nor have any pity.'),(12060,' Verily the blessed gods love not reckless deeds, but they honor justice and the righteous deeds of men.'),(12061,'  Even cruel foemen that set foot on the land of others, and Zeus gives them booty, and they fill their ships and depart for home—even on the hearts of these falls great fear of the wrath of the gods.'),(12062,' But these men here, look you, know somewhat, and have heard some voice of a god  regarding my master\'s pitiful death, seeing that they will not woo righteously, nor go back to their own, but at their ease they waste our substance in insolent wise, and there is no sparing.'),(12063,' For every day and night that comes from Zeus they sacrifice not one victim nor two alone, '),(12064,' and they draw forth wine, and waste it in insolent wise.'),(12065,' Verily his substance was great past telling,'),(12066,' so much has no lord either on the dark mainland or in Ithaca itself; '),(12067,' nay, not twenty men together have wealth so great.'),(12068,'Lo, I will tell thee the tale thereof; '),(12069,' twelve herds of kine has he on the mainland; '),(12070,' as many flocks of sheep; as many droves of swine; as many packed herds of goats do herdsmen, both foreigners and of his own people, pasture.'),(12071,' And here too graze roving herds of goats on the borders of the island, eleven in all, and over them trusty men keep watch.'),(12072,'  And each man of these ever drives up day by day one of his flock for the wooers, even that one of the fatted goats which seems to him the best.'),(12073,' But as for me, I guard and keep these swine, and choose out with care and send them the best of the boars.” '),(12074,' \nSo he spoke, but Odysseus eagerly ate flesh and drank wine,  greedily, in silence, and was sowing the seeds of evil for the wooers. '),(12075,' But when he had dined, and satisfied his soul with food, then the swineherd filled the bowl from which he was himself wont to drink, and gave it him brim full of wine, '),(12076,' and he took it, and was glad at heart; and he spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(12077,'\n  “Friend, who was it who bought thee with his wealth, a man so very rich and mighty, as thou tellest?'),(12078,' Thou saidest that he died to win recompense for Agamemnon;'),(12079,' tell me, if haply I may know him, being such an one.'),(12080,' For Zeus, I ween, and the other immortal gods know  whether I have seen him, and could bring tidings;'),(12081,' for I have wandered far.\"'),(12082,'Then the swineherd, a leader of men, answered him:'),(12083,' “Old man, no wanderer that came and brought tidings of him could persuade his wife and his dear son; nay, at random, when they have need of entertainment, do vagabonds  lie, and are not minded to speak the truth. '),(12084,' Whosoever in his wanderings comes to the land of Ithaca, goes to my mistress and tells a deceitful tale.'),(12085,' And she, receiving him kindly, gives him entertainment, and questions him of all things, and the tears fall from her eyelids, while she weeps,  as is the way of a woman, when her husband dies afar. '),(12086,' And readily wouldest thou too, old man, fashion a story, '),(12087,' if one would give thee a cloak and a tunic for raiment.'),(12088,'But as for him, ere now dogs and swift birds are like to have torn the flesh from his bones, and his spirit has left him; '),(12089,' or in the sea fishes have eaten him, and his bones lie there on the shore, wrapped in deep sand.'),(12090,' Thus has he perished yonder, and to his friends grief is appointed for days to come, to all, but most of all to me. '),(12091,' For never again shall I find a master so kind, how far soever I go,  not though I come again to the house of my father and mother, where at the first I was born, and they reared me themselves.'),(12092,' Yet it is not for them that I henceforth mourn so much, eager though I am to behold them with my eyes and to be in my native land; '),(12093,' nay, it is longing for Odysseus, who is gone, that seizes me.'),(12094,'  His name, stranger, absent though he is, I speak with awe, '),(12095,'for greatly did he love me and care for me at heart; '),(12096,' but I call him my lord beloved, for all he is not here.” '),(12097,' \nThen the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus answered him:'),(12098,' “Friend, since thou dost utterly make denial, and declarest  that he will never come again, and thy heart is ever unbelieving, '),(12099,'therefore will I tell thee, not at random but with an oath, that Odysseus shall return.'),(12100,' And let me have a reward for bearing good tidings, as soon as he shall come, and reach his home; '),(12101,'clothe me in a cloak and tunic, goodly raiment.'),(12102,'  But ere that, how sore soever my need, I will accept naught;'),(12103,' for hateful in my eyes as the gates of Hades is that man, who, yielding to stress of poverty, tells a deceitful tale.'),(12104,' Now be my witness Zeus, above all gods, and this hospitable board, and the hearth of noble Odysseus to which I am come,'),(12105,' that verily all these things shall be brought to pass even as I tell thee.'),(12106,' In the course of this self-same day Odysseus shall come hither,'),(12107,' as the old moon wanes, and the new appears. He shall return, and take vengeance on all those who here dishonor his wife and his glorious son.\"'),(12108,'  To him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say: '),(12109,'“Old man, neither shall I, meseems, pay thee this reward for bearing good tidings, nor shall Odysseus ever come to his home.'),(12110,' Nay, drink in peace, and let us turn our thoughts to other things, and do not thou recall this to my mind; '),(12111,'for verily the heart in my breast  is grieved whenever any one makes mention of my good master. '),(12112,'But as for thy oath, we will let it be; yet I would that Odysseus might come, even as I desire, I, and Penelope, and the old man Laertes, and godlike Telemachus.'),(12113,' But now it is for his son that I grieve unceasingly,  even for Telemachus, whom Odysseus begot.'),(12114,' When the gods had made him grow like a sapling, and I thought that he would be among men no whit worse than his dear father, glorious in form and comeliness, then some one of the immortals marred the wise spirit within him, or haply some man,'),(12115,' and he went  to sacred Pylos after tidings of his father. '),(12116,' For him now the lordly wooers lie in wait on his homeward way, that the race of godlike Arceisius may perish out of Ithaca, and leave no name.'),(12117,' But verily we will let him be; he may be taken, or he may escape, and the son of Cronos stretch forth his hand to guard him.'),(12118,'  But come, do thou, old man, tell me of thine own sorrows, and declare me this truly, that I may know full well.'),(12119,'  Where is thy city, and where thy parents?'),(12120,'  Where is thy city, and where thy parents?'),(12121,' On what manner of ship didst thou come,'),(12122,' and how did sailors bring thee to Ithaca?'),(12123,'Who did they declare themselves to be?'),(12124,'  For nowise, methinks, didst thou come hither on foot.”'),(12125,' \nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said: “Then verily I will frankly tell thee all.'),(12126,' Would that now we two might have food and sweet wine for the while,  to feast on in quiet here in thy hut, and that others might go about their work; '),(12127,'easily then might I tell on for a full year, and yet in no wise finish the tale of the woes of my spirit—even all the toils that I have endured by the will of the gods.'),(12128,'\n“From broad Crete I declare that I am come by lineage,  the son of a wealthy man.'),(12129,' And many other sons too were born and bred in his halls, true sons of a lawful wife; '),(12130,' but the mother that bore me was bought, a concubine. Yet Castor, son of Hylax, of whom I declare that I am sprung, honored me even as his true-born sons.  He was at that time honored as a god among the Cretans in the land for his good estate, and his wealth, and his glorious sons.'),(12131,' But the fates of death bore him away to the house of Hades, '),(12132,'and his proud sons divided among them his substance, and cast lots therefor. To me they gave a very small portion, and allotted a dwelling.'),(12133,'  But I took unto me a wife from a house that had wide possessions, winning her by my valor; for I was no weakling, nor a coward in fight.'),(12134,' Now all that strength is gone; yet even so, in seeing the stubble, methinks  thou mayest judge what the grain was; '),(12135,'for verily troubles in full measure encompass me. '),(12136,'But then Ares and Athena gave me courage, and strength that breaks the ranks of men; '),(12137,' and whenever I picked the best warriors for an ambush, sowing the seeds of evil for the foe, never did my proud spirit forbode death,  but ever far the first did I leap forth, and slay with my spear whosoever of the foe gave way in flight before me.'),(12138,' Such a man was I in war, '),(12139,'but labour in the field was never to my liking, nor the care of a household, which rears goodly children, but oared ships were ever dear to me,  and wars, and polished spears, and arrows,—grievous things, whereat others are wont to shudder.'),(12140,'  But those things, I ween, were dear to me, which a god put in my heart; '),(12141,' for different men take joy in different works.'),(12142,'For before the sons of the Achaeans set foot on the land of Troy,  I had nine times led warriors and swift-faring ships against foreign folk, and great spoil had ever fallen to my hands. '),(12143,' Of this I would choose what pleased my mind, and much I afterwards obtained by lot. '),(12144,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 14.233-14.234'),(12145,' \n  “But when Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, devised that hateful journey which loosened the knees of many a warrior, then they bade me and glorious Idomeneus to lead the ships to Ilios,'),(12146,' nor was there any way to refuse, for the voice of the people pressed hard upon us.'),(12147,'  There for nine years we sons of the Achaeans warred, and in the tenth we sacked the city of Priam, and set out for home in our ships, and a god scattered the Achaeans.'),(12148,' But for me, wretched man that I was, Zeus, the counsellor, devised evil.'),(12149,' For a month only I remained, taking joy in my children,  my wedded wife, and my wealth; '),(12150,'and then to Egypt did my spirit bid me voyage with my godlike comrades, when I had fitted out my ships with care. '),(12151,' Nine ships I fitted out, and the host gathered speedily.'),(12152,'Then for six days my trusty comrades  feasted, '),(12153,' and I gave them many victims, that they might sacrifice to the gods, and prepare a feast for themselves; '),(12154,'and on the seventh we embarked and set sail from broad Crete, with the North Wind blowing fresh and fair, and ran on easily as if down stream. '),(12155,'No  harm came to any of my ships, but free from scathe and from disease we sat, and the wind and the helmsman guided the ships.'),(12156,' “On the fifth day we came to fair-flowing Aegyptus, and in the river Aegyptus I moored my curved ships.'),(12157,' Then verily I bade my trusty comrades  to remain there by the ships, and to guard the ships, and I sent out scouts to go to places of outlook. '),(12158,' But my comrades, yielding to wantonness, and led on by their own might, straightway set about wasting the fair fields of the men of Egypt; and they carried off the women and little children,  and slew the men; '),(12159,'and the cry came quickly to the city. '),(12160,'Then, hearing the shouting, the people came forth at break of day, '),(12161,'and the whole plain was filled with footmen, and chariots and the flashing of bronze.'),(12162,' But Zeus who hurls the thunderbolt cast an evil panic upon my comrades, and none had the courage  to hold his ground and face the foe;'),(12163,' for evil surrounded us on every side.'),(12164,' So then they slew many of us with the sharp bronze, and others they led up to their city alive, to work for them perforce.'),(12165,' But in my heart Zeus himself put this thought—I would that I had rather died and met my fate  there in Egypt, '),(12166,'for still was sorrow to give me welcome. Straightway I put off from my head my well-wrought helmet, and the shield from off my shoulders, and let the spear fall from my hand, '),(12167,' and went toward the chariot horses of the king. I clasped, and kissed his knees, '),(12168,'and he delivered me, and took pity on me,  and, setting me in his chariot, took me weeping to his home. '),(12169,' Verily full many rushed upon me with their ashen spears, eager to slay me, for they were exceeding angry. But he warded them off, and had regard for the wrath of Zeus, the stranger\'s god, who above all others hath indignation at evil deeds. '),(12170,' \n  “There then I stayed seven years, and much wealth did I gather among the Egyptians, '),(12171,' for all men gave me gifts.'),(12172,' But when the eighth circling year was come, then there came a man of Phoenicia, well versed in guile, a greedy knave, who had already wrought much evil among men.'),(12173,'  He prevailed upon me by his cunning, and took me with him, until we reached Phoenicia, where lay his house and his possessions.'),(12174,' There I remained with him for a full year. '),(12175,'But when at length the months and the days were being brought to fulfillment, as the year rolled round and the seasons came on,  he set me on a seafaring ship bound for Libya, having given lying counsel to the end that I should convey a cargo with him, but in truth that, when there, he might sell me and get a vast price.'),(12176,' So I went with him on board the ship, suspecting his guile, yet perforce.'),(12177,' And she ran before the North Wind, blowing fresh and fair,  on a mid-sea course to the windward of Crete, '),(12178,' and Zeus devised destruction for the men.'),(12179,'  But when we had left Crete, and no other land appeared, but only sky and sea,  then verily the son of Cronos set a black cloud above the hollow ship, and the sea grew dark beneath it.'),(12180,'Therewith Zeus thundered, and hurled his bolt upon the ship, '),(12181,'and she quivered from stem to stern, smitten by the bolt of Zeus, and was filled with sulphurous smoke, '),(12182,' and all the crew fell from out the ship.'),(12183,'Like sea-crows they were borne on the waves about the black ship,'),(12184,'  and the god took from them their returning.'),(12185,'  But as for me, Zeus himself when my heart was compassed with woe, put into my hands the tossing mast of the dark-prowed ship, that I might again escape destruction.'),(12186,' Around this I clung, and was borne by the direful winds. '),(12187,'For nine days I was borne, but on the tenth black night  the great rolling wave brought me to the land of the Thesprotians.'),(12188,'There the king of the Thesprotians, lord Pheidon, took me in, and asked no ransom,'),(12189,'  for his dear son came upon me, overcome as I was with cold and weariness, and raised me by the hand, and led me until he came to his father\'s palace; '),(12190,' and he clothed me in a cloak and tunic, as raiment.'),(12191,' \n“There I learned of Odysseus,'),(12192,' for the king said that he had entertained him, and given him welcome on his way to his native land. And he showed me all the treasure that Odysseus had gathered, bronze, and gold, and iron, wrought with toil; '),(12193,' verily unto the tenth generation would it feed his children after him, '),(12194,'so great was the wealth that lay stored for him in the halls of the king.'),(12195,' But Odysseus, he said, had gone to Dodona, to hear the will of Zeus from the high-crested oak of the god, even how he might return to the rich land of Ithaca  after so long an absence, whether openly or in secret.'),(12196,' And moreover he swore in my own presence, as he poured libations in his house, that the ship was launched, and the men ready, who were to convey him to his dear native land.'),(12197,' But me he sent forth first,'),(12198,' for a ship  of the Thesprotians chanced to be setting out for Dulichium, rich in wheat. '),(12199,'Thither he bade them to convey me with kindly care, to king Acastus.'),(12200,' But an evil counsel regarding me found favour in their hearts, that I might even yet be brought into utter misery.'),(12201,' When the sea-faring ship had sailed far from the land,  they presently sought to bring about for me the day of slavery.'),(12202,' They stripped me of my garments, my cloak and tunic, and clothed me in other raiment, a vile ragged cloak and tunic, even the tattered garments which thou seest before thine eyes;'),(12203,' and at evening they reached the tilled fields of clear-seen Ithaca.'),(12204,'  Then with a twisted rope they bound me fast in the benched ship, and themselves went ashore, and made haste to take their supper by the shore of the sea.'),(12205,' But as for me, the gods themselves undid my bonds full easily, '),(12206,'and, wrapping the tattered cloak about my head,  I slid down the smooth lading-plank, and brought my breast to the sea, and then struck out with both hands, and swam, and very soon was out of the water, and away from them.'),(12207,' Then I went up to a place where there was a thicket of leafy wood, and lay there crouching.'),(12208,'  And they went hither and thither with loud cries;'),(12209,' but as there seemed to be no profit in going further in their search, they went back again on board their hollow ship.'),(12210,' And the gods themselves hid me easily, and led me, and brought me to the farmstead of a wise man; '),(12211,'for still haply it is my lot to live.” '),(12212,' \n  To him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say: '),(12213,' “Ah, wretched stranger, verily thou hast stirred my heart deeply in telling all the tale of thy sufferings and thy wanderings.'),(12214,' But in this, methinks, thou hast not spoken aright, nor shalt thou persuade me with thy tale about Odysseus.'),(12215,' Why shouldst thou, who art in such plight  lie to no purpose? '),(12216,'Nay, of myself I know well regarding the return of my master, that he was utterly hated of all the gods, in that they did not slay him among the Trojans, or in the arms of his friends, when he had wound up the skein of war. '),(12217,'  Then would the whole host of the Achaeans have made him a tomb,  and for his son too he would have won great glory in days to come. But as it is the spirits of the storm have swept him away, and left no tidings.'),(12218,'  I, for my part, dwell aloof with the swine,'),(12219,'  nor do I go to the city, unless haply wise Penelope bids me thither, when tidings come to her from anywhere.'),(12220,'  Then men sit around him that comes, and question him closely, both those that grieve for their lord, that has long been gone, and those who rejoice, as they devour his substance without atonement. '),(12221,' But I care not to ask or enquire, since the time when an Aetolian beguiled me with his story,  one that had killed a man, and after wandering over the wide earth came to my house,'),(12222,' and I gave him kindly welcome.'),(12223,' He said that he had seen Odysseus among the Cretans at the house of Idomeneus, mending his ships which storms had shattered.'),(12224,' And he said that he would come either by summer or by harvest-time,  bringing much treasure along with his godlike comrades. '),(12225,'Thou too, old man of many sorrows, since a god has brought thee to me, seek not to win my favour by lies, nor in any wise to cajole me.'),(12226,' It is not for this that I shall shew thee respect or kindness, but from fear of Zeus, the stranger\'s god, and from pity for thyself.”'),(12227,'\n  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said: “Verily thou hast in thy bosom a heart that is slow to believe, seeing that in such wise, even with an oath, I won thee not, neither persuade thee.'),(12228,' But come now, let us make a covenant, '),(12229,'and the gods who hold Olympus shall be witnesses for us both in time to come.'),(12230,'  If thy master returns to this house, clothe me in a cloak and tunic, as raiment, and send me on my way to Dulichium, where I desire to be.'),(12231,' But if thy master does not come as I say, set the slaves upon me, and fling me down from a great cliff,  that another beggar may beware of deceiving.”'),(12232,' \nAnd the goodly swineherd answered him, and said:'),(12233,' “Aye, stranger, so should I indeed win fair fame and prosperity among men both now and hereafter, if I, who brought thee to my hut and gave thee entertainment,  should then slay thee, and take away thy dear life. '),(12234,' With a ready heart thereafter should I pray to Zeus, son of Cronos.'),(12235,' But it is now time for supper, '),(12236,'and may my comrades soon be here, that we may make ready a savoury supper in the hut.\"'),(12237,'Thus they spoke to one another,  and the swine and the swineherds drew near. '),(12238,' The sows they shut up to sleep in their wonted sties, and a wondrous noise arose from them, as they were penned. Then the goodly swineherd called to his comrades saying: '),(12239,'\n“Bring forth the best of the boars, that I may slaughter him for the stranger  who comes from afar,'),(12240,' and we too shall have some profit therefrom, who have long borne toil and suffering for the sake of the white-tusked swine,'),(12241,' while others devour our labour without atonement.”'),(12242,'So saying, he split wood with the pitiless bronze, and the others brought in a fatted boar of five years old, '),(12243,' and set him by the hearth.'),(12244,'Nor did the swineherd forget the immortals,'),(12245,'  for he had an understanding heart, '),(12246,' but as a first offering he cast into the fire bristles from the head of the white-tusked boar, and made prayer to all the gods that wise Odysseus might return to his own house.'),(12247,'  Then he raised himself up, and smote the boar with a billet of oak, which he had left when splitting the wood,'),(12248,' And the others cut the boar\'s throat, '),(12249,' And the others cut the boar\'s throat, '),(12250,'and signed him, '),(12251,'and quickly cut him up, and the swineherd took as first offerings bits of raw flesh from all the limbs, and laid them in the rich fat. These he cast into the fire, when he had sprinkled them with barley meal,  but the rest they cut up and spitted, and roasted it carefully, and drew it all off the spits, and cast it in a heap on platters.'),(12252,' Then the swineherd stood up to carve,'),(12253,' for well did his heart know what was fair,'),(12254,'and he cut up the mess and divided it into seven portions.'),(12255,'  One with a prayer he set aside for the nymphs and for Hermes, son of Maia, and the rest he distributed to each.'),(12256,' And Odysseus he honored with the long chine of the white-tusked boar, and made glad the heart of his master; '),(12257,'and Odysseus of many wiles spoke to him, and said:'),(12258,'\n  “Eumaeus, mayest thou be as dear to father Zeus as thou art to me, since thou honourest me with a good portion, albeit I am in such plight.\"'),(12259,'To him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say:'),(12260,' “Eat, unhappy stranger, and have joy of such fare as is here.'),(12261,' It is the god that will give one thing and withhold another,  even as seems good to his heart; '),(12262,'for he can do all things.”'),(12263,' \nHe spoke, and sacrificed the firstling pieces to the gods that are for ever, and, when he had made libations of the flaming wine, he placed the cup in the hands of Odysseus, the sacker of cities, '),(12264,' and took his seat by his own portion.'),(12265,'And bread was served to them by Mesaulius, whom the swineherd  had gotten by himself alone, while his master was gone, without the knowledge of his mistress or the old Laertes, '),(12266,'buying him of the Taphians with his own goods.'),(12267,' So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them. '),(12268,'But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink,  Mesaulius took away the food, and they were fain to go to their rest, sated with bread and meat.'),(12269,'\nNow the night came on, foul and without a moon, and Zeus rained the whole night through, and the West Wind, ever the rainy wind, blew strong. '),(12270,'Then Odysseus spoke among them, making trial of the swineherd,  to see whether he would strip off his own cloak and give it him, or bid some other of his comrades to do so, since he cared for him so greatly:'),(12271,'\n“Hear me now, Eumaeus and all the rest of you, his men, with a wish in my heart will I tell a tale; '),(12272,'for the wine bids me, befooling wine, which sets one, even though he be right wise, to singing  and laughing softly, and makes him stand up and dance, aye, and brings forth a word which were better unspoken.'),(12273,' Still, since I have once spoken out, I will hide nothing.'),(12274,' Would that I were young and my strength firm as when we made ready our ambush, and led it beneath the walls of Troy.'),(12275,'  The leaders were Odysseus and Menelaus, son of Atreus, and with them I was third in command; '),(12276,'for so had they ordered it themselves.'),(12277,' Now when we had come to the city and the steep wall, round about the town in the thick brushwood among the needs and swamp-land  we lay, crouching beneath our arms, '),(12278,'and night came on, foul, when the North Wind had fallen, and frosty, '),(12279,'and snow came down on us from above, covering us like rime, bitter cold, and ice formed upon our shields.'),(12280,' Now all the rest had cloaks and tunics, and slept in peace, with their shields covering their shoulders, '),(12281,' but I, when I set out, had left my cloak behind with my comrades in my folly, for I did not think that even so I should be cold, and had come with my shield alone and my bright kilt.'),(12282,' But when it was the third watch of the night, and the stars had turned their course, then I spoke to Odysseus, who was near me,  nudging him with my elbow; '),(12283,'and he straightway gave ear:'),(12284,'\n“Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, lo now, no longer shall I be among the living. Nay, the cold is killing me, '),(12285,'for I have no cloak.'),(12286,'Some god beguiled me to wear my tunic only,'),(12287,'  and now there is no more escape.’'),(12288,'  “So I spoke, and he then devised this plan in his heart, such a man was he both to plan and to fight; '),(12289,'and speaking in a low voice he said to me:'),(12290,' ‘Be silent now, lest another of the Achaeans hear thee.’ '),(12291,' \n“With this he raised his head upon his elbow, and spoke, saying: '),(12292,' a dream from the gods came to me in my sleep.'),(12293,' a dream from the gods came to me in my sleep.'),(12294,' \nLo, we have come very far from the ships,'),(12295,'  and I would that there were one to bear word to Agamemnon, son of Atreus, shepherd of the host, in the hope that he might bid more men to come from the ships.’'),(12296,'\n“So he spoke, and Thoas, son of Andraemon, sprang up  quickly, and from him flung his purple cloak, and set out to run to the ships.'),(12297,' Then in his garment I gladly lay, and golden-throned Dawn appeared.'),(12298,' Would that I were young as then, and my strength as firm;'),(12299,'then would one of the swineherds in the farmstead give me a cloak  both from kindness and from respect for a brave warrior. '),(12300,' But as it is they scorn me, since I have foul raiment about me.\"'),(12301,'To him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say:'),(12302,' “Old man, the tale thou hast told is a good one, nor hast thou thus far spoken aught amiss or unprofitably.'),(12303,'  Wherefore thou shalt lack neither clothing nor aught else that a sore-tried suppliant should receive, when he meets one—for this night at least; '),(12304,'but in the morning thou shalt shake about thee those rags of thine.'),(12305,' For not many cloaks are here or changes of tunics to put on, but each man has one alone.'),(12306,'  But when the dear son of Odysseus comes, he will himself give thee a cloak and a tunic as raiment, and will send thee whithersoever thy heart and spirit bid thee go.\"'),(12307,'So saying, he sprang up and placed a bed for Odysseus near the fire, and cast upon it skins of sheep and goats.'),(12308,'  There Odysseus lay down,'),(12309,' and the swineherd threw over him a great thick cloak, which he kept at hand for a change of clothing whenever a terrible storm should arise.'),(12310,'\nSo there Odysseus slept, and beside him slept the young men. '),(12311,' But the swineherd  liked not a bed in that place, that he should lay him down away from the boars; so he made ready to go outside.'),(12312,' And Odysseus was glad that he took such care of his master\'s substance while he was afar. '),(12313,'First Eumaeus flung his sharp sword over his strong shoulders, and then put about him a cloak, very thick, to keep off the wind;  and he picked up the fleece of a large, well-fatted goat, took a sharp javelin to ward off dogs and men, '),(12314,'and went forth to lie down to sleep where the white-tusked boars slept beneath a hollow rock, in a place sheltered from the North Wind.'),(12315,' But Pallas Athena went to spacious Lacedaemon to remind the glorious son of great-hearted Odysseus of his return, and to hasten his coming. '),(12316,'She found Telemachus and the noble son of Nestor  lying in the fore-hall of the palace of glorious Menelaus. Now Nestor\'s son was overcome with soft sleep,'),(12317,' but sweet sleep did not hold Telemachus, but all through the immortal night anxious thoughts for his father kept him wakeful.'),(12318,' And flashing-eyed Athena stood near him, and said:'),(12319,'\n  “Telemachus, thou dost not well to wander longer far from thy home, leaving behind thee thy wealth and men in thy house so insolent,'),(12320,' lest they divide and devour all thy possessions, and thou shalt have gone on a fruitless journey.'),(12321,' Nay, rouse with all speed Menelaus, good at the war-cry,  to send thee on thy way, that thou mayest find thy noble mother still in her home. '),(12322,'For now her father and her brothers bid her wed Eurymachus, '),(12323,' for he surpasses all the wooers in his presents, and has increased his gifts of wooing.'),(12324,' Beware lest she carry forth from thy halls some treasure against thy will.'),(12325,' For thou knowest what sort of a spirit there is in a woman\'s breast; '),(12326,' she is fain to increase the house of the man who weds her, but of her former children and of the lord of her youth she takes no thought, when once he is dead, and asks no longer concerning them. '),(12327,'Nay, go, and thyself put all thy possessions in the charge of whatsoever one  of the handmaids seems to thee the best, until the gods shall show thee a noble bride.'),(12328,' And another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart.'),(12329,' The best men of the wooers lie in wait for thee of set purpose in the strait between Ithaca and rugged Samos, '),(12330,'  eager to slay thee before thou comest to thy native land.'),(12331,' But methinks this shall not be; '),(12332,' ere that shall the earth cover many a one of the wooers that devour thy substance.'),(12333,' But do thou keep thy well-built ship far from the islands, and sail by night as well as by day, '),(12334,'and that  one of the immortals, who keeps and guards thee, will send a fair breeze in thy wake.'),(12335,'But when thou hast reached the nearest shore of Ithaca, send thy ship and all thy comrades on to the city, but thyself go first of all to the swineherd who keeps thy swine, and withal has a kindly heart toward thee.'),(12336,' There do thou spend the night,'),(12337,'  and bid him to go to the city to bear word to wise Penelope that she has thee safe, and thou art come from Pylos.\"'),(12338,'So saying, she departed to high Olympus. But Telemachus woke the son of Nestor out of sweet sleep,  rousing him with a touch of his heel, and spoke to him, saying:'),(12339,'“Awake, Peisistratus, son of Nestor; bring up thy fiery-hoofed horses, and yoke them beneath the car, that we may speed on our way.” '),(12340,' \nThen Peisistratus, son of Nestor, answered, and said:'),(12341,' “Telemachus, in no wise may we  drive through the dark night, how eager soever for our journey; '),(12342,'and soon it will be dawn.'),(12343,' Wait then, until the warrior son of Atreus, Menelaus, famed for his spear, shall bring gifts and set them on the car, and shall send us on our way with kindly words of farewell.'),(12344,' For a guest remembers all his days  the host who shews him kindness.”'),(12345,'So he spoke, and presently came golden-throned Dawn.'),(12346,' Up to them then came Menelaus, good at the war-cry, rising from his couch from beside fair-tressed Helen. '),(12347,'  And when the prince, the dear son of Odysseus, saw him,  he made haste to put about him his bright tunic, and to fling over his mighty shoulders a great cloak, and went forth. Then Telemachus, the dear son of divine Odysseus, came up to Menelaus, and addressed him, saying:'),(12348,'\n“Menelaus, son of Atreus, fostered of Zeus, leader of hosts,  send me back now at length to my dear native land, '),(12349,'for now my heart is eager to return home.”'),(12350,' Then Menelaus, good at the war-cry, answered him: '),(12351,' “Telemachus, I verily shall not hold thee here a long time, when thou art eager to return.'),(12352,'Nay, I should blame another,   who, as host, loves overmuch or hates overmuch; '),(12353,' better is due measure in all things. '),(12354,' \'Tis equal wrong if a man speed on a guest who is loath to go, and if he keep back one that is eager to be gone.'),(12355,'One should make welcome the present guest, and send forth him that would go.'),(12356,'  But stay, till I bring fair gifts and put them on thy car, and thine own eyes behold them, and till I bid the women make ready a meal in the halls of the abundant store that is within.'),(12357,' It is a double boon—honor and glory it brings, and profit withal—that the traveller should dine before he goes forth over the wide and boundless earth.'),(12358,'  And if thou art fain to journey through Hellas and mid-Argos, be it so, to the end that I may myself go with thee, and I will yoke for thee horses, and lead thee to the cities of men.'),(12359,' Nor will any one send us away empty-handed, but will give us some one thing at least to bear with us, a fair brazen tripod or cauldron,  or a pair of mules, or a golden cup.”'),(12360,'Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(12361,' “Menelaus, son of Atreus, fostered of Zeus, leader of hosts, rather would I go at once to my home, '),(12362,'for when I departed I left behind me no one to watch over my possessions.'),(12363,'  I would not that in seeking for my god-like father I myself should perish, or some goodly treasure be lost from my halls.” '),(12364,' \nNow when Menelaus, good in battle, heard this, he straightway bade his wife and her handmaids make ready a meal in the halls of the abundant store that was within.'),(12365,'  Up to him then came Eteoneus, son of Boethous, just risen from his bed, for he dwelt not far from him.'),(12366,' Him Menelaus, good at the war-cry, bade kindle a fire and roast of the flesh;'),(12367,' and he heard, and obeyed.'),(12368,' And Menelaus himself went down to his vaulted treasure-chamber,  not alone, for with him went Helen and Megapenthes. '),(12369,'But when they came to the place where his treasures were stored, the son of Atreus took a two-handled cup, and bade his son Megapenthes bear a mixing bowl of silver.'),(12370,' And Helen came up to the chests  in which were her richly-broidered robes, that she herself had wrought.'),(12371,'One of these Helen, the beautiful lady, lifted out and bore away, the one that was fairest in its broideries, and the amplest. It shone like a star, '),(12372,' and lay beneath all the rest.'),(12373,'Then they went forth through the house until they came to  Telemachus; '),(12374,' and fair-haired Menelaus spoke to him, and said:'),(12375,'\n“Telemachus, may Zeus, the loud-thundering lord of Here, verily bring to pass for thee thy return, even as thy heart desires.'),(12376,' And of all the gifts that lie stored as treasures in my house, I will give thee that one which is fairest and costliest.'),(12377,'  I will give thee a well-wrought mixing-bowl.'),(12378,' It is all of silver, and with gold are the rims thereof gilded, the work of Hephaestus;'),(12379,' and the warrior Phaedimus, king of the Sidonians, gave it me, when his house sheltered me as I came thither; '),(12380,'and now I am minded to give it to thee.”'),(12381,'  So saying, the warrior, son of Atreus, placed the two-handled cup in his hands.'),(12382,' And the strong Megapenthes brought the bright mixing-bowl of silver and set it before him, '),(12383,'and fair-cheeked Helen came up with the robe in her hands, and spoke, and addressed him:'),(12384,'\n  “Lo, I too give thee this gift, dear child, a remembrance of the hands of Helen, against the day of thy longed-for marriage, for thy bride to wear it.'),(12385,' But until then let it lie in thy halls in the keeping of thy dear mother.'),(12386,' And for thyself I wish that with joy thou mayest reach thy well-built house and thy native land.” '),(12387,' \n  So saying, she placed it in his hands, and he took it gladly. '),(12388,'And the prince Peisistratus took the gifts, and laid them in the box of the chariot, and gazed at them all wondering in his heart.'),(12389,' Then fair-haired Menelaus led them to the house,'),(12390,'and the two sat down on chairs and high seats.'),(12391,'  And a handmaid brought water for the hands in a fair pitcher of gold, and poured it over a silver basin for them to wash, '),(12392,'and beside them drew up a polished table.'),(12393,' And the grave housewife brought and set before them bread, '),(12394,'and therewith meats in abundance, granting freely of her store. '),(12395,'  And hard by the son of Boethous carved the meat, and divided the portions, '),(12396,'and the son of glorious Menelaus poured the wine.'),(12397,' So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them. '),(12398,'But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, then Telemachus and the glorious son of Nestor  yoked the horses and mounted the inlaid car, and drove forth from the gateway and the echoing portico.'),(12399,' After them went the son of Atreus, fair-haired Menelaus, bearing in his right hand honey-hearted wine in a cup of gold, that they might pour libations ere they set out.'),(12400,'  And he took his stand before the horses, and pledged the youths, and said:'),(12401,'\n“Fare ye well, young men, and bear greeting to Nestor, shepherd of the host, '),(12402,'for verily he was kind as a father to me, while we sons of the Achaeans warred in the land of Troy.\"'),(12403,'Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(12404,'  “Aye, verily, king, fostered of Zeus, to him will we tell all this on our coming, as thou dost bid.'),(12405,' And I would that, when I return to Ithaca, I might as surely find Odysseus in his house, to tell him how I met with every kindness at thy hands, ere I departed and bring with me treasures many and goodly.”'),(12406,'  Even as he spoke a bird flew by on the right, an eagle, bearing in his talons a great, white goose, a tame fowl from the yard, '),(12407,' and men and women followed shouting.'),(12408,' But the eagle drew near to them, and darted off to the right in front of the horses; '),(12409,' and  they were glad as they saw it, and the hearts in the breasts of all were cheered.'),(12410,'And among them Peisistratus, son of Nestor, was first to speak:'),(12411,'\n“Consider, Menelaus, fostered of Zeus, leader of hosts, whether it was for us two that the god showed this sign, or for thyself.\"'),(12412,'so he spoke, and Menelaus, dear to Ares, pondered  how he might with understanding interpret the sign aright.'),(12413,' But long-robed Helen took the word from him, and said:'),(12414,'\n“Hear me, '),(12415,' and I will prophesy as the immortals put it into my heart, and as I think it will be brought to pass.'),(12416,'Even as this eagle came  from the mountain, where are his kin, and where he was born, and snatched up the goose that was bred in the house, even so shall Odysseus return to his home after many toils and many wanderings, and shall take vengeance; '),(12417,'or even now he is at home, and is sowing the seeds of evil for all the wooers.” '),(12418,' \nThen again wise Telemachus answered her: '),(12419,' “So may Zeus grant, the loud-thundering lord of Here; '),(12420,'then will I even there ever pray to thee, as to a god.\"'),(12421,'He spoke, and touched the two horses with the lash, '),(12422,' and they sped swiftly toward the plain, coursing eagerly through the city.'),(12423,' So all day long they shook the yoke they bore about their necks.'),(12424,'  And the sun set, and all the ways grew dark.'),(12425,' And they came to Pherae, to the house of Diocles, son of Ortilochus, whom Alpheus begot.'),(12426,' There they spent the night, and before them he set the entertainment due to strangers. '),(12427,'As soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered,  they yoked the horses, and mounted the inlaid car, and drove forth from the gateway and the echoing portico.'),(12428,' Then Peisistratus touched the horses with the whip to start them, and nothing loath the pair sped onward,'),(12429,' and soon thereafter they reached the steep citadel of Pylos.'),(12430,' Then Telemachus spoke to the son of Nestor, saying:'),(12431,'\n  “Son of Nestor, wilt thou now make me a promise, and fulfil it, as I bid?'),(12432,' Friends from of old we call ourselves by reason of our fathers\' friendship, and we are moreover of the same age, '),(12433,' and this journey shall yet more stablish us in oneness of heart.'),(12434,'Lead me not past my ship, O thou fostered of Zeus, but leave me there,  lest that old man keep me in his house against my will, fain to show me kindness, '),(12435,'whereas I must needs hasten home.\"'),(12436,'So he spoke, and the son of Nestor took counsel with his heart, how he might duly give the promise and fulfil it.'),(12437,' And, as he pondered, this seemed to him the better course.'),(12438,'  He turned his horses to the swift ship and the shore of the sea, and took out, and set in the stern of the ship the beautiful gifts, the raiment and gold, which Menelaus gave him.'),(12439,' And he urged on Telemachus, and addressed him with winged words:'),(12440,'\n“Make haste now to go on board, and bid all thy comrades to do likewise,  before I reach home and bring the old man word. '),(12441,'For well I know this in mind and heart,'),(12442,'so masterful is his spirit he will not let thee go, but will himself come hither to bid thee to his house; and, I tell thee, he will not go back without thee; '),(12443,'for very wroth will he be, despite of all.” '),(12444,'  So saying, he drove his horses with beautiful mane back to the city of the Pylians, and speedily reached the palace.'),(12445,' And Telemachus called to his men, and gave command to them, saying:'),(12446,'\n“Set all the gear in order, men, in the black ship, and let us go on board ourselves, that we may speed on our way.”'),(12447,'  So he spoke, and they readily hearkened and obeyed; and at once they went on board, and sat down upon the benches. '),(12448,' \nHe verily was busied thus, and was praying and offering sacrifice to Athena by the stern of the ship,'),(12449,'when there drew nigh to him a man from a far land, one that was fleeing out of Argos because he had slain a man;  and he was a seer.'),(12450,' By lineage he was sprung from Melampus, who of old dwelt in Pylos, mother of flocks, a rich man and one that had a very wealthy house among the Pylians, '),(12451,' but had afterward come to a land of strangers, fleeing from his country and from great-hearted Neleus, the lordliest of living men,  who for a full year had kept much wealth from him by force.'),(12452,' Now Melampus meanwhile lay bound with bitter bonds in the halls of Phylacus, suffering grievous pains because of the daughter of Neleus, and the terrible blindness of heart which the goddess, the Erinys, who brings houses to ruin, had laid upon him.'),(12453,'  Howbeit he escaped his fate, and drove off the deep-lowing kine from Phylace to Pylos, and avenged the cruel deed upon godlike Neleus, and brought the maiden home to be his own brother\'s wife.'),(12454,' For himself, he went to the land of other men, to horse-pasturing Argos,'),(12455,'for there it was appointed him  to dwell, bearing sway over many Argives. There he wedded a wife and built him a high-roofed house, and begot Antiphates and Mantius, two stalwart sons.'),(12456,'Now Antiphates begot great-hearted Oicles, and Oicles Amphiaraus, the rouser of the host,  whom Zeus, who bears the aegis, and Apollo heartily loved with all manner of love.'),(12457,' Yet he did not reach the threshold of old age, but died in Thebe, because of a woman\'s gifts.'),(12458,' To him were born sons, Alcmaeon and Amphilochus.'),(12459,' And Mantius on his part begot Polypheides and Cleitus.'),(12460,'  Now Cleitus golden-throned Dawn snatched away by reason of his beauty, that he might dwell with the immortals;'),(12461,' but of Polypheides, high of heart, Apollo made a seer, far the best of mortals, after that Amphiaraus was dead.'),(12462,' He removed to Hyperesia, having waxed wroth with his father,  and there he dwelt and prophesied to all men.'),(12463,'His son it was, Theoclymenus by name, who now came and stood by Telemachus;'),(12464,' and he found him pouring libations and praying by his swift, black ship, and he spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(12465,'\n  “Friend, since I find thee making burnt-offering in this place, I beseech thee by thine offerings and by the god, aye, and by thine own life and the lives of thy comrades who follow thee, tell me truly what I ask, and hide it not.'),(12466,' Where is thy city, and where thy parents?” '),(12467,' Where is thy city, and where thy parents?” '),(12468,' \n  And wise Telemachus answered him: '),(12469,'“Then verily, stranger, will I frankly tell thee all.'),(12470,' Of Ithaca I am by birth, and my father is Odysseus, as sure as ever such a one there was;'),(12471,' but now he has perished by a pitiful fate.'),(12472,' Therefore have I now taken my comrades and a black ship,  and am come to seek tidings of my father, that has long been gone.”'),(12473,'Then godlike Theoclymenus answered him:'),(12474,' “Even so have I, too, fled from my country, for that I slew a man, one of mine own kin.'),(12475,' And many brethren and kinsmen of his there are in horse-pasturing Argos, and mightily do they bear sway over the Achaeans.'),(12476,'  It is to shun death and black fate at their hands that I flee, for, I ween, it is my lot to be a wanderer among men.'),(12477,' But do thou set me on thy ship, since in my flight I have made prayer to thee, lest they utterly slay me; '),(12478,' for methinks they are in pursuit.\"'),(12479,'And wise Telemachus answered him:'),(12480,'  “Then will I in no wise thrust thee from my shapely ship, since thou art eager to come.\n Nay, follow with us,'),(12481,' and in our home shalt thou find entertainment such as we have.\"'),(12482,'So saying, he took from him his spear of bronze, and laid it at length on the deck of the curved ship,'),(12483,' and himself went aboard the seafaring ship. '),(12484,' Then he sat down in the stern and made Theoclymenus sit down beside him; '),(12485,' and his men loosed the stern cables.'),(12486,'And Telemachus called to his men and bade them lay hold of the tackling, '),(12487,' and they quickly obeyed. '),(12488,'The mast of fir  they raised and set in the hollow socket, and made it fast with fore-stays, and hauled up the white sail with twisted thongs of oxhide. '),(12489,' And flashing-eyed Athena sent them a favorable wind, blowing strongly through the sky, that, speeding swiftly, the ship might accomplish her way over the salt water of the sea.'),(12490,'  So they fared past Crouni and Chalcis, with its beautiful streams.'),(12491,'Now the sun set and all the ways grew dark. '),(12492,'And the ship drew near to Pheae, sped by the wind of Zeus, and on past goodly Elis, where the Epeans hold sway.'),(12493,' From thence again he steered for the sharp isles  pondering whether he should escape death or be taken.'),(12494,' \nBut the two, Odysseus and the goodly swineherd, were supping in the hut, '),(12495,' and with them supped the other men.'),(12496,'But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, Odysseus spoke among them, making trial of the swineherd to see  whether he would still entertain him with kindly care and bid him remain there at the farmstead, or send him forth to the city:'),(12497,'\n“Hearken now, Eumaeus, and all ye other men.'),(12498,' In the morning I am minded to go forth to the city to beg, that I may not be the ruin of thee and of thy men. '),(12499,' Now then, give me good counsel, and send with me a trusty guide to lead me thither; '),(12500,'  but through the city will I wander by myself perforce, in the hope that one haply will give me a cup of water and a loaf.'),(12501,'Aye, and I would go to the house of godlike Odysseus and bear tidings to the wise Penelope,  and join the company of the insolent wooers, if perchance they may give me a meal, since they have good cheer in abundance.'),(12502,' Straightway might I do good service among them in all that they would.'),(12503,' For I will tell thee, and do thou give heed and hearken.'),(12504,' By the favour of Hermes, the messenger, who  lends grace and glory to all men\'s work, in the business of serving no man beside can vie with me, in piling well a fire, in splitting dry faggots, in carving and roasting meat, and in pouring wine —in all things in which meaner men serve the noble.\"'),(12505,'  Then deeply moved didst thou speak to him, swineherd Eumaeus:'),(12506,' “Ah me, stranger, why has such a thought come into thy mind?'),(12507,' Verily thou art fain utterly to perish there, '),(12508,'if thou wouldest indeed enter the throng of the wooers, whose wantonness and violence reach the iron heaven.'),(12509,'  Not such as thou are their serving men; nay, they that serve them are young men, well clad in cloaks and tunics, and ever are their heads and bright faces sleek; '),(12510,'and polished tables are laden with bread, and meat, and wine.'),(12511,'  Nay, abide here;'),(12512,' there is none that is vexed by thy presence, not I, nor any other of the men that are with me.'),(12513,' But when the dear son of Odysseus comes, he will himself clothe thee in a cloak and a tunic as raiment, and will send thee whithersoever thy heart and spirit bid thee go.” '),(12514,' \n  Then the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus answered him: '),(12515,'“Would, Eumaeus, that thou mightest be as dear to father Zeus as thou art to me, for that thou hast made me cease from wandering and from grievous hardships.'),(12516,'Than roaming naught else is more evil for mortals;'),(12517,'  yet for their cursed belly\'s sake  men endure evil woes, when wandering and sorrow and pain come upon them.'),(12518,'But now, since thou keepest me here and biddest me await thy master, come, tell me of the mother of godlike Odysseus, and of the father, whom, when he went forth, he left behind him on the threshold of old age. Are they haply still living beneath the rays of the sun?   or are they now dead and in the house of Hades?\"'),(12519,'Then the swineherd, a leader of men, answered him:'),(12520,' “Then verily, stranger, will I frankly tell thee.'),(12521,' Laertes still lives, but ever prays to Zeus that his life may waste away from his limbs within his halls.'),(12522,'  For wondrously does he grieve for his son that is gone, and for the wise lady, his wedded wife, whose death troubled him most of all, and brought him to untimely old age.'),(12523,' But she died of grief for her glorious son by a miserable death, as I would that no man may die  who dwells here as my friend and does me kindness.'),(12524,' So long as she lived, though it was in sorrow, it was ever a pleasure to me to ask and enquire after her, for she herself had brought me up with long-robed Ctimene, her noble daughter, whom she bore as her youngest child.'),(12525,'  With her was I brought up, and the mother honored me little less than her own children.'),(12526,' But when we both reached the longed-for prime of youth they sent her to Same to wed, and got themselves countless bridal gifts, but as for me, my lady clad me in a cloak and tunic, right goodly raiment, and gave me sandals for my feet  and sent me forth to the field; '),(12527,' but in her heart she loved me the more.'),(12528,' But now I lack all this, '),(12529,'though for my own part the blessed gods make to prosper the work to which I give heed.'),(12530,' Therefrom have I eaten and drunk, and given to reverend strangers.'),(12531,'But from my mistress I may hear naught pleasant,  whether word or deed, for a plague has fallen upon the house, even overweening men.'),(12532,' Yet greatly do servants long to speak before their mistress, and learn of all, and to eat and drink, and thereafter to carry off somewhat also to the fields, such things as ever make the heart of a servant to grow warm.” '),(12533,' \n  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(12534,'“Lo now, surely when thou wast but a child, swineherd Eumaeus, thou didst wander far from thy country and thy parents. '),(12535,'But come now, tell me this, and declare it truly. Was a broad-wayed city of men sacked,  wherein thy father and honored mother dwelt? Or, when thou wast alone with thy sheep or cattle, did foemen take thee in their ships and bear thee for sale to the house of this thy master, who paid for thee a goodly price?\"'),(12536,'Then the swineherd, a leader of men, answered him:'),(12537,'  “Stranger, since thou dost ask and question me of this, hearken now in silence, and take thy joy, and drink thy wine, as thou sittest here. '),(12538,' These nights are wondrous long.'),(12539,'There is time for sleep, and there is time to take joy in hearing tales; '),(12540,'thou needest not lay thee down till it be time; '),(12541,'there is weariness even in too much sleep.'),(12542,'  As for the rest, if any man\'s heart and spirit bid him, let him go forth and sleep,'),(12543,' and at daybreak let him eat, and follow our master\'s swine.'),(12544,' But we two will drink and feast in the hut, and will take delight each in the other\'s grievous woes,  as we recall them to mind.'),(12545,'For in after time a man finds joy even in woes, whosoever has suffered much, and wandered much.'),(12546,' But this will I tell thee, of which thou dost ask and enquire. '),(12547,'“There is an isle called Syria, if haply thou hast heard thereof, above Ortygia, where are the turning-places of the sun.  It is not so very thickly settled, but it is a good land, rich in herds, rich in flocks, full of wine, abounding in wheat.'),(12548,' Famine never comes into the land, nor does any hateful sickness besides fall on wretched mortals; '),(12549,' but when the tribes of men grow old throughout the city,  Apollo, of the silver bow, comes with Artemis, and assails them with his gentle shafts, and slays them.'),(12550,' In that isle are two cities, and all the land is divided between them,'),(12551,' and over both ruled as king my father, Ctesius, son of Ormenus, a man like to the immortals. '),(12552,' \n  “Thither came Phoenicians, men famed for their ships, greedy knaves, bringing countless trinkets in their black ship.'),(12553,' Now there was in my father\'s house a Phoenician woman, comely and tall, and skilled in glorious handiwork.'),(12554,' Her the wily Phoenicians beguiled.'),(12555,'  First, as she was washing clothes, one of them lay with her in love by the hollow ship; for this beguiles the minds of women, even though one be upright.'),(12556,' Then he asked her who she was, and whence she came, '),(12557,' and she straightway shewed him the high-roofed home of my father, and said:'),(12558,'\n  “‘Out of Sidon, rich in bronze, I declare that I come, and I am the daughter of Arybas, to whom wealth flowed in streams.'),(12559,' But Taphian pirates seized me, as I was coming from the fields, and brought me hither, and sold me to the house of yonder man, '),(12560,'and he paid for me a goodly price.'),(12561,'  “Then the man who had lain with her in secret answered her: '),(12562,'‘Wouldest thou then return again with us to thy home, that thou mayest see the high-roofed house of thy father and mother, and see them too?'),(12563,' For of a truth they yet live, and are accounted rich.\''),(12564,'“Then the woman answered him, and said:'),(12565,'  ‘This may well be, if you sailors will pledge yourselves by an oath, that you will bring me safely home.\''),(12566,'“So she spoke, and they all gave an oath thereto, as she bade them.'),(12567,' But when they had sworn and made an end of the oath, the woman again spoke among them, and made answer:'),(12568,'\n  “‘Be silent now, and let no one of your company speak to me, if he meets me in the street or haply at the well, '),(12569,'lest some one go to the palace and tell the old king, and he wax suspicious and bind me with grievous bonds, and devise death for you.'),(12570,' Nay, keep my words in mind, and speed the barter of your wares.'),(12571,'  But, when your ship is laden with goods, let a message come quickly to me at the palace; '),(12572,' for I will also bring whatever gold comes under my hand.'),(12573,'Aye, and I would gladly give another thing for my passage.'),(12574,'  There is a child of my noble master, whose nurse I am in the palace, such a cunning child, who ever runs abroad with me.'),(12575,' Him would I bring on board, and he would fetch you a vast price, wherever you might take him for sale among men of strange speech.’ '),(12576,' \n“So saying, she departed to the fair palace.  And they remained there in our land a full year, and got by trade much substance in their hollow ship.'),(12577,' But when their hollow ship was laden for their return, then they sent a messenger to bear tidings to the woman.'),(12578,' There came a man, well versed in guile, to my father\'s house  with a necklace of gold, and with amber beads was it strung between.'),(12579,' This the maidens in the hall and my honored mother were handling, and were gazing on it, and were offering him their price;'),(12580,'  but he nodded to the woman in silence.'),(12581,' Then verily when he had nodded to her, he went his way to the hollow ship,  but she took me by the hand, and led me forth from the house.'),(12582,' Now in the fore-hall of the palace she found the cups and tables of the banqueters, who waited upon my father.'),(12583,' They had gone forth to the council and the people\'s place of debate, but she quickly hid three goblets in her bosom,  and bore them away;'),(12584,'and I followed in my heedlessness.'),(12585,' Then the sun set, and all the ways grew dark. '),(12586,'And we made haste and came to the goodly harbor, where was the swift ship of the Phoenicians.'),(12587,' Then they embarked,  putting both of us on board as well, and sailed over the watery ways,'),(12588,'and Zeus sent them a favorable wind.'),(12589,' For six days we sailed, night and day alike;'),(12590,' but when Zeus, son of Cronos, brought upon us the seventh day, then Artemis, the archer, smote the woman, and she fell with a thud into the hold, as a sea bird plunges.'),(12591,'  Her they cast forth to be a prey to seals and fishes, '),(12592,' but I was left, my heart sore stricken.'),(12593,' Now the wind, as it bore them, and the wave, brought them to Ithaca, where Laertes bought me with his wealth. '),(12594,'Thus it was that my eyes beheld this land.”'),(12595,'  To him then Zeus-born Odysseus made answer, and said: '),(12596,' “Eumaeus, of a truth thou hast deeply stirred the heart in my breast in telling all this tale of the sorrow thou hast borne at heart.'),(12597,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 15.488-15.491'),(12598,' Yet verily in thy case Zeus has given good side by side with the evil, since after all thy toil thou hast come to the house of  a kindly man, who gives thee food and drink, and that with kindness, and thou livest well; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 488 to line 491'),(12599,' \nThus they spoke to one another, and then lay down to sleep, for no long time, but for a little;'),(12600,'  for soon came fair-throned Dawn.'),(12601,'But the comrades of Telemachus, drawing near the shore, furled the sail, and took down the mast quickly, and rowed the ship to her anchorage with their oars.'),(12602,' Then they cast out the mooring-stones and made fast the stern cables,'),(12603,' and themselves went forth upon the shore of the sea,  and made ready their meal and mixed the flaming wine. '),(12604,'But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, among them wise Telemachus was the first to speak, saying:'),(12605,'\n“Do you now row the black ship to the city, but I will visit the fields and the herdsmen, '),(12606,' and at evening will come to the city when I have looked over my lands. '),(12607,' And in the morning I will set before you, as wages for your journey, a good feast of flesh and sweet wine.\"'),(12608,'Then godlike Theoclymenus answered him: '),(12609,' “Whither shall I go, dear child?'),(12610,' To whose house shall I come  of those who rule in rocky Ithaca? '),(12611,'Or shall I go straight to thy mother\'s house and thine?”'),(12612,' Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(12613,'“Were things otherwise, I should bid thee go even to our house, '),(12614,'for there is in no wise lack of entertainment for strangers, '),(12615,' but  it would be worse for thyself, since I shall be away, and my mother will not see thee.'),(12616,' For she does not often appear before the wooers in the house, but apart from them weaves at her loom in an upper chamber.'),(12617,' But I will tell thee of another man to whom thou mayest go, Eurymachus, glorious son of wise Polybus,  whom now the men of Ithaca look upon as on a god. '),(12618,' For he is by far the best man, and is most eager to marry my mother and to have the honor of Odysseus.'),(12619,' Nevertheless Olympian Zeus, who dwells in the sky, knows this, whether or not before marriage he will fulfil for them the evil day.” '),(12620,' \n  Even as he spoke a bird flew forth upon the right, a hawk, the swift messenger of Apollo.'),(12621,' In his talons he held a dove, and was plucking her and shedding the feathers down on the ground midway between the ship and Telemachus himself.'),(12622,' Then Theoclymenus called him apart from his companions,  and clasped his hand, and spoke, and addressed him:'),(12623,'“Telemachus, surely not without a god\'s warrant has this bird flown forth upon our right, for I knew, as I looked upon him, that he was a bird of omen.'),(12624,' Than yours is no other house in the land of Ithaca more kingly; nay, ye are ever supreme.\"'),(12625,'  Then wise Telemachus answered him again: '),(12626,' “Ah, stranger, I would that this word of thine might be fulfilled.'),(12627,' Then shouldest thou straightway know of kindness and many a gift from me, so that one that met thee would call thee blessed.\"'),(12628,'Therewith he spoke to Peiraeus, his trusty comrade:'),(12629,'   “Peiraeus, son of Clytius, it is thou that in other matters art wont to hearken to me above all my comrades, who went with me to Pylos; '),(12630,' so now do thou, I pray thee, take this stranger and give him kindly welcome in thy house, and show him honor until I come.\"'),(12631,'  Then Peiraeus, the famous spearman, answered him:'),(12632,'“Telemachus, though thou shouldest stay here long, I will entertain him, and he shall have no lack of what is due to strangers.\"'),(12633,'So saying, he went on board the ship, and bade his comrades themselves to embark and to loose the stern cables.'),(12634,' So they went on board straightway, and sat down upon the benches.'),(12635,'  But Telemachus bound beneath his feet his fair sandals, and took his mighty spear, tipped with sharp bronze, from the deck of the ship.'),(12636,' Then the men loosed the stern cables, '),(12637,'and thrusting off, sailed to the city, as Telemachus bade, the dear son of divine Odysseus.'),(12638,'  But his feet bore him swiftly on, as he strode forward, until he reached the farmstead where were his countless swine, among whom slept the worthy swineherd with a heart loyal to his masters.'),(12639,' Meanwhile the two in the hut, Odysseus and the goodly swineherd, had kindled a fire, and were making ready their breakfast at dawn, and had sent forth the herdsmen with the droves of swine; '),(12640,' but around Telemachus the baying hounds fawned,  and barked not as he drew near.'),(12641,'And goodly Odysseus noted the fawning of the hounds, and the sound of footsteps fell upon his ears;'),(12642,'  and straightway he spoke to Eumaeus winged words:'),(12643,'\n“Eumaeus, surely some comrade of thine will be coming, or at least some one thou knowest, for the hounds do not bark,  but fawn about him, '),(12644,'and I hear the sound of footsteps.”'),(12645,'Not yet was the word fully uttered, when his own dear son stood in the doorway.'),(12646,' In amazement up sprang the swineherd, and from his hands the vessels fell with which he was busied as he mixed the flaming wine. '),(12647,'And he went to meet his lord,  and kissed his head and both his beautiful eyes and his two hands,'),(12648,'  and a big tear fell from him.'),(12649,'And as a loving father greets his own dear son, who comes in the tenth year from a distant land—his only son and well-beloved, for whose sake he has borne much sorrow—  even so did the goodly swineherd then clasp in his arms godlike Telemachus, and kiss him all over as one escaped from death;'),(12650,'and with wailing he addressed him with winged words:'),(12651,'“Thou art come, Telemachus, sweet light of my eyes.'),(12652,' I thought I should never see thee more after thou hadst gone in thy ship to Pylos.'),(12653,'  But come, enter in, dear child, that I may delight my heart with looking at thee here in my house, who art newly come from other lands.'),(12654,' For thou dost not often visit the farm and the herdsmen, but abidest in the town;'),(12655,' so, I ween, has it seemed good to thy heart, to look upon the destructive throng of the wooers.\"'),(12656,'  Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(12657,' “So shall it be, father. '),(12658,'It is for thy sake that I am come hither, to see thee with my eyes, and to hear thee tell whether my mother still abides in the halls, or whether by now some other man has wedded her, and the couch of Odysseus  lies haply in want of bedding, covered with foul spider-webs.\"'),(12659,'Then the swineherd, a leader of men, answered him:'),(12660,' “Aye, verily, she abides with steadfast heart in thy halls,'),(12661,' and ever sorrowfully for her the nights and the days wane as she weeps.”'),(12662,'  So saying, he took from him the spear of bronze, '),(12663,' and Telemachus went in and passed over the stone threshold.'),(12664,' As he drew near, his father, Odysseus, rose from his seat and gave him place,'),(12665,' but Telemachus on his part checked him, and said:'),(12666,'“Be seated, stranger, '),(12667,'and we shall find a seat elsewhere  in our farmstead.'),(12668,'There is a man here who will set us one.”'),(12669,'and for Telemachus the swineherd '),(12670,'and for Telemachus the swineherd '),(12671,'strewed green brushwood beneath and a fleece above it, '),(12672,' and there the dear son of Odysseus sat down. '),(12673,'Then the swineherd set before them platters  of roast meats, which they had left at their meal the day before, and quickly heaped up bread in baskets, and mixed in a bowl of ivy wood honey-sweet wine, '),(12674,'and himself sat down over against divine Odysseus.'),(12675,' So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them.'),(12676,'  But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, Telemachus spoke to the goodly swineherd, and said:'),(12677,'\n“Father, from whence did this stranger come to thee?'),(12678,' How did sailors bring him to Ithaca?'),(12679,' Who did they declare themselves to be?'),(12680,' For nowise, methinks, did he come hither on foot.\"'),(12681,'  To him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say: '),(12682,'“Then verily, my child, I will tell thee all the truth.'),(12683,' From broad Crete he declares that he has birth, and he says that he has wandered roaming through many cities of mortals; '),(12684,'so has a god spun for him this lot.'),(12685,'  But now he has run away from a ship of the Thesprotians and come to my farmstead, and I shall put him in thy hands. '),(12686,' He declares himself thy suppliant.”'),(12687,' He declares himself thy suppliant.”'),(12688,' Then again wise Telemachus answered him:'),(12689,'“Eumaeus, verily this word which thou hast uttered stings me to the heart.'),(12690,'  For how am I to welcome this stranger in my house?'),(12691,' I am myself but young, nor have I yet trust in my might to defend me against a man, when one waxes wroth without a cause. '),(12692,'And as for my mother, the heart in her breast wavers this way and that, whether to abide here with me and keep the house,  respecting the bed of her husband and the voice of the people, or to go now with him whosoever is best of the Achaeans that woo her in the halls, and offers the most gifts of wooing. '),(12693,'But verily, as regards this stranger, now that he has come to thy house, I will clothe him in a cloak and tunic, fair raiment,  and will give him a two-edged sword, and sandals for his feet, and send him whithersoever his heart and spirit bid him go.'),(12694,' Or, if thou wilt, do thou keep him here at the farmstead, and care for him, '),(12695,'and raiment will I send hither and all his food to eat, that he be not the ruin of thee and of thy men.'),(12696,'  But thither will I not suffer him to go, to join the company of the wooers, '),(12697,'for they are over-full of wanton insolence, '),(12698,' lest they mock him, and dread grief come upon me.'),(12699,' And to achieve aught is hard for one man among many, how mighty soever he be, for verily they are far stronger.” '),(12700,' \n  Then the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus answered him: '),(12701,' “Friend, since surely it is right for me to make answer—verily ye rend my heart, as I hear your words, such wantonness you say the wooers devise in the halls in despite of thee, so goodly a man.'),(12702,'  Tell me, art thou willingly thus oppressed? Or do the people throughout the land hate thee, following the voice of a god? Or hast thou cause to blame thy brothers, in whose fighting a man trusts even if a great strife arise.'),(12703,' Would that with my present temper I were as young as thou,  either the son of blameless Odysseus, or Odysseus himself, '),(12704,' straightway then might some stranger cut my head from off my neck, if I did not prove myself the bane of them all when I had come to the halls of Odysseus, son of Laertes.'),(12705,'  But if they should overwhelm me by their numbers, alone as I was, far rather would I die, slain in my own halls, than behold continually these shameful deeds, strangers mishandled, and men dragging the handmaidens in shameful fashion through the fair halls,  and wine drawn to waste, and men devouring my bread all heedlessly, without limit, with no end to the business.”'),(12706,' And wise Telemachus answered him: '),(12707,'“Then verily, stranger, I will frankly tell thee all.'),(12708,'Neither do the people at large bear me any grudge or hatred,  nor have I cause to blame brothers, in whose fighting a man trusts, even if a great strife arise.'),(12709,' For in this wise has the son of Cronos made our house to run in but a single line.'),(12710,' As his only son did Arceisius beget Laertes, as his only son again did his father beget Odysseus, '),(12711,' and Odysseus  begot me as his only son, and left me in his halls, and had no joy of me.'),(12712,'Therefore it is that foes past counting are now in the house;'),(12713,'  for all the princes who hold sway over the islands—Dulichium, and Same, and wooded Zacynthus—and those who lord it over rocky Ithaca,  all these woo my mother and lay waste my house.'),(12714,' And she neither refuses the hateful marriage, nor is she able to make an end;'),(12715,' but they with feasting consume my substance, '),(12716,'and will ere long bring me, too, to ruin. '),(12717,'Yet these things verily lie on the knees of the gods.'),(12718,'  But, father, do thou go with speed, and tell constant Penelope that she has me safe, and I am come from Pylos.'),(12719,' But I will abide here, and do thou come back hither, when thou hast told thy tale to her alone;  '),(12720,' but of the rest of the Achaeans let no one learn it, '),(12721,'for many there are who contrive evil against me.” '),(12722,' \n  To him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say:'),(12723,' this thou biddest one with understanding. '),(12724,' this thou biddest one with understanding. '),(12725,' But come now, tell me this, and declare it truly; whether I shall go on the self-same way with tidings to Laertes also, wretched man, who for a time, though grieving sorely for Odysseus,  was still wont to oversee the fields, and would eat and drink with the slaves in the house, as the heart in his breast bade him.'),(12726,' But now, from the day when thou wentest in thy ship to Pylos, they say he has no more eaten and drunk as before, nor overseen the fields, but with groaning and wailing  he sits and weeps, and the flesh wastes from off his bones.\"'),(12727,'Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(12728,' “\'Tis the sadder; but none the less we will let him be, despite our sorrow;'),(12729,' for if in any wise all things might be had by mortals for the wishing, we should choose first of all the day of my father\'s return.'),(12730,' No, do thou come back, when thou hast given thy message, and wander not over the fields in search of Laertes;'),(12731,' but did my mother with all speed send forth her handmaid, the housewife, secretly, '),(12732,'for she might bear word to the old man.\"'),(12733,'With this he roused the swineherd,'),(12734,' and he took his sandals in his hands  and bound them beneath his feet and went forth to the city.'),(12735,' Nor was Athena unaware that the swineherd Eumaeus was gone from the farmstead, but she drew near'),(12736,' in the likeness of a woman, comely and tall, and skilled in glorious handiwork. '),(12737,' And she stood over against the door of the hut, shewing herself to Odysseus, '),(12738,' but Telemachus did not see her before him, or notice her; for in no wise do the gods appear in manifest presence to all. But Odysseus saw her, and the hounds, and they barked not, but with whining slunk in fear to the further side of the farmstead.'),(12739,'The she made a sign with her brows,'),(12740,'and goodly Odysseus perceived it,  and went forth from the hall, past the great wall of the court, and stood before her, '),(12741,'and Athena spoke to him, saying:'),(12742,'“Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices,'),(12743,' even now do thou reveal thy word to thy son, and hide it not, that when you two have planned death and fate for the wooers,  you may go to the famous city.'),(12744,' Nor will I myself be long away from you, for I am eager for the battle.”'),(12745,'With this, Athena touched him with her golden wand.'),(12746,'\n A well-washed cloak and a tunic she first of all cast about his breast, and she increased his stature and his youthful bloom. '),(12747,'  Once more he grew dark of color, and his cheeks filled out, and dark grew the beard about his chin.'),(12748,' Then, when she had wrought thus, she departed, '),(12749,'but Odysseus went into the hut.'),(12750,' And his dear son marvelled, and, seized with fear, turned his eyes aside, lest it should be a god.   And he spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(12751,'“Of other sort thou seemest to me now, stranger, than awhile ago, and other are the garments thou hast on, and thy color is no more the same.'),(12752,' Verily thou art a god, one of those who hold broad heaven.'),(12753,'\n Nay then, be gracious, that we may offer to thee acceptable sacrifices  and golden gifts, finely wrought; '),(12754,'but do thou spare us.”'),(12755,' \nThen the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus answered him:'),(12756,' why dost thou liken me to the immortals?'),(12757,' why dost thou liken me to the immortals?'),(12758,' Nay, I am thy father, for whose sake thou dost with groaning endure many griefs, and submittest to the violence of men.” '),(12759,'  So saying, he kissed his son, and from his cheeks let fall a tear to earth, '),(12760,'but before he ever steadfastly held them back.'),(12761,' Howbeit Telemachus—for he did not yet believe that it was his father—again answered, and spoke to him, saying:'),(12762,'\n“Thou verily art not my father Odysseus, but some god  beguiles me, that I may weep and groan yet more. '),(12763,' For nowise could a mortal man contrive this by his own wit, unless a god were himself to come to him, and easily by his will make him young or old.'),(12764,' For verily but now thou wast an old man and meanly clad, '),(12765,'  whereas now thou art like the gods, who hold broad heaven.”'),(12766,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(12767,' “Telemachus, it beseems thee not to wonder overmuch that thy father is in the house, or to be amazed. '),(12768,'For thou mayest be sure no other Odysseus will ever come hither;  but I here, I, even such as thou seest me, after sufferings and many wanderings, am come in the twentieth year to my native land.'),(12769,' But this, thou must know, is the work of Athena, driver of the spoil, who makes me such as she will—for she has the power—now like a beggar, and now again  like a young man, and one wearing fair raiment about his body.'),(12770,' Easy it is for the gods, who hold broad heaven, both to glorify a mortal man and to abase him.\"'),(12771,'So saying, he sat down, and Telemachus, flinging his arms about his noble father, wept and shed tears,  and in the hearts of both arose a longing for lamentation. '),(12772,' And they wailed aloud more vehemently than birds, sea-eagles, or vultures with crooked talons, whose young the country-folk have taken from their nest before they were fledged; '),(12773,'even so piteously did they let tears fall from beneath their brows.'),(12774,'  And now would the light of the sun have gone down upon their weeping, had not Telemachus spoken to his father suddenly:'),(12775,'\n“In what manner of ship, dear father, have sailors now brought thee hither to Ithaca?'),(12776,' Who did they declare themselves to be?'),(12777,' For nowise, methinks, didst thou come hither on foot.” '),(12778,' \n  And the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus answered him: '),(12779,'“Then verily, my child, I will tell thee all the truth.'),(12780,' The Phaeacians brought me, men famed for their ships, who send other men too on their way, whosoever comes to them. '),(12781,'And they brought me as I slept in a swift ship over the sea,  and set me down in Ithaca, and gave me glorious gifts, stores of bronze and gold and woven raiment.'),(12782,' These treasures, by the favour of the gods, are lying in caves.'),(12783,' And now I am come hither at the bidding of Athena, that we may take counsel about the slaying of our foes.'),(12784,'  Come now, count me the wooers, and tell their tale, that I may know how many they are and what manner of men,'),(12785,'and that I may ponder in my noble heart and decide whether we two shall be able to maintain our cause against them alone without others, or whether we shall also seek out others.\"'),(12786,'  Then wise Telemachus answered him: '),(12787,'“Father, of a truth I have ever heard of thy great fame, that thou wast a warrior in strength of hand and in wise counsel, '),(12788,' amazement holds me.'),(12789,' amazement holds me.'),(12790,'It could not be that two men should fight against many men and mighty.'),(12791,'  For of the wooers there are not ten alone, or twice ten, but full many more.'),(12792,' Here as we are shalt thou straightway learn their number.'),(12793,' From Dulichium there are two and fifty chosen youths, and six serving men attend them; '),(12794,'from Same came four and twenty men;  from Zacynthus there are twenty youths of the Achaeans; and from Ithaca itself twelve men, all of them the noblest, and with them is Medon, the herald, and the divine minstrel, and two squires skilled in carving meats.'),(12795,' If we shall meet all these within the halls,  bitter, I fear, and with bane will be thy coming to avenge violence. '),(12796,' Nay, do thou consider, if thou canst bethink thee of any helper—one that would aid us two with a ready heart.”'),(12797,'Then the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus answered him:'),(12798,'“Well, then, I will tell thee, and do thou give heed and hearken to my words, '),(12799,'  and consider whether for us two Athena, with father Zeus, will be enough, or whether I shall bethink me of some other helper.”'),(12800,'Then wise Telemachus answered him: '),(12801,' “Good, thou mayest be sure, are these two helpers whom thou dost mention, though high in the clouds do they abide,'),(12802,'and they  rule over all men alike and the immortal gods.”'),(12803,' \nThen the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus answered:'),(12804,' “Not long of a surety will those two hold aloof from the mighty fray, when between the wooers and us in my halls the might of Ares is put to the test.'),(12805,'  But for the present, do thou go at daybreak to thy house and join the company of the haughty wooers.'),(12806,' As for me, the swineherd will lead me later on to the city in the likeness of a woeful and aged beggar. '),(12807,'And if they shall put despite on me in the house,  let the heart in thy breast endure while I am evil entreated, even if they drag me by the feet through the house to the door, or hurl at me and smite me; '),(12808,' still do thou endure to behold it. '),(12809,'Thou shalt indeed bid them cease their folly, seeking to dissuade them with gentle words; '),(12810,'yet in no wise  will they hearken to thee, '),(12811,' for verily their day of doom is at hand. '),(12812,'And another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart. '),(12813,' When Athena, rich in counsel, shall put it in my mind, I will nod to thee with my head; and do thou thereupon, when thou notest it, take all the weapons of war that lie in thy halls,  and lay them away one and all in the secret place of the lofty store-room.'),(12814,' And as for the wooers, when they miss the arms and question thee, do thou beguile them with gentle words, saying:'),(12815,'“‘Out of the smoke have I laid them, since they are no longer like those which of old Odysseus left behind him when he went forth to Troy,  but are all befouled so far as the breath of the fire has reached them. '),(12816,' And furthermore this greater fear has the son of Cronos put in my heart, lest haply, when heated with wine, you may set a quarrel afoot among you and wound one another, and so bring shame on your feast and on your wooing.'),(12817,' For of itself does the iron draw a man to it.’'),(12818,'  “But for us two alone do thou leave behind two swords and two spears, and two ox-hide shields for us to grasp, that we may rush upon them and seize them; '),(12819,'while as for the wooers, Pallas Athena and Zeus, the counsellor, will beguile them.'),(12820,' And another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart.'),(12821,'  If in truth thou art my son and of our blood, then let no one hear that Odysseus is at home; neither let Laertes know it, nor the swineherd, nor any of the household, nor Penelope herself; but by ourselves thou and I will learn the temper of the women.'),(12822,'  Aye, and we will likewise make trial of many a one of the serving men, and see where any of them honours us two and fears us at heart, and who recks not of us and scorns thee, a man so goodly.”  '),(12823,' \nThen his glorious son answered him, and said: “Father, my spirit, methinks,  thou shalt verily come to know hereafter, '),(12824,' for no slackness of will possesses me. '),(12825,' But I think not that this plan will be a gain to us both, and so I bid thee take thought.'),(12826,' Long time shalt thou vainly go about, '),(12827,'making trial of each man as thou visitest the farms, '),(12828,'while in thy halls those others at their ease  are wasting thy substance in insolent wise, and there is no sparing. '),(12829,' Yet verily, as for the women, I do bid thee learn who among them dishonor thee, and who are guiltless.'),(12830,' But of the men in the farmsteads I would not that we should make trial, but that we should deal therewith hereafter,  if in very truth thou knowest some sign from Zeus who bears the aegis.”'),(12831,'Thus they spoke to one another, but meanwhile into Ithaca put the well-built ship that brought Telemachus and all his comrades from Pylos;'),(12832,'and they, when they had come into the deep harbor,  drew the black ship up on the shore, while proud squires bore forth their armour and straightway carried the beauteous gifts to the house of Clytius.'),(12833,'But they sent a herald forth to the house of Odysseus to bear word to wise Penelope  that Telemachus was at the farm, and had bidden the ship to sail on to the city, lest the noble queen might grow anxious and let round tears fall. So the two met, the herald and the goodly swineherd, on the self-same errand, to bear tidings to the lady.'),(12834,'  And when they reached the palace of the godlike king, the herald spoke out in the midst of the handmaids, and said: '),(12835,'\"Even now, queen, thy son has come back from Pylos.”'),(12836,'But the swineherd came close to Penelope and told her all that her dear son had bidden him say.'),(12837,'  And when he had fully told all that had been commanded him, he went his way to the swine and left the courtyard and the hall.'),(12838,'\nBut the wooers were dismayed and downcast in spirit, and forth they went from the hall past the great wall of the court, and there before the gates they sat down. '),(12839,' Then among them Eurymachus, son of Polybus, was the first to speak:'),(12840,'\n“My friends, verily a great deed has been insolently brought to pass by Telemachus, even this journey,'),(12841,' and we deemed that he would never see it accomplished.'),(12842,' But come, let us launch a black ship, the best we have, and let us get together seamen as rowers that they may straightway  bear tidings to those others speedily to return home.”'),(12843,' \nNot yet was the word fully uttered when Amphinomus, turning in his place, saw a ship in the deep harbor and men furling the sail, and with oars in their hands.'),(12844,' Then, breaking into a merry laugh, he spoke among his comrades:'),(12845,' for here they are at home.'),(12846,' for here they are at home.'),(12847,'\n Either some god told them of this, or they themselves caught sight of the ship of Telemachus as she sailed by, but could not catch her.\"'),(12848,'So he spoke, and they rose up and went to the shore of the sea. Swiftly the men drew up the black ship on the shore,  and proud squires bore forth their armour.'),(12849,'Themselves meanwhile went all together to the place of assembly, and none other would they suffer to sit with them, either of the young men or the old.'),(12850,'Then among them spoke Antinous, son of Eupeithes:'),(12851,'“Lo, now, see how the gods have delivered this man from destruction.'),(12852,'  Day by day watchmen sat upon the windy heights, watch ever following watch, '),(12853,' and at set of sun we never spent a night upon the shore, but sailing over the deep in our swift ship we waited for the bright Dawn, lying in wait for Telemachus, that we might take him and slay  the man himself; '),(12854,' howbeit meanwhile some god has brought him home. But, on our part, let us here devise for him a woeful death, even for Telemachus, and let him not escape from out our hands, '),(12855,' for I deem that while he lives this work of ours will not prosper.'),(12856,'For he is himself shrewd in counsel and in wisdom,  and the people nowise show us favour any more.'),(12857,'Nay, come, before he gathers the Achaeans to the place of assembly—for methinks he will in no wise be slow to act, but will be full of wrath, and rising up will declare among them all how that we contrived against him utter destruction, but did not catch him; '),(12858,' and they will not praise us when they hear of our evil deeds. '),(12859,' Beware, then, lest they work us some harm and drive us out from our country, and we come to the land of strangers.'),(12860,' Nay, let us act first, and seize him in the field far from the city, or on the road; '),(12861,'and his substance let us ourselves keep, and his wealth,  dividing them fairly among us; though the house we would give to his mother to possess, and to him who weds her. '),(12862,'Howbeit if this plan does not please you, but you choose rather that he should live and keep all the wealth of his fathers, let us not continue to devour his store of pleasant things  as we gather together here, but let each man from his own hall woo her with his gifts and seek to win her; '),(12863,'and she then would wed him who offers most, and who comes as her fated lord.” '),(12864,' \nSo he spoke, and they were all hushed in silence. '),(12865,' Then Amphinomus addressed their assembly, and spoke among them. He was the glorious son of the prince Nisus, son of Aretias, and he led the wooers who came from Dulichium, rich in wheat and in grass, and above all the others he pleased Penelope with his words, '),(12866,'for he had an understanding heart.'),(12867,' He it was who with good intent addressed their assembly, and spoke among them:'),(12868,'\n  “Friends, I surely would not choose to kill Telemachus;'),(12869,'a dread thing is it to slay one of royal stock.'),(12870,' Nay, let us first seek to learn the will of the gods.'),(12871,' If the oracles of great Zeus approve, I will myself slay him, and bid all the others do so; '),(12872,'  but if the gods turn us from the act, I bid you desist.”'),(12873,'Thus spoke Amphinomus, and his word was pleasing to them.'),(12874,' So they arose straightway and went to the house of Odysseus, and entering in, sat down on the polished seats.'),(12875,'\nThen the wise Penelope took other counsel,  to show herself to the wooers, overweening in their insolence.'),(12876,'For she had learned of the threatened death of her son in her halls, '),(12877,' for the herald Medon told her, who had heard their counsel.'),(12878,' So she went her way toward the hall with her handmaids. '),(12879,' But when the fair lady reached the wooers,  she stood by the doorpost of the well-built hall, holding before her face her shining veil; and she rebuked Antinous, and spoke, and addressed him:'),(12880,' “Antinous, full of insolence, deviser of evil! and yet it is thou, men say, that dost excel among all of thy years in the land of Ithaca  in counsel and in speech. '),(12881,'But thou, it seems, art not such a man. '),(12882,' Madman! why dost thou devise death and fate for Telemachus, and carest not for suppliants, for whom Zeus is witness. '),(12883,'\'Tis an impious thing to plot evil one against another.'),(12884,'Dost thou not know of the time when thy father came to this house a fugitive  in terror of the people? '),(12885,' For of a truth they were greatly wroth with him because he had joined Taphian pirates and harried the Thesprotians, '),(12886,' who were in league with us.'),(12887,'Him, then, they were minded to slay, and take from him his life by violence, and utterly to devour his great and pleasant livelihood; '),(12888,' but Odysseus held them back, and stayed them despite their eagerness. '),(12889,'His house it is that thou consumest now without atonement, and wooest his wife, and seekest to slay his son, and on me thou bringest great distress.'),(12890,' Nay, forbear, I charge thee, and bid the rest forbear.” '),(12891,' \nThen Eurymachus, son of Polybus, answered her:'),(12892,'  “Daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope, be of good cheer, '),(12893,'and let not things distress thy heart.'),(12894,' That man lives not, nor shall live, nor shall ever be born, who shall lay hands upon thy son Telemachus while I live and behold the light upon the earth.'),(12895,'  For thus will I speak out to thee, and verily it shall be brought to pass.'),(12896,' Quickly shall that man\'s black blood flow forth about my spear; for of a truth me, too, did Odysseus the sacker of cities often set upon his knees, and put roast meat in my hands, and hold to my lips red wine.'),(12897,'  Therefore Telemachus is far the dearest of all men to me, and I bid him have no fear of death, at least from the wooers; '),(12898,'but from the gods can no man avoid it.”'),(12899,'Thus he spoke to cheer her, but against that son he was himself plotting death. '),(12900,' So she went up to her bright upper chamber  and then bewailed Odysseus, her dear husband, until flashing-eyed Athena cast sweet sleep upon her eyelids.'),(12901,'\nBut at evening the goodly swineherd came back to Odysseus and his son, '),(12902,' and they were busily making ready their supper, and had slain a boar of a year old.'),(12903,'Then Athena  came close to Odysseus, son of Laertes, and smote him with her wand, and again made him an old man; and mean raiment she put about his body, lest the swineherd might look upon him and know him, and might go to bear tidings to constant Penelope, and not hold the secret fast in his heart.'),(12904,'\n  Now Telemachus spoke first to the swineherd, and said:'),(12905,'What news is there in the city? '),(12906,'What news is there in the city? '),(12907,' Have the proud wooers by this time come home from their ambush, or are they still watching for me where they were, to take me on my homeward way?\"'),(12908,'To him, then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer and say:'),(12909,'  “I was not minded to go about the city, asking and enquiring of this; '),(12910,'my heart bade me with all speed to come back hither when I had given my message.'),(12911,' But there joined me a swift messenger from thy companions, a herald, who was the first to tell the news to thy mother.'),(12912,'for I saw it with my eyes.'),(12913,'for I saw it with my eyes.'),(12914,'  I was now above the city, as I went on my way, where the hill of Hermes is, when I saw a swift ship putting into our harbor, '),(12915,' and there were many men in her, and she was laden with shields and double-pointed spears.'),(12916,'   And I thought it was they, but I have no knowledge.”'),(12917,'\nSo he spoke, and the strong and mighty Telemachus smiled and with his eyes he glanced at his father, but shunned the swineherd\'s eye.'),(12918,'\nAnd when they had ceased from their labour and had made ready the meal, they fell to feasting, nor did their hearts lack aught of the equal feast.'),(12919,'  But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink, they bethought them of rest, and took the gift of sleep.'),(12920,' As soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, Telemachus, the dear son of divine Odysseus, bound beneath his feet his fair sandals and took his mighty spear, that fitted his grasp,  hasting to the city; and he spoke to his swineherd, saying:'),(12921,' “Father, I verily am going to the city, that my mother may see me,'),(12922,'\n for, methinks, she will not cease from woeful wailing and tearful lamentation until she sees my very self.'),(12923,' But to thee I give this charge.'),(12924,'  Lead this wretched stranger to the city, that there he may beg his food, '),(12925,' and whoso will shall give him a loaf and a cup of water.'),(12926,'For my part, I can in no wise burden myself with all men, seeing that I have grief at heart.'),(12927,' But if the stranger is sore angered at this,  it will be the worse for him. '),(12928,'I verily love to speak the truth.”'),(12929,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said: '),(12930,' “Friend, be sure I am not myself fain to be left here.'),(12931,'For a beggar it is better to beg his food in the town than in the fields,'),(12932,' and whoso will shall give it me.'),(12933,'  For I am no more of an age to remain at the farmstead, so as to obey in all things the command of an overseer.'),(12934,' Nay, go thy way; '),(12935,'this man that thou biddest will lead me as soon as I have warmed myself at the fire, and the sun has grown hot. '),(12936,' For miserably poor are these garments which I wear, '),(12937,' and I fear lest  the morning frost may overcome me; '),(12938,' and ye say it is far to the city.” '),(12939,'\nSo he spoke, and Telemachus passed out through the farmstead with rapid strides, and was sowing the seeds of evil for the wooers.'),(12940,' But when he came to the stately house he set his spear in place, leaning it against a tall pillar,  and himself went in and crossed the threshold of stone.'),(12941,'Him the nurse Eurycleia was far the first to see, as she was spreading fleeces on the richly-wrought chairs. With a burst of tears she came straight toward him, '),(12942,' and round about them gathered the other maids of Odysseus of the steadfast heart,  and they kissed his head and shoulders in loving welcome.'),(12943,'\nThen forth from her chamber came wise Penelope, like unto Artemis or golden Aphrodite, and bursting into tears she flung her arms about her dear son, and kissed his head and both his beautiful eyes;  and with wailing she spoke to him winged words:'),(12944,'“Thou art come, Telemachus, sweet light of my eyes;'),(12945,'\n I thought I should never see thee more after thou hadst gone in thy ship to Pylos—secretly, and in my despite, to seek tidings of thy dear father.'),(12946,' Come, then, tell me what sight thou hadst of him.” '),(12947,' \n  Then wise Telemachus answered her:'),(12948,'“My mother, stir not lamentation, I pray thee, nor rouse the heart in my breast, seeing that I am escaped from utter destruction. '),(12949,'Nay, bathe thyself, and take clean raiment for thy body, and then, going to thy upper chamber with thy handmaids,  vow to all the gods that thou wilt offer hecatombs that bring fulfillment, in the hope that Zeus may some day bring deeds of requital to pass.'),(12950,' But I will go to the place of assembly that I may bid to our house a stranger who followed me from Pylos on my way hither. '),(12951,' Him I sent forward with my godlike comrades,  and I bade Peiraeus take him home and give him kindly welcome, and show him honor until I should come.\"'),(12952,'So he spoke, but her word remained unwinged.'),(12953,' Then she bathed and took clean raiment for her body, and vowed to all the gods that she would offer hecatombs  that bring fulfillment, in the hope that Zeus would some day bring deeds of requital to pass.'),(12954,'But Telemachus thereafter went forth through the hall with his spear in his hand,'),(12955,'\n and with him went two swift hounds.'),(12956,'And wondrous was the grace that Athena shed upon him,'),(12957,'  and all the people marvelled at him as he came.'),(12958,'  Round about him the proud wooers thronged, speaking him fair, but pondering evil in the deep of their hearts.'),(12959,' Howbeit he avoided the great throng of these men, but where Mentor sat, and Antiphus, and Halitherses, who were friends of his father\'s house of old,  there he went and sat down, '),(12960,' and they questioned him of each thing. '),(12961,'Then Peiraeus, the famous spearman, drew near, leading the stranger through the city to the place of assembly; '),(12962,' and Telemachus did not long turn away from his guest, but went up to him.'),(12963,' Then Peiraeus was the first to speak, saying:'),(12964,'\n  “Telemachus, quickly send women to my house, that I may send to thee the gifts which Menelaus gave thee.\"'),(12965,'Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(12966,' “Peiraeus, we know not how these things will be. '),(12967,'If the proud wooers  shall secretly slay me in my hall, and divide among them all the goods of my fathers, I would that thou shouldest keep and enjoy these things thyself rather than one of these.'),(12968,' But if I shall sow for them the seeds of death and fate, then do thou bring all to my house gladly, as I shall be glad.” '),(12969,' \nSo saying, he led the sore-tired stranger to the house.'),(12970,'  Now when they had come to the stately house they laid their cloaks on the chairs and high seats, and went into the polished baths and bathed.'),(12971,' And when the maids had bathed them and anointed them with oil, and had cast about them fleecy cloaks and tunics,  they came forth from the baths and sat down upon the chairs.'),(12972,' Then a handmaid brought water for the hands in a fair pitcher of gold, and poured it over a silver basin for them to wash,'),(12973,' and beside them drew up a polished table.'),(12974,' And the grave housewife brought and set before them bread,  and therewith meats in abundance, granting freely of her store.'),(12975,' And his mother sat over against Telemachus by the door-post of the hall, leaning against a chair and spinning fine threads of yarn.'),(12976,' So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them. But when they had put from them the desire of food and drink,  the wise Penelope spoke first among them:'),(12977,'“Telemachus, I truly will go to my upper chamber and lay me on my bed, which has become for me a bed of wailing, ever wet with my tears, since the day when Odysseus set forth with the sons of Atreus for Ilios.'),(12978,'But thou tookest no care,  before the proud wooers come into this house, to tell me plainly of the return of thy father, if haply thou heardest aught.\"'),(12979,'And wise Telemachus answered her:'),(12980,'\n “Then verily, mother, I will tell thee all the truth.'),(12981,' We went to Pylos and to Nestor, the shepherd of the people,'),(12982,' and he received me in his lofty house and gave me kindly welcome, as a father might his own son who after a long time had newly come from a far:'),(12983,' even so kindly he tended me with his glorious sons.'),(12984,' Yet of Odysseus of the steadfast heart,  whether living or dead, he said he had heard naught from any man on earth. '),(12985,' But he sent me on my way with horses and jointed car to Menelaus, son of Atreus, the famous spearman.'),(12986,' There I saw Argive Helen, for whose sake Argives and Trojans toiled much by the will of the gods. '),(12987,' \n  And straightway Menelaus, good at the war-cry, asked me in quest of what I had come to goodly Lacedaemon;'),(12988,'and I told him all the truth.'),(12989,' Then he made answer to me, and said:'),(12990,'\n“‘Out upon them! for verily in the bed of a man of valiant heart  were they fain to lie, who are themselves cravens. '),(12991,'Even as when in the thicket-lair of a mighty lion a hind has laid to sleep her new-born suckling fawns, and roams over the mountain slopes and grassy vales seeking pasture, and then the lion comes to his lair  and upon the two lets loose a cruel doom, so will Odysseus let loose a cruel doom upon these men. '),(12992,' I would, O father Zeus, and Athena, and Apollo, that in such strength, as when once in fair-stablished Lesbos he rose up and wrestled a match with Philomeleides  and threw him mightily, and all the Achaeans rejoiced, even in such strength Odysseus might come among the wooers; '),(12993,'then should they all find swift destruction and bitterness in their wooing. '),(12994,'But in this matter of which thou dost ask and entreat me, verily I will not swerve aside to speak of other things, nor will I deceive thee;  but of all that the unerring old man of the sea told me, not one thing will I hide from thee or conceal.'),(12995,' He said that he had seen Odysseus in an island in grievous distress, in the halls of the nymph Calypso, who keeps him there perforce.'),(12996,' And he cannot come to his own native land, '),(12997,'for he has at hand no ships with oars, and no comrades,  to send him on his way over the broad back of the sea.’\n“So spoke Menelaus, son of Atreus, the famous spearman.'),(12998,' Now when I had made an end of all this I set out for home, '),(12999,'and the immortals gave me a fair wind and brought me quickly to my dear native land.\"'),(13000,'  So he spoke, and stirred the heart in her breast.'),(13001,'Then among them spoke also the godlike Theoclymenus, saying:'),(13002,'\n“Honored wife of Odysseus, son of Laertes, he truly has no clear understanding; but do thou hearken to my words, '),(13003,'for with certain knowledge will I prophesy to thee, and will hide naught.'),(13004,'  Be my witness Zeus above all gods, and this hospitable board and the hearth of noble Odysseus to which I am come, that verily Odysseus is even now in his native land, resting or moving, learning of these evil deeds, and he is sowing the seeds of evil for all the wooers.'),(13005,'  So plain a bird of omen did I mark as I sat on the benched ship, and I declared it to Telemachus.\"'),(13006,'Then wise Penelope answered him:'),(13007,' “Ah, stranger, I would that this word of thine might be fulfilled.'),(13008,' Then shouldest thou straightway know of kindness and many a gift  from me, so that one who met thee would call the blessed.”'),(13009,' \nThus they spoke to one another. And the wooers meanwhile in front of the palace of Odysseus were making merry, throwing the discus and the javelin in a levelled place, as their wont was, in insolence of heart.'),(13010,'  But when it was the hour for dinner, and the flocks came in from all sides from the fields, and the men led them who were wont to lead, then Medon, '),(13011,'who of all the heralds was most to their liking and was ever present at their feasts, spoke to them, saying:'),(13012,'\n“Youths, now that you have all made glad your hearts with sport,  come to the house that we may make ready a feast; '),(13013,'for it is no bad thing to take one\'s dinner in season.\"'),(13014,'So he spoke, and they rose up and went, and hearkened to his word. '),(13015,'And when they had come to the stately house they laid their cloaks on the chairs and high seats,  and men fell to slaying great sheep and fat goats, aye, and fatted and swine, and a heifer of the herd, and so made ready the meal.'),(13016,' But Odysseus and the goodly swineherd were making haste to go from the field to the city; '),(13017,' and the swineherd, a leader of men, spoke first, and said:'),(13018,'\n  “Stranger, since thou art eager to go the city today, as my master bade—though for myself I would rather have thee left here to keep the farmstead; '),(13019,'but I reverence and fear him, lest hereafter he chide me, '),(13020,'and hard are the rebukes of masters—  come now, let us go. '),(13021,' The day is far spent, and soon thou wilt find it colder toward evening.”'),(13022,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said: '),(13023,'this thou biddest one with understanding. '),(13024,'this thou biddest one with understanding. '),(13025,' Come, let us go, and be thou my guide all the way.'),(13026,'  But give me a staff to lean upon, if thou hast one cut anywhere, for verily ye said that the way was treacherous.\"'),(13027,'He spoke, and flung about his shoulders his miserable wallet, full of holes, '),(13028,'slung by a twisted cord,'),(13029,'and Eumaeus gave him a staff to his liking.'),(13030,'  So they two set forth, and the dogs and the herdsmen stayed behind to guard the farmstead;'),(13031,' but the swineherd led his master to the city in the likeness of a woeful and aged beggar, leaning on a staff; '),(13032,'and miserable was the raiment that he wore about his body. '),(13033,' \nBut when, as they went along the rugged path,  they were near the city, and had come to a well-wrought, fair-flowing fountain, wherefrom the townsfolk drew water—this Ithacus had made, and Neritus, and Polyctor,'),(13034,'and around was a grove of poplars, that grow by the waters, circling it on all sides, and down the cold water flowed  from the rock above,'),(13035,'and on the top was built an altar to the nymphs where all passers-by made offerings—'),(13036,'there Melantheus, son of Dolius, met them as he was driving his she-goats, the best that were in all the herds, to make a feast for the wooers; '),(13037,' and two herdsmen followed with him.'),(13038,'  As he saw them, he spoke and addressed them, and reviled them in terrible and unseemly words,'),(13039,'and stirred the heart of Odysseus:'),(13040,'\n“Lo, now, in very truth the vile leads the vile. As ever, the god is bringing like and like together.'),(13041,' Whither, pray, art thou leading this filthy wretch, thou miserable swineherd,  this nuisance of a beggar to mar our feasts? '),(13042,' He is a man to stand and rub his shoulders on many doorposts, begging for scraps, not for swords or cauldrons.'),(13043,' If thou wouldest give me this fellow to keep my farmstead, to sweep out the pens and to carry young shoots to the kids,  then by drinking whey he might get himself a sturdy thigh.'),(13044,'But since he has learned only deeds of evil, he will not care to busy himself with work, but is minded rather to go skulking through the land, that by begging he may feed his insatiate belly.'),(13045,' But I will speak out to thee, and this word shall verily be brought to pass.'),(13046,'  If he comes to the palace of divine Odysseus, many a footstool, hurled about his head by the hands of those that are men, shall be broken on his ribs as he is pelted through the house.\"'),(13047,'So he spoke, and as he passed he kicked Odysseus on the hip in his folly,'),(13048,' yet he did not drive him from the path,  but he stood steadfast.'),(13049,' And Odysseus pondered whether he should leap upon him and take his life with his staff, or seize him round about, and lift him up, and dash his head upon the ground.'),(13050,' Yet he endured, and stayed him from his purpose.'),(13051,'And the swineherd looked the man in the face, and rebuked him, and lifted up his hands, and prayed aloud:'),(13052,'\n  “Nymphs of the fountain, daughters of Zeus, if ever Odysseus burned upon your altars pieces of the thighs of lambs or kids, wrapped in rich fat, fulfil for me this prayer; grant that he, my master, may come back, and that some god may guide him. '),(13053,'Then would he scatter all the proud airs  which now thou puttest on in thy insolence,ever roaming about the city, '),(13054,'while evil herdsmen destroy the flock.” '),(13055,' \nThen Melanthius, the goatherd, answered him:'),(13056,' “Lo now, how the cur talks, his mind full of mischief. Him will I some day  take on a black, benched ship far from Ithaca, that he may bring me in much wealth. '),(13057,' Would that Apollo, of the silver bow, might smite Telemachus to-day in the halls, or that he might be slain by the wooers, as surely as for Odysseus in a far land the day of return has been lost.\"'),(13058,'So saying, he left them there, as they walked slowly on,  but himself strode forward and right swiftly came to the palace of the king.'),(13059,'Straightway he entered in and sat down among the wooers over against Eurymachus, '),(13060,'for he loved him best of all.'),(13061,' Then by him those that served set a portion of meat, and the grave housewife brought and set before him bread,  for him to eat. '),(13062,'And Odysseus and the goodly swineherd halted as they drew nigh, and about them rang the sound of the hollow lyre, '),(13063,' for Phemius was striking the chords to sing before the wooers.'),(13064,' Then Odysseus clasped the swineherd by the hand, and said:'),(13065,'\n“Eumaeus, surely this is the beautiful house of Odysseus.  Easily might it be known, though seen among many.'),(13066,' There is building upon building, and the court is built with wall and coping, and the double gates are well-fenced; '),(13067,'no man may scorn it. '),(13068,'And I mark that in the house itself many  men are feasting: for the savour of meat arises from it, and therewith resounds the voice of the lyre, which the gods have made the companion of the feast.\"'),(13069,'To him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say:'),(13070,' “Easily hast thou marked it, for in all things thou art ready of wit.'),(13071,' But come, let us take thought how these things shall be.'),(13072,'  Either do thou go first into the stately palace, and enter the company of the wooers, and I will remain behind here, '),(13073,' or, if thou wilt, remain thou here and I will go before thee.'),(13074,' But do not thou linger long, lest some man see thee without and pelt thee or smite thee.'),(13075,' Of this I bid thee take thought.”'),(13076,'\n  Then the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus answered him:'),(13077,' this thou biddest one with understanding.'),(13078,' this thou biddest one with understanding.'),(13079,' But go thou before, and I will remain behind here;'),(13080,' for no whit unused am I to blows and peltings.'),(13081,' Staunch is my heart, for much evil have I suffered  amid the waves and in war;'),(13082,' let this too be added to what has gone before.'),(13083,'But a ravening belly may no man hide, an accursed plague that brings many evils upon men. Because of it are the benched ships also made ready, that bear evil to foemen over the unresting sea.” '),(13084,' \n  Thus they spoke to one another. '),(13085,'And a hound that lay there raised his head and pricked up his ears, Argos, the hound of Odysseus, of the steadfast heart, whom of old he had himself bred, but had no joy of him, for ere that he went to sacred Ilios.'),(13086,' In days past the young men were wont to take the hound to hunt  the wild goats, and deer, and hares; '),(13087,'but now he lay neglected, his master gone, in the deep dung of mules and cattle, which lay in heaps before the doors, till the slaves of Odysseus should take it away to dung his wide lands.'),(13088,'  There lay the hound Argos, full of vermin;'),(13089,' yet even now, when he marked Odysseus standing near, he wagged his tail and dropped both his ears, but nearer to his master he had no longer strength to move.'),(13090,' Then Odysseus looked aside and wiped away a tear,  easily hiding from Eumaeus what he did; and straightway he questioned him, and said:'),(13091,'“Eumaeus, verily it is strange that this hound lies here in the dung.'),(13092,'\n He is fine of form, but I do not clearly know whether he has speed of foot to match this beauty or whether he is merely as table-dogs  are, '),(13093,'which their masters keep for show.”'),(13094,'\nTo him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer and say:'),(13095,' “Aye, verily this is the hound of a man that has died in a far land.'),(13096,' If he were but in form and in action such as he was when Odysseus left him and went to Troy,  thou wouldest soon be amazed at seeing his speed and his strength.'),(13097,' No creature that he started in the depths of the thick wood could escape him,'),(13098,' and in tracking too he was keen of scent.'),(13099,' But now he is in evil plight, and his master has perished far from his native land, and the heedless women give him no care.'),(13100,'  Slaves, when their masters lose their power, are no longer minded thereafter to do honest service:'),(13101,' for Zeus, whose voice is borne afar, takes away half his worth from a man, when the day of slavery comes upon him.\"'),(13102,'So saying, he entered the stately house  and went straight to the hall to join the company of the lordly wooers. '),(13103,'But as for Argos, the fate of black death seized him straightway when he had seen Odysseus in the twentieth year.'),(13104,'\nNow as the swineherd came through the hall godlike Telemachus was far the first to see him, and quickly  with a nod he called him and to his side. '),(13105,'And Eumaeus looked about him and took a stool that lay near, on which the carver was wont to sit when carving for the wooers the many joints of meat, as they feasted in the hall.'),(13106,' This he took and placed at the table of Telemachus, over against him, and there sat down himself.'),(13107,' And a herald  took a portion of meat and set it before him, and bread from out the basket.'),(13108,' \nNight after him Odysseus entered the palace in the likeness of a woeful and aged beggar, leaning on a staff, '),(13109,'and miserable was the raiment that he wore about his body. '),(13110,' He sat down upon the ashen threshold within the doorway,  leaning against a post of cypress wood, which of old a carpenter had skilfully planed, and made straight to the line.'),(13111,' Then Telemachus called the swineherd to him, and, taking a whole loaf from out the beautiful basket, and all the meat his hands could hold in their grasp, spoke to him saying:'),(13112,'\n  “Take, and give this mess to yon stranger, and bid him go about himself and beg of the wooers one and all.'),(13113,' Shame is no good comrade for a man that is in need.\"'),(13114,'So he spoke, and the swineherd went, when he had heard this saying, and coming up to Odysseus spoke to him winged words:'),(13115,'\n  “Stranger, Telemachus gives thee these, and bids thee go about and beg of the wooers one and all.'),(13116,' Shame, he says, is no good thing in a beggar man.”'),(13117,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said, '),(13118,'“King Zeus, grant, I pray thee, that Telemachus may be blest among men,  and may have all that his heart desires.”'),(13119,'He spoke, and took the mess in both his hands and set it down there before his feet on his miserable wallet. Then he ate so long as the minstrel sang in the halls.'),(13120,' But when he had dined and the divine minstrel was ceasing to sing, '),(13121,' the wooers broke into uproar throughout the halls;'),(13122,' but Athena drew close to the side of Odysseus, son of Laertes, and roused him to go among the wooers and gather bits of bread, and learn which of them were righteous and which lawless.'),(13123,' Yet even so she was not minded to save one of them from ruin.'),(13124,'  So he set out to beg of every man, beginning on the right, stretching out his hand on every side, as though he had been long a beggar.'),(13125,' And they pitied him and gave, and marvelled at him, asking one another who he was and whence he came.'),(13126,'\nThen among them spoke Melanthius, the goatherd:'),(13127,'  “Hear me, wooers of the glorious queen, regarding this stranger, '),(13128,' for verily I have seen him before.'),(13129,'Truly it was the swineherd that led him hither, but of the man himself I know not surely from whence he declares his birth to be.\"'),(13130,'So he spoke, and Antinous rebuked the swineherd, saying:'),(13131,'  “Notorious swineherd, why, pray, didst thou bring this man to the city?'),(13132,' Have we not vagabonds enough without him, nuisances of beggars to mar our feast?'),(13133,' Dost thou not think it enough that they gather here and devour the substance of thy master, that thou dost bid this fellow too?” '),(13134,' \n  To him then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say: '),(13135,'“Antinous, no fair words are these thou speakest, noble though thou art.'),(13136,' Who pray, of himself ever seeks out and bids a stranger from abroad, unless it be one of those that are masters of some public craft, a prophet, or a healer of ills, or a builder,  aye, or a divine minstrel, who gives delight with his song?'),(13137,'For these men are bidden all over the boundless earth.'),(13138,' Yet a beggar would no man bid to be burden to himself.'),(13139,' But thou art ever harsh above all the wooers to the slaves of Odysseus, and most of all to me; '),(13140,'yet I  care not, so long as my lady, the constant Penelope, lives in the hall, and godlike Telemachus.\"'),(13141,'Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(13142,'  “Be silent: do not, I bid thee, answer yonder man with many words, '),(13143,'for Antinous is wont ever in evil wise to provoke to anger  with harsh words, aye, and urges on the others too.”'),(13144,'With this he spoke winged words to Antinous:'),(13145,' “Antinous, truly thou carest well for me, as a father for his son, seeing that thou biddest me drive yonder stranger from the hall with a word of compulsion.'),(13146,' May the god never bring such a thing to pass.'),(13147,'but rather myself bid thee give.'),(13148,'but rather myself bid thee give.'),(13149,'but rather myself bid thee give.'),(13150,'  In this matter regard not my mother, no, nor any of the slaves that are in the house of divine Odysseus.'),(13151,' But verily far other is the thought in thy breast; '),(13152,'for thou art far more fain thyself to eat than to give to another.”'),(13153,'  Then Antinous answered him, and said: '),(13154,'“Telemachus, thou braggart, unrestrained in daring, what a thing hast thou said! '),(13155,'If all the wooers would but hand him as much as I, for full three months\' space this house would keep him at a distance.”'),(13156,'\nSo he spoke, and seized the footstool  on which he was wont to rest his shining feet as he feasted, and shewed it from beneath the table, where it lay. '),(13157,'But all the rest gave gifts, and filled the wallet with bread and bits of meat.'),(13158,' And now Odysseus was like to have gone back again to the threshold, and to have made trial of the Achaeans without cost,'),(13159,'but he paused by Antinous, and spoke to him, saying:'),(13160,'  “Friend, give me some gift; '),(13161,'thou seemest not in my eyes to be the basest of the Achaeans, but rather the noblest, for thou art like a king.'),(13162,' Therefore it is meet that thou shouldest give even a better portion of bread than the rest; '),(13163,' so would I make thy fame known all over the boundless earth.'),(13164,'For I too once dwelt in a house of my own among men,  a rich man in a wealthy house, and full often I gave gifts to a wanderer, whosoever he was and with whatsoever need he came.'),(13165,' Slaves too I had past counting, and all other things in abundance whereby men live well and are reputed wealthy. '),(13166,' \nBut Zeus, son of Cronos, brought all to naught—so, I ween, was his good pleasure—  who sent me forth with roaming pirates to go to Egypt, a far voyage, that I might meet my ruin;'),(13167,'and in the river Aegyptus I moored my curved ships.'),(13168,' Then verily I bade my trusty comrades to remain there by the ships and to guard the ships,  and I sent out scouts to go to places of outlook. '),(13169,'But my comrades, yielding to wantonness and led on by their own might, straightway set about wasting the fair fields of the men of Egypt; and they carried off the women and little children, and slew the men; '),(13170,'and the cry came quickly to the city.'),(13171,'  Then, hearing the shouting, the people came forth at break of day,'),(13172,' and the whole plain was filled with footmen and chariots and the flashing of bronze.'),(13173,' And Zeus, who hurls the thunderbolt, cast an evil panic upon my comrades, and none had courage to take his stand and face the foe; '),(13174,'for evil surrounded us on every side.'),(13175,'  So then they slew many of us with the sharp bronze, and others they led up to their city alive, to work for them perforce.'),(13176,' But they gave me to a friend who met them to take to Cyprus, even to Dmetor, son of Iasus, who ruled mightily over Cyprus; '),(13177,'and from thence am I now come hither, sore distressed.\"'),(13178,'  Then Antinous answered him, and said: '),(13179,'“What god has brought this bane hither to trouble our feast?'),(13180,' Stand off yonder in the midst, away from my table, lest thou come presently to a bitter Egypt and a bitter Cyprus, '),(13181,' seeing that thou art a bold and shameless beggar.'),(13182,' Thou comest up to every man in turn,'),(13183,'  and they give recklessly; for there is no restraint or scruple in giving freely of another\'s goods, since each man has plenty beside him.”'),(13184,' Then Odysseus of many wiles drew back, and said to him:'),(13185,'“Lo, now, it seems that thou at least hast not wits to match thy beauty.'),(13186,'  Thou wouldest not out of thine own substance give even a grain of salt to thy suppliant, thou who now, when sitting at another\'s table, hadst not the heart to take of the bread and give me aught. '),(13187,'Yet here lies plenty at thy hand.”'),(13188,'So he spoke, and Antinous waxed the more wroth at heart, and with an angry glance from beneath his brows spoke to him winged words:'),(13189,'\n  “Now verily, methinks, thou shalt no more go forth from the hall in seemly fashion, since thou dost even utter words of reviling.” '),(13190,' \nSo saying, he seized the footstool and flung it, and struck Odysseus on the base of the right shoulder, where it joins the back.'),(13191,' But he stood firm as a rock, nor did the missile of Antinous make him reel;  but he shook his head in silence, pondering evil in the deep of his heart. '),(13192,'Then back to the threshold he went and sat down, and down he laid his well-filled wallet; and he spoke among the wooers:'),(13193,' \n“Hear me, wooers of the glorious queen, that I may say what the heart in my breast bids me.'),(13194,'  Verily there is no pain of heart nor any grief when a man is smitten while fighting for his own possessions, whether for his cattle or for his white sheep;'),(13195,' but Antinous has smitten me for my wretched belly\'s sake, an accursed plague that brings many evils upon men.'),(13196,'  Ah, if for beggars there are gods and avengers, may the doom of death come upon Antinous before his marriage.\"'),(13197,'Then Antinous, son of Eupeithes, answered him:'),(13198,' “Sit still, and eat, stranger, or go elsewhere; lest the young men drag thee  by hand or foot through the house for words like these, and strip off all thy skin.”'),(13199,'So he spoke, but they all were filled with exceeding indignation, '),(13200,'and thus would one of the proud youths speak:'),(13201,'\n“Antinous, thou didst not well to strike the wretched wanderer. Doomed man that thou art, what if haply he be some god come down from heaven!'),(13202,'  Aye, and the gods in the guise of strangers from afar put on all manner of shapes, and visit the cities, beholding the violence and the righteousness of men.\"'),(13203,'So spoke the wooers, but Antinous paid no heed to their words. '),(13204,' And Telemachus nursed in his heart great grief  for the smiting, though he let no tear fall from his eyelids to the ground; but he shook his head in silence, pondering evil in the deep of his heart.'),(13205,'\nHowbeit when wise Penelope heard of the man\'s being smitten in the hall, she spoke among her handmaids, and said:'),(13206,' “Even so may thine own self be smitten by the famed archer Apollo.\"'),(13207,'  And again the housewife Eurynome said to her: '),(13208,'“Would that fulfillment might be granted to our prayers.'),(13209,' So should not one of these men come to the fair-throned Dawn.\"'),(13210,'And wise Penelope answered her:'),(13211,' “Nurse, enemies are they all, for they devise evil.'),(13212,' But Antinous more than all is like black fate. '),(13213,'Some wretched stranger roams through the house, begging alms of the men, '),(13214,'for want compels him, '),(13215,'and all the others filled his wallet and gave him gifts, but Antinous flung a footstool and smote him at the base of the right shoulder.” '),(13216,' \n  So she spoke among her handmaids, sitting in her chamber, '),(13217,' \n while goodly Odysseus was at meat.'),(13218,' Then she called to her the goodly swineherd, and said:'),(13219,'\n“Go, goodly Eumaeus, and bid the stranger come hither, that I may give him greeting, and ask him  if haply he has heard of Odysseus of the steadfast heart, or has seen him with his eyes.'),(13220,' He seems like one that has wandered far.\"'),(13221,'To her, then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer, and say: “I would, O queen, that the Achaeans would keep silence, '),(13222,'for he speaks such words as would charm thy very soul.'),(13223,'  Three nights I had him by me, and three days I kept him in my hut, '),(13224,' for to me first he came when he fled by stealth from a ship,'),(13225,'but he had not yet ended the tale of his sufferings.'),(13226,' Even as when a man gazes upon a minstrel who sings to mortals songs of longing that the gods have taught him,  and their desire to hear him has no end, whensoever he sings, '),(13227,' even so he charmed me as he sat in my hall.'),(13228,' He says that he is an ancestral friend of Odysseus, and that he dwells in Crete, where is the race of Minos.'),(13229,' From thence has he now come on this journey hither, ever suffering woes  as he wanders on and on. '),(13230,'And he insists that he has heard tidings of Odysseus, near at hand in the rich land of the Thesprotians and yet alive; '),(13231,'and he is bringing many treasures to his home.\"'),(13232,'Then wise Penelope answered him:'),(13233,' “Go, call him hither, that he may himself tell me to my face. '),(13234,' But as for these men, let them make sport as they sit in the doorway '),(13235,'or here in the house, since their hearts are merry.'),(13236,' For their own possessions lie untouched in their homes, bread and sweet wine, '),(13237,'and on these do their servants feed. But themselves throng our house day after day,  slaying our oxen, and sheep, and fat goats, and keep revel and drink the flaming wine recklessly, '),(13238,' and havoc is made of all this wealth, '),(13239,' for there is no man here such as Odysseus was to keep ruin from the house.'),(13240,' But if Odysseus should come and return to his native land,  straightway would he with his son take vengeance on these men for their violent deeds.\"'),(13241,'So she spoke, and Telemachus sneezed loudly, and all the room round about echoed wondrously.'),(13242,' And Penelope laughed, and straightway spoke to Eumaeus winged words:'),(13243,'“Go, pray, call the stranger here before me.'),(13244,'  Dost thou not note that my son has sneezed at all my words.'),(13245,' Therefore shall utter death fall upon the wooers one and all, nor shall one of them escape death and the fates.'),(13246,' And another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart.'),(13247,' If I find that he speaks all things truly,  I will clothe him in a cloak and tunic, fair raiment.”'),(13248,'So she spoke, and the swineherd went when he had heard this saying; '),(13249,'and coming up to Odysseus he spoke to him winged words:'),(13250,' \n“Sir stranger, wise Penelope calls for thee, the mother of Telemachus,'),(13251,' and her heart  bids her make enquiry about her husband, though she has suffered many woes. '),(13252,' And if she finds that thou speakest all things truly, she will clothe thee in a cloak and tunic, which thou needest most of all.'),(13253,' As for thy food, thou shalt beg it through the land, and feed thy belly, '),(13254,'and whoso will shall give it thee.” '),(13255,' \n  Then the much-enduring goodly Odysseus answered him: '),(13256,' “Eumaeus, soon will I tell all the truth to the daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope.'),(13257,' For well do I know of Odysseus, and in common have we borne affliction.'),(13258,' But I have fear of this throng of harsh wooers,  whose wantonness and violence reach the iron heaven.'),(13259,' For even now, when, as I was going through the hall doing no evil, this man struck me and hurt me, neither Telemachus nor any other did aught to ward off the blow.'),(13260,' Wherefore now bid Penelope  to wait in the halls, eager though she be, till set of sun; '),(13261,'and then let her ask me of her husband regarding the day of his return, giving me a seat nearer the fire, '),(13262,'for lo, the raiment that I wear is mean, '),(13263,' and this thou knowest of thyself, for to thee first did I make my prayer.\"'),(13264,'So he spoke, and the swineherd went when he had heard this saying.'),(13265,'  And as he passed over the threshold Penelope said to him:'),(13266,' What does the wanderer mean by this?'),(13267,' What does the wanderer mean by this?'),(13268,' Does he fear some one beyond measure, or does he idly feel ashamed in the house?'),(13269,' \'Tis ill for a beggar to feel shame.\"'),(13270,'To her, then, swineherd Eumaeus, didst thou make answer and say:'),(13271,'  “He speaks rightly, even as any other man would deem, in seeking to shun the insolence of overweening men.'),(13272,' But he bids thee to wait till set of sun.'),(13273,' And for thyself, too, it is far more seemly, O queen, to speak to the stranger alone, and to hear his words.\"'),(13274,'  Then wise Penelope answered him: '),(13275,' he divines how it may be.'),(13276,' he divines how it may be.'),(13277,'There are no mortal men, methinks, who in wantonness devise such wicked folly as these.\"'),(13278,'So she spoke, and the goodly swineherd departed  into the throng of the wooers when he had told her all. '),(13279,'And straightway he spoke winged words to Telemachus, holding his head close to him that the others might not hear:'),(13280,'\n“Friend, I am going forth to guard the swine and all things there, thy livelihood and mine; '),(13281,' but have thou charge of all things here.'),(13282,'  Thine own self do thou keep safe first of all, and let thy mind beware lest some ill befall thee, '),(13283,'for many of the Achaeans are devising evil, whom may Zeus utterly destroy before harm fall on us.\"'),(13284,'Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(13285,'go thy way when thou hast supped.'),(13286,'go thy way when thou hast supped.'),(13287,'  And in the morning do thou come and bring goodly victims.'),(13288,' But all matters here shall be a care to me and to the immortals.\"'),(13289,'So he spoke, and the swineherd sat down again on the polished chair. But when he had satisfied his heart with meat and drink, he went his way to the swine, and left the courts and the hall  full of banqueters.'),(13290,' And they were making merry with dance and song,'),(13291,' for evening had now come on.'),(13292,' Now there came up a public beggar who was wont to beg through the town of Ithaca, and was known for his greedy belly, eating and drinking without end.'),(13293,' No strength had he nor might, but in bulk was big indeed to look upon.'),(13294,'  Arnaeus was his name, '),(13295,'for this name his honored mother had given him at his birth; '),(13296,'but Irus all the young men called him, because he used to run on errands when anyone bade him.'),(13297,' He came now, and was for driving Odysseus from his own house; and he began to revile him, and spoke winged words:'),(13298,' “Give way, old man, from the doorway, lest soon thou be even dragged out by the foot.'),(13299,'Dost thou not see that all men are winking at me, and bidding me drag thee?'),(13300,'Yet for myself, I am ashamed to do it. '),(13301,' Nay, up with thee, lest our quarrel even come to blows.\"'),(13302,'Then with an angry glance from beneath his brows Odysseus of many wiles answered him:'),(13303,'  “Good fellow, I harm thee not in deed or word, nor do I begrudge that any man should give thee, though the portion he took up were a large one.'),(13304,' This threshold will hold us both, and thou hast no need to be jealous for the goods of other folk.'),(13305,' Thou seemest to me to be a vagrant, even as I am; and as for happy fortune, it is the gods that are like to give us that.'),(13306,'  But with thy fists do not provoke me overmuch, lest thou anger me, and, old man though I am, I befoul thy breast and lips with blood.'),(13307,' So should I have the greater peace tomorrow,'),(13308,' for I deem not that thou shalt return a second time to the hall of Odysseus, son of Laertes.\"'),(13309,'  Then, waxing wroth, the vagrant Irus said to him: '),(13310,'“Now see how glibly the filthy wretch talks, like an old kitchen-wife.'),(13311,' But I will devise evil for him, smiting him left and right, and will scatter on the ground all the teeth from his jaws, as though he were a swine wasting the corn.'),(13312,'  Gird thyself now, that these men, too, may all know our fighting.'),(13313,'But how couldst thou fight with a younger man?\"'),(13314,' Thus on the polished threshold before the lofty doors they stirred one another\'s rage right heartily.'),(13315,' And the strong and mighty Antinous heard the two,  and, breaking into a merry laugh, he spoke among the wooers:'),(13316,'\n“Friends, never before has such a thing come to pass, that a god has brought sport like this to this house.'),(13317,' Yon stranger and Irus are provoking one another to blows.'),(13318,' Come, let us quickly set them on.”'),(13319,'  So he spoke, and they all sprang up laughing and gathered about the tattered beggars.'),(13320,' And Antinous, son of Eupeithes, spoke among them, and said:'),(13321,'\n“Hear me, ye proud wooers, that I may say somewhat.'),(13322,' Here at the fire are goats\' paunches lying, which  we set there for supper, when we had filled them with fat and blood.'),(13323,'Now whichever of the two wins and proves himself the better man, let him rise and choose for himself which one of these he will.'),(13324,' And furthermore he shall always feast with us, nor will we suffer any other beggar to join our company and beg of us.” '),(13325,' \n  So spoke Antinous, and his word was pleasing to them. '),(13326,' Then with crafty mind Odysseus of many wiles spoke among them:'),(13327,'\n“Friends, in no wise may an old man that is overcome with woe fight with a younger.'),(13328,' Howbeit my belly, that worker of evil, urges me on, that I may be overcome by his blows.'),(13329,'  But come now, do you all swear to me a mighty oath, to the end that no man, doing a favour to Irus, may deal me a foul blow with heavy hand, and so by violence subdue me to this fellow.\"'),(13330,'So he spoke, and they all gave the oath not to smite him, even as he bade.'),(13331,' But when they had sworn and made an end of the oath,  among them spoke again the strong and mighty Telemachus:'),(13332,'“Stranger, if thy heart and thy proud spirit bid thee beat off this fellow, then fear not thou any man of all the Achaeans, for whoso strikes thee shall have to fight with more than thou.'),(13333,' Thy host am I, and the princes assent hereto,  Antinous and Eurymachus, men of prudence both.”'),(13334,'So he spoke, and they all praised his words.'),(13335,' But Odysseus girded his rags about his loins and showed his thighs, comely and great, and his broad shoulders came to view, and his chest and mighty arms.'),(13336,' And Athena  drew nigh and made greater the limbs of the shepherd of the people. '),(13337,' Then all the wooers marvelled exceedingly, '),(13338,' and thus would one speak with a glance at his neighbor:'),(13339,'“Right soon shall Irus, un-Irused, have a bane of his own bringing, such a thigh does yon old man show from beneath his rags.”'),(13340,'  So they spoke, and the mind of Irus was miserably shaken; '),(13341,' yet even so the serving men girded him, and led him out perforce all filled with dread, '),(13342,'and his flesh trembled on his limbs. '),(13343,'Then Antinous rated him and spoke, and addressed him:'),(13344,'“Better were it now, thou braggart, that thou wert not living, nor hadst ever been born,  if thou quailest and art so terribly afraid of this fellow—a man that is old and overcome by the woe that has come upon him.'),(13345,' But I will speak out to thee, and this word shall verily be brought to pass. '),(13346,'If this fellow conquers thee and proves the better man, I will fling thee into a black ship and send thee to the mainland  to King Echetus, the maimer of all men, who will cut off thy nose and ears with the pitiless bronze, and will draw forth thy vitals and give them raw to dogs to rend.” '),(13347,' \nSo he spoke, and thereat yet greater trembling seized the other\'s limbs, '),(13348,'and both men put up their hands.'),(13349,'and both men put up their hands.'),(13350,'  Then the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus was divided in mind whether he should strike him so that life should leave him even there as he fell, or whether he should deal him a light blow and stretch him on the earth.'),(13351,' And, as he pondered, this seemed to him the better course, to deal him a light blow, that the Achaeans might not take note of him.'),(13352,'  Then verily, when they had put up their hands, Irus let drive at the right shoulder, but Odysseus smote him on the neck beneath the ear and crushed in the bones, '),(13353,' and straightway the red blood ran forth from his mouth, and down he fell in the dust with a moan, and he gnashed his teeth, kicking the ground with his feet. '),(13354,' But the lordly wooers  raised their hands, and were like to die with laughter.'),(13355,' Then Odysseus seized him by the foot, and dragged him forth through the doorway until he came to the court and the gates of the portico. '),(13356,'And he set him down and leaned him against the wall of the court, '),(13357,'and thrust his staff into his hand and spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(13358,'\n  “Sit there now, and scare off swine and dogs, and do not thou be lord of strangers and beggars, miserable that thou art, lest haply thou meet with some worse thing to profit withal.\"'),(13359,'He spoke, and flung about his shoulders his miserable wallet, full of holes, '),(13360,'and slung by a twisted cord.'),(13361,'  Then back to the threshold he went and sat down; '),(13362,'and the wooers went within, laughing merrily, and they greeted him, saying:'),(13363,'\n“May Zeus grant thee, stranger, and the other immortal gods what thou desirest most, and the dearest wish of thy heart, seeing that thou hast made this insatiate fellow to cease from begging  in the land. '),(13364,'For soon shall we take him to the mainland to King Echetus, the maimer of all men.\"'),(13365,'So they spoke, and goodly Odysseus was glad at the word of omen.'),(13366,' And Antinous set before him the great paunch, filled with fat and blood, '),(13367,'and Amphinomus  took up two loaves from the basket and set them before him, and pledged him in a cup of gold, and said:'),(13368,'\n“Hail, Sir stranger; may happy fortune be thine in time to come, '),(13369,'though now thou art the thrall of many sorrows.” '),(13370,' \nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said: '),(13371,'  “Amphinomus, verily thou seemest to me to be a man of prudence; '),(13372,' and such a man, too, was thy father, for I have heard of his fair fame, that Nisus of Dulichium was a brave man and a wealthy.'),(13373,' From him, they say, thou art sprung, and thou seemest a man soft of speech.'),(13374,' Wherefore I will tell thee, and do thou give heed and hearken.'),(13375,'  Nothing feebler does earth nurture than man, of all things that on earth are breathing and moving.'),(13376,' For he thinks that he will never suffer evil in time to come, so long as the gods give him prosperity and his knees are quick; '),(13377,' but when again the blessed gods decree him sorrow,  this too he bears in sore despite with steadfast heart; '),(13378,'for the spirit of men upon the earth is even such as the day which the father of gods and men brings upon them.'),(13379,' For I, too, was once like to be prosperous among men, but many deeds of wantonness I wrought, yielding to my might and my strength,  and trusting in my father and my brethren.'),(13380,' Wherefore let no man soever be lawless at any time, but let him keep in silence whatever gifts the gods give. '),(13381,'Aye, for I see the wooers devising wantonness, wasting the wealth and dishonoring the wife  of a man who, I tell thee, will not long be away from his friends and his native land; '),(13382,' nay, he is very near.'),(13383,'But may some god lead thee forth hence to thy home, and mayest thou not meet him when he comes home to his dear native land.'),(13384,' For not without bloodshed, methinks,  will the wooers and he part one from the other when once he comes beneath his roof.”'),(13385,'So he spoke, and pouring a libation, drank of the honey-sweet wine, and then gave back the cup into the hands of the marshaller of the people.'),(13386,' But Amphinomus went through the hall with a heavy heart, bowing his head; '),(13387,'for his spirit boded bane.'),(13388,'  Yet even so he did not escape his fate,'),(13389,' but him, too, did Athena set in bonds so that he might be slain outright at the hands of Telemachus and by his spear.'),(13390,' So he sat down again on the chair from which he had risen.'),(13391,'Then the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, put it in the heart of the daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope,  to show herself to the wooers, that she might set their hearts a-flutter and win greater honor from her husband and her son than heretofore.'),(13392,' Then she laughed a meaningless laugh and spoke, and addressed the nurse:'),(13393,'\n“Eurynome, my heart longs, though it has never longed before,  to show myself to the wooers, hateful though they are. '),(13394,' Also I would say a word to my son that will be for his profit, namely, that he should not consort ever with the overweening wooers, who speak him fair but have evil plans thereafter.” '),(13395,' \nThen the housewife, Eurynome, spoke to her and said:'),(13396,'   “Aye, verily, child, all this hast thou spoken aright. '),(13397,'Go, then, reveal thy word to thy son and hide it not; but first wash thy body and anoint thy face, '),(13398,'and go not as thou art with both cheeks stained with tears. Go, for it is ill to grieve ever without ceasing.'),(13399,'  For now, behold, thy son is of such an age, and it has been thy dearest prayer to the immortals to see him a bearded man.\"'),(13400,'Then wise Penelope answered her again:'),(13401,' “Eurynome, beguile me not thus in thy love to wash my body and anoint me with oil.'),(13402,'  All beauty of mine have the gods, that hold Olympus, destroyed since the day when my lord departed in the hollow ships.'),(13403,' But bid Autonoe and Hippodameia come to me, that they may stand by my side in the hall. '),(13404,'for I am ashamed.”'),(13405,'for I am ashamed.”'),(13406,'  So she spoke, and the old woman went forth through the chamber to bear tidings to the women, and bid them come.'),(13407,' Then again the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, took other counsel.'),(13408,'On the daughter of Icarius she shed sweet sleep, and she leaned back and slept  there on her couch, and all her joints were relaxed. '),(13409,' And meanwhile the fair goddess was giving her immortal gifts, that the Achaeans might marvel at her.'),(13410,' With balm she first made fair her beautiful face, with balm ambrosial, such as that wherewith Cytherea, of the fair crown, anoints herself when she goes into the lovely dance of the Graces; '),(13411,' and she made her taller, too, and statelier to behold, and made her whiter than new-sawn ivory.'),(13412,' Now when she had done this the fair goddess departed, and the white-armed handmaids came forth from the chamber and drew near with sound of talking.'),(13413,' Then sweet sleep released Penelope,  and she rubbed her cheeks with her hands, and said:'),(13414,' “Ah, in my utter wretchedness soft slumber enfolded me.'),(13415,'\n Would that pure Artemis would even now give so soft a death, that I might no more waste my life away with sorrow at heart, longing for  the manifold excellence of my dear husband, for that he was pre-eminent among the Achaeans.”'),(13416,' \nSo saying, she went down from the bright upper chamber, not alone, '),(13417,'for two handmaids attended her.'),(13418,' Now when the fair lady reached the wooers she stood by the doorpost of the well-built hall,  holding before her face her shining veil; '),(13419,'and a faithful handmaid stood on either side of her.'),(13420,' Straightway then the knees of the wooers were loosened and their hearts enchanted with love, and they all prayed, each that he might lie by her side.'),(13421,' But she spoke to Telemachus, her dear son:'),(13422,'  “Telemachus, thy mind and thy thoughts are no longer steadfast as heretofore.'),(13423,'When thou wast but a child thou wast wont to revolve in thy mind thoughts more cunning;'),(13424,'  but now that thou art grown and hast reached the bounds of manhood, and wouldest be called a rich man\'s son by one who looked only to thy stature and thy comeliness, being himself a stranger from afar,  thy mind and thy thoughts are no longer right as before.'),(13425,' What a thing is this that has been done in these halls, that thou hast suffered yon stranger to be so maltreated!'),(13426,' How now, if the stranger, while sitting thus in our house, should come to some harm through grievous mishandling?'),(13427,' On thee, then, would fall shame and disgrace among men.\"'),(13428,' Then wise Telemachus answered her:'),(13429,' “My mother, in this matter I take it not ill that thou art filled with anger.'),(13430,' Yet of myself I know in my heart and understand each thing, the good and the evil, '),(13431,'whereas heretofore I was but a child.'),(13432,'  But I am not able to plan all things wisely,'),(13433,' for these men here thwart my will, keeping by me, one on this side and one on that, with evil purpose, and I have none to help me.'),(13434,' Howbeit, I can tell thee, this battle between the stranger and Irus fell not out according to the mind of the wooers, but the stranger proved the better man.'),(13435,'  I would, O father Zeus, and Athena, and Apollo, that even now the wooers were thus subdued in our halls, and were hanging their heads, some in the court and some within the hall, and that each man\'s limbs were loosened, even as Irus now sits yonder by the gate of the court,  hanging his head like a drunken man, and cannot stand erect upon his feet, or go home to whatsoever place he is wont to go, because his limbs are loosened.\"'),(13436,'Thus they spoke to one another.'),(13437,' But Eurymachus addressed Penelope, and said:'),(13438,'\n  “Daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope, if all the Achaeans throughout Iasian Argos could see thee, even more wooers would be feasting in your halls from to-morrow on, for thou excellest all women in comeliness and stature, and in the wise heart within thee.” '),(13439,' \n  Then wise Penelope answered him:'),(13440,'“Eurymachus, all excellence of mine, both of beauty and of form, the immortals destroyed on the day when the Argives embarked for Ilios, and with them went my husband Odysseus.'),(13441,' If he might but come and watch over this life of mine,  greater would be my fame and fairer.'),(13442,' so many woes has some god brought upon me.'),(13443,' so many woes has some god brought upon me.'),(13444,' Verily, when he went forth and left his native land, he clasped my right hand by the wrist, and said:'),(13445,'\n“‘Wife, I deem not that the well-greaved Achaeans  will all return from Troy safe and unscathed, '),(13446,' for the Trojans, men say, are men of war, hurlers of the spear, and drawers of the bow, and drivers of swift horses, such as most quickly decide the great strife of equal war.'),(13447,'  Therefore I know not whether the god will bring me back, or whether I shall be cut off there in the land of Troy:'),(13448,' so have thou charge of all things here.'),(13449,' Be mindful of my father and my mother in the halls even as thou art now, or yet more, while I am far away.'),(13450,' But when thou shalt see my son a bearded man,  wed whom thou wilt, and leave thy house.’'),(13451,' and now all this is being brought to pass.'),(13452,' and now all this is being brought to pass.'),(13453,'The night shall come when a hateful marriage shall fall to the lot of me accursed, whose happiness Zeus has taken away.'),(13454,' But herein has bitter grief come upon my heart and soul,'),(13455,' for such as yours was never the way of wooers heretofore. '),(13456,'They who are fain to woo a lady of worth and the daughter of a rich man and vie with one another, these bring of themselves cattle and goodly flocks, a banquet for the friends of the bride, and give to her glorious gifts; '),(13457,'  but they do not devour the livelihood of another without atonement.”'),(13458,'So she spoke, and the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus was glad, because she drew from them gifts, and beguiled their souls with gentle words, but her mind was set on other things.'),(13459,'Then Antinous, son of Eupeithes, spoke to her again, and said:  “Daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope, as for gifts, if any man of the Achaeans is minded to bring them hither, do thou take them; '),(13460,'for it is not well to refuse a gift.'),(13461,' But for us, we will go neither to our lands nor elsewhither, until thou weddest him whosoever is best of the Achaeans.” '),(13462,' \n  So spoke Antinous, and his word was pleasing to them, '),(13463,'and each man sent forth a herald to bring his gifts.'),(13464,' For Antinous he brought a large and beautiful robe, richly broidered, '),(13465,'and in it were golden brooches, twelve in all, fitted with curved clasps.'),(13466,' And a chain did another straightway bring to Eurymachus, '),(13467,'one cunningly wrought of gold, strung with amber beads, bright as the sun.'),(13468,' A pair of earrings his squires brought to Eurydamas, with three clustering drops, '),(13469,' and great grace shone therefrom.'),(13470,' And out of the house of lord Peisander, son of Polyctor,  his squire brought a necklace, a jewel exceeding fair. '),(13471,'So of the Achaeans one brought one fair gift and one another.'),(13472,' But she thereafter, the fair lady, went up to her upper chamber, and her handmaids bare for her the beautiful gifts.\nBut the wooers  turned to dance and gladsome song, and made them merry, and waited for evening to come on. '),(13473,'And as they made merry dark evening came upon them.'),(13474,' Presently they set up three braziers in the hall to give them light,'),(13475,'and round about them placed dry faggots, long since seasoned and hard, and newly split with the axe;  and in the spaces between they set torches;'),(13476,'and in turn the handmaids of Odysseus, of the steadfast heart, kindled the flame.'),(13477,' Then Zeus-born Odysseus, of many wiles, himself spoke among the maids, and said:'),(13478,'\n“Maidens of Odysseus, that has long been gone, go to the chambers where your honored queen abides, '),(13479,'\n and twist the yarn by her side, and make glad her heart, as you sit in the chamber, or card the wool with your hands; '),(13480,' but I will give light to all these men.'),(13481,' For if they wish to wait for fair-throned Dawn, they shall in no wise outdo me. '),(13482,'I am one that can endure much.”'),(13483,'  So he spoke, and the maids broke into a laugh, and glanced at one another. '),(13484,' And fair-cheeked Melantho rated him shamefully, Melantho, whom Dolius begot, but whom Penelope had reared and cherished as her own child, and gave her playthings to her heart\'s desire.'),(13485,' Yet even so she had at heart no sorrow for Penelope,  but she loved Eurymachus and was wont to lie with him. '),(13486,'She then rated Odysseus with reviling words:'),(13487,'“Wretched stranger, thou art but a crack-brained fellow, unwilling to go to a smithy to sleep, or to a common lodge, but pratest here continually,  unabashed in the company of many lords, and hast no fear at heart. '),(13488,' Surely wine has mastered thy wits, or else thy mind is ever thus, '),(13489,'that thou dost babble idly.'),(13490,' Art thou beside thyself because thou hast beaten that vagrant Irus?'),(13491,'Beware, lest presently another better than Irus shall rise up against thee  to beat thee about the head with heavy hands, and befoul thee with streams of blood, and send thee forth from the house.” '),(13492,' \nThen with an angry glance from beneath his brows Odysseus of many wiles answered her:'),(13493,' “Presently shall I go yonder, thou shameless thing, and tell Telemachus, since thou speakest thus, that on the spot he may cut thee limb from limb.”'),(13494,'\n  So he spoke, and with his words scattered the women, '),(13495,' who fled through the hall, and the limbs of each were loosened beneath her in terror, '),(13496,'for they thought that he spoke truth.'),(13497,' But Odysseus took his stand by the burning braziers to give light, and looked upon all the men.'),(13498,'  Yet other things was the heart within him pondering—things that were not to be unfulfilled.'),(13499,'But Athena would in no wise suffer the proud wooers to abstain from bitter outrage, that pain might sink yet deeper into the heart of Odysseus, son of Laertes.'),(13500,' So among them Eurymachus, son of Polybus, began to speak,  jeering at Odysseus, '),(13501,' and making mirth for his companions:'),(13502,'“Hear me, wooers of the glorious queen, that I may say what the heart in my breast bids me.'),(13503,' Not without the will of the gods has this man come to the palace of Odysseus; '),(13504,'in any case there is a glare of torches from him—  from his head, for there is no hair on it, no, not a trace.”'),(13505,'Therewith he called to Odysseus, sacker of cities:'),(13506,' “Stranger, wouldest thou have a mind to serve for hire, if I should take thee into service on an outlying farm—thy pay shall be assured thee—gathering stones for walls, and planting tall trees?'),(13507,'  There would I provide thee with food the year through, and clothe thee with raiment and give thee sandals for thy feet.'),(13508,' But since thou hast learned only deeds of evil, thou wilt not care to busy thyself with work, but art minded rather to go skulking through the land, that thou mayest have wherewith to feed thy insatiate belly.” '),(13509,' \n  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said: '),(13510,' “Eurymachus, I would that we two might have a match in working in the season of spring, when the long days come, at mowing the grass, I with a curved scythe in my hands and thou with another like it,  and that the grass might be in plenty that so we might test our work, fasting till late evening.'),(13511,' Or I would again that there were oxen to drive—the best there are, tawny and large, both well fed with grass, of like age and like power to bear the yoke, tireless in strength—and that there were a field of four acres, and the soil should yield before the plough:'),(13512,'  then shouldest thou see me, whether or no I could cut a straight furrow to the end.'),(13513,' Or I would again that this day the son of Cronos might bring war upon us from whence he would, and I had a shield and two spears and a helmet all of bronze, that fitted well my temples: then shouldest thou see me mingling amid the foremost fighters,  and wouldest not prate, taunting me with this belly of mine.'),(13514,' But right insolent art thou, and thy heart is cruel,'),(13515,' and forsooth thou thinkest thyself to be some great man and mighty, because thou consortest with few men and weak. '),(13516,' If but Odysseus might return, and come to his native land,  soon would yonder doors, right wide though they are, prove all too narrow for thee in thy flight out through the doorway.\"'),(13517,'So he spoke, and Eurymachus waxed the more wroth at heart, and with an angry glance from beneath his brows spoke to him winged words:'),(13518,'“Wretch, presently will I work thee evil, that thou pratest thus,  unabashed in the presence of many lords, and hast no fear at heart.'),(13519,' Surely wine has mastered thy wits, or else thy mind is ever thus, '),(13520,' that thou dost babble idly.'),(13521,'Art thou beside thyself because thou hast beaten that vagrant Irus?” '),(13522,' \nSo saying, he seized a footstool,'),(13523,'but Odysseus  sat down at the knees of Amphinomus of Dulichium, in fear of Eurymachus.'),(13524,' And so Eurymachus struck a cup-bearer on the right hand, '),(13525,'and the wine-jug fell to the ground with a clang, and the bearer groaned, and fell backwards in the dust.'),(13526,' Then the wooers broke into uproar throughout the shadowy halls,  and thus would one man speak with a glance at his neighbor: '),(13527,'“Would that yon stranger had perished elsewhere on his wanderings or ever he came hither; '),(13528,'then should he never have brought among us all this tumult.'),(13529,' But now we are brawling about beggars, nor shall there be any joy in our rich feast, since worse things prevail.”'),(13530,'  Then among them spoke the strong and mighty Telemachus: “Strange sirs, ye are mad, and no longer hide that ye have eaten and drunk;'),(13531,'some god surely is moving you.'),(13532,' Nay, now that you have well feasted, go to your homes and take your rest, when your spirits bid you.'),(13533,' Yet do I drive no man forth.”'),(13534,'  So he spoke, and they all bit their lips, and marvelled at Telemachus, that he spoke boldly.'),(13535,' But Amphinomus spoke, and addressed them—he was son of the noble prince Nisus, son of Aretias:'),(13536,'\n“Friends, no man in answer to what has been fairly spoken  would wax wroth and make reply with wrangling words. '),(13537,'Abuse not any more this stranger nor any one of the slaves that are in the house of divine Odysseus.'),(13538,' Nay, come, let the bearer pour drops for libation in the cups, that we may pour libations, and go home to take our rest.'),(13539,'As for this stranger,  let us leave him in the halls of Odysseus to be cared for by Telemachus;'),(13540,' for to his house has he come.”'),(13541,'So said he, and the words that he spoke were pleasing to all.'),(13542,' Then a bowl was mixed for them by the lord Mulius, a herald from Dulichium, '),(13543,'who was squire to Amphinomus.'),(13544,'  And he served out to all, coming up to each in turn;'),(13545,' and they made libations to the blessed gods, and drank the honey-sweet wine.'),(13546,' Then when they had made libations and had drunk to their heart\'s content, they went their way, each man to his own house, to take their rest.'),(13547,' So goodly Odysseus was left behind in the hall, planning with Athena\'s aid the slaying of the wooers,'),(13548,'and he straightway spoke winged words to Telemachus:'),(13549,'\n“Telemachus, the weapons of war thou must needs lay away within  one and all, '),(13550,'and when the wooers miss them and question thee, thou must beguile them with gentle words, saying:'),(13551,' ‘Out of the smoke have I laid them, since they are no longer like those which of old Odysseus left behind him, when he went forth to Troy, but are all befouled, so far as the breath of fire has reached them.'),(13552,'  And furthermore this greater fear has a god put in my heart, lest haply, when heated with wine, you may set a quarrel afoot among you, and wound one another, and so bring shame on your feast and on your wooing.'),(13553,' For of itself does the iron draw a man to it.’”'),(13554,' So he spoke, and Telemachus hearkened to his dear father,  and calling forth the nurse Eurycleia, said to her:'),(13555,'“Nurse, come now, I bid thee, shut up the women in their rooms, while I lay away in the store-room the weapons of my father, the goodly weapons which all uncared-for the smoke bedims in the hall since my father went forth, '),(13556,'and I was still a child.'),(13557,'  But now I am minded to lay them away, where the breath of the fire will not come upon them.\"'),(13558,'Then the dear nurse Eurycleia answered him:'),(13559,' “Aye, child, I would thou mightest ever take thought to care for the house and guard all its wealth.'),(13560,' But come, who then shall fetch a light and bear it for thee, '),(13561,' since thou wouldest not suffer the maids, who might have given light, to go before thee?\"'),(13562,'Then wise Telemachus answered her;'),(13563,' “This stranger here; '),(13564,' “This stranger here; for I will suffer no man to be idle who touches my portion of meal, even though he has come from afar.\"'),(13565,' So he spoke, but her word remained unwinged,'),(13566,' and she locked the doors of the stately hall.'),(13567,'  Then the two sprang up, Odysseus and his glorious son, and set about bearing within the helmets and the bossy shields and the sharp-pointed spears;'),(13568,'and before them Pallas Athena, bearing a golden lamp, made a most beauteous light.'),(13569,'  Then Telemachus suddenly spoke to his father, and said:'),(13570,'“Father, verily this is a great marvel that my eyes behold;'),(13571,'\n certainly the walls of the house and the fair beams and cross-beams of fir and the pillars that reach on high, glow in my eyes as with the light of blazing fire.'),(13572,'  Surely some god is within, one of those who hold broad heaven.”'),(13573,'\nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(13574,' “Hush, check thy thought, and ask no question; '),(13575,'this, I tell thee, is the way of the gods that hold Olympus.'),(13576,' But do thou go and take thy rest and I will remain behind here,  that I may stir yet more the minds of the maids and of thy mother;'),(13577,' and she with weeping shall ask me of each thing separately.” '),(13578,' \nSo he spoke, and Telemachus went forth through the hall by the light of blazing torches to go to his chamber to lie down, where he had heretofore been wont to rest, when sweet sleep came upon him.'),(13579,'  There now too he lay down and waited for the bright Dawn.'),(13580,' But goodly Odysseus was left behind in the hall, planning with Athena\'s aid the slaying of the wooers.'),(13581,'\nThen wise Penelope came forth from her chamber like unto Artemis or golden Aphrodite,'),(13582,' and for her they set by the fire, where she was wont to sit, a chair inlaid with spirals of ivory and silver, '),(13583,'which of old the craftsman Icmalius had made, and had set beneath it a foot-stool for the feet, that was part of the chair, and upon it a great fleece was wont to be laid.'),(13584,' On this then wise Penelope sat down, '),(13585,' and the white-armed maids came forth from the women\'s hall.'),(13586,' These began to take away the abundant food, the tables, and the cups from which the lordly men had been drinking, '),(13587,' and they cast the embers from the braziers on to the floor, and piled upon the braziers fresh logs in abundance, to give light and warmth.'),(13588,'\n  But Melantho began again a second time to rate Odysseus, saying: '),(13589,'“Stranger, wilt thou even now still be a plague to us through the night, roaming through the house, and wilt thou spy upon the women?'),(13590,' Nay, get thee forth, thou wretch, and be content with thy supper,'),(13591,'or straightway shalt thou even be smitten with a torch, and so go forth.\"'),(13592,'  Then with an angry glance from beneath his brows Odysseus of many wiles answered her:'),(13593,' “Good woman, why, pray, dost thou thus assail me with angry heart?'),(13594,'Is it because I am foul and wear mean raiment on my body, and beg through the land?'),(13595,'  Aye, for necessity compels me. '),(13596,'Of such sort are beggars and vagabond folk.  For I too once dwelt in a house of my own among men, a rich man in a wealthy house, and full often I gave gifts to a wanderer, whosoever he was and with whatsoever need he came.'),(13597,' Slaves too I had past counting and all other things in abundance whereby men live well and are reputed wealthy. '),(13598,' so, I ween, was his good pleasure.'),(13599,' so, I ween, was his good pleasure.'),(13600,' Wherefore, woman, beware lest thou too some day lose all the glory whereby thou now hast excellence among the handmaids;'),(13601,' lest perchance thy mistress wax wroth and be angry with thee, or Odysseus come home; '),(13602,'for there is yet room for hope.'),(13603,'  But if, even as it seems, he is dead, and is no more to return, yet now is his son by the favour of Apollo such as he was—even Telemachus.'),(13604,' Him it escapes not if any of the women in the halls work wantonness; for he is no longer the child he was.” '),(13605,' \nSo he spoke, and wise Penelope heard him;  and she rebuked the handmaid and spoke, and addressed her:'),(13606,'“Be sure, thou bold and shameless thing, that thy outrageous deed is in no wise hid from me, and with thine own head shalt thou wipe out its stain.'),(13607,' Full well didst thou know, for thou hast heard it from my own lips, that I was minded  to question the stranger in my halls concerning my husband; for I am sore distressed.”'),(13608,'With this she spoke also to the housewife Eurynome, and said:'),(13609,' “Eurynome, bring hither a chair and a fleece upon it, that the stranger may sit down and tell his tale, and listen to me; '),(13610,'for I am fain to ask him of all things.” '),(13611,'  So she spoke, and Eurynome speedily brought a polished chair and set it in place, and on it cast a fleece.'),(13612,' Then the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus sat down upon it, '),(13613,'and the wise Penelope spoke first, and said:'),(13614,'\n“Stranger, this question will I myself ask thee first.'),(13615,' Where is thy city, and where thy parents?”'),(13616,' Where is thy city, and where thy parents?”'),(13617,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said:'),(13618,' “Lady, no one of mortals upon the boundless earth could find fault with thee, '),(13619,' for thy fame goes up to the broad heaven, as does the fame of some blameless king, who with the fear of the gods in his heart,  is lord over many mighty men, upholding justice; and the black earth bears wheat and barley, and the trees are laden with fruit, the flocks bring forth young unceasingly, and the sea yields fish, all from his good leading; and the people prosper under him.'),(13620,'  Wherefore question me now in thy house of all things else, but ask not concerning my race and my native land, lest thou fill my heart the more with pains, as I think thereon; for I am a man of many sorrows.'),(13621,' Moreover it is not fitting  that I should sit weeping and wailing in another\'s house, for it is ill to grieve ever without ceasing. '),(13622,'I would not that one of thy maidens or thine own self be vexed with me, and say that I swim in tears because my mind is heavy with wine.\"'),(13623,'Then wise Penelope answered him: '),(13624,'“Stranger, all excellence of mine, both of beauty and of form,  the immortals destroyed on the day when the Argives embarked for Ilios, and with them went my husband, Odysseus. If he might but come, and watch over this life of mine, greater would be my fame and fairer.'),(13625,' so many woes has some god brought upon me.'),(13626,' so many woes has some god brought upon me.'),(13627,'  For all the princes who hold sway over the islands—Dulichium and Same and wooded Zacynthus—and those who dwell around in clear-seen Ithaca itself, all these woo me against my will, and lay waste my house.'),(13628,' Wherefore I pay no heed to strangers or to suppliants  or in any wise to heralds, whose trade is a public one; '),(13629,'but in longing for Odysseus I waste my heart away.'),(13630,' and I wind a skein of wiles. '),(13631,' and I wind a skein of wiles. '),(13632,'First some god breathed the thought in my heart to set up a great web in my halls and fall to weaving a robe—  fine of thread was the web and very wide; '),(13633,'and I straightway spoke among them:'),(13634,'“‘Young men, my wooers, since goodly Odysseus is dead, be patient, though eager for my marriage, until I finish this robe—I would not that my spinning should come to naught—a shroud for the lord Laertes against the time when  the fell fate of grievous death shall strike him down; '),(13635,' lest any one of the Achaean women in the land should be wroth with me, if he were to lie without a shroud, who had won great possessions.’ '),(13636,' \n“So I spoke, and their proud hearts consented.'),(13637,' Then day by day I would weave at the great web,  but by night would unravel it, when I had let place torches by me. '),(13638,'Thus for three years I kept the Achaeans from knowing, and beguiled them; '),(13639,' but when the fourth year came, as the seasons rolled on, as the months waned, and the many days were brought in their course, then verily by the help of my maidens, shameless creatures and reckless,  they came upon me and caught me, and upbraided me loudly. '),(13640,'So I finished the web against my will perforce.'),(13641,' And now I can neither escape the marriage nor devise any counsel more, '),(13642,' and my parents are pressing me to marry, and my son frets, while these men devour his livelihood,  as he takes note of it all;'),(13643,'for by now he is a man, and fully able to care for a household to which Zeus grants honor.'),(13644,' Yet even so tell me of thy stock from whence thou art; '),(13645,' for thou art not sprung from an oak of ancient story, or from a stone.\"'),(13646,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said:'),(13647,'  “Honored wife of Odysseus, son of Laertes, wilt thou never cease to ask me of my lineage?'),(13648,' Well, I will tell thee; '),(13649,'though verily thou wilt give me over to pains yet more than those by which I am now held in thrall; '),(13650,'for so it ever is, when a man has been far from his country as long as I have now,  wandering through the many cities of men in sore distress.'),(13651,'Yet even so will I tell thee what thou dost ask and enquire.'),(13652,' There is a land called Crete, in the midst of the wine-dark sea, a fair, rich land, begirt with water, '),(13653,' and therein are many men, past counting, and ninety cities.'),(13654,'  They have not all the same speech, but their tongues are mixed.'),(13655,' There dwell Achaeans, there great-hearted native Cretans, there Cydonians, and Dorians of waving plumes, and goodly Pelasgians. '),(13656,' Among their cities is the great city Cnosus, where Minos reigned when nine years old, he that held converse with great Zeus,  and was father of my father, great-hearted Deucalion. Now Deucalion begat me and prince Idomeneus.'),(13657,' Idomeneus had gone forth in his beaked ships to Ilios with the sons of Atreus; but my famous name is Aethon; I was the younger by birth, '),(13658,'while he was the elder and the better man.'),(13659,'  There it was that I saw Odysseus and gave him gifts of entertainment; '),(13660,'for the force of the wind had brought him too to Crete, as he was making for the land of Troy, and drove him out of his course past Malea.'),(13661,' So he anchored his ships at Amnisus, where is the cave of Eilithyia, in a difficult harbor, and hardly did he escape the storm. '),(13662,' \n  Then straightway he went up to the city and asked for Idomeneus;'),(13663,'for he declared that he was his friend, beloved and honored.'),(13664,' But it was now the tenth or the eleventh dawn since Idomeneus had gone in his beaked ships to Ilios.'),(13665,' So I took him to the house, and gave him entertainment  with kindly welcome of the rich store that was in the house, '),(13666,'and to the rest of his comrades who followed with him I gathered and gave out of the public store barley meal and flaming wine and bulls for sacrifice, that their hearts might be satisfied.'),(13667,' There for twelve days the goodly Achaeans tarried, '),(13668,'  for the strong North Wind penned them there, and would not suffer them to stand upon their feet on the land, for some angry god had roused it.'),(13669,' But on the thirteenth day the wind fell and they put to sea.\"'),(13670,'He spoke, and made the many falsehoods of his tale seem like the truth,'),(13671,' and as she listened her tears flowed and her face melted '),(13672,' as the snow melts on the lofty mountains, the snow which the East Wind thaws when the West Wind has strewn it, '),(13673,'and as it melts the streams of the rivers flow full:'),(13674,' so her fair cheeks melted as she wept and mourned for her husband, who even then was sitting by her side. '),(13675,'And Odysseus  in his heart had pity for his weeping wife, but his eyes stood fixed between his lids as though they were horn or iron, '),(13676,' and with guile he hid his tears.'),(13677,' But she, when she had had her fill of tearful wailing, again answered him and spoke, saying:'),(13678,'\n  “Now verily, stranger, am I minded to put thee to the test, whether or no thou didst in very truth entertain there in thy halls my husband with his godlike comrades, even as thou sayest.'),(13679,' Tell me what manner of raiment he wore about his body, and what manner of man he was himself; and tell me of the comrades who followed him.\"'),(13680,'  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said: '),(13681,'“Lady, hard is it for one that has been so long afar to tell thee this, '),(13682,' for it is now the twentieth year since he went thence and departed from my country.'),(13683,' But I will tell thee as my mind pictures him.'),(13684,'  A fleecy cloak of purple did goodly Odysseus wear, a cloak of double fold, '),(13685,' but the brooch upon it was fashioned of gold with double clasps, '),(13686,' and on the front it was curiously wrought:'),(13687,' a hound held in his fore paws a dappled fawn, and pinned it in his jaws as it writhed.'),(13688,' And at this all men marvelled,  how, though they were of gold, the hound was pinning the fawn and strangling it, and the fawn was writhing with its feet and striving to flee.'),(13689,' And I noted the tunic about his body, all shining as is the sheen upon the skin of a dried onion, '),(13690,' so soft it was; and it glistened like the sun.'),(13691,'  Verily many women gazed at him in wonder.'),(13692,' And another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart.'),(13693,' I know not whether Odysseus was thus clothed at home, or whether one of his comrades gave him the raiment when he went on board the swift ship, or haply even some stranger, since to many men  was Odysseus dear, '),(13694,' for few of the Achaeans were his peers.'),(13695,' \n I, too, gave him a sword of bronze, and a fair purple cloak of double fold, and a fringed tunic, and with all honor sent him forth on his benched ship.'),(13696,' Furthermore, a herald  attended him, a little older than he, '),(13697,'and I will tell thee of him too, what manner of man he was.'),(13698,'He was round-shouldered, dark of skin, and curly-haired, and his name was Eurybates; '),(13699,' and Odysseus honored him above his other comrades, because he was like-minded with himself.\"'),(13700,'So he spoke, and in her heart aroused yet more the desire of weeping,  as she recognized the sure tokens that Odysseus told her.'),(13701,' But she, when she had had her fill of tearful wailing,'),(13702,' made answer and said to him:'),(13703,'\n“Now verily, stranger, though before thou wast pitied, shalt thou be dear and honored in my halls, '),(13704,' for it was I that gave him this raiment, since thou describest it thus, and folded it, and brought it forth from the store-room, and added thereto the shining brooch to be a thing of joy to him.'),(13705,' But my husband I shall never welcome back, returning home to his dear native land.'),(13706,' Wherefore it was with an evil fate that Odysseus  went forth in the hollow ship to see evil Ilios, that should never be named.”'),(13707,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said:'),(13708,' “Honored wife of Odysseus, son of Laertes, mar not now thy fair face any more, nor waste thy heart at all in weeping for thy husband.'),(13709,' I count it indeed no blame in thee; '),(13710,' for any woman weeps when she has lost her wedded husband, to whom she has borne children in her love, though he were far other than Odysseus, who, they say, is like unto the gods.'),(13711,' Yet do thou cease from weeping, and hearken to my words; '),(13712,'for I will tell thee with sure truth, and will hide nothing,  how but lately I heard of the return of Odysseus, that he is near at hand in the rich land of the Thesprotians, and yet alive,'),(13713,'and he is bringing with him many rich treasures, as he begs through the land.'),(13714,' But he lost his trusty comrades and his hollow ship on the wine-dark sea,  as he journeyed from the isle Thrinacia; '),(13715,'for Zeus and Helios waxed wroth against him '),(13716,'because his comrades had slain the kine of Helios. '),(13717,' \nSo they all perished in the surging sea, '),(13718,'  but he on the keel of his ship was cast forth by the wave on the shore, on the land of the Phaeacians, who are near of kin to the gods.  These heartily showed him all honor, as if he were a god, and gave him many gifts, and were fain themselves to send him home unscathed.'),(13719,' Yea, and Odysseus would long since have been here, '),(13720,'only it seemed to his mind more profitable to gather wealth by roaming over the wide earth; '),(13721,'  so truly does Odysseus beyond all mortal men know many gainful ways, nor could any mortal beside vie with him.'),(13722,' Thus Pheidon, king of the Thesprotians, told me the tale.'),(13723,' Moreover he swore in my own presence, as he poured libations in his halls, that the ship was launched and the men ready  who were to convey him to his dear native land.'),(13724,' But me he sent forth first,'),(13725,' for a ship of the Thesprotians chanced to be setting out for Dulichium, rich in wheat.'),(13726,' And he showed me all the treasure that Odysseus had gathered; '),(13727,' verily unto the tenth generation would it feed his children after him,  so great was the wealth that lay stored for him in the halls of the king.'),(13728,' But Odysseus, he said, had gone to Dodona to hear the will of Zeus from the high-crested oak of the god, even how he might return to his dear native land after so long an absence, whether openly or in secret.'),(13729,'\n  “Thus, as I tell thee, he is safe, and will presently come; he is very near, and not long will he now be far from his friends and his native land.'),(13730,' Yet will I give thee an oath.'),(13731,' Be Zeus my witness first, highest and best of gods, and the hearth of noble Odysseus to which I am come, '),(13732,' that verily all these things shall be brought to pass even as I tell thee.'),(13733,'In the course of this very month shall Odysseus come hither, as the old moon wanes and the new appears.\"'),(13734,'Then wise Penelope answered him:'),(13735,' “Ah, stranger, I would that this word of thine might be fulfilled.'),(13736,'  Then shouldest thou straightway know of kindness and many a gift from me, so that one who met thee would call thee blessed.'),(13737,' Yet in my heart I forebode it thus, even as it shall be.'),(13738,' Neither shall Odysseus any more come home, nor shalt thou obtain a convoy hence, since there are not now in the house such masters  as Odysseus was among men—as sure as ever such a man there was—to send reverend strangers on their way, and to welcome them. '),(13739,' \nBut still, my maidens, wash the stranger\'s feet and prepare his bed—bedstead and cloaks and bright coverlets—that in warmth and comfort he may come to the golden-throned Dawn.'),(13740,'  And right early in the morning bathe him and anoint him, that in our house at the side of Telemachus he may bethink him of food as he sits in the hall.'),(13741,' And worse shall it be for any man among them who vexes this man\'s soul with pain; '),(13742,' naught thereafter shall he accomplish here, how fierce soever his wrath.'),(13743,'  For how shalt thou learn of me, stranger, whether I in any wise excel other women in wit and prudent counsel, if all unkempt and clad in poor raiment thou sittest at meat in my halls?'),(13744,' Men are but short-lived. '),(13745,'If one be himself hard, and have a hard heart,  on him do all mortal men invoke woes for the time to come, while he still lives, and when he is dead all men mock at him.'),(13746,' But if one be blameless and have a blameless heart, his fame do strangers bear far and wide among all men, and many call him a true man.\"'),(13747,'  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said: '),(13748,'“Honored wife of Odysseus, son of Laertes, verily cloaks and bright coverlets became hateful in my eyes on the day when first I left behind me the snowy mountains of Crete, as I fared on my long-oared ship.  Nay, I will lie, as in time past I was wont to rest through sleepless nights;'),(13749,' for many a night have I lain upon a foul bed and waited for the bright-throned Dawn.'),(13750,' Aye, and baths for the feet give my heart no pleasure, '),(13751,'nor shall any woman touch my foot  of all those who are serving-women in thy hall, unless there is some old, true-hearted dame who has suffered in her heart as many woes as I; '),(13752,' such an one I would not grudge to touch my feet.\"'),(13753,' Then wise Penelope answered him again: '),(13754,' “Dear stranger, '),(13755,' “Dear stranger, never yet has a man discreet as thou, of those who are strangers from afar, come to my house as a more welcome guest, so wise and prudent are all thy words. '),(13756,' I have an old dame with a heart of understanding in her breast, who lovingly nursed and cherished my hapless husband,  and took him in her arms on the day when his mother bore him. She shall wash thy feet, weak with age though she be.'),(13757,' Come now, wise Eurycleia, arise and wash the feet of one of like age with thy master.'),(13758,' Even such as his are now haply the feet of Odysseus, and such his hands, '),(13759,' for quickly do men grow old in evil fortune.”'),(13760,' \nSo she spoke, and the old woman hid her face in her hands and let fall hot tears, uttering words of lamentation:'),(13761,'\n“Ah, woe is me, child, because of thee, for that I can do naught.'),(13762,' Surely Zeus hated thee above all men, though thou hadst a god-fearing heart.'),(13763,'  For never yet did any mortal burn to Zeus, who hurls the thunderbolt, so many fat thigh-pieces or so many choice hecatombs as thou gavest him, with prayers that thou mightest reach a sleek old age and rear thy glorious son.'),(13764,' But lo, now, from thee alone has he wholly cut off the day of thy returning.'),(13765,'  Even thus, I ween, did women mock at him too, in a strange and distant land, when he came to some man\'s glorious house, as these shameless creatures here all mock at thee. It is to shun insult now from them and their many taunts that thou dost not suffer them to wash thy feet,'),(13766,' but me, who am nothing loath, has  the daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope, bidden to wash thee. '),(13767,'Therefore will I wash thy feet, both for Penelope\'s own sake and for thine, for the heart within me is stirred with sorrow.'),(13768,' But come now, hearken to the word that I shall speak.'),(13769,' Many sore-tried strangers have come hither,  but I declare that never yet have I seen any man so like another as thou in form, and in voice, and in feet art like Odysseus.\"'),(13770,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said: '),(13771,'“Old dame, so say all men whose eyes have beheld us two, that  we are very like each other, even as thou thyself dost note and say.”'),(13772,'So he spoke, and the old dame took the shining cauldron with water wherefrom she was about to wash his feet, and poured in cold water in plenty, and then added thereto the warm.'),(13773,' But Odysseus sat him down away from the hearth and straightway turned himself toward the darkness,'),(13774,' for he at once had a foreboding at heart that, as she touched him, she might note a scar, and the truth be made manifest.'),(13775,' So she drew near and began to wash her lord, '),(13776,'and straightway knew the scar of the wound which long ago a boar had dealt him with his white tusk, when Odysseus had gone to Parnassus to visit Autolycus and the sons of Autolycus,  his mother\'s noble father, who excelled all men in thievery and in oaths.'),(13777,' It was a god himself that had given him this skill, even Hermes, '),(13778,'for to him he was wont to burn acceptable sacrifices of the thighs of lambs and kids; '),(13779,'so Hermes befriended him with a ready heart.'),(13780,' Now Autolycus, on coming once to the rich land of Ithaca,  had found his daughter\'s son a babe new-born, '),(13781,'and when he was finishing his supper, Eurycleia laid the child upon his knees and spoke, and addressed him:'),(13782,'\n“Autolycus, find now thyself a name to give to thy child\'s own child; '),(13783,'be sure he has long been prayed for.” '),(13784,' \n  Then Autolycus answered her, and said:'),(13785,'“My daughter\'s husband and my daughter, give him whatsoever name I say.'),(13786,' Lo, inasmuch as I am come hither as one that has been angered with many, both men and women, over the fruitful earth, '),(13787,' therefore let the name by which the child is named be Odysseus.'),(13788,'And for my part,  when he is a man grown and comes to the great house of his mother\'s kin at Parnassus, where are my possessions, I will give him thereof and send him back rejoicing.\"'),(13789,'It was for this reason that Odysseus had come, that Autolycus might give him the glorious gifts.'),(13790,' And Autolycus and the sons of Autolycus  clasped his hands in welcome and greeted him with gentle words, '),(13791,'and Amphithea, his mother\'s mother, took Odysseus in her arms and kissed his head and both his beautiful eyes.'),(13792,'  But Autolycus called to his glorious sons to make ready the meal,'),(13793,' and they hearkened to his call.  At once they led in a bull, five years old,'),(13794,' which they flayed and dressed, and cut up all the limbs. Then they sliced these cunningly and pierced them with spits, and roasted them skilfully and distributed the portions.'),(13795,' So, then, all day long till set of sun  they feasted, nor did their hearts lack aught of the equal feast.'),(13796,'But when the sun set and darkness came on they lay down to rest and took the gift of sleep.'),(13797,'\nBut as soon as early Dawn appeared, the rosy-fingered, they went forth to the hunt, the hounds and  the sons of Autolycus too, '),(13798,'and with them went goodly Odysseus.'),(13799,' Up the steep mountain Parnassus, clothed with forests, they climbed, and presently reached its windy hollows.'),(13800,' The sun was now just striking on the fields, as he rose from softly-gliding, deep-flowing Oceanus,  when the beaters came to a glade. '),(13801,'Before them went the hounds, tracking the scent, and behind them the sons of Autolycus, '),(13802,' and among these the goodly Odysseus followed, close upon the hounds, brandishing his long spear.'),(13803,' Now thereby a great wild boar was lying in a thick lair, '),(13804,' through which the strength of the wet winds could never blow nor the rays of the bright sun beat, nor could the rain pierce through it,'),(13805,' so thick it was; and fallen leaves were there in plenty. '),(13806,' Then about the boar there came the noise of the feet of men and dogs  as they pressed on in the chase,'),(13807,' and forth from his lair he came against them with bristling back and eyes flashing fire, and stood there at bay close before them.'),(13808,' Then first of all Odysseus rushed on, holding his long spear on high in his stout hand, eager to smite him; '),(13809,' but the boar was too quick for him and struck him  above the knee, charging upon him sideways, and with his tusk tore a long gash in the flesh, but did not reach the bone of the man.'),(13810,' But Odysseus with sure aim smote him on the right shoulder, and clear through went the point of the bright spear,  '),(13811,'and the boar fell in the dust with a cry, and his life flew from him. '),(13812,' \n  Then the dear sons of Autolycus busied themselves with the carcase, and the wound of noble, god-like Odysseus they bound up skilfully, and checked the black blood with a charm, and straightway returned to the house of their dear father. '),(13813,'And when Autolycus and the sons of Autolycus  had fully healed him, and had given him glorious gifts, they quickly sent him back with joy to his native land, to Ithaca.'),(13814,' Then his father and his honored mother rejoiced at his return, and asked him all the story, how he got his wound; '),(13815,'and he told them all the truth,  how, while he was hunting, a boar had struck him with his white tusk when he had gone to Parnassus with the sons of Autolycus.'),(13816,'\nThis scar the old dame, when she had taken the limb in the flat of her hands, knew by the touch, and she let fall the foot.'),(13817,' Into the basin the leg fell, and the brazen vessel rang.  Over it tilted,'),(13818,'  and the water was spilled upon the ground. '),(13819,'Then upon her soul came joy and grief in one moment, and both her eyes were filled with tears and the flow of her voice was checked.'),(13820,' But she touched the chin of Odysseus, and said:'),(13821,'\n“Verily thou art Odysseus, dear child, '),(13822,'and I knew thee not,  till I had handled all the body of my lord.”'),(13823,'She spoke, and with her eyes looked toward Penelope, fain to show her that her dear husband was at home.'),(13824,' But Penelope could not meet her glance nor understand, '),(13825,'for Athena had turned her thoughts aside. '),(13826,' But Odysseus,  feeling for the woman\'s throat, seized it with his right hand, and with the other drew her closer to him, and said:'),(13827,'\n“Mother, why wilt thou destroy me?'),(13828,' Thou didst thyself nurse me at this thy breast, '),(13829,'and now after many grievous toils I am come in the twentieth year to my native land.'),(13830,'  But since thou hast found me out, and a god has put this in thy heart, be silent lest any other in the halls learn hereof.'),(13831,'For thus will I speak out to thee, and verily it shall be brought to pass:'),(13832,'  if a god shall subdue the lordly wooers unto me, I will not spare thee, my nurse though thou art, when  I slay the other serving-women in my halls.”'),(13833,'Then wise Eurycleia answered him:'),(13834,' “My child, what a word has escaped the barrier of thy teeth!'),(13835,' Thou knowest how firm my spirit is and unyielding: I shall be as close as hard stone or iron.'),(13836,'  And another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart. '),(13837,'If a god shall subdue the lordly wooers unto thee, then will I name over to thee the women in thy halls, which ones dishonor thee, and which are guiltless.” '),(13838,' \nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said:  “Mother, why, pray, wilt thou speak of them?'),(13839,'  Thou needest not at all.'),(13840,' Of myself will I mark them well, and come to know each one.'),(13841,' Nay, keep the matter to thyself, and leave the issue to the gods.\"'),(13842,'So he spoke, and the old woman went forth through the hall to bring water for his feet, '),(13843,'for all the first was spilled.'),(13844,'  And when she had washed him, and anointed him richly with oil, Odysseus again drew his chair nearer to the fire to warm himself, and hid the scar with his rags.'),(13845,'\nThen wise Penelope was the first to speak, saying:'),(13846,' “Stranger, this little thing further will I ask thee myself, '),(13847,'  for it will soon be the hour for pleasant rest, for him at least on whom sweet sleep may come despite his care.'),(13848,' But to me has a god given sorrow that is beyond all measure, '),(13849,'for day by day I find my joy in mourning and lamenting, while looking to my household tasks and those of my women in the house,  '),(13850,' but when night comes and sleep lays hold of all, I lie upon my bed, and sharp cares, crowding close about my throbbing heart, disquiet me, as I mourn. '),(13851,'Even as when the daughter of Pandareus, the nightingale of the greenwood, sings sweetly, when spring is newly come,  as she sits perched amid the thick leafage of the trees, and with many trilling notes pours forth her rich voice in wailing for her child, dear Itylus, whom she had one day slain with the sword unwittingly, Itylus, the son of king Zethus; even so my heart sways to and fro in doubt,  whether to abide with my son and keep all things safe, my possessions, my slaves, and my great, high-roofed house, respecting the bed of my husband and the voice of the people, or to go now with him whosoever is best of the Achaeans, who woos me in the halls and offers bride-gifts past counting.'),(13852,'  Furthermore my son, so long as he was a child and slack of wit, would not suffer me to marry and leave the house of my husband; '),(13853,'but now that he is grown and has reached the bounds of manhood, lo, he even prays me to go back again from these halls, being vexed for his substance that the Achaeans devour to his cost.'),(13854,'  But come now, hear this dream of mine, and interpret it for me.'),(13855,' Twenty geese I have in the house that come forth from the water and eat wheat, and my heart warms with joy as I watch them.'),(13856,' But forth from the mountain there came a great eagle with crooked beak and broke all their necks and killed them; '),(13857,' and they lay strewn  in a heap in the halls, while he was borne aloft to the bright sky. '),(13858,' Now for my part I wept and wailed, in a dream though it was, and round me thronged the fair-tressed Achaean women, as I grieved piteously because the eagle had slain my geese. '),(13859,' \nThen back he came and perched upon a projecting roof-beam,  and with the voice of a mortal man checked my weeping, and said:'),(13860,'\n“‘Be of good cheer, daughter of far-famed Icarius;'),(13861,' this is no dream, but a true vision of good which shall verily find fulfillment.'),(13862,' The geese are the wooers, and I, that before was the eagle, am now again come back as thy husband,  who will let loose a cruel doom upon all the wooers.’'),(13863,'“So he spoke, and sweet sleep released me, '),(13864,' and looking about I saw the geese in the halls, feeding on wheat beside the trough, where they had before been wont to feed.\"'),(13865,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her and said:'),(13866,'  “Lady, in no wise is it possible to wrest this dream aside and give it another meaning, since verily Odysseus himself has shewn thee how he will bring it to pass.'),(13867,' For the wooers\' destruction is plain to see, for one and all; not one of them shall escape death and the fates.\"'),(13868,'Then wise Penelope answered him again:'),(13869,'  “Stranger, dreams verily are baffling and unclear of meaning, and in no wise do they find fulfillment in all things for men.'),(13870,' For two are the gates of shadowy dreams, '),(13871,' and one is fashioned of horn and one of ivory.'),(13872,' Those dreams that pass through the gate of sawn ivory  deceive men, bringing words that find no fulfillment. '),(13873,'But those that come forth through the gate of polished horn bring true issues to pass, when any mortal sees them.'),(13874,' But in my case it was not from thence, methinks, that my strange dream came.'),(13875,' Ah, truly it would then have been welcome to me and to my son.'),(13876,'  But another thing will I tell thee, and do thou lay it to heart.'),(13877,' Even now is coming on this morn of evil name which is to cut me off from the house of Odysseus; '),(13878,'for now I shall appoint for a contest those axes which he was wont to set up in line in his halls, like props of a ship that is building, twelve in all, '),(13879,'   and he would stand afar off and shoot an arrow through them.'),(13880,' \nNow then I shall set this contest before the wooers:'),(13881,' whosoever shall most easily string the bow in his hands, and shoot an arrow through all twelve axes, with him will I go and forsake this house  of my wedded life, a house most fair and filled with livelihood, '),(13882,' which, methinks, I shall ever remember even in my dreams.\"'),(13883,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said: “Honored wife of Odysseus, son of Laertes, no longer now do thou put off this contest in thy halls;'),(13884,'  for, I tell thee, Odysseus of many wiles will be here, ere these men, handling this polished bow, shall have strung it, and shot an arrow through the iron.”'),(13885,'Then wise Penelope answered him: '),(13886,'“If thou couldest but wish, stranger, to sit here in my halls  and give me joy, sleep should never be shed over my eyelids. '),(13887,'But it is in no wise possible that men should forever be sleepless, '),(13888,' for the immortals have appointed a proper time for each thing upon the earth, the giver of grain.'),(13889,'But I verily will go to my upper chamber  and lay me on my bed, which has become for me a bed of wailings, ever bedewed with my tears, since the day when Odysseus went to see evil Ilios, that should never be named.'),(13890,' There will I lay me down, '),(13891,'but do thou lie down here in the hall, when thou hast strewn bedding on the floor; or let the maids set a bedstead for thee.” '),(13892,'  So saying, she went up to her bright upper chamber, not alone, for with her went her handmaids as well.'),(13893,' And when she had gone up to her upper chamber with her handmaids, she then bewailed Odysseus, her dear husband, until flashing-eyed Athena cast sweet sleep upon her eyelids.'),(13894,' But the goodly Odysseus lay down to sleep in the fore-hall of the house.'),(13895,' On the ground he spread an undressed ox-hide and above it many fleeces of sheep, which the Achaeans were wont to slay, '),(13896,' and Eurynome threw over him a cloak, when he had laid him down.'),(13897,'  There Odysseus, pondering in his heart evil for the wooers, lay sleepless.'),(13898,' And the women came forth from the hall, those that had before been wont to lie with the wooers, making laughter and merriment among themselves.'),(13899,' But the heart was stirred in his breast,'),(13900,' and much he debated in mind and heart, whether he should rush after them and deal death to each, or suffer them to lie with the insolent wooers for the last and latest time; and his heart growled within him. '),(13901,'And as a bitch stands over her tender whelps  growling, when she sees a man she does not know, and is eager to fight, so his heart growled within him in his wrath at their evil deeds;'),(13902,' but he smote his breast, and rebuked his heart, saying:'),(13903,'a worse thing even than this didst thou once endure '),(13904,'a worse thing even than this didst thou once endure '),(13905,'on that day when the Cyclops, unrestrained in daring, devoured my  mighty comrades; '),(13906,' but thou didst endure until craft got thee forth from the cave where thou thoughtest to die.\"'),(13907,'So he spoke, chiding the heart in his breast, '),(13908,'and his heart remained bound within him to endure steadfastly; '),(13909,'but he himself lay tossing this way and that.'),(13910,'  And as when a man before a great blazing fire turns swiftly this way and that a paunch full of fat and blood, and is very eager to have it roasted quickly, so Odysseus tossed from side to side, pondering how he might put forth his hands upon the shameless wooers,  one man as he was against so many.'),(13911,' Then Athena came down from heaven'),(13912,' and drew near to him in the likeness of a woman,'),(13913,'and she stood above his head, and spoke to him, and said:'),(13914,'\n“Why now again art thou wakeful, ill-fated above all men?'),(13915,' Lo, this is thy house, and here within is thy wife  and thy child, such a man, methinks, as anyone might pray to have for his son.”'),(13916,'And Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said: '),(13917,' “Yea, goddess, all this hast thou spoken aright.'),(13918,'But the heart in my breast is pondering somewhat upon this, how I may put forth my hands upon the shameless wooers,  all alone as I am, '),(13919,'while they remain always in a body in the house. '),(13920,'And furthermore this other and harder thing I ponder in my mind:'),(13921,' even if I were to slay them by the will of Zeus and of thyself, where then should I find escape from bane?'),(13922,' Of this I bid thee take thought.” '),(13923,' \nThen the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, answered him:'),(13924,'  “Obstinate one, many a man puts his trust even in a weaker friend than I am, one that is mortal, and knows not such wisdom as mine; '),(13925,' but I am a god, that guard thee to the end in all thy toils.'),(13926,' And I will tell thee openly; '),(13927,' if fifty troops of mortal men  should stand about us, eager to slay us in battle, even their cattle and goodly sheep shouldest thou drive off. '),(13928,' Nay, let sleep now come over thee.'),(13929,'There is weariness also in keeping wakeful watch the whole night through; and even now shalt thou come forth from out thy perils.\"'),(13930,'So she spoke, and shed sleep upon his eyelids,  but herself, the fair goddess, went back to Olympus.'),(13931,'Now while sleep seized him, loosening the cares of his heart, sleep that loosens the limbs of men, his true-hearted wife awoke, '),(13932,' and wept, as she sat upon her soft bed.'),(13933,' But when her heart had had its fill of weeping,  to Artemis first of all the fair lady made her prayer:'),(13934,'\n“Artemis, mighty goddess, daughter of Zeus, would that now thou wouldest fix thy arrow in my breast and take away my life even in this hour; or that a storm-wind might catch me up and bear me hence over the murky ways,  and cast me forth at the mouth of backward-flowing Oceanus,'),(13935,' even as on a time storm-winds bore away the daughters of Pandareus.'),(13936,' Their parents the gods had slain, and they were left orphans in the halls, and fair Aphrodite tended them with cheese, and sweet honey, and pleasant wine,'),(13937,' and Here gave them beauty and wisdom above all women, and chaste Artemis gave them stature, and Athena taught them skill in famous handiwork. '),(13938,'But while beautiful Aphrodite was going to high Olympus to ask for the maidens the accomplishment of gladsome marriage—  going to Zeus who hurls the thunderbolt, for well he knows all things, both the happiness and the haplessness of mortal men—meanwhile the spirits of the storm snatched away the maidens and gave them to the hateful Erinyes to deal with.'),(13939,' Would that even so those who have dwellings on Olympus would blot me from sight,  or that fair-tressed Artemis would smite me, so that with Odysseus before my mind I might even pass beneath the hateful earth, and never gladden in any wise the heart of a baser man. '),(13940,'Yet when a man weeps by day with a heart sore distressed,  but at night sleep holds him, this brings with it an evil that may well be borne—for sleep makes one forget all things, the good and the evil, when once it envelops the eyelids—but upon me a god sends evil dreams as well.'),(13941,' For this night again there lay by my side one like him, even such as he was when he went forth with the host,  '),(13942,'and my heart  was glad, for I deemed it was no dream, but the truth at last.”'),(13943,' \nSo she spoke, and straightway came golden-throned Dawn.'),(13944,' But as she wept goodly Odysseus heard her voice, '),(13945,'and thereupon he mused, and it seemed to his heart that she knew him and was standing by his head.'),(13946,'  Then he gathered up the cloak and the fleeces on which he was lying and laid them on a chair in the hall, and carried the ox-hide out of doors and set it down; and he lifted up his hands and prayed to Zeus:'),(13947,'\n“Father Zeus, if of your good will ye gods have brought me over land and sea to my own country, when ye had afflicted me sore,  let some one of those who are awaking utter a word of omen for me within, and without let a sign from Zeus be shown besides.\"'),(13948,'So he spoke in prayer,'),(13949,' and Zeus the counsellor heard him. Straightway he thundered from gleaming Olympus, from on high from out the clouds; '),(13950,'and goodly Odysseus was glad. '),(13951,'   And a woman, grinding at the mill, uttered a word of omen from within the house hard by, where the mills of the shepherd of the people were set. At these mills twelve women in all were wont to ply their tasks, making meal of barley and of wheat, the marrow of men. '),(13952,' Now the others were sleeping, for they had ground their wheat,  but she alone had not yet ceased, for she was the weakest of all. '),(13953,'She now stopped her mill and spoke a word, a sign for her master:'),(13954,' \n“Father Zeus, who art lord over gods and men, verily loud hast thou thundered from the starry sky, yet nowhere is there any cloud:'),(13955,'surely this is a sign that thou art showing to some man.'),(13956,' Fulfil now even for wretched me the word that I shall speak.'),(13957,' May the wooers this day for the last and latest time hold their glad feast in the halls of Odysseus. They that have loosened my limbs with bitter labour,'),(13958,' as I made them barley meal, '),(13959,'may they now sup their last.”'),(13960,'  So she spoke, and goodly Odysseus was glad at the word of omen and at the thunder of Zeus, '),(13961,'for he thought he had gotten vengeance on the guilty.'),(13962,'Now the other maidens in the fair palace of Odysseus had gathered together and were kindling on the hearth unwearied fire,'),(13963,' and Telemachus rose from his bed, a godlike man,  and put on his clothing. '),(13964,' He slung his sharp sword about his shoulder, '),(13965,'and beneath his shining feet he bound his fair sandals; and he took his mighty spear,  '),(13966,'tipped with sharp bronze,'),(13967,'and went and stood upon the threshold, and spoke to Eurycleia:'),(13968,'“Dear nurse, have ye honored the stranger in our house  with bed and food, or does he lie all uncared for? '),(13969,'For such is my mother\'s way, wise though she is:'),(13970,' in wondrous fashion she honours one of mortal men,'),(13971,' \n though he be the worse, while the better she sends unhonored away.” '),(13972,' \nThen wise Eurycleia answered him:'),(13973,'  “In this matter, child, thou shouldest not blame her, who is without blame.'),(13974,' He sat here and drank wine as long as he would, but for food he said he had no more hunger,'),(13975,' for she asked him. '),(13976,' But when he bethought him of rest and sleep, she bade the maidens strew his bed.\n But he, as one wholly wretched and hapless, would not sleep on a bed and under blankets, but on an undressed ox-hide and fleeces of sheep he slept in the fore-hall, '),(13977,'and we flung over him a cloak.\"'),(13978,'So she spoke, and Telemachus went forth through the hall  with his spear in his hand, and with him went two swift hounds.'),(13979,' And he went his way to the place of assembly to join the company of the well-greaved Achaeans,'),(13980,' but Eurycleia, the goodly lady, daughter of Ops, son of Peisenor, called to her maidens, saying:'),(13981,'“Come, let some of you busily sweep the hall  and sprinkle it, and throw on the shapely chairs coverlets of purple, '),(13982,'  and let others wipe all the tables with sponges and cleanse the mixing-bowls and the well-wrought double cups,'),(13983,'and others still go to the spring for water and bring it quickly here.'),(13984,'  For the wooers will not long be absent from the hall, but will return right early; for it is a feast-day for all men.\"'),(13985,'So she spoke, and they readily hearkened and obeyed.'),(13986,' Twenty of them went to the spring of dark water, and the others busied themselves there in the house in skilful fashion.'),(13987,'  Then in came the serving-men of the Acheans, '),(13988,'who thereafter split logs of wood well and skilfully; and the women came back from the spring.'),(13989,' After them came the swineherd, driving three boars which were the best in all his herd.'),(13990,' These he let be to feed in the fair courts,  but himself spoke to Odysseus with gentle words:'),(13991,'“Stranger, do the Achaeans look on thee with any more regard, or do they dishonor thee in the halls as before?\"'),(13992,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said: '),(13993,'“Ah, Eumaeus, I would that the gods might take vengeance on the outrage  wherewith these men in wantonness devise wicked folly in another\'s house, and have no place for shame.\"'),(13994,'Thus they spoke to one another. And near to them came Melanthius the goatherd,'),(13995,' leading she-goats that were the best in all the herds,  to make a feast for the wooers,'),(13996,'and two herdsmen followed with him. '),(13997,'The goats he tethered beneath the echoing portico, and himself spoke to Odysseus with taunting words:'),(13998,'\n“Stranger, wilt thou even now still be a plague to us here in the hall, asking alms of men, and wilt thou not begone?'),(13999,'  \'Tis plain, methinks, that we two shall not part company till we taste one another\'s fists, for thy begging is in no wise decent.'),(14000,' Also it is not here alone that there are feasts of the Achaeans.” '),(14001,' \nSo he spoke, but Odysseus of many wiles made no answer, but he shook his head in silence, pondering evil in the deep of his heart.'),(14002,'\n  Besides these a third man came, Philoetius, a leader of men, driving for the wooers a barren heifer and fat she-goats.'),(14003,' These had been brought over from the mainland by ferrymen, who send other men, too, on their way, whosoever comes to them.'),(14004,' The beasts he tethered carefully beneath the echoing portico,  but himself came close to the swineherd and questioned him, saying: '),(14005,'“Who is this stranger, swineherd, who has newly come to our house? '),(14006,'From what men does he declare himself to be sprung? '),(14007,' Where are his kinsmen and his native fields? '),(14008,' Hapless man! Yet truly in form he is like a royal prince; '),(14009,' howbeit the gods bring to misery far-wandering men, whenever they spin for them the threads of trouble, even though they be kings.\"'),(14010,'Therewith he drew near to Odysseus, and stretching forth his right hand in greeting, spoke and addressed him with winged words:'),(14011,'\n“Hail, Sir stranger; '),(14012,' may happy fortune be thine in time to come, '),(14013,'though now thou art the thrall of many sorrows!'),(14014,' Father Zeus, no other god is more baneful than thou;'),(14015,' thou hast no pity on men when thou hast thyself given them birth, but bringest them into misery and wretched pains. '),(14016,'The sweat broke out on me when I marked the man, and my eyes are full of tears  as I think of Odysseus; for he, too, I ween, is clothed in such rags and is a wanderer among men, if indeed he still lives and beholds the light of the sun.'),(14017,' But if he is already dead and in the house of Hades, then woe is me for blameless Odysseus, who  set me over his cattle, when I was yet a boy, in the land of the Cephallenians. '),(14018,' And now these wax past counting; in no other wise could the breed of broad-browed cattle yield better increase for a mortal man.'),(14019,' But strangers bid me drive these now for themselves to eat, '),(14020,' and they care nothing for the son in the house,  nor do they tremble at the wrath of the gods, '),(14021,'for they are eager now to divide among themselves the possessions of our lord that has long been gone.'),(14022,' Now, as for myself, the heart in my breast keeps revolving this matter:'),(14023,' a very evil thing it is, while the son lives, to depart along with my cattle and go to a land of strangers,  even to an alien folk;'),(14024,' but this is worse still, to remain here and suffer woes in charge of cattle that are given over to others.'),(14025,' Aye, verily, long ago would I have fled and come to some other of the proud kings, for now things are no more to be borne; '),(14026,' but still I think of that hapless one, if perchance he might come back I know not whence,  and make a scattering of the wooers in his house.”'),(14027,' \nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(14028,' “Neatherd, since thou seemest to be neither an evil man nor a witless, and I see for myself that thou hast gotten an understanding heart, therefore will I speak out and swear a great oath to confirm my words.'),(14029,'  Now be my witness Zeus above all gods, and this hospitable board, and the hearth of noble Odysseus to which I am come, that verily while thou art here Odysseus shall come home,'),(14030,'and thou shalt see with thine eyes, if thou wilt, the slaying of the wooers, who lord it here.\"'),(14031,'  Then the herdsman of the cattle answered him: '),(14032,'“Ah, stranger, I would that the son of Cronos might fulfil this word of thine!'),(14033,' Then shouldest thou know what manner of might is mine, and how my hands obey.\"'),(14034,'And even in like manner did Eumaeus pray to all the gods that wise Odysseus might come back to his own home.'),(14035,'\n  Thus they spoke to one another, but the wooers meanwhile were plotting death and fate for Telemachus; '),(14036,' howbeit there came to them a bird on their left, an eagle of lofty flight, clutching a timid dove.'),(14037,' Then Amphinomus spoke in their assembly, and said:'),(14038,' \n  “Friends, this plan of ours will not run to our liking, even the slaying of Telemachus; '),(14039,'nay, let us bethink us of the feast.\"'),(14040,'So spoke Amphinomus, and his word was pleasing to them. '),(14041,'Then, going into the house of godlike Odysseus, they laid their cloaks on the chairs and high seats,  and men fell to slaying great sheep and fat goats, aye, and fatted swine, and the heifer of the herd.'),(14042,' Then they roasted the entrails and served them out, and mixed wine in the bowls, '),(14043,'and the swineherd handed out the cups.'),(14044,' And Philoetius, a leader of men, handed them bread  in a beautiful basket, and Melanthius poured them wine. '),(14045,'So they put forth their hands to the good cheer lying ready before them.'),(14046,'\nBut Telemachus, with crafty thought, made Odysseus sit within the well-built hall by the threshold of stone, and placed for him a mean stool and a little table.'),(14047,'  Beside him he set portions of the entrails and poured wine in a cup of gold, and said to him:'),(14048,'\n“Sit down here among the lords and drink thy wine,'),(14049,'and the revilings and blows of all the wooers will I myself ward from thee; for this is no public  resort, but the house of Odysseus, and it was for me that he won it.'),(14050,' And for your part, ye wooers, refrain your minds from rebukes and blows, that no strife or quarrel may arise.” '),(14051,' \nSo he spoke, and they all bit their lips and marvelled at Telemachus for that he spoke boldly; '),(14052,' and Antinous, son of Eupeithes, spoke among them, saying:'),(14053,'\n“Hard though it be, Achaeans, let us accept the word of Telemachus,'),(14054,'though boldly he threatens us in his speech.'),(14055,' For Zeus, son of Cronos, did not suffer it,'),(14056,' else would we ere now have silenced him in the halls, clear-voiced talker though he is.\"'),(14057,'but Telemachus paid no heed to his words.'),(14058,'but Telemachus paid no heed to his words.'),(14059,' Meanwhile the heralds were leading through the city the holy hecatomb of the gods,'),(14060,' and the long-haired Achaeans gathered together beneath a shady grove of Apollo, the archer-god.'),(14061,'\nBut when they had roasted the outer flesh and drawn it off the spits,  they divided the portions and feasted a glorious feast. '),(14062,'And by Odysseus those who served set a portion equal to that which they received themselves, '),(14063,'for so Telemachus commanded, the dear son of divine Odysseus.'),(14064,'\nBut the proud wooers Athena  would in no wise suffer to abstain from bitter outrage, that pain might sink yet deeper into the heart of Odysseus, son of Laertes.'),(14065,' There was among the wooers a man with his heart set on lawlessness—Ctesippus was his name, and in Same was his dwelling—'),(14066,'who, trusting forsooth in his boundless wealth,  wooed the wife of Odysseus, that had long been gone. '),(14067,'He it was who now spoke among the haughty wooers:'),(14068,'\n“Hear me, ye proud wooers, that I may say somewhat.'),(14069,' A portion has the stranger long had, an equal portion, as is meet; '),(14070,'for it is not well nor just to rob of their due  the guests of Telemachus, whosoever he be that comes to this house. '),(14071,' Nay, come, I too will give him a stranger\'s-gift, that he in turn may give a present either to the bath-woman or to some other of the slaves who are in the house of godlike Odysseus.” '),(14072,' \nSo saying, he hurled with strong hand the hoof of an ox, '),(14073,' taking it up from the basket where it lay. '),(14074,'But Odysseus avoided it with a quick turn of his head, and in his heart he smiled a right grim and bitter smile; '),(14075,' and the ox\'s hoof struck the well-built wall.'),(14076,' Then Telemachus rebuked Ctesippus, and said:'),(14077,'\n“Ctesippus, verily this thing fell out more to thy soul\'s profit.'),(14078,' for he himself avoided thy missile,'),(14079,' for he himself avoided thy missile,'),(14080,' else surely would I have struck thee through the middle with my sharp spear, and instead of a wedding feast thy father would have been busied with a funeral feast in this land.'),(14081,' Wherefore let no man, I warn you, make a show of forwardness in my house;'),(14082,' for now I mark and understand all things,  the good and the evil,'),(14083,' whereas heretofore I was but a child.'),(14084,' But none the less we still endure to see these deeds, while sheep are slaughtered, and wine drunk, and bread consumed,'),(14085,' for hard it is for one man to restrain many.'),(14086,' Yet come, no longer work me harm of your evil wills.'),(14087,'  But if you are minded even now to slay me myself with the sword, even that would I choose, and it would be better far to die than continually to behold these shameful deeds, strangers mishandled and men dragging the handmaidens in shameful fashion through the fair hall.\"'),(14088,'  So he spoke, and they were all hushed in silence,'),(14089,'but at last there spoke among them Agelaus, son of Damastor:'),(14090,'“Friends, no man in answer to what has been fairly spoken would wax wroth and make reply with wrangling words.'),(14091,' Abuse not any more the stranger nor any  of the slaves that are in the house of divine Odysseus. '),(14092,' But to Telemachus and his mother I would speak a gentle word, if perchance it may find favour in the minds of both.'),(14093,'So long as the hearts in your breasts had hope that wise Odysseus would return to his own house,  so long there was no ground for blame that you waited, and restrained the wooers in your halls; for this was the better course, had Odysseus returned and come back to his house.'),(14094,'  But now this is plain, that he will return no more.'),(14095,'Nay then, come, sit by thy mother and tell her this,  namely that she must wed him whosoever is the best man, and who offers the most gifts; to the end that thou mayest enjoy in peace all the heritage of thy fathers, eating and drinking, and that she may keep the house of another.”'),(14096,' Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(14097,'“Nay, by Zeus, Agelaus, and by the woes of my father,  who somewhere far from Ithaca has perished or is wandering, in no wise do I delay my mother\'s marriage, but I bid her wed what man she will, and I offer besides gifts past counting.'),(14098,' But I am ashamed to drive her forth from the hall against her will by a word of compulsion. '),(14099,'May God never bring such a thing to pass.” '),(14100,' \n  So spoke Telemachus, '),(14101,'but among the wooers Pallas Athena roused unquenchable laughter, and turned their wits awry.'),(14102,' And now they laughed with alien lips, and all bedabbled with blood was the flesh they ate,'),(14103,'and their eyes were filled with tears and their spirits set on wailing.'),(14104,' Then among them spoke godlike Theoclymenus:'),(14105,'\n“Ah, wretched men, what evil is this that you suffer?'),(14106,' Shrouded in night are your heads and your faces and your knees beneath you; '),(14107,' kindled is the sound of wailing, bathed in tears are your cheeks, and sprinkled with blood are the walls and the fair rafters.'),(14108,'  And full of ghosts is the porch and full the court, of ghosts that hasten down to Erebus beneath the darkness,'),(14109,'and the sun has perished out of heaven and an evil mist hovers over all.\"'),(14110,'So he spoke, but they all laughed merrily at him.'),(14111,' And among them Eurymachus, son of Polybus, was the first to speak:'),(14112,'  “Mad is the stranger that has newly come from abroad. '),(14113,'Quick, ye youths, convey him forth out of doors to go his way to the place of assembly, since here he finds it like night.\"'),(14114,'Then godlike Theoclymenus answered him:'),(14115,' “Eurymachus, in no wise do I bid thee give me guides for my way.'),(14116,'  I have eyes and ears and my two feet, and a mind in my breast that is in no wise meanly fashioned.'),(14117,' With these will I go forth out of doors, for I mark evil coming upon you which not one of the wooers may escape or avoid, of all you who in the house of godlike Odysseus  insult men and devise wicked folly.”'),(14118,'So saying, he went forth from the stately halls and came to Piraeus, who received him with a ready heart.'),(14119,' But all the wooers, looking at one another, sought to provoke Telemachus by laughing at his guests.'),(14120,'  And thus would one of the proud youths speak:'),(14121,'“Telemachus, no man is more unlucky in his guests than thou, '),(14122,'seeing that thou keepest such a filthy vagabond as this man here, always wanting bread and wine, and skilled neither in the works of peace nor those of war, but a mere burden of the earth.'),(14123,'  And this other fellow again stood up to prophesy. '),(14124,'Nay, if thou wouldst hearken to me it would be better far:'),(14125,' let us fling these strangers on board a benched ship, and send them to the Sicilians, whence they would bring thee in a fitting price.\"'),(14126,'So spake the wooers,'),(14127,'  but he paid no heed to their words.  Nay, in silence he watched his father, ever waiting until he should put forth his hands upon the shameless wooers.'),(14128,'\nBut the daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope, had set her beautiful chair over against them, and heard the words of each man in the hall.'),(14129,'  For they had made ready their meal in the midst of their laughing, a sweet meal, and one to satisfy the heart, for they had slain many beasts.'),(14130,' But never could meal have been more graceless than a supper such as a goddess and a mighty man were soon to set before them.'),(14131,' For unprovoked they were contriving deeds of shame.'),(14132,' But the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, put it into the heart of the daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope, to set before the wooers in the halls of Odysseus the bow and the gray iron, to be a contest and the beginning of death.'),(14133,'  She climbed the high stairway to her chamber, and took the bent key in her strong hand—a goodly key of bronze,'),(14134,' and on it was a handle of ivory.'),(14135,' And she went her way with her handmaidens to a store-room, far remote, '),(14136,'where lay the treasures of her lord,  bronze and gold and iron, wrought with toil. '),(14137,' And there lay the back-bent bow and the quiver that held the arrows, and many arrows were in it, fraught with groanings—gifts which a friend of Odysseus had given him when he met him once in Lacedaemon, even Iphitus, son of Eurytus, a man like unto the immortals.'),(14138,'  They two had met one another in Messene in the house of wise Ortilochus.'),(14139,' Odysseus verily had come to collect a debt which the whole people owed him, '),(14140,'for the men of Messene had lifted from Ithaca in their benched ships three hundred sheep and the shepherds with them.'),(14141,'  It was on an embassy in quest of these that Odysseus had come a far journey, while he was but a youth; '),(14142,' for his father and the other elders had sent him forth.'),(14143,' And Iphitus, on his part, had come in search of twelve brood mares, which he had lost, with sturdy mules at the teat; '),(14144,'but to him thereafter did they bring death and doom,  when he came to the stout-hearted son of Zeus, the man Heracles, who well knew deeds of daring; for Heracles slew him, his guest though he was, in his own house, ruthlessly, and had regard neither for the wrath of the gods nor for the table which he had set before him, '),(14145,'but slew the man thereafter,  and himself kept the stout-hoofed mares in his halls. '),(14146,'It was while asking for these that Iphitus met Odysseus, and gave him the bow, which of old great Eurytus had been wont to bear, and had left at his death to his son in his lofty house.'),(14147,' And to Iphitus Odysseus gave a sharp sword and a mighty spear,  as the beginning of loving friendship;'),(14148,'yet they never knew one another at the table, '),(14149,' for ere that might be the son of Zeus had slain Iphitus, son of Eurytus, a man like unto the immortals, who gave Odysseus the bow. '),(14150,'This bow goodly Odysseus, when going forth to war, would never  take with him on the black ships, but it lay in his halls at home as a memorial of a dear friend, and he carried it in his own land. '),(14151,' \nNow when the fair lady had come to the store-room, and had stepped upon the threshold of oak, which of old the carpenter had skilfully planed and made straight to the line—  thereon had he also fitted door-posts, and set on them bright doors—straightway she quickly loosed the thong from the handle and thrust in the key, and with sure aim shot back the bolts.'),(14152,' And as a bull bellows  when grazing in a meadow, '),(14153,'even so bellowed the fair doors, smitten by the key; and quickly they flew open before her.'),(14154,'  Then she stepped upon the high floor,'),(14155,' where the chests stood in which fragrant raiment was stored, '),(14156,'and stretched out her hand from thence and took from its peg the bow together with the bright case which surrounded it.'),(14157,'  And there she sat down and laid the case upon her knees and wept aloud, and took out the bow of her lord.'),(14158,' But when she had had her fill of tearful wailing, she went her way to the hall, to the company of the lordly wooers, bearing in her hands the back-bent bow and the quiver  that held the arrows,'),(14159,'and many arrows were in it, fraught with groanings. '),(14160,' And by her side her maidens bore a chest, wherein lay abundance of iron and bronze, the battle-gear of her lord.'),(14161,' Now when the fair lady reached the wooers, she stood by the door-post of the well-built hall,  holding before her face her shining veil; '),(14162,'and a faithful handmaid stood on either side of her.'),(14163,' Then straightway she spoke among the wooers, and said:'),(14164,'\n“Hear me, ye proud wooers, who have beset this house to eat and drink ever without end,  since its master has long been gone,'),(14165,'nor could you find any other plea to urge, save only as desiring to wed me and take me to wife.'),(14166,' Nay, come now, ye wooers, since this is shewn to be your prize.'),(14167,' I will set before you the great bow of divine Odysseus, '),(14168,' and whosoever shall most easily string the bow in his hands and shoot an arrow through all twelve axes, with him will I go, and forsake this house of my wedded life, a house most fair and filled with livelihood, which, methinks I shall ever remember even in my dreams.” '),(14169,' \n  So she spoke, and bade Eumaeus, the goodly swineherd, set for the wooers the bow and the grey iron.'),(14170,' And, bursting into tears, Eumaeus took them and laid them down,'),(14171,' and in another place the neatherd wept, when he saw the bow of his lord.'),(14172,' Then Antinous rebuked them, and spoke, and addressed them:'),(14173,'\n  “Foolish boors, who mind only the things of the day! Wretched pair, why now do you shed tears, and trouble the soul in the breast of the lady,'),(14174,'  whose heart even as it is lies low in pain, seeing that she has lost her dear husband?'),(14175,'Nay, sit and feast in silence,  or else go forth and weep, and leave the bow here behind as a decisive contest for the wooers; '),(14176,' for not easily, methinks, is this polished bow to be strung.'),(14177,' For there is no man among all these here such as Odysseus was, '),(14178,'  and I myself saw him.  For I remember him, though I was still but a child.”'),(14179,'So he spoke, but the heart in his breast hoped that he would string the bow and shoot an arrow through the iron.'),(14180,' Yet verily he was to be the first to taste of an arrow from the hands of noble Odysseus, whom then he,  as he sat in the halls, was dishonoring, and urging on all his comrades.'),(14181,'Then among them spoke the strong and mighty Telemachus: '),(14182,'“Lo now, of a truth Zeus, son of Cronos, has made me witless.'),(14183,'My dear mother, for all that she is wise, declares that she will follow another lord, forsaking this house; '),(14184,' yet I laugh, and am glad with a witless mind. '),(14185,'Come then, ye wooers, since this is shewn to be your prize, a lady, the like of whom is not now in the Achaean land, neither in sacred Pylos, nor in Argos, nor in Mycene,'),(14186,' \nWith this he flung the scarlet cloak from off his back, and sprang up erect; and he laid his sharp sword from off his shoulders.'),(14187,'  First then he set up the axes, when he had dug a trench, one long trench for all, and made it straight to the line, and about them he stamped in the earth.'),(14188,' And amazement seized all who saw him, that he set them out so orderly,'),(14189,' though before he had never seen them. '),(14190,' Then he went and stood upon the threshold, and began to try the bow. '),(14191,' Thrice he made it quiver in his eagerness to draw it, and thrice he relaxed his effort, though in his heart he hoped to string the bow and shoot an arrow through the iron.'),(14192,' And now at the last he would haply have strung it in his might, as for the fourth time he sought to draw up the string, but Odysseus nodded in dissent, and checked him in his eagerness.'),(14193,'  Then the strong and mighty Telemachus spoke among them again:'),(14194,'“Out on it, even in days to come shall I be a coward and a weakling, or else I am too young, and have not yet trust in my might to defend me against a man, when one waxes wroth without a cause.'),(14195,' But, come now, you that are mightier than I,  make trial of the bow, and let us end the contest.”'),(14196,'So saying, he set the bow from him on the ground, leaning it against the jointed, polished door, and hard by he leaned the swift arrow against the fair bow-tip, and then sat down again on the seat from which he had risen.'),(14197,'\n  Then Antinous, son of Eupeithes, spoke among them: '),(14198,'“Rise up in order, all you of our company, from left to right, beginning from the place where the cupbearer pours the wine.”'),(14199,' So spoke Antinous, and his word was pleasing to them.'),(14200,'Then first arose Leiodes, son of Oenops,  who was their soothsayer, and ever sat by the fair mixing-bowl in the innermost part of the hall; '),(14201,'deeds of wanton folly were hateful to him alone, and he was full of indignation at all the wooers.'),(14202,' He it was who now first took the bow and swift arrow,'),(14203,' and he went and stood upon the threshold, and began to try the bow;  but he could not string it.'),(14204,' Ere that might be his hands grew weary, as he sought to draw up the string, his unworn delicate hands;'),(14205,' and he spoke among the wooers:'),(14206,'\n“Friends, it is not I that shall string it; let another take it.'),(14207,'For many princes shall this bow rob of spirit and of life, since verily it is better far  to die than to live on and fail of that for the sake of which we ever gather here, waiting expectantly day after day.'),(14208,' Now many a man even hopes in his heart and desires to wed Penelope, the wife of Odysseus;'),(14209,'but when he shall have made trial of the bow, and seen the outcome, thereafter let him woo  some other of the fair-robed Achaean women with his gifts, and seek to win her; '),(14210,'then should Penelope wed him who offers most, and who comes as her fated lord.” '),(14211,' \nSo he spoke, and set the bow from him, leaning it against the jointed, polished door,  and hard by he leaned the swift arrow against the fair bow-tip, and then sat down on the seat from which he had risen.'),(14212,' But Antinous rebuked him, and spoke, and addressed him: '),(14213,'“Leiodes, what a word has escaped the barrier of thy teeth, a dread word and grievous! I am angered to hear it,  if forsooth this bow is to rob princes of spirit and of life, because thou art not able to string it.'),(14214,' For, I tell thee, thy honored mother did not bear thee of such strength as to draw a bow and shoot arrows;'),(14215,'but others of the lordly wooers will soon string it.\"'),(14216,'  So he spoke, and called to Melanthius, the goatherd: '),(14217,' “Come now, light a fire in the hall, Melanthius; and set by it a great seat with a fleece upon it, and bring forth a great cake of the fat that is within, that we youths may warm the bow, and anoint it with fat,  and so make trial of it, and end the contest.”'),(14218,'So he spoke, and Melanthius straightway rekindled the unwearied fire, and brought and placed by it a great seat with a fleece upon it, and he brought forth a great cake of the fat that was within.'),(14219,' Therewith the youths warmed the bow, and made trial of it, '),(14220,'but they could not  string it, for they were far lacking in strength.'),(14221,'Now Antinous was still persisting and godlike Eurymachus, leaders of the wooers, '),(14222,'who were far the best in valiance; '),(14223,' but those other two had gone forth both together from the hall, the neatherd and the swineherd of divine Odysseus; '),(14224,' and after them Odysseus himself went forth from the house. '),(14225,'But when they were now outside the gates and the court, he spoke and addressed them with gentle words:'),(14226,' \n“Neatherd, and thou too swineherd, shall I tell you something or keep it to myself?'),(14227,' Nay, my spirit bids me tell it.'),(14228,'  What manner of men would you be to defend Odysseus, if he should come from somewhere thus suddenly, and some god should bring him?'),(14229,' Would you bear aid to the wooers or to Odysseus?'),(14230,' Speak out as your heart and spirit bid you.\"'),(14231,'Then the herdsmen of the cattle answered him:'),(14232,'  “Father Zeus, oh that thou wouldest fulfil this wish! Grant that that man may come back, and that some god may guide him.'),(14233,' Then shouldest thou know what manner of might is mine, and how my hands obey.\"'),(14234,'And even in like manner did Eumaeus pray to all the gods that wise Odysseus; might come back to his own home. '),(14235,' \n  But when he knew with certainty the mind of these, he made answer, and spoke to them again, saying:'),(14236,'\n“At home now in truth am I here before you, my very self. After many grievous toils I am come in the twentieth year to my native land.'),(14237,' And I know that by you two  alone of all my thralls is my coming desired,'),(14238,'but of the rest have I heard not one praying that I might come back again to my home.'),(14239,' But to you two will I tell the truth, even as it shall be.'),(14240,' If a god shall subdue the lordly wooers unto me, I will bring you each a wife, and will give you possessions  and a house built near my own, '),(14241,'and thereafter you two shall be in my eyes friends and brothers of Telemachus.'),(14242,' Nay, come, more than this, I will shew you also a manifest sign, that you may know me well and be assured in heart, even the scar of the wound which long ago a boar dealt me with his white tusk,  when I went to Parnassus with the sons of Autolycus.\"'),(14243,'So saying, he drew aside the rags from the great scar.'),(14244,' And when the two had seen it, and had marked each thing well, they flung their arms about wise Odysseus, and wept; and they kissed his head and shoulders in loving welcome. And even in like manner Odysseus kissed their heads and hands.'),(14245,' And now the light of the sun would have gone down upon their weeping, had not Odysseus himself checked them, and said:'),(14246,'\n“Cease now from weeping and wailing, lest some one come forth from the hall and see us, and make it known within as well.'),(14247,'  But go within one after another, not all together, I first and you thereafter, '),(14248,'and let this be made a sign.'),(14249,' All the rest, as many as are lordly wooers, will not suffer the bow and the quiver to be given to me; '),(14250,'but do thou, goodly Eumaeus, as thou bearest the bow through the halls,  place it in my hands, and bid the women bar the close-fitting doors of their hall. And if any one of them hears groanings or the din of men within our walls, let them not rush out, but remain where they are in silence at their work.'),(14251,'  But to thee, goodly Philoetius, do I give charge to fasten with a bar the gate of the court, and swiftly to cast a cord upon it.\"'),(14252,'So saying, he entered the stately house,'),(14253,' and went and sat down on the seat from which he had risen. '),(14254,' And the two slaves of divine Odysseus went in as well.'),(14255,'\n  Eurymachus was now handling the bow, warming it on this side and on that in the light of the fire; '),(14256,' but not even so was he able to string it; and in his noble heart he groaned,'),(14257,' and with a burst of anger he spoke and addressed them:'),(14258,'“Out on it! Verily I am grieved for myself and for you all.'),(14259,'  It is in no wise for the marriage that I mourn so greatly, grieved though I am; '),(14260,'for there are many other Achaean women, some in sea-girt Ithaca itself, and some in other cities; '),(14261,' but I mourn if in truth we fall so far short of godlike Odysseus in might, seeing that we cannot string  his bow. '),(14262,'This is a reproach for men that are yet to be to hear of.”'),(14263,' \nThen Antinous, son of Eupeithes, answered him:'),(14264,'and thou of thyself too knowest it.'),(14265,'and thou of thyself too knowest it.'),(14266,' For to-day throughout the land is the feast of the god—a holy feast.'),(14267,' Who then would bend a bow?'),(14268,' Nay, quietly  set it by; '),(14269,'and as for the axes—what if we should let them all stand as they are?'),(14270,' No man, methinks, will come to the hall of Odysseus, son of Laertes, and carry them off.'),(14271,' Nay, come, let the bearer pour drops for libation into the cups, that we may pour libations, and lay aside the curved bow.'),(14272,'  And in the morning bid Melanthius, the goatherd, to bring she-goats, far the best in all the herds, that we may lay thigh-pieces on the altar of Apollo, the famed archer; and so make trial of the bow, and end the contest.\"'),(14273,'So spoke Antinous, and his word was pleasing to them.'),(14274,'  Then the heralds poured water over their hands, and youths filled the bowls brim full of drink, and served out to all, pouring first drops for libation into the cups.'),(14275,' But when they had poured libations, and had drunk to their heart\'s content, then with crafty mind Odysseus of many wiles spoke among them:'),(14276,'  “Hear me, wooers of the glorious queen,'),(14277,' that I may say what the heart in my breast bids me.'),(14278,' To Eurymachus most of all do I make my prayer, and to godlike Antinous, since this word also of his was spoken aright, namely that for the present you cease to try the bow, and leave the issue with the gods;'),(14279,' and in the morning the god will give the victory to whomsoever he will. '),(14280,' But come, give me the polished bow, that in your midst I may prove my hands and strength, whether I have yet might such as was of old in my supple limbs, or whether by now my wanderings and lack of food have destroyed it.”'),(14281,'  So he spoke, and they all waxed exceeding wroth, fearing lest he might string the polished bow.'),(14282,' And Antinous rebuked him, and spoke and addressed him:'),(14283,'\n“Ah, wretched stranger, thou hast no wit, no, not a trace. '),(14284,'Art thou not content  that thou feastest undisturbed in our proud company, and lackest naught of the banquet, but hearest our words and our speech, '),(14285,'while no other that is a stranger and beggar hears our words?'),(14286,' It is wine that wounds thee, honey-sweet wine, which works harm to others too, if one takes it in great gulps, and drinks beyond measure.'),(14287,'  It was wine that made foolish even the centaur, glorious Eurytion, in the hall of greathearted Peirithous, when he went to the Lapithae:'),(14288,' and when his heart had been made foolish with wine, in his madness he wrought evil in the house of Peirithous. '),(14289,' Then grief seized the heroes,  and they leapt up and dragged him forth through the gateway, when they had shorn off his ears and his nostrils with the pitiless bronze, '),(14290,' and he, made foolish in heart, went his way, bearing with him the curse of his sin in the folly of his heart.'),(14291,' From hence the feud arose between the centaurs and mankind; but it was for himself first that he found evil, being heavy with wine.'),(14292,'  Even so do I declare great harm for thee, if thou shalt string the bow,'),(14293,' for thou shalt meet with no kindness at the hands of anyone in our land, but we will send thee straightway in a black ship to king Echetus, the maimer of all men, '),(14294,'from whose hands thou shalt in no wise escape alive.'),(14295,' Nay, then, be still,  and drink thy wine, and do not strive with men younger than thou.”'),(14296,' \nThen wise Penelope answered him:'),(14297,' “Antinous, it is not well nor just to rob of their due the guests of Telemachus, whosoever he be that comes to this house. '),(14298,'Dost thou think that, if yon stranger  strings the great bow of Odysseus, trusting in his strength and his might, he will lead me to his home, and make me his wife?'),(14299,' Nay, he himself, I ween, has not this hope in his breast; '),(14300,'so let no one of you on this account sit at meat here in sorrow of heart; nay, that were indeed unseemly.\"'),(14301,'  Then Eurymachus, son of Polybus, answered her: '),(14302,'“Daughter of Icarius, wise Penelope, it is not that we think the man will lead thee to his home—'),(14303,'that were indeed unseemly—'),(14304,'but that we dread the talk of men and women, lest hereafter some base fellow among the Achaeans should say:  ‘Truly men weaker far are wooing the wife of a noble man, and cannot string his polished bow.'),(14305,' But another, a beggar, that came on his wanderings, easily strung the bow, and shot through the iron.'),(14306,'’ Thus will men speak, but to us this would become a reproach.\"'),(14307,'  Then wise Penelope answered him again:'),(14308,'“Eurymachus, in no wise can there be good report in the land for men who dishonor and consume the house of a prince.'),(14309,'  Why then do you make this matter a reproach?'),(14310,'This stranger is right tall and well-built,  and declares himself to be born the son of a good father.'),(14311,'Nay, come, give him the polished bow and let us see.'),(14312,' For thus will I speak out to thee, and this word shall verily be brought to pass; '),(14313,' if he shall string the bow, and Apollo grant him glory, I will clothe him with a cloak and tunic, fair raiment,  and will give him a sharp javelin to ward off dogs and men, and a two-edged sword; '),(14314,' and I will give him sandals to bind beneath his feet, and will send him whithersoever his heart and spirit bid him go.\"'),(14315,'Then wise Telemachus answered her: '),(14316,'“My mother, as for the bow, no man of the Achaeans  has a better right than I to give or to deny it to whomsoever I will—no, not all those who lord it in rocky Ithaca, or in the islands towards horse-pasturing Elis.'),(14317,' No man among these shall thwart me against my will, even though I should wish to give this bow outright to the stranger to bear away with him.'),(14318,'  But do thou go thy chamber, and busy thyself with thine own tasks, the loom and the distaff, and bid thy handmaids ply their tasks.'),(14319,' The bow shall be for men, for all, but most of all for me; '),(14320,'since mine is the authority in the house.” '),(14321,' \nShe then, seized with wonder, went back to her chamber, '),(14322,' for she laid to heart the wise saying of her son.'),(14323,'Up to her upper chamber she went with her handmaids, and then bewailed Odysseus, her dear husband, until flashing-eyed Athena cast sweet sleep upon her eyelids.'),(14324,'\nNow the goodly swineherd had taken the curved bow and was bearing it, '),(14325,' but the wooers all cried out in the halls. '),(14326,' And thus would one of the proud youths speak:'),(14327,'\n“Whither, pray, art thou bearing the curved bow, miserable swineherd, thou man distraught?'),(14328,' Soon by thy swine, alone and apart from men, shall the swift hounds devour thee—hounds thyself didst rear—if but Apollo  be gracious to us, and the other immortal gods.\"'),(14329,'So they spoke, and he set down the bow, as he bore it, in that very place, seized with fear because many men were crying out aloud in the halls.'),(14330,' But Telemachus on the other side called out threateningly:'),(14331,'“Father, bear the bow onward'),(14332,'—soon shalt thou rue giving heed to all—  lest, younger though I am, I drive thee to the field, and pelt thee with stones; '),(14333,'for in strength I am the better.'),(14334,'I would that I were even so much better in strength and might than all the wooers that are in the house;'),(14335,'  then would I soon send many a one  forth from our house to go his way in evil case; for they devise wickedness.\"'),(14336,'So he spoke, but all the wooers laughed merrily at him, and relaxed the bitterness of their anger against Telemachus.'),(14337,' Howbeit the swineherd bore the bow through the hall, and came up to wise Odysseus, and put it in his hands.'),(14338,'  Then he called forth the nurse Eurycleia, and said to her:'),(14339,'\n“Telemachus bids thee, wise Eurycleia, to bar the close-fitting doors of the hall,'),(14340,' and if any of the women hear within groanings or the din of men within our walls, let them not  rush out, but remain where they are in silence at their work.”'),(14341,'So he spoke, but her word remained unwinged; and she barred the doors of the stately halls.'),(14342,' \nBut in silence Philoetius hastened forth from the house, and barred the gates of the well-fenced court.'),(14343,'  Now there lay beneath the portico the cable of a curved ship, made of byblus plant, wherewith he made fast the gates, and then himself went within.'),(14344,' Thereafter he came and sat down on the seat from which he had risen, and gazed upon Odysseus; '),(14345,'now he was already handling the bow, turning it round and round, and trying it this way and that,  lest worms might have eaten the horns, while its lord was afar.'),(14346,' And thus would one speak with a glance at his neighbor:'),(14347,'“Verily he has a shrewd eye, and is a cunning knave with a bow.'),(14348,' It may be haply that he has himself such bows stored away at home, or else he is minded to make one, that he thus  turns it this way and that in his hands, the rascally vagabond.”'),(14349,' \nAnd again another of the proud youths would say:'),(14350,' “Would that the fellow might find profit in just such measure as he shall prove able ever to string this bow.\"'),(14351,'So spoke the wooers, '),(14352,'but Odysseus of many wiles,  as soon as he had lifted the great bow and scanned it on every side—even as when a man well-skilled in the lyre and in song easily stretches the string about a new peg, making fast at either end the twisted sheep-gut—so without effort did Odysseus string the great bow.'),(14353,'  And he held it in his right hand, and tried the string, '),(14354,'which sang sweetly beneath his touch, like to a swallow in tone.'),(14355,' But upon the wooers came great grief, and the faces of them changed color, '),(14356,' and Zeus thundered loud, shewing forth his signs.'),(14357,'Then glad at heart was the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus '),(14358,' that the son of crooked-counselling Cronos sent him an omen, '),(14359,' and he took up a swift arrow, which lay by him on the table, bare, '),(14360,' but the others were stored within the hollow quiver, even those of which the Achaeans were soon to taste.'),(14361,'This he took, and laid upon the bridge of the bow, and drew the bow-string and the notched arrow  even from the chair where he sat, and let fly the shaft with sure aim, and did not miss the end of the handle of one of the axes, but clean through and out at the end passed the arrow weighted with bronze. '),(14362,'But he spoke to Telemachus, saying:'),(14363,'“Telemachus, the stranger  that sits in thy halls brings no shame upon thee, nor in any wise did I miss the mark, or labour long in stringing the bow; '),(14364,'still is my strength unbroken—not as the wooers scornfully taunt me.'),(14365,' But now it is time that supper too be made ready for the Achaeans, while yet there is light, and thereafter must yet other sport be made  with song and with the lyre; '),(14366,'for these things are the accompaniments of a feast.\"'),(14367,'He spoke, and made a sign with his brows,'),(14368,' and Telemachus, the dear son of divine Odysseus, girt about him his sharp sword, and took his spear in his grasp, and stood by the chair at his father\'s side, armed with gleaming bronze.'),(14369,' But Odysseus of many wiles stripped off his rags and sprang to the great threshold with the bow and the quiver full of arrows, and poured forth the swift arrows right there before his feet, and spoke among the wooers:'),(14370,'  “Lo, now at last is this decisive contest ended;'),(14371,' and now as for another mark, which till now no man has ever smitten, I will know if haply I may strike it, and Apollo grant me glory.\"'),(14372,'He spoke, and aimed a bitter arrow at Antinous.'),(14373,'Now he was on the point of raising to his lips a fair goblet,  a two-eared cup of gold, and was even now handling it, that he might drink of the wine, '),(14374,'and death was not in his thoughts.'),(14375,' For who among men that sat at meat could think that one man among many, how strong soever he were, would bring upon himself evil death and black fate?'),(14376,'  But Odysseus took aim, and smote him with an arrow in the throat, and clean out through the tender neck passed the point;'),(14377,'he sank to one side, and the cup fell from his hand as he was smitten, and straightway up through his nostrils there came a thick jet of the blood of man; '),(14378,'and quickly  he thrust the table from him with a kick of his foot, and spilled all the food on the floor, '),(14379,' and the bread and roast flesh were befouled.'),(14380,' Then into uproar broke the wooers through the halls, as they saw the man fallen, and from their high seats they sprang, driven in fear through the hall, gazing everywhere along the well-built walls; '),(14381,' but nowhere was there a shield or mighty spear to seize. '),(14382,' But they railed at Odysseus with angry words:'),(14383,'\n“Stranger, to thy cost dost thou shoot at men; '),(14384,'never again shalt thou take part in other contests; '),(14385,'now is thy utter destruction sure.'),(14386,' Aye, for thou hast now slain a man who was far the best  of the youths in Ithaca; '),(14387,' therefore shall vultures devour thee here.”'),(14388,'So spoke each man, for verily they thought that he had not slain the man willfully; '),(14389,' and in their folly they knew not this, that over themselves one and all the cords of destruction had been made fast.'),(14390,' Then with an angry glance from beneath his brows Odysseus of many wiles answered them:'),(14391,'\n  “Ye dogs, ye thought that I should never more come home from the land of the Trojans, seeing that ye wasted my house, and lay with the maidservants by force, and while yet I lived covertly wooed my wife, having no fear of the gods, who hold broad heaven,  nor of the indignation of men, that is to be hereafter. '),(14392,' Now over you one and all have the cords of destruction been made fast.” '),(14393,' \nSo he spoke, and thereat pale fear seized them all, '),(14394,' \nand each man gazed about to see how he might escape utter destruction;'),(14395,'Eurymachus alone answered him, and said:'),(14396,'\n  “If thou art indeed Odysseus of Ithaca, come home again, this that thou sayest is just regarding all that the Achaeans have wrought—many deeds of wanton folly in thy halls and many in the field.'),(14397,' But he now lies dead, who was to blame for all, even Antinous; '),(14398,' for it was he who set on foot these deeds,  not so much through desire or need of the marriage, but with another purpose, which the son of Cronos did not bring to pass for him, that in the land of settled Ithaca he might himself be king, and might lie in wait for thy son and slay him.'),(14399,' But now he lies slain, as was his due, but do thou spare the people  that are thine own; '),(14400,'  and we will hereafter go about the land and get thee recompense for all that has been drunk and eaten in thy halls, and will bring each man for himself in requital the worth of twenty oxen, and pay thee back in bronze and gold until thy heart be warmed; '),(14401,' but till then no one could blame thee that thou art wroth.\"'),(14402,'  Then with an angry glance from beneath his brows Odysseus of many wiles answered him: '),(14403,'“Eurymachus, not even if you should give me in requital all that your fathers left you, even all that you now have, and should add other wealth thereto from whence ye might, not even so would I henceforth stay my hands from slaying until the wooers had paid the full price of all their transgression.'),(14404,'  Now it lies before you to fight in open fight, or to flee, if any man may avoid death and the fates; '),(14405,'but many a one, methinks, shall not escape from utter destruction.”'),(14406,'So he spoke, and their knees were loosened where they stood, and their hearts melted; '),(14407,'and Eurymachus spoke among them again a second time:'),(14408,'\n  “Friends, for you see that this man will not stay his invincible hands, but now that he was got the polished bow and the quiver, will shoot from the smooth threshold until he slays us all, '),(14409,'come, let us take thought of battle.'),(14410,'Draw your swords, and hold the tables before you against  the arrows that bring swift death,'),(14411,' and let us all have at him in a body, in the hope that we may thrust him from the threshold and the doorway, and go throughout the city, and so the alarm be swiftly raised; '),(14412,'then should this fellow soon have shot his last.” '),(14413,' \nSo saying, he drew his sharp sword  of bronze, two-edged, and sprang upon Odysseus with a terrible cry,'),(14414,'but at the same instant goodly Odysseus let fly an arrow, and struck him upon the breast beside the nipple, and fixed the swift shaft in his liver. '),(14415,' And Eurymachus let the sword fall from his hand to the ground, and writhing over the table  he bowed and fell, and spilt upon the floor the food and the two-handled cup.'),(14416,' With his brow he beat the earth in agony of soul, and with both his feet he spurned and shook the chair, '),(14417,'and a mist was shed over his eyes.'),(14418,'Then Amphinomus made at glorious Odysseus,  rushing straight upon him, and had drawn his sharp sword, in hope that Odysseus might give way before him from the door.'),(14419,' But Telemachus was too quick for him, and cast, and smote him from behind with his bronze-tipped spear between the shoulders, and drove it through his breast; '),(14420,' and he fell with a thud, and struck the ground full with his forehead.'),(14421,'  But Telemachus sprang back, leaving the long spear where it was, fixed in Amphinomus, '),(14422,'for he greatly feared lest, as he sought to draw forth the long spear, one of the Achaeans might rush upon him and stab with his sword, or deal him a blow as he stooped over the corpse.'),(14423,' So he started to run, and came quickly to his dear father,  and standing by his side spoke to him winged words: '),(14424,'“Father, now will I bring thee a shield and two spears and a helmet all of bronze, well fitted to the temples, and when I come back I will arm myself, and will give armour likewise to the swineherd and yon neatherd; '),(14425,'for it is better to be clothed in armour.\"'),(14426,'  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him and said: '),(14427,'“Run, and bring them, while yet I have arrows to defend me, lest they thrust me from the door, alone as I am.\"'),(14428,'So he spoke, and Telemachus hearkened to his dear father, and went his way to the store-chamber where the glorious arms were stored.'),(14429,'  Thence he took four shields and eight spears and four helmets of bronze, with thick plumes of horse-hair; '),(14430,' and he bore them forth, and quickly came to his dear father. Then first of all he himself girded the bronze about his body,'),(14431,'  and even in like manner the two slaves put on them the beautiful armour,  and took their stand on either side of Odysseus, the wise and crafty-minded.'),(14432,' But he, so long as he had arrows to defend him, '),(14433,'would ever aim, and smite the wooers one by one in his house, '),(14434,'and they fell thick and fast.'),(14435,'But when the arrows failed the prince, as he shot,  he leaned the bow against the door-post of the well-built hall, and let it stand against the bright entrance wall. For himself, he put about his shoulders a four-fold shield, and set on his mighty head a well-wrought helmet with horse-hair plume, and terribly did the plume wave above him; '),(14436,'  and he took two mighty spears, tipped with bronze.'),(14437,' \nNow there was in the well-built wall a certain postern door, and along the topmost level of the threshold of the well-built hall was a way into a passage, and well-fitting folding doors closed it.'),(14438,' This postern Odysseus bade the goodly swineherd watch,  taking his stand close by, '),(14439,'for there was but a single way to reach it.'),(14440,'Then Agelaus spoke among the wooers, and declared his word to all:'),(14441,'\n“Friends, will not one mount up by the postern door, and tell the people, that so an alarm may be raised straightway?'),(14442,' Then should this fellow soon have shot his last.”'),(14443,'\n  Then Melanthius, the goatherd, answered him:'),(14444,' “It may not be, Agelaus, fostered of Zeus,'),(14445,' for terribly near is the fair door of the court, and the mouth of the passage is hard.'),(14446,' One man could bar the way for all, so he were valiant.'),(14447,' But come, let me bring you  from the store-room arms to don, '),(14448,'for it is within, methinks, and nowhere else that Odysseus and his glorious son have laid the arms.\"'),(14449,'So saying, Melanthius, the goatherd, mounted up by the steps of the hall to the store-rooms of Odysseus.'),(14450,' Thence he took twelve shields, as many spears,  and as many helmets of bronze with thick plumes of horsehair, '),(14451,'and went his way, and quickly brought and gave them to the wooers.'),(14452,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 22.147-22.149'),(14453,' Then the knees of Odysseus were loosened and his heart melted, when he saw them donning armour and brandishing long spears in their hands, ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 147 to line 149'),(14454,'  but quickly he spoke to Telemachus winged words:'),(14455,'“Telemachus, verily some one of the women in the halls is rousing against us an evil battle, or haply it is Melanthius.\"'),(14456,'Then wise Telemachus answered him: '),(14457,'“Father, it is I myself that am at fault in this, and no other  is to blame, for I left the close-fitting door of the store-room open:'),(14458,' their watcher was better than I.'),(14459,' But go now, goodly Eumaeus, close the door of the store-room, and see whether it is one of the women who does this, or Melanthius, son of Dolius, as I suspect.”'),(14460,'  Thus they spoke to one another. But Melanthius, the goatherd, went again to the store-room to bring beautiful armour; '),(14461,'howbeit the goodly swineherd marked him, and straightway said to Odysseus who was near:'),(14462,'“Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices,  yonder again is the pestilent fellow, whom we ourselves suspect, going to the store-room.'),(14463,' But do thou tell me truly, shall I slay him, if I prove the better man, or shall I bring him hither to thee, that the fellow may pay for the many crimes that he has planned in thy house?” '),(14464,' \n  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him and said: '),(14465,'  “Verily I and Telemachus will keep the lordly wooers within the hall, how fierce soever they be, '),(14466,' but do you two bend behind him his feet and his arms above, and cast him into the store-room, and tie boards behind his back;  then make fast to his body a twisted rope, and hoist him up the tall pillar, till you bring him near the roof-beams, that he may keep alive long, and suffer grievous torment.\"'),(14467,'So he spoke, and they readily hearkened and obeyed. Forth they went to the store-room, unseen of him who was within.'),(14468,'  He truly was seeking for armour in the innermost part of the store-room, and the two lay in wait, standing on either side of the door-posts.'),(14469,' And when Melanthius, the goatherd, was about to pass over the threshold, bearing in one hand a goodly helm, and in the other a broad old shield, flecked with rust—  the shield of lord Laertes, which he was wont to bear in his youth, '),(14470,' but now it was laid by, and the seams of its straps were loosened'),(14471,' —then the two sprang upon him and seized him. They dragged him in by the hair, and flung him down on the ground in sore terror, and bound his feet and hands with galling bonds,  binding them firmly behind his back, as the son of Laertes bade them, the much enduring, goodly Odysseus; '),(14472,'and they made fast to his body a twisted rope, and hoisted him up the tall pillar, till they brought him near the roof-beams.'),(14473,' Then didst thou mock him, swineherd Eumaeus, and say:'),(14474,'\n  “Now verily, Melanthius, shalt thou watch the whole night through, lying on a soft bed, as befits thee,'),(14475,'nor shalt thou fail to mark the early Dawn, golden-throned, as she comes forth from the streams of Oceanus, at the hour when thou art wont to drive thy she-goats for the wooers, to prepare a feast in the halls.\"'),(14476,'  So he was left there, stretched in the direful bond,'),(14477,'but the two put on their armour, and closed the bright door, and went to Odysseus, the wise and crafty-minded.'),(14478,' There they stood, breathing fury, those on the threshold but four, while those within the hall were many and brave.'),(14479,'  Then Athena, daughter of Zeus, drew near them, like unto Mentor in form and voice, '),(14480,'and Odysseus saw her, and was glad; and he spoke, saying:'),(14481,'\n“Mentor, ward off ruin, and remember me, thy dear comrade, who often befriended thee.'),(14482,' Thou art of like age with myself.” '),(14483,' \n  So he spoke, deeming that it was Athena, the rouser of hosts.'),(14484,'  But the wooers on the other side shouted aloud in the hall,'),(14485,' and first Agelaus, son of Damastor, rebuked Athena, saying:'),(14486,'\n“Mentor, let not Odysseus beguile thee with his words to fight against the wooers and bear aid to himself.'),(14487,'  For in this wise, methinks, shall our will be brought to pass: '),(14488,'when we have killed these men, father and son, thereafter shalt thou too be slain with them, such deeds art thou minded to do in these halls:'),(14489,' with thine own head shalt thou pay the price.'),(14490,' But when with the sword we have stripped you of your might,  all the possessions that thou hast within doors and in the fields we will mingle with those of Odysseus, '),(14491,'  and will not suffer thy sons or thy daughters to dwell in thy halls, nor thy faithful wife to fare at large in the city of Ithaca.\"'),(14492,'So he spoke, and Athena waxed the more wroth at heart,  and she rebuked Odysseus with angry words:'),(14493,'\"Odysseus, no longer hast thou steadfast might nor any valor, such as was thine when for high-born Helen of the white arms thou didst for nine years battle with the Trojans unceasingly, and many men thou slewest in dread conflict,  and by thy counsel was the broad-wayed city of Priam taken.'),(14494,'How is it that now, when thou hast come to thy house and thine own possessions, thou shrinkest with wailing from playing the man, and that against the wooers?'),(14495,' Nay, friend, come hither and take thy stand by my side, and see my deeds, that thou mayest know what manner of man  Mentor, son of Alcimus, is to repay kindness in the midst of the foe.\"'),(14496,'She spoke, but did not give him strength utterly to turn the course of the battle, but still made trial of the might and valor of Odysseus and his glorious son;'),(14497,' and for herself,  she flew up to the roof-beam of the smoky hall, and sat there in the guise of a swallow to look upon.'),(14498,'Now the wooers were urged on by Agelaus, son of Damastor, by Eurynomus, and Amphimedon and Demoptolemus and Peisander, son of Polyctor, and wise Polybus,'),(14499,' for these were in valiance far the best of all the wooers  who still lived and fought for their lives; '),(14500,'but the rest the bow and the swiftly-falling arrows had by now laid low.'),(14501,' But Agelaus spoke among them, and declared his word to all:'),(14502,'\n“Friends, now at length will this man stay his invincible hands.'),(14503,' Lo, Mentor has gone from him, and has but uttered empty boasts,  and they are left alone there at the outer doors.'),(14504,'Therefore hurl not now upon them your long spears all at once, but come, do you six throw first in the hope that Zeus may grant that Odysseus be struck, and that we win glory.'),(14505,' Of the rest there is no care, once he shall have fallen.” '),(14506,' \n  So he spoke, and they all hurled their spears, as he bade, eagerly; '),(14507,' but Athena made all vain. One man smote the door-post of the well-built hall, another the close-fitting door,'),(14508,' another\'s ashen spear, heavy with bronze, struck upon the wall.'),(14509,'  But when they had avoided the spears of the wooers, first among them spoke the much-enduring goodly Odysseus:'),(14510,'\n“Friends, now I give the word that we too cast our spears into the throng of the wooers, who are minded to slay us in addition to their former wrongs.”'),(14511,'\n  So he spoke, and they all hurled their sharp spears with sure aim.'),(14512,' Odysseus smote Demoptolemus, Telemachus Euryades, the swineherd Elatus, and the herdsmen of the cattle slew Peisander.'),(14513,' So these all at the same moment bit the vast floor with their teeth,  and the wooers drew back to the innermost part of the hall.'),(14514,' But the others sprang forward and drew forth their spears from the dead bodies.'),(14515,'\nThen again the wooers hurled their sharp spears eagerly, '),(14516,'but Athena made them vain, many as they were. '),(14517,' One man  smote the door-post of the well-built hall, another the close-fitting door, '),(14518,' another\'s ashen spear, heavy with bronze, struck upon the wall.'),(14519,' But Amphimedon smote Telemachus on the hand by the wrist, a grazing blow, and the bronze tore the surface of the skin.'),(14520,' And Ctesippus with his long spear  grazed the shoulder of Eumaeus above his shield, '),(14521,' but the spear flew over and fell upon the ground.'),(14522,'Then once more Odysseus, the wise and crafty-minded, and his company hurled their sharp spears into the throng of the wooers,'),(14523,'  and again Odysseus, the sacker of cities, smote Eurydamas, and Telemachus Amphimedon, the swineherd Polybus,'),(14524,' and thereafter the herdsman of the cattle smote Ctesippus in the breast, and boasted over him, saying:'),(14525,'\n“Son of Polytherses, thou lover of revilings, never more at all do thou speak big, yielding to folly, but leave the matter to the gods, since verily they are mightier far.'),(14526,'  This is thy gift of welcome to match the hoof which of late thou gavest to godlike Odysseus, when he went begging through the house.” '),(14527,' \nSo spoke the herdsman of the sleek cattle.'),(14528,' But Odysseus wounded the son of Damastor in close fight with a thrust of his long spear, '),(14529,'and Telemachus wounded Leiocritus, son of Evenor,  with a spear-thrust full upon the groin, and drove the bronze clean through, '),(14530,' and he fell headlong and struck the ground full with his forehead.'),(14531,' Then Athena held up her aegis, the bane of mortals, on high from the roof, '),(14532,' and the minds of the wooers were panic-stricken, '),(14533,'and they fled through the halls like a herd of kine '),(14534,' that the darting gad-fly falls upon and drives along in the season of spring, when the long days come.'),(14535,' And even as vultures of crooked talons and curved beaks come forth from the mountains and dart upon smaller birds,'),(14536,' which scour the plain, flying low beneath the clouds,  and the vultures pounce upon them and slay them, and they have no defence or way of escape, '),(14537,' and men rejoice at the chase; '),(14538,' even so did those others set upon the wooers and smite them left and right through the hall.'),(14539,' And therefrom rose hideous groaning as heads were smitten, and all the floor swam with blood.'),(14540,'\n  But Leiodes rushed forward and clasped the knees of Odysseus, and made entreaty to him, and spoke winged words:'),(14541,'and do thou respect me and have pity.'),(14542,'and do thou respect me and have pity.'),(14543,' For I declare to thee that never yet have I wronged one of the women in thy halls by wanton word or deed; '),(14544,' nay,  I sought to check the other wooers, when any would do such deeds.'),(14545,' But they would not hearken to me to withhold their hands from evil, '),(14546,'wherefore through their wanton folly they have met a cruel doom.'),(14547,' Yet I, the soothsayer among them, that have done no wrong, shall be laid low even as they; so true is it that there is no gratitude in aftertime for good deeds done.\"'),(14548,'  Then with an angry glance from beneath his brows Odysseus of many wiles answered him: '),(14549,'“If verily thou dost declare thyself the soothsayer among these men, often, I ween, must thou have prayed in the halls that far from me the issue of a joyous return might be removed, and that it might be with thee that my dear wife should go and bear thee children; '),(14550,' wherefore thou shalt not escape grievous death.”'),(14551,'So saying, he seized in his strong hand a sword that lay near, which Agelaus had let fall to the ground when he was slain, '),(14552,'and with this he smote him full upon the neck.'),(14553,' And even while he was yet speaking his head was mingled with the dust. '),(14554,' \n  Now the son of Terpes, the minstrel, was still seeking to escape black fate, even Phemius, who sang perforce among the wooers.'),(14555,' He stood with the clear-toned lyre in his hands near the postern door, '),(14556,'and he was divided in mind whether he should slip out from the hall  and sit down by the well-built altar of great Zeus, the God of the court, whereon Laertes and Odysseus had burned many things of oxen, or whether he should rush forward and clasp the knees of Odysseus in prayer.'),(14557,' And as he pondered this seemed to him the better course, to clasp the knees of Odysseus, son of Laertes.'),(14558,'  So he laid the hollow lyre on the ground between the mixing-bowl and the silver-studded chair, and himself rushed forward and clasped Odysseus by the knees, and made entreaty to him, and spoke winged words:'),(14559,' and do thou respect me and have pity; '),(14560,' and do thou respect me and have pity; '),(14561,' on thine own self shall sorrow come hereafter, if thou slayest the minstrel, even me, who sing to gods and men.'),(14562,' Self-taught am I, and the god has planted in my heart all manner of lays, '),(14563,' and worthy am I to sing to thee as to a god; '),(14564,'wherefore be not eager to cut my throat.'),(14565,'  Aye, and Telemachus too will bear witness to this, thy dear son, how that through no will or desire of mine I was wont to resort to thy house to sing to the wooers at their feasts, but they, being far more and stronger, led me hither perforce.\"'),(14566,'So he spoke, and the strong and mighty Telemachus heard him,  and quickly spoke to his father, who was near:'),(14567,'“Stay thy hand, and do not wound this guiltless man with the sword.'),(14568,' Aye, and let us save also the herald, Medon, who ever cared for me in our house, when I was a child—unless perchance Philoetius has already slain him, or the swineherd,  or he met thee as thou didst rage through the house.\"'),(14569,'So he spoke, and Medon, wise of heart, heard him,'),(14570,' for he lay crouching beneath a chair, and had clothed himself in the skin of an ox, newly flayed, seeking to avoid black fate.'),(14571,'Straightway he rose from beneath the chair and stripped off the ox-hide,  and then rushed forward and clasped Telemachus by the knees, and made entreaty to him, and spoke winged words:'),(14572,' \n“Friend, here I am; stay thou thy hand and bid thy father stay his, lest in the greatness of his might he harm me with the sharp bronze in his wrath against the wooers, who wasted his  possessions in the halls, and in their folly honored thee not at all.”'),(14573,'\nBut Odysseus of many wiles smiled, and said to him:'),(14574,' “Be of good cheer, for he has delivered thee and saved thee, that thou mayest know in thy heart and tell also to another, how far better is the doing of good deeds than of evil.'),(14575,'  But go forth from the halls and sit down outside in the court away from the slaughter, thou and the minstrel of many songs, till I shall have finished all that I must needs do in the house.” '),(14576,' \nSo he spoke, and the two went their way forth from the hall and sat down by the altar of great Zeus,  gazing about on every side, ever expecting death. '),(14577,' And Odysseus too gazed about all through his house to see if any man yet lived, and was hiding there, seeking to avoid black fate.'),(14578,'  But he found them one and all fallen in the blood and dust—all the host of them, like fishes that fishermen  have drawn forth in the meshes of their net from the grey sea upon the curving beach,  '),(14579,'and they all lie heaped upon the sand, longing for the waves of the sea, '),(14580,'and the bright sun takes away their life;'),(14581,'even so now the wooers lay heaped upon each other.'),(14582,'   Then Odysseus of many wiles spoke to Telemachus:'),(14583,'\n“Telemachus, go call me the nurse Eurycleia, that I may tell her the word that is in my mind.”'),(14584,'\nSo he spoke, and Telemachus hearkened to his dear father, and shaking the door said to Eurycleia:'),(14585,'\n  “Up and hither, aged wife, that hast charge of all our woman servants in the halls.'),(14586,'  my father calls thee, that he may tell thee somewhat.\"'),(14587,'  my father calls thee, that he may tell thee somewhat.\"'),(14588,'So he spoke, but her word remained unwinged; she opened the doors of the stately hall,  and came forth, '),(14589,'and Telemachus led the way before her.'),(14590,' There she found Odysseus amid the bodies of the slain, all befouled with blood and filth, like a lion that comes from feeding on an ox of the farmstead,'),(14591,' and all his breast and his cheeks on either side  are stained with blood, and he is terrible to look upon;'),(14592,' even so was Odysseus befouled, his feet and his hands above.'),(14593,' But she, when she beheld the corpses and the great welter of blood, made ready to utter loud cries of joy, seeing what a deed had been wrought.'),(14594,' But Odysseus stayed and checked her in her eagerness,  and spoke and addressed her with winged words:'),(14595,'\n“In thine own heart rejoice, old dame, but refrain thyself and cry not out aloud:'),(14596,' an unholy thing is it to boast over slain men.'),(14597,' These men here has the fate of the gods destroyed and their own reckless deeds, '),(14598,'for they honored no one of men upon the earth,  were he evil or good, whosoever came among them; '),(14599,'wherefore by their wanton folly they brought on themselves a shameful death.'),(14600,' But come, name thou over to me the women in the halls, which ones dishonor me and which are guiltless.\"'),(14601,'Then the dear nurse Eurycleia answered him:'),(14602,' “Then verily, my child, will I tell thee all the truth.'),(14603,'  Fifty women servants hast thou in the halls, women that we have taught to do their work, to card the wool and bear the lot of slaves.'),(14604,' Of these twelve in all have set their feet in the way of shamelessness,  and regard not me nor Penelope herself. '),(14605,'And Telemachus is but newly grown to manhood, and his mother would not suffer him to rule over the women servants.'),(14606,' But come, let me go up to the bright upper chamber and bear word to thy wife, on whom some god has sent sleep.” '),(14607,' \n  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said:'),(14608,' “Wake her not yet, but do thou bid come hither the women, who in time past have contrived shameful deeds.\"'),(14609,'So he spoke, and the old dame went forth through the hall to bear tidings to the women, and bid them come; '),(14610,'  but Odysseus called to him Telemachus and the neatherd and the swineherd, and spoke to them winged words:'),(14611,'\n“Begin now to bear forth the dead bodies and bid the women help you, '),(14612,' and thereafter cleanse the beautiful chairs and the tables with water and porous sponges.'),(14613,'  But when you have set all the house in order, lead the women forth from the well-built hall to a place between the dome and the goodly fence of the court, and there strike them down with your long swords, until you take away the life from them all, and they forget the love  which they had at the bidding of the wooers, when they lay with them in secret.”'),(14614,'So he spoke, and the women came all in a throng, wailing terribly and shedding big tears.'),(14615,' First they bore forth the bodies of the slain and set them down beneath the portico of the well-fenced court,  propping them one against the other; '),(14616,' and Odysseus himself gave them orders and hastened on the work, '),(14617,' and they bore the bodies forth perforce.'),(14618,' Then they cleansed the beautiful high seats and the tables with water and porous sponges. '),(14619,'But Telemachus and the neatherd and the swineherd  scraped with hoes the floor of the well-built house,'),(14620,'and the women bore the scrapings forth and threw them out of doors.'),(14621,' But when they had set in order all the hall, they led the women forth from the well-built hall to a place between the dome and the goodly fence of the court,  and shut them up in a narrow space, whence it was in no wise possible to escape. '),(14622,' Then wise Telemachus was the first to speak to the others, saying:'),(14623,'\n“Let it be by no clean death that I take the lives of these women, who on my own head have poured reproaches and on my mother, and were wont to lie with the wooers.” '),(14624,' \n  So he spoke, and tied the cable of a dark-prowed ship to a great pillar and flung it round the dome, stretching it on high that none might reach the ground with her feet.'),(14625,' And as when long-winged thrushes or doves fall into a snare that is set in a thicket,  as they seek to reach their resting-place, and hateful is the bed that gives them welcome, even so the women held their heads in a row, and round the necks of all nooses were laid, that they might die most piteously.'),(14626,'And they writhed a little while with their feet, but not long.'),(14627,'Then forth they led Melanthius through the doorway and the court, '),(14628,' and cut off his nostrils and his ears with the pitiless bronze, and drew out his vitals for the dogs to eat raw, and cut off his hands and his feet in their furious wrath.'),(14629,'Thereafter they washed their hands and feet, and went into the house to Odysseus, and the work was done. '),(14630,' But Odysseus said to the dear nurse Eurycleia:'),(14631,' “Bring sulphur, old dame, to cleanse from pollution, and bring me fire, that I may purge the hall;'),(14632,' and do thou bid Penelope come hither with her handmaidens, '),(14633,'and order all the women in the house to come.\"'),(14634,'  Then the dear nurse Eurycleia answered him:'),(14635,' “Yea, all this, my child, hast thou spoken aright. '),(14636,'But come, let me bring thee a cloak and a tunic for raiment, and do not thou stand thus in the halls with thy broad shoulders wrapped in rags; '),(14637,' that were a cause for blame.”'),(14638,'\n  Then Odysseus of many wiles answered her: '),(14639,'“First of all let a fire now be made me in the hall.\"'),(14640,'So he spoke, and the dear nurse Eurycleia did not disobey, but brought fire and sulphur;'),(14641,'but Odysseus throughly purged the hall and the house and the court.'),(14642,'\n  Then the old dame went back through the fair house of Odysseus to bear tidings to the women and bid them come; '),(14643,' and they came forth from their hall with torches in their hands.'),(14644,' They thronged about Odysseus and embraced him, and clasped and kissed his head and shoulders  and his hands in loving welcome; '),(14645,'and a sweet longing seized him to weep and wail, for in his heart he knew them all.'),(14646,' Then the old dame went up to the upper chamber, laughing aloud, to tell her mistress that her dear husband was in the house.'),(14647,' Her knees moved nimbly, but her feet trotted along beneath her; '),(14648,'and she stood above her lady\'s head, and spoke to her, and said:'),(14649,'\n  “Awake, Penelope, dear child, that with thine own eyes thou mayest see what thou desirest all thy days.'),(14650,' Odysseus is here, and has come home, late though his coming has been, '),(14651,'and has slain the proud wooers who vexed his house, and devoured his substance, and oppressed his son.\"'),(14652,'  Then wise Penelope answered her:'),(14653,'“Dear nurse, the gods have made thee mad, they who can make foolish even one who is full wise, and set the simple-minded in the paths of understanding; '),(14654,'though heretofore thou wast sound of mind.'),(14655,'though heretofore thou wast sound of mind.'),(14656,'  Why dost thou mock me, who have a heart full of sorrow, to tell me this wild tale, and dost rouse me out of slumber, the sweet slumber that bound me and enfolded my eyelids?'),(14657,' For never yet have I slept so sound since the day when Odysseus went forth to see evil Ilios that should not be named.'),(14658,'  Nay come now, go down and back to the women\'s hall,'),(14659,' for if any other of the women that are mine had come and told me this, and had roused me out of sleep, straightway would I have sent her back in sorry wise to return again to the hall,'),(14660,' but to thee old age shall bring this profit.”'),(14661,'  Then the dear nurse Eurycleia answered her: '),(14662,' “I mock thee not, dear child, but in very truth Odysseus is here, and has come home, even as I tell thee. He is that stranger to whom all men did dishonor in the halls. '),(14663,'But Telemachus long ago knew that he was here,  yet in his prudence he hid the purpose of his father, till he should take vengeance on the violence of overweening men.\"'),(14664,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 23.32-23.33'),(14665,'So she spoke, and Penelope was glad, and she leapt from her bed and flung her arms about the old woman and let the tears fall from her eyelids; ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 32 to line 33'),(14666,'\n  “Come now, dear nurse, I pray thee tell me truly, if verily he has come home, as thou sayest, how he put forth his hands upon the shameless wooers, all alone as he was, while they remained always in a body in the house.\"'),(14667,'Then the dear nurse Eurycleia answered her:'),(14668,'  “I saw not, I asked not; only I heard the groaning of men that were being slain.'),(14669,' As for us women, we sat terror-stricken in the innermost part of our well-built chambers, and the close-fitting doors shut us in, until the hour when thy son Telemachus called me from the hall, '),(14670,'for his father had sent him forth to call me.'),(14671,'  Then I found Odysseus standing among the bodies of the slain, '),(14672,'and they, stretched all around him on the hard floor, lay one upon the other; '),(14673,'the sight would have warmed thy heart with cheer. '),(14674,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 23.48-23.51'),(14675,'and sent me forth to call thee.'),(14676,' Nay, come with me, that the hearts of you two may enter into joy, for you have suffered many woes.'),(14677,' But now at length has this thy long desire been fulfilled:'),(14678,'  he has come himself, alive to his own hearth, and he has found both thee and his son in the halls;'),(14679,'while as for those, even the wooers, who wrought him evil, on them has he taken vengeance one and all in his house.\"'),(14680,'Then wise Penelope answered her:'),(14681,' “Dear nurse, boast not yet loudly over them with laughter.'),(14682,'  Thou knowest how welcome the sight of him in the halls would be to all, but above all to me and to his son, born of us two.'),(14683,' But this is no true tale, as thou tellest it; nay, some one of the immortals has slain the lordly wooers in wrath at their grievous insolence and their evil deeds.'),(14684,'  For they honored no one among men upon the earth, were he evil or good, whosoever came among them; '),(14685,'therefore it is through their own wanton folly that they have suffered evil.'),(14686,' But Odysseus far away has lost his return to the land of Achaea, and is lost himself.\"'),(14687,'Then the dear nurse Eurycleia answered her:'),(14688,'  “My child, what a word has escaped the barrier of thy teeth, in that thou saidst that thy husband, who even now is here, at his own hearth, would never more return!'),(14689,' Thy heart is ever unbelieving.'),(14690,' Nay come, I will tell thee a manifest sign besides, even the scar of the wound which long ago the boar dealt him with his white tusk.'),(14691,'  This I marked while I washed his feet, and was fain to tell it to thee as well, '),(14692,' but he laid his hand upon my mouth, and in the great wisdom of his heart would not suffer me to speak.'),(14693,' So come with me;'),(14694,'  but I will set my very life at stake that, if I deceive thee, thou shouldest slay me by a most pitiful death.\"'),(14695,'  Then wise Penelope answered her: '),(14696,'“Dear nurse, it is hard for thee to comprehend the counsels of the gods that are forever, how wise soever thou art.'),(14697,' Nevertheless let us go to my son, that I may see the wooers dead and him that slew them.” '),(14698,' \n  So saying, she went down from the upper chamber,'),(14699,'and much her heart pondered whether she should stand aloof and question her dear husband, or whether she should go up to him, and clasp and kiss his head and hands.'),(14700,' But when she had come in and had passed over the stone threshold, she sat down opposite Odysseus in the light of the fire  beside the further wall; '),(14701,'but he was sitting by a tall pillar, looking down, and waiting to see whether his noble wife would say aught to him, when her eyes beheld him.'),(14702,' Howbeit she sat long in silence, and amazement came upon her soul; '),(14703,'and now with her eyes she would look full upon his face, and now again  she would fail to know him, for that he had upon him mean raiment. '),(14704,' But Telemachus rebuked her, and spoke, and addressed her:'),(14705,'\n“My mother, cruel mother, that hast an unyielding heart, why dost thou thus hold aloof from my father, and dost not sit by his side and ask and question him?'),(14706,'  No other woman would harden her heart as thou dost, and stand aloof from her husband, who after many grievous toils had come back to her in the twentieth year to his native land:'),(14707,' but thy heart is ever harder than stone.” '),(14708,'Then wise Penelope answered him:'),(14709,'  “My child, the heart in my breast is lost in wonder, and I have no power to speak at all, nor to ask a question, nor to look him in the face.'),(14710,' But if in very truth he is Odysseus, and has come home, we two shall surely know one another more certainly; '),(14711,' for we have signs which we two alone know, signs hidden from others.”'),(14712,'So she spoke, and the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus smiled, and straightway spoke to Telemachus winged words:'),(14713,'\n“Telemachus, suffer now thy mother to test me in the halls; '),(14714,'presently shall she win more certain knowledge.'),(14715,'  But now because I am foul, and am clad about my body in mean clothing, she scorns me, and will not yet admit that I am he.'),(14716,' But for us, let us take thought how all may be the very best. '),(14717,'For whoso has slain but one man in a land, even though it be a man that leaves not many behind to avenge him,  he goes into exile, and leaves his kindred and his native land;'),(14718,' but we have slain those who were the very stay of the city, far the noblest of the youths of Ithaca.'),(14719,' Of this I bid thee take thought.”'),(14720,'Then wise Telemachus answered him:'),(14721,' “Do thou thyself look to this, dear father; '),(14722,'for thy  counsel, they say, is the best among men, nor could any other of mortal men vie with thee.'),(14723,' As for us, we will follow with thee eagerly, nor methinks shall we be wanting in valor, so far as we have strength.” '),(14724,' \nThen Odysseus of many wiles answered him and said:  “Then will I tell thee what seems to me to be the best way.'),(14725,' First bathe yourselves, and put on your tunics, and bid the handmaids in the halls to take their raiment. '),(14726,'But let the divine minstrel with his clear-toned lyre in hand be our leader in the gladsome dance,  that any man who hears the sound from without, whether a passer-by or one of those who dwell around, may say that it is a wedding feast; '),(14727,'and so the rumor of the slaying of the wooers shall not be spread abroad throughout the city before we go forth to our well-wooded farm.'),(14728,' There  shall we afterwards devise whatever advantage the Olympian may vouchsafe us.”'),(14729,'So he spoke, and they all readily hearkened and obeyed. First they bathed and put on their tunics, and the women arrayed themselves, '),(14730,' and the divine minstrel took the hollow lyre and aroused in them the desire  of sweet song and goodly dance. '),(14731,' So the great hall resounded all about with the tread of dancing men and of fair-girdled women; '),(14732,'and thus would one speak who heard the noise from without the house:'),(14733,'“Aye, verily some one has wedded the queen wooed of many.'),(14734,' Cruel she was, nor had she the heart to keep the great house of her wedded husband to the end, even till he should come.”'),(14735,'So they would say, but they knew not how these things were.'),(14736,'Meanwhile the housewife Eurynome bathed the great-hearted Odysseus in his house, and anointed him with oil,  and cast about him a fair cloak and a tunic; '),(14737,' and over his head Athena shed abundant beauty, making him taller to look upon and mightier, '),(14738,' and from his head she made locks to flow in curls like the hyacinth flower.'),(14739,'And as when a man overlays silver with gold,  a cunning workman whom Hephaestus and Pallas Athena have taught all manner of craft, and full of grace is the work he produces,'),(14740,' even so the goddess shed grace on his head and shoulders, '),(14741,'and forth from the bath he came, in form like unto the immortals.'),(14742,' Then he sat down again on the chair from which he had risen,  opposite his wife; and he spoke to her and said:'),(14743,'“Strange lady! to thee beyond all women have the dwellers on Olympus given a heart that cannot be softened.'),(14744,' No other woman would harden her heart as thou dost, and stand aloof from her husband who after many grievous toils  had come to her in the twentieth year to his native land.'),(14745,' Nay come, nurse, strew me a couch, that all alone I may lay me down,'),(14746,' for verily the heart in her breast is of iron.\"'),(14747,'Then wise Penelope answered him: '),(14748,'“Strange sir, I am neither in any wise proud, nor do I scorn thee,  nor yet am I too greatly amazed, but right well do I know what manner of man thou wast, when thou wentest forth from Ithaca on thy long-oared ship.'),(14749,' Yet come, Eurycleia, strew for him the stout bedstead outside the well-built bridal chamber which he made himself.'),(14750,' Thither do ye bring for him the stout bedstead, and cast upon it bedding,  fleeces and cloaks and bright coverlets.”'),(14751,' \nSo she spoke, and made trial of her husband.'),(14752,' But Odysseus, in a burst of anger, spoke to his true-hearted wife, and said:'),(14753,' “Woman, truly this is a bitter word that thou hast spoken.'),(14754,' Who has set my bed elsewhere? '),(14755,'Hard would it be for one,  though never so skilled, unless a god himself should come and easily by his will set it in another place.'),(14756,' But of men there is no mortal that lives, be he never so young and strong, who could easily pry it from its place, for a great token is wrought in the fashioned bed, '),(14757,'and it was I that built it and none other.'),(14758,'  A bush of long-leafed olive was growing within the court, strong and vigorous, '),(14759,'and girth it was like a pillar.'),(14760,' Round about this I built my chamber, till I had finished it, with close-set stones, and I roofed it over well, and added to it jointed doors, close-fitting.'),(14761,'  Thereafter I cut away the leafy branches of the long-leafed olive, and, trimming the trunk from the root, I smoothed it around with the adze well and cunningly, and made it straight to the line, thus fashioning the bed-post; and I bored it all with the augur.'),(14762,' Beginning with this I hewed out my bed, till I had finished it,  inlaying it with gold and silver and ivory, '),(14763,'and I stretched on it a thong of ox-hide, bright with purple.'),(14764,' Thus do I declare to thee this token; '),(14765,' but I know not, woman, whether my bedstead is still fast in its place, or whether by now some man has cut from beneath the olive stump, and set the bedstead elsewhere.”'),(14766,'  So he spoke, and her knees were loosened where she sat, and her heart melted, as she knew the sure tokens which Odysseus told her.'),(14767,' Then with a burst of tears she ran straight toward him, and flung her arms about the neck of Odysseus, and kissed his head, and spoke, saying:'),(14768,'\n“Be not vexed with me, Odysseus, for in all else  thou wast ever the wisest of men.'),(14769,'It is the gods that gave us sorrow, the gods who begrudged that we two should remain with each other and enjoy our youth, and come to the threshold of old age.'),(14770,' But be not now wroth with me for this, nor full of indignation, because at the first, when I saw thee, I did not thus give thee welcome.'),(14771,'  For always the heart in my breast was full of dread, lest some man should come and beguile me with his words; '),(14772,'for there are many that plan devices of evil.'),(14773,'Nay, even Argive Helen, daughter of Zeus, would not have lain in love with a man of another folk,  had she known that the warlike sons of the Achaeans were to bring her home again to her dear native land.'),(14774,' Yet verily in her case a god prompted her to work a shameful deed; '),(14775,'nor until then did she lay up in her mind the thought of that folly, the grievous folly from which at the first sorrow came upon us too.'),(14776,'  But now, since thou hast told the clear tokens of our bed, which no mortal beside has ever seen save thee and me alone and one single handmaid, the daughter of Actor, whom my father gave me or ever I came hither, even her who kept the doors of our strong bridal chamber, lo, thou dost convince my heart, unbending as it is.”'),(14777,' \nSo she spoke, and in his heart aroused yet more the desire for lamentation; '),(14778,'\nand he wept, holding in his arms his dear and true-hearted wife.'),(14779,' And welcome as is the sight of land to men that swim, whose well-built ship Poseidon  has smitten on the sea as it was driven on by the wind and the swollen wave, '),(14780,'and but few have made their escape from the gray sea to the shore by swimming, and thickly are their bodies crusted with brine, and gladly have they set foot on the land and escaped from their evil case; '),(14781,'even so welcome to her was her husband, as she gazed upon him,  and from his neck she could in no wise let her white arms go. '),(14782,'And now would the rosy-fingered Dawn have arisen upon their weeping, had not the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, taken other counsel. '),(14783,'The long night she held back at the end of its course, and likewise stayed the golden-throned Dawn at the streams of Oceanus, and would not suffer her  to yoke her swift-footed horses that bring light to men, Lampus and Phaethon, who are the colts that bear the Dawn.'),(14784,' \nThen to his wife said Odysseus of many wiles: “Wife, we have not yet come to the end of all our trials, but still hereafter there is to be measureless toil,  long and hard, which I must fulfil to the end; '),(14785,'for so did the spirit of Teiresias foretell to me on the day when I went down into the house of Hades to enquire concerning the return of my comrades and myself.'),(14786,' But come, wife, let us to bed, that  lulled now by sweet slumber we may take our joy of rest.\"'),(14787,'Then wise Penelope answered him: '),(14788,'“Thy bed shall be ready for thee whensoever thy heart shall desire it, since the gods have indeed caused thee to come back to thy well-built house and thy native land.'),(14789,'  But since thou hast bethought thee of this, and a god has put it into thy heart, come, tell me of this trial, for in time to come, methinks, I shall learn of it, and to know it at once is no whit worse.” '),(14790,' \nAnd Odysseus of many wiles answered her, and said: '),(14791,'“Strange lady! why dost thou now so urgently bid me  tell thee?'),(14792,' Yet I will declare it, and will hide nothing.'),(14793,'Verily thy heart shall have no joy of it,'),(14794,'  even as I myself have none; for Teiresias bade me go forth to full many cities of men, bearing a shapely oar in my hands, till I should come  to men that know naught of the sea, and eat not of food mingled with salt; '),(14795,' aye, and they know naught of ships with purple cheeks, or of shapely oars that serve as wings to ships.'),(14796,' And he told me this sign, right manifest; nor will I hide it from thee.'),(14797,' When another wayfarer, on meeting me,  should say that I had a winnowing fan on my stout shoulder, then he bade me fix my oar in the earth, and make goodly offerings to lord Poseidon—a ram and a bull and a boar, that mates with sows—and depart for my home, and offer sacred hecatombs  to the immortal gods, who hold broad heaven, to each one in due order.'),(14798,' And death shall come to me myself far from the sea, a death so gentle, that shall lay me low, when I am overcome with sleek old age, '),(14799,' and my people shall dwell in prosperity around me.'),(14800,' All this, he said, should I see fulfilled.\"'),(14801,'  Then wise Penelope answered him: '),(14802,'“If verily the gods are to bring about for thee a happier old age, there is hope then that thou wilt find an escape from evil.\"'),(14803,'Thus they spoke to one another; '),(14804,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 23.289-23.290'),(14805,'Thus they spoke to one another; and meanwhile Eurynome and the nurse made ready the bed  of soft coverlets by the light of blazing torches. ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 289 to line 290'),(14806,' and when she had led them to the bridal chamber, she went back.'),(14807,'And they then gladly came to the place of the couch that was theirs of old.'),(14808,' But Telemachus and the neatherd and the swineherd stayed their feet from dancing, and stayed the women, and themselves lay down to sleep throughout the shadowy halls.'),(14809,'\n  But when the two had had their fill of the joy of love, they took delight in tales, speaking each to the other. She, the fair lady, told of all that she had endured in the halls, looking upon the destructive throng of the wooers, who for her sake  slew many beasts, cattle and goodly sheep; and great store of wine was drawn from the jars.'),(14810,' But Zeus-born Odysseus recounted all the woes that he had brought on men, and all the toil that in his sorrow he had himself endured, '),(14811,'and she was glad to listen, nor did sweet sleep fall upon her eyelids, till he had told all the tale. '),(14812,' \n  He began by telling how at the first he overcame the Cicones, and then came to the rich land of the Lotus-eaters, '),(14813,'and all that the Cyclops wrought, and how he made him pay the price for his mighty comrades, whom the Cyclops had eaten, and had shown no pity. '),(14814,'Then how he came to Aeolus, who received him with a ready heart,  and sent him on his way; but it was not yet his fate to come to his dear native land, nay, the storm-wind caught him up again, and bore him over the teeming deep, groaning heavily.'),(14815,' Next how he came to Telepylus of the Laestrygonians, who destroyed his ships and his well-greaved comrades  one and all, '),(14816,'and Odysseus alone escaped in his black ship. '),(14817,' Then he told of all the wiles and craftiness of Circe, and how in his benched ship he had gone to the dank house of Hades to consult the spirit of Theban Teiresias, and had seen all his comrades  and the mother who bore him and nursed him, when a child. '),(14818,'And how he heard the voice of the Sirens, who sing unceasingly, and had come to the Wandering Rocks, and to dread Charybdis, and to Scylla, from whom never yet had men escaped unscathed.'),(14819,' Then how his comrades slew the kine of Helios, '),(14820,' and how Zeus, who thunders on high, smote his swift ship with a flaming thunderbolt, and his goodly comrades perished all together, while he alone escaped the evil fates.'),(14821,' And how he came to the isle Ogygia and to the nymph Calypso, who kept him there  in her hollow caves, yearning that he should be her husband, and tended him, and said that she would make him immortal and ageless all his days; '),(14822,'yet she could never persuade the heart in his breast. '),(14823,'Then how he came after many toils to the Phaeacians, who heartily showed him all honor, as if he were a god,  and sent him in a ship to his dear native land, after giving him stores of bronze and gold and raiment.'),(14824,' This was the end of the tale he told, when sweet sleep, that loosens the limbs of men, leapt upon him, loosening the cares of his heart. '),(14825,' \nThen again the goddess, flashing-eyed Athena, took other counsel.'),(14826,'  When she judged that the heart of Odysseus had had its fill of dalliance with his wife and of sleep, straightway she roused from Oceanus golden-throned Dawn to bring light to men;'),(14827,'and Odysseus rose from his soft couch, and gave charge to his wife, saying:'),(14828,'\n  “Wife, by now have we had our fill of many trials, thou and I, thou here, mourning over my troublous journey home, '),(14829,' while as for me, Zeus and the other gods bound me fast in sorrows far from my native land, all eager as I was to return.'),(14830,'But now that we have both come to the couch of our desire,  do thou care for the wealth that I have within the halls; as for the flocks which the insolent wooers have wasted, I shall myself get me many as booty, and others will the Achaeans give, until they fill all my folds; '),(14831,'but I verily will go to my well-wooded farm  to see my noble father, who for my sake is sore distressed, '),(14832,'and on thee, wife, do I lay this charge, wise though thou art.'),(14833,' Straightway at the rising of the sun will report go abroad concerning the wooers whom I slew in the halls.'),(14834,' Therefore go thou up to thy upper chamber with thy handmaids,  and abide there. Look thou on no man, nor ask a question.”'),(14835,'He spoke, and girt about his shoulders his beautiful armour, and roused Telemachus and the neatherd and the swineherd, and bade them all take weapons of war in their hands.'),(14836,' They did not disobey, but clad themselves in bronze,  and opened the doors, and went forth, '),(14837,'and Odysseus led the way. '),(14838,'By now there was light over the earth, but Athena hid them in night, and swiftly led them forth from the city.'),(14839,' Meanwhile Cyllenian Hermes called forth the spirits of the wooers.'),(14840,' He held in his hands his wand, a fair wand of gold, wherewith he lulls to sleep the eyes of whom he will, while others again he wakens even out of slumber;'),(14841,' with this he roused and led the spirits, and they followed gibbering.'),(14842,' And as in the innermost recess of a wondrous cave bats flit about gibbering, when one has fallen from off the rock from the chain in which they cling to one another, so these went with him gibbering,'),(14843,' and   Hermes, the Helper, led them down the dank ways.'),(14844,'Past the streams of Oceanus they went, past the rock Leucas, past the gates of the sun and the land of dreams, '),(14845,'and quickly came to the mead of asphodel, where the spirits dwell, phantoms of men who have done with toils.'),(14846,'  Here they found the spirit of Achilles, son of Peleus, and those of Patroclus, of peerless Antilochus, and of Aias, who in comeliness and form was the goodliest of all the Danaans after the peerless son of Peleus.'),(14847,'So these were thronging about Achilles, and near to them  drew the spirit of Agamemnon, son of Atreus, sorrowing; '),(14848,' and round about him others were gathered, the spirits of all those who were slain with him in the house of Aegisthus, and met their fate.'),(14849,' And the spirit of the son of Peleus was first to address him, saying:'),(14850,'“Son of Atreus, we deemed that thou  above all other heroes wast all thy days dear to Zeus, who hurls the thunderbolt, because thou wast lord over many mighty men in the land of the Trojans, where we Achaeans suffered woes.'),(14851,' But verily on thee too was deadly doom to come all too early, the doom that not one avoids of those who are born.'),(14852,'  Ah, would that in the pride of that honor of which thou wast master thou hadst met death and fate in the land of the Trojans.'),(14853,' Then would the whole host of the Achaeans have made thee a tomb, and for thy son too wouldst thou have won great glory in days to come; '),(14854,'but now, as it seems, it has been decreed that thou shouldst be cut off by a most piteous death.” '),(14855,' \n  Then the spirit of the son of Atreus answered him: '),(14856,' “Fortunate son of Peleus, godlike Achilles, that wast slain in the land of Troy far from Argos, '),(14857,' and about thee others fell, the best of the sons of the Trojans and Achaeans, fighting for thy body; '),(14858,'and thou in the whirl of dust  didst lie mighty in thy mightiness, forgetful of thy horsemanship.'),(14859,' We on our part strove the whole day long,'),(14860,' nor should we ever have stayed from the fight, had not Zeus stayed us with a storm.'),(14861,' But after we had borne thee to the ships from out the fight, we laid thee on a bier, and cleansed thy fair flesh  with warm water and with ointment,'),(14862,' and many hot tears did the Danaans shed around thee, and they shore their hair.'),(14863,' And thy mother came forth from the sea with the immortal sea-nymphs, when she heard the tidings,'),(14864,'and a wondrous cry arose over the deep, and thereat trembling laid hold of all the Achaeans.'),(14865,'  Then would they all have sprung up and rushed to the hollow ships, had not a man, wise in the wisdom of old, stayed them, even Nestor, whose counsel had before appeared the best.'),(14866,' He with good intent addressed their assembly, and said:'),(14867,'\n“‘Hold, ye Argives; flee not, Achaean youths.'),(14868,'  \'Tis his mother who comes here forth from the sea with the immortal sea-nymphs to look upon the face of her dead son.\''),(14869,'“So he spoke, and the great-hearted Achaeans ceased from their flight.'),(14870,' Then around thee stood the daughters of the old man of the sea wailing piteously, and they clothed thee about with immortal raiment.'),(14871,'  And the Muses, nine in all, replying to one another with sweet voices, led the dirge.'),(14872,' There couldst thou not have seen an Argive but was in tears,'),(14873,' so deeply did the clear-toned Muse move their hearts.'),(14874,' Thus for seventeen days alike by night and day did we bewail thee, immortal gods and mortal men, '),(14875,' and on the eighteenth we gave thee to the fire, and many well-fatted sheep we slew around thee and sleek kine.'),(14876,' So thou wast burned in the raiment of the gods and in abundance of unguents and sweet honey; '),(14877,' and many Achaean warriors moved in their armour about the pyre, when thou wast burning,  both footmen and charioteers,'),(14878,' and a great din arose. But when the flame of Hephaestus had made an end of thee, in the morning we gathered thy white bones, Achilles, and laid them in unmixed wine and unguents.'),(14879,' Thy mother had given a two-handled, golden urn,'),(14880,' and  said that it was the gift of Dionysus, and the handiwork of famed Hephaestus.'),(14881,'In this lie thy white bones, glorious Achilles, and mingled with them the bones of the dead Patroclus, son of Menoetius, but apart lie those of Antilochus, whom thou didst honor above all the rest of thy comrades after the dead Patroclus.'),(14882,'  And over them we heaped up a great and goodly tomb, we the mighty host of Argive spearmen, on a projecting headland by the broad Hellespont, that it might be seen from far over the sea both by men that now are and that shall be born hereafter. '),(14883,' \n  But thy mother asked of the gods beautiful prizes, and set them in the midst of the list for the chiefs of the Achaeans.'),(14884,'PLACE HOLDER for: urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg002.perseus-grc1 - 24.87-24.89'),(14885,' Ere now hast thou been present at the funeral games of many men that were warriors, when at the death of a king the young men gird themselves and make ready the contests, ----------------------------------------------------------------------\nfrom line 87 to line 89'),(14886,'for very dear wast thou to the gods.'),(14887,' Thus not even in death didst thou lose thy name, but ever shalt thou have fair renown among all men, Achilles.  But, as for me, what pleasure have I now in this, that I wound up the skein of war?'),(14888,' For on my return Zeus devised for me a woeful doom at the hands of Aegisthus and my accursed wife.”'),(14889,'Thus they spoke to one another, but the messenger, Argeiphontes, drew near,  leading down the spirits of the wooers slain by Odysseus; and the two, seized with wonder, went straight toward them when they beheld them.'),(14890,' And the spirit of Agamemnon, son of Atreus, recognized the dear son of Melaneus, glorious Amphimedon, '),(14891,' who had been his host, dwelling in Ithaca.'),(14892,' Then the spirit of the son of Atreus spoke first to him and said: '),(14893,'“Amphimedon, what has befallen you that ye have come down beneath the dark earth, all of you picked men and of like age?'),(14894,' One would make no other choice, were one to pick the best men in a city.'),(14895,' Did Poseidon smite you on board your ships,  when he had roused cruel winds and long waves?'),(14896,'Or did foemen work you harm on the land, while you were cutting off their cattle and fair flocks of sheep, or while they fought in defence of their city and their women?'),(14897,'for I declare that I am a friend of thy house.'),(14898,'for I declare that I am a friend of thy house.'),(14899,'  Dost thou not remember when I came thither to your house with godlike Menelaus to urge Odysseus to go with us to Ilios on the benched ships?'),(14900,' A full month it took us to cross all the wide sea, for hardly could we win to our will Odysseus, the sacker of cities.\"'),(14901,'  Then the spirit of Amphimedon answered him, and said: '),(14902,'“Most glorious son of Atreus, king of men, Agamemnon, I remember all these things, O thou fostered of Zeus, even as thou dost tell them; '),(14903,'and on my part I will frankly tell thee all the truth, how for us an evil end of death was wrought.'),(14904,'  We wooed the wife of Odysseus, that had long been gone,'),(14905,' and she neither refused the hateful marriage, nor would she ever make an end, devising for us death and black fate. Nay, she contrived in her heart this guileful thing also:'),(14906,' she set up in her halls a great web, and fell to weaving—  fine of thread was the web and very wide; '),(14907,'and straightway she spoke among us:'),(14908,'“‘Young men, my wooers, since goodly Odysseus is dead, be patient, though eager for my marriage, until I finish this robe—I would not that my spinning should come to naught—a shroud for the lord Laertes against the time when  the fell fate of grievous death shall strike him down; lest any of the Achaean women in the land should be wroth at me, if he were to lie without a shroud, who had won great possessions.’ '),(14909,' \n“So she spoke, and our proud hearts consented.'),(14910,' Then day by day she would weave at the great web,  but by night would unravel it, when she had let place torches by her. '),(14911,'Thus for three years she by her craft kept the Achaeans from knowing, and beguiled them;'),(14912,' but when the fourth year came, as the seasons rolled on, as the months waned and many days were brought in their course, even then one of her women who knew all, told us,  and we caught her unravelling the splendid web. '),(14913,'So she finished it against her will perforce.'),(14914,'\n“Now when she had shewn us the robe, after weaving the great web and washing it, and it shone like the sun or the moon, then it was that some cruel god brought Odysseus from somewhere  to the border of the land, where the swineherd dwelt.'),(14915,' Thither too came the dear son of divine Odysseus on his return from sandy Pylos in his black ship, '),(14916,'and these two, when they had planned an evil death for the wooers, came to the famous city, Odysseus verily  later, but Telemachus led the way before him.'),(14917,' Now the swineherd brought his master, clad in mean raiment, in the likeness of a woeful and aged beggar, leaning on a staff,'),(14918,' and miserable was the raiment that he wore about his body;'),(14919,'and not one of us could know that it was he,  when he appeared so suddenly, no, not even those that were older men, but we assailed him with evil words and with missiles.'),(14920,' Howbeit he with steadfast heart endured for a time to be pelted and taunted in his own halls; '),(14921,'but when at last the will of Zeus, who bears the aegis, roused him,  with the help of Telemachus he took all the beautiful arms and laid them away in the store-room and made fast the bolts. Then in his great cunning he bade his wife set before the wooers his bow and the grey iron to be a contest for us ill-fated men and the beginning of death.'),(14922,'  And no man of us was able to stretch the string of the mighty bow; nay, we fell far short of that strength.'),(14923,' But when the great bow came to the hands of Odysseus, then we all cried out aloud not to give him the bow, how much soever he might speak; '),(14924,' but Telemachus alone urged him on, and bade him take it. '),(14925,'Then he took the bow in his hand, the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus, and with ease did he string it and send an arrow through the iron. Then he went and stood on the threshold, and poured out the swift arrows, glaring about him terribly, and smote king Antinous.'),(14926,'  And thereafter upon the others he with sure aim let fly his shafts, fraught with groanings, '),(14927,'and the men fell thick and fast.'),(14928,' Then was it known that some god was their helper;'),(14929,' for straightway rushing on through the halls in their fury they slew men left and right, and therefrom rose hideous groaning,  as heads were smitten, and all the floor swam with blood.'),(14930,' Thus we perished, Agamemnon, and even now our bodies still lie uncared-for in the halls of Odysseus;'),(14931,' for our friends in each man\'s home know naught as yet—our friends who might wash the black blood from our wounds  and lay our bodies out with wailing; '),(14932,'for that is the due of the dead.”'),(14933,' \nThen the spirit of the son of Atreus answered him:'),(14934,' “Happy son of Laertes, Odysseus of many devices, of a truth full of all excellence was the wife thou didst win, '),(14935,'so good of understanding was peerless Penelope,  daughter of Icarius, '),(14936,'in that she was loyally mindful of Odysseus, her wedded husband. '),(14937,'Therefore the fame of her virtue shall never perish, but the immortals shall make among men on earth a pleasant song in honor of constant Penelope. Not on this wise did the daughter of Tyndareus devise evil deeds  and slay her wedded husband, and hateful shall the song regarding her be among men, and evil repute doth she bring upon all womankind, even upon her that doeth uprightly.\"'),(14938,'Thus the two spoke to one another, as they stood in the house of Hades beneath the depths of the earth.'),(14939,'\n  But Odysseus and his men, when they had gone down from the city, quickly came to the fair and well-ordered farm of Laertes, which he had won for himself in days past, and much had he toiled for it.'),(14940,' There was his house, and all about it ran the sheds in which ate, and sat, and slept  the servants that were bondsmen, that did his pleasure; '),(14941,' but within it was an old Sicilian woman, who tended the old man with kindly care there at the farm, far from the city.'),(14942,' Then Odysseus spoke to the servants and to his son, saying:'),(14943,'\n“Do you now go within the well-built house,  and straightway slay for dinner the best of the swine;'),(14944,'but I will make trial of my father, and see whether he will recognize me and know me by sight, or whether he will fail to know me, since I have been gone so long a time.\"'),(14945,'So saying, he gave to the slaves his battle-gear.'),(14946,'  They thereafter went quickly to the house; but Odysseus drew near to the fruitful vineyard in his quest.'),(14947,' Now he did not find Dolius as he went down into the great orchard, nor any of his slaves or of his sons,'),(14948,' but as it chanced  they had gone to gather stones for the vineyard wall, and the old man was their leader.'),(14949,'But he found his father alone in the well-ordered vineyard, digging about a plant;'),(14950,'  and he was clothed in a foul tunic, patched and wretched, and about his shins he had bound stitched greaves of ox-hide to guard against scratches,  and he wore gloves upon his hands because of the thorns, '),(14951,' and on his head a goatskin cap; and he nursed his sorrow. '),(14952,' \nNow when the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus saw him, worn with old age and laden with great grief at heart, he stood still beneath a tall pear tree, and shed tears.'),(14953,'  Then he debated in mind and heart whether to kiss and embrace his father, and tell him all, how he had returned and come to his native land, or whether he should first question him, and prove him in each thing.'),(14954,' And, as he pondered, this seemed to him the better course,  to prove him first with mocking words. '),(14955,'So with this in mind the goodly Odysseus went straight toward him.'),(14956,' He verily was holding his head down, digging about a plant,'),(14957,'and his glorious son came up to him, and addressed him, saying:'),(14958,'“Old man, no lack of skill hast thou to tend  a garden; nay, thy care is good, and there is naught whatsoever, either plant or fig tree, or vine, nay, or olive, or pear, or garden-plot in all the field that lacks care.'),(14959,' But another thing will I tell thee, and do thou not lay up wrath thereat in thy heart: thou thyself enjoyest no good care, but  thou bearest woeful old age, and therewith art foul and unkempt, and clad in mean raiment.'),(14960,' Surely it is not because of sloth on thy part that thy master cares not for thee, nor dost thou seem in any wise like a slave to look upon either in form or in stature;'),(14961,' for thou art like a king, '),(14962,' even like one who, when he has bathed and eaten,  should sleep soft; '),(14963,'for this is the way of old men.'),(14964,' But come, tell me this, and declare it truly. Whose slave art thou,'),(14965,' and whose orchard dost thou tend?'),(14966,' and whose orchard dost thou tend? And tell me this also truly, that I may know full well, whether this is indeed Ithaca, to which we are now come, as  a man yonder told me, who met me but now on my way hither. In no wise over sound of wit was he, for he deigned not to tell me of each thing, nor to listen to my word, when I questioned him about a friend of mine, whether haply he still lives, or is now dead and in the house of Hades.'),(14967,'  For I will tell thee, and do thou give heed and hearken.'),(14968,' I once entertained in my dear native land a man that came to our house, and never did any man beside of strangers that dwell afar come to my house a more welcome guest.'),(14969,' He declared that by lineage he came from Ithaca, and said  that his own father was Laertes, son of Arceisius. '),(14970,' So I took him to the house and gave him entertainment with kindly welcome of the rich store that was within, and I gave him gifts of friendship, such as are meet. '),(14971,'Of well-wrought gold  I gave him seven talents, and a mixing-bowl all of silver, embossed with flowers, and twelve cloaks of single fold, and as many coverlets, and as many fair mantles, and as many tunics besides, and furthermore women, skilled in goodly handiwork, four comely women, whom he himself was minded to choose.” '),(14972,' \n  Then his father answered him, weeping: '),(14973,' “Stranger, verily thou art come to the country of which thou dost ask, but wanton and reckless men now possess it.'),(14974,' And all in vain didst thou bestow those gifts, the countless gifts thou gavest. '),(14975,'For if thou hadst found him yet alive in the land of Ithaca,  then would he have sent thee on thy way with ample requital of gifts and good entertainment; for that is the due of him who begins the kindness.'),(14976,' But come, tell me this, and declare it truly. How many years have passed since thou didst entertain that guest, that hapless guest, my son—as sure as ever such a man there was—  my ill-starred son,'),(14977,' whom far from his friends and his native land haply the fishes have devoured in the deep, or on the shore he has become the spoil of beasts and birds?'),(14978,' Nor did his mother deck him for burial and weep over him, nor his father, we who gave him birth, '),(14979,'no, nor did his wife, wooed with many gifts, constant Penelope,  bewail her own husband upon the bier, as was meet, when she had closed his eyes in death; '),(14980,' though that is the due of the dead.'),(14981,' And tell me this also truly, that I may know full well.'),(14982,' Where is thy city, and where thy parents?'),(14983,' Where is thy city, and where thy parents?'),(14984,' Where is the swift ship moored that brought thee hither  with thy godlike comrades? '),(14985,'Or didst thou come as a passenger on another\'s ship, and did they depart when they had set thee on shore?\"'),(14986,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(14987,' “Then verily will I frankly tell thee all.'),(14988,' I come from Alybas, where I have a glorious house,  and I am the son of Apheidas, son of lord Polypemon, '),(14989,' and my own name is Eperitus.'),(14990,' But a god drove me wandering from Sicania to come hither against my will '),(14991,' and my ship lies yonder off the tilled land away from the city.'),(14992,'But as for Odysseus, it is now the fifth year  since he went thence, and departed from my country. Hapless man!'),(14993,' Yet he had birds of good omen, when he set out, birds upon the right. So I was glad of them, as I sent him on his way,'),(14994,' and he went gladly forth, and our hearts hoped that we should yet meet as host and guest and give one another glorious gifts.\"'),(14995,'  So he spoke, and a dark cloud of grief enwrapped Laertes, '),(14996,'and with both his hands he took the dark dust and strewed it over his grey head with ceaseless groaning.'),(14997,' Then the heart of Odysseus was stirred, and up through his nostrils shot a keen pang, as he beheld his dear father.'),(14998,' And he sprang toward him, and clasped him in his arms, and kissed him, saying:'),(14999,'“Lo, father, I here before thee, my very self, am that man of whom thou dost ask; I am come in the twentieth year to my native land.'),(15000,' But cease from grief and tearful lamenting, '),(15001,' though great is the need of haste.'),(15002,' though great is the need of haste.'),(15003,'  The wooers have I slain in our halls, and have taken vengeance on their grievous insolence and their evil deeds.” '),(15004,' \nThen Laertes answered him again, and said:'),(15005,' “If it is indeed as Odysseus, my son, that thou art come hither, tell me now some clear sign, that I maybe sure.\"'),(15006,'  And Odysseus of many wiles answered him and said: '),(15007,'“This scar first do thou mark with thine eyes, the scar of the wound which a boar dealt me with his white tusk on Parnassus, when I had gone thither.'),(15008,' It was thou that didst send me forth, thou and my honored mother, to Autolycus, my mother\'s father, that I might get  the gifts which, when he came hither, he promised and agreed to give me. '),(15009,' And come, I will tell thee also the trees in the well-ordered garden which once thou gavest me, and I, who was but a child, was following thee through the garden, and asking thee for this and that.'),(15010,' It was through these very trees that we passed, and thou didst name them, and tell me of each one.'),(15011,'  Pear-trees thirteen thou gavest me, and ten apple-trees, and forty fig-trees.'),(15012,' And rows of vines too didst thou promise to give me, even as I say, fifty of them, which ripened severally at different times—'),(15013,'and upon them are clusters of all sorts—whensoever the seasons of Zeus weighed them down from above.”'),(15014,'  So he spoke, and his father\'s knees were loosened where he stood, and his heart melted, as he knew the sure tokens which Odysseus told him.'),(15015,' About his dear son he flung both his arms, '),(15016,'and the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus caught him unto him fainting.'),(15017,' But when he revived, and his spirit returned again into his breast,  once more he made answer, and spoke, saying:'),(15018,'“Father Zeus, verily ye gods yet hold sway on high Olympus, if indeed the wooers have paid the price of their wanton insolence.'),(15019,' But now I have wondrous dread at heart, lest straightway all the men of Ithaca come hither against us, and  send messengers everywhere to the cities of the Cephallenians.”'),(15020,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said:'),(15021,' “Be of good cheer, and let not these things distress thy heart.'),(15022,' But let us go to the house, which lies near the orchard, '),(15023,'for thither  I sent forward Telemachus and the neatherd and the swineherd, that with all speed they might prepare our meal.”'),(15024,'So spoke the two, and went their way to the goodly house.'),(15025,' And when they had come to the stately house, they found Telemachus, and the neatherd, and the swineherd carving flesh in abundance, and mixing the flaming wine. '),(15026,' \n  Meanwhile the Sicilian handmaid bathed great-hearted Laertes in his house, and anointed him with oil, and about him cast a fair cloak.'),(15027,' But Athena drew near, and made greater the limbs of the shepherd of the people, and made him taller than before and mightier to behold.'),(15028,'  Then he came forth from the bath,'),(15029,' and his dear son marvelled at him, seeing him in presence like unto the immortal gods.'),(15030,' And he spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(15031,'\n“Father, surely some one of the gods that are forever has made thee goodlier to behold in comeliness and in stature.\"'),(15032,'  Then wise Laertes answered him: '),(15033,'“I would, O father Zeus, and Athena, and Apollo, that in such strength as when I took Nericus, the well built citadel on the shore of the mainland, when I was lord of the Cephallenians, even in such strength I had stood by thy side yesterday in our house  with my armour about my shoulders, and had beaten back the wooers.'),(15034,' So should I have loosened the knees of many of them in the halls, and thy heart would have been made glad within thee.\"'),(15035,'So they spoke to one another.'),(15036,' But when the others had ceased from their labour, and had made ready the meal,  they sat down in order on the chairs and high seats. '),(15037,'Then they were about to set hands to their food, when the old man Dolius drew near, and with him the old man\'s sons, wearied from their work in the fields, for their mother, the old Sicilian woman, had gone forth and called them, she who  saw to their food, and tended the old man with kindly care, now that old age had laid hold of him. '),(15038,'And they, when they saw Odysseus, and marked him in their minds, stood in the halls lost in wonder.'),(15039,' But Odysseus addressed them with gentle words, and said:'),(15040,'\n“Old man, sit down to dinner, and do ye wholly forget your wonder, '),(15041,' for long have we waited in the halls, though eager to set hands to the food, ever expecting your coming.\"'),(15042,'So he spoke, and Dolius ran straight toward him with both hands outstretched, and he clasped the hand of Odysseus and kissed it on the wrist, and spoke, and addressed him with winged words:'),(15043,'\n  “Dear master, since thou hast come back to us, who sorely longed for thee, but had no more thought to see thee, and the gods themselves have brought thee—hail to thee, and all welcome, and may the gods grant thee happiness.'),(15044,' And tell me this also truly, that I may know full well. Does wise Penelope yet know surely  that thou hast come back hither, or shall we send her a messenger?”'),(15045,'Then Odysseus of many wiles answered him, and said: “Old man, she knows already; '),(15046,'why shouldst thou be busied with this?”'),(15047,'So he spoke, and the other sat down again on the polished chair. '),(15048,'And even in like manner the sons of Dolius gathered around glorious Odysseus  and greeted him in speech, and clasped his hands. Then they sat down in order beside Dolius, their father. '),(15049,' \nSo they were busied with their meal in the halls; '),(15050,'but meanwhile Rumor, the messenger, went swiftly throughout all the city, telling of the terrible death and fate of the wooers.'),(15051,'  And the people heard it all at once, and gathered from every side with moanings and wailings before the palace of Odysseus. Forth from the halls they brought each his dead, and buried them; and those from other cities they sent each to his own home, placing them on swift ships for seamen to bear them, '),(15052,' but they themselves went together to the place of assembly, sad at heart.'),(15053,' Now when they were assembled and met together Eupeithes arose and spoke among them, '),(15054,'for comfortless grief for his son lay heavy on his heart, even for Antinous, the first man whom goodly Odysseus had slain.'),(15055,'  Weeping for him he addressed their assembly and said:'),(15056,'“Friends, a monstrous deed has this man of a truth devised against the Achaeans.'),(15057,' Some he led forth in his ships, many men and goodly, and he has lost his hollow ships and utterly lost his men; '),(15058,' and others again has he slain on his return, and these by far the best of the Cephallenians.  Nay then, come, before the fellow goes swiftly to Pylos or to goodly Elis, where the Epeans hold sway, let us go forth; '),(15059,'verily even in days to come shall we be disgraced forever.'),(15060,' For a shame is this even for men that are yet to be to hear of, if we shall not  take vengeance on the slayers of our sons and our brothers. '),(15061,'To me surely life would then no more be sweet; rather would I die at once and be among the dead.'),(15062,' Nay, let us forth, lest they be too quick for us, and cross over the sea.\"'),(15063,'So he spoke, weeping, and pity laid hold of all the Achaeans.'),(15064,'Then near them came Medon and the divine minstrel  from the halls of Odysseus, for sleep had released them; and they took their stand in the midst, '),(15065,'and wonder seized every man.'),(15066,' Then Medon, wise of heart, spoke among them:'),(15067,'\n“Hearken now to me, men of Ithaca, '),(15068,'for verily not without the will of the immortal gods has Odysseus devised these deeds.'),(15069,'  Nay, I myself saw an immortal god, who stood close beside Odysseus, and seemed in all things like unto Mentor.'),(15070,' Yet as an immortal god now in front of Odysseus would he appear, heartening him, and now again would rage through the hall, scaring the wooers; '),(15071,'and they fell thick and fast.” '),(15072,' \n  So he spoke, and thereat pale fear seized them all. '),(15073,' Then among them spoke the old lord Halitherses, son of Mastor, '),(15074,' for he alone saw before and after: '),(15075,'he with good intent addressed their assembly, and said:'),(15076,'“Hearken now to me, men of Ithaca, to the word that I shall say.'),(15077,' Through your own cowardice, friends, have these deeds been brought to pass, '),(15078,' for you would not obey me, nor Mentor, shepherd of the people, to make your sons cease from their folly. They wrought a monstrous deed in their blind and wanton wickedness, wasting the wealth and dishonoring the wife  of a prince,'),(15079,' who, they said, would never more return. '),(15080,'and do you hearken to me, as I bid.'),(15081,'and do you hearken to me, as I bid.'),(15082,' Let us not go forth, lest haply many a one shall find a bane which he has brought upon himself.\"'),(15083,'So he spoke, but they sprang up with loud cries, more than half of them,'),(15084,' but the rest remained together in their seats; '),(15085,' for his speech was not to their mind, but they hearkened to Eupeithes, '),(15086,' and quickly thereafter they rushed for their arms.'),(15087,' Then when they had clothed their bodies in gleaming bronze, they gathered together in front of the spacious city.'),(15088,' And Eupeithes led them in his folly, '),(15089,' for he thought to avenge the slaying of his son; yet he was himself never more to come back, but was there to meet his doom.'),(15090,'\nBut Athena spoke to Zeus, son of Cronos, saying:'),(15091,' “Father of us all, thou son of Cronos, high above all lords, tell to me that ask thee what purpose thy mind now hides within thee.'),(15092,'  Wilt thou yet further bring to pass evil war and the dread din of battle, or wilt thou establish friendship betwixt the twain?\"'),(15093,'Then Zeus, the cloud-gatherer, answered her, and said:'),(15094,' “My child, why dost thou ask and question me of this?'),(15095,' Didst thou not thyself devise this plan,  that verily Odysseus should take vengeance on these men at his coming? '),(15096,'but I will tell thee what is fitting. '),(15097,'but I will tell thee what is fitting. '),(15098,' Now that goodly Odysseus has taken vengeance on the wooers, let them swear a solemn oath, and let him be king all his days, and let us on our part  bring about a forgetting of the slaying of their sons and brothers; '),(15099,'and let them love one another as before, and let wealth and peace abound.\"'),(15100,'So saying, he roused Athena, who was already eager, and she went darting down from the heights of Olympus.'),(15101,'\nBut when they had put from them the desire of honey-hearted food,  the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus was the first to speak among his company, saying:'),(15102,' “Let one go forth and see whether they be not now drawing near.\"'),(15103,' and a son of Dolius went forth, as he bade; '),(15104,' and a son of Dolius went forth, as he bade; '),(15105,'he went and stood upon the threshold, and saw them all close at hand, '),(15106,'and straightway he spoke to Odysseus winged words: '),(15107,'Quick, let us arm.”'),(15108,'Quick, let us arm.”'),(15109,' \nSo he spoke, and they rose up and arrayed themselves in armour: Odysseus and his men were four, and six the sons of Dolius, '),(15110,'and among them Laertes and Dolius donned their armour, grey-headed though they were, warriors perforce.'),(15111,'  But when they had clothed their bodies in gleaming bronze, they opened the doors and went forth, and Odysseus led them.'),(15112,'\nThen Athena, daughter of Zeus, drew near them in the likeness of Mentor both in form and in voice, '),(15113,'and the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus was glad at sight of her,'),(15114,' and straightway spoke to Telemachus, his dear son:'),(15115,'\n“Telemachus, now shalt thou learn this—having thyself come to the place of battle, where the best warriors are put to the trial—to bring no disgrace upon the house of thy fathers, for we have ever excelled in strength and in valor over all the earth.\"'),(15116,'  And wise Telemachus answered him: '),(15117,'“Thou shalt see me, if thou wilt, dear father, in my present temper, bringing no disgrace upon thy house, even as thou sayest.\"'),(15118,'So said he, and Laertes was glad, and spoke, saying:'),(15119,' Verily right glad am I:'),(15120,' Verily right glad am I:'),(15121,'my son and my son\'s son are vying with one another in valor.”'),(15122,'Then flashing-eyed Athena came near him and said:'),(15123,' “Son of Arceisius, far the dearest of all my friends, make a prayer to the flashing-eyed maiden and to father Zeus, and then straightway raise aloft thy long spear, and hurl it.”'),(15124,'  So spoke Pallas Athena, and breathed into him great might. Then he prayed to the daughter of great Zeus, and straightway raised aloft his long spear, and hurled it, and smote Eupeithes through the helmet with cheek-piece of bronze.'),(15125,' This stayed not the spear, but the bronze passed through,  and he fell with a thud, and his armour clanged about him. '),(15126,'Then on the foremost fighters fell Odysseus and his glorious son, and thrust at them with swords and double-pointed spears.'),(15127,' And now would they have slain them all, and cut them off from returning, had not Athena, daughter of Zeus, who bears the aegis,  shouted aloud, and checked all the host, saying:'),(15128,'“Refrain, men of Ithaca, from grievous war, that with all speed you may part, and that without bloodshed.\"'),(15129,'So spoke Athena, and pale fear seized them.'),(15130,' Then in their terror the arms flew from their hands  and fell one and all to the ground, as the goddess uttered her voice, '),(15131,'and they turned toward the city, eager to save their lives.'),(15132,' Terribly then shouted the much-enduring, goodly Odysseus, and gathering himself together he swooped upon them like an eagle of lofty flight, '),(15133,'and at that moment the son of Cronos cast a flaming thunderbolt,  and down it fell before the flashing-eyed daughter of the mighty sire.'),(15134,' Then flashing-eyed Athena spoke to Odysseus saying:'),(15135,'\n“Son of Laertes, sprung from Zeus, Odysseus of many devices, stay thy hand, and make the strife of equal war to cease, lest haply the son of Cronos be wroth with thee, even Zeus, whose voice is borne afar.\"'),(15136,'  So spoke Athena, and he obeyed, and was glad at heart. '),(15137,'Then for all time to come a solemn covenant betwixt the twain was made by Pallas Athena, daughter of Zeus, who bears the aegis, in the likeness of Mentor both in form and in voice.');
